<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT WHITE SOX, 5-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The baton carried by the New York Yankees' left
fielders was passed once more on Tuesday night, from Ricky Ledee to
Shane Spencer. What they could really use, however, is a rabbit's
foot or a four-leaf clover.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after Spencer was activated from the disabled list
after recovering from an irregular heartbeat, Ledee strained a
groin muscle while running out an infield hit. Spencer replaced
Ledee and drove home a run with a sacrifice fly as the Yankees
edged the White Sox, 5-3, for their seventh consecutive victory.
Orlando Hernandez (12-6) pitched six innings before departing with
an apparent minor injury.
</P>
<P>
   As Hernandez warmed up to pitch the bottom of the sixth inning,
he had a problem that prompted Manager Joe Torre and the trainer
Gene Monahan to go to the mound. Hernandez chatted amiably with
Torre and persuaded his manager to leave him in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But after Hernandez pitched the sixth inning, he was relieved by
the left-hander Allen Watson, despite the fact that Hernandez had
thrown only 71 pitches, or about 40 fewer than normal. The Yankees
announced that Hernandez, who has a history of back trouble, hadn't
suffered any injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about my next start,'' Hernandez said afterward.
``In five days, El Duque.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson pitched into the eighth, permitting consecutive singles
with one out and the Yankees leading by 4-2. The right-hander Jason
Grimsley relieved Watson and prompted Frank Thomas to bounce to
third for what should have been an easy double play.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius threw to second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who
failed to catch the ball. One run scored, the potential tying run
moved to third and there was still one out. But Magglio Ordonez
broke his bat on a soft lineout to short for the second out.
Grimsley then stunned Paul Konerko with a slider for an
inning-ending strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday night's game, the Yankees' left fielders had
a cumulative batting average of .210, with 12 homers and 32 runs
batted in, meager numbers but a vast improvement from June. Since
then, Spencer and then Chad Curtis and Ledee all got hot
intermittently. Torre indicated before Tuesday night's game that
even if the Yankees did not make a trade for a left fielder, he was
sure that Ledee, Spencer and Curtis could get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't stay healthy. Ledee chopped a ground ball to the
left side of the infield in the second inning and after he lunged
to safely reach first, he grabbed his upper thigh before limping
off. The Yankees announced that Ledee had suffered a slight groin
strain, but Torre usually treats injuries conservatively.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer singled and scored a run in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and nobody on base, Paul O'Neill pulled the ball
down the right-field line. But the ball curled foul at the pole,
prompting O'Neill to stare down the line, squinting to see if the
ball should have been ruled fair.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill returned and smashed a high drive to right-center field,
where fans in the stands waited for the ball to land. Chris
Singleton had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox center fielder leaped at the wall to backhand
O'Neill's shot before falling to the ground. O'Neill, by his
standards, watched passively.
</P>
<P>
   Having just missed a home run before being robbed of another,
O'Neill started the Yankees' fourth-inning rally with a double,
flaring the ball down the left field line. Bernie Williams slammed
a single to right field, but the ball hit hard enough to force
O'Neill to stop at third. O'Neill scored when Tino Martinez dumped
a single in front of Singleton to put the Yankees ahead, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   When Chili Davis hit a fly to straightaway center field, the
deepest part of the field, Williams tagged up and took third as
Martinez tagged up at first and raced for second. After Singleton
made a strong throw toward second, shortstop Mike Caruso
inexplicably cut off the ball rather than allow Ray Durham attempt
a tag on Martinez. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
