<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE MAKES PINPOINT LANDING AFTER TELESCOPE DELIVERY MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BETH DICKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The first woman to command a U.S. space mission
returned to Earth in the space shuttle Columbia late Tuesday,
capping a smooth, five-day mission to deliver a telescope by making
a pinpoint landing in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Blazing a fiery trail in the night sky over the Gulf of Mexico,
the winged spaceship, with Col. Eileen M. Collins of the Air Force
at the controls, touched down at 11:20 p.m., Eastern time at the
Kennedy Space Center in Florida not far from where it was launched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbia home, completing a mission that made history and
opened a new eye on the universe,'' said James Hartsfield, a
commentator at Mission Control here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston, Columbia. Wheels stopped,'' Colonel Collins, 42,
radioed from the cockpit as the 100-ton spaceship rolled to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome home,'' Mission Control's Scott Altman radioed back.
``Eileen, to you and the crew, just an outstanding job deploying
Chandra and bringing Columbia home for a beautiful landing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Kennedy Space Center, rocket engineers were standing by
to investigate a more down-to-earth mystery, why the Columbia
apparently leaked explosive hydrogen fuel from the moment it was
launched all the way into orbit early last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials characterized the leak as small. But a larger
leak could have caused the engine to shut down early, forcing the
crew to attempt a risky emergency landing in Florida or across the
Atlantic in Africa minutes after liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the mission saw the crew of two women and three
men deploy NASA's Chandra X-Ray Observatory, a $1.5 billion space
telescope designed to help solve the mysteries of black holes and
other intriguing astronomical objects.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Colonel Collins aboard the Columbia were the mission
pilot, Capt. Jeffrey S. Ashby, 45, of the Navy, and three mission
specialists: Lt. Col. Catherine G. Coleman, 38, of the Air Force, a
polymer chemist; Steven A. Hawley, 47, an astronomer, and Col.
Michel Tognini, 49, of the French Air Force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
