<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PATIENTSRIGHTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ONE MORE CHANCE FOR PATIENTS' RIGHTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs last graf for clarifying rewrite)  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 28:
</P>
<P>
   The fight for strong legislation to protect the rights of
patients in managed-care health plans has now moved to the House.
The House Republican leadership will make a serious mistake if it
insists on replicating the Senate's feeble efforts. Americans are
plainly worried about managed-care abuses. A number of dissident
Republicans have heard these concerns and are pushing for tougher
patient protections, including the right to sue health plans when
they improperly deny coverage. The issue is whether these
Republicans can get their leaders to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   Any meaningful legislation has to cover all 161 million
Americans with private health insurance. It should require that
appeals of denials of coverage be heard by an independent panel
with broad powers of review. The bill should prohibit health plans
from dodging this process by defining ``medical necessity'' in
unfairly narrow ways. It should also contain a strong enforcement
mechanism so that consumers who are injured by wrongful denials of
care can get legal redress.
</P>
<P>
   Current federal law bars the roughly 125 million people covered
by private employer-sponsored insurance from suing a health plan
for damages caused by improper coverage denials. Without the right
to sue, there is no meaningful deterrent against abuses. Critics
predict a flood of litigation and a rise in premiums. But studies
of groups that are not barred from suing _ notably state and local
employees _ have found that litigation has been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   The House leadership opposes the right to sue, and has
tentatively decided to offer a version of the Senate bill, probably
modified to cover more people. But even that change would not be
sufficient. The Clinton administration has signaled that it will
veto an inadequate measure. The House Republicans need political
cover on this issue, but passing a sham bill will not protect them
from angry voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
