<SLUG> BC-KCHOT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWING CONCERN FOR HEAT MEANS A LOT TO OLDER RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD AND RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvey Brown set down a white box fan and knocked on Mary
Grizzle's door. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, four days into the heat wave that's hunkered on top
of Kansas City, Grizzle's 19-year-old air-conditioner gave out.
That left the 67-year-old homebound Kansas Citian with little
choice but to sweat out the temperatures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To sleep at night, she covered herself in towels soaked in ice
water. Still, that hasn't been a very safe, or comfortable,
solution for Grizzle, who has high blood pressure, severe arthritis
and diabetes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Tuesday afternoon, Grizzle was grateful not only for the
Meals on Wheels delivery from the Don Bosco Community Center, but
also for the white box fan as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just on the phone to church, asking people to pray for
those who don't have air conditioning,'' she said. ``And look,
already you've brought me a fan. God bless you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During what some are calling Kansas City's worst heat wave in a
decade, Brown and other service workers like him are being hailed
as quiet heroes. During sweltering summer weather, Brown and others
serve a vital role: to make sure those people most at risk for
heat-related health problems _ the elderly, disabled or ill _ are
coping with the heat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, a 65-year-old man died July 8, and a day later,
an 81-year-old Lee's Summit, Mo., woman died, both of heat-related
illnesses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around Kansas City, Tuesday marked the 10th day on which
temperatures have soared past 90 degrees. Downtown Kansas City
recorded 100 degrees, with a heat index of 110 degrees. At Kansas
City International Airport, the high was 99. An Ozone Red Alert was
also in place and planned for today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No other heat-related deaths were reported Tuesday, although
area hospitals reported having treated more than 30 people in the
past week for heat-related problems, from dehydration to heat
exhaustion. One person at Baptist Medical Center in Kansas City
remained in critical condition Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement and public safety agencies Tuesday throughout
the Northland said that despite searing temperatures, there were
virtually no heat-related calls. Dispatchers for the Excelsior
Springs Police Department said police and fire officials responded
to two calls of people overheating, but both persons were quickly
treated without further incident. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These sun-drenched, sizzling days will continue into the
weekend, according to the National Weather Service in Pleasant
Hill, Mo. A high-pressure system is stifling the area with
sweltering temperatures while fending off cold fronts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Any showers in northern Missouri or along the Kansas-Nebraska
border will provide little comfort for the metro area, said
meteorologist Janice Bunting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Utilities that have watched soaring power consumption reported
no problems meeting the demand Tuesday, but continued to ask that
residents help conserve electricity by setting thermostats to
higher levels and avoiding high-consumption activities, such as
doing laundry, during the hottest part of the day, generally from 2
p.m. to 8 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pam Levetzow, a spokeswoman for Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co.,
said older residents and people with health problems should not
attempt any power reductions that could prove harmful. Simply
turning off extra lights or not using a dishwasher during peak
demand could help, without resulting in health risks, she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, cities _ and their water supplies _ are coping well,
despite threats of breaks as pipes buckle in the shifting earth.
Several area water departments reported high-level consumption;
Johnson Countians smashed a previous record on Sunday night. None
of the water departments, however, plans conservation measures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson Countians easily topped their previous water consumption
record on Sunday night, when Water District No. 1 poured 122
million gallons into its service area. That amount was far greater
than the previous record of 117 million gallons, but well below the
165-million-gallon capacity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Independence, Mo., which supplies water for parts of Blue
Springs, Mo., and Lee's Summit, Mo., the water department pumped
37.9 million gallons on Sunday, close to the 38.1 million gallon
record set July 4, 1997. Independence, Mo. is rated to pump 42
million gallons daily. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Kansas City's water department can produce about 240
million gallons of water a day, the summer average is about 160
million gallons. Last week, the city average exceeded 170 million
gallons. On Tuesday, that surged to about 185 million gallons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problems are the greatest for older residents, said Jon
Dedon, a Truman Medical Center geriatrician internist who also
teaches at University of Missouri-Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The organs of older people, Dedon said, are less able to divert
blood to the skin to cool the body while still maintaining a
healthy blood pressure and pulse. Often, senior citizens don't
realize when they are thirsty, Dedon said. Seniors with dementia
can't plan for the heat; they might not turn on their air
conditioner even if they have one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During hot times, medicinal treatments for the elderly also can
be a curse. Diuretic medicines are often used, for example for
treating heart disease and blood pressure, but they can cause
dehydration during the summertime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daily visits _ whether from a neighbor, a family member, or a
delivery man _ can often make the difference isolated senior
citizens need to stay alive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the eyes and ears for seniors who live alone,'' said
Bobbie Proctor, the home services supervisor for the Neighborhood
Family Project, a nonprofit which serves elderly residents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Don Bosco's Brown stopped to check on
85-year-old Zelma Hubbard, he noticed that the thermometer in her
front sun room registered 100 degrees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In her living room, the temperature seemed to be at least that.
Hubbard was seated between two fans. The windows were locked shut,
because she said she lacks the strength to open them on her own and
because she fears leaving her home exposed to burglars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awfully hot,'' she noted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any way to cool off besides these fans?'' Brown
asked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I do have an air conditioner. But I have to wait until
the girl who stays with me in the afternoons gets here to turn it
on.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's in the basement.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a minute and I can get that for you.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
