r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APARTFIRE-KAN &LR;      07-28 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS ENCOUNTER SECOND GAS SCARE AT FIRE SITE 
</HEADLINE>
 FIRE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN HOFFMAN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As utility and fire officials investigated a suspected gas leak
and explosion that occurred Monday night near 41st and Walnut
streets, a second leak Tuesday sent a scare through the
neighborhood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A pile of bricks and burnt rubble was all that remained of the
corner building of the Weaver Apartments, where more than a dozen
residents had fled their homes to safety about 20 hours earlier. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By 4 p.m. Tuesday, the area had begun to settle down. Only three
police officers, a few representatives of the Salvation Army and a
handful of utility workers remained at the scene. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then they detected a hissing noise and the strong odor of
natural gas, which sent members of the utility crew slowly backing
away. A police officer used his public address system to tell
people to get back. Television news trucks a block away were
evacuated. Fire pumpers quickly arrived and police began roping off
the area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Crockett, a spokesman for Missouri Gas Energy, said
contractors for Southwestern Bell were trying to restore service to
parts of the area and struck a gas main. He said about 30 to 40
persons were evacuated from a three-block area. They were allowed
to return about 6:30 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Valerie McGriff was home Tuesday with her husband, Don, at 19 E.
41st St. when a firefighter knocked on their door and told them to
leave. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked up the cat and packed some baggage,'' said McGriff,
who said she could smell the natural gas blowing into her home.
``When he came to the door, I knew.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As they dealt with the disruption of a second evacuation within
24 hours, some residents expressed dismay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was pathetic. It just happened last night,'' said
Jennie Richards, who lives around the corner on Walnut. ``They
should have better control.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crockett said Tuesday that Missouri Gas officials still were
investigating the explosion. He said workers had been called to the
apartments about 6:30 p.m. Monday for a reported gas leak. Two
workers had been in the basement just before the explosion. A third
had been in a truck parked along 41st Street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The workers in the basement suffered burns on their faces and
throats and were being treated at a hospital. One was in critical
condition Tuesday night, and one was in fair condition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing much better, and their injuries are not
life-threatening,'' said Darrek Porter, vice president of public
affairs for the gas company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missouri regulators said Tuesday that Missouri Gas officials
told them the main gas pipe and the pipe to the apartment building
had been replaced with plastic pipe in October. The replacements
were part of a program by the utility to replace old pipe in the
utility's service territory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Case, a maintenance worker for the apartments, said he
had been called to the scene for the gas leak. Initially, he said,
the gas crew told him that everything was under control. He said he
went outside the building and stood on Walnut talking to a woman
who lived in a basement apartment. A moment later, he was jolted by
the blast and showered with flying glass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me and blew my glasses off,'' Case said. ``I still
haven't found them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Case said he helped a resident with a child as others tended to
the woman he had been talking to. Neighbors used a door that had
blown off its hinges to carry the woman away from the burning
building. She remained in the hospital Tuesday with a possible
concussion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, as he helped secure vacated apartments, Case thought
about how lucky he was. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing I wasn't in front of the building, or I
would be dead,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jenni Carlson, a sports columnist for The Kansas City Star who
lived in the apartment building, said all residents of the
eight-unit building and the two adjacent buildings were fortunate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My thought is that if I was in the kitchen, I wouldn't have
been so lucky,'' Carlson said. ``There were 14 people who had to be
in a good spot.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carlson said she was sitting on her couch of her second-floor
apartment, looking over some bills, when the blast rocked her. She
said it seemed to have come from her left and below her. She ran to
the front door, and there she noticed the first real sign of the
devastation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see down into the stairwell so the wall behind my
couch had blown out,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unable to open her door, Carlson ran to a sliding door to her
balcony and threw a potted plant through the glass. She used the
plant's stand to clear away shards of glass and made it out to the
deck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I yelled for help several times,'' she said. ``A man (on the
ground) said, `You need to jump! `You need to jump!' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of jumping was not inviting, nor was the idea of
crawling down a nearby drain pipe. Carlson decided to get down by
climbing over her porch railing, hanging from her patio floor and
dropping to the porch below. Her plan didn't work; instead, she
fell about 15 to 20 feet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her left foot and hand were cut, requiring 12 stitches, and her
left arm was badly bruised. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
