<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUEL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAVES RELUCTANTLY OPTS FOR FEDERAL REFORMULATED GASOLINE PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With some reluctance, Kansas Gov. Bill Graves announced Tuesday
that he will ask for federal permission to bring reformulated
gasoline to the Kansas City metro area to reduce air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement virtually assures that millions of dollars in
highway construction _ including the Chouteau Bridge project in
Missouri and $250 million in projects in Johnson and Wyandotte
counties _ can proceed without delays.
</P>
<P>
   Graves' announcement to join the federal reformulated gasoline
program came only hours after Environmental Protection Agency
Administrator Carol Browner called for a significant reduction in
the use of MTBE, the most popular additive in reformulated
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``...We must begin to significantly reduce the use of MTBE in
gasoline as quickly as possible without sacrificing the gains we've
made in achieving cleaner air,'' Browner said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials are concerned about MTBEs potential to contaminate
ground water.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan was expected to announce
today that he also would ask the EPA to include the Kansas City
metro area in the federal reformulated gasoline program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no reason to believe that there's any reservation on
Carnahan's part (in making the request),'' said Mell Henderson,
transportation director at the Mid-America Regional Council.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan's chief of staff, Chris Sifford, said that Carnahan
would make an announcement soon. ``We're still looking and
analyzing our options,'' Sifford said.
</P>
<P>
   Browner's announcement didn't trouble Carnahan, Sifford said.
``We think if we opt into the program, the EPA will update the
program to address the environmental concerns associated with
MTBE.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves and Carnahan had considered today as the last in which
they could decide to opt into the program and ensure no delays in
highway construction.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, federal highway officials and the EPA decided
that area transportation plans were out of compliance with clean
air rules. To fix it, transportation officials said the governors
would have to ask the EPA to use reformulated gasoline in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   It will be at least a year before reformulated gasoline is be
available at area pumps, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Graves was thought to be the least likely of the two governors
to join the federal program. He and his staff had expressed
concerns about the reformulated gasoline program, including
lawsuits and water pollution problems resulting from the increased
use of reformulated gasoline nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Graves expressed reluctance Tuesday in joining the
federal program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our staff worked diligently to explore more palatable options,
acceptable to consumers and Kansas-based refiners,'' Graves said.
``Our hope was to choose an option which did not require the
introduction of this potential source of ground water pollution,
but the timeframe established by EPA and the Federal Highway
Administration made that impractical.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves' concerns were echoed in Washington when Browner
announced Tuesday that the EPA _ which has long promoted the fuel
to reduce air pollution _ should try to phase out the fuel
additive. She said the EPA had never intended to sacrifice clean
water to produce clean air.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, including Missouri, MTBE has contaminated
drinking water supplies as it has leaked from underground storage
tanks, pipes and even into lakes from boat engines. California has
already announced a ban on the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   In changing course, Browner cited a report by an EPA advisory
panel, the Blue Ribbon Panel on Oxygenates and Gasoline. The panel
called for a host of new actions to protect the nation's water
supplies from MTBE and other fuel additives. It also recommended
Congress remove the federal requirement for oxygen-adding
chemicals, including MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommended that MTBE, currently used in 85 percent of
reformulated gasoline, be phased out. In 2004, other regulations
will require reductions in sulfur and other pollutants in gasoline.
The result should be an alternative to reformulated gasoline that
provides similar air quality benefits.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE's promoters, including the Oxygenated Fuels Association,
expressed concerns about the Blue Ribbon panel's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not restrict the availability of oxygenates before we
have ensured that non-oxygenated cleaner-burning fuels can really
produce the needed air quality benefits generated so readily by
fuels that use oxygenates,'' said Terry Wigglesworth, executive
director of the association.
</P>
<P>
   Some local and state officials also worried Tuesday that
switching from MTBE to some other alternative fuel may take time
and cause delays in Kansas City's efforts to improve air quality.
</P>
<P>
   But EPA officials in the agency's regional offices in Kansas
City, Kan., said that Graves' decision on reformulated gasoline
should have long-reaching, positive impacts for the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be good for air quality in Kansas City,''
said the EPA's Royan Teter.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Thompson, a spokeswoman for the Missouri Department of
Natural Resources, said the agency is pleased with the action the
EPA is taking and doesn't expect any delays in bringing the
reformulated gasoline to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson added that the Department of Natural Resources has
upgraded nearly all underground storage tanks in Missouri to
prevent leaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we actually get reformulated gasoline to Kansas
City, there's going to be alternatives available,'' Thompson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
