<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOKANE NOW KNOWS WHAT'S WRONG, BUT NOT SURE HOW TO REPAIR IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On May 31, Forbes magazine ranked Seattle No. 1 out of 162
cities in the United States for business and careers. The magazine
ranked Spokane, Wash., 161st, ahead of only Johnson City, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   This created hardly a stir in Seattle. Spokane noticed. The
leaders of the state's second-largest city were irritated at being
ranked with a town in the Appalachians near the birthplace of Davy
Crockett. They were even more irritated at yet another disparaging
comparison with Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Tom Matthews, chairman of Avista Corp., holding
company for the former Washington Water Power Co. Matthews said
June 10 he might move Avista's four unregulated businesses out of
Spokane. He was having trouble attracting talent. Avista had
interviewed 100 people nationwide for $80,000-to-$100,000 a year
jobs, and none would move to Spokane. Many worried about finding
jobs for their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   Avista is also supporting 66 students on scholarships at local
colleges. ``Not one of them plans to go to work here,'' Matthews
said.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews moved to Spokane a year ago from Houston. Blunt talk
from an out-of-town guy was taken by some as negative. But he says,
``The general reaction was, `We've all thought it; now at least
Matthews is willing to stand up and say it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Spokane does not lack for jobs. But the average household earns
almost $15,000 less in Spokane County than in King County, where
Seattle is. The average house, according to Windermere Real Estate,
also sells for about half: $130,000 in Spokane vs. $264,000 in
northwest Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   On June 30, Spokane held an economic forum in which Ross DeVol,
an analyst with the Milken Institute in Santa Monica, Calif., said
Spokane's problem is technology companies: It doesn't have enough
of them. ``My sense is that the public sector doesn't understand
how important technology industries are,'' DeVol says.
</P>
<P>
   The June 30 forum, the first of several planned, wasn't
organized by downtown business leaders. ``We didn't want this first
one called by the existing leadership because we have to take a new
direction,'' said John Stone, president of John Stone Development.
He quickly added, ``We are not going to exclude anybody, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers said Spokane had focused too much on downtown
retail. ``It was fascinating to see Nordstrom being built downtown,
and people touting it,'' DeVol says. ``Everybody likes to have a
Nordstrom. But economic development through retail is a zero-sum
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokane leaders tread delicately on the Nordstrom issue: It is a
done deal. Controversy swirls over the proposed convention center
project, another example of downtown-first priorities. ``I could
argue with that myself,'' Matthews says. ``But the money's there,
the time's right, so let's do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The message of the conference is that the future priorities
should be different, that Spokane needs to train a high-tech
workforce and recruit and grow the companies to employ them.
</P>
<P>
   The city has no research university comparable to the University
of Washington in Seattle. It does have Gonzaga, Whitworth and
Eastern Washington universities and a branch of Washington State
University, and a will to make the most of these assets. Gonzaga
and WSU will begin a joint program in computer engineering this
fall. Father Robert Spitzer, Gonzaga's president, says, ``We're
going to try to do the same thing in manufacturing engineering.''
</P>
<P>
   But he adds, ``We've got to have jobs that will attract very
bright students to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   One of DeVol's ideas is that Spokane build up a cluster of
test-and-measurement companies, some of which it already has. The
existing employers, however, are not interested in recruiting
rivals to hire away their workers, says Rich Hadley, president of
the Spokane Area Chamber of Commerce. Yet it is in the workers'
interest _ and the employers' long-run interest _ that other
companies come, wages get bid up, and workers learn the new
specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Spokane has tried more than parking garages. Partly because of
pressure from former House Speaker Tom Foley, The Boeing Co. opened
an operation in Spokane a decade ago. Others have opened offices in
Spokane. The problem, says John Stone, is ``they don't grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokane needs something that will grow, and that pays well.
Otherwise people will leave town or do their work out of town, as
Stone does. He just built a 155-unit mixed-use project, the Allegro
One and Two, in Seattle's University District. ``Seattle's the hot
market,'' he says. ``You go where the activity is.''
</P>
<P>
   He ponders his hometown. ``It needs to change here,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
