<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SOX WIN A WILD ONE
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-TORONTO-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By GORDON EDES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ This is how Butch Huskey, the hulking Red Sox newcomer
who uses up more bolts of cloth for one uniform than newly promoted
second baseman Donnie Sadler requires for his entire wardrobe,
sized up his new team, even before Tuesday night's 11-9
come-from-behind win against the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to fight, and I'm here to fight with 'em,'' said
the 6-foot-4-inch Huskey, who is built like an NBA small forward
but had three hits as DH in his Sox debut Tuesday night, including
a phantom home run that was ruled a single in the Sox' six-run
fifth inning. ``We're all in this together now.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskey, who took his place at the back of the Sox conga line to
exchange high-fives with his new teammates after the game, had no
reason to alter his view after the Sox rallied from a 7-3 deficit
to overtake the Blue Jays, who were nine games under .500 on June
12, but had won 29 of their next 39 games to overtake the Sox in
the AL wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit, we hit,'' he said after the Sox, playing their 100th
game of the season, pulled to within a half-game of the Blue Jays
in the wild-card pecking order by amassing 18 hits, including three
apiece by Darren Lewis and Nomar Garciaparra. ``They scored, we
scored. Coming to the end, there are going to be games like that.
Those are the ones that hopefully we're going to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that has the ability to scrap and fight. I saw,
even from the other side, that they have the players and the
chemistry to come back and win ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with reinforcements in Huskey and Sadler, who was Jimy
Williams's telling choice to start at second base instead of
All-Star Jose Offerman, this was hardly an optimum time for the Sox
to be engaged in a border skirmish with the Blue Jays, who had won
a league-leading 17 games this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, losers of four of their previous five games, also
seemed stuck in self-destruct mode, squandering a first-inning
rally when third-base coach Wendell Kim sent John Valentin on a
ridiculous dash to the plate with no outs, then blowing a 3-0 lead
in the bottom of the second, when the Blue Jays exploited a
throwing error by second baseman Sadler to score five runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying anything,'' Valentin said about being waved
home.
</P>
<P>
   When Willie Greene cranked a two-run home run off Bret
Saberhagen in the fourth inning to make it 7-3, the Blue Jays
appeared well on their way to their 10th win in the last 11 games,
much to the delight of a SkyDome crowd of 38,631 that was lined up
so deep at the ticket windows, the start of the game was delayed 12
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it appeared the Sox were about to yield more
ground to the Blue Jays in the wild-card sweepstakes, they showed
some of that gumption Huskey detected from a continent away,
playing in Seattle until his trade by the Mariners on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   They arose in the fifth inning to score six runs on seven hits
against Blue Jays starter David Wells, who ripped his jersey off in
frustration in the Blue Jays dugout, and reliever Roy Halladay.
They then added two runs in the eighth, which began with Troy
O'Leary's triple, assuaging fears of another comeback by the Blue
Jays, who since June 29 have won 10 games in their last at-bat, 16
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to come back and win a game like this,'' said
Saberhagen, who needed 43 pitches just to get through the second
inning but was picked up Tuesday night by a five-man relief effort
that held the Blue Jays to five hits and two runs (one unearned) in
the last 5 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice we showed a little character to come back and win a
game we probably should have lost,'' he added. ``A lot of people
are putting a lot of emphasis on this short two-game series, and if
we had lost tonight, that probably would have put a lot of pressure
on us to win tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not even August and there are a lot of games left, but we
just need to get things a little better. I couldn't find the groove
tonight, but there's no need to jump off a bridge. To spit the hook
and still win the game, that's beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskey played his part in the decisive fifth inning with an RBI
single that should have gone into the books as a three-run home
run, according to replays showing the ball striking a bar in the
bullpen, beyond the outfield wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the longest singles I've ever seen,'' said Williams.
``But what do we have here? I'm a guy who wears glasses just to
read.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskey certainly thought it was a homer, waving his index finger
in a circular motion that umpires use to signal a home run. But it
wasn't mirrored by third-base umpire Bill Welke, who instead gave
the ``safe'' sign, meaning the ball was still in play.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. The Sox, who had 14 hits in the first five
innings, including seven doubles, managed to clear the bases even
after Huskey was denied that privilege.
</P>
<P>
   An inning that began with a double by Garciaparra and singles by
Mike Stanley and Huskey continued with a two-run groundball double
by Troy O'Leary, a successful squeeze by Damon Buford, RBI doubles
by Jason Varitek and Valentin sandwiched around a walk by Lewis,
and an RBI single by Garciaparra, his second hit of the inning, one
in which 11 Sox batters paraded to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, turning suddenly cautious, elected not to wave home
Valentin on Garciaparra's hit _ a ground ball up the middle _ for
what would have been Boston's 10th run. Perhaps he was aware of the
way Valentin flung his helmet when he returned to the dugout in the
first inning, which began with Lewis's double and Valentin's
single. Garciaparra followed with a double that scored Lewis, but
Kim decided to try and have Valentin score on the play, too, even
with no outs.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto scored once in the sixth when All-Star outfielder Shawn
Green, who earlier extended his hitting streak to 25 games, was hit
with a pitch by Rheal Cormier with the bases loaded. But Cormier
then induced cleanup man Carlos Delgado to roll into a double play
(``biggest outs of the night,'' Williams said), then combined with
Derek Lowe to strike out the side in the seventh. Tim Wakefield
finished for his 13th save, with the win going to Mark Guthrie, his
first with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used six pitchers, nine other players, 15 players to help
you win a game,'' Williams said. ``From our standpoint, it's a good
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
