<SLUG> BC-GAMBLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY CASINO REVENUES ARE DOWN $3 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the temperature rose in June, Kansas City's riverboat
gamblers cooled off.
</P>
<P>
   Casino revenues slipped by nearly $3 million, to $39.3 million,
after record-setting months of $42 million-plus in March, April and
May, according to the latest reports by the Missouri Gaming
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Harrah's North Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel led the
local marketplace, posting a $14.1 million month. Harrah's also
wrapped up Missouri's 1999 fiscal year on June 30 as the statewide
overall market leader, with a record $169 million year.
</P>
<P>
   Station Casino Kansas City last September surpassed Harrah's as
Kansas City's market leader, but after one month slipped back to
second place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I like being in second place? No,'' said John Finamore,
Station vice president and general manager. ``We're still learning
what works best here and what our guests respond to.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that Station's corporate strategy for the near
term was paying down debt. That means fewer giveaways, especially
cash coupons that bring in the foot traffic, but at a steep cost to
the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have responsibilities to our shareholders,' Finamore said.
``We're very focused on the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's General Manager Michael St. Pierre could not be reached
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When Sam's Town casino in Kansas City closed a year ago, Station
and Flamingo Hilton Casino grabbed the lion's share of Sam's
customers. Since then, the marketplace has stabilized, with
Harrah's and Argosy Riverside Casino posting modest gains.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Kansas City casino market expanded by about 8.5
percent from the 1998 fiscal year, to $475 million from $438
million.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same story statewide, only more so, with annual
growth of 11.9 percent to $898 million from $803 million a year
ago. Kansas City's four casino operations represented almost 53
percent of the statewide total, a slight drop from 55 percent a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Taylor, executive director of the statewide anti-gambling
lobby Casino Watch, laments the growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are now spending more annually on gambling than they
do on groceries,'' he said, quoting a congressional study on the
effects of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that along with the increase in revenue is an
increase in compulsive gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   While Harrah's paced all local and state competitors for the
past 12 months, it did so while drawing fewer customers _ 6.5
million compared with 7.3 million a year ago. The difference is
those gamblers, on the average, are wagering and losing more this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The average Harrah's gambler left behind $25.93 per two-hour
visit over the past 12 months. The figure a year ago was $23.47.
Statewide, the average is $22.02.
</P>
<P>
   Station draws more visitors than Harrah's by virtue of more
restaurants, bars, theaters and other nongambling attractions. But
those visitors gamble less, averaging about $20.67 per two-hour
cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's wasn't alone in entertaining fewer visitors the past 12
months. Overall attendance slipped in the Kansas City market, to
21.4 million from 22.1 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That number could rebound, however, if the Missouri Gaming
Commission eliminates its restrictions on boarding times and allows
open boarding later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaming Commission was scheduled to meet today in Jefferson
City to discuss whether to approve an open-boarding pilot project
this summer that could be in place within a month, probably in the
St. Louis market and aboard the Admiral riverboat.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators last year devised a pilot project as a way to
ease into round-the-clock gambling on weekends, which now is the
rule statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Casino Watch's Taylor said his group objected to the
pilot-project approach. He said the Gaming Commission ought to wait
for the Missouri General Assembly to approve such a fundamental
change in the state's casino environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gaming Commission should be enforcing laws, not making
public policy,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The change does not require legislative action. Commission
officials have said the boarding-times rule was enacted as a way to
equalize competition in the St. Louis area, which has had the
permanently docked Admiral riverboat in operation since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Casino patronage statewide was up slightly during the past 12
months, with 40.8 million two-hour cruise visits, compared with
39.5 million in fiscal year 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ryan, executive director of the Missouri Riverboat Gaming
Association, said the revenue growth meant ``$162 million (in
gaming taxes) that will go to education. That's $17 million more
than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Argosy Riverside Casino maintained the local market's
``loosest slots'' title, again posting the highest electronic-games
jackpot payoffs to players in the most popular denominations _
nickels, quarters and dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
