<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVERSIDE HAS NEW POST OFFICE, BUT NOT ZIP CODE THEY WANTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ZIP is gone from the joy Riverside officials felt when the
city's first full-service post office opened this month.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, Riverside paid the $2 million building tab
to get better mail service. But what officials sought and prized
most _ the city's own ZIP code instead of sharing those issued for
Kansas City neighborhoods _ is still an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Two ZIPs once shared by Riverside and Kansas City were
consolidated into one 64150 code for mail delivery within
Riverside. That ZIP had served much of Riverside, and the U.S.
Postal Service now considers it the city's own ZIP.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent notice from the Postal Service told patrons they
could use either Riverside or Kansas City as their home city in
mailing addresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they need to do now is write us a check for $2 million,''
said Mayor Ed Rule. ``We wasted our time and money if we didn't get
our own ZIP code.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's disappointment surprised U.S. Postal Service
officials in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a shared ZIP, and I believe they understood that
when it started,'' said Jim Herrmann, operations and project
support manager.
</P>
<P>
   The ZIP is shared in that Riverside has a branch of the Kansas
City post office, not its own post office with a postmaster.
</P>
<P>
   But Rule said Riverside thought it was getting its own post
office and ZIP.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very unhappy,'' Rule said. ``It's the only reason we
built it, to get our own ZIP code.''
</P>
<P>
   One fear of Riverside officials is that residents and businesses
will give a Kansas City address and Riverside will lose tax
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   That is valid, says Pat Gifford, manager of sales and use taxes
for the Missouri Department of Revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem statewide and nationwide, especially with use
taxes,'' Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
   The department shares its list of business taxpayers with cities
so officials can check to see whether any businesses are missing,
but problems can still arise.
</P>
<P>
   A city's share of sales tax from an automobile purchase, based
on the buyer's residency, may go to the wrong coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a (Riverside) person says they're from Kansas City, we
might not have any reason to question that,'' Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban cities losing use taxes from purchases made over the
Internet or through mail order catalogues is a growing problem.
</P>
<P>
   If a Riverside resident or business purchases merchandise
through the Internet and gives a mailing address as Kansas City,
Gifford said, Kansas City would get the tax money.
</P>
<P>
   Rule said Riverside had never done an audit to determine the
extent of its tax losses, if any. Officials are concerned, though,
because the city has no property tax for operating costs, only a
sales tax. Also, a new flood levee nearing construction is expected
to bring more commercial businesses operating regionally and
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   But pride also is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   When Rule last renewed his driver's license, he turned one in
that said he was from Riverside. He got a new one that said he was
from Kansas City _ because of the ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   Other residents have faced similar situations, like having to
get proof from City Hall that they lived in Riverside and weren't
trying to avoid Kansas City taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann said the Postal Service has changed its computer system
so the 64150 ZIP shows not only Kansas City but also Riverside and
indicates that Riverside is the preferred address.
</P>
<P>
   The first three ZIP numbers, 641, signify the Kansas City Post
Office. To have its own code, Riverside needs a ZIP that begins
with 640.
</P>
<P>
   So why not give them a 640 code?
</P>
<P>
   The assigned 641 ZIP was a directive from postal officials in
Washington and St. Louis, Herrmann said. And the trend is to
consolidate services rather than expand.
</P>
<P>
   Washington officials say the Postal Service has met its
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The 64150 boundary matches Riverside's municipal boundary, said
Jackie Estes, an operations specialist in Washington who met with
city officials when the idea was proposed. The Postal Service
delivers mail but isn't responsible for other entities adopting ZIP
codes for uses they weren't designed for, such as sorting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard or seen anything yet that somebody promised
something that wasn't delivered,'' Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   Riverside's initial request in 1997 for a new post office and
its own ZIP code was denied by the Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   So city officials rallied congressional support and in 1998
traveled to Washington. They offered to spend riverboat gambling
revenue to build a post office in exchange for full service and a
single ZIP code. This time the Postal Service agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann said the agreement from the beginning was for a shared
ZIP. A survey of postal patrons in April 1998 as planning for the
post office began stated that addresses could be Kansas City or
Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe when we sit down and talk about this, we'll remedy
this,'' Herrmann said. ``Hopefully, they'll remember some of the
discussions they had.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rule said he was told the Kansas City reference in the
survey was intended for patrons living outside of Riverside, not
Riverside residents.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and City Attorney Steve Crystal say Riverside's
contract with the Postal Service calls for the city to have its own
ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   After accepting use of the building, the contract says, ``the
Postal Service will grant to the City of Riverside their own
designated Riverside, Missouri Zip Code Delivery number for this
newly constructed postal facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Rule believes that makes it clear that Kansas City shouldn't be
acceptable in a Riverside address.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll talk, but we don't have much to say,'' Rule said. ``We
have an agreement, and we'll take whatever steps we need to enforce
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
