<P>
   CALIF-DANGEROUS-SCHOOL (Los Angeles) _ It looms on a lonely lot
at the edge of downtown, a hulking pile of buff brick and brown
stone, like some half-finished temple or Pharaoh's tomb. It would
be the most expensive public high school ever built in the nation,
at a cost of more than $200 million, but now the Belmont Learning
Center may never be finished _ and if it is, no one may want to go
to school there. The school was built atop an abandoned oil field,
despite repeated red flags and warnings, and officials now say
there may be no way to vent away seeping methane gas and other
hazards to make it safe enough to occupy. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-CAMPAIGN (Chicago) _ In an interview, Jesse Jackson says
he hopes he can still have influence in the presidential campaign
without being a candidate. He says he likes Gore and Bradley,
although he feels closer to Gore. Having both in the race could
lead to a debate over issues he's interested in _ workers rights,
health care, school financing. He's withholding his endorsement
until a date uncertain. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
