<HEADER>
A6389 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIPELINE-SPI &LR;      07-28 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NTSB HEAD ASSAILS PIPELINE AGENCY FOR `DISMAL' SAFETY RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal agency responsible for protecting the
public from pipeline accidents is a failure, the government's top
safety official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board Chairman James Hall blasted
the Office of Pipeline Safety for disregarding not only safety
recommendations from his agency, but also requirements imposed by
Congress. He said some pipeline accidents in recent years,
including the deadly explosion in Bellingham, Wash., last month,
could have been prevented if the federal government had heeded the
safety board's advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their mission statement, they say their mission is to
protect the American people and the environment,'' Hall said.
``They have failed in that mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said that the pipeline agency has not followed a
29-year-old recommendation to require the installation of automated
valves to speed the shutdown of leaking pipelines, a 12-year-old
recommendation for a requirement for regular inspections of
pipeline integrity and a 12-year-old recommendation for improved
pipeline personnel training.
</P>
<P>
   He called the agency's inaction ``unacceptable,'' described the
rules the agency has adopted as ``too little, too late,'' and
concluded by saying ``this dismal record has continued far too long
and it needs to be addressed immediately and more aggressive action
has got to be taken if we are going to protect public safety and
our environment in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The blistering criticism from Hall came during a congressional
hearing on the renewal of pipeline-safety laws, which expire next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the transportation subcommittee holding the
hearing, Rep. Bob Franks, R-N.J., described himself as ``very
troubled'' by Hall's criticism of the Office of Pipeline Safety. He
pledged to hold a separate hearing on the Bellingham accident and
said he will not cooperate with efforts by friends of the oil and
gas industry to rush renewal of the pipeline safety laws through
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Office of Pipeline Safety) have clearly had a
grossly unacceptable record of adopting regulations,'' Franks said.
``That's very troubling to me, particularly in areas as critical as
operator training and automatic shutoff valves. ... There will be
steps taken, in view of today's hearing, to put direct pressure on
(the Office of Pipeline Safety) to move toward adopting
comprehensive training and automatic shutoff valve regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was officially about the arcana of pipeline safety
laws, but it was overshadowed by the specter of the horrific
explosion in Bellingham, which killed two boys and a teenager. With
a photograph of the giant tower of smoke rising over Bellingham on
June 10 resting on a nearby easel, every congressman who spoke
expressed sorrow over the Bellingham incident, as did officials
from the industry, the National Transportation Safety Board and the
Office of Pipeline Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The families in your district have borne a tragedy that no
family should have to endure, and I hope that you will let them
know and convey to them the seriousness of this subcommittee in
seeing that those young people did not die in vain,'' the ranking
Democrat on the committee, Rep. Robert Wise, D-W.Va., said to the
congressman who represents Bellingham, Rep. Jack Metcalf, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf, the first witness to testify, laid out in painstaking
detail the events of June 10: how a pipeline ruptured and spilled
so much gasoline into Whatcom Creek that the water level rose
several feet; how two young boys playing with bottle rockets in a
nearby park accidentally ignited the liquid gasoline, setting off
an explosion that incinerated them and an 18-year-old
fly-fisherman; how a fireball then raced as much as 1.5 miles down
the creek, killing everything in the water and as much as 200 feet
on either side of the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret the difficult circumstances which brought me here
today,'' Metcalf said. He went on to warn that although underground
pipelines criss-cross the nation, ``there are precious few people
who possess a thorough knowledge of the industry,'' and said that
in his own study of what went wrong in Bellingham, ``my discussions
regarding the Office of Pipeline Safety have been the most
troubling of all.''
</P>
<P>
   The administrator of the Office of Pipeline Safety, Kelley
Coyner, said she is willing to entertain the legislative
recommendations of members of the Washington state congressional
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragic consequence of pipeline incidents such as
Bellingham underscore the need for all of us to have unremitting
attention to the impact of pipeline transportation on people's
lives,'' Coyner said.
</P>
<P>
   Coyner said she is committed to eliminating all deaths from
pipeline accidents, and said that she is particularly concerned
that as the number of incidents has declined, the number of
fatalities has risen, particularly in accidents involving gas
distribution systems. (Environmental groups disagree that the
number of incidents is declining, and the gas industry disagrees
that the number of fatalities is rising.)
</P>
<P>
   Coyner defended her agency's handling of safety recommendations,
saying that sometimes her agency has simply disagreed with the
safety board, while at other times the recommendations require
complex regulations that take time to develop.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, utility executives defended the performance of
the Office of Pipeline Safety, and said the nation's pipeline
safety laws do not need to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bellingham disaster does not represent anything close to
the norm in our industry, and it should not precipitate drastic
changes in public policy,'' said Steven Ball, a pipeline industry
executive who represented the Association of Oil Pipelines and the
American Petroleum Institute. ``Bellingham notwithstanding, oil
pipelines are safe and are getting safer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
