<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA EYES DREIFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Arizona Diamondbacks are concerned that
pitcher Todd Stottlemyre, on the disabled since May after
undergoing shoulder surgery, might not be healthy enough for the
stretch drive and are interested in obtaining Dodgers right-hander
Darren Dreifort, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort has pitched twice against the Diamondbacks this season
and been impressive both times, and it's becoming more apparent the
only way the Dodgers will be able to make a major move before
Saturday's trading deadline is to include one of their starting
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   It's uncommon for teams to make a deal within the division,
especially one that can come back to haunt them. But general
manager Kevin Malone said he would deal within the NL West if he
had to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would prefer not to, but if you could make yourself
better and improve your club, you have to consider it,'' said
Malone, speaking of no deal in particular. ``I think it would just
have to be the best option for the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Dodgers played Cincinnati on Tuesday, manager Davey
Johnson said the organization might move one of the pitchers for
the right price. Sources said Arizona would be willing to move
lefty Brian Anderson, who pitched eight shutout innings against the
Dodgers on Saturday, but they would be stuck if the Dodgers insist
on Double-A pitcher John Patterson being in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to give up pitchers, especially when you talk
about the talent of (Ismael) Valdes, (Chan Ho) Park and Dreifort,''
Johnson said. ``I'm not in favor of doing anything that would make
us weaker, unless I'm extremely confident it would make us stronger
today, tomorrow, in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort is 8-9 with a 5.68 ERA, and his inconsistency has
management frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the interest regarding a Dodgers starter surrounds
Valdes, who is 8-8 with a 3.33 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Malone and Cincinnati general manager Jim Bowden talked before
the game about the Reds acquiring Valdes, but the Dodgers want
either reliever Scott Williamson or Danny Graves and a prospect,
sources said. The Reds, who use a bullpen by committee, are
reluctant to deal one of their key relievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you trade one of your best pitchers?'' Johnson said in
regards to Valdes. ``Only if those players (acquired) will be an
immediate help to the ballclub next year. They have to be close.
Double-A, Triple-A.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring training update: The Fort McDowell Indian Community's
proposed $40million spring training complex near Phoenix is being
reviewed by the Dodgers, and the biggest obstacle isn't the
physical layout but the revenue split.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers director of business development Fred Coons said terms
need to be worked out with money brought in from parking, tickets
and concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many different variables,'' Coons said. ``We
obviously are working diligently and haven't given up hope, but
there's so many issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort McDowell's plan doesn't include the on-site housing the
Dodgers wanted, but it does include six practice fields and the
stadium. Fort McDowell wants an answer from the Dodgers within the
next few weeks, or it will begin looking for other teams to lure to
the complex.
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Todd Hollandsworth started in right field in place of Raul
Mondesi, whose average has dropped to .241.... Craig Counsell got
his first start at second since Eric Young was benched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
