<SLUG> BC-COPPER-RIVER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED ROAD FOR COPPER RIVER DELTA HAS ENVIRONMENTALISTS AGHAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORDOVA, Alaska _ The Copper River, renowned for succulent
salmon that create an annual frenzy in Seattle-area restaurants and
markets, is home to Alaska's fiercest environmental battle _ one
that some believe could count salmon among its casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The latest skirmish over the big muddy river, which enters the
Gulf of Alaska 150 miles southeast of Anchorage, will be fought
Wednesday at a House hearing in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Copper River is known not only for its first-of-the season
fishery, but for its 700,000-acre delta. It is North America's
largest wetland, visited annually by 16 million seabirds and home
to the continent's largest populations of beavers and otters.
</P>
<P>
   But the delta also is an impediment to logging some 8,000 acres
of timber owned by the Chugach Alaska Corp. The native-owned
corporation wants to build a road through the wild eastern reaches
of the Copper River Delta to log forests at a site called Carbon
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   They claim the land and the salmon would be protected.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are aghast.
</P>
<P>
   Concern for the environment
</P>
<P>
   The road would cross 27 miles of Chugach National Forest land
and traverse what Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman calls ``an
extraordinarily environmentally sensitive area managed for wildlife
and fish.'' The region was put into the national forest system 90
years ago by President Theodore Roosevelt to prevent such
exploitation as logging and mining.
</P>
<P>
   The project would ``change the entire character'' of the Copper
River Delta, said Dune Lankard, a Cordova native and Chugach Alaska
Corp. shareholder. Lankard will testify in Washington, D.C., on
Wednesday on behalf of opponents ranging from the Eyak Tribal
Elders Council to the National Wildlife Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the eastern part of the delta is totally wild. You
really have to want to get there. ... A heavily used logging road
would inevitably impair wildlife and aesthetic values and could
even threaten the Copper River salmon fishery,'' said Lankard, who
fishes the delta and was named last year a ``Hero for the Planet''
by Time magazine for his environmental activism.
</P>
<P>
   The Copper River Salmon Producers Association argued in a letter
to Congress that the proposed road ``may irreversibly damage'' the
delta and possibly its fishery.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation took ownership of the land it wants to log under
the provisions of the 1971 Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act, in
which native corporations were given some of the state's richest
timberlands, most previously part of the Chugach and Tongass
national forests.
</P>
<P>
   Some cash-strapped native corporations allowed their forests to
be clearcut, often with huge volumes of slash left on the ground
and without replanting. Stream protection has been ignored in road
building.
</P>
<P>
   Sheri Buretta, new chairwoman of Chugach Alaska, insists her
corporation is different. ``In areas we have cut, we have
replanted,'' she said. ``We care very much about the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters make their case
</P>
<P>
   The Chugach Alaska Corp. denies that it would do anything to
endanger salmon runs, which are fished by many of its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``To suggest our road is going to keep salmon off (the) plates
of people in Seattle is ludicrous,'' said Rick Rogers, the
corporation's manager of lands and resources.
</P>
<P>
   Chugach Alaska attorney Peter Giannini said the corporation has
picked a route that mitigates environmental impacts ``to the
fullest extent possible'' and that ``moves around the wetlands.''
</P>
<P>
   The road is championed by Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, chairman of
the House Resources Committee. Young has introduced legislation to
order the Forest Service to grant the Chugach Alaska Corp. a
road-building easement across national forest land.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration opposes the legislation, and Rep. Jay
Inslee, D-Wash., a member of the Resources Committee, has concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting a swath through the world's largest wetland, in a
river system famous for its salmon, gives me concern,'' Inslee
said. ``I would be very reluctant for Congress to step in and give
orders to the Forest Service.''
</P>
<P>
   Young charges the administration with ``animus toward property
owners in Alaska's national forests.'' He argues that enough
forests have already been ``locked up'' in the Chugach and Tongass
national forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we denying the employment of Alaskans and the survival
of towns when we already have the trees set aside?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   On the Copper River itself, the major resource at issue is not
trees, but the river's prized salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   The pink salmon and herring fisheries of nearby Prince William
Sound have endured periods of steep decline since the 1989 Exxon
Valdez oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   Copper River salmon are the economic lifeblood of the town of
Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   Renowned for their oil content and rich flavor, Copper River
kings have become a celebrity of the salmon world. Television
stations film the race to get the fish into Seattle markets each
May.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon are also cherished by Alaskans. Upriver, a narrow
road gives access to the Copper River as it plunges through Wood
Canyon south of the hamlet of Chitina. On spring and early summer
weekends, all accessible spots on the river's west bank are
occupied by fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   A proposed alternative
</P>
<P>
   The National Wildlife Federation recently commissioned a study
by the Oregon-based consulting firm of ECONorthwest on the
economics of the proposed road and logging. It concluded that the
logging was unlikely to be profitable and that Chugach Alaska Corp.
might lose a substantial amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders in the corporation would get a much greater return
on their money if they give up attempts at logging and negotiate a
conservation easement with the federal government, said Tony
Turrini, director of the Alaska office of the National Wildlife
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   An easement would allow the native corporation to retain title
to the land, but it would give up development rights in exchange
for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   A model for sale of development rights exists in Prince William
Sound, just west of the Copper River Delta.
</P>
<P>
   The Exxon Corp. agreed to a $900 million settlement and $125
million fine for environmental damage done to Prince William Sound
by its 1989 oil spill. The money was put under management of a
committee of federal and state trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past eight years, the trustees have used the money to
purchase conservation easements on more than 650,000 acres of
native-owned land on Kodiak and Afognak islands, and in Prince
William Sound. The result has been a $380 million windfall to
native village corporations _ and major tracts of salmon habitat
spared from logging.
</P>
<P>
   The conservation acquisitions have been opposed by Alaska's
pro-development congressional delegation. Under pressure, trustees
have earmarked most of the remaining Exxon money for scientific
research.
</P>
<P>
   Young's bill would give the Chugach Alaska Corp. the right to
reclaim burial sites and historically important lands that it says
were ```inappropriately acquired'' by the spill trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Lankard, the Chugach Alaska shareholder who opposes the road
project, scoffs at the provision. He points out that in 1992 a
native corporation clearcut Eyak Indian village and burial sites
near Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironically, these culturally sensitive lands have more
protection now then when they were owned by the village
corporations,'' he says in testimony prepared for Wednesday's
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Chugach Alaska Corp. will not consider alternatives until it
is granted an easement for the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``No discussions of any kind are possible without the road
easement,'' said Giannini, the corporation's lawyer. ``Without the
road easement, the land has no value.''
</P>
<P>
   A 100-year war
</P>
<P>
   The Copper River may qualify as America's longest environmental
battle. The fight over its resources rolls on 90 years after
Roosevelt put the delta into America's second-largest national
forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theodore Roosevelt's legacy is unfinished,'' said Turrini of
the National Wildlife Federation. ``He attempted to protect one of
the world's great places. So far, we have been unsuccessful in
finishing the job. Nearly 100 years later, we are fighting the same
battles.''
</P>
<P>
   A different view comes from Buretta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy Roosevelt identified this land as pristine and pure,''
she said. ``All that is fine. Look at all the national parks that
the conservationists have succeeded in creating in Alaska. What we
want is to achieve the rights to our lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``To cast judgment on what we do with that land, before we have
done anything, is unfair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
