<SLUG> BC-HOMICIDE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE MAKE ARREST IN TRIPLE SLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VANESSA HO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Last month, Melvin Johnson Jr. attended a mournful
triple funeral for his family: Someone had killed his sister, niece
and 6-year-old grand-niece in their Mount Baker day care home, and
the killer was on the loose.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out Johnson himself was the likely suspect,
according to Seattle police. On Wednesday, a King County judge
ordered him held for investigation of the homicides on a hefty $3
million cash-only bail.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 29, has not been charged in the slayings. King County
Prosecutor's spokesman Dan Donohoe said a decision about whether to
charge the suspect will be made Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the June 8 slayings, homicide detectives believed a
family member killed 50-year-old Patricia Whitfield, a popular day
care provider, her daughter, Artis ``T.Z.'' Ingram, 24, and her
granddaughter Champagne Younger, 6.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives had received a crush of anonymous tips from people
claiming to be relatives accusing other family members of the
killings. But for weeks, detectives didn't have enough information
to make an arrest, and the unsolved slayings permeated relatives
and neighbors with uneasiness.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, relatives and neighbors viewed the arrest, which
occurred Monday for an unrelated crime, with a mix of melancholy
and comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief,'' said a nephew who didn't want to be named.
``At last, we're going to get justice. But it hurts more knowing
that it was `Mellie.' You hate for it to be a family member, but it
wasn't right, and a baby, who didn't even know right from wrong,
was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the killings and arrest have been agonizing for his
large, extended family. Many had suspected Johnson, who had fought
with Whitfield over money and her handling of the house owned by
their mother, who died in 1996. The nephew said Johnson felt
``deceived'' by Whitfield regarding the house, and that despite his
attendance at the funeral, he had been uncharacteristically aloof
after the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last two months, it's been tough,'' the nephew said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle police spokeswoman Pam McCammon would not comment on a
motive, circumstance of arrest, or even the location where Johnson
was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was a teenager, Johnson has seen his share of jail.
When he was 13, he pleaded guilty to attempted rape, in which he
used a knife, according to court records. He has since racked up
numerous convictions for assaults, thefts and drug charges in three
counties.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he and Whitfield entered an Alford plea to a charge of
attempted malicious harassment, in which prosecutors accused them
of harassing an interracial couple in the Central District. The
couple wasn't assaulted, but police were called. People entering an
Aflord plea do not admit wrongdoing, but tell the court they are
pleading guilty because they believe there is a substantial
likelihood they would be found guilty at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Johnson was charged with forgery, in which
prosecutors say he forged a $9,000 check to buy a sports car.
</P>
<P>
   The killings shocked the quiet, close-knit neighborhood, where
Whitfield's day care was known as a safe, loving hangout for
children.
</P>
<P>
   The killer had shot the victims overnight. The next morning,
four young children entered the unlocked house, and for about an
hour before going to school, they played near the bodies. Later,
they told police they thought the victims were sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   About six hours later , a relative discovered the bodies, along
with another disturbing find: Ingram's two youngest daughters,
Chandelier Gaines, 1 week old, and Chabrowe Gaines, 11 months, had
been in the house during the slayings. They were unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Whitfield's day care home appeared deserted, with
its unmowed lawn, unused toys and missing day care sign. Neighbors
who remembered her as a caring mother said the arrest brought
closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely makes me feel better,'' said Sirelle Wilkerson,
a neighbor living next to Whitfield's house in the 3200 block of
34th Avenue South.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Elaine Porterfield
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
