<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN'S WORLD IS JUST FINE, HE SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Michael Irvin showed up at training camp
Tuesday to work and talk. He held nothing back in either case. His
messages were a mixed bag: He isn't selfish. He isn't feeling any
disrespect. And he isn't going anywhere, not this season.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who understands more than anybody the power of
perception, finished an unsupervised morning workout with
quarterback Troy Aikman and receiver Raghib Ismail on a field
adjacent to where Dallas Cowboys rookies and selected veterans
opened two-a-days at Midwestern State University. Then he spoke his
mind on the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin was asked about San Francisco 49ers wide receiver Jerry
Rice's recent comments about being inspired by San Antonio Spurs
center David Robinson, who proclaimed on his way to a first NBA
title that he was willing to take a secondary role at this stage of
his career in order to win a world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Public perception seems to favor Rice for being touched by
Robinson's ability to come to grips with his new role on a team
featuring Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Could something similar come out of Irvin's mouth to
improve his public perception in light of off-season issues that
included him being mentioned in trade talks and possibly taking on
a reduced role in the team's offense?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: We'll never know. ``I don't have to say that,'' Irvin
said of Rice's feel-good reaction to Robinson's feel-good comment.
``Maybe Jerry has done some things in the past that seem very
selfish now, and he has to vindicate himself. I don't feel the same
way about myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been the biggest team player. I've taken less money to
stay here. Everybody knows that I want to do whatever it takes to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I need to say that David Robinson (inspired me)
because by me saying that, I would be saying that I was selfish
when we were winning. And I wasn't that. I think Jerry has come out
and yelled after (the 49ers) won games in which he had only six
catches and somebody else had nine. I catch no balls and we win ...
am I happy with it? No. Do I make a fuss about it? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, 33, will make $2.99 million base salary in the final year
of his contract. In coach Chan Gailey's system, the ball will be
thrown to where the opponents' defense is weakest, not necessarily
to the best receiver on the field. Somebody who has been called
``The Playmaker'' for most of his 11 seasons with the Cowboys might
have some problem with that.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin said Tuesday that he can live with any gameplan that wins
games for the Cowboys. And he said a lot more about many of the
issues that have made him a topic of conversation in and around
Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin on Gailey's plan to reducing the 33-year-old receiver's
workload without ``changing'' his role:
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan says he's going to try to keep us (older veterans) fresh,
and that's all well and good. But the game will dictate what's
really going to happen. Hopefully, everything works out and we
stick to a plan, but we also have to be smart enough to adjust to
what happens on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin on not having a contract extension:
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, guys, and I don't want this to sound bad, but
financially I'm in seventh heaven. If you guys really think about
where I come from ... quite honestly, I deserve whatever this
franchise sees fit to give me. I'm going to say this again, I have
never barked about needing a long-term deal. I have never, ever
said, in any way, that I felt disrespected. Jerry Jones is a
businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin on comments by former Cowboys coach Jimmy Johnson that
Irvin is overpriced at $2.99 million for his production at this
point in his career, and that there is no interest in adding Irvin
to the Dolphins:
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy hears that I want out, or whatever you guys reported, so
Jimmy comes out and says those things. All Jimmy is doing is trying
to pull down my value. If I get released, I guarantee you Jimmy is
going to be in line trying to sign me. I've been around long to
understand the business side of football.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin on what the chances are that he won't be with the Cowboys
this season:
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on. Where am I going to be? I hope this doesn't sound
arrogant, and it may. I've never needed anybody to tell me that I
can play. I've always known I could play.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin on conversations with Gailey:
</P>
<P>
   ``Every (NFL) team in the Final Four last year had two
1,000-yard receivers. I don't know, but maybe that says you need to
use the pass more than the run, maybe that's the trend now. Chan
said, `Yes, I've thought about that same thing exactly.' These are
the kind of conversations we have... It is never confrontational.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Tuesday afternoon, Irvin ran a few more routes. Between
working and talking, it seemed to be a full day. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
