</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIPS MISSED THE CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While Richie Phillips was leading the charge, the
rest of the world was yawning.
</P>
<P>
   While he was railing about the decline of civilization through
the eyes of a baseball union chief, Phillips failed to realize that
nobody cared _ not the fans, not the players, not even his own
people.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, after two weeks of cracking from within, the umpires
told baseball they have decided to rescind the mass resignations
Phillips had planned for Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a good thing? A bad thing? It's nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Phillips' bombast rippled though the sport
because the announcement came the day after the All-Star Game and
there wasn't much going on. Labor lawyers were brought in to
explain Phillips' strategy of mass resignations in an effort to
force baseball to take them seriously. More people wondered, ``Just
how fat is Eric Gregg?''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips failed to realize he wasn't representing players, the
only true commodities in the game. Most of the umpires liked him
because of his arrogance, especially the National League guys, who
used to visit when they came through his native Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   In a profession in which presence is almost as important as
calling balls and strikes, he epitomized authority. Phillips had
gotten the umpires a good deal in the last contract, with better
pay, great benefits and in-season vacations. They just didn't feel
loved. Sounds like most of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still behind him,'' said Dana DeMuth, the crew chief
for the Cincinnati Reds/Dodgers series. ``This is not a reflection
on him, just some weakness in our ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   As the last two weeks proved, that is not exactly true. The
American League umpires knew they wouldn't have much leverage when
the old agreement expired in December. They also knew that they
couldn't walk out because there is a no-strike clause in the
existing contract.
</P>
<P>
   Their concern was forfeiting the $15 million in severance they
are due. The umpires thought a strike would void their contract and
void everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips made the umpires believe they were bound by law to get
the $15 million now. Baseball would see how much they were needed,
especially during the postseason when everyone is watching.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pipe dream.
</P>
<P>
   To some, Phillips looked stronger when minor-league umpires, who
do not have a union of their own, said they would not work if the
big guys resigned. But that movement quickly fizzled when they
realized that nobody cared.
</P>
<P>
   For months, commissioner Bud Selig had his own pit bull, Sandy
Alderson, figuring out a contingency plan. High school and college
umpires looked pretty good to him.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the biggest issue was control. Baseball wanted to put
umpires under their umbrella. Umpires wanted to govern themselves.
They didn't want the commissioner's office to tell them when an
umpire was getting too old or out of shape to remain sharp.
</P>
<P>
   The union wanted to protect its own. Baseball wanted to hire and
fire based on a merit system. The union thought seniority had to
count for something. In that regard it was a classic
union/management showdown, but this never was going to be the
Teamsters sticking up for the United Auto Workers.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been nice if the Major League Players Association
had become part of the debate. The players crush the owners every
time there is a labor dispute. After each settlement, they talk
about having a greater say in the day-to-day operation of baseball.
They could have sided with the umpires, using the integrity of the
game as a platform.
</P>
<P>
   The players have gotten rich as a result of their union's power
and the owner's lack of solidarity. But the players never had any
intention of getting involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't expect them to,'' AL umpire Dale Scott said. ``They
would only come in after the replacement umps were in there and say
how much this was hurting the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners wanted to break the union, that is no secret.
Baseball is wrong to think trained seals could do the job.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the union filed a suit against baseball, claiming it
was not bargaining in good faith on a new contract. It is right and
probably will win that suit.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad that 20 umpires are expected to lose their jobs as a
result of Phillips' strutting, but they probably would have been
out anyway during the next collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Now Phillips will be gone, too. And no one will care. He was too
arrogant thinking that The Show could not go on without him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Sports Editor Matt McHale covers baseball for the Daily
News. He can be reached at (800) 777-4953 or mch013aol.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
