<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-VARGAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCER AT CENTER OF VARGAS CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The incident that led to the arrest of boxer
Fernando Vargas of Oxnard on Sunday started when he was confronted
by the ex-boyfriend of a dancer he met at a Santa Barbara strip
club, according to police and reports.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, who was arrested with four companions in the early
morning hours for investigation of assault with a deadly weapon,
met the woman at the Spearmint Rhino, where the ex-boyfriend works
as a bouncer.
</P>
<P>
   The dancer _ whose name is being withheld by police _ invited
Vargas to the Summerland home she shares with another dancer at the
club, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-boyfriend, identified on Tuesday as 21-year-old Anthony
Arria of Santa Barbara, arrived unannounced _ and uninvited,
according to police _ at the home at about 4 a.m. and an argument
quickly escalated into a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Vargas was in the home by invitation, Mr. Arria was not.
There was some confusion about that (on Monday),'' Santa Barbara
County sheriff's Sgt. Bill Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   The fight was broken up by 23-year-old Doug Rossi, who was with
the other woman at the time and had let Arria into the house,
according to police. Afterward, Arria left.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, four of Vargas' companions arrived and beat up
Rossi with unidentified weapons, although police found golf clubs
in the house during their ongoing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The five then left in Vargas' Lexus sports-utility vehicle and
were stopped on the Ventura Freeway by police, who were tipped off
by the woman, and later arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Police had not determined whether Vargas took part in the
beating of Rossi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't specifically identified Vargas in the group that
attacked Mr. Rossi, but we haven't ruled him out, either,'' Turner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Arria nor Rossi have been arrested, Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas' representatives insist he will be vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be pretty obvious to everyone,'' said Shelly Finkel,
Vargas' co-manager.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, 21, and his friends reportedly had frequented the club
about once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he's not well liked by management. Gary Grantham, a
manager at Spearmint Rhino, told the Santa Barbara News-Press that
Vargas has hassled the bouncers and has a ``smart mouth.'' A
spokesman for Spearmint Rhino refused to comment further on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, the IBF junior middleweight champion, recently signed an
endorsement contract with Miller Brewing Company. Miller indicated
in a statement that it's too early to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, until all involved have had the opportunity to
be heard by the legal system, it would be inappropriate for us to
comment further,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested with Vargas were Ernesto Vargas, 27; Vincent Arenas,
20; Carlos Alberto Lopez, 28; and Freddie Flores, 21. All are from
Oxnard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
