<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' TOP TWO DRAFT PICKS ARRIVE IN CAMP AFTER SIGNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys defensive end Ebenezer
Ekuban was hardly the freshest player on the field for the first
day of training-camp workouts Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who reached contract agreement with Ekuban late
Monday and second-round pick Solomon Page last night, were hardly
worried.
</P>
<P>
   Not after Ekuban's wild night. Cowboys owner Jerry Jones'
private jet picked him up in Maryland at 1:45 a.m. and got him to
Midwestern State University at 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly three hours later Ekuban was up and preparing to go on
the field with his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to hold out due to my lack of experience,'' the
former North Carolina standout said. ``I told my agent I didn't
want to haggle over little things. When they told me a plane was on
the way, I had to hurry up and pack. I forgot a couple of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a five-year, $5,625,000 contract, Ekuban should have
no trouble replacing what he forgot.
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban's deal calls for him to make base salaries of $280,000,
$350,000, $420,000, $420,000, $490,000 and $560,000 the next five
years. It does not include any performance incentives, but Cowboys
vice president Stephen Jones said the team will reward Ekuban for
superior performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he becomes a great player and fits in with this team, he
probably won't every see the end of his contract,'' Jones said.
``We've historically extended a guy like that and kept them.''
</P>
<P>
   Page's ride to Wichita Falls wasn't as exciting, as he simply
drove in from Dallas last night after an agreement was reached with
his agent, Angelo Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Page got a four-year deal worth $1,982,500 including an $800,000
signing bonus. Page will receiver base salaries of $215,000 in
1999, $268,750 in 2000, $322,500 in 2001 and $376,250 in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied with it,'' Wright said. ``Ekuban's deal and my
deal were good deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys vice president Jerry Jones Jr. said he was just happy to
complete the negotiation process and get all of the picks in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our mind, all of our picks that will play for us are in
camp,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have not signed seventh-round pick Kelvin Garmon,
but he is not expected to play this season because of a broken leg.
Jerry Jones Jr. said the Cowboys will turn their attention to
getting some money for Garmon. AIKMAN READY TO GO
</P>
<P>
   Though he won't start practicing in earnest until the rest of
the veterans show up Thursday, Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman says
he's in great shape physically and is ready to begin work outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good,'' Aikman said. ``I feel like I had a good
off-season as far as conditioning is concerned. I am ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey encouraged the veteran quarterbacks
and receivers to report with the rookies, but only to practice
among themselves. The group includes quarterback Jason Garrett,
receivers Michael Irvin, Ernie Mills and Raghib Ismail and tight
end Eric Bjornson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Chan had in mind,'' Aikman said. ``To get us back
into it gradually. We will work in once the veterans come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who didn't participate in any of the team's voluntary
workouts during the spring, said coming early gave them a chance to
work on their timing. LETT TO GIVE BACK BONUS Suspended defensive
tackle Leon Lett already stands to lose a portion of his $400,000
base salary for every game he misses in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stephen Jones acknowledges that Lett will have to pay the
Cowboys back a portion of the $1.5 million signing bonus he
received for restructuring his contract in February. Jones said
it's a standard clause in all contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The league has yet to decide on the length of Lett's suspension,
though the Cowboys quietly believe it will be four games.
</P>
<P>
   Lett stands to lose $23,529 per game in salary and $88,235 per
game in bonus money. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
