<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6400 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     07-28 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN ERA ENTERS DECISIVE STAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ To some, it would be the end of an era. To
others, the end of an error. With Michael Irvin, the public
reaction is basically void of emotional middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   But at age 33, Irvin was sweating away Tuesday on the Midwestern
State University practice field. Reality did not escape him, and
neither did most of Troy Aikman's bullet throws.
</P>
<P>
   This was the opening workout of what might well be Irvin's final
training camp for the Dallas Cowboys. He knows it, and he knows we
know he arrived in Wichita Falls needing an 18-wheeler to carry all
his baggage. Which, of course, has nothing to do with an otherwise
ample wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   The Irvin odometer shows a lot of football miles going into his
12th Cowboys training camp. Plus, he's coming off what was
personally a nonproductive kind of season. Plus, this is the final
year of a contract with no Jerry Jones renewal offer, at least thus
far. Plus, there are rumblings that coach Chan Gailey might be
ready to move on without Irvin, although Gailey becomes huffy at
the mere mention of that theory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with all this hanging over him, Irvin was a combined
bundle of optimism, enthusiasm and realism Tuesday as the morning
practice came to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm troubled by only one thing,'' he said, ``and that's that
some people seem to think I'm gonna be a problem for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I told Jerry Jones is I'm tired of people trying to make
something out of nothing. And there was nothing to any of the
stories or rumors I wanted to be traded. I never said that. Jerry
knows I never said that. I am closer to Jerry Jones than any player
who has ever been here. I would never do anything to show up
Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, of course, is all about Cowboys history, starting with
him being the last player remaining on the roster who served all
four head coaches. He also either holds or is co-holder of 20
franchise receiving records, including all the major ones. And when
the Cowboys were winning Super Bowls, Irvin was a major reason why.
</P>
<P>
   But on the flip side, there is another kind of Cowboys history _
this one involving the image demise of the '90s. Michael also leads
the team in that decline. And when there's doubt about him being
able to produce on the field, the other stuff will come home to
roost, which is normal. Irvin made his own fouled nest.
</P>
<P>
   What still goes unquestioned, however, is Irvin's work ethic and
his fierce team loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been Christmas every day playing for this team and
playing with this group of guys,'' Irvin said. ``I absolutely love
being here, but if the business end says I have to go elsewhere
next season, then I truly understand and can accept that
unconditionally.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Gailey a 100 percent believer in Irvin's ability?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the answer to that,'' Michael said, ``but for my
sake and the team's sake, he better make everyone believe he still
is. But like I said, if my time is winding down here, I'm not gonna
be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Irvin's overall numbers don't look that bad from
1998: 74 catches for 1,057 yards. Only one touchdown, however, says
the ol' Playmaker wasn't playmaking. Then, in the final five games
of the season, counting the playoffs, Irvin averaged a measly three
catches and 44 yards a game. For the first time in their parallel
careers, Troy Aikman appeared to be looking elsewhere besides Irvin
for an open receiver. In Irvin's case, the emphasis was on
``open.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he blames himself for Irvin's sudden slump, saying
his strategy to help Irvin and the offense ended up backfiring.
Irvin played the inside, or slot receiver, more than his normal
outside position. The idea was to create less double coverage. But
on the outside, the priority is usual on physical force, a Michael
specialty. On the inside, finesse and precise patterns can be the
norm. Irvin didn't fit, and he freely admits to struggling with the
transition. ``I was doing more thinking as opposed to just
reacting,'' Irvin said. ``I wasn't sure of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael will be back doing what he does best,'' said Gailey,
meaning at outside receiver. Free-agent speedster Rocket Ismail was
brought in to handle the inside game and, in theory, to help
Michael work open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Chan,'' Irvin said. ``Chan is always straight in
dealing with you. Our relationship is not confrontational, not even
close (to confrontational). We've talked a lot about why this
didn't work, or what I was thinking when I ran a certain route. I
do admit a preference for the outside (receiver) muscle game. It's
something I do pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting now, Irvin must also re-prove that he can do what he
always did so well. His football clock is ticking in Wichita Falls,
but as of Tuesday, Michael was still full of joy.
</P>
<P>
   With him, the paradox never ends. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
