<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6409 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN     07-28 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS DEFEATS TOP JUNIOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He walked onto the UCLA court Tuesday looking like
Pete Sampras' ball boy. He walked off to a standing ovation and had
young kids wanting his autograph despite losing 6-1, 6-2 to the
world's No.2-ranked player in a Mercedes-Benz Cup first-round
match.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the ATP Tour, 17-year-old Phillip King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great,'' said the Long Beach native and this country's
top-ranked junior. ``I live around here and I practice here. I
thought everyone came to see Pete. I couldn't believe how many
people were rooting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Frenchman Guillaume Raoux continued his success in
this event by upsetting third-seeded Tim Henman 6-3, 7-6 (7-4). All
other seeded players posted victories, including top-seeded Andre
Agassi, who won 6-2, 6-2 over Jan-Michael Gambill, who had beaten
Agassi twice previously.
</P>
<P>
   Many among the sold-out crowd must like the underdog, and King
is about as great an underdog as they come.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the prestigious Easter Bowl this spring, King
received a wild-card entry into this, his first pro event. And he
found out at Friday's draw that he got Sampras, who he said seemed
``untouchable'' to him growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had four days to sleep on it,'' he said. ``At first, I
couldn't sleep, then last night I did. (But) once the sun set
(Tuesday), the jitters came back.''
</P>
<P>
   King's goals were modest: Get his racket on the ball, run down
every shot possible and not lose in 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using these guidelines, King could consider this match a
success. It lasted 54 minutes, with King scoring eight points off
Sampras' serve, including a hard cross-court forehand on match
point. He also scored at least one point each time he served.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I wanted to keep the ball in to get a rally
going,'' he said. ``In the middle, I thought, `Oh, no, there's a
rally going. I don't want to mess up. At the end, I felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   He also served consistently above 100 mph and got in 48 percent
of his first serves.
</P>
<P>
   Still, King had no answer for Sampras' drop volleys and six
aces, many of which sped past him at speeds exceeding 130 mph.
Sampras also demonstrated his ability to find the corners.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras broke King to go up 3-1 in the first set and sailed.
King held serve in the second set, getting the score to 2-2 before
Sampras broke him.
</P>
<P>
   King has hit with Sampras before at the Riviera Country Club,
yet he was amazed at the older man's calm demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost startling to me,'' King said. ``It's like trying
to beat up an iron man. You can't knock him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was gracious in victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handled himself well and tried hard,'' Sampras said. ``He's
going to get better as he gets stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Raoux often seems strong here, having reached the semifinals of
the last two tournaments, beating Mark Philippoussis and Patrick
Rafter in 1997, Goran Ivanisevic last year and now Henman, from who
he had never won a set in four previous meetings. One of those
matches was last year's semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more impressive, Raoux wasn't in perfect health. He
flew 11 hours to get here Saturday from an exhibition in Lebanon,
suffering from diarrhea during the flight. He called the trip his
worst ever.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he became a new father in May, so his motivation for
tennis waned temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, my daughter (Maena) was born,'' he said. ``Life goes on.
My life is tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   He showed as much, winning the first set and breaking Henman to
start the second set. Raoux also knew Henman's penchant for
charging the net, so he modified his second serve to have more
movement. The result was Henman's early exit a week after earning
his highest ranking ever (fifth). This was his first event since
reaching the semifinals at Wimbledon earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what I wanted, but it's not a reason to start
panicking,'' Henman said. ``I need to go away and hit lots of balls
on the practice court for the next four to five days until next
week (at Montreal), to get back into a rhythm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
