<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6426 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UCLA-CONFESS-LADN     07-28 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UCLA-CONFESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA PLAYERS 'FESS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Story moving in the ``a'' national news file, the ``s'' sports
news file and in the ``n'' California news file.) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 and   HARRISON SHEPPARD  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nine UCLA football players plan to plead guilty of
lying to the Department of Motor Vehicles to get
handicapped-parking permits, and each expects to pay a fine and
perform 200 hours of community service with the disabled, their
attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Rafer Johnson, a 1960 Olympic Games track champion, helped work
out the agreement and is expected to appear in court today on the
players' behalf, sources said. Johnson is active in Special
Olympics, where many of the players are expected to perform their
community service.
</P>
<P>
   Harland Braun, attorney for the nine players who will plead
guilty, said he hopes to persuade five others charged in the case
to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to nine of them and will meet with the others and
try to get this behind them. I'm not making excuses for them
because what they did was wrong, but this is a pretty stiff
penalty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people would get a $200 fine,'' but the players expect to
be fined as much as $500 each, Braun said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are getting five weeks of community service with
people who won't be too happy with them, and I'm sure they'll let
them know,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The misdemeanor charges carry a maximum sentence of six months
in jail and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the University of California, Los Angeles, will not
comment on the charges or any internal discipline of the players
until the court case is resolved, sports information director Marc
Dellins said.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocates for handicapped people said the probable
sentences are too lenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's adequate,'' said David Howell, the head of
Americans Disabled for Attendant Programs Today _ Los Angeles.
``They should do their community service at an independent living
center _ get to know something about the people who do need those
spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   The California Foundation of Independent Living Centers did not
object to a community service sentence but plans a demonstration in
front of the courthouse on the issue of handicapped parking
enforcement in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want them to go to jail, but we want them to heighten
their sensitivity around the issue,'' said Lillibeth Navarro,
foundation spokeswoman. ``Those parking spaces are there for a
reason. They are there for people with disabilities who have real
difficulties competing for parking spaces to do their daily
activities, like shopping and going to the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, this issue is on the map. Accessible
parking spaces are routinely violated, and no one thinks about it _
except (the disabled), of course. People go scot-free violating
these spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have not decided whether to charge three other
players who have turned professional after graduating from UCLA,
including quarterback Cade McNown, now with the Chicago Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still waiting to hear from UCLA police on those
cases,'' said Mike Qualls, a spokesman for the City Attorney's
Office. ``Once they complete their case, we'll look at it and take
the appropriate action.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are accused of illegally obtaining permits by
signing fraudulent statements and using the placards to park in
preferred lots on the crowded UCLA campus.
</P>
<P>
   In their requests for the permits, they claimed a variety of
problems, including knee and back injuries, torn ligaments, asthma
and Bell's palsy, prosecutors say, and they submitted phony names
of physicians.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA police broke the case on Jan. 16 when one officer said he
spotted a car with an improperly placed handicapped permit and was
told by the driver that he borrowed the placard from a football
player.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes were charged with illegally possessing permits and
giving false information to the DMV.
</P>
<P>
   The case sparked outrage among disabled groups and others, and
some said the players should go to jail. It has been a major
embarrassment for the football program, whose season will start
Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Toledo has promised, as an example to others, to add
to any punishment the court administers to the players.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 charged in the case are Deatra Clinton, Ali Abdul Azziz,
Damian Domin Allen, Marque Deon Anderson, Oscar Cabrera, James
Michael Ghezzi, Duval Jerome Hicks and Robert Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Ryan Clint Nece, Durrell Rayton Price, Mark Reynosa, Ryan
Jason Roques, Craig Hilary Walendy and Anthony Dewaye White. All
are from Southern California. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 0210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0035 </DOCNO>
