<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAKES PROGRESS IN NFL MEETING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As vague as it was, progress was hailed after Gov.
Gray Davis' representative met briefly with the NFL expansion
committee for the first time Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Chadwick, given the charge by Davis to direct a unified Los
Angeles' expansion bid, met with the owners in what Commissioner
Paul Tagliabue called a preview of his presentation to the full
membership today.
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick faced the owners without anyone from the competing
ownership groups _ Michael Ovitz-Ron Burkle and Eli Broad-Ed Roski
Jr. _ that he has helped bring together in this new-team Los
Angeles effort.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the three-hour meeting consisted of Tagliabue and league
staff updating the expansion committee on progress made since
Chadwick entered the scene six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who has been skeptical over
the Los Angeles bid largely because of a lack of public support,
said he came away encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the Los Angeles position was DOA six weeks ago, and
now it's breathing,'' Jones said. ``Whether or not we can get it to
where we need to in the amount of time that's left to do that is
questionable. Certainly what he was able to do would indicate to me
there is a slim chance of that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the meetings, Jones said he was unimpressed by progress
at the Coliseum and still expected Houston to emerge with the next
expansion team. Los Angeles has until Sept. 15 to convince league
owners the situation is right in Southern California, or the league
said it will next expand to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue termed Tuesday night's meeting a preparation for
today's more involved presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed what has been done, what needs to be done,''
Tagliabue said. ``I think their consensus was, it's still a work in
progress and that we have to keep working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick said he came away convinced that owners believe
tremendous progress has been made in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're looking for a way to say yes,'' Chadwick said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite talks of progress, Chadwick said he did not pass out
copies of financing plan, or detailed site and stadium plans.
Economics remain the owners' biggest concern at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not ask the details,'' he said. ``I was a little bit
surprised. I thought we'd get into that more, and it's a tough area
because there are a lot more questions than answers, but they
really didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
