<HEADLINE>
SPARKS BEAT ORLANDO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The last time the Sparks and Orlando Miracle met,
the Sparks blew a 15-point lead and lost the game by two points.
Not so Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A much improved, defensive-minded Sparks team protected its
16-point halftime lead and blew out the Miracle 81-60 before 5,079,
the Sparks' smallest crowd of the season at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play together on the defensive end, we tend to be a
lot better, and that's what we did tonight,'' Sparks coach Orlando
Woolridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie turned in another stellar game with 19 points, 10
rebounds and four assists as the Sparks (14-6) earned their fourth
consecutive victory and 11th in 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   It was highlight-reel night for the Sparks, but the play of the
game came when they were on a break and Mwadi Mabika flipped the
ball behind her back to Leslie, who sailed in for the layup to give
the Sparks a 75-58 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando's top scorer, Nykesha Sales, who averages 14.5 points,
finished the game scoreless on 0-of-8 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   La'Keisha Frett drew most of the defensive duties on Sales but
didn't take all of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just me alone,'' Frett said. ``I played with Nykesha
before on the USA Basketball team and I kind of knew what she
wanted to do. I just tried to take away what she likes to do. She
likes to dip her head a lot and drive a lot. I just tried to put my
forearm on her and hold her back.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks carried a 43-26 lead into halftime and stretched it
to 50-31 less than five minutes into the second half. The Miracle
got as close as 67-58 but was held scoreless in the last 5{
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks got off to a good start against the Miracle, jumping
out to a 20-9 advantage at 11:34. Orlando was able to trim the lead
to seven on two occasions, but the Sparks closed the period with a
14-3 run.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie had 11 points in the first half. Sales picked up three
fouls in the first half and played 10 scoreless minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Grubin converted four 3-pointers and scored 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   Taj McWilliams had 17 points and seven rebounds, and Sheri Sam
had 15 points for Orlando (9-11).
</P>
</TEXT>
