r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LBPT     07-28 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS SCHOOLS KING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A King by name and often a king on the court,
Phillip King learned Tuesday night what it's like to live a
pauper's life.
</P>
<P>
   King, a 17-year-old Long Beach resident, had the misfortune of
making his debut on the professional tour against what he considers
the best player ever to grace the court, Pete Sampras, in the first
round of the Mercedes-Benz Cup at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   It was quick and painless Sampras won 6-1, 6-2 in 54 minutes but
it was not without some moments to cherish for King.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a pair of break points in the final game and fought
off one set point before walking off the court to a standing
ovation from the sellout crowd of 7,176. He was even asked for his
autograph by a crowd of teen-agers who might have passed for his
classmates at Poly High and afterward talked with Tom Ross, the
agent for Michael Chang.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great,'' King said of the standing ovation. ``I live
here, I practice (at UCLA) sometimes. I didn't think so many people
would be rooting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   King, whose family parents David and Karen and younger sisters
Mindy, Ivana and Vania arrived 2 1/2 hours before the match,
learned on Friday that he would play Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   He professed to having a hard time sleeping until Monday night.
He spent most of Monday playing Legos with his sisters, trying
anything to keep his mind off Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   King found it much more difficult to build any momentum against
Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   King is the No.1-ranked junior in the country, but he's ranked
No.708 overall to Sampras' No. 2. He'd practiced against Sampras
last month at Riviera Country Club but it wasn't until Tuesday that
he found out how big the gap was.
</P>
<P>
   King hustled and made some plays, but Sampras' strength, skill
and shot-making ability left King looking like Sisyphis pushing a
ball around the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like trying to beat up an iron man,'' King said.
``Nothing moves him. ... When I came out I thought he was going to
ace every single point.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the juniors, the mindset is so different. Half the matches
are won because one player thinks he's better than the other. Here
rankings don't mean anything. Nobody breaks down the one who wins
the match is the one who takes the match.''
</P>
<P>
   King managed to hold his serve against Sampras in the second
game, but never came close to winning a game in the first set. In
fact, he won just four points off Sampras' serve the entire match.
Often Sampras' serve which reached into the 130 mph range (about 30
mph faster than King's) just about took the racket out of King's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough at the beginning,'' King said. ``There was
nothing much I could do when he hit winners.''
</P>
<P>
   King, who relied on his scrambling and steady backhand, made it
a little more difficult in the second set. He came from 15-40 down
in the third game, going up 2-1 when he dug a ball out of the
corner and forced Sampras to short hop a volley into the net.
</P>
<P>
   He won the longest rally of the night to stave off a breakpoint
in the fifth game and then was up 40-30 before losing the seventh
game, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   The best tennis was saved for the final game. Sampras, after
double faulting to make it 30-30, hit a backhand into the net after
King chased down three tough shots. He simply responded by firing
an ace.
</P>
<P>
   King answered by passing Sampras for a backhand winner that left
him pumping his left fist.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras then delighted the crowd with something resembling a
Michael Jordan dunk as he ran and leaped at the net before
hammering a lob. King saved a match point, though, by hammering a
forehand return at Sampras feet that he hit into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Sampras put King away with a service winner and an ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handled himself well,'' Sampras said. ``He's going to get
better as he gets stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   King appreciated the kind words Sampras gave him at the net
afterward, though he wasn't quite sure what to say himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I could say,'' King said, smiling. ```Thanks
for giving me three games?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
