<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 ROYALS BEAT UP ON M'S FASSERO; GRIFFEY HITS 33RD HOMER
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Several hours before it got even worse, a
veteran Mariner was asked for an interview on the state of the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about the team,'' he said. ``Some things
are better left unsaid.''
</P>
<P>
   And some games are better left unseen.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's game was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners continued their descent, falling 9-7 to the Kansas
City Royals at Kauffman Stadium and dropping to 12 games behind the
Texas Rangers in the American League West. The Mariners weren't
even this far back at the end of last season; they finished their
'98 campaign 11{ games behind.
</P>
<P>
   With scouts from the New York Yankees, Boston Red Sox and others
looking on, Jeff Fassero lost his American League-leading 12th
game. Whether it was his final Mariners appearance will be known by
the trading deadline on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what's going to happen,'' Fassero said.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked about his preference if he's traded, Fassero
cracked a smile. ``An NL team _ that way, it's all zeroes across
the board. I would hate to go to an AL team and keep the same
numbers,'' he said. ``The NL would be a clean, fresh slate. Over
here, I would have to have the same nasty numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero is 4-12 with a 7.06 earned run average after allowing
six runs on nine hits in 41/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella had considered shifting the left-hander to
the bullpen, but Fassero convinced Piniella he could correct a flaw
he spotted on video, and he kept the start. Piniella said Fassero
is scheduled to start again on Sunday at home against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero shook his head when he mentioned that the Orioles will
start ace Mike Mussina on Sunday. Fassero thought he would avoid
other teams' No. 1 starters when Jamie Moyer took over the No. 1
spot in the M's rotation. But he drew Kevin Appier Tuesday night,
and the Royals right-hander held the Mariners to two runs over
seven innings, improving to 12-3 lifetime against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   It's always something for Fassero this year. He matched Appier
for a while, throwing three shutout innings, then succumbed to a
four-run, two-out rally in the fourth, started by a wild pitch and
sustained by five singles _three sneaking through holes in the
infield, one never reaching the outfield and another up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no walks out there, and I think I went to
three-ball counts on only two guys,'' said Fassero, who slowed his
delivery, which he's been unable to do much of this year. ``I was
ahead of most everybody, which means they were hitting my pitches.
But they were hitting them where we weren't in the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do. That's the way everything goes.
You do throw good, and it was frustrating out there tonight.
(Stuff) keeps going on.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Mariners lately, it's been going on against Minnesota
and Kansas City, who share the worst record in the American League.
The M's dropped two of three over the weekend to the Twins, and
both teams have shown something to Piniella. He took note of their
first-to-third speed, as well as their skill at situational
hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing is young, athletic clubs just taking it to
you,'' said Piniella. ``And they've got some talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth inning exemplified the kind of rally that so often
eludes the older, station-to-station Mariners. Fassero retired 10
of his first 12 hitters before Mike Sweeney doubled with one out.
After getting a second out on a grounder, Fassero threw a wild
pitch, bringing in Sweeney for the game's first run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about that time, he lost concentration,'' pitching
coach Stan Williams said of Fassero. ``He might not agree with
that, but that was my impression. Kind of a `Here we go again' type
of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The five singles followed, the Royals' lead swelled to 4-0, and
it only got worse in the fifth. A run-scoring double by Jermaine
Dye knocked out Fassero, and with two outs and Ken Cloude pitching,
a walk, two singles and a throwing error by Ken Griffey Jr. made it
7-1 Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners rallied in the ninth off rookie reliever Ken Ray.
Griffey belted his 33rd home run, a 420-foot, two-run blast to
right, and singles by Edgar Martinez and David Segui put runners at
first and second. With Jay Buhner batting, Ray's pitch got away
from catcher Chad Kreuter, and Martinez broke for third _ where he
was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Three more runs would score, but it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mistake was thinking about getting out of the double
play,'' Martinez said. ``But still, it's a terrible play.''
</P>
<P>
   Another that was better left unseen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
