<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6436 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-SURFING-LBPT     07-28 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-SURFING-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CROWDED SURFING SEASCAPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you go to the Huntington Beach Pier this week, you might not
know where to look first.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the focus definitely would be on surfing. After
all, the mainland United States' only World Championship Tour
surfing event starts today in Huntington Beach, and the creative
and athletic moves of the world's top surfers often have awed
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   However, while the beach's focus still may be on the surfing and
what is called the Gotcha Pro California, other sports will vie for
beach goers' attention.
</P>
<P>
   In-line skating, BMX biking, wakeboarding and skateboarding are
some of the sports that will be played simultaneously with surfing.
Corporate sponsors continue to support these other sports, which
offer $150,000 in prize money, while surfing has $250,600 prize
money at Huntington Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Complementing the sports, more than 20 tents of various
enterprises, from the KROQ radio station to Gold's Gym, are set
along the beach to advertise and hand out freebies.
</P>
<P>
   So while the festival atmosphere can offer beach goers a full
day's activity, the surfing may be affected. Among professional
surfers, there are two reactions to the ever-growing festivities.
The most common reaction is the more activities, the better.
Another reaction is that the festivities detract from the event's
focus surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me personally, I don't care about BMX biking or
volleyball,'' said Sunny Garcia, a Hawaiian regarded as one of the
top surfers in the world. ``What I think is that it should only be
surfing. It's a surfing event, and it doesn't have to add
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, 29, with other surfers similar in age, has a different
perspective than younger pro surfers. When Garcia became a pro
surfer, he wasn't guaranteed money at events. If he didn't advance
past trial heats, he didn't get paid. Plus, if he did advance, he
wasn't guaranteed a reasonable purse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started it was really hard,'' Garcia said. ``If you
came in 33rd, you'd get $300, and that probably wasn't enough for
groceries and a place to stay. It was very hard and stressful. A
lot of times everybody stayed in the same place, and you'd have the
rooms filled with people sleeping on the floors.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia paid his dues in professional surfing when there was
doubt he could make a substantial living. Now, if a young surfer
makes it to the WCT, the surfer is guaranteed money and won't have
to struggle like surfers from past years.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsors have made prize money respectable, making a
career in surfing more feasible. An easy example to see how
corporate sponsors have changed the money situation on the WCT is
to look at Mark Occhilupo's prize earnings. Occhilupo, 34, has been
one of the world's top surfers for more than 13 years and is ranked
first in the WCT this year. His career prize money on the WCT is
approximately $350,000, and in 1997 alone, won $119,600. But with
the increasing prize money, pro surfing's culture may have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young surfers expect certain things,'' Garcia said.
``They don't cherish what they get, like we (older surfers) do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat O'Connell, 27, is another of the world's top surfers who
like Garcia, Occhilupo and the biggest names in surfing is expected
to compete at Huntington. O'Connell grew up in Laguna Niguel and
has seen the the sport's changes. When he was 12, he saw his first
pro surfing contest at Huntington Beach, so he has witnessed the
event's evolution.
</P>
<P>
   While the event at Huntington always has been considered the
biggest festival of the WCT, it continues to grow until this year
in which the crowd is expected to exceed 250,000. That large crowd
could help surfing grow, but perhaps only if the crowd focuses on
the surfing, which is not a given.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does feel a little strange to pull up to the beach and see
people on roller blades or on bikes,'' O'Connell said. ``But when
you get to into the water, it's just like any other event.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Simmons, 25, who attended Los Alamitos High and lives in
Seal Beach, also remembers seeing the pro surfing at Huntington
Beach as a child. Simmons competed in last week's U.S. Open of
Surfing and has seen many changes to pro surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nineties beach culture has blown up, especially with
skateboarding and volleyball,'' Simmons said. ``It's all been in a
good way. I don't see any negatives to it.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of other beach sports could increase surfing's
popularity. And if the level of pro surfing is an indication, then
surfing is going in the right direction. Surfers agree that any of
the 45 competing in the Gotcha Pro could win the event. In past
years, only a handful of surfers would have a legitimate chance.
</P>
<P>
   Surfers who came on the scene in the early '90s, Rob Machado,
Shane Dorian, Tim Curran and Taylor Knox among others, are the
favorites for the Gotcha Pro. But then again, these surfers have
been favorites for close to a decade and likely will remain in that
position for years.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Malloy, a pro surfer from Ventura, pointed out that
surfboards were revolutionized in the early '90s to make them
lighter, stronger and more mobile. The surfers from the early '90s
took advantage of this and have remained on top ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still the strongest force out there,'' Malloy said.
``There are going to be younger guys, though. There always will be
young fresh guys who will turn heads. But it's those other guys who
have dominated and continue to dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   But with increased prize money, individuality has been called
into question. Young surfers have been accused of simply chase
purses, instead of the intangible goals of older surfers. Some say
young surfers' personalities are not distinctive, like those from
the past. If that's so, then perhaps it is a solid argument against
the direction that surfing is heading.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said, ``Everybody wants to be the next guy. Nobody wants
to be himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
