<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHREMPF, FANS LOSE IN SONICS' LATEST EQUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Free agency in the NBA begins Sunday, so here's the
first question on your test to become a team general manager:
</P>
<P>
   Do you commit:
</P>
<P>
   a) $87 million to a superbly talented superstar who doesn't
practice and is also a pain to many of his teammates;
</P>
<P>
   b) $87 million to a superbly talented star who is fatter and
softer than ice cream on pumpkin pie;
</P>
<P>
   c) Offend your hardest working, most reliable player with a
potential offer of the minimum veteran's salary;
</P>
<P>
   d) All of the above, then enroll in the Rancho Absurdo Sports
Executive Therapy Club (Woody Woodward, president).
</P>
<P>
   Sonics president Wally Walker apparently has chosen d),
establishing that his capacity for self-abuse is far greater than
previously credited.
</P>
<P>
   If Walker can create a serious playoff contender from that
choice, he not only will be executive of the year, the College of
Cardinals will have him next in line for the papacy.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's dilemma was outlined in remarks Tuesday by Detlef
Schrempf, choice c) in the question.
</P>
<P>
   In a broadcast interview, the free agent forward declared his
Sonics days over because he believes the club plans to offer him
only $1 million for a single year.
</P>
<P>
   While describing the potential offer as an insult caused
eyebrows to soar among grocery baggers across Puget Sound, the
possibility marks a substantial pay cut from his $3.3 million
salary last year. And that was a season when he was among the few
Sonics not to require a dietician, nurse and anger-management
counselor just to get through practice.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his 36 years, Schrempf was a stalwart in a
lockout-ruined season rife with incompetence and contempt. But
rather than be rewarded, Schrempf sees choice b), Vin Baker, likely
to receive from the Sonics the maximum contract allowable under the
new collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Baker last season was virtually the anti-Det _ undedicated,
unprofessional and timid. Even this summer's dalliance with the
U.S. team in the Olympic qualifying tournament in Puerto Rico
established he was still out of shape despite five months of nearly
constant basketball.
</P>
<P>
   That is not an easy accomplishment. Baker is a clear and present
danger to the world's supply of fries and milk shakes.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf also sees that choice a), Gary Payton, has been richly
rewarded and allowed to skip most practices, despite curiously
disappearing in some games and this summer attempting to dictate to
management about acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Since Schrempf doesn't much care for Payton anyway, the prospect
of returning to his hometown club under these developments has all
the appeal of Pennzoil shortcake.
</P>
<P>
   Although it isn't much of a surprise that the Sonics may end up
lowballing Schrempf _ nothing can happen until Sunday _ it is
another reminder of how cornered the Sonics are under the new labor
rules.
</P>
<P>
   With so much salary potentially committed to Payton, Baker and
newly acquired forward Horace Grant (about $24 million next year
alone), the Sonics must go light on the rest of the roster. They
can get away with that with youngsters Jelani McCoy, Vladimir
Stepania and Rashard Lewis, but the remaining six roster spots must
be filled by veterans willing to work relatively cheaply, at least
by NBA standards.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf claims he will not be among them, even though he said
repeatedly Tuesday his decision wasn't about money (wink, nudge).
But whether his reasons are financial or basketball, the system is
set up to squeeze the middle class of players where he resides.
</P>
<P>
   By renouncing the rights to Schrempf and five other free agents,
the Sonics could clear enough room under the salary cap to pursue a
high-end free agent such as Mitch Richmond. But his acquisition
would further top-load a roster that, along with Grant, would now
have two 34-year-olds on the downside of their careers receiving
huge multi-year deals.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the worst situation, but it does resemble the picture
painted last year by the Houston Rockets. While sporting three of
the 50 greatest players in NBA history, the salary-constrained
Rockets were forced to start two rookie guards to support Hakeem
Olajuwon, Charles Barkley and Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   Bad scene. One likely to be repeated here without the expertise
of Schrempf, whose versatility helped plug the talent hole of the
night. That virtue, little appreciated, will become more visible
next year when the Sonics are overloaded with either youth or
one-position players.
</P>
<P>
   A case can be made that Schrempf is too old to justify a larger
contract. It also could be argued that Walker, despite the flops of
Jim McIlvaine and Billy Owens, is due to hook a good one in free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   But jettisoning Schrempf eliminates any wiggle room the roster
had to absorb mistakes. And it puts much of the weight of the
franchise on the re-signing and the re-energizing of Baker.
</P>
<P>
   As if he needs the pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
