<SLUG> BC-BOX-BIGBEAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BEAR ATTRACTS BOXERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEAR LAKE -- They come from South Africa, New Zealand,
Mexico and Poland, from Oxnard, East Los Angeles, Pomona, Detroit
and New York.
</P>
<P>
   From near and far, prize fighters are flocking to this mountain
hideaway to train.
</P>
<P>
   The altitude, they believe, improves their endurance. The
solitude, they know, bolsters their psyche, keeping them out of
trouble and focused on business.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Bear boon started nine years ago with just one camp --
Larry Goossen's Boxing Gym. Local fighters like Gabe and Rafael
Ruelas became its mainstays. Today, Big Bear Lake, elevation 7,200
feet, has become boxing's training mecca.
</P>
<P>
   It's 9 a.m. on a summer morning. Francois Botha of South Africa
and Jesus Salud of Hawaii are chopping wood on what soon will be
the fourth training camp located here.
</P>
<P>
   This one belongs to Abel Sanchez. The West Covina native,
considered one of the game's top trainers, is building a camp with
two houses. The complex will also include an indoor pool and indoor
training center.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, the former IBF heavyweight champion, is training for his
Aug. 7 bout against Shannon Briggs.
</P>
<P>
   For one four-minute round after another, sweat pours down
Botha's bare chest. He relentlessly swings a lead-handled ax,
cutting into a gigantic tree trunk, wood chips flying up to 50 feet
away.
</P>
<P>
   It's Botha's first time here. He wishes it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was here (training for Mike Tyson),'' said Botha, who
was knocked out by Tyson last Jan. 17 in the fifth round. ``The
elevation is excellent. When I first time came here I couldn't chop
wood for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm up to an hour and fifteen minutes. Once you are up
here to train, you struggle at first. But then you get in shape.
Once you go down to lower level, your breathing is so much better.
If you can't get in shape in this altitude, you can't get in shape
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Oscar De La Hoya. That's why he's in great shape,
because he trains up here. Look how he finished against (Ike)
Quartey.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Goossen's Boxing Gym is now the Big Bear Boxing &AMP; Fitness
Gym. There is also Oscar De La Hoya's gym, and Emanuel Steward's
Kronk Gym West.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, Lennox Lewis, Shannon Briggs, Fernando Vargas,
``Sugar'' Shane Mosley, Floyd Mayweather Jr., Botha, Salud, Oba
Carr, Andrew Golota, Jimmy Thunder, Carlos Navarro, Roberto Garcia,
Orlin Norris, Miguel Angel Gonzalez, Lou Del Valle and Raul Marquez
are some of the marquee fighters who train here.
</P>
<P>
   Some are local. Many -- like New York's Briggs, Michigan's
Mayweather, England's Lewis, Poland's Golota, New Zealand's
Thunder, South Africa's Botha, Hawaii's Salud, Detroit's Carr and
Mexico's Gonzalez -- are not.
</P>
<P>
   They hear about high altitude training, about the serenity. And
they come to see if it's true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kept hearing different things about fighters coming up
here: Oscar De La Hoya, Floyd Mayweather Jr.,'' said Briggs, of
Brownsville, N.Y., who has asthma. This is his first time training
in Big Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hearing different stories and I had once trained for the
Olympics at the Olympic Training Center in Colorado. And I had felt
the difference once I went down. So I wanted to give this a shot.
Plus, I needed the solitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm not in Las Vegas, because those crap tables would
be calling my name. I'm happy I'm here. I love this town. It's a
beautiful place.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Woodworth, who manages several fighters who train here,
swears by the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gone up for nearly 10 years,'' said Woodworth, who
manages Garcia, Norris, Felipe Campa, Israel Correa and Carlos
Madrigal, all of whom train here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeal for me as a manager is you have isolation, number
one. There are not a lot of things to do to get in trouble up
there. When you have guys come to Vegas early in their careers,
there are a lot of temptations.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the altitude. With that kind of wind, the running and the
training, by the time you get back down to sea level you are going
to have more wind left in the championship rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   This, apparently, is debatable. De La Hoya and Vargas have
previously said the altitude is a supreme factor in training here,
as did every fighter interviewed for this story. Not everyone,
however, agrees on the positive effects of altitude training.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong emphasis has been on altitude,'' said Steward, who
turned an old Army Surplus store in Big Bear into what is now Kronk
Gym West. Steward owns the original Kronk Gym in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one who doesn't believe in that,'' Steward said. ``If you
are fighting in high altitude, then I believe in it. But if you
don't, it doesn't do you any good. And how many times do you fight
in high altitude?
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you are in shape or you are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward offers proof. He said that for the second Riddick
Bowe-Evander Holyfield fight in November of 1993, Bowe trained in
high altitude. Holyfield did not. Holyfield won.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Evander went 12 beautiful rounds,'' Steward said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first Thomas Hearns-Sugar Ray Leonard fight, Hearns
trained in high altitude and wilted in the later rounds. He trained
in Detroit for their second bout and floored Leonard in the 11th
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy Hearns trained up there a little bit and did not like
it,'' Steward said. ``He said driving up and down the mountains is
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Another famous trainer, Gil Clancy, said he believes altitude
training is beneficial, whatever the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I am only concerned with Oscar,'' said Clancy,
De La Hoya's assistant trainer to Roberto Alcazar. ``He has an
absolute perfect training camp. He has a home up there and he is
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it is 8,000 feet above sea level, so it helps his stamina
when he gets down to sea level.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Steward's comments, Clancy said: ``This is one of the
few times I disagree with Emanuel. When you are training up there
in strenuous conditions, you still have to expand to get more
oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when you get down, your lungs I think will provide you with
more oxygen than ordinary circumstances. I think it is the high
altitude. And I think that more and more guys are following Oscar's
lead. They see what it has done for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, Oba Carr followed him here for his last
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr fought a tremendous fight against De La Hoya in May before
being stopped in the 11th round.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy isn't the only one who believes training at altitude is
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is probably to a certain extent so,'' said Dr.
Robert Karns, the former chief medical examiner for the California
State Athletic Commission. ``It is like climatizing yourself at a
higher altitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your oxygen-carrying capacity is increased. It's like skiing.
The first couple of days you don't feel so good (because of the
altitude).''
</P>
<P>
   Karns, however, said the benefits shrink if you are not actually
going to fight in altitude, giving credence to Steward's claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are fighting in an area like that, you will do very
well,'' said Karns, who specializes in internal medicine and
cardiology. ``The boxers will have that advantage when they go down
to sea level, too. They probably have one or two more grams of
hemoglobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's call it a form of blood building. But it will dissipate
quickly. It really doesn't make all that much difference. Once you
are down there for about a week, it is gone. It would, however,
help you if you were to fight two days later.''
</P>
<P>
   Salud, the former WBA junior featherweight champ, isn't buying
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been here the last six, seven years because of the high
altitude,'' Salud said. ``It makes a difference. When you go down
to the lower elevation, you got a lot of wind. And the atmosphere.
It is nice and quiet. It makes you concentrate more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, who has trained seven world champions, said there is no
substitute for a strong mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solitude keeps them away from everyday life, the family,''
said Sanchez, a 1974 graduate of Edgewood High School in West
Covina. ``When they come up here they are coming up here for a
major fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the distractions are left at home. For them it seems to
work out better because they can sleep at night. They don't have to
worry about what the kids are doing, the neighbor, the fence fell
down, they gotta go fix a car.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
