<SLUG> BC-BOX-BIGBEAR-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE TRAINING CAMPS RESIDE AT BIG BEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEAR LAKE -- When Larry Goossen opened the first training
camp here for boxers in 1990, it was located in a hangar at the Big
Bear Airport.
</P>
<P>
   He was booted out of it after eight months, but eventually
re-located at a 2,000 square-foot building that was designed to be
an auto repair shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough getting kicked out of there,'' Goossen said,
``but they said only airplanes belonged there.''
</P>
<P>
   Little did Goossen know that nine years later he would be in
Denver, training fighters out of his brother Dan's America Presents
stables.
</P>
<P>
   Today Big Bear is home to three training camps, with a fourth to
be completed in October. That means the tough buck Goossen was
earning running training camps for the likes of Riddick Bowe,
Michael Moorer and Michael Nunn has become even tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Once word of mouth circulated about the solitude of training in
Big Bear, and the benefits of high altitude training, fighters
flocked to this mountain resort.
</P>
<P>
   It took a while. Oscar De La Hoya opened his gym in 1995.
Emanuel Steward opened his Kronk Gym West in 1997. And Abel Sanchez
completes his gym in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody started building gyms up there, so I said, `There
goes the honeymoon,' '' said Goossen, who sold part ownership of
Larry Goossen's Boxing Gym to Dr. Les Cohen, who three years ago
moved the camp next door and re-named it Big Bear Boxing &AMP; Fitness
Gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it is tough. The money is not as good.''
</P>
<P>
   For Goossen, who moved to Denver last September, running his gym
was his life's work. It was how he made his living. Now, he sits
and watches from 1,100 miles away, almost astonished at what has
transpired over nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked, to tell you the truth,'' he said. ``Because I
got so much negative response. People were saying, `How is that
going to work?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It worked because Goossen brought in world-class fighters. His
first camp was with Reggie Johnson, the former IBF light
heavyweight champ. He had Moorer, Bowe, Nunn, the Ruelas brothers
and even De La Hoya before De La Hoya built his gym.
</P>
<P>
   Things were so good the first few years, Goossen admittedly got
carried away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought summer would be really busy and winter would
be slower,'' Goossen said.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Although some boxers who had never experienced a real
winter left once it hit, there was never a shortage of fighters
willing to pay the fee Goossen charged to train at his gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest problem was overbooking my camp (during the
winter),'' said Goossen, who grew up as part of the fighting
Goossen family in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got going, everybody wanted to go there. So instead of
running four camps, I would run six, seven, eight camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got greedy. From that point, it was bombardment. When winter
came around, I didn't even want to go up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Goossen leaves it to De La Hoya, Steward, Sanchez and Cohen
to duke it out.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya probably doesn't care how many people train at his
camp. It is private, and he only rents to a specific few, like his
buddy Raul Marquez, who was knocked out by Fernando Vargas on July
17.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez? The West Covina native said his camp will also be
private, but that it would be available to rent by any fighter who
can pay what figures to be an expensive fee.
</P>
<P>
   Steward is a smart businessman. He rents Kronk Gym West to more
fighters than any other camp.
</P>
<P>
   Lennox Lewis, Vargas, ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley, Shannon Briggs and
Lou Del Valle are just some of the marquee fighters who train at
Kronk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear on TV that this guy just came from camp in Big
Bear,'' Steward said. ``And then based on the high profile and
publicity they got, other fighters start to follow them up there.''
</P>
<P>
   They can have it all, Goossen said, because he is really a city
boy. Denver might not be L.A. or New York, but it is livelier than
Big Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't wait to get the hell out of there,'' he said. ``It
was too damn small up there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
