<HEADLINE>
SCHREMPF'S CAREER APPEARS OVER IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Calling the latest contract offer from the Sonics
``insulting,'' ``embarrassing'' and a ``slap in the face,'' Detlef
Schrempf left little hope he'll be wearing a Sonics jersey next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf made the comments to Dave Mahler of Seattle's Sports
Radio KJR-AM Tuesday morning. He was responding to questions about
published reports that he would rather retire or play for another
team than take the Sonics' $1 million offer to play next season. A
14-year veteran, Schrempf made $3.3 million this past season _ his
sixth with Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics cautioned Tuesday that they haven't renounced
Schrempf's rights and are still willing to negotiate. But team
officials conceded the lower offer is an option.
</P>
<P>
   A provision in the NBA's collective bargaining agreement allows
teams to sign a single free agent to a one-year, $1 million salary
exception when the club is at or above the salary cap. That option
would give the Sonics salary flexibility to sign a more expensive
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me that's an insult,'' Schrempf said. ``It's not about the
money. I'm being told they really don't want me but they still want
to keep me for PR reasons, and that's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need that, and I'm not going to play for that. ...
I've paid my dues, and I feel like I deserve more respect than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonics president Wally Walker was in Boston Tuesday and
unavailable for comment. The team's vice president of basketball
operations, Billy McKinney, said because he didn't hear Schrempf's
broadcast comments he would rather not respond directly to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the comments are premature based on my understanding
of the situation,'' McKinney said. ``There are still a lot of
moving parts with free agency. Soon we should have a better idea
with the players we're talking to about free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with any contract negotiations there will always be
something said either positive or negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf said he might be willing to play for the lower $1
million figure if Walker would guarantee another higher-paying
contract for the following year. However, the collective bargaining
agreement doesn't allow that kind of deal even under the guise of
an informal ``gentleman's handshake agreement.'''
</P>
<P>
   The popular former University of Washington player said he
doesn't expect any further Sonics offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically done,'' said Schrempf, whose 15 points, 7.4
rebounds and 3.7 assists per game were second best on the team last
season, behind only star guard Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf conceded he didn't expect a four-or five-year contract
but felt like Walker's offer forced him to make a big sacrifice for
the team with little personal gain in return.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf is among six Sonics players whose contracts have
expired. The team can renounce Sunday some or all free agents to
get below the salary cap. If it does not get below the salary cap,
under the Larry Bird exception, it may re-sign its own free agents
at any salary without regard to the cap.
</P>
<P>
   That precludes the team from pursuing another team's expensive
free agent, but it would allow the Sonics to pay Schrempf a salary
closer to what he made last year.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf also questioned why the Sonics wouldn't instead sign
him to a larger contract and trade him _ preferably to a West Coast
team. Schrempf mentioned Portland, Utah and San Antonio as
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Those options aside, Schrempf hinted at retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need that kind of abuse,'' Schrempf said of the
Sonics' offer. ``I'd rather retire than play under those terms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
