r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BIGBEAR-SIDEBAR2-     07-28 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BIGBEAR-SIDEBAR2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXERS WELCOMED BY COMMUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEAR LAKE -- One store clerk says boxers help the economy in
this community.
</P>
<P>
   A fast-food restaurant employee was saddened that the gym being
built by Abel Sanchez resulted in 28 trees being chopped down.
</P>
<P>
   But all in all, the estimated 50 boxers training here at a given
time don't have a huge impact on the community, says Connie Baker,
publicist for Big Bear Resort Association, an arm of the Big Bear
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight contender Shannon Briggs recently visited Bear
Necessities, a health food store here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lady told me that boxers are good for the economy,''
Briggs said. ``That's good. People are finally saying something
positive about boxers.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Linda Fares, an employee at Bear Necessities: ``More and
more, boxers are training here. I think it is good. I think they
are a boon to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are nice gentlemen. Their trainers are nice gentlemen.
They are also very aware of what they put into their bodies. They
are probably more knowledgeable about what they put into their
bodies than two-thirds of the people up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker understands how some of the retailers affected by boxers
training here could react this way. But the ``boon'' Fares spoke of
is not across the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly think that for somebody who handles
supplements, that is a valid statement,'' she said. ``An athlete in
training is going to be more likely to choose their services.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, you have somewhere around 120 to 150 people --
including trainers and camp members -- doing what every other
resident is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, they rent a camp, or they go to the supermarkets,
the local pub, the theaters, gas stations,'' Baker said. ``Their
impact is more like that of the resident community.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, however, did say that Oscar De La Hoya created something
for residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly from the standpoint that Oscar De La Hoya has made
Big Bear one of his homes has made an awareness for Big Bear,'' she
said. ``He said the quality of community and high altitude was very
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he could still go to L.A. for everything else he does.
When Kronk was established, that certainly added to it. It has
become more of a local awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are there as much as I am, we see the people
training. They are not your usual jogger. You are aware that
someone is running down the street, semi-jogging or skipping
rope.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said chances are many residents have no idea that by
October the area will be home to four boxing training camps.
</P>
<P>
   But one Carl's Jr. employee knows only too well. Sanchez's gym
is being built about 100 feet behind the fast-food hamburger joint,
which is located on Big Bear Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty mad at him because he cut down 28 trees,'' the
cashier said. ``But he's a nice man, so we forgave him.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sanchez must re-plant 14 of those trees upon
completion of his camp, expected by October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an issue,'' Baker said. ``If we end up with a bare city
surrounded by forest, there is no charm. It is important we protect
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
