<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYALS RECALL SEATTLE-NATIVE FOR SERIES AGAINST HOMETOWN TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Glendon Rusch had a question: ``Is Jamie
Moyer pitching this series?''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals left-hander from North Seattle was told
that Moyer had pitched the finale of the Mariners' last series and
won't face the Royals this week. That's too bad for Rusch, a
Shorecrest High product who models himself after the Mariners
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch was recalled from Class AAA Omaha before Tuesday night's
game, and will take his place in the Royals bullpen. The
24-year-old found himself back in the minors this year after
spending the last two seasons in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game is fastball and changeup,'' Rusch said. ``I need to
have command like Moyer does to be able to throw both pitches in
and out and keep it down in the zone. I wasn't able to do that, and
that's what hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusch was 6-9 in '97, 6-15 last year and failed to make the
Royals out of spring training this season. He was 3-6 with a 4.02
earned run average at Omaha, allowing 100 hits in 781/3 innings.
But he had improved in recent starts and was promoted when the
Royals optioned left-hander Tim Byrdak.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're down at a lower level, and you're struggling
there, then you feel like the organization's looking down on you,
saying, `If he's struggling there, what's he going to do here?'''
Rusch said. ``That can weigh on your mind. It's almost a no-win
situation down there, unless you're producing and doing well. But I
just tried to keep the best positive attitude I could and get back
here as soon as possible. I'm happy to be back, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusch was so happy, he left Omaha as soon as he got the call,
arriving in Kansas City at 2 a.m. Tuesday. He was rushing so he
could finally sleep in his own bed _ Rusch bought a home in
Overland Park, Kan., after the 1997 season and lives there
year-round.
</P>
<P>
   He's looking forward to the Royals' trip to Safeco Field in
September, especially because he was injured when Omaha played at
Tacoma and hasn't been back home in months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You miss the scenery there, the mountains and the trees,''
Rusch said. ``You get out here, and you hardly even have a hill.
But as much as I like it out there, I like it here a lot, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A-ROD SCRATCHED: Shortstop Alex Rodriguez missed Tuesday's game
with a sore left wrist, the result, he said, of a check-swing and a
slide in Sunday's win at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first game Rodriguez has missed since returning from
his knee injury in mid-May. He was available only to pinch-run and
play defense Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just woke up and it was aggravated,'' Rodriguez said after
the game. ``But I should be all right to play tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   OH, HENRY? The Mariners aren't counting on him, but left-hander
Butch Henry still plans to return sometime next month. He's hoping
to provide some stretch-drive help to a team that is short on
left-handers just three days before the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're by no means out of it,'' Henry said. ``Those games in
August and September are going to be real important. If I can get
back and help us win one or two or five or six games, that's
something. That's what I'm shooting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry, who has been throwing lightly for most of this month,
threw 20 pitches off a mound Tuesday. It was the first time he had
thrown off a mound since tearing the labrum in his throwing
shoulder in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just interested in getting back to help the team that's
been paying me all year long,'' said Henry, who was 2-0 in four
starts before the injury. ``I've said August all along, and that's
what I've got my sights set on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: Game-time temperature was 93 degrees at
Kauffman Stadium Tuesday night, with 100 degrees in the forecast
for today's matinee. ... Kauffman Stadium is the only American
League park in which Alex Rodriguez has played in but not hit a
home run. He has homered in 19 of the 21 parks in which he has
played, including four of five National League parks. The lone NL
park in which he's gone homerless is Dodger Stadium. ... Rodriguez
turned 24 years old Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
