<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ TO MINORS; DODGERS LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the second straight day, the Dodgers lost to
Cincinnati 5-3 in 10 innings Tuesday night at Dodger Stadium as
they collapsed again in extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise here. The Dodgers are 3-8 in extra-inning games and
lost this one when the Reds' only hit in the 10th went about 15
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers reliever Alan Mills (2-4) walked a pair of Reds before
Aaron Boone's basehit bunt loaded the bases, then he walked Chris
Stynes to give the Reds the lead 4-3 in the 10th. Mark Lewis added
a sacrifice fly. The Reds have won four straight games in their
final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, anything that takes place on the field doesn't
seem to matter much.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the talk afterward was about left-handed pitcher Carlos
Perez being optioned to Triple-A Albuquerque, where he's expected
to make at least four starts.
</P>
<P>
   Also, recently benched second baseman Eric Young had MRIs done
on his ailing hamstring and ankle. Trainer Charlie Strasser said
results should be available today.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said Perez's demotion is based on
the lefty not being able to regain his stuff pitching out of the
bullpen. The Dodgers needed to clear a roster spot for right-hander
Robinson Checo, who starts tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would serve (Perez) better than pitching out of the
bullpen,'' Johnson said. ``We just don't feel he can get it back
pitching out of the pen.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez's demotion was expected, but it paints an even uglier
picture on his season. Perez, who declined comment, signed a
three-year, $15.5 million guaranteed contract with the Dodgers in
the offseason. In response, he was 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA. He also
missed one start with a mysterious knee injury in Montreal, and it
was widely reported he was injured while out late the night before
a start.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, 27, also bashed a water cooler in the Dodgers' dugout
after another horrific outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel, (pitching coordinator Jim) Benedict's there, he has a
history with Carlos, and we feel that will benefit him,'' Johnson
said. ``Maybe he'll make four starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Young saga continues. The recently benched second
baseman wants to go on the disabled list and could have his wish
granted based on the MRI. Young, who is complaining of a sore
hamstring, was examined by team doctors before the game. Young
wants to go on the disabled list so he can rest his ailing legs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers don't want to place Young on the disabled list
because baseball rules prohibit trading a player on the DL, and the
Dodgers have been actively shopping him the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' Young said. ``They'll know more
(today). That's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the confusing matter of whether the Dodgers will
trade first baseman Eric Karros or one of the starting pitchers.
The latest club to enter into talks about possibly acquiring Karros
is Toronto, in desperate need of right-handed power in order to
make a push for the wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   There's also discussions ongoing between the Reds and Dodgers
concerning L.A. right-hander Ismael Valdes for either reliever
Danny Graves or Scott Williamson and a minor-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   The chance of that deal happening might have improved with Mark
Grudzielanek's seventh-inning single. Grudzielanek lined a two-out
pitch off Brett Tomko's right hand, knocking the right-hander from
the game. It came after Todd Hundley tied the score 3-3 on a solo
homer earlier in the inning, his 15th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the uncertainty that can only worsen until
Saturday's trading deadline, there was actually a game. Chan Ho
Park left trailing 3-2. He allowed an RBI single to Mike Cameron in
the first, one to Michael Tucker in the third and a run-scoring
single to Stynes in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth's sacrifice fly in the fourth accounted for
the Dodgers' first run and Devon White singled in a run in the
bottom of the sixth to pull the Dodgers within 3-2. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
