<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6465 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-HOMICIDES-SF     07-28 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-HOMICIDES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 POLICE NOW BELIEVE HANDYMAN'S SOLO-KILLER TALE  &HT;     By STACY FINZ, JAXON VAN DERBEKEN and SUSAN SWARD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Law enforcement officials said Tuesday that they
now have independent evidence supporting a motel maintenance man's
confession that he acted alone in the February killings of three
Yosemite tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Stayner, 37, is charged with last week's decapitation
killing of naturalist Joie Ruth Armstrong. Authorities are now
building a case to charge Stayner with the slayings of Carole Sund,
42, her 15-year-old daughter Julie and their 16-year-old friend
Silvina Pelosso. The three visited Yosemite in February and were
last seen alive at the Cedar Lodge _ the motel where Stayner worked
as a fix-it man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good sense of what happened,'' said Tuolumne County
Deputy District Attorney Timothy Clancy. Investigators now have
specific details about how the three were marked for death, killed
and how their bodies were disposed.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the growing body of evidence, investigators have
documented a taxi ride Stayner took after two of the bodies were
dumped. They also said Stayner had information about the weapons
used and the condition of the crime scene _ details only the killer
would know.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, investigators disclosed new information about
Armstrong's death, saying she struggled mightily with her attacker.
``She put up a fight,'' said one source close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner told the FBI and a television reporter that he has
dreamed of tormenting and killing women since he was a young boy.
Speaking to a reporter for stations KNTV in San Jose and KBWB in
San Francisco on Monday night, Stayner said he strangled Carole
Sund and Silvina Pelosso in their motel room in El Portal, just
outside Yosemite's western border. Then he took Julie Sund to a
lake, where he killed her. He did not say how he picked the women
as victims, but swore that he did not torture or sexually assault
them. Authorities would not confirm that information.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner says he took the bodies of Silvina Pelosso and Carole
Sund in their rental car to a secluded spot about 50 miles away in
Long Barn. Stayner then called a cab to take him back to El Portal.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Horvath, co-owner and driver for Courtesy Cab Co. in
Sonora, remembered the $125 fare the moment she saw his picture in
the news. She had picked him up from the Sierra Village Market,
near Long Barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really tired, worn out, he hadn't shaved in a couple of
days,'' she said Tuesday, recalling that he was carrying just a
backpack and told her he had been stranded after coming to the area
with some friends who left without him. He needed to get back to
his job, doing rewiring work in the park, he told her. But at the
gate, he preferred to pay the visitor's fee rather than reveal who
he worked for, she said. Workers are exempt from the fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of creepy,'' she said. ``That's why I usually drive
during the day, because of things like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Horvath said she and her husband were interviewed by FBI agents
during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the cab ride, Stayner says, he returned to Long
Barn to burn evidence and retrieve Carole Sund's wallet, which he
then dumped in Modesto to confuse authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The car was found a month later. Julie Sund was discovered a few
days after that on the banks of Lake Don Pedro _ her head nearly
severed from her body. Sources say Stayner has taken credit for a
letter mailed to the FBI, tipping them to the exact location of the
teenager's body.
</P>
<P>
   The letter is now being analyzed to determine whether it was
indeed sent by Stayner, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   But they believe that he knows too much about the crime and that
there is too much evidence to back up his statements for him not to
be the killer, said one source close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   According to the official, Stayner knew information about what
was taken from the sightseers' motel room and about the conditions
of the bodies. Stayner also knew that knives were used in the
killings, a detail that has not been released to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Even though officials initially had a hard time believing that
Stayner overcame three women on his own and was able to drop their
rental car in Long Barn by himself, they have now come to the
conclusion that he is telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we now know how the transportation occurred,''
Clancy said of how the tourists' rental car was driven to the
wooded area and the killer was able to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner, fond of sunbathing in the nude, was arrested Saturday
at a clothing optional resort near Sacramento. Clancy said local
prosecutors will probably prosecute the handyman in the
Sund/Pelosso case. Clancy is scheduled to meet with Mariposa County
prosecutors later this week to discuss when they will file charges
against Stayner and which county will try the case. The U.S.
attorney's office will try Stayner for Armstrong's slaying, because
she was killed in a national park.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the farm town of Merced, Stayner is the older brother
of Steven Stayner, who was abducted on his way home from school in
December 1972 and sexually abused by his kidnapper for more than
seven years. He escaped in March 1980 and was reunited with his
family, only to be killed nine years later in a motorcycle crash at
age 24.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators interviewed Stayner about the time the three
tourists were reported missing but excluded him as a potential
suspect. Agents believed that several people were involved in the
killings and were focusing on two half brothers from Modesto. One
of the brothers admitted to authorities that he played a role in
the killings. And acrylic blanket fibers found on the bodies
matched fibers found in the men's cars _ leading investigators to
believe they were on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   Now they don't know what to make of the matching fibers,
believing that it may have been a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, a Fresno grand jury has been listening to testimony
about the half brothers and an assortment of their drug associates.
But no charges were ever filed.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, the FBI is saying that the half brothers are still
being investigated to determine whether there is a link.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are still being evaluated,'' said Tron Brekke,
deputy assistant director of the FBI. ``No one is being ruled out.
We don't base our cases on what subjects say _ we base them on the
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stanislaus County Public Defender Tim Bazar, who represents
one of the brothers, said the FBI should leave his client alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have, and never did have, any real evidence to
connect (him) or anyone else (in the group) to the crime _ even
though they kept making the bold statement that they were confident
they had the killer behind bars.''
</P>
<P>
   Bazar said the fiber evidence was dubious at best. Acrylic
blankets are very common and ``you know, heck, ... you probably
have some fibers on you right now from an acrylic blanket,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense attorney said the FBI and police may have focused on
his client out of sheer desperation to solve the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to wait and hear their explanation for that,'' he
said. ``I suppose the one thing they could have done is announced
publicly that they didn't have anything and still needed the
public's help. But they didn't do that. They told everybody the
killers were in custody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bazar said his client continues to cooperate with authorities
and has been interviewed three times, one interview taking place
after Armstrong's body was found several hundred feet from her
Yosemite cabin about four miles from the Cedar Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Armstrong's grieving mother spoke publicly for the
first time since she was notified of her daughter's death Thursday
night. ``Joie was phenomenal _ she rose to every occasion,'' Leslie
Armstrong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
