<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACKING KUBLA KHAN'S DINING CAR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I worked on the railroad once, and the term for lunch break was
``go to beans,'' and we bought snacks from the ``bean wagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Railroaders in Berkeley are hipper. They do drive-by takeout
from Xanadu, a cutting-edge Asian restaurant in what was once a
train station.
</P>
<P>
   Freight trains chuff past several times a day. Last week, a
patron of a nearby pub parked his car on the tracks and an SP train
bashed into it, as trains will do to cars. While the crew was
waiting for the mess to be cleared, Xanadu owner George Chen
invited the lads in for a bite.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later the Xanadu phone rang. It was the same train
crew, ordering take-out. But it's against train rules to make
unauthorized stops, unless there's a car on the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   No, George Chen didn't run out and park a car on the tracks. He
bagged the food and stood trackside as the train approached and
slowed. A crewperson jumped off the engine, gave George a handful
of cash, took the chow and hopped back on.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the story of Berkeley's mu shu choo-choo.
</P>
<P>
   THE NFL is proud of its marketing, but one strange little side
effect is that bad guys like the logo stuff, and it seems like
every time a mass murderer gets arrested, there's a news photo of
him in wearing an NFL team cap or shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle ran a photo of confessed murderer Cary Stayner,
taken in '90 after his uncle was ``mysteriously'' murdered. Cary is
wearing a 49ers cap.
</P>
<P>
   Bad timing. The 49ers just signed a convicted woman-beater,
their in-limbo owner once settled a lawsuit that accused him of
beating a woman, and the backup quarterback was recently tried for
rape, and although declared innocent, evidence indicated behavior
unbecoming a quarterback and a gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   Sure makes it hard for a 49ers fan to make fun of the Dallas
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   LET'S PUT new 49er running back Lawrence Phillips' past behind
him, fine. And let's not nitpick everything he says.
</P>
<P>
   But ... at his welcoming press conference, Phillips talked of
the time he'd been bounced out of pro football as a bad guy and a
lousy player and he was sitting home watching games on TV and no
teams were calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most humbling experience I had,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Not the arrest for beating up a college woman and dragging her
by her hair down several flights of stairs. Not the arrest for
punching a woman in a nightclub because she wouldn't dance with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope those moments are fairly high on Phillips' Top Ten
humbling-experiences list.
</P>
<P>
   BUT PHILLIPS doesn't have a corner on the strange-statements
market. Take the FBI, please.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as Moe Edelstein points out, James Maddock, head of
the FBI in Sacramento, said, ``We have no reason to believe there
is a continuing threat (in Yosemite). I have reason to believe that
there's a killer loose somewhere, but I don't believe the killer is
planning another crime.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; We have tapped into the killer's subconscious mind; now we're &LR; 
 &UR; trying to get his name and address. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AND WHY, wonders Solomon Fisher, did the FBI say there appeared
to be no link between the killing of Joie Armstrong and the murders
of three tourists?
</P>
<P>
   Last seen near Yosemite ... Young women ... Bodies dumped ...
Decapitation ... Nope, no links there.
</P>
<P>
   AS THE OLD saying goes, I never repeat gossip, so listen
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   The Spreckels Mansion in Pacific Heights, now owned by Danielle
Steel, is for sale. Top prospect to buy the manse: John Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   And A Source reports that the Russian River has become a magnet
for very attractive male and female hookers, specifically near the
Bohemian Grove encampment. Source wonders, ``Republicans looking
for their own Monicas?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   WELCOME TO San Francisco, where we beg you not to make the
offhand comment, ``There oughtta be a law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A can for every butt,'' that's our new motto. Mabel Teng's
sidewalk ashtray law passed the supervisors, 9 to 2 (``Leno, Newsom
Soft on Butts''), and now we need a law to fine bar and restaurant
owners who let their butt cans runneth over.
</P>
<P>
   We have no place to park our cars, but at least now everyone
will have a place to park his or her butt.
</P>
<P>
   It's an OK law, as laws go, but the bottom (so to speak) line on
the butt problem: We're a bunch of lazy slobs.
</P>
<P>
   ONE OF THE perks of big-league baseball fame is you get to
choose your own walk-on music, the snippet of song played over the
PA system as you stroll from the on-deck circle to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Giants' shortstop Rich Aurilia, for instance, picked the Beastie
Boys' ``No Sleep Till Brooklyn,'' Rich being a Brooklyn dude.
Charlie Hayes likes Ice Cube's ``We Be Clubbin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds may have changed his tune since the recent flare-up
of his old prenup battle with his former wife. But Barry's walk-on
theme is Puff Daddy's ``Mo Money Mo Problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell me about it, Barrissimo.
</P>
</TEXT>
