 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 438 -- July 28, 1999  ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 438 -- July 28, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. THE BEAT GOES ON FOR CHER Over the years, Cher has zoomed to
musical heights and plummeted to the bottom, but she is
philosophical about it. ``If I had my choice of the two places, the
top is better. But for me, it doesn't change who I am,'' she says.
Currently the roller coaster is at a peak with the phenomenal
success of ``Believe.'' By Jim Sullivan. From The Boston Globe.
1,400 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
WHY THE DVD IS HERE TO STAY It seems that every time a new video
technology emerges, it is announced as the greatest advance since
Al Jolson destroyed the silent film with the immortal words ``You
ain't heard nothin' yet'' in 1927's ``The Jazz Singer.'' Digital
versatile disc (DVD,) a format destined to replace VHS, is
fulfilling the promise. While there are still only about 4,000
titles available - in contrast to nearly 68,000 VHS tapes - the DVD
is setting a faster sales pace than VHS. By Michael Blowen. From
The Boston Globe. 1,500 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
SEASON OF THE 'WITCH' On October 21, 1984, three young people hiked
into Maryland's Black Hills Forest to shoot a documentary film on a
local legend, ``The Blair Witch.'' They were never heard from
again. One year later, their footage was found. Now you can see it
yourself at a cinema near you. Or can you? Five young Florida
filmmakers are currently riding a surprising wave of intrigue and
interest, concerning their first film, ``The Blair Witch Project,''
which cleverly blurs the line between fiction and reality. By
Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
PHIL COLLINS HELPS 'TARZAN' SWING
Singer/musician/songwriter/producer - and occasional actor - Phil
Collins - has released eight multimillion-selling solo albums, plus
another half dozen during his years with the band Genesis. But even
he is awed by the scale of his latest project, five songs for the
Walt Disney Co.'s new animated feature, ``Tarzan.'' ``It has the
potential to be vast - and I don't necessarily mean in financial
terms, just in terms of the kind of audience it can reach once
these things get on a roll,'' Collins says. By Gary Graff. 1,000
words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. ROGER DALTREY : A ROCK 'N ROLL SURVIVOR LOOKS BACK When
singer/actor Roger Daltrey, a pop icon since his days with The Who,
was asked to play an aging rock superstar with serious problems
with drinking and drugs, he hesitated. ``It was a bit too close to
home for me,'' he says. Finally he accepted the role of Nobby
Clegg, an English rocker with serious drink and drugs problems, in
the TV series ``Rude Awakening.'' At 55, Daltrey is one of a
handful of survivors who seem to have emerged more or less intact
from the cauldron of sex, drugs and rock 'n roll. By Ivor Davis.
1,500 words + photos. (N/A Great Britain and Australia.)
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
THE GREAT AND NOT-SO-TERRIBLE OZ ON 'STAR WARS,'
</P>
<P>
   YODA AND JAR JAR BINKS Beyond providing the syntax-challenged
croak of The Force's guiding light in ``Star Wars : The Phantom
Menace,'' Frank Oz also manipulated the Yoda puppet, with
assistance from three fellow puppeteers. He honed his puppeteering
skills under Muppetmaster Jim Henson and is still the voice and
hands behind ``Sesame Street'' and Muppet favourites such as Miss
Piggy, Bert, Cookie Monster and Fozzie Bear. ``The challenge is
taking myself and the other people working the character and
rehearsing for days before we shoot, to get all of our movements
right,'' says Oz. By Ian Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
GHOST STORY : JAN DE BONT DIRECTS 'THE HAUNTING' Jan de Bont, the
high-powered, Dutch-born director of the ``Speed'' films and
``Twister'' says making his kind of movie is very hard and not
always a lot of fun because there's a lot more pressure from the
studio and it's nerve-wracking to get them done. De Bont is back
with another emotional roller-coaster ride for the audience : ``The
Haunting,'' a $75 million horror film. The aural element is very
important in the film. ``It's not only what you can't see, but what
you can hear and can't see that can scare you,'' he says. ``It's
quite often the smallest sound that starts the imagination going.''
By Ian Spelling. 1,500 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
