<HEADLINE>
ALICEA SPARKS RANGERS TO NINTH CONSECUTIVE VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Texas Rangers general manager Doug Melvin created a
petty fuss among several of his peers in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some within the industry found it absurd that the Rangers
committed nearly $5.5 million over the course of the 1998 and 1999
seasons to reserves Luis Alicea and Roberto Kelly. Yet, those
investments continue to reap dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea replaced injured right fielder Juan Gonzalez in the
lineup and drove in three runs for the white-hot Rangers, who won
their ninth consecutive game Tuesday night with an 8-6 victory
against the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any good ballclub has to have a good bench,'' said
left fielder Rusty Greer, whose two-out, two-run double in the
second inning gave the Rangers a 4-2 lead. ``The bench on our club
has a tough job. They don't play regularly with the guys we've got.
They play once in awhile, and they do a great job of performing the
way they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicea learned only minutes before the game that Gonzalez
(strained ligaments, right wrist) would not be available. Rangers
manager Johnny Oates juggled his lineup and placed second baseman
Mark McLemore in right field, and Alicea replaced McLemore at
second base.
</P>
<P>
   The first pitch Alicea saw from Orioles right-hander Mike
Mussina (13-5) resulted in a two-run, game-tying homer in the
second inning. His second plate appearance produced a third-inning
sacrifice fly ball that scored third baseman Todd Zeile and gave
the Rangers a 5-2 lead against Baltimore's Mussina, arguably one of
the American League's three best starting pitchers this season
along with Boston's Pedro Martinez and New York's David Cone.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this has been an atypical season in terms of production for
Alicea, a quality reserve who entered Tuesday night's game hitting
.165 (17-for-103).
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be there when it matters, though,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``Plus, he does all the little things that don't
show up in the box score. We're very fortunate to have Luis Alicea
and Roberto Kelly in this organization. There are a lot of clubs
out there who would love to have them as starters.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Aaron Sele (10-6) pitched into the seventh inning
to join the league's short list of 10-game winners, and the bullpen
allowed only one run over the final three innings when closer John
Wetteland surrendered a ninth-inning, solo home run to Orioles
center fielder Brady Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who allowed eight hits, took a 7-3 lead into the seventh
inning before losing steam. Sele issued a leadoff walk to catcher
Charles Johnson, the Orioles' No. 9 hitter, and then fell behind in
the count to Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson eventually pummeled a 3-1 fastball for the first of his
two home runs, and that pulled the Orioles within two runs.
Left-hander Mike Venafro and right-hander Jeff Zimmerman, though,
slammed the door there by pitching two scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Rangers not only extended their winning steak, but the
victory snapped the Orioles' six-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing well right now,'' said Alicea, who fielded all
five of chances in the field cleanly and was involved in one double
play. ``Every facet of our team is doing well. Everything is going
right.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
