<HEADLINE>
WRIST AILING RANGERS' GONZALEZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Right fielder Juan Gonzalez will undergo a magnetic
resonance imaging test once the Rangers return to Texas should the
discomfort in his right wrist persist, trainer Danny Wheat said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez removed himself from the lineup Tuesday night after
experiencing more discomfort during batting practice and remains
day-to-day. Gonzalez injured the wrist Friday while sliding into
third base. X-rays taken then revealed no fracture, but Gonzalez
strained ligaments in the wrist, Wheat said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez returned to the lineup Sunday after missing Saturday's
game and was examined again Monday in Cooperstown, N.Y., by Dr.
John Conway, the Rangers' orthopedic consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore replaced Gonzalez in right field,
and reserve infielder Luis Alicea replaced McLemore as the second
baseman. DECLINING INTEREST RATE
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' level of interest in Orioles right-hander Juan
Guzman appears to be declining.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles plan to start Guzman (5-8, 4.21 earned-run average)
tomorrow against the Rangers, but general manager Doug Melvin, who
accompanied the team to Baltimore, does not plan to stay for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen him enough,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman, who will earn $5 million this season and can become a
free agent this winter, remains the subject of trade speculation.
Nevertheless, Melvin did not meet Tuesday with Orioles general
manager Frank Wren.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin plans to travel to Pulaski, Va., tomorrow and spend two
days there to evaluate the Rangers' rookie-league affiliate in the
Appalachian League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been to Pulaski in the two years they've been with
us,'' Melvin said, ``and I'd like to see our rookies.'' BELLE
REJECTS KRLD
</P>
<P>
   Orioles right fielder Albert Belle rejected a request to be the
guest for the Rangers' pregame radio show during this three-game
series in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Belle, Albert's brother and business manager, informed
KRLD's Eric Nadel through an e-mail that ``Albert really wants to
focus on the games at hand and just doesn't have time in his
schedule for an interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadel informed the Belles that the interview would require only
four or five minutes and among the topics to be discussed included
Albert's charitable contributions. Nadel also informed the Belles
of their willingness to do the interview and any time and that it
would be broadcast by the Rangers' radio network, which includes an
affiliate in Shreveport, La., Belle's hometown. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Luis Alicea snapped two streaks with his two-run,
second-inning home run off right-hander Mike Mussina Tuesday night.
It was Alicea's first home run since Sept. 22, 1998, and the first
of his career against the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno attended Tuesday night's game
and sat in the stands with four secret-service agents. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
