<HEADLINE>
STARS RE-SIGN YOUNG WINGERS MARSHALL, WRIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After saying goodbye during this off-season to veterans Pat
Verbeek, Craig Ludwig and Dave Reid, the Dallas Stars have given
new contracts to restricted free-agents Grant Marshall and Jamie
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Stars general manager Bob Gainey said Tuesday the club had
signed Marshall to a three-year deal and Wright to a one-year pact.
Financial terms were not released.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, a physical right winger, suffered a severe groin
injury that sidelined him for all six games of the Stanley Cup
Finals win over the Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall, a four-year veteran, established personal
career-high marks in the regular season with 13 goals and 31 points
while playing on an effective third line with Mike Keane and Guy
Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, 29, also set highs for game-winning goals with four
and shots taken with 112. He was fourth on the team in penalty
minutes with 85. He has 37 goals, 89 points and 390 penalty minutes
in his four seasons with the Stars, covering 282 games.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall also proved durable, playing in every regular season
game last season, becoming the only Stars player to do so. He added
three assists in the postseason, all in the Western Conference
semifinals against the St. Louis Blues. He played in 14 playoff
games.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, a 23-year-old left winger, appeared in 11 games for the
Stars last season and didn't score. He has appeared in 32 games for
the Stars over two seasons, scoring four goals and six points.
</P>
<P>
   A Stars' fourth-round selection in the 1994 NHL Entry Draft, he
spent most of last season with the Kalamazoo (Mich.) K-Wings in the
International Hockey League. There, he totaled 16 goals, 15 assists
and 92 penalty minutes. He will be given a chance to make the
Stars' 24-man roster. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
