<HEADLINE>
VOLS HEAR CALL TO WIN TITLE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Tee Martin remembers getting asked while
making a flight connection in New Orleans. Phillip Fulmer remembers
being asked 10 minutes after Tennessee had defeated Florida State
to win the 1998 national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you repeat?''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, a nice question to face for a quarterback, a coach,
a program. The Volunteers' quest to win back-to-back national
championships was a hot topic Tuesday during the Southeastern
Conference football media days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flew to New Orleans from Arizona, and when I got off the
plane somebody asked, `Can we do it again?' '' said Martin, a
senior quarterback who is 13-0 as a starter. ``I said, `Man, let me
enjoy this one first.' They're demanding at Tennessee. The put
pressure on you to perform. I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer said that, soon after his team's 23-16 victory against
the Seminoles in the Fiesta Bowl, he was being asked during his
postgame radio show about redshirt freshmen and who would figure in
plans for this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the `Coach, are we going to do it again?' a lot,'' he
said Tuesday. ``Our players know they have a target on their backs,
but I really don't think it's that much different from years
past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers, ranked No. 2 or No. 3 in most preseason polls,
return 14 starters. They should be especially strong at running
back and on the lines. However, Fulmer must replace middle
linebacker Al Wilson, the defensive leader, and big-play wide
receiver Peerless Price.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee opens the season Sept. 4 at home against Wyoming. The
Volunteers face SEC road challenges at Florida, Alabama and
Arkansas, plus a nonconference home game against Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the potential to be better than last year's team,''
Martin said. ``We've just got to go out and do it. I think this
team is still humble. We're ready to go work hard and get dirty.''
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Arkansas coach Houston Nutt said his coaching staff made an
off-season visit to Michigan to study the Wolverines' program.
``They've got three offensive lines, three defensive lines,'' Nutt
said. ``They're doing drills, and the coaches just say, `Next.'
That's a good word for a coach. That means you've got depth. We
want to get to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia sophomore quarterback Quincy Carter, who has played in
the Chicago Cubs' minor-league system as a right fielder,
questioned his future with the Cubs. ``I check out their games to
see how their right fielder (Sammy Sosa) is doing,'' Carter said
with a smile. ``That guy is going to be there for five, 10 years. I
don't think I'm going to be playing right field in Wrigley Field.
Maybe they'll move me to left.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Said LSU coach Gerry DiNardo: ``We're expanding our stadium to
91,600 in 2000. So, we'll have another 10,000 coordinators.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
