<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOERNER CAN'T ELUDE MEMORY OF FUMBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ It wasn't a brain-dead triple bogey to lose a
major golf championship. It wasn't a grounder through the legs to
lose a World Series. All Clint Stoerner's Big Mistake did was
change the course of last year's college football season.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas was leading top-ranked Tennessee, 24-22, in Knoxville,
Tenn. The Razorbacks had the ball and were 1:43 away from going 9-0
and landing feet first in the national championship race.
</P>
<P>
   Then Stoerner, a junior who threw for a school record 2,629
yards and 26 touchdowns, stumbled on a roll out. As he fell, he
fumbled. Tennessee recovered, drove for the winning points and went
on to win the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   All Stoerner has is a lifelong memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play, I don't think I'll ever be allowed to forget it, by
myself or anybody else,'' Stoerner said in the middle of an
interview huddle Tuesday during Southeastern Conference football
media days. ``It's the biggest play, from the negative side, I've
ever been a part of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get mad at you guys for asking the question. I'm
comfortable talking about it. In football, bad things come along
with the good things.''
</P>
<P>
   For Arkansas, the good thing was an unexpected turnaround. The
Razorbacks, 4-7 in 1997, were picked to finish last in the SEC
West. Instead, under first-year coach Houston Nutt, Arkansas rode
its 8-0 start to a 9-3 finish that included a trip to the Citrus
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner, a 6-2, 210-pound senior from Baytown Lee (Texas) High
School, leads an offense that returns its leading rusher, passer
and top five receivers. Seven starters return on defense. This
season, the Razorbacks are predicted to battle Alabama for the SEC
West Division title.
</P>
<P>
   But the memory of The Fumble is casting a shadow over the 1999
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard to get away from,'' Stoerner said. ``Right
after it happened, it seemed like it popped up every week. I'm a
big fan of ``SportsCenter'' and I was happy to be on there.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner has turned his link with infamy into a positive. Nutt
said that in his first season he noticed the Razorbacks were
national champions in the blame game. Stoerner is evidence that is
no longer the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had guys who would say, `I confess, it's your fault,' ''
Nutt said, crossing his arms and pointing his fingers in opposite
directions. ``What I loved about Clint in that situation, (after
the fumble) was that he stepped up in front of all those
microphones and said, `It was my fault' over and over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner's fumble was Tennessee's greatest escape in a
championship season that included narrow victories against
Syracuse, Florida and Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 20, 21 years old, and to have something like that
happen, I can feel his pain,'' Volunteers quarterback Tee Martin
said of Stoerner's fumble. ``Every day you're going to hear about
it. I know today that's the main question he's been asked. I admire
him for being a man about it. It says a lot to fall down and lose
what you have and then get back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner, while sticking to the time-honored tradition of one
game at a time, said he has Nov. 13 circled on his calendar. That's
when Tennessee plays at Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up to be a responsible individual. When you do
something, good or bad, you take responsibility for it,'' Stoerner
said. ``Honestly, that was my first reaction after the fumble.
There's no sense in pointing fingers.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
