<SLUG> BC-CAR-LABONTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOTAL PACKAGE HAS LABONTE IN PURSUIT OF CUP TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett's chances of winning the Pennsylvania 500 were
hampered by a balky clutch, but even with perfect equipment the
Winston Cup points leader realized it would have been tough to
catch race-winner Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we could have caught Bobby,'' the
ever-gracious Jarrett said after finishing second. ``They have the
complete package: fuel mileage, setups.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's first comment referred to Labonte's dominant
performance Sunday at Pocono International Raceway. The 35-year-old
native of Corpus Christi won by a whopping 8.655 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second comment, though, that's important. Jarrett was
commenting on Labonte's season as a whole, not just one race.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's team has the complete package _ a talented driver,
good equipment, good personnel _ and that's why he's having the
best season of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we do have all the ingredients,'' crew chief Jimmy
Makar said. ``You can't ask for more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte used to be an ``on any given Sunday'' driver. On any
given Sunday he was a threat to win.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Joe Gibbs Racing in 1995 and won seven races in four
seasons. The team was one of the best on the Winston Cup circuit,
finishing seventh and sixth in the points the past two seasons, but
it wasn't among the handful of elite groups that are serious title
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac is a
threat to win on every given Sunday, and Labonte is in the
championship hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, the younger brother of two-time Cup champion Terry
Labonte, is third in the points, a mere 29 behind Mark Martin in
second. Jarrett is just a blip on the radar screen, 254 ahead of
Martin and 283 in front of Labonte. He'll be tough to catch,
especially if he keeps having races like the one Sunday, when he
finished second despite equipment problems.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, though, isn't ready to concede.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can still catch Dale Jarrett in the points race,''
he said. ``We haven't given up on the championship by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte can match Jarrett in almost every statistical category.
</P>
<P>
   The victory at Pocono was his third of the year, the same as
Jarrett; only Jeff Burton and Jeff Gordon, with four each, have
more.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte has earned four poles and has 13 top-five and 14 top-10
finishes. He has led at least one lap in 16 of the 19 races.
</P>
<P>
   It's the other races that have him looking up at Jarrett. He has
five finishes of 24th or worse, including 37th in the Food City 500
at Bristol (Tenn.) Motor Speedway and 38th in the Jiffy Lube 300 at
New Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Inconsistency kept Labonte from being among the elite last year,
when he failed to finish six races. He said that hasn't been the
case this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had some bad luck in a few races, and that's cost
us,'' he said. ``But even in the races where we finished bad, we
were running very well until our luck went bad.`
</P>
<P>
   Every successful team needs a little bit of racing luck to be
successful. Parts can't break; wrecks must be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   But fortune has little to do with Labonte's breakthrough season.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the success is that Labonte, in his seventh
season as a Cup driver and his fifth with Gibbs, is at his peak as
a driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's matured a lot as a race-car driver,'' Makar said. ``One
big thing I've seen him do is learn patience. I think early in his
career he had been trying a little too hard to impress people and
show what he could do in a race car and maybe pushed the envelope a
little bit to make that statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Another is Gibbs' decision to join the ranks of the multicar
teams and add Tony Stewart as Labonte's teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Stewart has really helped our program,'' Labonte said.
``A second team has brought more resources and more ideas to the
table. We've been able to get a lot of helpful feedback from Tony
and that team. They've already tested 10 times and we've tested
five, so they've been to five more racetracks than we have and come
back with more information.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Makar was concerned that adding a team would mean a
slow start because of the adjustment period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we were going to give something up in the first
half of the season with the new car and a new team coming on board,
with the distractions and the learning curve,'' he said. ``We felt
like we'd go through some growing pains that might hinder our
performance early in the year. Quite the contrary has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   What has happened, though, is Labonte establishing himself as
one of the truly elite drivers in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a great season no matter what happens from tomorrow
on,'' Labonte said. ``I won't forget that. I've definitely done
more than I've done in a whole season before. It's been a great
season no matter where we finish in points.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
