<HEADLINE>
GOLFING MOM REACHES HALL OF FAME DOORSTEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confession being good for the soul, golf instructor Brian
Inkster offered this telltale tidbit about his favorite former
pupil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think she would ever get back to being a great
player again,'' Inkster said, reflecting on a winless stretch from
1993-96 that led his wife, Juli, to consider retiring from the LPGA
Tour to stay home with the couple's two daughters. ``I guess that
shows how much I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. By Sunday night, Inkster could be married to a Hall of
Famer. At the very least, he's married to a 39-year-old who has a
chance to become the first LPGA player since 1986 to win three
major championships in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Bradley made her mark that year. Juli Inkster, with a
victory in this week's du Maurier Classic, would match that feat.
And she would do so with the pitter-patter of tiny feet belonging
to daughters Hayley, 9, and Cori, 5, tromping along in her gallery.
</P>
<P>
   At the box office, this summer may belong to Sam. But on the
LPGA Tour, June and July have belonged to Juli. With victories at
the U.S. Women's Open and the LPGA Championship, Inkster has struck
a blow for working mothers. Four years after considering
retirement, she stands one victory away from enshrinement in the
LPGA Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I wanted to prove myself after I had my family
that I could come back out here and be a top player again,'' said
Inkster, whose task has grown simpler as her children have outgrown
port-a-cribs and diapers. ``It was very frustrating for me when the
girls were little, coming out here and being a mediocre player. I'd
always been a top player and I knew I had it in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster has proved that this summer. Now, she stands in the path
of history and at the threshold of the Hall of Fame. But Inkster
declines to dwell on what might happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy with what's going on in my life and with my
golf game,'' said Inkster, who has four victories this season and
owns a slight lead over Karrie Webb in the race for player of the
year. ``I'm planning to enjoy this week because I'll probably never
have this chance again. If I don't play good in another tournament,
no one can take these past six months away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Least of all a husband who is happy to admit he underestimated
his wife's resolve in her darkest days as a professional golfer.
TOP PLAYERS TAKING DIFFERENT APPROACHES TO `SHOWDOWN'
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it's time to bestow bragging rights on one of the two
players who have exchanged the title of world's top-ranked golfer
throughout the 1999 season. And the respective methods in which
Tiger Woods and David Duval are preparing for Monday's overhyped,
made-for-TV showdown in Thousand Oaks, Calif., sheds ample light on
the importance each gives to the event.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is skipping this week's PGA Tour stop, the Canon Greater
Hartford Open, and has indicated he may squeeze in a practice round
at Sherwood Country Club before meeting Duval in Monday's 7 p.m.
match on WFAA/Channel 8. Duval is playing in Hartford, Conn.. If he
contends or wins, he may arrive in California fresh off a
cross-country flight on the morning of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he's excited to have a match with Duval because
``people have talked about us having a rivalry that could last 20
years, and we've never really gone head to head before.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval is more subdued, noting that the ``Showdown at Sherwood''
barely qualifies as a blip on the radar screen in terms of global
golfing significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to determine who the best player in the world
is,'' Duval said. ``It's not the U.S. Open or the Masters on
Sunday, with us going head to head.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's the closest thing TV executives can provide until the
world's top two players actually play their way into a meaningful
shootout at a major championship.
A SHORT(S) STORY
</P>
<P>
   This week's Canon Greater Hartford Open marks the second event
in a three-week stretch in which caddies will be allowed to wear
shorts at PGA Tour events when the heat index reaches 100 degrees.
The policy will be reviewed by tour officials after the Buick Open
(Aug. 5-8), the final event in the trial period. Shorts remain off
limits for PGA Tour players, regardless of weather conditions.
ENCOURAGING WORDS
</P>
<P>
   Lori Kane, owner of seven second-place finishes without a
victory in a three-year LPGA career, said words from Hall of Famer
Nancy Lopez helped ease her pain after a playoff loss to Sherri
Steinhauer at the Big Apple Classic (July 15-18).
</P>
<P>
   ``Lopez reminded me that, even though she's won 48 times, she's
also had 48 second places. That helped,'' Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Lopez has 49 runner-up finishes _ one more than her
career total of victories. Lopez, 42, will compete in this week's
du Maurier Classic after missing the past month because of
arthroscopic knee surgery. SHORT PUTTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Austin, Texas, resident J.L. Lewis, champion of last week's
John Deere Classic, became the 13th first-time winner in the
event's 28-year history. A former Nike Tour participant, Lewis also
extended a streak in which at least one Nike Tour graduate has
cracked the top 10 in 164 consecutive PGA Tour events. The last
miss came in the 1996 Mercedes Championship.
</P>
<P>
   _ Come-from-behind victories have been rare on the Senior Tour
this season. Final-round leaders have held on to win 17 of 23
events.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS ... PERENNIAL WINNERS
</P>
<P>
   Of the 25 active players on the PGA Tour with at least 10
victories, only five have averaged more than one win per season
throughout their careers. A breakdown of the top 10: Player Seasons
Wins Avg. Tiger Woods 4 10 2.5 David Duval 5 11 2.2 Phil Mickelson
8 13 1.6 Tom Watson 28 34 1.2 Greg Norman 16 18 1.1 Nick Price 17
