<HEADLINE>
STRAIGHT TEETH BECOMING A MUST
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color cartoon of a girl with braces 
 Includes a 700-word sidebar 
 By Suzanne Boynton 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Braces have become almost a rite of passage in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The number of youngsters with braces has quadrupled since the
1960s, and it's up from 3.5 million in 1989 to more than 4.5
million now.
</P>
<P>
   Greater awareness of the benefits of orthodontia, easy-credit
financing and more dentists practicing orthodontia account for the
increase, say the experts.
</P>
<P>
   Some 80 percent of the orthodontia patients are juveniles, 20
percent are 18 and older, and the majority are female.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodontics treatment averages about $4,000 per patient. It's
not covered by many dental plans, but financing plans are widely
available.
</P>
<P>
   The ''perfect smile'' is often mentioned as the goal of
orthodontia, and it usually does improve appearance. But there are
even more vital reasons to straighten teeth: crooked teeth are
harder to clean, wear unevenly, and cause stress on the jaw and gum
tissues. These can add up to more severe, more expensive problems
later. The need for treatment is increasing, say orthodontists.
</P>
<P>
   ''About 50 percent of the people could use it; 25 percent need
it,'' says Dr. Donald Guest, who has practices in Santa Rosa and
Petaluma, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Fossil records show a steady decline in jaw size during the past
1,000 years. The number and size of teeth also has diminished, but
not as fast as jaw size. For the last 100 years or so, few people
have had room for their wisdom teeth, or 17-year molars. These
teeth are often turned sideways, so they cannot come in correctly,
a condition dentists call ''impacted.'' Impacted molars can
continue to cause trouble if they're not surgically removed.
</P>
<P>
   To call themselves orthodontists, dentists must graduate from an
accredited academic program. Certification by the American Board of
Orthodontics is not required. To become board-certified,
orthodontists must pass a two-part written exam and present 10
completed patient cases before a group of peers. The process can
take as long as a decade to complete.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,895 orthodontists are board-certified in the specialty,
according to the American Board of Orthodontists _ roughly 25
percent of the number who belong to the American Association of
Orthodontists.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodontics practices gross between $227,000 and $579,000
annually, with about half going for office overhead and the rest as
profits.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about orthodontists, contact:
</P>
<P>
   The American Board of Orthodontics, 401 N. Lindbergh Blvd.,
Suite 308, St. Louis, Mo. 63141 or visit the board's Web site:
www.americanboardortho.com. The board will confirm whether an
orthodontist is certified in the specialty.
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for an orthodontist in your area, call the
American Association of Orthodontists at its toll-free telephone
number, 1-800-787-2444. The organization's Web address is
www.braces.org.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebar:
 &UR; Hi-tech braces less painful, less noticeable &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Kitschy television shows have been broadcasting nostalgia for
the 1960s and '70s. But those were the bad old days for kids with
crooked teeth. A lot has changed since the era of metal bands,
pliers and pulled teeth. Let's review: Back Then
</P>
<P>
   Braces were installed by gluing around each tooth a metal band
with a bracket attached. A stiff, stainless-steel wire was fastened
to the brackets with short lengths of wire that the orthodontist
bent and twisted into the desired shape with needle-nose pliers.
</P>
<P>
   This painful process was repeated every few weeks or so, causing
predictably sore gums and, not uncommonly, headaches. Every few
visits, a stiffer wire was applied, adding to the discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   The total thickness of all the bands in the mouth was about
equal to that of a tooth, said orthodontist Dr. Thomas Bales of
Santa Rosa, Calif. To make room for the bands in an already crowded
mouth, a tooth often had to be pulled.
</P>
<P>
   But they couldn't remove just one.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mouth is symmetrical, so if you remove one on one side,
you have to remove one on the other side,'' Bales says. ''Remove
two on top, and you have to remove two on the bottom, or you create
an overbite.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a set of braces almost always meant pulling at least four
teeth.
 &UR; Today's Braces &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are no bands around the teeth. The brackets are
glued to the outside of the teeth and are fitted to the shape of
each tooth, so the wire doesn't have to be twisted to get the
desired shape.
</P>
<P>
   Stainless steel has been retired. The wire band is now a
''memory'' metal alloy of nickel and titanium developed by NASA for
use on satellites. The memory wire is bent into the shape of the
ideal dental arch. Under refrigeration, it slumps like spaghetti,
and is easy for the orthodontist to work with. Once it's installed
and reaches mouth temperature, it ''remembers'' its original shape
and begins gently urging the teeth into that perfect-smile shape.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is much lower than that exerted by the old wires,
yet it works just as quickly, with longer periods between
adjustments, said Dr. Donald Guest, an orthodontist in Santa Rosa
and Petaluma, Calif. ''The discomfort is a lot less _ some adults
have none.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else has changed, too. Kids want today's high-tech
braces.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 7- to 9-year-olds seem to enjoy the process,'' Guest says.
''It's cool for them to have braces.''
</P>
<P>
   Today many orthodontists favor a two-stage treatment for most
patients. It usually starts at age 7 to 9, goes for 12 to 15
months, takes a break until adolescence, then goes another 12 to 15
months.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used to do it only when all the teeth were through, age 13
to 15,'' Bales says. ''Most of the growth had taken place, so
severe overbites would become even more severe, and you'd ask a
15-year-old to wear headgear 20 hours a day. That was not very
realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The more serious the malocclusion (bad bite), the worse you
need two-phase treatment,'' says Guest, because orthodontics can't
deal with both the major crowding problems and the more detailed
work of perfecting the bite at the same time.
 &UR; Pick Your Colors &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Today's braces have accessories that also make the wearing easy.
</P>
<P>
   There's a special wax to press onto the parts of the braces that
rub the inside of a tender lip at night or while eating.
</P>
<P>
   There's the floss threader, which enables those with braces to
floss between her teeth above the braces.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the rainbow of rubber band colors.
</P>
<P>
   The rubber bands that hold the wire to the brackets are changed
at each visit.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could have red for Valentine's Day, red and blue for the
Fourth of July, orange and black for Halloween, favorite team
colors,'' Bales says. ''Our visits used to run 12 minutes each. Now
it's 15 _ it takes three extra minutes for the kids to pick their
colors.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Suzanne Boynton writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
