<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWING-GOURDS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY-TO-GR0W GOURDS MAKE NIFTY CRAFT PROJECTS
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of colorful large and small gourds 
 By SUSAN McCLURE 
 c.1999 Susan McClure 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before copper and ceramics, people relied on natural containers
_ such as gourds _ to carry water and food.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest preserved examples of gourds come from Mexico and
Peru. Choctow and Chickasaw Native Americans made gourd birdhouses
to attract colonies of purple martins and clear the air of insects.
Gourds have been, and still are, made into instruments _ drums,
harps, lyres, and primitive guitars and banjos.
</P>
<P>
   More than mere ordinary household objects, gourds also have
generated their own superstitions, writes Ginger Summit in ''Gourds
in Your Garden.'' In Hawaii, pot-bellied men planted gourd seeds
with the hope that the gourd would grow to mimic the planter's
round physique. In 16th century England, women were not allowed to
handle gourds for fear they would ''feeble and wither.''
</P>
<P>
   Today gourds are avidly grown by gardeners and crafters.
</P>
<P>
   Bottle gourds, most of which originate in Africa, include a
variety of rounded, hard-shelled gourds named by their shape _
cannon ball, basket ball, canteen, sugar bowl, bushel basket, and
kettle. There are pear-shaped bottle gourds and long-necked penguin
gourds used for bird houses, vases, and, of course, bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Dipper gourds have a bottom bulb with a long, thin, handle-like
neck. Banana and snake gourds are long and slim _ some growing into
oddities 5 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond these classic gourds are the ornamental gourds you use to
stuff a cornucopia at Thanksgiving time. True kid-pleasers, these
gourds come in bright green, gold and orange and are shaped like
oranges, pears, spoons, crown of thorns, apples, and bells with
smooth or warty textures.
</P>
<P>
   Loofa gourds, available in elongated oval or small ball shapes,
are commonly harvested when very young for Oriental cuisine and
served marinated, pickled, or stuffed. Let the gourd reach full
maturity and the fibrous interior becomes an organic scrubber for
kitchen or bath.
 &UR; Growing Gourds &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Plant seedlings outdoors in a garden with full sun and plenty of
space or a trellis to ramble up.
</P>
<P>
   To eliminate weeds, you can cover the gourd bed with black
plastic mulch. Summit suggests cutting planting holes in the
plastic every 4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Fast and feisty growers, gourd vines need rich soil, best
provided by adding extra compost or rotted livestock manure to the
planting area or even the entire gourd bed.
</P>
<P>
   If seedlings start slowly, they may need an extra fertility
boost. Water with fish emulsion now and again as the plants begin
to vine. But once the flowers appear, stop applying nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
   Such lavish, tropical vines use an abundance of water so run a
soaker hose beside the vines. Be sure not to let the soil dry out
for the first 4 to 6 weeks after planting. After that you may need
to water only once or twice as week. It's natural for the large
leaves to wilt during hot summer days _ even if the soil is moist _
so don't worry. But if the leaves don't perk up by evening, that's
a sign the plants need more water.
</P>
<P>
   Stop watering in fall as the gourds grow mature and hard.
</P>
<P>
   To get more gourds and less rambling growth, Summit suggests
cutting off the growing tip of 10-foot long vines to encourage side
branches to sprout. Side branches produce more female blossoms and
thus more fruit.
</P>
<P>
   If you get a kick out of growing big pumpkins and zucchini,
you'll probably want to try some of the monstrous snake gourds and
other big gourds. They may be best allowed to ramble along the
ground where weight will not be an issue. If growing gourds on a
trellis, provide extra support with a pantyhose sling to keep a
hefty gourd from tearing the vines down.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've conquered gourd growing, you can explore the fine
art of gourd shaping. While young and pliable, gourds are
especially malleable. You can etch patterns in the surface of a
gourd, using care not to push through the skin. You can surround
the gourd with a firm mold, such as a wooden box to make the gourd
assume a square shape. You also can twist a long-necked gourd
around a post to make it into a spiral.
</P>
<P>
   Let gourds mature completely before harvesting them. For long
lasting hard-shelled types, this means waiting until the vine dies
to cut them free. Expect to give them another couple months to dry
indoors too, until the gourd is light and the seeds rattle inside.
Although it might appear something is going wrong, these gourds
reach their prime when the outer skin discolors and appears to
decay.
</P>
<P>
   To reveal the beautiful woody gourd beneath, soak the gourd in
warm water for an hour, holding it down beneath a weighted pan lid,
then use a copper kitchen scrubber to remove the skin.
</P>
<P>
   You can polish gourds with liquid floor wax or vegetable oil to
show off their natural luster and also carve them and decorate as
desired.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan McClure lives in Indiana and writes about gardening.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
