A6676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHERRY-TOMATOES29-COX     07-28 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERRY-TOMATOES29-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Cherry tomatoes: Roundly applauded
</P>
<P>
   By Ann Heller
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Some backyard gardeners worry about rampant
zucchini. They probably haven't confronted a cherry tomato plant on
a roll.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in the summer, the cherry tomatoes ripen in waves.
Vines are weighted down with fat clusters, begging to be pulled off
by the handful.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly they end up being eaten like a snack. But there are other
ways to put this abundance to good _ and very easy _ use. Unlike
big tomatoes, these sweet little morsels don't have to be peeled,
seeded or cored. They're ready to use after a brief rinse.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a one-size-fits-all crop. Cherry tomatoes come in a
variety of sizes, colors and sweetness, from the so-called yellow
pear to red grape tomatoes, so it's worth sampling the offerings of
various farmers to find what you like.
</P>
<P>
   One variety fancied in this area is the low-acid, super-sweet
Sweet One Million cherry tomato, an offspring of the better known
Sweet One Hundred.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a handful of ways to let cherry tomatoes star in your
meals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make grown-up snacks called Tomatoes Margarita: This easy
recipe is so good it should become the hit of the summer party and
picnic season. First, pull the stems from two pints of cherry
tomatoes. Mince 1/4 cup cilantro very fine and combine with 1/2 cup
coarse sea salt in a small bowl. Combine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup tequila and the juice of a lime in another bowl. Tell
guests to dip the tomatoes in the tequila, then into the seasoned
salt. Addictive!
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The recipe is from the new book ``Tomatoes'' by Patricia Mack
(Record, $16.75).
</P>
<P>
   _ Saute cherry tomatoes as an easy side dish. Rinse the tomatoes
and remove the stems. Place on paper towels to dry. Heat a little
oil or butter in a large skillet and add some minced onion or
slivered garlic. Cook a minute or two. Add cherry tomatoes, no
deeper than a single layer. Cook over medium heat just until the
tomato skins start to blister, about four or five minutes. Sprinkle
with salt, pepper and snippets of fresh herbs such as basil or
mint. The tomatoes should remain whole; if they collapse they
become mushy. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a quick pasta sauce. While pasta is cooking, heat equal
parts of olive oil and butter in a large skillet. Saute the chopped
white and green parts of a bunch of green onions and when they are
soft, add about a teaspoon minced garlic. Stir for a minute and add
a heaping pint of stemmed cherry tomatoes and cook, shaking the
pan, three or four minutes. Season with salt and pepper and a
generous handful of chopped herbs. Add a half cup or so of the
pasta cooking water to the sauce and continue cooking. As the
tomato skins begin to burst remove from heat. Drain the pasta and
toss with the sauce. Top with freshly grated Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make German tomatoes using cherry tomatoes in this family
recipe that can last for days in the refrigerator. Rinse and stem a
pint of cherry tomatoes. Wash and cut an equal amount of small
pickling cucumbers into slices. Cut a medium onion into rings.
Combine vegetables in a bowl and sprinkle with salt and pepper and
2 or 3 tablespoons sugar. Combine 5 tablespoons cider vinegar and 3
tablespoons water and mix with the vegetables. Stir until sugar is
dissolved and taste for balance, adding more sugar or vinegar if
needed. Refrigerate for at least an hour.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a balsamic cherry tomato salad: Cut the cherry tomatoes
in half and sprinkle with coarse salt to draw out juices to flavor
the dressing. After a half hour, sprinkle with snipped chives and
parsley. Make a balsamic vinegar dressing (two parts olive oil to
one part vinegar) and pour over tomatoes. Arrange a mound of
arugula (now available at some supermarkets by the bag instead of
the ounce) on a plate and pile the tomatoes on top. Because both
the tomatoes and vinegar are sweet, taste and add salt to balance
the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
