<HEADER>
A6677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHERRYTOMATO-RECIPES2     07-28 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERRYTOMATO-RECIPES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tomatoes add zest to dishes
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Cherry tomatoes are showcased in this
French-style gratin that's a wonderful summer side dish. The
tomatoes are covered with a ricotta-and-basil mixture and baked
just 15 minutes, so they remain whole. Take a bite and each warm
tomato explodes with flavor.
</P>
<P>
   CHERRY TOMATO GRATIN
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dried bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup snipped fresh basil, divided
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ricotta
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Choose a shallow baking dish large enough to hold the tomatoes
snugly packed in a single layer. Using 2 tablespoons of the olive
oil, grease the bottom and sides of the dish. Add the tomatoes,
rolling them around to coat with the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the bread crumbs, garlic, 5 tablespoons of the basil,
1/4 teaspoon of the salt and the pepper. Sprinkle half of the
mixture over the tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the ricotta, the remaining 3 tablespoons basil and 1/2
teaspoon salt, the eggs and cream. Stir until well blended and
creamy. Pour over the crumb-topped tomatoes. Sprinkle with the
remaining bread-crumb mixture and drizzle with the remaining 1
tablespoon oil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake about 15 minutes until bubbling. The tomatoes should not
have burst. Let cool slightly before serving. Offer crusty bread to
mop up the juices.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 164 calories, 11 g
fat, 69 cholesterol, 158 sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _ The recipe is from ``The Vegetarian Table'' (France) by
Georgeanne Brennan (Chronicle, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Cherry tomatoes also do well in a supporting performance in this
pasta salad that a friend adapted from ``Food and Wine'' magazine.
For more cherry tomato inspiration, check out the July issue of
``Gourmet'' magazine, which has Sicilian cherry tomato pasta sauce
on the cover, Greek cherry tomato and tuna salad as ``The Last
Touch'' and a BLT salad made with cherry tomatoes in between.
</P>
<P>
   NICOISE-STYLE ORZO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound orzo
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup oil-cured olives, pitted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small red onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons drained capers
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Bring a medium pot of salted water to a boil. Add the orzo and
cook until al dente. Drain and rinse under running water, then
drain again. Transfer to a bowl and add the olives, tomatoes,
onion, parsley and capers.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the vinegar, garlic and a pinch each of kosher salt and
pepper. Whisk in the oil until emulsified and pour over orzo
mixture. Toss to mix. Refrigerate but bring to room temperature
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 375 calories, 16.6
g fat, no cholesterol, 213 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
