<HEADER>
A6678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHERRYTOMATO-TIPS29-C     07-28 0196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERRYTOMATO-TIPS29-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   If you must tinker with a good thing. . .
</P>
<P>
   While cherry tomatoes beg to be used as is, there are recipes
that call for hollowing them, stuffing them and serving them as
appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   It's time-consuming and fiddling work, but if you feel inclined,
here's a tip to make it easier:
</P>
<P>
   Many recipes suggest hollowing out the stem end and trimming a
smidgen off the bottom so the tomato will sit flat. But if you do
that it quickly begins to seep juices.
</P>
<P>
   A much better technique is to set the tomato stem side down
without cutting it. Hollow out only the other side, which is the
blossom end. Positioned stem-side down, the tomatoes are less
likely to roll. If the possibility still worries you, serve
tomatoes on a stabilizing bed of rock salt.
</P>
<P>
   Also make sure you select large cherry tomatoes. It's difficult
to hollow out small ones (the melon baller is the usual tool
suggested).
</P>
<P>
   Fillings are myriad. Think of seasoned cream cheese, hummus,
olive tapanade and bean purees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ann Heller, Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
