A6680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COLLEGE-PREVIEW29     07-28 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-PREVIEW29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols, 'Noles on collision course
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida State and Tennessee, opponents for the national
championship last January, are on a collision course for a rematch
in the 2000 Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Six of seven preseason magazines on college football ranked
Florida State No. 1, and a seventh, The Sporting News, put Penn
State on top. Tennessee, which won the national championship by
beating Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl, edged Penn State for the
second spot because it was ranked No. 2 four times and No. 3 three
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the talent everybody has coming back, a
Florida State-Tennessee rematch seems like a real possibility,''
said Charlie Miller of Athlon magazine. ``There are very few teams
around that can put as much talent on the field as those two.'' One
of them could be Penn State, which would have been No. 2 if not for
a No. 7 ranking from Street &AMP; Smith's. Coach Joe Paterno returns 41
of his top 48 players and has a favorable schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, it just looks like all the stars are lined up for Penn
State,'' said Tom Dienhart of The Sporting News, which ranked the
Nittany Lions No. 1. ``This is Paterno's 50th year at Penn State.
Jerry Sandusky, his longtime defensive coordinator, is retiring
after this year. They don't play Wisconsin, and they have Michigan
and Ohio State at home. It seems set up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn State does, however, have a potentially dangerous season
opener against No. 4 Arizona, which travels to State College on
Aug. 28 for the Pigskin Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State is a strong No. 1 based on the return of wide
receiver Peter Warrick and running back Travis Minor on offense and
a defense expected to be even faster and more talented than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team can be as good as it wants to be,'' Warrick said at
last week's ACC Football Meetings. ``And we want to be very, very
good. Losing to Tennessee hurt this team. We want another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus of the magazines picked Michigan No. 5, followed
by Texas A&AMP;M and Nebraska. Wisconsin and Florida tied for eighth,
and Ohio State was 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech was ranked No. 11 with a high ranking of No. 8 and
low of 14. Georgia was tied with the University of Miami for No. 13
with a high ranking of No. 8 and a low of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Picking the Top 25 is no exact science, but it can be a
painstaking effort for the magazines.
</P>
<P>
   At Athlon, for example, Miller gets input from the five members
of his editorial staff and from the various freelance writers who
contribute to the magazine. He also has a fact sheet on each of the
114 Division I teams with information about the key returning
players and how recruiting could affect the quality of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I lock us all up in a big room, and we fight it out until
we have 25,'' Miller said. ``Some picks are very easy. Others we
have real battles over.''
</P>
<P>
   At The Sporting News, Dienhart makes the final selections after
consulting with his writers and reading fact sheets on each
Division I school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, we'll go a little out on a limb with a pick,''
Deinhart said. ``But that's what makes this business fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ACC, Florida State was the unanimous pick to win a least
a share of the title for the eighth year in a row. Georgia Tech got
all of the No. 2 votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the SEC, all seven of the magazines picked Tennessee to win
the Eastern Division, with Florida and Georgia following. Two
magazines, Athlon and Jeff Whittaker, picked the Bulldogs to finish
ahead of Florida. In the Western Division, Arkansas got four
first-place votes to edge out Alabama. LSU was a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
