<HEADER>
A6681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS29-TAKE     07-28 1974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS29-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take one of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: News reports say that if the space shuttle Columbia had to
make an emergency landing, it would be either in Florida or West
Africa. I've never heard that NASA had any landing strip in Africa.
Do you have any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: NASA says there are four contingency Transoceanic Abort
Landing (TAL) sites: Yundum International Airport, Banjul, Gambia;
Ben Guerir Air Base, Morocco; and Moron Air Base and Zaragoza Air
Base, both in Spain. The TAL sites for STS-93 are Yundum (primary)
and Ben Guerir (alternate), according to NASA spokeswoman Kirsten
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on mission requirements, an orbiter follows an orbital
insertion inclination between 28.5 and 57 degrees, with the lower
inclination preferred because it allows for a higher maximum
payload weight.
</P>
<P>
   Yundum is on a flat plain 7 miles inland from the Atlantic and 6
miles south of the Gambia River. It lies almost directly below the
28.5-degree flight path. The runway is 11,810 feet long and 150
feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco is between 27 degrees and 37 degrees north. Ben Guerir,
a former Strategic Air Command base abandoned in 1963, is on a
flat, rocky plain about 36 miles north of Marrakech. Its runway is
14,000 feet long and 200 feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several articles have referred to the penthouse residence of
John F. Kennedy Jr. and Carolyn Bessette Kennedy in TriBeCa. What
does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: Spelled both TriBeCa and Tribeca, it's an area of Manhattan
whose name stands for Triangle Below Canal (Street).
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the story concerning the father of Lauren Bessette and
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy? He hasn't been mentioned in all the
coverage about the sisters' deaths.
</P>
<P>
   A: The sisters' father, William Bessette, and their mother, Anne
Freeman, divorced when Lauren Bessette and her twin, Lisa Ann, were
8 (Carolyn was 18 months younger). The children were raised by
their mother and her second husband, Dr. Richard Freeman, chief of
orthopedic surgery at White Plains Hospital in White Plains, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Bessette has remained conspicuously out of the public eye and
apparently didn't attend public services for his daughters. Or if
he did, it escaped notice. Very little is known about him. One
report published last week described him as a cabinet salesman from
White Plains; another said he was an architectural engineer in
White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani visiting
Arkansas mentioned the state's lieutenant governor, Winthrop
Rockefeller. Is he part of the northeast Rockefeller clan? Do you
have any other information about him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, he's part of the clan. Winthrop P., the Republican
lieutenant governor of Arkansas, is the only son of Winthrop
Rockefeller, who served as the Republican governor of Arkansas from
Jan. 10, 1967, to Jan. 12, 1971. John Davison Rockefeller of
Standard Oil fame had one son, John D. Jr.; John D. Jr. had five
sons (John D. III, Nelson, Laurance, Winthrop and David).
</P>
<P>
   Winthrop P. (or ``Win'') has been involved in public service in
Arkansas for more than 25 years, working with the Boy Scouts of
America, the Nature Conservancy, the Winthrop Rockefeller
Foundation, the Arkansas Cancer Research Center, the Arkansas Arts
Center Foundation, the Arkansas Crime Commission and the Arkansas
State Police Commission. He also was chairman of the President's
Council on Rural America, appointed by President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller attended Oxford University and is a graduate of
Texas Christian University. He has seven children and with his
wife, Lisenne, maintains homes in Little Rock and at Winrock Farms,
Petit St. Jean Mountain, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about ``Unto These Hills,'' the
outdoor drama? What is the subject, and how can we get tickets?
</P>
<P>
   A: The play, in its 50th anniversary season, covers nearly 300
years of Cherokee history, from 1540 (the encounter between the
Cherokees and Spanish explorer Hernando de Soto) until the late
1830s (the ``Trail of Tears,'' the forced removal of the people to
Oklahoma). It's presented nightly (except Sundays) in the outdoor
Mountainside Theatre, a 2,800-seat facility in Cherokee, N.C. The
current season opened June 11; it ends Aug. 21. Tickets are $11-$14
for adults, $5 for children 6-12. Information: online at
www.dnet.net/(tilde)cheratt or 828-497-2111.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did John F. Kennedy Jr. ever serve in the Navy? If not, how
was he eligible for burial ceremonies at sea involving a Navy ship?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kennedy never served in the military. Under Navy regulations,
U.S. citizens without military connections can be buried from a
naval vessel only if the chief of naval operations makes an
exception in recognition of their ``notable service or outstanding
contributions to the United States.'' Adm. Jay Johnson, the chief
of naval operations, ordered the USS Briscoe to participate after
being Defense Secretary William Cohen asked him to support a
request by Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.).
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon statement said Kennedy qualified for burial at sea
not only because his father was president and a World War II Navy
hero, but also because the 38-year-old Kennedy's contributions to
his country ``are both notable and outstanding.'' The statement
cited his role as head of Reaching Up, a nonprofit group that
assists people who work with the disabled, and his service on the
President's Commission on Mental Retardation.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 members of the military and their children are buried
at sea each year, according to the Navy, but they are buried en
masse, their ashes scattered during normal naval exercises. By
contrast, the destroyer Briscoe was diverted from routine training
exercises offshore of Norfolk, Va., to the site off Martha's
Vineyard, Mass., where the ashes of Kennedy, his wife and
sister-in-law were committed to the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With flags being lowered for John F. Kennedy Jr.'s death,
everyone seems to say ``half-staff.'' But when I was growing up,
the term I always heard for displaying flags during periods of
mourning was ``half-mast.'' Which is correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: It should be half-staff on land, half-mast at sea. The terms
are used interchangably in a civilian context, but in military
useage, it depends on the branch of service involved. It's
half-mast in the Navy and Coast Guard, half-staff for all other
branches.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm fascinated by the name Martha's Vineyard. Was there a
Martha, and was there a vineyard?
</P>
<P>
   A: The island first was called Louisa, according to the Martha's
Vineyard Chamber of Commerce. It got that name in 1542 by Italian
navigator and pirate Giovanni da Verrazano, who sailed past it. The
Indians called it Noepe, and other explorers gave it different
names. But the one that stuck was given in 1602 by Bartholomew
Gosnold, who named it for one of his daughters, Martha, and for the
wild grapes that grew on it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With all the interest in Kathleen Ann Soliah and the
Symbionese Liberation Army, I'm wondering: What has become of the
boyfriend who was living with Patty Hearst when she was kidnapped?
And what has happened to Patty herself?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hearst was engaged to Steven Weed when the kidnapping
occurred at their apartment in Berkeley, Calif., on Feb. 5, 1974.
He now is married, the father of two sons, and works for a property
management and real estate investment firm in Menlo Park, Calif. He
seems to prefer not dwelling on the past, and isn't much interested
in discussing the present, either. ``That's the beginning and the
end,'' he once told Time magazine. Weed did, however, write a book
in 1976 titled ``My Search for Patty Hearst.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, meanwhile, is married, has two teenage daughters, and is
a resident of New York and Westport, Conn. She has written two
books and has appeared in several films by offbeat director John
Waters. She shows up often at celebrity and charity events in New
York, where her husband, Bernard Shaw, a former San Francisco
police officer and her onetime bodyguard, is an executive with the
Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm 76 and have been following the space program ever since
the early '50s. What was the temperature encountered by the
American astronauts when they landed on the moon? I've never seen
it reported.
</P>
<P>
   A: The surface temperature of the moon at the time and in the
place of the lunar landing site was estimated at 40-90 degrees F in
the sun and 150 degrees below zero F in the shade. Neil Armstrong
and Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin Jr. were encased in spacesuits providing
a temperature-controlled atmosphere that was kept at about 68
degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the JFK Jr. accident, did all of the government agencies
respond on a normal basis, or was it at the behest of the president
or family members in Massachusetts with clout?
</P>
<P>
   A: Federal officials said that in the early days, when the focus
was on finding survivors, the mission essentially was like
thousands of others. But it's obvious that the search became much
more aggressive and sophisticated than efforts usually launched for
average citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about it at a news conference, President Clinton said:
``Because the Coast Guard felt they had the capacity to succeed and
because of the role of the Kennedy family in our national lives, I
thought it was appropriate to give them a few more days. And if
anybody believes that was wrong, the Coast Guard is not at fault, I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that the federal government spends at least
$370 million a year on small plane and boat search and rescue
operations. The Coast Guard alone says it handles more than 40,000
rescue cases a year, including 400-500 plane crashes. The National
Transportation Safety Board, the other lead agency in the Kennedy
case, says it investigates every plane crash, including some 1,900
accidents involving private planes last year.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials, meanwhile, say public interest and the media
contributed to the decision to add resources to the Kennedy search.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was no media interest, we wouldn't need to have as
many people there,'' said Phil Frame of the NTSB.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any directory of fax, cell phone and pager numbers?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, but you can find some of those numbers in some
advertisements in the Yellow Pages. BellSouth spokesman Jeff
Batcher said it's up to consumers whether their cell, fax or pager
numbers will be made public. Those are considered private numbers
of the individuals, so they're listed only at the customer's
request.
</P>
<P>
   Q: California State Sen. Tom Hayden has proposed a new law to
force the elderly to take annual driving tests. Is he the anti-war
activist once married to Jane Fonda?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, Hayden, a Democrat, is Fonda's ex. His measure, which
would apply to drivers in California, narrowly cleared the state
Senate last month and faces stiff opposition in the state Assembly
from the senior citizen lobby. Hayden's bill, SB 335, is also
called the Brandi Mitlock Safe Drivers Act, after a 15-year-old
killed by a 96-year-old hit-and-run driver as she crossed a Santa
Monica street. The driver reportedly had rebuffed repeated attempts
by family members to surrender his car keys.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require California drivers 75 and older to take
written, vision and road tests for regular license renewals. After
age 80, they would be required to take those tests every three
years; after 86, every two years; and after 90, every year.
</P>
<P>
   (More)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
