<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6682 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS29-TAKE     07-28 1829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS29-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2 takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A said the Atlanta Hawks basketball team once played as the
Tri-City Blackhawks. Where was that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tri-City refers to the sister cities of Davenport, Iowa, and
Moline and Rock Island, Ill. The term Blackhawks probably came from
the famous Native American chief, Black Hawk, who once lived in the
region. The Blackhawks, of the old National Basketball League,
started there in 1946. When the team moved to Milwaukee in 1951,
owners shortened the name to Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can we obtain tickets to next year's baseball All-Star
game in Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   A: Information is not yet available. Look for an announcement
about tickets sometime between the first of next year and the start
of spring training, said Braves publicist Glen Serra.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is Caesar Rodney and why is he depicted on the 1999
Delaware quarter?
</P>
<P>
   A: The coin honors Rodney for a historic horseback ride July
1-2, 1776, that made him the hero of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   The Continental Congress was meeting that spring and summer to
contemplate declaring independence from the British Crown. The
Delaware delegates included Thomas McKean and George Read, both of
New Castle, and Rodney, of Kent. McKean and Rodney were in favor of
independence, but Read felt that it was too drastic a move.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney received a message from McKean saying that on July 2, the
Continental Congress would vote on the issue. Knowing that Read was
opposed, McKean asked Rodney to rush to Philadelphia. Despite
hardships _ historical accounts say he was suffering from a serious
facial cancer and asthma, and he endured summer heat and
thunderstorms _ Rodney made the 80-mile ride and arrived at the
Pennsylvania State House during the last minutes of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   He made it just in time to cast his vote, breaking the tie among
Delaware's delegates in favor of the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you quote the passages of Scripture that John F. Kennedy
Jr. read at the services after his mother, Jacqueline Kennedy
Onassis, died?
</P>
<P>
   A: At the funeral mass May 23, 1994, at Manhattan's St. Ignatius
Loyola Roman Catholic Church, Kennedy prefaced his Scripture
reading and those of others by saying they ``captured the essence
of my mother . . . her love of words, the bonds of home and family
and her spirit of adventure.'' His reading, from Isaiah 25:8: ``The
Lord God will wipe away the tears from all faces.''
</P>
<P>
   At the graveside service at Arlington National Cemetery, he read
from 1 Thessalonians 4:13-18: ``But I would not have you to be
ignorant, brethren, concerning them which are asleep, that you
sorrow not, even as others which have no hope, for if we believe
that Jesus died and rose again, even so them also which sleep in
Jesus will God bring with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this we say unto you by the word of the Lord, that we
which are alive and remain unto the coming of the Lord shall not
prevent them which are asleep, for the Lord Himself shall descend
from heaven with a shout, with the voice of the archangel and with
the trumpet of God, and the dead in Christ shall rise first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, we which are alive and remain shall be called up
together with them in the clouds, to meet the Lord in the air, and
so shall we ever be with the Lord. Therefore comfort one another
with these words.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of former Milwaukee/Atlanta Brave Eddie
Mathews? During the great pregame show at the All-Star Game, it
seemed like every living old-timer was there except him.
</P>
<P>
   A: Mathews, who lives in Del Mar, Calif., was injured in a fall
a few years ago, requiring a lengthy convalescence. But he has made
a ``fine recovery,'' said Braves spokesman Glen Serra. Mathews is
doing so well, in fact, that he's scheduled to be in Atlanta for
induction into the inaugural Braves Hall of Fame ceremony Aug. 20,
along with Henry Aaron, Phil Niekro and Warren Spahn.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did former House Speaker Newt Gingrich ever fully repay the
$300,000 he borrowed to pay his ethics fine?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. But he didn't borrow the money after all, even though it
was widely reported that Bob Dole had offered to make such a loan.
Gingrich paid the penalty out of his own personal funds. The
payment was structured so that Gingrich would close the books on
his punishment by the end of the 105th Congress, which, as it
turned out, also was the end of Gingrich's congressional career
because of his unexpected retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where I can file a complaint against an airline? I don't want
to write to the airline itself.
</P>
<P>
   A: The U.S. Department of Transportation's Aviation Consumer
Protection Division is the place. It operates a complaint handling
system for consumers who experience air travel service problems
(not to be confused with concerns about airline safety or
security).
</P>
<P>
   Call, write or e-mail the ACPD to register your concerns. The
24-hour phone line: 202-366-2220. Regular mail address: Aviation
Consumer Protection Division, U.S. Department of Transportation,
Room 4107, C-75, Washington, DC 20590. E-mail address:
airconsumer(AT)ost.dot.gov
</P>
<P>
   The division requests that you be brief and concise in
describing your problem, and that you include your name, address
and daytime phone number; the name of the airline or company about
which you're complaining; and the flight date, flight number and
origin and destination cities of your trip. If you write, you also
should include a copy of your airline ticket (not the original) and
any correspondence you already may have exchanged with the company.
</P>
<P>
   While the division doesn't mediate individual consumer
complaints, all complaints are entered into the DOT's computerized
aviation industry monitoring system and are charged to the company
in question in the monthly Air Travel Consumer Report.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you provide some background information on Eileen
Collins, commander of the latest space shuttle mission? Also, is
she by any chance the daughter of Michael Collins, one of the
Apollo 11 astronauts?
</P>
<P>
   A: Air Force Col. Eileen Marie Collins, the first woman assigned
by NASA as a space shuttle commander, is not related to Michael
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   She was born Nov. 19, 1956, in Elmira, N.Y., to Jim and Rose
Collins. She graduated from Elmira Free Academy in 1974; received
an associate in science degree in math/science from Corning (N.Y.)
Community College in 1976; a bachelor of arts degree in math and
economics from Syracuse University in 1978; a master of science
degree in operations research from Stanford University in 1986; and
a master of arts degree in space systems management from Webster
University (St. Louis) in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Selected by NASA in January 1990, Collins became an astronaut in
July 1991. Initially assigned to Orbiter engineering support, she
also has served on the astronaut support team, worked in Mission
Control as a spacecraft communicator, and served as the astronaut
office space systems branch chief. A veteran of two space flights,
Collins logged more than 419 hours in space before the recent
Columbia flight. She piloted STS-63 (Feb. 2-11, 1995) and STS-84
(May 15-24, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   She is married to Pat Youngs; they have one child.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the Federal Aviation Administration require operators of
hot air balloons to be licensed?
</P>
<P>
   A: An individual operating a hot air balloon is required to have
a private pilot certificate with a balloon rating. That rating is
an addendum to a private pilot certificate allowing the person to
operate a balloon, said agency spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do porter and stout beers compare in calories and alcohol
content to regular beer and lite beer?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's ``quite a bit of variability'' in the percentages of
alcohol content and calories in beer, said Chris Rosenbloom,
spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association and a professor
at Georgia State University. A number of factors are involved,
including the country where the beer is produced.
</P>
<P>
   But she cited these as average, approximate comparative
statistics, based on a serving of 12 ounces (a normal-size bottle):
regular beer, 5 percent alcohol, 155-170 calories; lite beer, 4.1
percent alcohol, 100-120 calories; stout, 4 1/2 to more than 7
percent alcohol, 170-220 calories; and porter, 5 1/2-6 1/2 percent
alcohol, 212-240 calories.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Articles about the Kennedy family tragedies listed the death
of Patrick Bouvier Kennedy shortly after birth. But didn't John F.
Kennedy and Jackie have a fourth child, who was stillborn some
seven months before John F. Kennedy Jr. was born? That child never
seems to be mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   A: A daughter was stillborn, but not in the time frame you
mention. That daughter, who was unnamed, was stillborn on Aug. 23,
1956. Caroline Kennedy was born on Nov. 27, 1957. John Jr. was born
on Nov. 25, 1960. Another son, Patrick Bouvier, was born
prematurely on Aug. 7, 1963; he died two days later. Both the
stillborn child and Patrick are buried at Arlington National
Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Two of John and Jacqueline Kennedy's children were buried at
Arlington National Cemetery. I thought Arlington was restricted to
those with a military background. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because of limited space, burial at Arlington is reserved for
specific categories of honorably discharged U.S. service members,
such as those who died while on active duty; those who have had at
least 20 years of active duty or active reserve service; and
several other categories, including the spouse of an eligible
service member and any unmarried minor children (under 21 years).
Exceptions have been granted by the secretary of the Army.
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy was eligible for burial in Arlington by his
military service in World War II and by his position as the
nation's commander-in-chief, explained Sgt. 1st Class Lewis Matson
of the U.S. Military District of Washington. As such, his
under-21children were eligible for burial with him. In December
1963, his two deceased children were reburied in Arlington: Patrick
Bouvier Kennedy, who died two days after he was born prematurely on
Aug. 7, 1963; and an unnamed daughter who was stillborn on Aug. 23,
1956.
</P>
<P>
   Complete information on Arlington, including burial policies,
can be found online at the Military DIstrict's Web site:
www.mdw.army.mil
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know the Red Cross is experiencing a shortage of blood, and
I want to help. How can I find out where to donate?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call 1-800-GIVE-LIFE (1-800-448-3543), which is set up
through the Red Cross national offices in Washington. It will route
calls to your local blood services region and will provide blood
drive information for your area up to four weeks in advance. This
information changes routinely as blood drives are added or removed
from the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   End Take Two.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
