<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSESHOES29-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The town that loves horseshoe competition
</P>
<P>
   By Ben Sutherly
</P>
<P>
   Miami County Bureau
</P>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, Ohio _ Tori Eaton raised her right arm until the
horseshoe in her gloved hand leveled with her forehead.
</P>
<P>
   She paused, her eyes focused 30 feet away on a steel stake
driven into a bed of clay. Riveted onlookers tuned out clanks from
other pitching courts at Greenville's city park.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, with a windup less pronounced but just as deliberate
as that of an underhand softball pitch, Eaton lobbed the horseshoe.
One of its heels caught the stake and the shoe spiraled down. A
ringer.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, another metallic clink boosted Eaton's standing
in the World Horseshoe Tournament's 17-and-under girls division.
She and her opponent walked up to the pitching box to inspect their
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two ringers _ six,'' Eaton called to the scorekeeper, who
marked the scorecard with two O's, each denoting three points.
</P>
<P>
   Before the World Horseshoe Tournament ends Saturday, some 1,500
competitors hailing from 47 states, Canada and Norway will pepper
scoresheets with thousands of X's and O's _ a tangible tribute to
Greenville's love affair with horseshoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here pitches, versus at home, where everyone's like,
'What's horseshoes?''' said Eaton, 17, of Andover, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a fling, any longtime Greenville resident will
tell you. Although home to only 14,000 residents, the Treaty City
is holding its fifth world tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our best horseshoe tournaments have been pitched here
in Greenville,'' noted Paul Stewart, field vice president of the
National Horseshoe Pitchers Association, which oversees the
tournament. ``This was a hotbed for horseshoes for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Darke County's horseshoe tradition had humble beginnings, with
many learning the game by tossing shoes once trodden by draft
horses at stakes driven into dirt barn floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the late 1940s or early 1950s, a group of Greenville
residents began pitching from one guy's backyard across an alley
into another guy's backyard,'' recalled Jerry Williams, a member of
the Darke County Horseshoe Club, which boasts more than 80 members.
</P>
<P>
   Four pitching courts opened in the city's park not long after
that, Williams said, and the Annual Ringer Classic, held over the
Fourth of July weekend, soon became a staple of summer life in
Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's horseshoe pitching championships were first held here in
1957; since then, Greenville has held all but one state
competition. The park had 18 pitching courts by 1962, when the city
welcomed its first world tournament.
</P>
<P>
   While the park still holds several world tournament games,
including the championships, which begin Thursday, most of the
competition is at the Darke County Fairgrounds. The two-week event
is expected to draw 7,000 people. Adding to crowds last weekend at
the fairgrounds were festivities celebrating the life of Annie
Oakley, another dead ringer with Darke County roots.
</P>
<P>
   In the power-washed, freshly painted swine barn, four huge fans
stirred sultry air as competitors pitched on 16 courts surrounded
by chain link fence. Though accustomed to pitching in
air-conditioned comfort at the world tournament, many veteran
competitors made light of temperatures in the mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that handkerchief?'' grinned Lee Wallace, 74, of Dallas,
Ore., holding out a sweat-soaked red cloth as he exited the swine
barn. ``Oregon doesn't have this kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, whose 43.0 ringer percentage at the 1994 world
tournament in Syracuse, N.Y., earned him the senior Class C
championship, can appreciate Darke County's legacy of horseshoe
pitching. A World War II veteran, he described a photograph of
himself as a young serviceman, holding a horseshoe while standing
in front of a pitching court in Guam.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace still harbors hopes of finding a horseshoe with a
``U.S.'' marking someday, though he suspects the military
deep-sixed many of its horseshoes in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the horseshoes didn't come back,'' he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   But friends from past competitions do. Wallace says he still
exchanges Christmas cards and insults with a Kansan he met at his
first world tournament 12 years ago in Eau Claire, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just typical of the salt-of-the-earth types you meet in
horseshoes,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Though more likely to forge a friendship than pitch a fit, most
contestants come to the World Horseshoe Tournament already familiar
with the sport's finer points and ready to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out with a flip, but now I throw a turn shoe,''
mused David Crichlow, 39, of Lakewood, N.J., as he pored over an
array of $45 horseshoes designed to meet any pitcher's style.
``I've raised my average _ (the turn shoe) holds more ringers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to playing horseshoes besides just wanting to,''
added Crichlow, who is competing in his first world tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers like Crichlow must have competed in at least four
sanctioned events to qualify for the tourney. World tournaments
tend to bring out more first-time pitchers like Crichlow when held
in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,900 qualifiers competed at Columbus, Ohio in 1992 _
an all-time record in the event's 81-year history. Ontario, Canada,
attracted the event's second largest group _ 1,700 pitchers _ in
1997. The pitchers gathered here will put Greenville right after
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Local entrepreneurs aren't missing the economic opportunities
linked with their visitors. Kids in Christ, a youth group at
Painter Creek Church of the Brethren in Arcanum, is making its
first booth appearance at a world tournament. By collecting cans
and selling drinks, snacks and ice cream to horseshoe pitchers, the
group hopes to offset the cost of attending a national youth
conference in Colorado in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business has been fantastic,'' said Edna Fourman, a church
member. ``The kids are doing it. We're just supervising.''
</P>
<P>
   Businesses beyond the fairgrounds also are looking to cash in on
the tournament, which will pump an estimated $3 million to $4
million into the area's economy, said Tracy Tryon, chairman of
Greenville City Council's finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Stardust Motel on Ohio 49 at Greenville's southern edge
hasn't needed its flashing neon star to beckon weary travelers
since the horseshoe tournament kicked off July 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's filled us up for two weeks,'' said Carolyn Irvine, an
assistant at the motel.
</P>
<P>
   With just 178 rooms available in Darke County, many horseshoe
pitchers are lodging in neighboring communities. One-third of the
guests at Troy's Super 8 Motel are in town for the tournament, and
pitchers booked 50 of 62 rooms at the Howard Johnson Express Inn in
Piqua.
</P>
<P>
   During their two-week stay, horseshoe pitchers have been
``regulars'' at Will's Family Dining on Greenville's Wagner Avenue.
The restaurant normally closes at 11 p.m., but will remain open
until midnight through the tournament to accommodate additional
patrons, manager Sheryll Kovacs said.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant employees have been jolted by a few culture shocks
while serving horseshoe pitchers, Kovacs added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelle had a table of three men, and they did not understand
shucking corn,'' Kovacs said. ``It was really neat hearing her tell
them about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Connecticut guys?'' waitress Michelle Lengers chimed in,
still amazed that someone could confuse field corn and sweet corn.
``They were a riot. They had no clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, visitors have taught Greenville that its luck extends
beyond a strong tradition in horseshoe pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCombs, president of the Darke County Horseshoe Club,
recalled a Philadelphia couple who asked him if their children
could play in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a surprised McComb told them, but their next question
about the park made him think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the security?''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Sutherly writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
