<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stresses of high school not forgotten _ or are they?
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was the week before our 25th high school
reunion, and the e-mails poured in like distress signals from a
sinking ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last week before this reunion thing and panic is
setting in,'' wrote my friend Janet. ``The letter said the Saturday
night thing would include `games'? What do they mean by this?
Trivial Pursuit? The kinds of idiotic games one plays at Tupperware
parties? Who can name the high school football team members? Also,
what does one wear? Helphelphelphelp .''
</P>
<P>
   I tried to reassure her there would be no such horrors as high
school Jeopardy. The e-mails came anyway:
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last quarter century I've confronted and dealt with a
number of pieces of my past and tried to make my peace with them.
High school, however, is not one of those things. I'm afraid I'll
have flashbacks. Do you know, one of my shrinks actually tried to
diagnose me with post-traumatic stress disorder?''
</P>
<P>
   I wondered how many people, from the most popular to the
outcast, experience post-high-school PTSD. What is it about high
school memories that turn normally self-confident adults into great
quivering globs of jellyfish?
</P>
<P>
   Janet, granted, had more reason than most to be apprehensive. We
became friends in 9th grade in part because of natural bookworm
affinity, and in part because nobody else would have us. While I
had been actively ignored, she had been, at times, actively picked
on _ one of those kids too brainy, too head-in-the-clouds, to
comprehend how to navigate the social firmament.
</P>
<P>
   In vain my friends and I tried to convince her that she had
every reason to go to the reunion and gloat _ a great job, great
husband, great life.
</P>
<P>
   But the e-mails kept coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my hair done for the occasion and told my stylist to
make me look 'successful and sane.' When she said, `Oh no, here
comes the wish list,' I replied, `At least I didn't ask for young
and thin.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the big night arrived, and hundreds of my classmates _
the Kettering Fairmont East class of '74 _ congregated on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   I arrived fashionably late to find Janet in a huddle of friends.
I hovered protectively for a minute, but she didn't seem to need
me.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seemed to have exorcised the Ghosts of High School
Past. For Janet, it was a night of revelations, the reunion having
achieved what all her friends had not. All our talk of her
accomplishments had not gotten to the heart of the issue. More
important, she realized, is that since high school ``I have become
a better person _ more stable, more able to deal with people, more
confident, more able to sympathize with and help others, more able
to sustain friendships, more able to try new things.''
</P>
<P>
   The other big revelation: ``Not everyone hated me,'' she said.
``So many people seemed happy to see me and interested in what I'd
been doing that I decided that probably wasn't true after all.''
</P>
<P>
   In adolescence our images are refracted through so many
distorted lights _ the way we see ourselves, the way everyone else
sees us, the way we fancy everyone else sees us.
</P>
<P>
   I recalled a conversation I overheard at the reunion. Two women
dissected high school cliques in descending order of popularity (a
society as exquisitely stratified as any Edith Wharton novel).
Their tone was half amusement, half sociological interest. How
fascinating it all was, and how completely it didn't matter now.
</P>
<P>
   What mattered was that, on a balmy Saturday night, we could all
talk face to face, as adults, as equals, as friends.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
