<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-EGGLADY29-COX     07-28 2036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EGGLADY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impoverished, laborers count on offerings from 'Egg Lady'
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ They call it the day-labor site, this paved lot
with covered benches at the foot of Austin's skyline. Scrub trees
and weeds line a chain-link fence where trash collects. Police cars
frequent the area almost as much as the day laborers and homeless
people. There are smelly, bedhead men with wild eyes. You don't
want to be here if you don't have to _ really, it's an open, giant
trash bin.
</P>
<P>
   The street people here are no better off than the pigeons. And
they both wait for food, because they know it will come.
</P>
<P>
   The Egg Lady is their lone hope this morning.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m., she drives into the lot. The men, like the pigeons,
are stirred. Lynn Goodman-Strauss, a portly, gray-haired woman of
53, has barely opened the back seat door when they've formed a line
like choir boys.
</P>
<P>
   The buffet starts at the hood of her 1986 Buick Century, where
she gives the communion of the street: hard-boiled eggs, two H-E-B
tortillas and a banana. Everyone eats: The men get the food, the
pigeons pick at the eggshells discarded on the ground. The line
wraps around to the trunk area, where a Hungry Man-size bottle of
Louisiana Hot Sauce and a salt shaker make the crude breakfast
tacos tastier. This simple offering is their jump-start of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eggs get our bodies going in the morning,'' says Sam
Hernandez, 52, who travels here from Houston to find work. ``But
it's her words that give us hope. She really cares.''
</P>
<P>
   They're Austin's downtrodden, but this devoted crusader sees
goodness. Everyone here is her friend.
</P>
<P>
   Every Monday, Tuesday and Thursday for the past 10 years,
Goodman-Strauss has appeared like clockwork at the corner of Cesar
Chavez and San Antonio streets, where more than 300 men come daily
with hopes of getting picked up to do a variety of odd jobs no one
else wants to do.
</P>
<P>
   Now, her ministry with the city-operated day-labor program is
coming to an end: When the city moves the program to Interstate 35
and 51st Street, her free-breakfast program cannot follow. But
Goodman-Strauss just plans to move to other areas in the city where
people are hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food we provide is a symbol of encouragement and hope that
these men will find work. I can do that anywhere _ that is,
encourage people not to give up,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Eggs are sacred to her; they symbolize resurrection. She finds
it peaceful when she's cooking them. She washes her hands for 20
seconds because she read somewhere that that's how long it takes to
get them completely clean. Then she prays over the 90 eggs she's
stacked so carefully in the blue speckled stockpot. ``Thank you
God, for the animals and the people that make this possible.'' She
brings them to a boil and then cooks them 10 minutes more. ``I used
to like to eat hard-boiled eggs, but I'm sick of them now,'' she
confesses.
</P>
<P>
   She's handed out more than 150,000 over the years.
</P>
<P>
   To get a sense of why she does it, we need to go back to when
Goodman-Strauss was a 14-year-old attending St. Stephens Episcopal
School in Austin. She was influenced by a chaplain who repeated and
repeated Jesus' teaching that ``those to whom much has been given,
much will be required.'' Then her father went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   She had to wear second-hand clothes, and people at church bought
her school supplies. She found out what it was like to be in need.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1967 on a trip to New York City with her then-husband,
Goodman-Strauss visited Dorothy Day's Catholic Worker program,
founded during the Depression on the principle of Matthew 35 and
36: (ITAL) ``For I was hungry, and you gave Me something to eat; I
was thirsty, and you gave Me drink; I was a stranger, and you
invited Me in; I was naked, and you clothed Me; I was sick, and you
visited Me; I was in prison, and you came to Me.'' (END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   With a 6-week-old child in her arms, Goodman-Strauss found
herself fascinated with the soup line. ``The people giving the food
knew the people getting the food,'' she recalls. The experience
took root and never left her.
</P>
<P>
   Then when she was 25 and already the mother of two boys,
complications from a miscarriage sent her into a coma. She saw this
``wonderful light'' she knows was God. He told her this was the
only time she'd ever have the choice of coming toward the light or
going back to her family. ``I could hear the loving voices of
angels and saints,'' she says. God showed her her babies in a field
with their father walking toward her. They were all getting older
as they got closer. ``I said, 'I want to go back to my babies.'''
That is where her near-death experience ended. That day at Seton
Hospital changed her. She converted to Catholicism from her
Episcopal upbringing, at about the same time that she and her
husband divorced. That prompted a 1972 trip to London to get a
teaching degree in the Montessori method. And that led to a job at
Austin's Cristo Rey Catholic Church working with Spanish-speaking
children. There, she learned the Spanish that is so important to
her work on the street. In 1981, she earned a history degree at the
University of Texas and took a job as an administrative assistant
in the College of Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1989 when the memorable experience of Day's Catholic
Worker operation in New York City re-emerged with a vengeance. She
thought about it even more when she drove by the day-labor site.
For months, she agonized about the idea. ``I didn't want to do it;
I was afraid,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She prayed about it daily and one spring morning got the courage
to go there. She remembers being uneasy that first day when she
walked among the men to ask them if she brought them food, would
they eat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she was crazy but wonderful,'' says Chico Gonzalez,
48, who saw her there.
</P>
<P>
   She returned the next day with two dozen hard-boiled eggs and
tortillas. They went fast. The grass-roots Egg McMinistry quickly
grew to 10 dozen eggs daily. She enlisted the help of volunteers
from St. George's Episcopal Church to meet the growing demand.
(Bill Wilkerson, a member of the church, was inspired. He still
delivers eggs, tortillas and coffee to the day-labor area on
Fridays.)
</P>
<P>
   The men dubbed her ``The Egg Lady,'' which she accepted as some
kind of honor. She now had a street name, just like Indian Joe and
Bicycle Scotty. She was one of them. They shared their tales of
weekend revelry, falling in love and getting arrested for one thing
or another.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, she quit her UT job and got on a train to visit
Catholic Worker programs in the western United States. She returned
to open Mary House Catholic Worker _ really her 672-square-foot
home west of downtown. She had the blessing of Bishop John McCarthy
of the Diocese of Austin, who kicked in $100 of his own money and
$1,000 from the diocese so she could officially start the ministry
she already had been financing with her savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like the work of Mother Teresa,'' says McCarthy. ``She
just wants to lessen their pain and make them feel appreciated and
respected.''
</P>
<P>
   It works, says James Stewart, 28, a homeless man: ``We hear so
many putdowns every day about what terrible people we are. She
makes us feel like we're somebody.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop's seed money lasted but a few months. Goodman-Strauss
found herself challenged to keep the ministry going.
</P>
<P>
   She did, though. News of her kind work reached the Christian
community. Small donations came in. The most meaningful donation to
Goodman-Strauss came from a homeless man who gave her a quarter.
She was tempted to return it but kept it to preserve his dignity.
Today, the meager, but steady, stream of private money pays for the
ministry, which operates on $16,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly developed a reputation among agencies that help the
homeless as savvy with street people who have mental disabilities.
David Gomez, the program manager for ACCESS, an Austin-Travis
County program for homeless mentally ill people, initially referred
people to Goodman-Strauss. ``She would take in our most vulnerable
clients and work magic with them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman-Strauss says it was the work of her black cat, Arabella,
whom she calls a psychiatrist, because Arabella would sit by
troubled people and calm them.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Hose, the former associate pastor of St. Mary's Cathedral,
met her in 1992. ``With Lynn's help, I came to understand that the
homeless were as much a part of daily parish life as anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The words of two men 10 years ago keep her going: ``You know,
this is the only time in my life when I get something and no one
wants anything in return,'' one said. And the other: ``This is the
only time I haven't had to fill out a form for someone to talk to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   She thinks about those two men on the days she's not 100 percent
into her work. First of all, she says, she's not a morning person,
but you can't tell it from her banter with the men, a lot of it in
Spanish. She's not feeling well some of the time because she has
chronic asthma. When it's cold, she's tested but reminded of
Dorothy Day's teaching ``that if you don't have the love, you don't
give out the bread.''
</P>
<P>
   The elimination of a free breakfast program at the new day-labor
site will affect more people than Goodman-Strauss. City officials
have been talking with Wilkerson of St. George's church, who
delivers food on Friday morning, and members of St. Mary's
Cathedral, who bring breakfast on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman-Strauss has heard enough, though. ``They're worried free
food attracts other people who come just for the food, not to find
work. I can respect that. I won't take this personally. I will miss
the guys, though,'' she says. (City officials maintain the men
themselves asked to end the program.)
</P>
<P>
   When the new day-labor site opens Aug. 1, Goodman-Strauss will
simply take food to another location, a place on Seventh Street
behind the police station where other day laborers congregate.
</P>
<P>
   And it's times like these that strengthen her and push her to do
more than just feed the men in the morning. She collects clothing
and distributes it to programs like the Austin Resource Center for
the Homeless. She coordinates what she calls ``slumber parties'' at
a local church for homeless people on cold nights. She's taken in
battered women.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez at ACCESS knows more: ``She'd coordinate churches to cook
lunches for our clients. She'd come with all this stuff in her car
and home-cooked meals. She served and cleaned up. During the
winter, she does a blanket drive for people on the street. She
doesn't ask stores for donations of food or clothing. ``This work
belongs to the individuals and churches who support it, and I'm
accountable to them. I'm working on their behalf, and that's a
privilege,'' she says. And there is a life outside her street
ministry. Friends and contributors to her program sometimes take
her out to dinner or a movie. Some mornings, she lives it up at Nau
Enfield Drug on West Lynn by splurging on a 75-cent cup of coffee.
It's a luxury to have someone else make the coffee, pour it and
wash the cup afterward. It's an even bigger deal to get a $2.50
breakfast special or find a discarded New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   She calls Nau Enfield Drug a ``village,'' where everyone knows
and cares about each other. One day, an old man couldn't read a
number in the phone book. One of the waitresses put her work down,
read the number and wrote it down in big print for the man to see.
When Goodman-Strauss' brother, Joe, died in 1996, employees and
regulars sent flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it is so '50s in here. You can get a Cherry Coke, a root
beer float and the best banana split in town,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling recharged, she heads out in her car with 174,000 miles
on the odometer to collect more stuff that will help people. Lessen
their pain. Help their situation.
</P>
<P>
   And to boil more eggs to take the growl out of their stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Gandara writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: rgandara(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
