<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-KIDS-SHELTER29-     07-28 2658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-KIDS-SHELTER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A children's house: The place for kids who have nowhere else to
go
 &HT;    (EDS: Photos available. Call CoxNet at 800-950-3739.
 &HT;    By Julie Bonnin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ They are little girls in pink polyester
nighties, sisters who ought to already be asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we take our nightgowns home?''4-year-old Veronica is
saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want some green shoes. Go look. Go get some,'' says
3-year-old Nina, a slightly smaller version of her sister with
straight bangs fringing dark eyes. Then, ``I want to wear these to
bed.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a little after 10 p.m., and in darkened bedrooms down the
hall, other children lie in their beds. But the sisters and their
older brother were late arrivals at the Austin Children's Shelter _
a way station for kids who are removed from their homes, usually
because they have been abused or neglected.
</P>
<P>
   So the girls _ whose family background includes allegations of
sexual abuse _ sit on the floor in a bedroom choosing shoes, as
shelter supervisor Sherree Paschall gently eases them into bed.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after Paschall dims the light and begins
reading ``101 Dalmatians,'' Nina begins flailing around in her bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``MOMMY-MOMMY-MOMMY-MOMMY. . .'' she screams, hair flying, wide
eyes scanning the unfamiliar, darkened room.
</P>
<P>
   The sobbing only subsides after Paschall invites her to come sit
in her lap. Even then, her body convulses with each breath.
</P>
<P>
   Then Nina points to the shoes lined up across the room, shudders
a final time and pronounces, ``Those are mine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about what fun things we'll do tomorrow,'' Paschall
says softly, after both girls are lying quietly in their beds. Her
hands lightly circle each child's back as they fall asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ring around the rosies,'' she says. ``Bubbles . . . ride bikes
. . . hokey pokey . . . eat breakfast . . . roller skates.''
</P>
<P>
   Her voice trails off into a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   And the sweet images ward off the darkness of night.
</P>
<P>
   Where kids can be kids
</P>
<P>
   Daylight brings the controlled chaos of 30 children and
teen-agers who live in the Austin Children's Shelter's adjoining
houses at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   They are babies, school-age children, as old as 17 when they
come here to spend a month, on average, before packing up again to
go to a foster home or to live with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   They come here if a judge agrees with a caseworker that it's too
dangerous for them to stay with their parents or caretakers. They
come here when they have nowhere else to go.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-year-old becomes so frightened when her parents start
fighting that she runs out of the house, carrying her baby sister
in an infant car seat. The baby isn't strapped in and falls out,
smashing her head on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   They are here.
</P>
<P>
   A 13-year-old and his younger sister are living with their
grandfather, who gets arrested. The kids go to stay with other
relatives, but the boy begins wearing makeup and says he may be
gay, and the little girl is acting out.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives decide the kids are too much to handle.
</P>
<P>
   They are here.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a 9-year-old boy, drowning in a too-big T-shirt and
pants that bag around his ankles. Sitting outside in a wooden
playhouse at the shelter, he says he likes math, science, and fairy
tales. And then he says, about his mother's boyfriend: ``He beats
up women when he's drunk. My mom thinks he's gonna be nice forever,
but they change, you know. Once you live with them, they change.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later the boy is gone, replaced by some other child
with a heart-rending history _ the mentally retarded toddler with a
broken collarbone, the 17-year-old working as a prostitute who's
never been to school.
</P>
<P>
   The staff, volunteers and others who support this place can't be
mothers and fathers, exactly.
</P>
<P>
   But here, at least, children can be children, children can be
safe.
</P>
<P>
   Always more need
</P>
<P>
   Two toddlers caught in the revolving door of emergency care are
here one busy Friday afternoon in June: A blond 2-year-old in a
seersucker jumpsuit is leaving, walking hand in hand with her
caseworker from Child Protective Services, a division of the
state's Department of Protective and Regulatory Services. She had
spent the night after her baby brother was hospitalized because of
suspected abuse, and now is going to stay with her grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Shelter I supervisor Sherree Paschall appears in
the same doorway, carrying a new admission, a sleepy toddler still
wearing a hospital gown.
</P>
<P>
   James' caseworker reports that the boy has a skull fracture,
that he's been asleep since about 11 a.m. (Children's names have
been changed for this story.) Then, as the 2-year-old is taken to
change clothes and eat supper, she details a family tree that fits
many of the kids here: parents, grandparents and other relatives
with abusive histories.
</P>
<P>
   James clings to the arms of yet another staff member as he
enters a room full of children. (Paschall has moved on to care for
another little boy who is getting ready to go to the hospital
because his temperature keeps climbing.)
</P>
<P>
   His older brother, admitted the night before, doesn't
acknowledge him. The 2-year-old's brows are knitted intently as he
takes in the children, corralled in the older kids' living room
because of work being done next door. There are more than a half
dozen babies, toddlers and preschoolers, two or three staff members
and a volunteer _ and the kids are everywhere, watching cartoons,
climbing on couches, tossing a ball back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   A little girl who's barely walking opens a video cabinet and
begins dragging out the contents. A 4-year-old flashes her eyes and
wags her bottom back and forth against a stranger's legs, a
provocative gesture typical of children who've been sexually
abused.
</P>
<P>
   A staffer snips the hospital bracelet from James' cocoa-brown
arm, which still bears traces of sticky white tape. James is quiet
but his liquid eyes are bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   He begins howling a few minutes later, as everyone gathers
around the supper table for brisket and beans. James won't eat
unless he's cuddled in someone's lap. Clearly his head hurts, but a
bureaucratic glitch keeps the staff from getting prescribed
medicine to him immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, the seasoned shelter employee working the phones to
get him what he needs, breaks down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   One child. One afternoon. Somebody waiting to take his place.
</P>
<P>
   Since the day it opened in 1984, the Austin Children's Shelter
has struggled to keep up with the demands of a community with so
many children in need. The nonprofit shelter _ in a residential
neighborhood not far from downtown _ is supported by money from the
state, county and city, as well as from grants, foundations and
private donations. It takes in children from 30 counties, but 95
percent of the kids it serves are from Austin and Travis County,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And, with just two other shelters in the Austin area (in Round
Rock and Pflugerville), the same booming population that's crowding
our highways is causing a pileup of abuse and neglect cases, says
state District Judge Scott McCown.
</P>
<P>
   The problem can be simply stated if not easily solved: Not
enough foster homes for all the Central Texas kids who need them,
and not enough shelter beds for interim emergency care and
assessment. Until September, the Austin shelter had just 15 beds;
it immediately filled 15 more beds in a second house that opened
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter is expected to serve 400 kids this year, but will
have turned away nearly 200 in the same period. That means local
kids are being placed in shelters far from their homes and schools,
in places like San Antonio and Waco, or with relatives or in foster
homes that may or may not be a good fit.
</P>
<P>
   And the shelter is bracing for even more calls from CPS
caseworkers before the year is over. The good news is that more
money from the Legislature that McCown pushed for will mean more
resources for child abuse investigation. The bad news is that the
shortage of foster homes and shelter beds will be felt even more
acutely. Compounding the urgency: The number of Texas children who
died from abuse or neglect increased more than 70 percent between
1997 and 1998, according to a state study.
</P>
<P>
   Like a real home
</P>
<P>
   McCown pictured something out of Charles Dickens when he first
began hearing child abuse cases and learned of the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he soon found himself ``so touched by how homelike it
is,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The kids in Shelter II _ a light-filled, older home with
gleaming wood floors _ start waking up around 6 or 7 a.m.,
depending on their schedules. They sleep four to a room in bunk
beds, in rooms without doors, and the staff member on duty sits
outside in the hallway keeping an eye on things.
</P>
<P>
   By 7:50 a.m., most of them have brushed their teeth, found
something to wear and made it downstairs to eat breakfast before
boarding a bus to summer school.
</P>
<P>
   Gathered around a big wooden table covered with breakfast dishes
and boxes of cereal _ Razzle Dazzle Rice Krispies, Frosted Flakes
and Kellogg's Corn Pops _ the kids talk about what they want to be
when they grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Radiologist. Lawyer. Navy SEAL.
</P>
<P>
   Shawnda, the youngest, an 8-year-old with a head full of
pigtails, has been angling for attention all morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I'm gonna be? You know what I'm gonna be?'' she
says, trying to be heard above the conversation and clinking of
spoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna fly,'' she says, flapping her arms like a bird.
``I'm gonna be a fish. I wanna be a bird, a dolphin, a whale. I
wanna be one of these,'' she says, poking at her Corn Pops.
</P>
<P>
   For the staff, this is a low-stress morning. The biggest
concerns among the 15 children are one needy, overly imaginative
kid, a boy who took a dive off his bunk bed, a dawdling pre-teen
who didn't want to get up, and a teen-ager with a cassette tape of
music with foul language that had to be confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   But when the kids first arrive, ``they're very frightened,''
says executive director Susan Wills. ``What they know about
grown-ups are that they are people they can't trust or who hurt
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And the kids often come in with physical and emotional wounds in
need of immediate attention. The staff tries to divert children
with severe problems to hospitals. But it's not unusual for someone
to be admitted wearing a body cast, or healing from a bad burn, or
stab wounds. Maybe they need to be shown how to use a nebulizer for
asthma that's never been treated. Occasionally a younger child will
come in with internal injuries no one has identified.
</P>
<P>
   One child became injured while at the shelter, but ``never made
a sound,'' Wills says. ``They have learned if they cry out, they'll
get beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   The shelter responds to the tumult of the kids' backgrounds with
structured surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   The stability is itself therapeutic. And here the kids learn
about rules, about setting boundaries and about people who care
about their well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone participates in group therapy, and many of the kids
also have individual counseling at the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   There are meetings with caseworkers, supervised visits with
parents, phone calls to grandparents. The shelter connects kids
with appropriate social service agencies and makes recommendations
to CPS about what kind of foster home or residential treatment
facility might be best for them when they leave.
</P>
<P>
   Behavior is molded, in part, by a point system, with points
subtracted for not following rules. And kids can trade a surplus of
points for perks or small prizes like cameras or toys. The children
in both shelters also operate according to a ``stoplight'' system.
Kids who listen and follow rules are on green light, with the most
privileges. Those on red light aren't allowed on field trips and
have the earliest bedtimes.
</P>
<P>
   Success is measured in tiny increments _ a 12-year-old who
sleeps through the night without wetting his bed, a child who
learns to ask for a hug.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their bleak backgrounds, or perhaps because of them, the
atmosphere inspired by the children here is light-filled, not
dreary and dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the horror,'' says Wills, ``but there's a level of joy
that's very life-affirming.''
</P>
<P>
   One hot spring morning the little kids are running around
outside playing and a 16-month-old, small for her age, is sitting
on the ground, sifting rocks through her tiny fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Something in her eyes warns you away, sizes you up.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, she is reserved and cautious and rarely smiles. But
by the time she and her older siblings leave the shelter for a
foster home more than a month later, she is toddling around at top
speed, grinning at strangers and asking to be picked up.
</P>
<P>
   A picture of joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you plant a seed that they're loved, that they're
important, that it's not their fault,'' Wills says, ``they remember
it all of their life.''
</P>
<P>
   Never enough help
</P>
<P>
   In Shelter I, where up to 15 younger children eat, sleep and
play, keeping up with the breakfast dishes, juice cups, baths and
dirty diapers _ not to mention temper tantrums that send kids
running under beds and occasional angry outbursts _ can seem a
never-ending challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter depends on 90 to 100 volunteers, who donate at least
eight hours a month. But there are never enough arms here, or next
door, where the kids are bigger and more independent, but needy
just the same.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members are trained to connect, but not cling too tightly.
Even so, their jobs can seem overwhelming. Average employment here
is about seven months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go to work at Whataburger, and not have to deal with
the emotional trauma of working with children who have been beaten
within an inch of their life,'' Wills says.
</P>
<P>
   Instability recently hit the shelter's executive branch as well:
Wills, the director for eight years, has been asked to take an
administrative leave by the nonprofit's board.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Oliver Smith would not comment on Wills' leadership
except to say that the children's care has not been in question.
Smith said the board is working to identify a consultant to help
assess the shelter's ``organizational structure,'' in light of its
significant growth in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Wills has made it a priority to raise the shelter's profile in
the community in the past few years. There have been many generous
gifts: The Meadows Foundation this year paid off remaining debt on
the new shelter building. Elmar Prambs, executive chef of the Four
Seasons, comes once a week to prepare supper for the staff and
kids. Numerous businesses help pay for field trips to theme parks
and other places.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a growing number of children with nowhere else to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Wills has watched as community members have stepped forward to
support the arts in recent months. ``Maybe there'll be a gift of a
home for these kids we're having to turn away,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to take care of Austin is to take care of kids at
risk,'' Wills says. ``There are many great causes in Austin, but
none greater than our children.''
</P>
<P>
   She keeps a collection of drawings and letters from children
who've stayed at the shelter but are long gone. There's a crayoned
thank-you note scrawled by a child who said she was happy to be in
a place where someone would wake and feed her each day.
</P>
<P>
   One 9-year-old boy came to the shelter after police found him
driving around town, peering over the steering wheel of a car from
his perch atop a thick phonebook. His mother, a prostitute, had a
drug habit, and his older brother had recently been shot and
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel happy to be here,'' he wrote. ``It is fun to be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Bonnin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jbonnin(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
