<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, July 28, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-KILLINGS (San Francisco) _ As a U.S. senator and the
relatives of victims questioned the FBI's investigation into four
murders that have shaken Yosemite National Park, a cab driver who
gave the confessed killer a two-hour ride from one of the crime
scenes said the bureau had failed to contact her. By SETH
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   SUTURES (Undated) _ A medical manufacturer has been hit with a
new flurry of lawsuits in connection with an infection outbreak
allegedly caused by contaminated surgical sutures. In two
class-action suits, seven surgical patients in California and
Nevada charged that they had suffered raging infections because the
Johnson &AMP; Johnson subsidiary Ethicon Inc. allegedly distributed
sutures contaminated with infectious bacteria. By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ San Francisco police Capt. Richard
Cairns, whose role in the 1989 police sweep of Castro Street
resulted in his suspension from the force, has picked up papers
declaring his intent to run for mayor. Cairns has until Aug. 6 to
officially enter the race. Twenty-five people already have declared
their intent to run. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNIST-DISCIPLINED (San Jose, Calif.) _ Two editors of
suspended San Jose Mercury News columnist Chris Nolan were
themselves disciplined, sources said. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   PC-USERS (San Francisco) _ Despite high-tech industry hype about
computers becoming the focus of our future, users really want their
machines to become everyday household appliances, helping them do
the laundry, stand in line at the Department of Motor Vehicles and
handle other mundane chores. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-BUSINESS (San Francisco) _ About two years ago, Veronica
Ruiz had a Web site for her business, a supply and repair store for
typewriters and fax machines, but she got tired of paying $78 a
month to a Web posting company for nothing. Ruiz's frustration with
the Web is fairly typical of small businesses. By VICTORIA
COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-BETTING (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ If you're worried when
placing a bet on the horses, just think of the clerk who takes the
money at the betting window. If the clerk makes a mistake, he or
she must pay for it. The largest error last year cost one unlucky
bet taker $1,500, close to the $2,000 clerks may earn in a season.
By LINDA TRISCHITT.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (Stockton, Calif.) _ Given the way Jim
Druckenmiller's career has played out with the 49ers, the swell of
camera crews and reporters clamoring for his insights on Tuesday
seemed odd. This wasn't Steve Young on the other end of those
questions. It was a third-year quarterback most observers had
written off months ago. By JEFFRI CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-CBS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Last season CBS embarked on an
effort to go after an audience that had eluded the network: males
and younger people. To a point CBS succeeded. So what does CBS do
for this coming season? It offers three female lawyer shows _
``Family Law,'' ``Judging Amy'' and ``Work with Me.'' These shows,
two dramas and a sitcom, are not exactly tailored toward young
males. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BERRIES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Blueberries and raspberries seem to be
like the best married couples. They have a few things in common and
just enough differences to keep things interesting. By RUTH
FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ As the population ages and the
cost of medical care shoots up, health insurers struggle to save
money while physicians and patients struggle to obtain adequate
care. At the moment, all three sides in this epic clash seem to be
losing. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   FERRIES (San Francisco) _ Plans for a huge expansion of ferry
service in the Bay Area ignore problems caused by ferry boats. Even
the most modern ferries are 10 times more polluting per passenger
than recently built cars, and 34 times more polluting than the
natural-gas bus designs proposed for Golden Gate Transit.
High-speed ferries would also increase safety risk and create large
wakes that erode shorelines. By RUSSELL LONG.
</P>
