<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6738 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-SOFTWAR     07-28 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-SOFTWARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLICATIONS THAT ADVERTISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SIMSON L. GARFINKLE   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIFWorks and 3DTextMaker are two neat programs for creating
images to put on Web pages. But these programs also represent
fundamental change in the direction of desktop computing _ a change
that might ultimately make more software available at lower prices
for everyone, while making them more annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, they could simply be momentary economic aberrations.
It's really too early to tell for sure.
</P>
<P>
   GIFWorks and 3DTextMaker, developed by Andover.Net in South
Acton, Mass., are Web-based applications. Unlike normal
applications, which you download and run on your computer, these
two are run through a Web browser while you are connected to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   GIFWorks is the simpler program of the two. It can rotate
images, resize them, or apply a number of different ``effects,''
such as embossing or sharpening. The program also has a number of
features that are optimized for Web page creation: You can reduce
the number of colors, or create an animated GIF. Andover has also
put together a large collection of images that you can freely
incorporate into your own Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   3DTextMaker is a program for making buttons with text that go on
Web pages. You choose a font, a color, and effect, and add some
text. Then you click a button and the Web site creates a button or
a banner with the text that you requested. Once you make a button,
you can then save it to your computer's hard drive, or you can
click a link, take the program back into GIFWorks, and make further
changes to it there. Or you can click a menu item that says ``FTP
Transload'' and send the image to Web site using the Internet's
File Transfer Protocol.
</P>
<P>
   GIFWorks and 3DTextMaker are just two of the applications that
the folks at Andover.Net have put together for building Web sites.
Another application is ButtonMaker, which turns a GIF into a
button. There also is FontMapper, a simple utility that shows how
different characters are displayed in different fonts. And there is
HTMLWorks, a program that lets you edit the HTML code on your Web
page, save it back to your Web server, and validate _ that is, to
check it to make sure that there aren't any errors.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Andover's programs are a bit buggy _ for example, I
couldn't get the ``sharpen'' feature in GIFWorks to work properly.
Others are somewhat limited. But fortunately, since these are
Web-based applications, all Andover has to do is fix the program.
Unlike a traditional software publisher, such as Microsoft, Andover
doesn't have take the time or spend the money to distribute the
fixed program to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest difference between the Andover Web-based
applications and traditional computer apps is the advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Andover.Net is a network of advertiser-supported Web sites.
Every time you click a button on the GIFWorks or 3DTextMaker Web
page, a new banner advertisement appears at the top of the screen.
According to the company's rate card, these ads cost between $42
and $70 for every thousand impressions. Those rates may seem rather
high; Andover justifies its prices by saying that 41 percent of its
Web site visitors work in information technology, and 69 percent
are personally responsible for purchasing computer products for
their companies.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenue adds up quickly for Web-based applications.
For example, a typical session with GIFWorks might involve clicking
50 menu items, which translates to roughly $2 in revenue. Use the
program to design even a small Web site and you might earn $20 or
more for the company. Use Andover's tools religiously for a few
months, and you could earn hundreds of dollars for them.
</P>
<P>
   These economics stand in stark contrast to the way traditional
application programs are sold. Consider Adobe ImageStyler, a
program that is far more sophisticated than the Web-based
applications that Andover has put together. ImageStyler has a
retail price of $130, of which Adobe probably sees less than $100.
So while Andover's programs may be ``free'' for the user, they
ultimately cost far more than the alternative. The cost is hidden
because the user doesn't pay _ the advertiser does.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think this situation can be stable for very long.
Something has to give. One possibility is that Andover's
advertisements are overpriced. Andover's claims that its Web site
visitors are decision-makers may be true, but most of the
advertisements that I have seen on the 3DTextMaker Web site are for
instant-win sweepstakes, low-cost telephone cards, Web-based email
services, and the Women's World Wrestling Federation. Ultimately,
the company many not be able to justify the cost of its
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another way the economics could work out. We might
start seeing advertisements in other applications as well.
</P>
<P>
   For example, my copy of Quicken '99 shows me ads when I download
stock quotes and news stories from the Internet. (You are supposed
to be able to turn off the ads, but for some reason that feature of
Quicken '99 doesn't work for me.) Another program that comes
prewired to display advertising is the new ``G2 Player'' from
RealNetworks.
</P>
<P>
   A few years from now, paid advertisements might be a standard
part of most desktop applications. After all, advertising is an
untapped and potentially large source of revenue for software
publishers. This potential might be difficult for them to resist.
</P>
<P>
   There might be two versions of Adobe's ImageStyler program in
the future: a low-cost version that shows advertisements, and a
high-cost version that doesn't. Ultimately, our computer screens
might resemble the signs along a typical highway, with a few
rectangles devoted to the actual business of desktop computing, and
the rest of the rectangles devoted to the advertising.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a future that I eagerly await.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  You can find GIFWorks on line at www.gifworks.com,
3DTextMaker at www.3dtextmaker.com, and ButtonMaker at
www.buttonmaker.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Two weeks ago we erroneously reported Andover.Net's Internet
address. It's at www.internettrafficreport.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Simson L. Garfinkel can be reached at plugged-in(at)simson.net)
</P>
