<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, THE WAIT IS AS EXCITING AS THE MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people count down the days until their wedding or the last
day of school. Others anticipate the call from the doctor or the
visit from Santa. And in theater circles, folks have been known to
wait for Lefty and some guy named Godot.
</P>
<P>
   But wait for a movie? It used to be that only Trekkers and
aspiring Jedi knights obsessed about the minute details of their
favorite films. But now, it seems like every movie is dissected on
the Internet months before it even opens. Of course you expect
advance mania with ``Star Wars.'' But the Net has buzzed all summer
with feverish speculation about movies big and small, from ``Wild
Wild West'' to ``The Blair Witch Project.'' A movie isn't just a
movie anymore: It's an Event. Anticipation has become a popular
pastime, a form of entertainment in itself. Buzz is the new
buzzword, waiting the new game.
</P>
<P>
   Take Tim Doyle. Two years ago, he was an ad salesman in Toronto,
going about his business and seeing the occasional film. Today,
he's on an ``extended vacation'' in Los Angeles, putting together a
business plan for countingdown.com, the Web site that breathlessly
reports on upcoming films. ``We have mobilized anticipation in a
more organized fashion,'' Doyle, 28, says of the site, which he
launched with two other film buffs.
</P>
<P>
   This is a big day for Doyle and his cohorts, what with the
opening of the long-awaited Stanley Kubrick film ``Eyes Wide
Shut.'' They've been counting down to the opening for months,
dishing out the latest rumors about stars Nicole Kidman and Tom
Cruise and castigating Warner Brothers for digitally altering a
65-second orgy scene. Who cares if the film is worth the wait? The
wait is worth the wait to Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like opening presents before Christmas, sneaking a
peak,'' he explains of this Information Age obsession. ``It's like
a guilty pleasure, like being let in on some deep, dark secret.''
</P>
<P>
   And every day is Christmas Eve in cyberspace. The film industry
was slow to respond to the Internet phenomenon, but fans are now
rewriting the rules about movie premieres. Nothing is secret, and
reviews are not embargoed. Amateur sites like aint-it-cool-news.com
and darkhorizons.com publish anything they can dredge up about
upcoming films, and industry honchos are flinching about their loss
of spin control. Last month, director Barry Sonnenfeld blamed the
Internet for the tepid response to ``Wild Wild West.'' ``You can
ruin a movie through anonymous reviews on the Internet,'' he said,
failing to note that the mainstream press didn't exactly embrace
the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that can make or break a film is the film
itself,'' says Lew Harris, editor-in-chief of E! Online. But even
Harris, whose site fuels the obsession with pop culture, says the
buzz has escalated this month. ``There is an increasing mania, and
I don't know where it's going to end,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, it's not going to end. You know the line between
fact and fiction is blurring when a film becomes an urban legend in
its own right. That's what happened with ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' a mock documentary by independent filmmakers Daniel
Myrick and Eduardo Sanchez. The film tells the story of three
students who disappear while making a documentary about witches in
Blair, Md. The whole thing is fiction, but you wouldn't know it
from the Web site (www.blairwitch.com). The site draws you into the
mythology, presenting ``evidence'' including photographs and
weathered documents. There isn't a single clue that the legend
isn't true, except for one link that leads to an on-line store
where you can purchase T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly an ingenious, if manipulative, marketing ploy,
since word flies on the Internet. A few weeks ago, the ``Blair
Witch Project'' appeared on www.snopes.com, a popular site that
debunks urban legends that multiply in cyberspace. David Mikkelson,
who runs the site with his wife, Barbara, says he set up the
``Blair Witch'' page as a response to numerous inquiries. ``We
still have plenty of folks who will cling to whatever beliefs fit
their world view, facts be damned,'' Mikkelson says.
</P>
<P>
   It's only a movie, right?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. Rumors and legends about movies aren't the only
things that proliferate in cyberspace these days. An avid fan
posted the complete footage of ``Phantom Menace'' on line days
after the film opened; a streaming video version of the last
episode of ``Buffy: The Vampire Slayer,'' which had been postponed
because of the Columbine High tragedy in Colorado, appeared on line
immediately after it was aired on Canadian television.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to wait for Christmas morning anymore. So now that
the folks at countingdown.com finally get to see ``Eyes Wide
Shut,'' they have something else to anticipate. Remember those 65
seconds? The scene that was altered to mask body parts in an orgy
scene? The film is being released uncensored in Europe, so it's
only a matter of time before someone sneaks a camera into a theater
and posts the original clip on line. It will happen, guaranteed.
All you have to do is wait.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  With all due respect to Marshall McLuhan, the medium is the
medium _ at least in an Internet seance.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, we checked out ``Web Seance,'' the latest project
by digital artists Nina Sobell and Emily Hartzell that was
commissioned by the Banff Center for the Arts in Alberta, Canada.
Two artists were hooked up to an electroencephalographic machine,
which traces electronic forces in the brain, and drawings of their
brainwaves were transmitted to the Web site. On-line participants
asked questions that scrolled across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The drawings themselves were abstract blurs, eerie and
incandescent. The questions were amusing, a combination of mishegas
and mysticism. A sampling: ``Can I touch the medium?'' and ``Is
this a medium or a comedian?'' I logged in late, posing the query:
``Is this over?'' Alas, the medium didn't answer.
</P>
<P>
   The site is at http://artists.banff.org/parkbench/seance/; the
next seance is set for July 28 at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send e-mail to cyberlinks(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-22-99 1340EDT &QL;
</P>
