<HEADLINE>
YOUTHFUL LEADER FOR INTERNET PUSH   
 TELCORDIA'S BIG CONTRACT  
 PLAYBOY ENTERPRISES DENIED AN INJUNCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though only 28, Seth Goldstein is a veteran member of
New York's Internet industry, having started the Site Specific ad
agency in 1995. But recently, he has been the Inspector Gadget of
Silicon Alley.
</P>
<P>
   It was after selling Site Specific in 1997 to what is now
USWeb/CKS that Goldstein started a business called Root.net, which
aimed to help digital road warriors assemble their portable
arsenals. When that venture did not travel well, Goldstein became
an entrepreneur in residence with Flatiron Partners, the Internet
venture capital arm of Chase Manhattan. His mission has been to
figure out how to make money from the emergence of gadgets _ other
than PCs _ that may be connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is talking about how people will access the Internet
throughout the day, from the refrigerator in the morning telling
them the weather to their car dashboard giving directions and
playing music from MP3 files,'' he said. ``But it's not clear how
we're going to get there. And that uncertainty creates investment
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase has agreed to put up as much as $50 million to back gizmo
companies. And in seven months, Goldstein has managed to go through
half that money by investing in a handful.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is Scout, a San Francisco company making a small
device that would sell for less than $100 and would receive
broadcasts of information of interest to ``urban youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Another is Vertical One, an Atlanta maker of software to bring
together balances from several banks; it would be used first on Web
sites and later on wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Appliance Network, a company that Goldstein created
with backing from Russell Pillar, chief executive of Virgin
Entertainment, is also in the group. It would offer online services
based on small devices used only for e-mail and Web surfing.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking Media is another of the companies. It is a New York
concern that makes a Java software program called Sonata that is
used in online advertising and has applications in wireless
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Kozmo.com is also getting an infusion from Flatiron. The
increasingly popular New York service employs an army of bicycle
messengers and promises to deliver rental videocassettes and snacks
to wired, sugar-starved couch potatoes within an hour of an order
placed through its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein helped secure backing for Kozmo by using a computer to
summon a messenger to the Chase conference room where he was making
the pitch. ``A guy shows up with 15 pints of Ben &AMP; Jerry's within
half an hour,'' he recalled. ``That really greased the wheels.''
</P>
<P>
   _ SAUL HANSELL
</P>
<P>
   Large Phone Contract From South Africa
</P>
<P>
   The newly renamed American company Telcordia Technologies Inc.
plans Monday to announce a big contract to help modernize Telkom
South Africa's antiquated telephone systems and bring phone service
to millions of South Africans for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The exact size of the deal was not revealed, but the contract
will be worth hundreds of millions of dollars to Telcordia over
roughly three years, executives close to the agreement said.
</P>
<P>
   Until March, Telcordia was known as Bellcore, the former joint
research operation formed by the regional Bell companies after the
breakup of AT&AMP;T Corp. in 1984. Bellcore, which helped develop
standards and software for local phone networks, was acquired by
Science Applications International Inc. in 1997, after the Bell
companies increasingly went their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   Telkom, South Africa's telephone monopoly, is 30 percent owned
by a consortium of the American telephone giant SBC Communications
Inc. and Telekom Malaysia. SBC executives are essentially running
the company under a mandate from the South African government to
expand and improve service.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem has been Telkom's outdated systems.
Telcordia will help revamp the company's networks and train
Telkom's technicians with an eye to expanding Telkom's reach from 5
million to 7 million lines by 2002. The companies plan to deploy
many of the new lines in rural areas that have not previously had
telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   _ SETH SCHIESEL
</P>
<P>
   Playboy Loses Round Over Search Engine Ads
</P>
<P>
   Giving a green light to a common but controversial Internet
advertising practice, a federal judge in California has refused a
request by Playboy Enterprises to stop the Web search services
Excite.com and Netscape.com from placing ads for pornography sites
with the search results for the words ``playboy'' or ``playmate.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining Playboy's request for a preliminary injunction, Judge
Alicemarie Stotler of U.S. District Court in Santa Ana, Calif.,
said Playboy was unlikely to succeed in a trial with its contention
that Excite Inc. had violated trademark laws.
</P>
<P>
   Marissa Gluck, an analyst with the research firm Jupiter
Communications, said the decision was good news for search
services, which she said derived 20 to 30 percent of their ad
revenue from the sale of banner ads linked to keywords.
</P>
<P>
   In its lawsuit against Excite and America Online's Netscape
Communications unit, which licenses Excite's search technology,
Playboy had challenged this practice, known as banner ad keying,
saying that it could divert customers looking for Playboy's site
and also tarnish its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion on June 24, Stotler found that although Playboy
held trademarks for Playboy and Playmate, it did not have a
monopoly on the generic use of those words in English. For that
reason and others, the court said, Playboy had not shown that
Excite had made commercial use of Playboy's trademark, as would be
necessary to justify a trademark infringement lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Stotler also ruled that even if Excite had used Playboy's
trademarks, that use would not have been improper because Playboy
had offered no evidence that consumers would be confused about the
relationship between Playboy and a banner ad for a pornography
site.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Playboy said the company would appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   _ CARL S. KAPLAN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-25-99 2214EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
