<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-E-COMMERCE-MARKET     07-28 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-E-COMMERCE-MARKETING-ART-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL MERCHANTS GOING ONLINE NEED FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike most people drawn to the siren song of Internet commerce,
Phil Worley started a Web site last spring with a modest goal: to
bring in some additional sales for his small-town hardware
business. No 50-page business plan. No venture capital. No initial
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   After three months of advertising Weber grills on the site _
which is hosted by The Hartford Courant (www.courant.com) _ at
prices lower than those of many competitors, he found that not even
his humble expectations were met. In other words, he has not sold a
thing online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen much payback,'' said Worley, owner of Worley
Ace Hardware in Canton, Conn., a town of about 8,000 that is 14
miles west of Hartford. ``But I feel like I need to be there, since
so many in my industry are. I'm keeping the faith.''
</P>
<P>
   For many people dipping their toes into e-commerce, the process
requires an element of faith _ whether for consumers concerned
about security, investors uncertain of their return or retailers
with no idea how consumers' online behavior will evolve. But for
local merchants who want to participate in the world's hottest
industry, faith is perhaps the biggest component of the business
model.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only that owners of small businesses often lack the
time, expertise and marketing budgets to compete with bigger
companies. It is not yet clear that people will look to local
merchants when they surf the Net for bargains. Meanwhile, online
city guides, which seek to aggregate local businesses for
advertising and transactions, are a fragmented bunch, with only
experimental ideas on how to approach local markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a pretty picture for local merchants right now,''
said Lisa Allen, an e-commerce analyst with Forrester Research, an
Internet consulting firm. ``First of all, a lot of what's sold
online are commodities, and you don't need to buy a book or CD from
a local-yokel store,'' she said. ``But also, the national players
have the deep pockets to create sites with the best user experience
and market them. And the mom-and-pops don't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Allen said local merchants would attract $680 million in
Internet sales this year, or 9 percent of the total $7.8 billion
projected by Forrester. By 2003, Forrester expects local merchants
to increase those sales to $6 billion, but that number will account
for just 6 percent of the projected $108 billion in Web sales.
</P>
<P>
   In touting the potential of local e-commerce, some executives
point to the fact that people spend nearly 80 percent of their
money within a 20-mile radius of their homes. But ``interests, not
geography, will be important online,'' Ms. Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a wine aficionado, you won't necessarily go to the
local site,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, certain categories that show greater local
potential online _ including tickets, which Forrester anticipates
will reap 43 percent of local Web sales, or $2.6 billion, by 2003.
Such numbers bode well for Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch, which
hosts a network of city guides catering primarily to
entertainment-minded consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps mindful of the limits of local e-commerce, many
merchants use the Web for marketing rather than for completing
transactions with customers. Here businesses like employment
agencies, real estate agents and car dealerships are among the
biggest spenders, analysts and executives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more things in the real estate industry will be done
online, so I'd expect our ad budget to grow online in the next
couple of years,'' said Stat Geer, regional manager for Chicago
Title Insurance Co., which advertises on the Chicago Digital City
site, operated by America Online in conjunction with The Chicago
Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at least one study shows that local advertising online
is gaining momentum. According to a report last month by Kelsey
Group and Constat Inc., the Web has surpassed direct mail as an
advertising medium for local businesses, and is nearly equal to
local spending on newspaper advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that 17.2 percent of businesses involved in
local commerce use the Web for advertising and promotion, vs. 15.5
percent for direct mail, 18.7 percent for newspapers and 37.2
percent for Yellow Pages.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Online city guides like Digital City and Citysearch, as well as
guides owned by newspapers (including The New York Times, which
publishes the New York Today site), have until recently attracted
advertisers using the same formula as any local media: provide
local news and entertainment information, and sell ads surrounding
that content.
</P>
<P>
   But with the e-commerce bandwagon picking up speed, more local
merchants are demanding not only advertising opportunities but
sophisticated Web sites that enable them to sell goods within the
city guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar is a lot higher now,'' said Charles Conn, chief
executive of Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch. ``When we used to sell
sites in our city guides to merchants, they wanted four or five
pages with pictures, maybe a menu if they were a restaurant. Now
they want streaming audio, the recipe of the day, and merchants
want the ability to transact.''
</P>
<P>
   Conn, who said merchants pay between $100 and $700 a month for a
site within a Citysearch guide, noted that consumers, too, will
increasingly expect local merchants to offer more transaction
capabilities. ``I think because people have been trained by tools
like Amazon and eBay for buying online, they'll look not only for
fresh information from sites like ours but transaction tools to
help them get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is the great hope of merchants like Worley, of
Worley Ace Hardware, who pays $200 a month for his site. ``As with
so many people who are trying e-commerce, this is a large
experiment for me,'' he said. ``But I haven't really given this a
lot of attention, since I have so much going on running the
business. I suppose to do it right you have to do it big. And I
haven't done that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-25-99 2104EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
