</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-ADDRESSES-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLANNED INTERNET YELLOW PAGES DRAWS FEDERAL SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Aggravating an already charged political dispute
over its monopoly control of Internet addresses, Network Solutions
Inc. on Monday is set to introduce a new Yellow Pages-type
directory for the Internet, built around valuable data that the
Clinton administration insists belong to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The company is billing its new Dot-Com Directory as a ``find
engine'' that will make it easier for people to contact and get
information on businesses with Web sites. The directory taps data
that Network Solutions has compiled as the federal government's
exclusive registrar of more than 5 million addresses that end in
.com, .net and .org.
</P>
<P>
   Because Network Solutions has denied others the data for such
services, the introduction of the Dot-Com Directory is adding fuel
to its growing dispute with the government over both ownership of
the data base and the larger issue of the terms for opening its
main business, the registration of Internet addresses, to
full-scale competition.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say it could also raise new antitrust complaints
against Network Solutions, which is already under investigation by
the Justice Department's antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, the Commerce Department's general counsel, Andrew
J. Pincus, sent a letter to Network Solutions requesting that it
open the data to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions declined comment over the weekend, saying that
senior management had not yet had a chance to review the letter.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was sent the same day that Democratic leaders of the
House Commerce Committee's oversight panel sent a letter to
Secretary of Commerce William Daley calling the Dot-Com Directory
``a very troubling development by a company in a monopoly position
that already appears very reluctant to give up that position.''
This latest controversy follows the company's refusal to recognize
the authority of the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and
Numbers, or ICANN, the oversight body picked by the Commerce
Department last year to oversee the introduction of global
competition to the business of registering Internet addresses,
known as domains.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the oversight committee held a hearing _ largely at
the urging and lobbying of Network Solutions _ to investigate
accusations that ICANN was overstepping its authority.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the hearing got under way, ICANN had defused
much of the criticism of its conduct by agreeing earlier in the
week to open its next board meeting to the public, as well as to
defer collection of a controversial $1-a-year tax on domain-name
registrations and to further limit its own authority.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Network Solutions found the tables turned at the
hearing, where it was peppered with questions about both its
resistance to working with ICANN and its stalemate with the
Commerce Department over rights to the data base, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   During questioning, Network Solutions' chief executive, Jim
Rutt, asserted that his company owned the intellectual-property
rights to the data base. The Commerce Department countered that the
information is public property.
</P>
<P>
   In its letter to Network Solutions on Friday, the Commerce
Department said it had no problem with the Dot-Com Directory as a
product but objected to its proprietary nature, which Pincus said
``appears effectively to insulate the Dot-Com Directory against any
real competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the Cooperative Agreement nor in existing law gives
NSI the right to restrict access to this information, which NSI
obtained in the course of providing registry and registrar services
_ on an exclusive basis _ under the authority of the United States
government,'' Pincus wrote. NSI refers to Network Solutions Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Network Solutions were to convince the Commerce
Department and Congress that the data base is its intellectual
property, it could add fuel to the Justice Department's
investigation of whether the company engaged in antitrust
violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly raises the stakes in its antitrust battles,''
said Hillard Sterling, who specializes in antitrust law in Chicago.
``Network Solutions would be well advised to minimize its allegedly
abusive activities.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hillard added: ``It is possible that the DOJ will mandate the
sharing of this data base regardless of who technically owns the
information. Ownership isn't the only question. The underlying
inquiry involves the possibility of anticompetitive effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those pressing the Department of Justice to get involved
in the dispute is Joe Sims, the lawyer for ICANN, which is
currently overseeing a test in which five companies are being
allowed to compete against Network Solutions. Full-scale
competition cannot be introduced until the Commerce Department
reaches an agreement with the company on the terms for opening its
business _ or until the Commerce Department takes the drastic step
of turning the domain-registration business over to another company
or group.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers say the latter option would be a last resort,
as it could disrupt the Internet and force a split of its central
network.
</P>
<P>
   Still, from a business perspective, the company might have
little choice but to risk a legal battle with the government.
Although it has reported 11 straight quarters of record profits,
primarily on the registration of domain names, the $70 fee Network
Solutions currently charges is expected to go down once full-scale
competition is introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, said Bill Whyman, an Internet analyst with the Legg Mason
investment firm in Washington, future profits from the
domain-registration business, will center on ancillary services
like the Dot-Com Directory. To get a leg up on the competition, he
said, the company must use its exclusive position while it still
has it.
</P>
<P>
   The Dot-Com Directory encourages customers to choose Network
Solutions over competitors by essentially giving them a free domain
registration. The company will charge $119 for a registration, but
that fee includes a listing in the directory. People who register
domain names with competitors will have to pay $119 just to be
listed in the directory.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Wolford, Network Solutions' senior vice president for
marketing, says the directory has about three times as many
listings as the most complete competing service.
</P>
<P>
   The Dot-Com Directory will also carry advertisements. At its
launching today, it will offer listings and information on 1.8
million businesses with some 3.5 million Web sites. The directory
is available at www.comdirectory.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-25-99 2035EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
