<SLUG> BC-KAPLAN-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERNARD KAPLAN, VETERAN FOREIGN CORRESPONDENT, DIES IN PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Bernard D. Kaplan, a veteran foreign correspondent for
The Hearst Newspapers and one of the youngest reporters to cover
the Korean war, died Tuesday at the American Hospital in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kaplan, 71, died of complications from cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   As a roving Paris-based European correspondent for the past 42
years, Mr. Kaplan was regarded as an authoritative analyst who
explained complicated world affairs with clarity and wit, often
adding a nugget of history or religion or culture to make his
point.
</P>
<P>
   His sweeping repertoire of journalistic expertise earned him the
reputation as a ``renaissance reporter'' equally adept at writing
about diplomacy, global economics, politics, the British royal
family or an occasional wry commentary on the foibles of the
French.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kaplan's last article, written Nov. 30, employed his typical
historical sweep to dissect the intricate relationship between
Germany and Russia over the centuries. His point: Germany's current
economic ties with Russia explain the Berlin government's
solicitous overtures to the faltering administration of Russian
President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Mr. Kaplan personified the urbane foreign
correspondent who moved with ease through the diplomatic corridors
of Europe. He was a personal acquaintance of many of the world
leaders he covered and had an enormous reservoir of background
information about them and the issues they were involved with. He
also was an impeccable dresser who knew which Parisian restaurants
and wines were in vogue at any particular time.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kaplan was active in the Anglo-American Press Association in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Frank A. Bennack, Jr., president and chief
executive officer of The Hearst Corporation, issued a statement
describing Mr. Kaplan as a ``warm and valued colleague.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie Kaplan's service to the Hearst organization, which goes
back to his days with INS during the Korean War, was known by all
of us to be of the highest and most professional caliber,'' Bennack
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His work on behalf of the Hearst Newspapers since 1975
resulted in reports which were always insightful and often unique.
Additionally, his contributions to the columns of William Randolph
Hearst, Jr., our late editor-in-chief, were always meaningful.
Bernie will be missed by all of us both professionally and
personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kaplan began his career as one of the youngest American
correspondents covering the Korean War, working for the
International News Service, a wire service then owned by the Hearst
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Mr. Kaplan was drafted and served two years in
the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, he joined the North American Newspaper Alliance as a
correspondent based in Paris, where he made his home until his
death. He also worked for the Montreal Star, the Canadian
Broadcasting Corporation and NBC in Paris before joining the Hearst
Newspapers in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   He won the Canadian Newspaper Publishers Award for best foreign
coverage in 1965 for a series on the European Common Market.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Brooklyn, N.Y., Mr. Kaplan graduated from Washington
&AMP; Lee University in Lexington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife of 48 years, Antonia Kaplan; their
two children, Charles and Juliette, both of Paris; two
grandchildren; his brother, Leonard, of Palm Beach, Fla., and a
sister, Doris Chieffetz, of Huntington, L.I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
