u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY27-COX     07-28 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY27-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Non-Intel chip a subtle sign corners might have been cut 
By Bill Husted  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a good reason _ as far as I'm concerned _ to
think twice about buying a computer with a non-Intel processor
chip.
</P>
<P>
   That reason has very little to do with whether the non-Intel
chip works as well or as fast as the Intel chip.
</P>
<P>
   When I started messing with PCs, the choice was simple. You got
the chip that was available from Intel. Now there are chips from
AMD, Cyrix and others. If you read computer magazines, you'll find
almost monthly reviews of some of these non-Intel chips and the
results of so-called benchmark tests where the chip is tested for
speed against chips from Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the non-Intel chips win in these benchmark tests,
sometimes Intel wins. In almost every case, the margin of victory
is so slim that you'd never notice the speed increase in real-life
computing.
</P>
<P>
   So speed, or lack of it, isn't a good reason to care about the
brand of the processor chip. The best reason to care about the
non-Intel chips is price. The usual rule of thumb is that the chip
(not the computer made using the chip) is usually about 20 percent
less expensive than an Intel chip of the same speed.
</P>
<P>
   So you are most likely to find these chips in computers designed
to compete based on price. If you thumb through a computer magazine
or walk the aisles of a computer store, you'll soon notice that
these chips are mostly found in low-cost machines.
</P>
<P>
   So far I've dealt with the facts.
</P>
<P>
   But if we were at a party together and you asked me if you
should consider one of these PCs with a non-Intel chip, I'd say get
the real thing. I'd tell you first that, if I sat down at the
computer without knowing whether it had an Intel chip, it would be
unlikely that I could tell the difference. Most of your programs
would run fine on either machine and occasionally screw up on
either machine. Both machines would be fast and work OK.
</P>
<P>
   But here's what scares me about non-Intel chips. Since they are
mostly found in machines that are designed to sell at the lowest
possible price (and that's really the only reason a manufacturer
would use a non-Intel chip, since the Intel name is a well-known
brand that helps sell computers), I worry that the desire to sell
the lowest-price computer means compromises elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty easy, even for an amateur, to know what kind of
processor chip is inside the computer. But, when it comes to the
type and quality of components like disk drives, sound cards, video
cards, RAM (the memory chips) and, obviously, resistors and
capacitors ... most people don't have a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Common sense tells me that if I am trying to make a computer
that I can sell at a price below the competition, I'm going to look
for other ways besides the processor chip to lower my costs.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that I am highly ethical and I do my best to get stuff
that works OK (and not every company is that ethical). I'll still
have to make some compromises. After all, the biggest and best
companies can get parts as cheap or cheaper than I can. So the only
way to save money is to go down a grade in quality.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, that won't keep the low-cost computer from
starting up fine when you hit the switch. But there truly is a
reason that some components cost more than others. With
electronics, that reason often is that the quality control is
higher and the long-term failure rate somewhat lower.
</P>
<P>
   So, and remember this is my opinion, think of the non-Intel chip
as a tiny warning flag that says: We built this computer using
parts from the lowest-priced vendor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-26-99 1044EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
