 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Well-connected: Home networking concept booming 
By Gerry Yandel  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A network computer crash is never a pretty thing.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly on Richard Bodor's network.
</P>
<P>
   ``My users cry, kick and hold their breath when the network is
down,'' he says. ``They say, `I don't like Daddy. He's not getting
a Father's Day present.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bodor has been networking the computers in his Alpharetta home
for seven years. That network gets extensive use by the five
computer-adept Bodors. Wife Kim uses it for real estate searches
and tracking stocks; Denise, 13, uses America Online Instant
Messenger to keep up with friends; Richard, 11, is the gamer; and
Amy, 8, is into ``activityware'' like ``Mr. Potatohead'' and
``Spiderman Animator.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the network is up and running smoothly, things can
still be, well, tricky on the Bodor network.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son convinced me to set up a `Quake' (a game that can be
played over a network) server for the network, then ran crying to
his mother an hour later screaming, `Daddy is trying to blow me
up,''' says Bodor. ``He expected me to just stand there and let him
shoot me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creepy.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a fine line between dad and sysop.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his job at Rockwell Automation outside Atlanta, where
Bodor is up to his elbows in hardware, he has been able to indulge
in what he calls a hobby. His five-machine home network consists of
some 448 megabytes of RAM and 18 gigabytes of hard drive space
running on Pentiums of all flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Bodor says that when he connected his home network to the
Internet, his kids' interest in computers increased tenfold. Since
then, the network has become an integral part of the Bodors' home
life.
</P>
<P>
   While he admits it might appear odd to walk into his house and
find the whole family logged in at machines in different rooms,
Bodor says the family still does things offline together, like go
to movies. And the home network has opened a new avenue of family
communication, especially between father and adolescent daughter:
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect I could bring up things in an e-mail, like about her
friends or about boys, that I could never say face to face,'' he
says. ``When she tells me she's getting married, it'll be in an
e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Bodors' situation may be unique in that their network
has been around since 1992, they are an example of a market that
has the computer industry salivating. The home networking boom,
which began to build industry buzz only last year, is about to
explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market is just developing and starting to take off,''
said Thomas L. Funk, manager of strategic marketing for Compaq, but
speaking on behalf of the HomePNA. The Home Phoneline Networking
Association is a consortium of industry heavyweights formed last
summer to help develop standards for the technology allowing people
to use their existing telephone lines as a home network
infrastructure. Besides Compaq, other founding companies include
Microsoft, 3Com, Intel, AT&AMP;T, Lucent, AMD and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, generally there are about 15 to 20 million homes in
the United States that have multiple PCs,'' Funk said. ``Any home
that has multiple devices or is considering buying another computer
is a candidate (for home networking).''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with shrinking margins from PC sales, the computer
manufacturers see a way to recoup some of those losses: marketing
home networks so people will buy more than one computer. In fact,
computer companies large and small will gather in San Francisco
this week for Homenet '99, a two-day affair addressing this
emerging market.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a home network becomes more enticing as telecoms,
cable companies and Internet service providers merge and morph into
one-stop shops providing phone service, TV signals and Internet
access through a single big, fat data pipe into your home.
</P>
<P>
   The result, says Mike Wolf, networking industry analyst for the
high-tech market research firm Cahner's In-Stat Group, is that the
2 million home networks in the United States today will explode
into 13.8 million networked households by 2003, with end-use
revenues projected to be $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf and Funk point to plummeting PC prices and access to
high-speed broadband technology as the main forces helping to drive
this new trend. Besides the wholehearted endorsement of the
computer industry, there are other factors at play as well _ like
the way people have so readily adapted to high technology and the
Internet and its staggering growth and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone understands what the Net is, and the concept of a
network isn't as foreign as it used to be,'' says Wolf.
``Manufacturers have masked the difficulty of the technology.
They've softened and candy-coated it with install wizards and
things like that to make it easier, so the end user won't have to
really understand how a TCP stack works.''
</P>
<P>
   ven though he could probably offer a credible definition of a
TCP stack, Bob Vogel, who manages a 40-person network engineering
department for the satellite company Panamsat Corp., never really
had to deal with it. Even when he used software called Wingate, one
of several server software packages tailored to home networking, to
set up the three-machine Local Area Network running off a cable
modem in his Rockdale County home. The only thing required on his
end was for Vogel to install Wingate on the machine he designated
as a server and to copy a small program onto each of his other
machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program sets itself up,'' he said. One thing Vogel plans
to change, though, is which machine he uses as the server. It's
currently on the machine used by his 15-year-old son, Eric, who is
deeply into network gaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever he reboots, the whole network freezes,'' Vogel says.
``He's one of these kids who actually blows out his machine and
reloads Windows every now and then. He's always downloading stuff
from the Internet to try out and rebooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a home network is not much more difficult than
installing Wingate. The network doesn't need to be anything more
than some machines using Windows 95 or better and each equipped
with a network interface card and some cable connecting them.
</P>
<P>
   Because most people want to use a home network to share a single
Internet connection _ which can be done easily whether you use a
cable modem, ADSL or even a 56k dial-up modem _ some server
software is needed. (It acts as a traffic cop, making sure that the
different requests from each user's machine for access to the Net
don't collide and crash the whole shooting match.)
</P>
<P>
   If there will be more than two machines on the network, hardware
like a hub or router acts as a distribution point to the computers
on the LAN.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most difficult aspect of installing their networks
for Vogel and Bodor was running the cable. They each bought Cat5
cable, which consists of four twisted pairs of wire, as opposed to
standard telephone wire, which is two twisted pairs.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with not much more than a drill, Vogel and Bodor ran wire
through closets, across the basement, around baseboards and out of
ceilings when they retrofitted their homes for a network.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not elegant,'' said Vogel. ``What I did was go from the
bottom floor down to the basement, and the builder had a PVC pipe
with a flue that went from the basement to the attic. If that
wasn't there, I don't know what I would have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men said they wanted Cat5's capabilities to transmit data
at the blazingly fast speed of 100 megabytes per second. While that
may sound like the be-all and end-all in data speed, Cat6 cable _
which boasts a transmit rate of 250mbps _ is already on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Vogel and Bodor recommend buying network hardware from the Web
for the best prices and the most current versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't skimp on the NICs (network cards) and hubs,'' says
Vogel, who also suggests online auctions as a source of good
hardware. Vogel paid $30 apiece for some ``slightly used''
name-brand 100BaseT network interface cards that retail for about
$100 directly from the manufacturer's resellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great deals, and they worked fine. (There's) no software or
documentation, but you can get the latest drivers and manuals
directly from the 3Com Web site,'' he said. ``Name-brand LAN
hardware is so simple. There is little risk of DOAs (equipment that
doesn't work when it arrives), so Web buying is the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone wants to go around the house drilling holes in the
floor. But, like any good computer technology story, there are
several ways to go when setting up a home network ... none of which
is compatible with any of the others.
</P>
<P>
   Funk's consortium would call Vogel's network ``structured
wiring.'' The HomePNA advocates technology using already existing
phone lines, making home network set-up that much easier. Other
options currently available include RF (radio frequency) networks
and ``powerline'' networks, which use existing electrical lines as
a network infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Although structured wiring-type networks are predominant today
among the 2 million homes In-Stat currently counts, more than half
of those 13.8 million networks in 2003 are expected to use
phone-line technology, according to Wolf's research.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology's development will follow the whims of the
consumers, says Funk.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, consumers are weighing their choices while assessing
the benefits of home networking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like the old days when there was one telephone
and everyone had to fight over it. There are lots of anecdotal
stories of schedules hung by the PC _ whoever has a school paper
due tomorrow gets to use the computer first,'' Funk said. ``(When)
the consumer can have multiple points in the house using an
Internet connection, there's no more fighting over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter which technology is used to realize those
multiple-access points, the impact on families _ and how families
communicate in the new millennium _ should be substantial.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time, my son, wife and myself were all chatting with
grandpa at the same time,'' says Frank Romero, another home LAN
administrator who put a network into his Doraville home six months
ago when cable modem became available. ``He couldn't believe we
could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogel offers another example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally one of the kids will write a paper for
homework,'' he says, ``and I can be downstairs, and Eric will say,
`Would you take a look at one of my homework papers?' And I can
call it up (on the network).''
</P>
<P>
   But the benefits will always carry a downside, like where,
exactly, is that line between dad and sysop drawn? Certainly the
home networking boom will bring its own set of intrafamilial
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the gateway out (to the Internet). But I respect their
privacy, I don't look at their e-mail,'' says Bodor, defining the
gray area between dad and netmaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get a user calling me (about network trouble) after 9
p.m., I got a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-26-99 1043EDT &QL;
</P>
