 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
NPR still sluggish, but at least it's trying 
By Frances Katz  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When we last left our hero, the Web-challenged
National Public Radio, we were both amused and confused by NPR's
sheer lack of Web marketing know-how. Also taken to task were
Amazon.com and other online retailers for seriously underestimating
NPR's audience.
</P>
<P>
   In May, when I wrote the column about NPR's minimal use of the
Web, none of the big three booksellers was doing much to promote or
even stock NPR titles, which was odd, given the upscale, literate
and computer-savvy audience of NPR listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners were cheered somewhat several weeks ago when NPR
announced a deal to offer its programming on America Online. Users
who go to AOL keyword NPR will be connected to the latest news from
NPR in audio or video slide show format.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it seemed that NPR was hopping on the Web bandwagon in
a big way. A presence on AOL, consistently ranked the top news
destination on the Web by Media Metrix, would be a giant step
forward toward giving NPR a greater online presence.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that NPR will be a great asset to AOL's
already-considerable news area. Now users who are tired of generic
news have the option of tuning in to NPR's unique perspective on
world and national events. It's also a great opportunity for NPR to
put its best foot forward in front of AOL's 20 million users.
</P>
<P>
   However, NPR may have been smart enough to do the deal, but
still not smart enough to figure out how to build out its brand in
the interactive world. It makes you kind of want to shake your head
the way ABC newsman Ted Koppel did at presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis the night before Ronald Reagan won his landslide
victory in 1988, and mutter, ``You just don't get it, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   The NPR area of AOL is just as bland and boring and completely
devoid of personality as the NPR Web site. AOL users can listen to
NPR broadcasts without downloading any special software. This is
good. Listeners can also e-mail comments to NPR for possible on-air
reading. This is also good.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, here is where all the good things end. There are too many
missed opportunities to count. However, the area isn't even a month
old and, hopefully, there's a lot to this area users haven't seen
yet.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there is a link called ``transcripts,'' but all it
does is give you a phone number and an address to either call or
send away for tapes. Very reliable sources tell us that calling
this number to order tapes puts you into a voice mail system
reminiscent of Dante's seven circles of hell. Why NPR just doesn't
take advantage of AOL's infrastructure to let people order tapes
online is positively bewildering.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the message boards so listeners can e-mail such
airwave celebrities as Scott Simon, Nina Tottenberg or Terri Gross?
</P>
<P>
   It was encouraging to see a link called ``programs,'' but here
again, NPR drops the ball. Clicking any of the NPR programs listed
just gives you a written description _ a written description! _ of
the programs. At the very least there could have been a little
bitty sound clip of Gross plugging her wonderful show ``Fresh
Air.'' If there are issues involving rights and clearances that
keep NPR from putting more of its content online or making more of
it available online, please just tell us. We'll understand.
</P>
<P>
   However, users can link to the far more colorful Web sites for
member stations from Maine to California. Even the smallest site
for the smallest station in the smallest city lets users pledge
money, check out program schedules, volunteer, post messages and
provide feedback to the station. Makes you think, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the world waits for National Public Radio to
develop a Web strategy, Amazon and Borders were busy stocking up on
NPR-featured books and CDs. They were also busy building out
special areas for the items featured on NPR.
</P>
<P>
   Special mention goes to Borders.com, which also has an in-store
relationship with NPR. It went from a sad little NPR page that
didn't even have pictures of half the books to a pretty nice area
highlighted by some clever copy about how hard it is to keep track
of every book mentioned on NPR. However, the site gallantly offers
to try, and its selection is good. Amazon.com, which had a small
section devoted to NPR-featured materials, has added more stock to
its NPR area, which can be found in its ``As Featured in the
Media'' section.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, retailers don't need to be told twice when there's
money to be made on the Web. Hopefully, NPR will use its new home
on AOL to take advantage of the interactive as well as the audio
and text aspects of the Web and create something that will charm
longtime listeners and attract new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-26-99 1043EDT &QL;
