<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-KILLINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI'S YOSEMITE EFFORTS CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As a U.S. senator and the relatives of victims
questioned the FBI's investigation into four murders that have
shaken Yosemite National Park, a cab driver who gave the confessed
killer a two-hour ride from one of the crime scenes said the bureau
had failed to contact her.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Paul told The San Francisco Examiner that around Feb. 15
she picked up a man matching accused killer Cary Stayner's
description from Sierra Village _ near where the bodies of Yosemite
tourists Carole Sund and Silvina Pelosso were later found dead in
the trunk of their rented car _ and gave him a $170 cab ride back
to Yosemite Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But while it is routine police practice to canvass public
transportation operators in the area of a major crime, she said no
investigator contacted her or her husband, Geza Horvath, who run
Courtesy Cab Co. in Sonora.
</P>
<P>
   And though she later thought about phoning the FBI about her
unusual passenger after hearing that Pelosso, Sund and Sund's
daughter, Juli, disappeared last Feb. 15, she didn't because the
bureau by then had announced that all the suspects were in custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' she said. ``It was a shot in the dark. Plus, they
later said they had caught the people.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until she saw Stayner's face on television Sunday
following his arrest as a suspect in the killing of park naturalist
Joie Armstrong that she believed she'd had the alleged killer in
her gray, four-door 1994 Chevrolet Caprice cab. She then called the
FBI, which sent agents who duly took down her information.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it was critical because it placed him in the area,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Rossi, an FBI spokesman in Sacramento, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   A month after they disappeared, the charred bodies of Carole
Sund and Pelosso were found in their burned-out rental car near
Long Barn, not far from Sierra Village. Juli's nearly decapitated
body was found a week later near Don Pedro Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators had interviewed Stayner soon after their murders,
but they rejected him as a suspect. That decision has come under
fire in the wake of Stayner's reported confession that he killed
all four women.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa, a member of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, said the ``dismissal of Cary Stayner as a suspect ... by
the FBI means that the latest killing may have been preventable.''
</P>
<P>
   Raquel Pelosso, Silvina's mother, said she couldn't see how the
FBI missed Stayner, who worked as a handyman at the Cedar Lodge
Motel, where the three sightseers were staying the night they
disappeared as a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI interviewed him early on along with other motel
employees and dismissed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the FBI was on the right path before, and now it
shows that they were wrong, or they were not (looking at) the right
people,'' Pelosso said in a phone interview from her Argentina
home. ``We were really sorry this had to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tron Brekke, deputy assistant director of the FBI in Washington,
D.C., defended the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case, you're limited by the facts you develop,'' he
said. ``These are not for the most part Perry Mason moments, where
you interview somebody and they immediately confess. They aren't
solved in 30 minutes, like on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Stayner, 37, reportedly confessed to all four killings after his
arrest Saturday, sought because his car was seen near the cabin of
his latest victim. Armstrong, 26, a naturalist for the Yosemite
Institute, was reported missing last Wednesday and her decapitated
body was found in the park Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a report broadcast Wednesday, KNTV in San Jose said that
Stayer confessed in a jailhouse interview that he has fantasized
about killing women since childhood and committed all of the crimes
because he ``couldn't help himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Stayner, who was being held without bail in Sacramento County
Jail, claims he acted alone. He is the only person charged in the
case, and has been charged only with Armstrong's murder.
</P>
<P>
   The homicides have stirred enormous concern across the West,
because Yosemite, which is about 150 miles east of San Francisco,.
is a premier vacation destination, drawing 4 million visitors a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The case also has drawn criticism of the FBI amid signs that the
agency's task force investigating the killings might have focused
on the wrong suspects, alleged members of a local, loose-knit group
of petty criminals and methamphetamine abusers.
</P>
<P>
   Several of these backwoods dwellers _ whom local police call
``cranksters'' because they say their drug of choice is called
crank on the street _ have been in custody for unrelated crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials have said it was too soon to conclude
Stayner acted alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
