<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6882 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARRY-MARSHALL-LADN     07-28 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARRY-MARSHALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S WRONG WITH MAKING AUDIENCES FEEL GOOD?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Director Garry Marshall isn't into preaching
family values, but he seems to practice them both on and off the
set. On screen, Marshall's signature is sweet, often nostalgic
comedies. For television, he created and executive produced such
shows as ``Happy Days'' and ``Laverne &AMP; Shirley''; his movie
credits include ``The Flamingo Kid'' and ``Beaches,'' in addition
to ``Runaway Bride,'' the Julia Roberts/Richard Gere romantic
comedy opening Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall makes no apologies for making feel-good entertainment.
``People often say my films are too sweet ... That's OK,'' said
Marshall. With his thick Bronx accent and self-effacing manner,
he's a favorite of actors to both work with and imitate. At a
recent round of interviews for ``Bride,'' every actor, from Gere to
Rita Wilson to Hector Elizondo, had his or her own impression of
the affable Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that part of my directing style is that if I allow them
to make fun of me, then I can make fun of them, and we can all
relax,'' Marshall said, while fiddling with a toothpick (a
substitute for a cigarette; he kicked smoking more than a decade
ago, he says). ``A lot of people say you have to be above it all to
be an authority figure. One of my cinematographers told me I should
stand on a ladder, that that's how you direct. But I think it's
what you say, not where you stand, that puts you in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Another secret to Marshall's success is working well with
members of his family. He directed his sister, Penny Marshall (now
a director herself) in ``Laverne &AMP; Shirley.'' Now, he often uses
his son Scott as a second-unit director and has worked with
daughter Lori, who's a writer.
</P>
<P>
   His children wear many hats on his productions _ on ``Bride,''
for example, his son played bass in an impromptu scene where Gere
plays with a band on the street, while Lori stepped in to help Joan
Cusack and Julia Roberts improvise some dialogue in another scene.
That's one reason Marshall likes working with them. ``I find that I
can talk shorthand with them. I find that they will help my work
and not have an ego problem,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just his own kids who are benefiting from
Marshall's show-business experience. In November 1997, Marshall
opened the Falcon Theatre in Burbank, partly as a venue to
introduce young people to theater and to season up-and-coming
writers and actors who later may move into film and television.
</P>
<P>
   The theater sponsors an annual young playwright's competition
for students around the country and puts on plays for both adults
and children. Lori Marshall wrote a version of ``Rapunzel'' that
recently was staged at the theater; Gary's daughter Kathleen has
produced shows there, and Scott has directed.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said a big hope for the 99-seat theater is to create a
kind of farm team for TV and movies. ``I think you've got to
develop some writers and actors,'' Marshall said. ``In live
theater, not so much is at stake. The budgets are so high on movies
now ... vaudeville's out now, the clubs are out, so there's nowhere
else for these people to develop.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
