 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, July 29.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Beijing) _ On the receding danger that China will
use force against Taiwan. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA (Pristina) _ The Kosovo Liberation Army has taken
sweeping political control in Kosovo and its leaders are vowing
that they will not cede their power _ organized into a network of
self-appointed ministries, local councils and seized businesses _
to the U.N. administrators appointed to oversee the province. By
Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-ACCIDENT (Boenigen, Switzerland) _ More on the adventurers
``canyoning'' down the gorges, rivers and creeks of the Swiss Alps
who were killed when a thunderstorm suddenly stuck and they were
overtaken by a flash flood. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-CANYONING (Undated) _ The wild, new age sport of
``canyoning'' is outlawed in several states. By Christopher S.
Wren.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-RIGHTS (Paris) _ France, a country that has proudly
enshrined human rights since 1789, is ordered by the European Court
of Human Rights to pay the equivalent of $100,000 to a convicted
Dutch-Moroccan drug dealer for violating his rights with police
``torture'' to make him confess. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate opens debate on its
version of the tax bill, with amendments voted on through the
night. Final vote expected on Thursday. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-MANAGED-CARE (Washington) _ A Kaiser Foundation survey
of doctors and nurses finds that they believe managed care is
having a negative impact on their patients; 9 in 10 say their
patients have been denied coverage by health plans and 61 percent
say HMOs have denied their patients prescriptions. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   CLARK-RETIRE (Washington) _ Even though the chairman of the
Joint Chiefs, Gen. Henry H. Shelton, spent all of Thursday with the
NATO commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark last week, Shelton didn't tell
Clark that his tour would be shortened by two months until
yesterday when he was called on an official trip to Lithuania. How
and why the Pentagon decided to let Clark retire from his post as
Supreme Commander of NATO rather than lose Gen. Joseph Ralston, of
the Air Force, the vice-chairman of the Joint Chiefs, who will
replace him. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-JEWS (Washington) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton tries to
mend fences with Jewish leaders over some of the political
positions she has taken recently. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-PRISONS (Miami) _ The FBI and state law-enforcement
officials are investigating Florida prisons to see whether there is
widespread abuse of prisoners by guards. The inquiry was set off by
the recent stomping death of a death-row inmate. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TEACHER (Andover, Mass.) _ A profile of retiring Phillips
Academy teacher Tom Lyons, who was recently hailed by George W.
Bush as the best teacher he ever had. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI-ALA (Birmingham) _ New York City's Mayor winds up his
Southern fundraising tour. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARK-FLAG (New York) _ The battle of the flag (the Arkansas
one put up by Mayor Giuliani) continues here with the speaker of
the City Council, Peter Vallone, arguing that the City Council has
jurisdiction over what flags can fly over City Hall and he wants
the Arkansas one down immediately.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CRIME-SCENE (New York) _ News organizations settle with the
Giuliani administration over access to crime scenes. By Alan
Finder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SLOAN-VARMUS (New York) _ Folo report that Harold Varmus,
the powerful and respected chief of the National Institutes of
Health, is about to be hired away by Memorial Sloan-Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-CELLS (Undated) _ Years after they learned how to
make mouse cells cancerous, researchers report in the journal
Nature that they have finally managed to do the same with human
cells. It takes introduction of just three proteins to cause a
human cell to divide wildly like a cancer cell; one protein turns
out to be the enzyme telomerase, which regulates the ends of
chromosomes. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-SOCIETY (Undated) _ Lobbying over the issue of human
embryonic stem cell research has generated such heat that the
American Cancer Society has withdrawn its sponsorship of Patient's
Cure, a group founded to publicize the medical benefits of stem
cell research. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BIG-BOARD-SURVIVE (New York) _ Skeptics are again predicting the
demise of the New York Stock Exchange. Its trading floor is no
match, they say, for the new computer-driven trading systems.
Indeed, the Big Board and its chief executive, Richard A. Grasso,
face a daunting array of challenges as they search for a survival
strategy. The exchange must protect its franchise and find a way to
blend the best aspects of its floor-based auction system with the
speed and the capacity that only computers can provide. It must
become more cost-efficient without becoming less careful about how
it conducts business. And, as a public company, it must figure out
how to make money doing all this _ enough money to placate
potentially impatient shareholders. By Diana Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-IPO (New York) _ Looking at Nasdaq's plan to go public.
By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-IPO (Undated) _ Charter Communications Inc., the company
founded by Paul Allen that has become the fourth-largest cable
television operator in the United States, says it plans to raise
$3.45 billion in an initial public offering. By Geraldine
Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-DAEWOO (Seoul) _ No one can quite divine the meaning of
the government's decision to step in with more than $8 billion to
prevent Daewoo from defaulting. In bringing to an end the series of
debt rollovers that has kept Daewoo going for the last several
years, has the government indicated a renewed commitment to reform?
Or was the intervention reminiscent of the past, when
government-directed lending and political considerations, rather
than market forces, determined the winners and losers in South
Korea's economy? By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column. By Michael M.
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Alan Greenspan reprises his testimony
from last week, this time before the Senate Banking Committee. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Compaq Computer is expected to
report earnings. A loss of 11 cents a share is the consensus
forecast. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   SOCCER-BIZ (Manchester, England) _ Manchester United, soccer
champions of England and Europe, has a difficult challenge ahead in
matching its phenomenal success as a business. BSkyB's 1 billion
pound offer for the club, had sharply raised market expectations
for professional soccer before British regulators blocked the offer
last March. BSkyB, for its part, received some good news today,
when a court upheld the satellite TV provider's contract with
England's soccer league. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ By late morning, stocks were slightly lower.
The Dow Jones industrial average was down 16 points, the S&AMP;P down
nearly 2 points and the Nasdaq composite index flat. The 30-year
bond was yielding 6.03 percent. European markets were slightly
higher, with London up 0.28 percent and Frankfurt up 0.10 percent.
The Nikkei closed up 0.67 percent and the Hang Seng ended up 0.50
percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America'' and William Safire's ``Essay.''
