<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOSE OF HMO IS BAD MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's the job of medicine to help people die young
as late in life as possible. Supposedly, it's the job of health
insurance companies to assist in that chore.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, though, the healers and their patients are
at war with health insurance company bean counters. As the
population ages and the cost of medical care shoots up, health
insurers struggle to save money while physicians and patients
struggle to obtain adequate care.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, all three sides in this epic clash seem to be
losing. Nobody understands that better than Elsa Goldstein. She had
a medical emergency one night not long ago. She went to a hospital
emergency room, was given a medication in the hospital by a
physician and a prescription that the doctor wrote for aftercare.
She had to take this stuff twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the local pharmacy,'' she told me, ``where I have
coverage through my HMO, and it was rejected. They wanted to charge
me $109 for this medication.''
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``The pharmacist told you that the insurance company
wouldn't pay for this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct,'' Elsa Goldstein said. ``I had to call the
insurance company, and they said they would not pay because it was
not the HMO doctor who wrote the prescription. So, I went home, and
I called the insurance company again, and the gentleman who
answered the phone told me that they wouldn't pay for a
prescription written by a doctor who was not on their panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I explained that I was seen by an emergency room physician
and that he gave me the prescription. And he said, `It still has to
be written by your primary care doctor.'''
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``That doctor's office is closed now, and I need to take
this medicine tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``It still has to be written by your primary care
doctor. Anyway, that drug isn't on formula, and we wouldn't pay for
it anyhow.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he said, ``Why don't you take _ and he mentioned an
over-the-counter preparation instead.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which seriously annoyed Elsa Goldstein because she
happens to be a physician herself. Dr. Goldstein spent many years
in training to learn which medications are appropriate for which
ailments. This guy on the other end of the phone was recommending
something that not only wouldn't work but could cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incorrect medical advice,'' she told me. ``It was
dangerous medical advice ... Fortunately, I knew better than to
take his advice. But, also, this was illegal. He was practicing
medicine without a license.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Goldstein is a colon-rectal surgeon. She spent a decade as
an HMO employee before she went into private practice and began
using her husband's medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The transition was a shock of profound proportions. She'd had
fine health care as an HMO employee. But, as a non-connected
consumer of health care, everything was different.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Goldstein understood the HMO rules. She knew what was
covered. But her HMO just wouldn't pay for covered services. Time
and again, they would allege that they hadn't been billed properly
or even billed at all _ even when the bill was faxed to them.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Goldstein suspects that this HMO is simply refusing to pay
and hoping that nervous patients, dunned enough times, will pay
instead, even though they shouldn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   After repeated incidents of this, she wrote a letter of
complaint to the New York State Insurance Department. The fact is,
though, that the managed care system is less about care than about
costs. The insurance companies exhibit little to zero concern for
prolonging human life and preventing human suffering.
</P>
<P>
   And, in case you haven't noticed, the politicians are doing
nothing much to fix that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
