<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6914 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-CYC-SOIGNEUR-BOS &LR;      07-28 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-CYC-SOIGNEUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S US POSTAL'S SOIGNEUR PAR EXCELLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARBES, France _ Yes, US Postal Service bicycle team director
Johan Bruyneel knows a lot about his riders legs and the strength
that makes them go. But someone else has a pretty good idea, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's Emma O'Reilly, the head soigneur on the team, or the
person who serves as combination masseuse, nutritionist, and
confidante. The team has four soigneurs to look after the nine
riders, and O'Reilly is the head one who is assigned to Tour winner
Lance Armstrong and teammate Kevin Livingston. After every race for
the past three weeks, she's the one who has loosened their leg
muscles, listened to their moods, and mostly been the quiet leader
behind the team and the member who won the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly will travel with Armstrong to whatever races he enters
with the Postal Service team through this season, which ends in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Soigneurs have always played an important role in cycling. But
mirroring the male environment of European proofessional bicycling,
women have rarely, if ever, been admitted to the club. That meant
wives and girlfriends were off limits during the race, and of
course a woman was never a staff member.
</P>
<P>
   But leave it to the Americans to break that barrier. When
7-Eleven, the first US-based team to ride the Tour, entered it in
1986, the roster included two women soigneurs. In America, it's
typical to have women work on men's teams, so why not in Europe?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the breakthough didn't seem to have any impact, and when
the 7-Eleven folded and left Eruope, so did women's participation.
</P>
<P>
   Enter O'Reilly, who was signed with the Postal Service team when
it was formed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gorski, the general manager, acknowledges that he had
underestimated her influence on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we didn't know how much better she'd be than a
guy soigneur, but she's just phenomenal,'' he said. ``She just has
more sensitivity, knows what the guys need. She's professional and
has a great attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, he said, she was looked upon as a publicity gimmick by
the other European teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only team in professional cycling that has a woman
soigneur, and initially they thought we were crazy, that we were
unfocused,'' he said. ``But now I think lot of teams realize we
have an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly, on one of the team's rare days off in the Tour, sits
in her small hotel room that is crammed with her luggage, as well
as coolers of water, boxes of cereal, and her folded-up massage
table leaning against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the other soigneurs have driven to town to pick up more
groceries, while another is doing the riders' laundry in the washer
and dryer in the team's truck.
</P>
<P>
   Her work will involve giving massages to Armstrong and
Livingston after their training rides, filling the riders' musettes
(feed bags) with processed food and energy bars, and generally
looking after the riders' non-racing needs like making sure enough
liters of bottled water are put inside every room.
</P>
<P>
   The soigneurs will eat dinner after the riders that night, and
before the riders the next morning. Then they'll finish filling the
feed bags with omelet cakes and paninis (rolls filled with cream
cheese), drive ahead to the ``feed zone'' halfway down the race
course, and stand on the side of the road to dangle the musettes
for the racers to grab as they ride by. After that, it's a rushed
drive on back roads to get to the finish before the men do and
position themselves at the line to greet the riders and steer them
toward the team car to take them to their hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the soigneurs will get to the hotel, set up their
massage tables to rub down each rider, and think about having
dinner before they do it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly, with auburn hair and a lilting Irish accent, is
nothing like the mostly large, French, Spanish, and
Italian-speaking men who surround her on the course.
</P>
<P>
   She stumbled onto her current job when she and her family used
to travel around Ireland to watch her brother race. After high
school, O'Reilly, 29, enrolled in electrician's trade school, took
massage and sports injury courses, then started doing massages part
time.
</P>
<P>
   When she was asked to be a soigneur on the Irish national team,
she leapt at the chance, but not really from a passion for cycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really did it because I could take holidays with the
national team,'' O'Reilly said as her eyes lit up. ``I mean,
touring for nothing, how great.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, after a friend who was a mechanic on an American
racing team invited her to come to America, O'Reilly got her green
card, packed up her massage table and headed across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went not knowing I had job, but I'd quit my job and wanted
to travel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After a year rooming with a racer's girlfriend in Boulder,
Colo., the Shaklee team offered her a job in 1995. The following
year the Postal Service team was formed, and recruited O'Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very lucky,'' she said. ``But I never really chased it, I
just liked to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly said that being in the minority at work is nothing new
to her, since she was the only women among 40 men at her
electrician's job. She shrugs and laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always get the dirty joke first; you know what I mean?'' she
said. ``Things like that . . . and they always laugh at me because
I shower so quick at home.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly said that even though she's treated equally at the race
by the other soigneurs (``They're grand''), it wasn't always that
way.
</P>
<P>
   When she started, marshalls at the finish line would ignore her
credential and push her away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would literally be lifted and dropped like 10 feet away,''
said the 5-foot-4-inch O'Reilly. ``But the other soigneurs would
come help, and say `leave her alone, she's with us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly, whose job is kind of like a resident assistant's in a
dormitory, always keeps her door open so the riders can come in and
get water from the coolers in her room. So the key is always in the
door, until O'Reilly decides that it's lights-out, and time for
some privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's just pure survival mode, and I put the water
outside my door,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly, is there to clean up ``the lads' scrapes,'' listen to
them talk about their day as they lay on the massage table, or
ignore them if they're talking on a cell phone the whole time. And
even if other teams look on O'Reilly as a curiousity, her team is
blase about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had women soigneurs on the national team and other teams,
so it's no big deal for us,'' Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Emma's great; she takes good care of us,'' he said. ``If
we've might had bad day, she's there to cheer you up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
