<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6917 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWENGLAND-Y2K-2TAKES     07-28 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWENGLAND-Y2K-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRMS APPEAR TO BE READY FOR Y2K 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER AND PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- With just over five months to go before the crucial
test of Y2K computer readiness, New England institutions generally
have strong confidence that residents will be able to turn on the
lights, flush the toilet, and use the telephone and teller machine
come Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many officials are worried about what might
happen if too many people try to prove it to themselves at 12:01
a.m. and trigger a host of problems potentially as bad as anything
caused by technical malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   A Globe survey of Massachusetts utilities, hospitals, government
agencies, and other major institutions found that most say their
key computer systems are ready to handle the date changeover to
01/01/00.
</P>
<P>
   While a considerable number of smaller organizations _ such as
municipal governments, police departments, and local banks _ have
not upgraded their systems to handle Y2K issues, planners expect
these institutions will have enough time to finish and test their
remediation programs.
</P>
<P>
   Just how to make their optimism credible is still a matter of
controversy among regulators. But with the bulk of reviews
complete, officials say, they don't expect major technical
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can give 1,000 percent guarantees of anything,'' said
Cathy Minehan, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston.
``But we're beginning to start feeling as confident about our
systems now as we want to be at the start of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hannon, top information systems officer for the city of
Boston, agreed. ``Clearly, the work that we've done has paid off,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A federal report earlier this month cited Boston and Dallas as
the only big-city governments in the United States where key
services were already prepared for the date change.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K, short for Year 2000, refers to a potential glitch in many
older computer systems that represent years as only two digits in a
code. When 99 becomes 00, some computers may be confused about what
year is intended and crash or shut down.
</P>
<P>
   With Y2K worries gradually easing, attention is shifting to
secondary issues, such as how to cope with the tendency to hoard
money and food as the end of the year approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is mainly one of public relations. Even curiosity
could be cause for concern: If a significant number of people turn
on lights and appliances or pick up their phones at 12:01 a.m. Jan.
1 just to see if they work, some service networks might not be able
to handle the extra load.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest national risk we have is overreaction from the
public,'' said John Koskinen, President Clinton's senior adviser on
Y2K matters. To ease worries, Koskinen has appeared at scores of
public forums around the country where public officials and
business leaders tout their progress.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-jitter efforts are also moving into high gear at companies
such as Bell Atlantic, which recently finished a $400 million-plus
Y2K repair job involving 11,000 components of its telephone
network, such as switches and call routers..
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is still a real human behavior issue,'' says Skip
Patterson, Bell Atlantic's top Y2K compliance official. ``If
everyone goes off hook at midnight to see if they are going to get
dial tone, they won't all get dial tone.''
</P>
<P>
   For economic reasons, the typical central office, serving 10,000
phone numbers, is designed to handle calls from only 20 percent at
a time, the typical maximum.
</P>
<P>
   A stampede to the telephone at the stroke of midnight could
cause many people to get fast busy signals, perhaps triggering
fears that the phone network has gone down or, in rare cases,
causing a collapse of telephone switching equipment.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the risk of a power surge from people turning on
lights and appliances at 12:01 a.m. Jan. 1 to make sure they still
work, New England power managers ``will have twice as much power
available as we would normally need on a cold Friday night in
December when businesses and offices are shut down,'' said Walter
Salvi, a Boston Edison spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a contingency our Y2K management team has anticipated,
and we are confident we can handle it'' by having power plants
warmed up to cover a demand spike, Salvi said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Water Resources Authority officials are also
optimistic on water and sewer service.
</P>
<P>
   Water to Greater Boston residents' taps is ``principally driven
by gravity, and there's no way that Y2K can screw that up,'' said
agency chief Douglas B. MacDonald. If all 1.9 million water
customers stockpiled 50 gallons in a bathtub the week before New
Year's Day, that would drain only 0.02 percent of the Quabbin
Reservoir's capacity.
</P>
<P>
   At the Deer Island sewage plant, the MWRA is installing $800,000
worth of emergency generators and will top them off with fuel in
late December to make sure the pumps that treat and move sewage
keep working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our principal Y2K strategy is to run our own (emergency)
generators through the night until we are confident the rest of the
electric system works'' and the MWRA can switch back to Boston
Edison for power, MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge remaining is to persuade the public to
accept the reassurances of electric and telephone utilities, said
Bell Atlantic's Patterson. ``We think that's basically our last
battle in this war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed's Minehan and other government officials have
applauded work by the private sector, regulators are facing growing
pressure to disclose more of what they know about firms that lag on
Y2K readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, the public hasn't been given good reason not to head
for the hills,'' Richard Torrenzano, a former spokesman for the New
York Stock Exchange, told bank regulators in a speech last month.
He proposed ``seals of approval'' for banks that have met
government standards.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6919 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWENGLAND-Y2K-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     07-28 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWENGLAND-Y2K-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... government standards.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It would serve the public interest to know more'' about
preparations at individual companies, said Howard Rubin, a computer
science professor at Hunter College in New York and a Y2K
consultant to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to the airport, you get a list of what other
airports are dangerous to go to'' because of lax security, Rubin
said. ``This should be no different.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one major industry group is about to heed this advice.
The North American Electric Reliability Council, charged by the US
Energy Department with ensuring that the nation's electric grids
will continue to function through the date change, so far has
spoken of utility readiness only in generalities. But in a report
due Aug. 3, the council plans to disclose names of major
electric-power companies that met, or nearly met, a June 30
deadline to ready their systems.
</P>
<P>
   While the group will not single out failing companies, those
whose names do not appear on the two other lists can count on tough
questions from customers, shareholders, and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to release more detail is intended to increase
accountability and ease public worries about Y2K-triggered
blackouts, said Gary L. Neale, an Indiana power-company executive
who is chairman of the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten together and said if we don't start releasing
more information, then we'll never combat the fear factor,'' said
Neale.
</P>
<P>
   Said Michael Morris, head of Northeast Utilities in Berlin,
Conn.: ``You're never going to get people's confidence if you're
not going to let them see things. You can't just say, `Trust me.'
You've got to get a little deeper into it.''
</P>
<P>
   The reliability council's approach hasn't caught on in the
banking and financial services sector, another key area for Y2K
worries. So far, financial regulators have been willing to speak
only in broad terms about Y2K compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Citing federal rules, US officials won't specify which banks
they have found lacking, except for a handful of very small but
seriously troubled institutions. Of the 10,400 government-insured
banks in the country, only 2 percent, or about 200, missed recent
target dates to upgrade their systems, down from 357 in March, the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You label somebody unsatisfactory, and they're labeled that
for eternity, when it doesn't mean they won't be ready for Y2K,
just that there are deficiencies in their program,'' FDIC spokesman
David Barr said. ``It's still solvable.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor will the FDIC allow large banks like BankBoston Corp. to
disclose what grades they have received from federal examiners,
even if the grades are good and would bolster customers' confidence
their money will be accessible and properly tallied.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts banking commissioner, Thomas Curry, said the
downside of identifying laggards or allowing compliant banks to
tout their success is that doing so could destabilize otherwise
sound institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Curry said two small Bay State banks missed a June 30 deadline
to make certain fixes, but he would not name them.
</P>
<P>
   To cope with the demand for extra cash, the Federal Reserve is
printing $50 billion of additional cash later this year, an amount
equal to $184 for every person in the United States. Officials
expect this extra currency will be enough to cover the needs of
bank customers who take out, say, a week's worth of cash to have on
hand in case their local ATM fails on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators also say they have taken action against a handful of
small institutions, such as First Alliance Bank and Trust Co. in
Manchester, N.H., which for almost a year has been operating under
the terms of a federal order aimed at improving its operations.
</P>
<P>
   First Alliance, which is the 14th largest of New Hampshire's 20
commercial banks, doesn't admit or deny allegations by regulators
last year that it had failed to prepare for Jan. 1, 2000, and
otherwise operated in ``an unsafe and unsound manner,'' according
to a First Alliance filing with the FDIC.
</P>
<P>
   But in accepting the order last September, the bank consented to
FDIC demands that it upgrade its computers, hire outside
consultants, and name a new top executive.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the bank has spent about $50,000 reviewing its
computers and putting its 18 employees to work on backup plans in
case its two ATMs crash. Now the bank plans to stock provisions
like extra bookkeeping pads and a manual typewriter to draw up
money orders, as well as plastic sheeting to cordon off office
space if a heating system fails.
</P>
<P>
   New chief executive Alan J. Cieto has also been telling scores
of the bank's largest clients about his efforts to make
improvements. None of his roughly 2,000 customers have closed
accounts as a result of Y2K worries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cieto wasn't required to disclose details of the federal review
to customers and in most cases hasn't done so, instead sending out
general letters summarizing the bank's remediation efforts. Several
of the bank's patrons said that they had heard of the deficiencies
only in broad terms, but that Cieto's communiques persuaded them
not to worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they're really on top of it,'' said Mark
Padfield, president of New Hampshire Blacktop Sealers Inc. in
Auburn. Beside, federal insurance should cover any losses that
might result from Y2K problems, he said. ``If something screws up,
they'll just be bought out, and I'll be paying my mortgage to
somebody else,'' Padfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials bet most people will wind up regarding Y2K as
does Padfield. An April Massachusetts Bankers Association poll of
200 people found 18 percent considered Y2K a serious problem, with
39 calling it a moderate problem and 31 percent saying it was
minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a hard core of people who think this is the
apocalypse,'' said Robert Fichter of the bankers group. But their
numbers will dwindle, he said. ``Most people will realize their
money's not going to disappear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
