<HEADLINE>
RESTRAC RESURRECTS ITSELF VIA THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can find many things on the Internet, even an occasional
second chance.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Restrac Inc., a Lexington, Mass. company that sold
high-tech systems for companies to automate and track their
recruiting operations. The stock went public with the usual hype in
the summer of 1996, took a terrible beating when it failed to meet
expectations for its very first quarter out and stayed down.
</P>
<P>
   Restrac was a ``fallen angel,'' in the parlance of investors who
buy small high-tech stocks. Once those angels fall, it is
notoriously difficult for them to get back on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to June 1 this year when the company rechristened
itself as Webhire Inc., provider of ``end to end'' Internet
recruiting services.
</P>
<P>
   An even more important development occurred last week. Internet
super investor Softbank Capital Partners pumped $20 million into
the company and bought an existing 1.7 million share block for
about $10 million more to suddenly acquire a 40 percent interest in
the company.
</P>
<P>
   It was a glorious turn of events for shareholders who had stuck
through the brief but glum public life of Restrac/Webhire stock.
The shares, which could be purchased for 5 per share on June 1,
finished Tuesday at 14 1/8 and traded nearly a dollar higher than
that at its midsession peak.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest beneficiary of all was Softbank, which now owns
an interest in Webhire worth nearly double what it paid a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, there was nothing new about Webhire's operation or
its strategy. A shift of its product line toward Internet
applications had been gradually underway since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an overnight Internet success story just waiting
12 to 18 months to happen,'' said analyst Robert Austrian of
BancAmerica Securities. ``We finally got the match thrown in the
tinderbox.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift toward an Internet world, and the wide-eyed investor
expectations that go along with it, is a common event at
corporations doing all kinds of work. In businesses like Webhire
that focus on the management of information, you can move with the
Internet tide or, probably, drown.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those companies once known for whatever service they
provided to customers suddenly become defined for investors not by
the service but by the Web delivery system they adopt.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether those companies can use the Internet to
grow business to the degree suggested by hyperbolic Web-stock
valuations. Some will, but many others can't possibly make good on
the hope.
</P>
<P>
   One key to distinguishing the winners: whether the Web actually
expands the kinds of services a company offers to a broader base of
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Webhire began investing in Internet services shortly after its
stock crashed, when it was known as Restrac. The company spent more
money on research and development in 1997 than it had for the
previous seven years combined. Its stock price couldn't get much
worse, and Restrac began to record losses as a result of its
research and development investment.
</P>
<P>
   Webhire president Martin J. Fahey said the company was certain
its traditional business of automating resumes and recruiting
information on relatively expensive client-server computer hardware
would be affected by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But it also saw an opportunity to build a business that could
electronically sort through thousands of resumes posted on other
Internet sites for its corporate clientele, dramatically expanding
the pool of potential job candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Even better: though many Internet businesses had been built to
cater to job seekers of all kinds, there was practically no big
competition to serve the people who were doing the hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the issues with our company three or four years ago was
that we were a big fish and a small pond,'' said Fahey. ``When we
went public, the question was, `How big could your market possibly
be?' ''
</P>
<P>
   A booming economy and the very tight labor market that followed
made demand for a broader Webhire seem even more plausible.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're not all the way there, the things we thought would
happen definitely have,'' said Fahey. ``It's a rebirth in that
sense, something we're very proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   But there isn't any rebirth in Webhire's financial numbers so
far. The company posted the widest quarterly losses in its public
history recently, and revenues have been down in year-ago
comparisons for three straight quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Fahey said Webhire's weaker revenues are partly due to the
financial ups and downs of converting many existing customers to
Web-based systems, some of which are priced differently. His
argument: much of Webhire's new Internet-based revenues are a
recurring, annuity-style stream of cash that will be a big
long-term plus.
</P>
<P>
   Our question: Can Webhire live up to its suddenly explosive
stock price or will shareholders with big expecations be
disappointed again?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that the expecations have become so radical,''
said analyst Austrian. It's more that there's suddenly a
recongition of great potential that is dramatically more likely to
be realized with Softbank as a partner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
