u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-PLATTERS-ART-BO     07-28 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PLATTERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT PRETENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Concertgoers at the Cape Cod Melody Tent in Hyannis
got a dose of musical nostalgia Saturday night as the Platters, the
Drifters, and the Coasters crooned soulful oldies, including
love-soaked tunes like ``The Magic Touch'' and ``Smoke Gets In Your
Eyes,'' that made the bands famous in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   On the same evening, Herb Reed and the Platters _ a group that
features Reed himself, the only surviving member of the original
Platters band _ performed at a nightclub in East Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement may seem unusual, but the practice is
commonplace at concert halls and musical venues across the country,
where numerous same-name knockoffs of other legendary oldies
groups, including the Supremes, the Spinners, and the Marvelettes,
can be found singing on stage virtually every day of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But there seem to be more Platters out there than you would find
in an Italian restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sahara casino in Las Vegas, for example, a band called
the Platters plays nightly, year-round. In Branson, Mo., another
group dubbed the Platters puts on about 200 shows annually.
</P>
<P>
   As the summer concert season swings into full gear, a
long-running debate over who has the legal authority to use the
names of the Platters and other famed oldies bands has emerged with
renewed vigor.
</P>
<P>
   To musicians like Reed, who founded the original Platters and
coined the group's name more than 45 years ago, the growing
prevalence of copycat bands _ many of whom pass themselves off as
originals _ amounts to blatant musical plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just raping my name and stealing my legacy,'' Reed,
who lives in Arlington, said in his gravelly baritone. ``It really
breaks your heart to see a group that calls itself the Platters
appearing here and there when you've never even met these people
and they have nothing to do with your success or your name.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, often due to poor business decisions made decades
ago, original band members have lost the right to use monikers they
coined in the 1950s and 1960s. Other aging singers, having failed
to trademark the names of groups they founded in their youth, now
find they have lost the rights to perform under those names.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has spawned dozens of legal battles nationwide between
original band members and so-called imposter bands. And it has
caused confusion among many music lovers, who often pay steep
ticket prices in anticipation of seeing original oldies groups,
only to hear imitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are bands who are not the '50s and '60s recording stars
they're advertising themselves to be,'' said East Boston musician
Pat Benti, executive director of a nonprofit group called FAME,
which stands for Friends Against Musical Exploitation. ``To me,
it's just not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Musical purists won a legal victory in April, when a federal
appeals court issued a ruling in San Francisco that granted Reed
exclusive use of the ``Platters'' trademark. Similar litigation is
pending in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But many concert producers who routinely book copycat bands say
the issue is far from black and white, and insist that most
non-original groups are legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a group is licensed, has a trademark, and presents music in
fashion that is professional and consistent with the way this music
was originally recorded, then they are valid to perform before the
public,'' said Harvey Robbins, a Boston-area producer of oldies
concerts who calls the issue ``extremely, extremely complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are a renegade outfit with no license and no legal
claim to the name,'' added Robbins, who has debated the topic on
several talk-radio programs, ``then they can't and should not
appear.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of non-original bands also say any savvy consumer
should realize that few 1950s-era musical groups are likely to be
intact today. They also note that, unlike musicians of the 1980s
and 1990s whose individual identities are all-important _ such as
Madonna, Bruce Springsteen, or Rod Stewart _ bands of the 1950s and
1960s were known by name rather than by their members.
</P>
<P>
   And they point out that Reed's band isn't authentic, either,
since it includes only one founding member of the original group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, legislative efforts are under way to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Several musicians are working with a bipartisan group of Capitol
Hill legislators who have introduced the Truth in Rock Act, a bill
aimed at protecting the names of original oldies groups from being
appropriated by phonies.
</P>
<P>
   And in Massachusetts, consumer protection legislation has been
filed by state Representative Salvatore F. DiMasi, a North End
Democrat, to address the issue of consumers buying tickets to
concerts featuring performers who are not original band members.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, said Reed's lawyer, T. Christopher Donnelly, such
legislation should prevent imposter groups from ``riding the
coattails'' of original bands' success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
