<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6924 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-CHERRIES-BOS &LR;      07-28 1461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-CHERRIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON HARVEST BRINGS JOBS HOUSING WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WENATCHEE, Wash. _ In a tangle of trees down by the Columbia
River, just past a sign advertising triple ripe cherries for sale,
64-year-old Gilberto Vallejo sleeps in the back of his red pickup
truck and envies Alberto Hernandez's accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks now, Hernandez, 50, has been sleeping, four men to a
tiny tent, beside the railroad tracks. The floor is no more than a
sheet of plastic, but at least he has access to water for washing
and bathrooms to stumble toward in the dark. Still, he wishes he
had Lourdes Alvarado's living arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarado, her husband and two sons have a spot in one of
Washington's choicer camps for cherry pickers. Among the amenities
in their tent _ larger than some studio apartments and provided
free by the orchard owner _ are a full-size refrigerator, ice
chest, and battery-operated lanterns. The floor is solid. There are
bunk beds with mattresses. Even so, Alvarado dreams of being able
to afford a motel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have hot water,'' exclaimed Alvarado, 50, wearing a
pink-and-white checkered apron as she prepared her ``spinach
special'' on the portable stove also provided by the orchard owner.
``It's better every year. It's better than nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing _ no place to sleep, no place to cook, no place to wash
_ is what thousands of migrant workers found awaiting them when
they returned to Washington for this summer's cherry harvest. In a
dispute that everyone from federal overseers to state officials to
the pickers themselves say is tinged with irony, efforts to improve
the living conditions of migrant workers have led most of the
grower-run labor camps to close.
</P>
<P>
   Those camps, some little more than a collection of pup tents
pitched on bare ground, some far more elaborate than the camping
facilities in state parks, were all that many of the migrants who
make their way to Washington from California and Mexico each year
had to call home.
</P>
<P>
   But the state-licensed camps weren't enough to ease the housing
crisis that confronts agricultural workers everywhere. Neither did
they meet minimum federal standards for temporary worker housing.
So in May, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration
ordered growers to upgrade or face sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have more and better camps unless you have
regulations and incentives,'' said Richard Terrill, OSHA's regional
director. ``If a camp by the river or a camp where workers bring
their own tents becomes an acceptable standard, that's all you will
ever have. This year saw some tough choices.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, all but a handful camps chose not to reopen, forcing
2,000 pickers into their vans or onto the riverbank come nightfall.
Like Ramon Gomez, 40, who has been sleeping in a state park, they
joined the thousands of other migrants who never had housing in the
first place. An estimated 16,000 to 30,000 workers pick Washington
cherries each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'd prefer to live somewhere with a bathroom,
someplace where I could wash up after work,'' said Gomez, who
follows the cherry harvest in an old tan-and-white van shared by a
half-dozen friends. ``But we couldn't get into a camp. There never
were a lot of places to stay and now there are none.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at its 1997 peak, only a minuscule fraction of the cherry
orchards _ 32 out of 1,800 _ participated in the state's pilot
housing program, said Maria Gardipee, who oversees agricultural
employee programs at the state Department of Health. This year, the
number of licensed camps fell to eight _ all of them relying on
tents the state had made to meet federal standards and is now
renting out for $200 a month. But there are only 29 tents, far too
few to meet worker demand. The state hopes to have more on hand
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The clash between OSHA, which sets standards for migrant farm
worker housing, and the state, which runs the licensing program,
centers on living conditions that are modest by most measures. The
agencies agree orchard owners should provide drinking water,
bathrooms and showers. But federal rules also require six-person
tents tall enough to stand in, with screened ventilation, floors,
cots and electrical connections.
</P>
<P>
   The hitch: the state allowed workers to bring their own tents
and to pile in as many people as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Worker advocates and others ``are saying unless they can have
everything they want, they'd rather have nothing for the migrant
workers,'' said Michael Gempler, head of the Washington Growers
League in Yakima. ``That's unfortunate, because the migrant workers
are the ones who are suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   The cherry-picking season is short, running from about June 1 to
Aug. 1, and labor intensive, with pickers pouring into the orchards
before dawn and ending their day when the thermometer hits 80
degrees _ the temperature at which the cherries begin to bruise and
their stems fall off. An orchard can be picked clean in a week or
sooner, so workers keep moving south to north as the weather warms
and the crops ripen.
</P>
<P>
   Others have made cities such as Wenatchee their homes, staying
year-round to prune the cherry, apple, peach and pear trees, and to
pack the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet cherries are a $125 million to $150 million a year
industry, and workers are paid by the box. The quickest among them
can earn as much as $80 a day; others barely break the minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the United Farm Workers union has sided with OSHA, saying
the state has made strides toward improving conditions, but that it
had already given growers too much time to provide their employees
with the basics and was about to give them even more. Now the union
wants the state to declare a state of emergency and call in the
National Guard to erect safe and sanitary tent camps similar to the
ones set up in Albania for Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state had always used the excuse that the licensing
program was temporary and the philosophy was it's better than
nothing, and that's what we ended up with,'' said Guadalupe Gamboa,
Washington state director of the union, which does not formally
represent the workers. ``We saw what the state wanted as the
implementation and sanction of Third World living standards.''
</P>
<P>
   But Governor Gary Locke always saw the current standards as the
short-term component in a long-term housing plan, said spokesman
David Chai. This year, he said, the state approved measures that
would create permanent housing for 10,000 workers in the next
decade. It also opened the first state-financed housing development
for migrants and added additional camp inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Dorsing Farms in Royal City spent $125,000 to
build a camp for the scores of workers needed to pick its 150 acres
of sweet cherries. It installed a pumice block shower, toilets,
sinks, and clothes-washing basins. It added barbecue pits, picnic
tables, and lights along the trails. Tents, however, were not
included, a violation of federal standards. Now the camp is open
only from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. Workers can wash up, but must sleep
somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year there were a few more camps, but then the
controversy started and really shot down the program,'' said Kevin
Dorsing, the third generation of his family to farm cherries.
``Growers got gun shy of lawsuits or fines. . . . It's a real cost
to put up these facilities, especially for new growers or small
growers, and to have to provide tents on top of that is even
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Providing somewhere to sleep and eat, of course, is not pure
altruism on the part of orchard owners. Many of Washington's 21,000
acres of sweet cherries are located a half-hour drive or more from
any town. Growers want their pickers in the orchards early. They
want them healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The Wenatchee orchards at which Lourdes Alvarado and her family
work are on what locals call ``the hill.'' The owner, Stemilt
Growers, has had a camp there since the 1950s and has provided
workers with tents since the early 1990s. This year, it is renting
12 from the state and is waiting for three. In the interim, Stemilt
is using six of its old tents and, in essence, daring to be fined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we're willing to be the test . . .,'' said Jan
Mathison, whose husband's family started Stemilt. ``It's all kind
of ridiculous. We've had to turn people away because we don't have
room for them.''
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials say they hope to work out standards
that are acceptable to all sides before the next cherry crop comes
in. Otherwise, as Alberto Hernandez put it, the owner-operated but
apparently illegal roadside camp where he is staying will not be
improved. It will be closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
