<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6926 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-28 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR BYSTANDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It will be two years ago this week that William of
Weld waved his figurative sword in lordly fashion at the State
House dome, informed his loyal acolyte, ``It's all yours,'' and
strode from the scene, leaving Paul Cellucci with a cushy surplus,
a team in place, and a head start on reelection.
</P>
<P>
   Lots can happen in two years. That's the gestation period for a
female elephant, to name just one thing. Two years is certainly
long enough to form a judgment about the quality and merit of an
administration that was reelected (by a margin of 3 percent) nine
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just my opinion _ no, it's also the opinion of a lot of other
people who expect a high-caliber performance from a Massachusetts
governor _ that Cellucci presides over the most lackluster Corner
Office clique since the four-year interregnum of Ed King injected a
speed bump in the 12 years cumulative of the Dukakis era. This is
not about style or ideology; it's about competence, character, and
delivering the goods.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci is a populist proletarian where Weld was a proud
plutocrat. Cellucci is popular with people, press, and politicians;
his poll numbers are pleasing, prosperity anesthetizes the
citizenry. Lots of people say he's a nice man. But in terms of
leadership, programs, government innovation, and crispness in
administering, he's a small-time guy in a big-time job. Governor
Smallbore.
</P>
<P>
   If a politician's choices are lead, follow, or get out of the
way, it's now pretty apparent that Cellucci is a get-out-of-the-way
guy. A longtime State House figure who knows him, likes him, voted
for him, and works for him admits: ``I don't know what he's doing,
what he stands for. There's nothing going on. No one seems to
understand it, either. The regulars up here, both parties, are
confused by the vacuum. It's a stalemate.''
</P>
<P>
   We now know what Cellucci likes: to cut ribbons, go on trade
missions, muse upon what fun it'll be for his friend George W. Bush
to be president, and go home to Hudson, rent a video, microwave the
popcorn. When it comes to the heavy lifting of government, alas,
this governor is AWOL. He's Governor Bystander.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots were on the verge of moving to Hartford, he
was not even a factor. The Pats came slinking back into town, at
gunpoint, under the itchy trigger-finger of NFL owners who didn't
want to make the Krafts richer while their take got skimmed by
losing TV revenue from Boston's bigger market. Cellucci had nothing
to do with their going or coming.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the state minimum wage? Cellucci rode along for the ride
on that too. The state budget? There's a laugh. House experts like
Paul Haley, chairman of Ways and Means, hoot at his arithmetic. The
deals will all be cut by Speaker Tom Finneran and Senate President
Tom Birmingham, each of whom can roll over the tiny band of
Republicans in their midst any time they want.
</P>
<P>
   The talent level has fallen off dramatically since Weld loped
onstage with libertarian brio, demanding tax cuts, the heads of
dead criminals, a walrus slaughter to decimate the state payroll,
and leaner-meaner gummint all round. Weld delivered on the first
and last; he got his tax cuts and leaner-meaner.
</P>
<P>
   But the walruses turned into Weld-Cellucci lapdogs. The death
penalty never happened, despite annual charades involving the
relatives of slain cops and lectern-pounding over the timeliest
local atrocity. Then the Weld appointees, some of them but by no
means all first-rate, began slip-sliding away. The thrill was to be
with Bill; with Paul set in the pall.
</P>
<P>
   Nine long years into the Weld-Cellucci thing, the cupboard is
bare. Tired, spent, agenda-poor, and patronage-rich, the
Cellucci-Swift operation is anything but swift of foot or nimble of
brainpower. I'm not saying they're all dopes and mopes and
second-raters. Andrew Natsios, a brainy former state rep with
top-shelf international aid credentials, is worth the benefit of
the doubt as budget overseer. But we're talking Pawtucket or worse
when you go down the rest of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The self-professed ``education governor'' names as chief of the
higher education system Steve Tocco? A
pharmacist-turned-bureaucrat-turned-lobbyist? To summon the deities
of academe in the land of Horace Mann and James Conant? Of Boston
Latin and Harvard and MIT? I swallowed John Silber, Bill Bulger,
and Jim Carlin, tough-guy Democrats all, when Weld gambled on their
potential for juicing education. Each made solid contributions. But
Steve Tocco?
</P>
<P>
   Governor Law-and-order in the campaign mode was four-square
against crime. But Governor Tax-cut has presided over the shrinkage
of the State Police from 2,416 four years ago to 2,171 now, a
downsizing of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   We've all chortled over the fiasco of Governor Back-hoe making a
big deal of demolishing turnpike toll booths for the benefit of his
reelection, then raising tolls when the heat was off. And his
plundering of the political system for campaign contributions
reached into the National Guard, where he had to fire his Guard
commander for hocus-pocus involving the euchring of campaign money
for Cellucci's reelection. Before that, out went the
underperforming Registrar of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Since Weld quit, of the first 34 judges Cellucci nominated, not
one of them came from an Ivy League law school. Hmmm. Seven flunked
the bar exam on their first try. Double-hmmm. And eight held
political jobs. Triple-hmmm. Nineteen of the first 34 are
Democrats, suggesting Cellucci is still paying off the renegades
who left their party to endorse him last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Dig? Don't ask; it'll top out at $15 billion and beggar
the state road-and-bridge budget for a decade more. The new runway
for Logan? Cellucci's Big Business buddies want it, but the Guv
can't deliver. The business crowd now sees Cellucci as a marginal
player when big things get decided. Governor Nice Guy to his pals
on Beacon Hill is Governor No-show when it comes to delivering the
goods. Three more years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
