<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-UNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE IN PENSION PLAN STIRS UNION TALK AT IBM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of his 18-year career at IBM, test engineer John Mendes
of Burlington, Vt., never thought about joining a union. After all,
Big Blue paid well, its benefits were generous, and it was the
world's top computer company.
</P>
<P>
   But six years after IBM introduced a cost-cutting program to
stem losses, Mendes has joined a group of mostly midcareer
manufacturing and professional workers who are determined to bring
in a union.
</P>
<P>
   The root of their rebellion is a change in the IBM pension plan.
The old plan, in place for decades, promised employees a
predictable monthly check upon retirement based on years of service
_ a traditional ``defined benefits'' pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, IBM on July 1 began setting up retirement
accounts for each of its 140,000 employees in the United States,
and posting to those accounts a fixed amount of money each month,
based on each employee's salary or wage.
</P>
<P>
   These deposits will accumulate interest over time. The program
is called a ``cash balance'' plan, and it follows a model now used
by 12 percent of US corporations _ double the number of companies
five years ago _ as they seek ways to deal with a tight labor
market and an increasingly mobile work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are really angry about the changes. They feel
betrayed,'' said Mendes, 41, who holds an engineering degree from
the University of North Carolina at Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Notified in May about the change, employees at the company's
plants in Essex Junction, Vt., and at Poughkeepsie, East Fishkill
and Endicott, N.Y., contacted the 630,000-member Communications
Workers of America, which responded by holding organizing sessions
with IBM workers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, union leaders and labor specialists are
watching this movement closely. Any union success at IBM would be a
significant inroad into the high technology industry, where
employees have long shunned collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Prounion employees say the IBM pension changes penalize
midcareer employees _ about 40 percent of IBM's US work force _
while rewarding about the same number of newer workers, most of
them hired since 1993, when IBM chief executive Louis V. Gerstner
instituted a sweeping series of cost-cutting moves.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, IBM says the old pension plan is not being closed
out and will continue to pay previously scheduled benefits to
people already retired and to those employees within five years of
retirement _ about 20 percent of the giant's US work force.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the new plan will help it attract and keep the
best talent in the high-tech marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that significantly fewer people are staying with one
company their full careers means that, more and more, people are
looking for opportunities to contribute and be rewarded sooner in
their careers,'' IBM said in a letter to workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not reducing the total amount of money we spend in
benefits,'' IBM spokeswoman Jana Weatherbee said. ``We are shifting
or changing how we spend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put a lot of money into our pension plan, but when you
look at the marketplace, the traditional defined benefit plan is
not what our competitors are offering.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM says it spends $3.5 billion annually on benefits in the
United States. The change to a cash-balance pension plan is
expected to save $200 million, which will be shifted to
performance-based compensation programs such as stock options and
variable salary increases, IBM said.
</P>
<P>
   IBM also has, in addition to the other plans, a 401(k)
retirement program to which employees can make contributions, some
of which the company matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional pension plans take a lot of money and basically
give it to the career employee who eventually retires, but it gives
little to those who come and go early in their careers,'' according
to Michael Johnston of Hewitt Associates, a benefits consultancy
based in Lincolnshire, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Defined-benefit plans ``throw the money to those in the back-end
of their career,'' Johnston said. Cash balance plans are
``egalitarian,'' he argues. These plans ``say, `You're here for
five years, when you go we will still reward you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the plans have been criticized for eliminating the
boosts in compensation older employees in traditional plans receive
near the end of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   That's why IBM computer programmer Ginny Roarabaugh, 48, of
Austin, Texas, was upset about the change. In May, she launched a
Web site for workers around the country who want to know more about
the current union drive.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said workers who are 40 or older, or whose age
plus years of service equal 50, may qualify for extra pay
``credits'' and a higher payment into their monthly cash balance
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But Roarabaugh contends that even with those changes, the switch
will cost her money. She had planned to retire at 55.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this new plan, I won't have the same income when I
retire,'' she said in a telephone interview. ``The way things used
to work, the more time you had in the company the more points you
got, and you got a big bang in your retirement during the last five
years. Under the old plan, I would have had $2,200 per month until
I die _ way more than a cash plan that will give me a lump sum
payment of cash in the $90,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a cash balance plan, being younger is better,'' said Lee
Conrad, a 49-year-old machine operator at IBM's Endicott, N.Y.,
plant who has twice tried, unsuccessfully, to organize a union at
the company. ``If you're young you can build (the plan) up over
time. Older people, middle-aged people don't have that kind of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Midcareer workers are not the only ones who don't like the
change. US Representative Bernard Sanders, an Independent from
Vermont, says he plans to hold a ``town meeting'' in Burlington
soon to air IBM workers' concerns. On July 13, Sanders and 10
Congress members sent a letter to the Internal Revenue Service
asking that it cease authorizing company proposals to switch to
cash balance accounts pending an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRS should not sign off on the IBM plan until a thorough
investigation has been done to determine if there was age
discrimination,'' said Sanders. ``There are people who had the
option of remaining in the old plan, but there are many others who
are not within five years of retirement who will see a 30 percent
reduction in their retirement. These are people who were loyal to
the firm.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Weatherbee defended the change. ``We would not have put a
plan into place that violates the law,'' she said. ``Midcareer
people have a transition benefit and an enhanced annuity to bridge
them into the new plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what people are hearing is more rhetoric than anything
else,'' said Phil Rueppel, an analyst at Deutche Bank Alex. Brown
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talk of unionization in high tech has been around for
awhile and it has been largely unsuccessful. Right now, companies
are having to offer very attractive packages to keep employees. If
they don't, it is very easy to get jobs at another firm. Given
that, it is difficult for a union to find a lever to gain
acceptance. I would be very surprised if this effort led to a major
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, any attempt to unionize Big Blue will be an uphill
battle. Although its plants in Europe are unionized, IBM's North
American work force historically has given unions the cold
shoulder. Conrad, who led organizing efforts in the 1970s and
1980s, said: ``Paternalism was in high gear at the company then,
and IBM was the only game in town. We were looked down on as
dissatisfied workers.''
</P>
<P>
   But this organizing drive could be different. ``Unions have
tried to organize IBM in the past, but if you stood up for a union
at IBM 10 years ago, you were considered a spoiler,'' said Cornell
University labor professor Kate Bronfenbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the push to unionize is coming from inside. People feel
they had an implied contract, but it has been broken. I really
believe this will have a snowball affect,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
