<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DVIDENDS OF A HOSTILE TAKEOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the two seasons in which two professional women's
basketball leagues co-existed, it didn't take long for each to
assume a clearly defined identity.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA: superior financial backing, tremendous media exposure, and
savvy public relations.
</P>
<P>
   ABL: smaller markets, lack of national exposure, but deeper and
better talent.
</P>
<P>
   A common criticism _ that the level of play in each league was
diluted thanks to the other's existence _ was rendered moot when
the ABL declared bankruptcy and folded last December, enabling the
WNBA to absorb many of the former league's players.
</P>
<P>
   As the WNBA moves into the final one-third of its regular
season, several ABL players have assumed dominant roles in the
WNBA, including the following All-Stars:
</P>
<P>
   --Yolanda Griffith has made a profound impact in Sacramento. The
6-foot-3-inch Griffith, whose 13 double-doubles are best in the
league, ranks second to Houston's Cynthia Cooper in scoring with
20.2 points per game and leads in rebounding (12.3). A Most
Valuable Player award may not be far away.
</P>
<P>
   --Utah's Natalie Williams, a former ABL MVP and scoring
champion, is third in scoring (19.3) and second in rebounding (9).
At 6-2, the daughter of former NBA guard Nate Williams is, like
Griffith, a prototype power forward.
</P>
<P>
   --Tonya Edwards and Shannon ``Pee Wee'' Johnson, last season's
backcourt for the Columbus Quest, haven't let up in their new
homes. Edwards is averaging 16.4 points a game for Minnesota and is
fifth in the WNBA in 3-pointers made, while the 5-7 Johnson's 13.8
points, 5.2 assists, and league-leading 36.7 minutes per game have
given a boost to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   --Orlando's Taj McWilliams is the rare center who can mix it up
inside but who can also drift outside and hit 3-pointers
consistently; she's 6-2 but has made 50 percent of her long-range
shots to rank second in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL is represented on each WNBA team, but nowhere has the
old league manifested itself more grandly than in Minnesota and
Orlando. The two expansion teams were allowed to keep five former
ABL players, while the eight existing teams were limited to three.
</P>
<P>
   The Lynx, in the playoff hunt, are a WNBA version of Columbus;
their five ABL veterans are all former Quest players. Not
coincidentally, Minnesota's coach is Brian Agler, who led the Quest
to the ABL's only two championships.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, McWilliams, and rookie Nykesha Sales of Connecticut
have helped keep the Miracle in playoff contention. The ``Cool
Keesh'' signs sprouting in the O-rena lend testimony to the impact
and popularity of Sales; her 14.5 points per game lead the team.
</P>
<P>
   A lingering lack of name recognition may explain why no former
ABL players were elected by fans to start in the All-Star Game,
though six were chosen as reserves (Washington's Nikki McCray, who
jumped to the WNBA a season ago, was the other former ABL
All-Star).
</P>
<P>
   Considering that New York's Rebecca Lobo, out for the year after
tearing an anterior cruciate ligament in the season's first game,
was selected to start lends credence to the theory that All-Star
voting in any sport is little more than a game of popularity and
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Magnificent Monarchs
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most dramatic impact of the ABL on existing WNBA
teams has come in Sacramento, where the Monarchs have become the
league's most-improved team. ABL refugee Kedra Holland-Corn (13
pgg) has joined Griffith in resucitating Sacramento, which is tied
for the league's third-best record at 13-7, already has far
surpassed last season's win total of eight and gained additional
credibility by handing defending champ Houston one of its four
defeats. The Monarchs, the league's second-highest scoring team a
year after being the worst, also have benefited from the return of
Ruthie Bolton-Holifield, out nearly all of last season with a torn
ACL, and the maturation of second-year point guard Ticha
Penachiero, the league's assist leader at 7.3 per game. Former
Maine star Cindy Blodgett has seen little action, averaging 3.6
minutes and 1.1 points in eight games . . . Is it the WNBA or the
WBA? A brawl last Friday between Detroit and Cleveland led to five
suspensions and/or fines, including one to Detroit's Dominique
Canty for throwing a ``connecting punch.'' A few days earlier, it
was quite a sight when Phoenix's Debbie Black, a 5-2 guard, got
into a scuffle with 6-3 Venus Lacy of New York . . . Lin Dunn, a
former ABL Coach of the Year with Portland, has been named
coach/general manager of the expansion Seattle franchise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
