A6933 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-DIVERSITY-BOS &LR;      07-28 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-DIVERSITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY REPORTS MIXED RESULTS ON SPORTS DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Critics who dismiss sports as having no relation to real life
can take both vindication and pause from the latest project of
Northeastern Univerity's Center for the Study of Sport in Society.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of diversity, there is indeed no comparison _ the world
of fun and games far outpaces society in general. But there is
still much room for improvement in professional and college
athletics.
</P>
<P>
   That is the conclusion of the NU center's 10th annual Racial and
Gender Report Card, which covers 1998 and rates what it considers
the three major professional sports organizations _ the National
Football League, National Basketball Association, and Major League
Baseball _ as well as NCAA Division 1 schools. In addition, the
National Hockey League, Major League Soccer, and the Women's NBA
(as well as the defunct American Basketball League) were examined,
though no grades were issued because this was the first extensive
study of those enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Using as its barometer the federal affirmative action policy
that the makeup of the workplace should reflect that of the general
population _ which is approximately 12 percent black _ the NU study
graded the leagues accordingly: A (at least 24 percent minority), B
(12 percent), C (9 percent), D (6 percent), and F (5 percent). In
addition, grades regarding the inclusion of women were issued for
the first time and the entire report was released on the Internet
(www.nuway.neu.edu/sport).
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the NBA received an A-minus, the NFL a B-plus, and
Major League Baseball a B for racial diversity. Gender was another
matter: Only the NBA was rated highly (B), while the NFL received a
D-plus and MLB did not supply sufficient data.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of player opportunities, the Big Three went to the head
of the class _ the NBA and NFL got A-pluses, MLB an A.
</P>
<P>
   But positions of authority remain problematic as pro sports,
with the exception of the NBA, have done little to alter the
perception that there is an artificial ceiling for minorities and
women. The NBA got an A-plus/B-minus for its league office minority
staffing (22 percent), a B-plus for head coaches (17 percent), an A
for principals in charge (general managers or their equivalent; 24
percent), and a B for senior administration (directors,
coordinators, managers; 14 percent). Regarding gender, its league
office received a B-plus (45 percent), senior administration a B
(41 percent).
</P>
<P>
   In the league office, the NFL earned a B-plus for minorities (21
percent) but a D for gender (26 percent). For minority head
coaches, it got a C-plus (10 percent), and its front-office grade
was B (13 percent). While its senior administration graded out to a
B (12 percent), the NFL was lacking in gender diversity at that
level, posting a D-minus (27 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased that the progress we have made is being
recognized,'' said NFL spokesman Greg Aiello. ``We also understand
we have more progress to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball received a B-plus for its central office in terms of
minorities (21 percent) but a C-minus for gender (34 percent). Its
managerial rating was a solid B (13 percent), but it flunked the
front-office category (0 percent) and did not provide the necessary
information for ranking its senior administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an area in which Major League Baseball works very hard,''
said spokesman Rich Levin. ``It's an area in which we're going to
continue to work very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the study found that the increase in off-field
opportunities for women far surpassed those for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   At the college level, NCAA headquarters _ which are in the
process of relocating from Overland Park, Kan., to Indianapolis _
scored highly in both race (B-plus; 20.5 percent) and gender
(A-minus; 49 percent). But individually, its members did not make
the grade. Head coaching rated only a D-plus (7.8 percent) for both
men's and women's teams, though the opportunities for women coaches
were considerably higher (B; 43.7 percent). And athletic directors'
jobs were almost exclusively a white male domain as the Division 1
schools got Fs in race (4.6 percent) and gender (8.2 percent).
Opportunities for student athletes _ A in race (32 percent),
B-minus in gender (39 percent) _ helped raise the overall college
marks to C in race and gender.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Laronica Conway said no one from the NCAA hierarchy
had seen the report or was currently in position to comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colleges have been kind of operating on the moral
imperative _ they think it's the right way to go, to hire more
minorities and women,'' said Richard Lapchick, the NU center's
director and the study's author. ``The pros years ago realized that
it's also a business imperative, that it's right for business to
reflect globalization, not just the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the men's pro leagues, the NHL led the way in women among
non-senior professional administrators at 45 percent. MLS was first
for minorities in both senior (20 percent) and non-senior (22
percent) administrators.
</P>
<P>
   In all the men's pro leagues, only two teams (MLB's Seattle
Mariners and the NHL's Tampa Bay Lightning) are owned by minorities
and only three (the NFL's St. Louis Rams and San Francisco 49ers,
MLB's Cincinnati Reds) by women.
</P>
<P>
   One myth shattered is that the number of black athletes at the
pro and college level continues to rise; in fact, the opposite is
true _ MLB (15 percent) has its lowest black participation in a
decade, while the NBA (77 percent) and NFL (65 percent) ratios are
the lowest since 1992-93. Lapchick considers the major reason for
this decrease the globalization of sports, citing as an example the
fact that the number of Latinos playing major league baseball _ 25
percent _ is at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   More disturbing, the study reveals that so-called position
stacking _ de facto segregation of what it calls ``thinking and
control'' positions _ continues. In the NFL, 9 percent of
quarterbacks were black; in baseball, the ratio was worse _ 5
percent of pitchers, 4 percent of catchers. And in the three major
pro sports graded in the report, there were only 11 minority
managers or head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, says the report, is that ``too few (management
positions) are filled by minorities or women.''
</P>
<P>
   But it also points out that ``even those sports where grades are
low generally have better records on race and gender than society
as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   In sum, the study indicates that the situation for minorities
and women in sports is better _ but not nearly as good as it should
be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Shira Springer of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
