<SLUG> BC-Y2K-MOVIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME MOVIE MAKERS DON'T WANT TO RISK FRIGHT OVER DATE PROBLEM  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warner Bros. has canceled plans for a movie called ``Y2K,'' a
decision its producer says reflects a lack of faith in audiences to
tell the difference between fictional and real-world computer
disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they don't even want to talk about Y2K,'' said Bing
Howenstein, president of George Street Pictures, the production
company behind the film, which was to have featured Chris
O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. won't discuss the reasons behind its decision, but
it is not the first time material depicting Y2K problems has
sparked controversy. Last month, Polaroid Corp. agreed to pull a
television ad after bankers complained its portrayal of Y2K-related
glitches in an automatic teller machine might lead to unwarranted
fears about the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the public would be better off if it were easier to
imagine _ and poke fun at _ bad-news scenarios. By quashing films
and ads, ``we're keeping people in the dark, and it's something
that will contribute to social fragility if the worst comes,'' says
Richard Landes, a Boston University historian who studies public
reactions to the millennial change.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, O'Donnell was to star as a computer programmer who
discovered a Y2K-related computer bug that could leave New York
City security systems vulnerable to terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   At least one critic on a United Nations panel reviewing Y2K
preparedness had criticized the movie as too provocative, a charge
that Howenstein counters by noting he worked on the script with
Toronto-based software consultant Peter de Jager, a widely quoted
specialist on preparing for the date change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The script I saw was totally nonvolatile, and I had no
objection,'' de Jager said. ``And I'm very sensitive to the whole
issue of stirring things up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
