</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT IS TIME WE ALL LET LEWIS REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, a woman woke up and decided that she didn't
feel like talking on the phone. A couple of her best friends called
more than once before their messages were returned. The
conversations were brief. The friends understood.
</P>
<P>
   You've been there, right? Those are the days when you are
thanking the technological gods for annoyance prevention, which is
also known as Caller ID. Sometimes it feels good to shut out the
world, free from any outside nonsense. But here's the biggest thing
that separates most of us from that 34-year-old woman, Donna
Harris-Lewis: Whether she answers the phone or not, the chattering
continues. She has had to hear it _ either whispered or screamed _
for six straight years. Her emotions are raw and unsettled. Her
peace comes in fragments.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think she should have to live this way anymore, even
though I understand why she does.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago this Tuesday (July 27), Reggie Lewis left his
house in the afternoon to go play basketball. His wife remembers
all the details from that day in 1993. She was pregnant. It was 75
degrees, windy and rainy in Boston. The Red Sox had just had their
10-game winning streak snapped by the Brewers. Chris Corchiani was
trying to make it with the Celtics. And Lewis, the Celtics'
captain, never returned home. July 27 was the day he died on a
basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)There is no evidence that he has any form of
cardiomyopathy or life-threatening ventricular arrhythmias . . . I
have rendered a medical judgment and I have advised him of what
that judgment is . . .(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   She still remembers those quotes from her husband's
cardiologist, Gilbert Mudge. Those quotes were not accurate. Lewis
did have a life-threatening heart condition, just as New England
Baptist Hospital doctor Mark Josephson said he did. A Suffolk
Superior Court jury saw those facts clearly _ and still failed to
say, overwhelmingly, that Mudge was at fault for Lewis's death.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, those are the facts we have about the death of
Lewis. Unless you believe in some intricate conspiracy, the facts
are also that Reggie Lewis did not use cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   It seems strange to say that now in New England, even though the
opposite should be true. There isn't anyone in the region who can
prove that Lewis was so attached to coke that it scarred his heart
and eventually snuffed out his life. There are whispers. There are
anonymous quotes. There are shady characters who say they did the
drug with him, but can't remember where. There are those who say
they did, retract their claims and then demand money for additional
stories. There is no proof.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, I don't blame Harris-Lewis for chasing down
every accusation and correcting every false story. Earlier this
month, she faxed and e-mailed a letter to Sports Illustrated
because the magazine contained a news brief about Lewis that
``reeked of malice and a reckless disregard for the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might see Harris-Lewis's behavior as obsessive. Some
Celtics fans talk about her in the same disdainful context that
John Lennon fans talk about Yoko Ono. Her deeply personal choices _
such as her decision not to get her late husband a headstone _ are
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, I am still amazed by some of our audacity. As
sports fans, we are used to criticizing those who can't make
15-footers or throw strikes. But who the hell are we to criticize
someone for the way they grieve? In a recent tragedy, the Kennedy
and Bessette families tossed the remains of their loved ones in the
Atlantic. It was their choice. Harris-Lewis does not have a
headstone for her husband. Her choice.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Harris-Lewis and her attorneys did not make the best
decision by inviting the shockingly arrogant Arn Tellem to be an
expert witness for them in court. But that is no reason to dismiss
the fact that a cardiologist said Lewis had a normally functioning
heart when, in fact, he did not.
</P>
<P>
   It can be painful when cold facts intersect with incomplete
grieving. If you have ever lost your best friend suddenly, you can
begin to understand how Harris-Lewis feels. If you have ever been a
wife who waited for your husband to come home and he never did, you
can begin to understand how she feels. If you have ever had someone
try to remix your husband's memory . . . well, then you know what
it's like six years after a funeral, avoiding the phone and
remembering exactly where you were and what you were thinking when
it happened.
</P>
<P>
   She should not have to live this way anymore. There is no proof
that her husband did cocaine. There is proof that he was in Roxbury
on Thanksgiving mornings, handing out turkeys. There is proof that,
in 1992, the Cleveland Cavaliers beat the Celtics in an Eastern
Conference semifinal series, even though they had no way of
stopping Lewis. There is proof _ through the paintbrushes and spray
cans of graffiti artists who have put up murals _ of his impact and
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now we can let Lewis finally have his peace. And his widow
have hers, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
