<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6937 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GILLETTE-DURACELL-ART     07-28 1548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-DURACELL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDE AND CONQUER, DURACELL-STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- To chart progress in the battery wars, a score card of
TV ads may be helpful. Let's see. Rayovac has Michael Jordan.
Energizer has a memorable bunny. And Duracell? The battery maker
now owned by Gillette Co. has neither pitchman nor pitch-beast.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. What Duracell does have is some of its biggest leads
ever over Energizer, mostly as a result of applying the same
strategies to batteries that Gillette uses so well to sell razors.
</P>
<P>
   A year after Duracell debuted the Ultra, the battery equivalent
of Gillette's much ballyhooed Mach3 razor, number one Duracell is
opening a wide gap over number two Energizer, which is also being
hurt by number three Rayovac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, they're winning,'' says Edward Jones analyst Tony
Vento of Duracell and its big lead in US market share.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if current trends hold up, Gillette's battery sales may
some day eclipse razor sales. Razors accounted for about 30 percent
of overall 1998 sales of just over $10 billion, batteries for about
25 percent, or $2.58 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the popularity of digital cameras, Palm Pilots,
and cell phones, the $12 billion worldwide market for general
purpose batteries is growing far faster than the $7 billion
wet-shaving market.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette already dominates the shaving market, which includes
gels and shaving cream, with about a 70 percent share. Duracell
owns about less than half, so batteries offer Gillette a big growth
opportunity. (With much higher profit margins than batteries,
though, razors should continue to be the biggest component of
Gillette's earnings.)
</P>
<P>
   The battery war is hardly over. At the moment, Duracell seems to
be sacrificing profits for market share. Heavy spending on ads and
promotions were the reason for ``notably lower'' second-quarter
operating profits for Duracell, according to Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   As Gillette continues to be hurt by ailing economies in key
foreign markets, the challenge will be to convert battery market
share gains into bottom-line results.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duracell's big US lead is a big change from a decade ago,
when Duracell and Energizer often ran neck and neck.
</P>
<P>
   For the month of June, Duracell claims to have had a 50.2
percent share of the US dollar market, up from a 48.2 percent share
the previous June. Energizer had a 31.2 percent share last month,
down from a 34.7 percent share the previous June, says Duracell,
citing A.C. Nielsen data; Rayovac had a 10.3 share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing damage to their business,'' Duracell senior vice
president Bruce Cleverly says of Energizer.
</P>
<P>
   Energizer declined to comment. In an earnings report released
last week, it said ``the impact of significant volume
improvements'' in North American sales of alkaline batteries was
``offset by lower average selling prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently losing customers to both Duracell and Rayovac,
Energizer has been discounting aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   How could Energizer lose so much market share so quickly? Part
of the answer is Rayovac, and part of it is Duracell.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1998, about 18 months after its acquisition by
Boston-based Gillette for $7.82 billion in stock and debt, Duracell
unveiled the Ultra premium battery, in essence taking a page from
Gillette's razor playbook and adapting it to alkaline batteries.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, a razor blade _ like the battery _ would seem
to be the humblest of commodities. But time and again, Gillette has
persuaded consumers to pay more for a razor marketed as a
state-of-the-art product that gives added value.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, it was Trac II. Then came Atra and Sensor. Each time,
consumers were bombarded by ads urging them to upgrade to a more
expensive razor. Each time, the strategy worked.
</P>
<P>
   In retail lingo, Gillette ``segmented the market'' by giving
consumers a range of razor choices at different prices. Male
shavers can buy a Sensor, a SensorExcel _ or the new Mach3.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Gillette has applied variations of this formula
to other categories, including toothbrushes and pens.
</P>
<P>
   But not every attempt to transform a commodity into a premium
brand through a big marketing campaign has met with success.
</P>
<P>
   Take Gillette's stationery lines. Its Parker and Paper Mate pens
have been hit by declining sales, and some investors now think
Gillette should sell off its stationery business _ and maybe get
rid of all or part of its underperforming Braun appliance division
as well; that way, Gillette could focus on its strongest product
categories of razors, batteries, and oral care products, they
argue.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the strategy of segmenting the market and urging
consumers to trade up seems to be working for Duracell.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ultra came out last year, skeptics scoffed. The last
thing the world needed, they said, was an upscale battery, one
costing 20 to 30 percent more than Duracell's standard batteries.
All alkaline batteries are alike, the critics said, and consumers
should buy whichever brand was on sale.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying the product as hero, Duracell ad campaigns suggest
otherwise. What the Mach3 is to the SensorExcel, it said, the Ultra
is to the standard Duracell battery.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, a no-name battery is fine for a Cub Scout's $3 flashlight,
but for such ``high-drain'' devices as cell phones and digital
cameras, the Ultra is the gold standard of battery technology,
something well worth paying extra for, ads hint.
</P>
<P>
   Alkaline battery sales figures for the last seven months suggest
that consumers are responding to that message.
</P>
<P>
   With a 7.3 percent dollar share of the US market for the month
of June, Ultra is the big reason why Duracell has been widening its
dollar market share lead over Energizer.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Energizer's parent, Ralston Purina Co., announced
plans to spin off its Energizer and Eveready battery lines to focus
on its more profitable pet food business. While Ralston Purina has
sold several business units recently, the Energizer spinoff may be
partly due to Duracell's widening lead.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoff is ``an admission right there that Gillette has been
a very formidable competitor,'' says Fred Russell, whose Oklahoma
investment firm has owned Gillette stock since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   A spinoff would likely have little effect on Duracell. Whether
alone or as part of larger company, Energizer will continue to be a
player to be reckoned with, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Energizer has been hurt as much by Rayovac as by Duracell.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Boston investment firm Thomas H. Lee Co. bought out
family-run Rayovac Corp. and took the company public in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Making big strides ever since, Rayovac uses Michael Jordan ads
to promote Rayovac as a ``value brand,'' with prices 15 to 20
percent lower than those of Duracell and Energizer.
</P>
<P>
   According to company spokesman John Daggett, a big part of
Rayovac's recent surge has come from doubling the number of US
retail outlets where its batteries are available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a distribution game,'' Daggett says of the battery
business. ``Eighty percent of batteries are bought on impulse. It's
not a category with a lot of brand loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   With Duracell on the high end and Rayovac on the low end,
Energizer has gotten squeezed in the middle, say analysts, who
expect Energizer to come out with its own premium battery line to
compete with Ultra.
</P>
<P>
   One man not overly impressed by Duracell's widening market share
lead is John McMillin, a Prudential Securities analyst who follows
Ralston Purina.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Duracell's recent gains have come from consumers
replacing their regular Duracell batteries with costlier Ultra
batteries, he says; it's Rayovac that's stealing customers from
Energizer, a point Duracell disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Market share is all very fine, but what about profits?
</P>
<P>
   According to Duracell, its plan of investing heavily in
marketing and promotions now will reap big future profits.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to be bullish on batteries these days _ even without
Y2K concerns that may have some folks scrambling to stockpile
Duracells and Rayovacs for their survival kits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, a typical US household owned just two battery-powered
devices, a flashlight and a transistor radio, and old-fashioned
zinc batteries were more than adequate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the wide use of everything from GameBoys to smoke
detectors and Walkmans, a US household owns about 20 portable
devices and spends just over $20 a year on batteries to power them.
With more portable and digital products coming onto the market all
the time, that amount is only likely to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Most batteries bought in the United States are alkaline, but
many other countries still rely on zinc batteries, which aren't as
well suited to newer high-tech devices. As these countries upgrade
to alkaline, it should benefit Duracell, a company with an alkaline
focus and a global distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of unit sales, the battery market is growing by 8
percent a year, notes analyst McMillin, adding, ``There are not
many (product) categories doing that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
