<HEADLINE>
OL' BROWN EYES IN GQ; VERVE POST-MORTEM IN Q 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Puff Daddy the black Sinatra?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, why not _ especially if you can overlook the fact that
he's a talentless hack who's never had an original idea in his
life, and has made his fortune plundering everyone from David Bowie
to Grandmaster Flash to Led Zeppelin. But in the August issue of
GQ, Puffy tells writer David Kamp he views himself as some kind of
ghetto-fabulous reincarnation of Ol' Blue Eyes _ ``Ol' Brown
Eyes,'' if you will. See, the mogul born Sean Combs, has this room
_ ``the Lounge,'' he calls it _ in his midtown Manhattan recording
studio, where he and his artists can chill during sessions. With
its low-slung furniture and wet bars, he was going for that Rat
Pack vibe. ``The whole concept of it was Black Sinatra,'' Puff
explains. ``Like if Frank Sinatra was black, and he was my age, and
he was me, what kind of hangout would he have for Dean and Sammy
and the guys to come see him at the studio.'' But, says Puffy,
don't let the Bentley, the home in the Hamptons, and the
ever-present bottles of Cristal fool you. He's just a former altar
boy trying to get a little love and respect. He's Mr. Contrition
when he discusses his April arrest for second-degree assault on
Interscope Records executive Steve Stoute, after Stoute resisted
the removal of a crucified Puffy from Nas's ``Hate Me Now'' video.
``I was thinking whatever I had to do to get that video off the
air, I was ready to do,'' Puffy says. ``And I was wrong _ as a
Christian, you have to turn the other cheek.'' Stoute has since
dropped charges, but alas, the Manhattan district attorney's office
is still pursuing the case. But as Puffy himself once said, ``Can't
nobody take my pride, can't nobody hold me down'' _ oh, wait a
minute, he sampled that rejiggered line from Matthew Wilder's
``Break My Stride.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many a band has gone belly-up in the quagmire of egos, drugs,
and just plain stupidity that has fueled popular music for nearly a
half-century. One of the more recent examples is the Verve, which
finally came undone just as it seemed they were about to crash the
States. Shortly after the British band's 1997 hit ``Bitter Sweet
Symphony,'' broke big, the Verve broke up. In Q's post-mortem, Phil
Sutcliffe gets to the core of the split from ``prologue to
hari-kari.'' From their early 1990s birth, the five-member band,
led by mercurial Richard Ashcroft, was always a fragile but
fascinating unit. Their music fell somewhere between the pure
muscle-pop of Oasis, and the thinking-cap rock of Radiohead.
Success at home came quickly, and so did the inherent problems of
fame _ various mood- and mind-altering substances, identity crises,
shattered love lives, and a bitter rift between Ashcroft and
guitarist Nick McCabe, exacerbated by both men's delicate mental
states. Writes Sutcliffe of Ashcroft and McCabe, ``They were great
together and they never got on. A lot of magic, a load of loss.''
By article's end, it's less a wonder that the band imploded than
that they were ever a band at all.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so electronica never really became the Next Big Thing the
know-nothings assured us it would be. Still, it has produced
several standout artists including Fatboy Slim, Underworld,
Propellerheads, and the Chemical Brothers, who have a sit-down with
Q's Andrew Collins. Far from being weirdo tech-heads more
comfortable with machines than humans, the ``brothers'' _ Tom
Rowlands and Ed Simons _ come off as regular guys who just happen
to love turntables more than guitars (well, at least live ones).
Not surprisingly, they take umbrage at those who trivialize what
electronica artists do _ even when the words come from a turntable
compatriot like Norman ``Fatboy Slim'' Cook. ``I don't like the
idea that he has to present it as dumb music for a Saturday
night,'' says Simons, who adds that he and Rowlands want to ``dumb
up'' dance music. ``It's not dumb music. It's galling when he says
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Poz, David Groff explores the art of Barton Benes, who has
created such controversial works as a palette of HIV medications,
an hourglass with the ashes of friends, and a watergun filled with
his own HIV-positive blood. Benes has always been a collector of
the strange and macabre. Among his peculiar treasures: a mummified
Egyptian cat, Larry Hagman's gallstone, a skull fragment from a
victim of the Black Plague. In Sweden, ``Lethal Weapons,'' his
exhibit of poisonous darts, perfume atomizers, Molotov cocktails,
and water pistols filled with his blood and placed under safety
glass, was quarantined until Benes allowed it to be heated at 160
degrees in a hospital oven. In Britain, tabloid headlines branded
it an ``AIDS Horror Show.'' But Benes _ whose next exhibit,
``Transubstantiation,'' includes a piece of rubble from O. J.
Simpson's Rockingham Estate carved into the shape of a knife, and a
picture of a bird painted with oil from the Exxon Valdez _ is
undeterred. He wants to make political art that provokes,
challenges, and disturbs its viewers. ``It's not something you can
look at like a decorative thing on the wall,'' Benes says. ``You
have to read it. And once you do, it's like trying to put down a
good book. You can't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
