A6939 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-LOVE-BOS &LR;      07-28 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAUNCHY, ERUDITE, HILARIOUS `LOVE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
LOVE IN A DEAD LANGUAGE 
By Lee Siegel 
University of Chicago Press, 375 pp., illustrated, $25.00 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to its publicist, ``Love in a Dead Language'' is a
novel that can be read in many positions, but you'd better be able
to laugh in all of them.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the novel is love, and the principal narrative is a
love story. Leopold Roth is an American professor of Asian studies
who is undertaking a new translation of the ``Kamasutra,'' the
celebrated ancient Sanskrit philosophical text about sex and love.
As he works, Roth becomes obsessed by one of his students, Lalita
Gupta, an all-American girl of Indian descent who thinks she's in
love with the college basketball star. Although he's been
respectably, even happily, married for years, Roth is prepared to
risk everything for love. He will stoop to the most ingenious and
humiliating stratagems to have Lalita; he even arranges a bogus
study-in-India program, and she will be his only student. For his
folly, Roth will pay a very high price; in disgrace with fortune
and in men's eyes, he dies under mysterious circumstances after
being stuck in the face by a copy of Monier Monier-Williams's
mighty Sanskrit-English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   The story unfurls and unravels as Roth's translation and
autobiographical commentary on the ``Kamasutra,'' with additional
commentary by the Persian translator of the ``Kamasutra,''
Pralayananga Lilaraja, and by Roth's pedantic graduate student,
Anang Saighal.
</P>
<P>
   These texts and commentaries are supplemented by others,
including pages from a script of a movie that had starred Roth's
parents; pages from a proposed Classics Illustrated comic devoted
to the ``Kamasutra''; several CD-ROM screens; the privately printed
memoirs of a randy Victorian colonialist; a synopsis of a feminist
forgery of a nonexistent ``Kamasutra'' written from a woman's point
of view (a ``discovery'' of a self-invented scholar who calls
herself Tajma Hall); a ``Kamasutra'' board game (more fun than
Parcheesi); the autobiography of the priapic movie star Jock
Newhouse (English for Jacques Casanova); an interview in a porn
magazine called Cocktail; some correspondence between Leo Delibes,
the composer of the opera ``Lakme,'' and the widow of the first
English translator of the ``Kamasutra,'' Sir Richard Burton; and
earnestly inept passages from a term paper by Lalita Gupta herself
_ ``People acting out the divine ground of the universe in weird
positions are common in Indian art.'' Lakme's ``Bell Song''
tintinnabulates out to very far horizons.
</P>
<P>
   The book affectionately satirizes two world cultures and the
ways they view and illuminate each other; it is an academic novel
about nonacademic subjects; it spans high culture and low comedy.
To accommodate all of this, the book must be a triumph of
typographical virtuosity. Some of it has the look of a scholarly
text, with footnotes, a bibliography (``Everything about erotica is
invariably disguised behind false authors, publishers, dates, and
places of publication. Nothing is what it seems, and it is this
more than anything else that is the fascination of the subject for
its bibliographers''), and even an index. The book is printed in
different fonts and colors; some of it is upside down, and some of
it is inverted and can be read only with the assistance of a
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Chicago Press deserves congratulations for
producing such a sensuous and unusual volume out of Lee Siegel's
hypertexts. The press is also to be congratulated for publishing
``Love in a Dead Language'' at all, because the book is such an
intellectual extravaganza, but with belly laughs _ a set of
virtuoso linguistic and psychological variations on a theme of the
widest popular appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel is a professor of Indian religions at the University of
Hawaii; he is also a professional magician who has obviously pulled
more than one rabbit out of his hat. He even introduces himself
into his novel as a jealous academic rival of Leopold Roth. From
``Love in a Dead Language,'' it is clear that Siegel is widely read
in several languages, that he likes the way languages work and
play, that he revels in Maria Montez movies, that he relishes human
ingenuity, sympathizes with self-delusion, enjoys thinking about
sex, and can't be embarrassed by anything. Collectively, the book
is a meditation on the dignity and indignity of sex and the rapture
of love, and their complicated and explosively tragicomic effects
on human behavior. The novel is seriously funny and outrageously
philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   The reader can tell that Siegel admires Laurence Sterne's
``Tristram Shandy'' and Vladimir Nabokov's ``Pale Fire'' and
``Lolita,'' as well as the the metafictions of John Barth, but
those works have only helped his book become the unique thing it
is: preposterous, lubricious, enjoyable, and memorable, an
elaborately entertaining joke about a subject that's no joke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
