<HEADLINE>
`DEEP BLUE' DELIVERS A NOT-QUITE-SO-KILLER SHARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DEEP BLUE SEA 
Directed by: Renny Harlin 
Screenplay by: Wayne Powers, Duncan Kennedy &AMP; Donna Powers 
Starring: Saffron Burrows, Thomas Jane, LL Cool J, Jacqueline
McKenzie, Michael Rapaport, Stellan Skarsgard, Samuel L. Jackson 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Rated: R (graphic shark attacks, and for language) 
Star rating: 1 1/2 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smart sharks are the gimmick in ``Deep Blue Sea.'' But they
aren't smart enough to keep it from seeming the lame ``Jaws''
wannabe it is. Its only amusing element is campy dialogue,
including ripe throwbacks to the cheeseball exposition of '50s
sci-fi, with lines like ``Using genetic engineering, we increased
the brain mass, with a side effect that the sharks got smarter.''
Oh. That explains why the sharks don't phone for takeout, but use
their enlarged brains to destroy the floating lab and start eating
the scientists clinging to bits of submerged wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's more old dark house stuff in ``Deep Blue Sea''
than sci-fi. The old dark house here consists of a series of
chambers through whose steel doors the sharks keep hammering while
the survivors, led by Saffron Burrows and Thomas Jane, try to keep
from undergoing the usual shark movie career change from scientists
to submarine sandwiches. The formula is the genre's most ancient
and most reactionary, namely don't mess with the status quo, which
makes so many sci-fi fantasies fundamentally antiscience. The
problem with this one is that it's antimovie as well.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of water stained red, a string of narrow escapes,
the rapidly diminishing suspense that accompanies guessing which
ones will make it and which won't, plus a surprising racial
stereotype that involves LL Cool J playing a terrified cook who
keeps talking to God and clutching his crucifix every time his
teeth stop chattering. Scientists and technicians die, but Stepin
Fetchit lives! On the other end of the socioeconomic scale is
Samuel L. Jackson's investment banker coolly assessing the
experiments he's backing, ready to pull the plug on the expensive
research.
</P>
<P>
   The bait that scientist Burrows dangles before him is that
they'll all grow rich if her brain research yields a cure for
Alzheimer's. The bait she dangles before the sharks _ animatronic,
computer generated, and film clips of the real thing _ is herself
and her colleagues when she hoists a shark into the lab and it
begins flailing around with spectacular destructiveness after the
anesthetic wears off too quickly. Although these sharks attack in
coordinated ways and are said to be herding their prey, they behave
pretty much as all the other sharks do in all the other shark
movies.
</P>
<P>
   At times suggesting a series of outtakes from ``Waterworld,''
``Deep Blue Sea'' is as shallow as this kind of film gets. For all
the carnage, it's surprisingly boring. And forget characterization.
There are some interesting-looking actors aboard, but any
discussion of them must be deferred until they are connected to
material more substantial than this. It has not so far been a great
summer for aquatic terror. ``Lake Placid,'' the giant croc movie,
is dead in the water. And although ``Deep Blue Sea'' seems to think
it's about artificial intelligence, it plays as if it's much more
committed to artificial stupidity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
