<HEADER>
A6941 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-28 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HARD TO TELL SOME PLAYERS WITHOUT A SCORECARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not too long ago I bumped into John Auerbach, the executive
director of Boston's public health commission. Auerbach seemed like
a competent, articulate, and caring fellow. Yet I ended up shouting
at him: ``You're not Jon Auerbach!''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Auerbach is the best newspaper writer on the Eastern
Seaboard. Onetime Globe scribbler, now a Wall Street Journal
apologist for the titans of capital, Auerbach wrote the single best
piece of journalism this decade: A brief essay on the agony of
putting your mother on ``hold.'' Already ensconced in my personal
Pulitzer pantheon, he only added to his luster with his recent,
published admission that he uses two different, German-made
toothpastes, one formulated for morning brushing, and one for p.m.
use.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he would like to borrow my patented, sterling silver
floss rings. Cleanliness may be next to godliness, but oral hygiene
is the ultimate state of grace.
</P>
<P>
   However, I digress. You see the problem. Too many interesting
people. Too few names.
</P>
<P>
   There are three Michael Jordans, for instance. There's
you-know-who, then the Michael Jordan who ran Westinghouse before
it took over CBS, and he got shunted aside. Then there's a very
unlucky M.J. who plays guard on the University of Pennsylvania
basketball team. When his performance falls short of expectations,
opponents taunt him: ``You're not the real Michael Jordan!''
</P>
<P>
   What about the four Richard Cohens, all of them media
somebodies? One used to produce the CBS evening news and still
consults for the network. Another reports for the National Law
Journal, and another is a columnist for the Washington Post. That
Richard Cohen has occasionally received compliments for the Jewish
mafia book ``Tough Jews,'' which was actually written by Rolling
Stone's Rich Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Comes with the territory. Washington Post writer John Kelly
added the initial F to his byline, to distinguish himself from
other famous John Kellys, including the Beatles' ``Magical Mystery
Tour'' photographer and the Baltimore Sun writer. (``John Kelly''
was also an alias used by Alger Hiss.) ``Now people ask me if I'm
the guy who wrote that book about the FBI crime lab, `Tainted
Evidence,' '' says my friend JFK. The author? John F. Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa L. Williams is the former Miss America who had to
relinquish her title after revelations that she had posed in less
than a swimsuit for Penthouse before winning her 1984 crown. She
was initial-less for many years, and carved out a successful career
as an actor and singer, until an actor on Melrose Place forced her
to take the initial, as actors' union rules forbid two
personalities having the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Wallace, who apparently doesn't follow his father Mike's
career too closely, phoned to congratulate him for winning the
Pulitzer Prize this year. The winner turned out to be New York City
historian Mike Wallace, not the pride of Brookline High. St.
Martin's Press was over the moon to learn that Oprah Winfrey had
chosen a Mary Morris novel for her book club of the air. But the
novel was ``Songs In Ordinary Time'' by Andover's Mary McGarry
Morris, not the M.M. who writes for St. Martin's.
</P>
<P>
   You might have noticed that earlier this year President Clinton
attended a ceremony at which Newsweek's Michael Isikoff received
the Edgar A. Poe award for his Lewinsky-gate reporting. The award
is named not for the great author-fabulist, but for the longtime
Washington correspondent of the New Orleans Times-Picayune. ``A
true gentleman,'' George Bush called him, words his successor would
hold in reserve when discussing Isikoff.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Harper's magazine reprinted a portion of a
1998 interview with a retired German tour bus driver named Adolf
Hittler. Herr H. never changed his name, and suffered the
consequences. The younger of his two sons junked the name. ``When I
found out, I was surprised,'' the senior Hittler said.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago I received this e-mail message from someone with the
screen name ``Poetrywoman'': ``Did you once work as a reporter at
the Boston Herald? As I recall, a very tall, very slim, very nice
guy named Alex Beam. . . '' There can be no doubt that it was me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
