<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6944 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ROGERS-ARTHUR-ART-     07-28 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROGERS-ARTHUR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOGETHER: TWO TITANS OF TYKE TV 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HINGHAM, Mass. _ It was, as they say, nifty gallifty. A
beautiful day in the neighborhood for aardvarks and icons alike.
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny morning in February, Fred Rogers of ``Mr. Rogers'
Neighborhood'' fame met ``Arthur'' creator Marc Brown at Brown's
home on Main Street. The summit meeting between two members of
public television's royal family, children's program branch, was
taped for later broadcast on Rogers's show, and Wednesday (July 28)
was the day.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting constituted a return visit of sorts. Last year an
animated likeness of Mr. Rogers did a guest turn on ``Arthur,''
where the story line cast Rogers as a houseguest of Arthur's
family. Embarrassed to be seen with the cardigan-clad idol of
preschoolers everywhere, Arthur tried to hide Rogers from his pals,
fearing they would make fun of him. In the end the 8-year-old
Arthur learned a valuable lesson about true friendship and the
pains of growing up, two of Rogers's favorite topics.
</P>
<P>
   Returning the favor _ after all, what are friends for? _ Rogers
drops by Brown's studio for a drawing lesson and a chat with the
author and illustrator of dozens of Arthur books. Also on hand is
Michael Yarmush, the 16-year-old Canadian actor who provides the
voice for Arthur. Later in the show, Arthur _ in puppet form _ gets
a guided tour of Rogers's fabled Neighborhood of Make-Believe.
</P>
<P>
   Call it kiddie-show synergy or clever cross-promotion on the
part of PBS producers and executives, but the rapport between
Brown, 52, and Rogers, 71, seemed relaxed and heartfelt during the
long day of taping at Brown's studio, which began at 7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Rogers were if anything even more deferential to one
another in person than mere professional courtesy might warrant.
Asked during a break in the shooting what had attracted him to
appear on ``Arthur,'' Rogers, now celebrating his 30th anniversary
on the public airwaves, broke into an expansive smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the word go,'' Rogers said, ``Marc was interested in
children. And that's much different from someone who cares first of
all about what you can sell around a show. He not only cares about
children, he's still in touch with his own childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone working in children's television,'' added Rogers,
``should remember the order of those two words, children and
television. And Marc does.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers went on to note that while his viewers tend to be younger
than most ``Arthur'' fans, not all ``Neighborhood'' viewers are
preschoolers. College students and senior citizens send in fan mail
too, he said, and one reason for that may be that Rogers, a
vegetarian and exercise buff, projects as much youthful vigor as he
does grandfatherly wisdom and reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of grandchildren, Rogers mentioned that his own
grandkids, aged 10 and 6, are ``Arthur'' devotees too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've walked through airports and had older kids come up to me
saying, `I've seen you on Arthur!' '' Rogers said with a twinkle in
his eye, tucking into a grilled vegetable sandwich. ``I love that,
because on that show I'm an aardvark.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, during another break between scenes, recalled traveling
to Pittsburgh last year, where Rogers's show is produced, to sketch
the host for his guest appearance on ``Arthur.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the best experiences of my life,'' Brown
remembered, leaning against a studio wall lined with ``Arthur''
books and artwork. ``I walked down a long hallway, opened a door,
and there was Fred. `I've been waiting for you, have a seat,' he
said. I felt like I'd known him all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown credited his producers for writing Rogers into an
``Arthur'' script, a script on which Rogers made only minimal
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made a great story about something that's embarrassing to a
young person,'' said Brown, who has three children _ two sons in
their 20s and a 12-year-old daughter _ all of whom grew up in
Rogers's familiar, and familial, presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred has been a hero of mine for a long time,'' Brown
continued. ``You knew if your kids were exposed to shows like
Fred's, they were in good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The cross-pollination between ``Arthur'' and ``Mr. Rogers'
Neighborhood'' is a rare one for both creators. Other than
appearances on ``Sesame Street'' and a Russian children's program,
Rogers has stayed for the most part in his own televised backyard.
His visit here was a milestone for Brown as well, the first time
Brown had allowed another TV show _ other than a news program _ to
come into Arthur's inner sanctum and poke around.
</P>
<P>
   Along with ``Mr. Rogers' Neighborhood,'' ``Arthur'' has become
one of PBS's franchise shows. After just three seasons it already
airs in 60 countries worldwide. From books and videos to plush toys
and Web sites, it has spawned a merchandising empire as well. One
of Brown's sons helps oversee the Arthur-licensing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take this one day at a time,'' said Brown, shrugging as he
led a visitor on a tour of his basement warehouse stacked with
Arthur-related products. ``It's already been a wild ride.''
</P>
<P>
   To those who criticize Rogers's show for what might be called
its high saccharine content, Brown was quick to offer a pointed
rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a very adultist world,'' he said. ``It's easy to
forget what it's like to be the age these kids are. Fred's gift is
that he talks to them, not down to or around them.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown then recalled his first trip to see Rogers. He was packing
up to leave, he said, when an Arthur doll he had given to Rogers
poked its head around the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   Brown laughed. ``I heard Fred say, in Arthur's voice, `Don't
worry, Marc. I'll be all right,' '' he said. ``Now who else would
do that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
