<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6948 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-28 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLERGY APPEAL TO HOLLYWOOD: REIN IN THE SEX, VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Religious leaders joined entertainers and politicians who issued
a public appeal this week urging Hollywood executives to tone down
violent and sexual content in the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking the entertainment industry to assume a decent
minimum of responsibility for its actions and to take some modest
steps of self-restraint,'' according to the statement, called ``An
Appeal to Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we are asking parents to help in this task, not just by
taking responsibility for shielding their own children, but also by
making their concerns known to media executives and advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging the need for parents to control their
children's access to entertainment, the statement, released
Wednesday in Washington and available on the Internet
(www.media-appeal.org), asks industry executives to embrace ``a new
social compact.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Allowing children unsupervised access to today's media is the
moral equivalent of letting them go play on the freeway,'' the
appeal reads. ``But today even the most conscientious parent cries
out for help from an industry that too often abdicates its
responsibility for its powerful impact on the young.''
</P>
<P>
   Signatories of the statement include Episcopal Bishop Frederick
Borsch of Los Angeles and Mandell Ganchrow, president of the Union
of Orthodox Jewish Congregations.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal was sent to executives of such giant entertainment
companies as Time Warner, Walt Disney, CBS, MGM Studios, and
Nintendo of America.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also suggests a voluntary code of conduct that
would:
</P>
<P>
   --Set minimum standards for sexual, violent, and degrading
content.
</P>
<P>
   --Make clear the entertainment industry's responsibility for the
cultural health of the country.
</P>
<P>
   --Ask the industry to commit to reducing entertainment violence.
</P>
<P>
   _Prohibit the targeting of adult-oriented entertainment to
youths.
</P>
<P>
   _Provide parents more accurate information on media content.
</P>
<P>
   _Seek the industry's commitment to increase development of
family-oriented entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood has an enormous influence on America, particularly
the young,'' the statement reads. ``By making a concerted effort to
turn its energies to promoting decent, shared values and
strenghtening American families, the entertainment industry has it
within its power to help make an America worthy of the third
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the most heinous crimes of America's civil rights
era. Four little black girls were killed on a Sunday morning in
1963 when the Sixteenth Street Baptist Church in Birmingham, Ala.,
was bombed.
</P>
<P>
   Ku Klux Klansman Robert Chambliss is the only person ever
convicted in the bombing that shocked the nation. He died in prison
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But fellow Klansman Bobby Frank Cherry, 67, who suffers from
heart disease and lives in Mabank, Texas, has long been a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, one of Cherry's three ex-wives told reporters that he
boasted about being involved in the bombing. ``He admitted it,''
Willadean Brogdon told reporters last week in Birmingham where a
federal grand jury is hearing testimony on the case. ``He bragged
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry, however, has repeatedly denied any involvement.
</P>
<P>
   --More than two dozen religious groups have sent a letter to US
senators urging them to pass the proposed Hates Crimes Prevention
Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although 40 states and the District of Columbia now provide
enhanced penalties for hate crimes, significant gaps still exist in
protecting all Americans from bias-motivated crimes,'' the groups
state.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would strengthen existing law by extending hate crime
protection to people who are victimized because of their sexual
orientation, gender, or disability.
</P>
<P>
   Among the signers of the letter are the National Council of
Churches, the Episcopal Church, the Unitarian Universalist
Association of Congregations, and the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we believe that state and local governments should
continue to have the primary responsibility for investigating and
prosecuting hate crimes, an expanded federal role is necessary to
ensure an adequate and fair response in all cases,'' supporters of
the bill wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has been opposed by several conservative religious
groups, including the Family Research Council and the Southern
Baptist Ethics and Religious Liberty Commission. They argue the
bill would threaten the religious freedom of those who preach that
homosexuality is a sin.
</P>
<P>
   _The Southern Christian Leadership Conference was supposed to
gather Sunday (July 25) for its national convention in Charleston,
S.C.
</P>
<P>
   But four days ago, the group canceled its meeting to protest
South Carolina legislators' refusal to remove the Confederate
battle flag from the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The prominent civil rights group was expected to attract 2,500
delegates to its convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will urge every organization and corporation who lives
justice to join this effort to push America back from the brink of
senseless tribalism,'' Martin Luther King III, president of the
SCLC, told reporters from the steps of the Statehouse in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot at this point in history resurrect ghosts of the
past and allow the resurgence of racism, discrimination, and the
politics of resentment that the Confederate flag reclaims,'' added
King, son of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diego Ribadeneira's address is Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
via e-mail to religion(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
