<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGRONSKY'S LOW-KEY STAR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ He was innovative yet utterly traditional. He
was aggressive yet always a gentleman. Martin Agronsky, who died in
Washington Sunday at 84, was in the heroic pantheon of radio and
television news, a list that included Elmer Davis, Edward R.
Murrow, Howard K. Smith, Eric Sevareid, and John Chancellor. All
were serious, but all knew how to have a good time.
</P>
<P>
   Agronsky was a pioneer at least twice in his career. In 1956 he
helped open up the political nominating conventions. ``The zoom
lens and floor access changed everything,'' he once told me. ``No
smoke-filled room could overturn the verdict of the primaries when
people were watching in their living rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, after working for all three networks, he started
``Agronsky and Company,'' a talking-head session on Saturday nights
on Channel 9 in Washington. The format was simple and
much-imitated, except that Agronsky, who never raised his voice,
set an example for his panelists. It was a conversation, not a food
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Working for ABC, he covered the first televised conventions from
Philadelphia in 1948. The coaxial cable then reached only from
Boston to Richmond. Politicians had to be cajoled off the floor for
interviews. ``Worse yet, they had to wear heavy makeup, with
practically black lipstick. The equipment was primitive, the lights
were incredibly hot, and everyone was sweating,'' he recalled. ``It
was horrible _ also hilarious.''
</P>
<P>
   Reuven Frank, Agronsky's boss at NBC, now lives ``in deep
retirement'' in New Jersey. He recalls that ``Nobody was allowed on
the floor then, and nobody thought much of it. It was the way
things were; 1948 was the dark ages.'' By 1952, the platform and
credentials battles between the forces of Dwight D. Eisenhower and
Robert A. Taft ``made it a drama for us. They didn't allow us into
the committee rooms. They allowed reporters in, but no cameras, so
we kept taking a picture of the closed door.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1956, ``Martin was one of my floor reporters. Cameras were
still not allowed on the floor, so we had cameras on the periphery,
in the gallery and the radio booth.'' Agronsky regarded the
technology as a magic wand. ``It was terrific to get a governor or
a county chairman live, when something was happening,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1956 convention, the presidential nominee, Adlai
Stevenson, bowed to the television genie by allowing delegates, not
bosses, to choose his running mate. The contest among Senators
Albert Gore, Estes Kefauver, and John F. Kennedy made JFK a
television star.
</P>
<P>
   The conventions made television reporters into stars, too. The
Agronsky caucus outranked that of the governor of Idaho or the
chairman from Onondaga County. Agronsky was unfazed by fame. In the
early 1970s, he started a nightly program on Channel 26 in
Washington, ``Evening Edition,'' the forerunner to today's
``NewsHour'' on PBS. ``We're out here on the Shirley Highway, next
to the Beanie Weenie,'' Martin told guests he tried to coax onto
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``Agronsky and Company,'' which made print reporters
into stars recognized by cab drivers, bank tellers, and bartenders.
Peter Lisagor of the Chicago Daily News received almost a state
funeral; President Gerald Ford ordered him buried in Arlington
National Cemetery even though Pete had been only a sergeant. The
show survives today as ``Inside Washington,'' under the tutelage of
Gordon Peterson, the Channel 9 anchorman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agronsky's effort was a lower-decibel thing,'' Reuven Frank
says. ``Something else he did still hangs over that program. The
participants in that repertory company had the assignment of
covering a story for at least a couple of days that week. They knew
what they were talking about, so you got more than their opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   On too many channels today, Martin Agronsky's legacy of low-key
dignity is as quaint and distant as black lipstick under the hot
lights in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
