</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME FOR BLACKS TO TUNE OUT TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC, ABC, CBS, and Fox have 26 new television shows this fall
with no person of color in a lead role. The NAACP said the networks
were guilty of ``ethnic purification'' and ``a virtual whitewash.''
NAACP national president Kweisi Mfume has virtually assured some
sort of a boycott, saying, ``As sure as I'm standing here, you can
bet it's going to come down to that.''
</P>
<P>
   For all that smoke, it is a false alarm. Whitewashing pales next
to the brainwashing of black viewers. Ethnic purification is bad
but is merely a logical outcome of the putrifying world of
commercial TV. Boycott? Yes, boycott. But do not boycott on the
brushfire sparked by a dry white season. Boycott because black
folks need to turn off the television, period.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the networks have obviously assumed that
white viewers do not want to see black actors in power roles,
either in white or black shows. The comedies made for black
audiences are more Stephin Fetchit than Bill Cosby. Malcolm-Jamal
Warner, a star of the Cosby show, said today's black shows feature
``characters who say how ugly your mama is. . . . What Cosby showed
America was that black people can be funny without relying on
rehashed stereotypes, and, unfortunately, since Cosby, it's almost
as if everyone has totally forgotten that.''
</P>
<P>
   Television has so forgotten black folks, as well as other people
of color, senior citizens, the poor and anyone else who is not
living a perfect, wealthy, and youthful Upper East Side life, it is
time to forget television. African-Americans have the television on
in their homes an average of 70 hours a week, compared with 50
hours a week in the rest of the United States, according to Nielsen
Media Research and TN Media.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP is absolutely right in the narrow sense, but it should
be far more concerned that black folks are watching nearly a full
day more TV a week than the average household. It should be far
more alarmed that on Saturday mornings, 40 percent of black
households have the TV tuned to shows light on education and heavy
on toy selling and violent action compared with 24 percent of
nonblack households.
</P>
<P>
   If black folks watched 20 hours more of shows like ``Eyes on the
Prize'' or ``Nova,'' that might be one thing. That is not the case.
The two top syndicated shows in black households are the World
Wrestling Federation and Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest that white viewers are smarter or their
shows are better, with shows more about gross guys than gracious
gentlemen. And everyone is entitled to some vacuous entertainment
after a hard day. But black folks cannot afford to watch quantum
volumes more of dumb TV when studies suggest that massive viewing
indeed damages the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a survey of 2,245 grade-school children published in
the Journal of the American Academy of Child and Adolescent
Psychiatry found that children who watch more than six hours of
television a day are more likely to be depressed, anxious, angry,
and violent than children who watch less TV.
</P>
<P>
   A study by researchers at the University of Michigan that
followed children from the age of 8 until they were 30 found that
the children who watched significant amounts of violent television
were more likely to be more violent. A Case Western study found
sixth-graders to become more violent as television viewing
increased past three hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that educational television can increase
self-confidence, learning ability, and grades, while commercial TV
lowers them all. But with children averaging 90 minutes a day on
school days watching television, compared with just over 20 minutes
a day of study time, the learning is often diluted and drowned. The
90 minutes a day of watching television equals the average time
spent reading by a 12-year-old for an entire week. A survey of more
than 1,000 successful women in the new book ``See Jane Win'' by
Sylvia Rimm found that most of them watched less than two hours of
television a day as children.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Singer, professor of psychology at Yale University, said,
``The evidence is very strong that heavy viewing of TV by children,
particularly commercial programming, is deleterious for development
of cognitive skills and fosters agressiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   It also fosters bad health. A Harvard University study found
that men who watched TV six hours a day were more than twice as
likely to get diabetes than men who watched TV less than two hours
a week. A study published last year in the Journal of the American
Medical Association found that 43 percent of African-American
children spend more than four hours watching TV, compared with 20
percent of white children. Children who watched TV at least four
hours a day had about 20 percent more body fat than children who
watched less than two hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that can be changed,'' said Steven Gortmaker
of the Harvard School of Public Health. ``Kids don't have to watch
TV 28 hours a week.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what the NAACP should be trying to change. The racial
gaps in academic achievement and health demand that black folks
watch less television no matter what concessions the NAACP wrangles
out of the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Even if black faces are added to this dry white season,
commercial television will still be a desert. African-Americans are
in need of another oasis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
