<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6957 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-CUBA-BOS &LR;      07-28 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CUBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA TURNS COLD ON CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Whether happily puffing on pricey Cohiba Esplendidos
or jetting off for cheap vacations on the sun-drenched beaches of
Varadero, Canadians have long flaunted their country's friendly
ties with Fidel Castro's Cuba, much to the irritation of American
presidents as far back as John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But the fatigues-clad dictator's continuing suppression of basic
freedoms is finally stirring outrage in the nation that has emerged
as Cuba's most important economic partner since the collapse of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusted by Castro's most recent crackdown on dissidents,
Canada suddenly is putting the chill on its relations with the
Western hemisphere's only communist state _ an odd coupling that
for decades has represented the most serious foreign policy
divergence between Ottawa and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, 40 years after shooting his way to power, Cuba's
self-styled Maximum Leader is close to losing his last best friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still engaged with (Cuba), but it's time to put some
northern ice in the middle,'' said Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien, whose high-profile visit to the island last year gave a
boost to Castro's image even as it incensed Cuban Americans,
conservatives in Congress and international human rights watchdogs.
</P>
<P>
   Castro threw in a little ice of his own during a Revolution Day
speech on Monday, lumping in Ottawa with normal bad-boy Washington
to accuse both North American giants of dirty tricks aimed at
harming Havana during the Pan American Games in Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's tougher Cuban stance, which includes suspending new
foreign aid projects, comes as human rights groups intensify
condemnation of Castro's persecution of Cubans who dare criticize
his governance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba stands alone in the hemisphere for this kind of rights
abuse _ criminalizing free speech, imprisoning dissidents and
denying access to human rights monitors,'' said Jose Miguel
Vivanco, executive director of the Americas branch of Human Rights
Watch, which last week issued a stinging report on Cuba's abysmal
record.
</P>
<P>
   In Ottawa, the hardening attitude toward Cuba reflects general
displeasure with the deteriorating human rights situation as well
as Chretien's particular outrage at the jailing earlier this year
of four prominent dissidents whose cases he'd pleaded personally
with Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Canada is finally waking to the unhappy reality
that years of ``constructive engagement'' with Castro have produced
little in the way of democratic change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba has not liberalized politically, it has regressed,'' said
Archibald R.M. Ritter, professor of economics and international
relations at Ontario's Carleton University, and a prominent Cuba
scholar. ``The basic rationale for Canada's policy toward Cuba is
disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The final straw came in March, when a Cuban tribunal found four
well-known dissidents guilty of ``counterrevolutionary
activities,'' and sentenced them to five-year prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the secret trial, Chretien had implored Castro either
to release the four or try them in open court, in front of Western
media and human rights observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, Castro has bitten the extended hand,'' said
Ritter.
</P>
<P>
   According to Amnesty International, at least 350 political
prisoners are languishing in Cuban jails, most guilty of nothing
more than voicing criticism of the communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the United States, which imposed an economic embargo
against Cuba after the missile crisis of 1962 brought the world to
the edge of nuclear war, Canada has kept full diplomatic ties with
Havana since Castro's ``Fidelistas'' toppled the corrupt Batista
regime in 1959 and took charge of the island that lies just 90
miles off the tip of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the outset, Canada simply believed Castro represented an
improvement for Cuba, and that the country deserved encouragement
and help, not sanctions,'' said Caroline Andrew, professor of
political science at the University of Ottawa. ``But eventually the
policy congealed into a rather bizarre form of antiAmericanism _ a
symbol by which Canada could show its independence from the US.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how harmless Canada's support has been is being debated
today even by longtime proponents of constructive engagement. In a
recent editorial, the influential Globe &AMP; Mail newspaper noted that
four decades of Canadian ``trade partnerships, investment,
bilateral friendship and prime ministerial visits have done nothing
to improve Cuba's wretched human rights record.''
</P>
<P>
   To counter the situation, Canada has scrubbed all upper-level
official contacts with the Castro regime and suspended most new aid
projects. For the first time in years, Canadian officials are
publicly chiding Castro _ a big switch from Ottawa's usual moaning
about US sanctions against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is quietly, if a bit sarcastically, applauding
Canada's change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as really quite appropriate that Canada has made the
amazing discovery that Mr. Castro is actually a rather nasty piece
of work,'' said a US government official who monitors Latin
American issues.
</P>
<P>
   While drastic by Canadian standards, and almost certainly
delivering a big shock to Havana, Ottawa's move still amounts to
little more than a wrist slap from the country that has become
Castro's most important economic ally _ no other country sends more
tourists to Cuba, no other country funnels so much foreign aid and
hard-currency investment into the country.
</P>
<P>
   That's not going to change much, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa has no plans to interfere with the Canadian firms that
have become Cuba's No. 1 source of foreign investment or clip the
wings of the 150,000 or so Canadian ``snowbirds'' who sustain the
island's nascent tourist economy.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way commerce between Cuba and Canada came to $555 million
last year, with Canada's imports of Cuban nickel alone accounting
for nearly one-quarter of Cuba's hard currency revenues. Since
1990, meanwhile, Canadian firms have invested more than $600
million in Cuba _ building airports, golf courses, pizza outlets,
power facilities, hotels and mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadians should hang in, come hell or high water,'' said
businessman Ron Weissberger, vice president of Intelcan
Technosystems Inc., an Ontario-based civil aviation and
telecommunications firm. ``Those who stay will reap the benefits
later on.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian investors tend to shrug off moral concerns over doing
business in Castro's police state, noting that other countries,
most notoriously China, have much worse records but are still
eagerly courted by investors and economic officials from Western
democracies, including Canada and the US.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials, meanwhile, refuse to comment on their country's
damaged ties with Canada. A spokesman for the Cuban embassy in
Ottawa said only that any differences will be resolved directly
with Canada, not discussed with an American newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed, however, that the hierarchy in Havana is
especially alarmed by Canada's threat to stop backing Castro's
attempts to reintegrate Cuba into the community of Western
hemispheric nations.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa was set to go to bat for Cuba's admission to the
Organization of American States, something that Castro would
desperately like to accomplish before the the Summit of the
Americas, to be held in Quebec City in 2001. But Canadian officials
say they no longer will support Cuba until it dramatically cleans
up its human rights act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada is moving progressively toward a hardball approach to
Cuba,'' said John Kirton, a professor of political science at the
University of Toronto. ``Cuba's human rights record has become
Canada's embarrassment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
