<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL SOCIETY MISSION FALLS ILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Twenty-seven years ago, the Massachusetts Medical Society
chastised one of its members for ``undue promotion'' because his
research findings were reported in Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Medical Society fired the editor of the New
England Journal of Medicine because he balked at a marketing scheme
to trade on the name and reputation of the prestigious scientific
publication.
</P>
<P>
   My, how sensibilities have changed at the nation's oldest
medical society!
</P>
<P>
   The forced resignation of Dr. Jerome P. Kassirer would be a
trade publishing footnote were it not for the backdrop of public
suspicion about the direction of American medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The unease in the medical community that greeted word of Dr.
Kassirer's abrupt dismissal mirrors the fears of patients that
their doctors are basing treatment decisions less on medical than
on financial considerations.
</P>
<P>
   That fear and unease are well-placed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack T. Evjy, president of the Massachusetts Medical
Society, says Dr. Kassirer was forced out of his job because of
``administrative and publishing issues.'' What he means is that Dr.
Kassirer would not exploit the New England Journal's highly-prized
brand name to hawk less rigorously edited newsletters and other
commercial publications being launched to line the coffers of the
already resource-rich Medical Society.
</P>
<P>
   It is technically true that the Massachusetts Medical Society
has owned the 187-year-old New England Journal of Medicine since
1921. In that time, the publication has grown into one of the most
well-respected arbiters of medical research. But the scientific
community has long considered the Medical Society less an owner
than a trustee, a guardian of the high standards represented by Dr.
Kassirer's eight-year tenure as editor.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kassirer broadened the Journal's scope, inviting more
submissions from overseas researchers and making articles more
accessible to the general practitioner. He says the Medical Society
never tried to exert editorial control over the 230,000-circulation
magazine, but it is hard to imagine that parochial bunch
enthusiastically embracing Dr. Kassirer's stands in favor of the
medicinal use of marijuana and against the excesses of managed
care.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Society's concerns have always been of a much more
pedestrian and self-absorbed nature _ financing construction of an
office building in Waltham to house its growing publishing empire,
hiring lobbyists to fight any effort to tighten disciplinary rules
governing Massachusetts physicians.
</P>
<P>
   By injecting itself and its financial interests into the
operation of the New England Journal of Medicine, the Medical
Society further undermines confidence that any arm of the medical
establishment in the United States is committed first to the public
health.
</P>
<P>
   Is everything in modern medicine, even as trusted a symbol of
scientific rigor as the New England Journal of Medicine, just a
tool to enhance the bottom line?
</P>
<P>
   The same year that Time magazine's report on the research of the
chief of plastic surgery at Children's Hospital prompted a sharp
rebuke from the Massachusetts Medical Society, the organization
also censured the director of Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Society accused the late Dr. John H. Knowles of
undermining ``mutual confidence and goodwill'' in the profession
because he said, in a published interview, that he suspected that
30 to 40 percent of American doctors were getting rich by
performing unnecessary medical procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Knowles, who was leaving Boston to become president of the
Rockefeller Foundation in New York, scoffed at his critics in the
Medical Society. He refused even to attend the meeting called to
chastise him for his alleged breach of collegiality. His words
ought to lift Dr. Kassirer's spirits this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to diddle around with these jerks,'' Dr. Knowles
said of his decision to boycott the Medical Society's formal
disciplinary hearing. ``How is it that I am the only one to be
censured by the Society in the last half century? Who have they
picked? A guy who for 20 years has run the best hospital in the
country. When the John Birch Society votes to censure
(then-President Richard) Nixon for going to China, is he going to
fight them about it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamamra's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
