<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.F. POLICE CAPTAIN EYES RUN FOR MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects misspelling; changes description of Castro Street)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco police Capt. Richard Cairns, whose
role in the 1989 police sweep of a mostly gay and lesbian part of
the city resulted in his suspension from the force, has picked up
papers declaring his intent to run for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The move allows Cairns to raise money and explore a run for the
mayor's job without formally entering the mayor's race. ``I am
still debating (whether to run or not),'' he said in an interview,
``but I'm 90 percent sure I will run for mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Cairns has until Aug. 6 to officially enter the race.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five people have declared their intent to run, including
current Mayor Willie Brown, Supervisor Tom Ammiano, former Mayor
Frank Jordan and political consultant Clint Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in San Francisco, Cairns is a 30-year, highly
decorated veteran of the police force. He was mentioned as a
possible choice for police chief early in Brown's administration,
but that post went to then Deputy Police Chief Fred Lau. Cairns
also was mentioned as a possible member of the command staff, but
did not get that promotion, either. Currently, he is the captain in
charge of the Treasure Island station.
</P>
<P>
   Cairns said his being overlooked for a promotion earlier had
nothing to do with him considering a run for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The police captain said he had been thinking about a run for
``quite a while'' and has been encouraged by friends and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what prompted me to was seeing politicians setting up to
run but not really wanting to run, and people who want to see
change but not wanting to make the changes,'' he said. ``The
professional politicians are not fixing the city. I'm an ordinary
kind of person. I relate to people. Maybe, it's time for an
ordinary person to make the city work.''
</P>
<P>
   If he runs, Cairns may have to overcome criticism from the some
members of the gay and lesbian community for his role in the Oct.
6, 1989, police sweep of Castro Street. Cairns, who was head of the
police tactical unit at the time, was given a 45-day suspension for
striking protesters and ordering a false arrest during an AIDS
demonstration in the Castro District.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was 10 years ago,'' said Cairns. ``It's behind me. I was
disciplined for whatever. I'm not going to debate the pros and cons
of that issue. ... Except that one issue, I've not had any problems
with any community.''
</P>
<P>
   During the incident, police arrested 50 people after shutting
down part of Castro Street to cars and pedestrians. People in the
area, not all of them demonstrators, were herded down the street
and prohibited from leaving stores and businesses for nearly 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cairns said he's since talked to gay and lesbian groups.
</P>
<P>
   If he runs for mayor, Cairns will have to take a leave of
absence from his police job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take a leave,'' he said. ``That's not a problem. On Nov.
2, I'll be back to work or going over to City Hall one or the
other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
