<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-WOODSTOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODSTOCK'S TUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woodstock: The Riot. That's what last weekend's 30th-anniversary
concert turned into, although promoters are reluctant to use the
word. They strain for euphemisms _ melee, disturbance, fracas _ and
their inability to look the problem in the eye is what helped
create it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This festival did not collapse into chaos,'' Oneida County
Executive Ralph Eannace told reporters. ``This festival had a very
serious problem for a few hours last night.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``very serious problem'' was described as a ``war zone'' by
concertgoers who watched 12 storage trailers go up in flames, a
sound tower topple, a telephone truck burn, a Mercedes flipped and
trashed, tents pulled down, and three ATM machines vandalized.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters seeking to re-create the 1969 peace and love fest _
and cash in on the popularity of the retro-'60s movement _ relied
on young, inexperienced volunteers, called ``the peace patrol,'' to
keep order. Accounts said these volunteers ignored much of the drug
use, drunkenness, and nudity exhibited over the weekend, which may
explain why the event, attended by 220,000 people, was considered
``orderly'' until Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   When an estimated 200 to 500 people became violent at the
concert's conclusion, the untrained volunteers did not know what to
do. The rampaging and looting went on for nearly two hours before
police moved in to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Had the promoters considered plain vanilla crowd control
focusing on public safety first, there might have been a stronger
police presence from day one and less rubble to sweep away at
Griffiss Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   But Woodstock has achieved mythic status not only in the minds
of those who were there and who have forgotten how deep the mud was
but for those who wish they'd been there, experiencing what
supposedly ``defined a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock was spontaneous, extraordinary, crazy, and
unforgettable, but it can't be duplicated. Anyone who tries will be
disappointed or worse. That's the great lesson in the passage of
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0148 </DOCNO>
