<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEDICAL JOURNAL'S INTEGRITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New England Journal of Medicine is a national asset. Its
mission to publish authoritative reports about medical advances and
to lead the debate about health-related issues should not be
compromised in any way.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what the Massachusetts Medical Society has done by
deciding to fire Dr. Jerome Kassirer, whom the president of the
Medical Society describes as a great editor. Kassirer's one offense
was to oppose plans to dilute the integrity of the Journal by
holding its reputation hostage to less-renowned Medical Society
publications.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kassirer nor Dr. Jack Evjy, the Medical Society's
president, will reveal the details, but the disagreements go back
several years and include such matters as whether there should be a
link to the Barnes &AMP; Noble Web site in Journal book reviews posted
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Kassirer and his staff pride themselves on integrity, going so
far as to insist on the segregation of advertising pages from
editorial content. Journal procedures can seem archaic at times,
from the use of pencils in editing to its refusal to leave its
offices at the Harvard Medical School library for the Medical
Society's headquarters in Waltham, Mass. But the publication is
second to none in credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Kassirer took the Journal onto the Internet, established a
fast-track procedure for urgent medical news, and used the opinion
columns to respond nimbly to issues ranging from cloning and
medical use of marijuana to starvation in Somalia. He is hardly
caught in the musty past. He understands, however, that the Journal
needs to be protected from even the appearance that its good name
will be used to promote other agendas.
</P>
<P>
   If the Medical Society insists on replacing Kassirer, it should
choose an editor of equal integrity and skill. Dr. Marcia Angell,
the executive editor, would be an excellent choice, but she shares
many of Kassirer's concerns. Evjy said, ``We are absolutely
committed to maintaining the Journal's preeminent position.'' He
can do that by finding another superb editor and making sure the
society keep hands off its most authoritative publication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6993 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-CHINA-BOS &LR;      07-28 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WISE VOTE IN FAVOR OF CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week's 260-170 House vote to renew China's normal trade
status _ misleadingly called most-favored-nation status _ comes at
a time when US-Chinese relations are troubled and Chinese leaders
are showing signs of insecurity. Fortunately, both the Clinton
administration and the Republican leadership in Congress called
forcefully for extending to China the same low tariffs that nearly
all other US trading partners enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Not to renew China's trade status would have made a bad
situation gratuitously worse. With Beijing still smarting from the
bombing of its embassy in Belgrade and with Washington straining to
dissuade the Communists from taking military action in response to
Taiwan's retreat from the one-China principle, a vote to raise
tariffs on Chinese goods could have wreaked incalculable harm on
bilateral relations and US interests.
</P>
<P>
   No less delicate was the relation of the House vote to the
crucial economic decisions that China's leaders are poised to make.
Their panicky crackdown on Falun Gong, a faith-healing sect, may
well stem from their worries about the effects of economic
difficulties that have left millions of Chinese workers unemployed
and millions of others without proper pensions or health care.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress was debating China's trade status, Chinese leaders
were congregating in the seaside resort of Beidahe to set policy on
potentially explosive issues. They must decide whether to continue
closing or privatizing money-losing state-owned enterprises. They
cannot solve their mounting economic problems without completing
this transition to a market-driven system, yet these indispensable
reforms threaten social stability and the Communist political
order. If the decision makers had thought Chinese goods would be
singled out for punitive tariffs, they might have felt impelled to
reverse the course of reform and devalue the yuan, thereby
deflecting the economic recovery underway among their Asian
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   This is a time to speed China's entry into the World Trade
Organization, not play sorcerer's apprentice with the world's most
populous country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
