<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7012 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PC-USERS-HNS &LR;      07-28 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PC-USERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE A BUTLER THAN A MUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite high-tech industry hype about computers
becoming the focus of our future, users really want their machines
to become everyday household appliances, helping them do the
laundry, stand in line at the Department of Motor Vehicles and
handle other mundane chores.
</P>
<P>
   So says a recent survey of 1,001 computer users released by
Texas- based computer manufacturer Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The random survey, conducted between June 14 and June 28,
questioned computer users who use the Internet at least once a
week. Approximately 67.5 million users in the United States access
the Internet weekly.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Dell survey, various DMV tasks topped the
computer-task wish list, including renewing driver's licenses and
license plates (90 percent) and paying speeding and parking tickets
(70 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Voting was also a popular computer choice, according to 78
percent of the respondents. Manipulating photos was also a big hit
(80 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Half of those who answered the survey said they also want their
computers to help them do the laundry and water the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-seven percent of those surveyed want their computers to
handle home security. A little less than half _ 47 percent _ said
they would use their computers to order groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Marci Grossman, a Dell Computer spokeswoman, said the survey
shows how the computer is being integrated into our lives. ``It's
central in daily life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the survey shows that users want their computers to
fade into the background, becoming just another common household
appliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of technology is to get the hell out of the way,''
said Cliff Stoll, a University of California at Berkeley astronomer
and author. ``The point of technology is not to have a computer.
The point of technology is to get something done.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Computing does its best work when you can't tell
it's there. The computer that controls the fuel injectors in your
car is great. I have a lot of respect for that.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``the computer that crashes every time I fire up three
programs is terrible. Yet it is the one that gets the attention _
the rave reviews in the computer magazines,'' Stoll said.
</P>
<P>
   The computer as home-based taskmaster is a view echoed by
visitors to a Microsoft store in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the high-tech store, a banner proclaims, ``Where do you
want to go today?''
</P>
<P>
   According to passersby, not very far. Of the 20 people
questioned at Metreon, 18 said they want their computers to handle
routine, day-to-day home chores, such as balancing a checkbook,
controlling the lights in a house and, of course, avoiding DMV
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers were supposed to be our slaves,'' said Joan Didre of
Wisconsin. ``Now,'' she said, gesturing to the flashing screens and
lights of the Metreon interior, ``they're taking us over. It's time
we put them to work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be way cool to not have to go the DMV, ever,'' said
Emus Landers of San Francisco. ``And I'd love to vote from my
house.''
</P>
<P>
   (Two visitors said they wanted their computers to help them find
love.)
</P>
<P>
   Kim Alexander, president of the Sacramento-based California
Voter Foundation, is cautious about the prospects of online
balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of privacy, security and fraud concerns that
need to be addressed before people would be comfortable with voting
over the Internet,'' said Alexander, who is part of a state task
force studying the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are on the Internet to save time, not to waste time, so
it's not surprising, especially with government transactions, that
they want to cast a ballot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Security is also a road block to online DMV transactions, said
California DMV spokesman Evan Nossoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we're looking at,'' he said. ``We really don't
want people to come to the DMV field offices to stand in line.''
</P>
<P>
   Nossoff added that the DMV does want to see in person those
taking the license renewal test, required every 15 years. Because
of a 50 percent failure rate for that test, Nossoff said, ``there's
a huge potential for fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dell survey points to a contradiction: While computers
become increasingly complex, users struggle to make them perform
simple tasks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a battle San Jose's Randy Tamez has to fight every day.
</P>
<P>
   Blinded by a brain tumor in 1989, Tamez depends on his computer
and special software to perform routine tasks, such as reading his
e-mail, city bus schedules, radio guides and the like. As the
Internet and the computers that access it become laden with
features, he has to scramble to find ways to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My computer is an essential tool,'' he said. ``I depend on it
for very simple stuff, but the manufacturers are intent on making
them more and more complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Tamez: ``All the advertising and marketing says hooray for
this or that new computer feature, but all it does is leave people
in the dust. It's disheartening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
