<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-LATINOS _ WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who
declined an invitation by La Raza to speak at its national
convention this week, has also recently declined other invitations
to speak to Hispanic and other minority groups. The groups'
reaction and the possible political import. (Heath, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LA-RAZA _ HOUSTON _ Vice President Al Gore makes the
keynote address on the final day of the National Council of La Raza
convention Wednesday. Latinos are a key constituency for Gore's
presidential hopes, and his speech as he invades George W. Bush's
home turf will provide clues to his strategy for retaining their
loyalty. (Shepard, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   With GORE-DATA.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   GWBUSH-FAITH _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush argues that
``faith-based'' programs can transform lives in ways that
government can't, and he has pushed hard for more ties between
Texas and ``faith-based'' and community groups since 1996. But as
he seeks to take the idea national in his presidential bid, Texas
officials don't have solid empirical evidence on performance and
critics worry about violating the separation of church and state.
While there are many questions, the programs have lots of
supporters because they can provide what government can't:
confidence and faith in oneself. (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FAITH-WHAT _ What is ``faith-based''? (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FAITH-PRESIDENT _ What do the other candidates say about
faith-based initiatives? (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   RUDY-ALA _ Coverage of New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani's
fundraising stops in Alabama. (Vejnoska, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BALKANS _ SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzogovina _ President
Clinton arrives Friday in the capital that introduced most of the
world to Balkan bloodshed. The mission this time is peace, as
Clinton and his counterparts from more than three dozen countries
gather to map out a blueprint for knitting the region back into the
fabric of south-central Europe. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: This story can be held to run on Fri., July 30.
</P>
<P>
   FALUN-GONG _ While the Chinese government cracks down on
practitioners of Falun Gong, we talk to Atlanta-area practitioners
of the new meditation sect to find out what it is and what they
think of the crackdown in China. They're not angry about it _
because they're never angry about anything _ but they're very sad
and concerned. About 15 or 20 Atlanta Falun Gongians are in D.C.
right now, protesting in front of the Chinese embassy when they can
get a permit. They say they fear Chinese authorities may even begin
executing practitioners, and that is what their demonstration is
meant to prevent. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-CRUISES _ WASHINGTON _ A House subcommittee holds a
hearing Wednesday on a bill to restore the effectiveness of state
laws over gambling ``cruises to nowhere.'' (Lipman, Cox News
Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   REINSURANCE _ WASHINGTON _ The House Banking Committee holds a
hearing on a bill to establish a federal program to provide
reinsurance for state disaster insurance programs. (Hall, Cox News
Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SUICIDE _ WASHINGTON _ Surgeon General David Satcher is to
announce a new national suicide prevention initiative at the White
House on Tuesday. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). 14.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-SHULMAN _ WASHNGTON _ Louis T. Shulman, a Dayton
businessman, and his wife, Blanche, are contesting an IRS order to
pay more than $1.05 million in additional gift taxes. The couple's
petitions claimed the IRS overvalued the value of gifts when they
formed the Shulman Family Limited Partnership. (Mokal, Cox News
Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TAXENGLISH _ HUNTSVILLE, Ala. _ In multiple languages, Welcome!
flies on blue banners that flutter from lightposts. The local
chamber of commerce promotes international trade. Companies from
Greece, South Korea, Japan and Indoneisa run offices in town.
Populations of Hispanic and Asian residents are among the fastest
growing in Alabama. It's here Julio and Carmen de Paula chose to
retire. Immigrants from the Dominican Republic, they moved from New
York City in 1995 and bought a three-bedroom brick house for
$54,000. They were welcomed everywhere _ except in the office of
Madison County Tax Assessor Wayland Cooley. The 83-year-old
official refused to grant them homestead exemptions because they
couldn't speak English. Without the exemption, the de Paulas pay
nearly triple in property taxes. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   HORSESHOES _ GREENVILLE, Ohio _ Just as deliberate as that of an
underhand softball pitch, Eaton lobbed the horseshoe. One of its
heels caught the stake, and the shoe spiraled down. A ringer.
Seconds later, another metallic clink boosted Eaton's standing in
the World Horseshoe Tournament's 17-and-under girls division.
Before the World Horseshoe Tournament ends Saturday, some 1,500
competitors hailing from 47 states, Canada and Norway will pepper
scoresheets with thousands of X's and O's _ a tangible tribute to
Greenville's love affair with horseshoes. (Southerly, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
