<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7043 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-BUSINESS-HNS &LR;      07-28 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-BUSINESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL BUSINESS OWNERS CAUTIOUS ABOUT THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ About two years ago, Veronica Ruiz had a Web
site for her business, a supply and repair store for typewriters
and fax machines, but she got tired of paying $78 a month to a Web
posting company for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any good in it. I got maybe one call in eight
months,'' said Ruiz, owner of San Francisco Business Machines Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz's frustration with the Web is typical of small businesses.
A Gallup survey commissioned by GTE Corp. found most small business
owners realize it's important to have some sort of Internet
presence, but are unsure about what the technology can do for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an increasingly high level of awareness, but a low
level of understanding,'' said John McDonald, marketing vice
president at GTE Directories. ``A lot of people believe intuitively
it's important to their business, and while they're excited about
it, they are also apprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the growth in Internet usage, Ruiz said she would be
willing to try it again _ as long as her teenage son could set it
up for free.
</P>
<P>
   According to GTE, 31 percent of small businesses have a Web site
or some sort of Internet presence. That could amount to as little
as a posting on another site or having an e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some confusion. People think because they have an
e-mail address, they're a Web warrior,'' McDonald said. ``There are
people who say `I have a URL' _ it sounds hip. But some fail to
include that on their letterhead.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five percent of the 500 businesses surveyed had their own
Web page (as opposed to a listing or personal page) and 18 percent
claimed to be selling a product or service over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Messina, GTE Directories' new media marketing director, said
some of those transactions may be conducted off-line.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers _ especially the transaction figure _ sounded high
to Andrew Beebe, founder of Bigstep, a San Francisco-based Web site
devoted to bringing small businesses online for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small business people are busy people. They don't have time,
and they don't have a lot of money,'' said Beebe. ``They
intuitively understand the power of the Net, but are not currently
seeing the return on the investment.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that of those small businesses owners
selling via the Internet, two-thirds expected sales to increase.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, 61 percent of the businesses surveyed with Web
sites said they expected to conduct sales or transactions on the
Web within the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen, the primary reason today for people in
the local small business arena to have a Web site and a presence is
image,'' McDonald said. ``I think expectations are tempered, but
that will probably not last long.''
</P>
<P>
   Several small business owners in the San Francisco-area said
they recognized the importance of having some sort of presence on
the Internet, but they didn't want it to take much time or effort.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Loui, owner of the Casket Wholesale Centre, has his
business listed with Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch Inc., a
Pasadena-based Internet city guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``People use it to find the location, hours and some services,''
said Loui, who does not plan to create an independent Web site for
his business or sell caskets online. ``Just to have the presence is
sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   CitySearch executives said an average Web page of seven to 10
pages costs businesses $200 to $250 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Several business owners mentioned they were listed on the Web
site of a major company as a supplier or distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz said her San Francisco Business Machines was listed on
Brothers International's site. J.C. Plumbing, Electrical and
Heating Supply is listed on fixture manufacturer Kohler's site, but
a co-owner said he would eventually like the store to have its own
Web page and sell online.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I've got to computerize this whole store,'' said J.C.
Plumbing's Jim Cheng, explaining the company had just moved next
door to a larger space. ``There's a lot of research we need to do
before we really can go into the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Wood, owner of Forest Books, which has general interest
books but specializes in rare Eastern religion books, plans to
start selling online by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said he plans to have his offerings listed on the site of
one of a variety of independent book warehouses rather than develop
and maintain his own site. ``Even if only a few sell, it should pay
for itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several small business owners had no interest in being online,
but their reasons varied.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Wong, owner of Exclusively Volvo, looked into setting up
his own site but decided against it. ``We're so localized and so
specialized,'' he said, adding that 90 percent of his customers are
from San Francisco. ``For us to have worldwide exposure wouldn't do
us a lot of good.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Dekelaita, owner of Ideal Upholstery, doesn't have a
computer and doesn't expect to get one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so set in our ways after almost 30 years in business,''
said Dekelaita, 63. ``I imagine if the owners are young, they will
go into it whether they need it or not. It's a gadget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
