<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JFK-BOOK-BOS &LR;      07-28 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JFK-BOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISAPPROVAL OF JFK JR. BIOGRAPHY SPEAKS VOLUMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Fitzgerald, a New York literary agent, thought he was doing
an obvious thing when he proposed a quickie biography of John F.
Kennedy Jr. last week.
</P>
<P>
   He contacted an appropriate author; wrote up a proposal for a
quick, commemorative print run of 40,000; and faxed it off to 12
publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, he had 12 rejections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really amazed,'' said Fitzgerald, who works at the Carol
Mann Agency. ``The comments I got were interesting. One of them
said, `We do quickie books, but we won't do John-John.' One said,
`We don't think there's any market for it,' which was really
insane.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Fitzgerald had given up the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``If tomorrow we went in and Elton John died, guess what? It
would work,'' he said. ``But there was something a little too
sacrosanct about John-John.''
</P>
<P>
   As Americans hit hard by Kennedy's death emerge from their
mourning, the attempt to market his memory has started.
</P>
<P>
   But so has the public's disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   As periodicals about the Kennedys fly off shelves, publishing
circles were buzzing with news of who will come out with the first
``quickie bio'' _ the cheaply made, lightly researched books that
often emerge weeks after a major news event but that Boston
literary agent Lane Zachary of Zachary Shuster said would be ``so
incredibly cheesy'' in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say Kennedy's death may be the rare event in
which the public hunger for information is overcome by repugnance
at the thought of profiting off of a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a revulsion factor,'' said Ike Williams, a literary
agent with Palmer and Dodge in Boston. ``There's a certain place
where you better not go as a medium when you try to use something
sacred for profit. There is a point where you can make people so
angry that they destroy your company.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the public's grief over Kennedy's death is inevitably
compared to global mourning over Princess Diana's death two years
ago, the response from the New York publishing industry over the
last week has been far different.
</P>
<P>
   Within three days of Diana's death, publishers were announcing
reissues of 12 different titles, rushing more than 2.5 million
books onto the market, said Nora Rawlinson, editor of Publishers'
Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   This time, by contrast, Ballantine, Pocket Books, and St.
Martins Press were quick to tell Rawlinson's trade magazine they
have no plans to put out quickie biographies.
</P>
<P>
   Some publishing specialists speculated that retailers felt they
had gotten burned by overstocked Diana books, which languished on
shelves long after the thirst for information was satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean, however, that the accident hasn't generated
some surprise literary stars.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Spignesi _ whose 28 books include ``What's Your `Mad
About You' IQ?'' and ``She Came in through the Kitchen Window:
Recipes Inspired by the Beatles and their Music'' _ was buried in
his latest project, ``a consumer guide to jewelry for a major
marketing network,'' when word of the accident reached him.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has watched his 1997 book, ``The John F. Kennedy,
Jr. Scrapbook,'' climb from a spot ``in the 60-70,000 range'' on
Amazon.com's (www.amazon.com) bestseller list to as high as number
4.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Scrapbook,'' which had sold 9,500 copies up until
Kennedy's death, had a back order of 65,000 on the Monday after the
crash, according to the book's publisher, Stephen Shragis of
Citadel Press.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Spignesi was working feverishly on a revised
edition that goes on sale this week with a print run of 125,000,
complete with a new epilogue, a more dignified visual treatment,
and the more respectful title ``John F. Kennedy, Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My book has been out for 2 1/2 years,'' he said. ``Now they're
fielding nonstop calls from distributors. People want this book.
They want it now. Up until last week, no one wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   But even those making a profit draw their own line for
appropriate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   After watching bidding for his book go as high as $151 on the
Internet auction site eBay (www.ebay.com), Spignesi called the
online auctioneers ``commercially predatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other sellers on eBay chastised opportunists who
didn't wait ``a respectful amount of time'' to start selling
Kennedy memorabilia, ranging from hundreds of back issues of
Kennedy's magazine, George, to Internet domain names like
``www.kennedyaccident.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have been turned off by the behavior of the media and
pundits.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers at George removed associate editor Douglas Brinkley's
name from the magazine's masthead last week after Brinkley's
numerous television appearances commenting on Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, head of the Center for Government Studies at the
University of Virginia, reached a point of disgust last weekend
when a network news producer asked him to be a commentator on
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   When Sabato said he had only met Kennedy once, the producer told
him, ``That's good enough for me,'' Sabato recalled. Sabato refused
to appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there are a few standards left, but I'd be surprised,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although book publishers have been up front with their
squeamishness about capitalizing on Kennedy's death, skeptics
wonder if their hesitance might be motivated by money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sense of seemliness or anything else,'' said
Helene Atwan, a veteran of New York mass market publishing who is
now the publisher of Boston's Beacon Press. ``If they're not doing
quickie bios, I suspect it's because they don't think they're going
to make any money,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, three reissued biographies of Kennedy are due out soon.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the Spignesi book, an Andrews McMeel title, ``John F.
Kennedy, Jr.: A Life in the Spotlight,'' will be available Aug. 1
with a print run of 200,000, and Signet's ``Prince Charming: The
John F. Kennedy, Jr. Story'' will have a print run of 350,000 and
go on sale Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a Kensington Press book titled ``The Kennedys: The
Third Generation,'' originally slated for October, will be hurried
to press this week, with a print run of 375,000.
</P>
<P>
   And as Rawlinson, the editor of Publishers' Weekly, pointed out,
not everyone sees quickie books as disrespectful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think providing people with that kind of thing is such
a bad thing,'' she said. ``I personally like to see books being
involved in the national culture and the national consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the word of the moment in publishing is restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary, the Boston literary agent, said she had never been as
proud of the industry as she is right now.
</P>
<P>
   This is a moment, Zachary said, when public disapproval has the
potential to trump the profit motive. It is an event, as one
observer wrote upon the death of the poet Alexander Pushkin, ``so
tragic as to silence even gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it were a wonderful tribute, there's something about
putting out a book before the body's cold that has a kind of
rudeness to it,'' Zachary said. ``The publishing world, like the
fashion world, is driven by money, but I think there is a line. I
really do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
