<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIRY-QUEEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIRY QUEEN: A LOVE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't fool Warren Buffett. There's a reason he's the world's
most respected financier. This is a man who knows a good thing when
he sees one. This is a man who buys a good thing when he sees one _
and Warren Buffett owns Dairy Queen.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Dairy Queen, the fast-food franchise that time forgot and
summer embraces. Even at the height of its season, though, DQ is
anything but high-end. Small wonder that when Buffett's company,
Berkshire Hathaway, acquired Dairy Queen in 1997, a stock analyst
sniffed to Bloomberg Financial Markets that this ``lower-tier brand
name . . . doesn't fit well with what I would see as a typical
Warren Buffett investment.''
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the analyst had a point. DQ may have nearly
6,100 outlets in 25 countries and rank ninth among US restaurant
chains, but it remains a throwback to an era when the prefix ``Mc''
meant someone Scottish and Haagen-Dazs sounded like the name of a
UN secretary general. As franchising and fast foods have become the
cutting edge of global capitalism, as ice cream has attained the
status of haute cuisine (The New York Times food section reported
last month that Manhattan's priciest eateries now offer such
flavors as Tahitian vanilla-bourbon and raspberry hibiscus), Dairy
Queen has remained the endearingly clunky, enduringly
unprepossessing operation it has been since the first one opened on
June 22, 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy Queen sells its soft serve with a soft sell. Items that
bear such names as Buster Bar, Dillywich, Dilly bar, or Peanut
Buster Parfait do not cry out for admission to the high-concept
hall of fame. Uncool in everything but the temperature of its
products, DQ is Midwest retro at its most amiably American.
</P>
<P>
   Yet its resolute unhipness is part of what makes DQ so
appealing. McDonald's has more or less taken over the world. Burger
King wants to surpass McDonald's. Wendy's wants to surpass both of
them. Pizza Hut, Taco Bell, and KFC, which Pepsi spun off two years
ago as a single corporate entity, are one big artery-clogging
advertisement for that supreme '90s buzzword ``synergy.'' Against
such up-to-the-minute marketing, DQ stands as a model of
steady-state stolidity in the big-bang universe of
late-20th-century American fast food.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Dairy Queen logo. The sans-serif type and modified
amoeboid shape belong to a kind of high-'50s style that, alas,
already seemed dated by the time the logo was introduced in 1961.
It seems even more dated today, since it hasn't changed a whit
since _ nor have the outlets' red mansard roofs (Dairy Queen as
dairy barn?), also introduced in the early '60s. No, DQ does
without such concessions to the fickleness of public opinion as
design overhauls or up-to-the-minute product tie-ins. McDonald's
currently has ``Tarzan.'' KFC-Taco Bell-Pizza Hut offers ``Phantom
Menace'' giveaways. Burger King has ``Wild, Wild West'' sunglasses
up for grabs. Dairy Queen? It has the same entertainment tie-in
it's had since 1972: Dennis the Menace.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's true, some things never go out of style _ but that's
assuming they were in style in the first place. This is the beauty
of DQ. Like an endless stream of soft serve extruding itself from
God's spigot, it just keeps on going its own vanilla (and
chocolate) way.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the Blizzard, of course. The Blizzard is where DQ's
deeply American love of tradition meets a deeply American love of
innovation _ and profit. The Blizzard flavor treat, a name as
beguiling as the product that bears it, is soft serve blended in a
cup with fruit, candy, or nuts of the patron's choice. The result
is dessert sublimity: the easeful texture of soft serve softened
further by the blending process and then delightfully varied by the
mixed-in crunchiness of, say, Heath bar bits or Oreo crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   A Dairy Queen franchiser named Sam Temperato tasted a product
that bore the painfully unpalatable name of ``the Concrete'' at a
St. Louis frozen custard stand. The Concrete was soft serve with
mix-ins. ``One taste of this product and I knew it was a natural
for Dairy Queen,'' he later recalled. It was Temperato who came up
with the name Blizzard and prevailed upon Dairy Queen to introduce
the product. Quite shockingly, in retrospect, he met with strong
opposition. The first DQ Blizzard was whirled (the preferred verb)
in 1985. Within a year, 200 million had been sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Blizzard's success has spawned numerous imitators, including
such palatable, if inferior, items as McDonald's McFlurry and
Friendly's Cyclone. Alas, McFlurries and Cyclones are far easier to
come by in Massachusetts than Blizzards are. The commonwealth
boasts 230 McDonald's and 112 Friendly's _ but a mere 33 Dairy
Queens. It could be worse. New Hampshire has just nine, Vermont
two, and Rhode Island is alone among the 50 states in having no
Dairy Queens within its borders. Even Alaska, a state where it
takes an act of will not to lower-case Blizzard, manages to support
at least one DQ.
</P>
<P>
   How DQ-deprived is Massachusetts? There's only 1 DQ for every
185,394 inhabitants. Contrast that with Minnesota, Dairy Queen's
corporate home and, clearly, a far more civilized state. The figure
there is 1 per 14,694.
</P>
<P>
   While driving through the Midwest, it sometimes seems that one
sees almost as many DQs as silos. Indeed, Dairy Queen very much
remains a heartland phenomenon, which is as it should be. It was in
Green River, Ill., that J. F. (Grandpa) McCullough and his son,
Alex, invented soft-serve ice cream. It was in nearby Kankakee that
the McCulloughs unveiled the new delicacy at Sherb Noble's ice
cream parlor on Aug. 4, 1938. ``We dished up over 1,600 servings in
about two hours,'' Noble recalls in Dairy Queen's corporate
history, ``The Cone With the Curl on Top.'' Less than two years
later, the McCulloughs and Noble opened the first DQ, in Joliet,
Ill. The rest is food franchising history. (That's no Blizzard of
hyperbole, either: Ray Kroc, the founder of McDonald's, started out
selling cups and machinery to Dairy Queen franchisees, and later
credited his exposure to DQ as teaching him the ins and outs of
food franchising.)
</P>
<P>
   My first Dairy Queen experience was in Stoneham. Appropriately,
the site is now occupied by a bank: a symbol of DQ-disdaining
Massachusetts putting its money where its mouth ought to be. This
introduction was a good two decades or more before the arrival of
the Blizzard. I was as likely then to order from the Brazier side
of the menu _ which offers burgers, franks, and fries _ DQ's
attempt to provide some ballast for the frozen treats to follow. I
also had a weakness for the Mr. Misty, a slush concoction one
drinks through a straw. This method has the unfortunate tendency of
removing the syrup while leaving behind a cupful of unflavored
slush. Not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   My first Blizzard was in Kirtland, N.M., on Nov. 14, 1989. Some
facts a man just doesn't forget _ though the fall of the Berlin
Wall a few days before may have something to do with my clarity of
recollection. It was love at first lick. The Cold War was over, and
a cold compulsion had begun. I have since had Blizzards in Arizona,
Nevada (the only business establishment I saw in Reno without slot
machines was the DQ), New York, Ontario, Wisconsin, Minnesota,
Iowa, Oregon, California, Georgia, Pennsylvania, Maine, Florida,
and, of course, Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   I've yet to have a Blizzard in Texas, though, and Texas is one
place that knows, and appreciates, Dairy Queen. It is home to 729
DQs (Illinois comes in a very distant second, with 282). It's only
fitting that the state's unofficial novelist laureate, Larry
McMurtry, has written a memoir called ``Walter Benjamin at the
Dairy Queen.'' Simon &AMP; Schuster will publish it in November.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin, the German cultural critic and essayist, would hardly
seem a DQ man (coincidence or no, he died only days after the first
one opened). Yet two years before the McCulloughs and Noble served
up their first soft serve, and another 49 before Sam Temperato
turned Concrete into dessert-treat gold, Benjamin wrote his most
famous essay, whose title captures as does no other the essence of
Dairy Queen's most popular product in all its frozen glory. What is
a Blizzard, after all, if not ``The Work of Art in the Age of
Mechanical Reproduction''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
