<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7082 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADDOGS-PART1-4thTake     07-28 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADDOGS-PART1-4thTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: he says. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Milner's Mississippi experiences also inspired his first and
only novel, ``Incident at Ashton.'' The book was published in 1961,
the same year he returned to Texas after working as an
editorial-page assistant at the doomed ``New York Herald Tribune.''
</P>
<P>
   While in New York, Milner covered the beginnings of the American
folk music uprising. Individuals such as Bobby Dylan and Joan Baez
and groups like Peter, Paul and Mary were taking their music in a
new direction. A decade later, Milner would participate in a
similar uprising in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   His longtime crony, Larry King, also launched his career as a
newspaper reporter, first in an abbreviated stopover at the Hobbs
(New Mexico) ``Daily Flare'' and later, in the early Fifties, at
the ``Midland Reporter-Telegram'' and the ``Odessa American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect,'' King later wrote, ``I believe I was fortunate
to work for small dailies where young reporters had the opportunity
to cover everything: city hall, murder trials, sports, labor
disputes, oil-well fires, state and regional politics, the police
beat with its hard-boiled cops and hard-nosed crooks.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, King arrived in Washington with a newly elected Texas
congressman and a powerful urge to carve out a writing career. When
his hero's political career went south, King leased his loyalty to
another, more successful Texan, House Speaker-in-waiting Jim
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   King free-lanced articles and started a novel while working for
Wright. But in 1964, over the congressman's protests, he left to
write full time. Though he would produce some of his finest work in
the mid-Sixties, principally for ``Harper's'' magazine, he would
never be more than a few dollars from being deadbeat broke, until
``Whorehouse'' pranced onto Broadway in the late Seventies.
</P>
<P>
   ``King wouldn't answer the phone or the door for fear of
confronting some ill-tempered creditor,'' says Fort Worth
free-lancer Mike Blackman, who lived in New York in the Seventies
and later was editor of the Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   King had gotten his first book contract and a $1,500 advance for
a political novel called ``The One-Eyed Man.'' It was published in
1966 to mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorably cruel twist, the first review appeared in his
hometown ``Washington Post,'' and it was devastating. Recounting
that episode in ``None but a Blockhead,'' King spent the night
furiously cursing, smoking dope and guzzling beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it ... really that bad, Lar?'' his wife, Rosemarie, asked
as he stomped through their Washington apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rosie,'' he responded, ``it was the ugliest thing to appear in
print since my ex-wife's divorce deposition.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Back home, history of a special kind was being made in the '50s
at the old ``Fort Worth Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackie Sherrod, the Vince Lombardi of sports writing, had hired
Jenkins, Shrake and Cartwright at the small but noisy little
tabloid, and eventually they followed him to the ``Dallas Times
Herald.''
</P>
<P>
   With columnist Dick Hitt rounding out their quirky quartet,
Jenkins, Shrake and Cartwright were proving daily that anything
worth doing was worth doing to excess.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Cartwright's hero and role model back then was
actor Robert Mitchum, the first Hollywood rebel arrested for
marijuana possession. To this day, Cartwright savors Mitchum's
response when asked about life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like Hollywood,'' he replied, ``but without the
riffraff.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright also was impressed with the story about Mitchum's
appearance at a Hollywood costume party, his naked body slathered
with ketchup and covered only by two buns.
</P>
<P>
   ``On several occasions, I did an imitation of Mitchum's act,
though I didn't always wait for a costume party or bother with
buns,'' he wrote in ``HeartWiseGuy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins meanwhile was cementing his lifelong rapport with J&AMP;B,
researching what later appeared in his novel ``Baja Oklahoma'' as
the 10 stages of drunkenness. The widely quoted infamous 10 include
Witty and Charming, Parts I and II, right on up to Invisible and
Bulletproof. The best line is too vivid to repeat here but involves
forgoing dinner.
</P>
<P>
   He soon would turn out several nonfiction books and a string of
hilariously raunchy and mostly successful novels, including one
called ``Limo'' that he co-authored with Shrake.
</P>
<P>
   And Shrake himself was beginning to demonstrate an astounding
range of writing talents, even more so considering his own
nocturnal habits. Shrake's friends always envied, or at least
admired, his choice of women, which sometimes outshone his talents,
which were enormous.
</P>
<P>
   Once, between wives, which was not an infrequent state, Shrake
got involved with a stripper named Jada who performed at Jack
Ruby's notorious Carousel Club. Jada's erotic act featured a
stuffed Bengal tiger and ``screaming orgasmic arias'' as Cartwright
described them.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright still claims Jada was the most interesting and exotic
woman he ever met, although he probably was influenced by a wedding
gift Jada gave him and his second wife.
</P>
<P>
   It was a 2-pound cookie tin filled with manicured marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PART 1: In the beginning: lyrics, literature and lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   PART 2: Wasted days, wasted nights, surprising success.
</P>
<P>
   PART 3: Looking back: Remorse and regret ... but not much.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
