<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7084 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADDOGS-PART1-3rdTake     07-28 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADDOGS-PART1-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: title itself. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Foremost among Milner's confessions, incidentally, is his
admission that native son McMurtry was probably right when he
declared that Texas hasn't produced one truly great book. That
could be true if one excludes McMurtry's own Pulitzer Prize-winning
``Lonesome Dove'' or, as some might argue, Katherine Anne Porter's
``Ship of Fools'' (her Pulitzer was to come for ``Collected
Stories'' in 1966). Or maybe even William Humphrey's ``The
Ordways,'' if not ``Home From the Hill,'' which became a hit movie
starring Robert Mitchum.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Texas did produce, beginning in the 1960s, was a rabble
of writers,'' Milner says, ``including songwriters, who had the
courage to step up to the plate at a time when being a serious
writer from Texas was ... seldom heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dogs and their buddies ``blazed the trail for Texans who
came along later and dared to write about today's Texas.'' Of
course, throughout the Mad Dog era, other exceptional writers had
been at work in Texas, such as Horton Foote and William Goyen, John
Graves and Elmer Kelton, Beverly Lowry and Elroy Bode, to name a
few. But they were decidedly less rambunctious than the Mad Dogs
and, for whatever other reasons, never seemed to consistently
capture as much public attention.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the Mad Dog lifestyle may have overshadowed the
early Mad Dog offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure at the time people were mindful of all the talent
floating around,'' says Griff Singer, the eminent University of
Texas professor who for more than 30 years has been closely tied to
the best of Texas journalism and literature. ``I don't think we
knew what we had here.''
</P>
<P>
   Over coffee one recent evening, Jay Milner discussed how this
``rabble'' of writers bridged the gap between J. Frank Dobie and
the ``old bulls,'' and the current, bountiful crop of Texas
writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't many writers in Texas, and what we had, left,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   An exception of sorts was McMurtry, whose ``Horseman, Pass By''
was published in 1961 and became a Paul Newman movie called
``Hud.'' He followed that with ``Leaving Cheyenne'' in 1963, which
developed an almost cult following among readers but lost its
bearings on the way to the screen as ``Lovin' Molly.''
</P>
<P>
   And of course there was ``The Last Picture Show'' in 1966, which
Hollywood transformed into an acclaimed film classic.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nearly 20 years and several epics later before
McMurtry received his Pulitzer for ``Lonesome Dove.'' The book and
blockbuster television miniseries converted two old Texas Rangers,
Gus and Call, into beloved literary characters.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the Sixties, Billie Lee Brammer was bouncing from
one misadventure to another, a tragedy hellbent on happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brammer was the all-time champion of wasted talent,'' says
A.C. Greene.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say he was a tragic figure. He was a dreamer, and
his many friends adored him. They still speak of him with poorly
concealed wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billie Lee had a rare charisma,'' Milner wrote of Brammer.
``Strange and powerful. His compelling charm had something to do
with the fact that he had written that famous book everyone had
read, or heard about, and perhaps related to.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was more than that. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Brammer's friend Billy Porterfield wrote once of reading a
review in ``The New Yorker'' of an F. Scott Fitzgerald memoir
written by his former secretary, Frances Kroll Ring. The reviewer
said of Ring and Fitzgerald, ``Like others who knew him, she
emphasizes his gentleness, kindness and generosity, and his
gallantry in the face of crushing circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Porterfield insists that Ring could have been describing Brammer
``as we, his friends, saw him.''
</P>
<P>
   After the huge critical acclaim of ``The Gay Place,'' which
centered on a political character strikingly similar to Lyndon
Johnson, Brammer slipped slowly into a hazy funk. There were
interludes with ``Time'' magazine, ``Texas Monthly'' and the
``Observer,'' but to this day, stories of Brammer and his
euphemistic ``heart medicine'' are legend.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, yes, but inevitably fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Lee never got around to writing a sequel to his novel,
though he didn't spurn his publisher's advances. In February 1978,
in his Austin duplex, he died of an overdose of speed.
</P>
<P>
   He was 48.
</P>
<P>
   His last job was busing tables at the Driskill Hotel, where,
when the mood struck him, he would also smuggle frozen T-bones from
the kitchen freezer for him and his friends.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, most of the Texas writers made their early
mark in a variety of journalistic venues.
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s, Jay Milner was newspapering in Mississippi, most
impressively at Hodding Carter's courageous little ``Delta
Democrat-Times'' in Greenville. Carter was known nationally on
several levels, not least of which was as an author and a Pulitzer
Prize winner for editorials urging racial understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Milner recalls lounging around on the floor of the Carters' home
one evening with such Hollywood, Broadway and literary luminaries
as Budd Schulberg, Eli Wallach, Robert Penn Warren and Elia Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gatherings such as this inspired me to catch up on my
reading,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
