<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7088 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADDOGS-PART1-2ndTake     07-28 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADDOGS-PART1-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: waiting for.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Austin of the Sixties and Seventies was of course much cozier,
less crowded, not so pricey and, as Cartwright says, the prettiest
and most interesting city in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright remains smitten with Austin's ``rolling hills,
spring-fed rivers and creeks and a laid-back attitude that seems
immune to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Milner says Austin once was arguably the best little city in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Says Walker wistfully, ``Somebody was throwing a party every
night after the bars closed.''
</P>
<P>
   On one such night in the early Seventies, the revelers descended
as they frequently did on the home of Fletcher Boone, a struggling
artist, sculptor and fellow dog. As Jerry Jeff tells it, Boone
declined an invitation to join the party, explaining that he needed
to get some work done in his art gallery to pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Walker looked around the room, spotted a painting on the wall
and blurted: ``How much for that painting?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight-hundred dollars,'' Boone replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll buy it,'' Walker declared, whipping out the cash. ``Now
you can go play with us.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jerry Jeff recounted the story, a visiting reporter glanced
at Susan Walker for confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was $900, not $800,'' she said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Mad Dogs all, and still proud of it, though their drink of
choice these days is rarely beer or booze but coffee or Diet Coke.
They still pop pills, but for medicinal rather than delusional
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Their wasted days and nights, albeit colorful, are history.
</P>
<P>
   Generally in their 60s now, most have ``hit the wall,'' which is
Mad Dog talk for heart attacks and bypass surgery and other
life-threatening episodes. This is traceable to years of exotic
food, drink and drugs and a relentless waltz on the wild side with
the wife or woman du jour.
</P>
<P>
   The article in ``The Texas Observer'' recently touched on this
Mad Dog phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of these cowboys,'' Mark Smith writes, ``the endgame
has been remarkably similar: a ride home from the triple bypass (or
transplant) in a water wagon steered by a good-lovin' second, third
or fourth wife.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cartwright, it was a heart attack. For Shrake, it was
diabetes and a wounded liver. For Jenkins, whose major vices were
Scotch and Winstons, it was triple-bypass surgery. For Milner, it
was depression. For Billie Lee Brammer, an enigmatic one-novel
wonder (''The Gay Place''), it was an early death. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Remorse? Occasionally. Regrets? More than they want to admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew then what I know now, I'd change the hell out of
it,'' says Shrake. ``But I don't drink now.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Cartwright: ``The thought slipped through my mind when I
had my heart attack that at least I deserved it. ... But that was
our time, and we weren't going to be restrained by anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jerry Jeff, a kid of 57, grinning like a guy who regrets
nothing about his long reign of terror: ``We had the longest
childhood of any group in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he doesn't remember much of it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright, 64, a senior writer at ``Texas Monthly,'' says it
was during his own fuzzy-memory period that Mad Dog was born in
Austin in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shrake and I formed this shadowy organization for no
particular purpose except that the Vietnam War was going on and it
seemed like a good idea,'' he wrote in his 1997 memoir-health
guide, ``HeartWiseGuy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We prided ourselves on living on the edge: Some would say that
we lived delusionally, but from our perspective, reality covered
more than a single dimension. Mad Dog reflected that perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, Mad Dog remains an ill-defined brood, although two
charter members were Jodi Gent and husband Pete, the former Dallas
Cowboys receiver who wrote the darkly scandalous sports classic
``North Dallas Forty.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the pack were Austin attorney David Richards and his
silver-tongued wife, Ann, who cleverly camouflaged her Mad Dog
affiliation in a successful campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced now and and often spotted in public with Shrake, the
former first lady of Texas joked in Cartwright's book that she and
her artistic allies often entertained one another with embellished
and enhanced stories. But she argued that this was OK, ``because
everyone always had a different version of what happened the night
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaye Northcott, a former writer and editor at the ``The Texas
Observer'' and now an editor at the Star-Telegram, was admittedly a
bad Mad Dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be a good Mad Dog because I couldn't stay up all
night, which was a requirement,'' she says with a smile. ``I had
the right attitude, if not the stamina.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mad Dogs had a motto, ``Doing Indefinable Services to
Mankind,'' and a credo, ``Everything that is not a mystery is
guesswork.'' But as Cartwright admitted up front, their purpose was
a mite vague.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the official name itself was so fanciful that Milner
misspelled it (''Maddogs'') not only in his book but in the title
itself.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
