<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7110 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADDOGS-PART1-2500(4T     07-28 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADDOGS-PART1-2500(4TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
 (DUPLICATION ALERT: Story also
moving in ``a'' general news category) 
(EDS: This is Part 1 of a three-part series. Part 1 can stand
alone. Parts 2 and 3 will move on successive days.) 
MAD DOGS: THE POETS, JOURNALISTS AND MUSICIANS WHO BRANDED TEXAS
CULTURE (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &HT;    _
 &HT;    ``They were an interesting bunch. It was kind of like watching
fireworks.'' _ Texas author-historian A.C. Greene on the literary
``Mad Dogs.''
 &HT;    _ By MIKE COCHRAN c. 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ They worked hard, played harder. They drank too
much, slept too little, womanized incessantly, and frittered away
days and nights with mind-bending chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   They called themselves ``Mad Dogs,'' and they embraced the image
with the passion of mildly deranged journalists and musicians,
which they were.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this handful of writers and ``picker poets'' created a
significant body of work, influenced a generation of Texas artists,
and changed for all time the state's music and literary landscape.
</P>
<P>
   What's scary, and not remotely illogical, is that most of the
crew could have been wiped out 25 years ago on any number of
ill-conceived and drunken madcap excursions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A van wreck would have changed the culture of Texas forever,''
says University of Texas at Arlington journalism Professor David
McHam, one of the state's top educators and a keen observer of
Texas' creative talents over the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Stranger still, most of the renegade writers and
singer-songwriters are with us today, decidedly unrepentant but
reflective and productive, and less like mad dogs than miffed
puppies.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking Bud Shrake and Gary Cartwright, Jay Milner and
Billie Lee Brammer, Willie Nelson and Jerry Jeff Walker, and an
assortment of artists, writers, politicians, actors and oddballs
that gravitated to Austin in the Sixties and Seventies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud, Gary and all these people kind of made Austin the center
of Texas literature after the death of Dobie,'' says author and
historian A.C. Greene, at 75, a patriarch of sorts of Texas
letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were kind of a dangerous group, (but) they made a great
contribution to Texas literature.''
</P>
<P>
   The literary Larrys of the era, King and McMurtry, weren't
card-carrying Mad Dogs, but they easily qualified as pseudo-Dogs
even while living halfway across the country in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of expatriate Dan Jenkins, who fled to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously enough, Shrake and Jenkins were from Fort Worth and
Cartwright from nearby Arlington, and all three were Texas
Christian University grads, which should not be held against that
fine institution.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all Mad Dogs were writers, and not all writers
were Mad Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   It just seemed that way.
</P>
<P>
   King, from the tiny west central town of Putnam, worked and
played with the dogs and embodied their hedonistic philosophy. Even
today, he is a Mad Dog at heart. While many of his magazine
articles were masterpieces, King got himself rich with the Broadway
musical ``The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The prolific McMurtry, meanwhile, was drifting in and out of
Austin and socializing with a onetime roommate and longtime friend,
Billie Lee Brammer, perhaps the maddest of the Dogs, and, some say,
the most talented.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the semi-urbane Jenkins wasn't officially a Mad Dog,
but his chums were, and he escaped only by opting for Manhattan and
Elaine's over Austin and Scholz Garten.
</P>
<P>
   An honorary dog, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas Observer,'' for half a century the chronicler and
critic of all things cultural and political, was generous in its
praise of the Mad Dogs and Jay Milner's new memoir, ``Confessions
of a Maddog.'' But Austin writer Mark Smith points out that Milner
prompted a question he never addressed: Do these guys together form
a literary school or movement?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have said so before, but Milner's memoiristic
confessions argue a case for The Maddog School,'' Smith writes.
``Call them The Mesquite Beats: For what is a literary movement,
other than a simultaneous rising of a group of writers and artists
in a given time and place, colleagues who write in a similar manner
about common subjects, and who share similar values?''
</P>
<P>
   By this definition, the Mad Dogs qualify handily.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Confessions,'' Milner tells the story of a 1987 reunion
that reveals a lot about the Mad Dogs then and now. The occasion
was the inclusion of Jenkins, Shrake, Cartwright and King in the
``Walk of Stars'' along Austin's Sixth Street.
</P>
<P>
   The honorees gathered that evening in the lobby of the Driskill
Hotel to await limos ferrying them to a reception. Among those
present were Gary and Phyllis Cartwright; Dan and June Jenkins;
Pete Gent's wife, Jodi; Larry King and his longtime friend Mike
Blackman of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram; and Jerry Jeff's wife,
Susan Walker, the queen mother of Mad Dog Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed to the teeth in blue blazers and basic black dresses,
they were languishing around a sofa when a barefooted, scraggly
Austin relic staggered in the door and toppled at their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``His thousand-yard stare landed on Susan,'' Milner recounts,
``and he rose to his knees and whispered something incoherent into
her ear before a hotel employee scurried up and hustled him back
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The group watched silently as the drama unfolded. Then Jenkins
spoke. ``Ten years ago,'' he said, ``that's the fellow we'd have
been waiting for.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
