inclinations, to replay the most heartbreaking disasters of the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   First came the question of whether the hero could survive the
calamity _ whether, as in this case, the impact of an airplane
crash or, in an earlier age, a bullet to the brain. That was
followed by a national wake, with eulogies by pundits and friends.
</P>
<P>
   If memories of the 1960s had in any way dimmed, the networks and
cable channels resurrected the visual symbolism of the decade's
death watches.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers could relive the funeral processions of President John
F. Kennedy and Martin Luther King Jr., or stare again at the
picture of Robert Kennedy sprawled in a pool of his own blood on
the kitchen floor of a Los Angeles hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the images of horror, this was a week in which
the various meanings attributed to the 1960s collided.
</P>
<P>
   The week began not with another Kennedy family tragedy, but with
a remembrance of the first landing of men on the moon in 1969, a
feat that was one of President Kennedy's most enduring legacies.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the week, the myth of Camelot was ubiquitous _ a time
presumably full of promise, presided over by a man whose wit,
urbanity and ironic sensibility made him seem less conventionally
American than a citizen of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the week, it was possible to recall a
different 1960s. Friday was not only the occasion of the memorial
service for John F. Kennedy Jr. It was also the 30th anniversary of
Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   Television newscasts showed the clash of symbols that marked the
decade's confident beginning and its convulsive end.
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief glimpse of Robert McNamara, the former U.S.
defense secretary, leaving the service, followed by clips from the
movie version of Woodstock. On television, at least, the last
surviving members of the best and the brightest were meeting the
remnants of the counterculture and the anti-war movement.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone shared in the nostalgia for Camelot or Woodstock.
There was an undercurrent of resentment toward the extravagant TV
coverage of the Kennedys, past and present.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the anger was ideological, with conservatives objecting
to the idealization of a family and a decade whose values they had
been trying for 30 years to repel.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of the exasperation was generational. On talk radio,
people in their 20s or 30s voiced complaints that they had no
emotional connections to John F. Kennedy Jr., his father or the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   For people outside the United States, the attention paid to the
death of another Kennedy might have seemed narcissistic. The
upheavals of the 1960s were global, not exclusively American.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam was as much a home of the counterculture as was San
Francisco. The rebellions in Paris, Berlin, Mexico City and Prague
in 1968 were as significant as the anti-war demonstrations in
Berkeley or Boston.
</P>
<P>
   America may have been the epicenter of the political and
cultural earthquakes of the 1960s, but the aftershocks were felt
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that decade haunts many middle-aged Americans. They feel
stigmatized by the assassinations and by the carnage in Vietnam. In
mourning John F. Kennedy Jr., they were expressing their sadness
for a once innocent, now vanished era of youthful adventure and
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, then, the disparate images of President Kennedy playing
with his 3-year-old son, the moon landing and the festival at
Woodstock were not so jarring after all. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Richard Pells, a historian at the University of
Texas, is author of ``Not Like Us: How Europeans Have Loved, Hated,
and Transformed American Culture Since World War II.'' He
contributed this commentary to the International Herald Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
