<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTLAND-MUSEUM-ART-2     07-28 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-MUSEUM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCOTTISH STORY, TOLD BY THE OBJECTS THAT SHAPED IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURGH, Scotland _ The notion that Scotland is a more
beguiling place than the dark and rugged land it occupies has found
fitting expression in the alluring new Museum of Scotland. In a
modern building set on a hillside in Edinburgh's medieval old town,
the museum has a smoothly turned drum tower, a furrowed roof
terrace, slender windows and a sandstone exterior with the amber
flush of a sunset spreading across a Highland moor.
</P>
<P>
   Enter and you're in a luminous castle keep. Light from
discreetly placed skylights pours down sloping white walls into a
central atrium, indoor bridges span the lofty courtyard space and
staircases and narrow passageways disappear invitingly into walls.
It is a building of chanced-upon spaces that promise a series of
adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're object-driven,'' George Dalgleish, a curator, said,
explaining the collection of 10,000 art pieces, personal
belongings, tools and household items gathered to give visitors a
grasp on the Scotland beyond rockbound coasts, windswept cliffs and
baronial, ancestral piles.
</P>
<P>
   Where there are no objects to support the narrative, the story
is left untold. ``We don't want to recreate the past,'' Dalgleish
said. ``We want to give evidence of it and let people make up their
minds how it fits in.''
</P>
<P>
   The building is a testament to the communicability of inanimate
objects, he said. ``We're not trying to tell the entire history of
Scotland,'' he added. ``We didn't want to do this in a
heavy-handed, didactic way.''
</P>
<P>
   Built by the Anglo-Scottish architectural partnership of Gordon
Benson and Alan Forsyth, the museum speaks across the centuries to
the historic buildings surrounding it, capturing them and
effectively bringing them inside as additional objects on display.
Windows frame Greyfriars Church, a central location in Scots
history, where the National Covenant was signed, and the half-moon
battlements of Edinburgh Castle, the building that most symbolizes
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952 it was decided that Scotland needed a new building to
show off the largely unseen collections held by the National Museum
of Scottish Antiquities. But efforts to build it failed because of
inadequate financing and feuds over where the museum would go.
Today, it adjoins the Royal Scottish Museum, whose goal is to bring
the outside world to Scotland, while the new museum has taken on
the mission of presenting Scotland to the world.
</P>
<P>
   From the basement upward through five levels, the new museum
takes a loosely chronological trip from a time when most of what is
now Scotland lay under water, through the archaeology of early
settlers to the ``Kingdom of the Scots'' from 1100 to 1707, when
Scotland was an independent nation, and finally to modern times,
when the country played a role in international commerce and
industry, culture and science.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of objects serve as milestones. Among them are a rock
that is 2.9 billion years old from the Isle of South Uist, Viking
coins and jewelry, modern kitchen appliances, 17th-century pistols
from Dundee, communion cups from the Reformation, tattered battle
flags and 19th-century golf clubs from the land where the game
started. Bulking up through three of the levels is an 1861 Newcomen
engine that was used to pump water from coal mines in Ayrshire.
</P>
<P>
   Mundane objects deliberately outnumber the majestic. A majority
excite the imagination more than they please the eye, though some _
like the 12th-century chess pieces, the silver canteen of cutlery
given to Bonnie Prince Charlie on his 21st birthday in 1741 and a
shrine carried into the Battle of Bannockburn in 1314, when the
Scots defeated the English _ are stunningly beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   This is not prettified history. Sharing privilege of place are
police batons for beating Roman Catholic protesters, a 16th-century
guillotine, leather straps for disciplining students and a miner's
collar _ a grim reminder that feudalism persisted in the
countryside into the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years in the planning, the museum coincidentally opened in
November 1998, at a time when Scotland was gaining a degree of
freedom it had not experienced since union with England in 1707. A
principal reform instituted by Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain
has brought regional government back to Scotland for the first time
in nearly 300 years, and the new Scottish Parliament was opened by
Queen Elizabeth II on July 1 in Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Some people who favor outright independence for Scotland seized
on the museum's rich chronicling of Scottish achievement in the
centuries before union with England as proof that this land was
once a robust nation all by itself, and has the wherewithal to
become one again. Dalgleish said the curators were a little
surprised to find themselves in the midst of an ardent debate, but
they adjusted to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the very act of building this, we realized it's a way of
saying this place called Scotland existed,'' he said. ``It's a
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence-minded visitors were heartened to find inscribed on
a ground-floor wall the defiant words from the Declaration of
Arbroath of 1320: ``As long as 100 of us remain alive, we shall
never submit to the domination of the English.'' Linger by the
television screen that replays great moments in Scottish soccer,
and you'll note that the truly delirious moments are those when
Scots beat an English team.
</P>
<P>
   You will look in vain, however, for mention of William Wallace,
the Braveheart of Scottish lore and Hollywood embellishment. The
curators had no relics to anchor any of Wallace's deeds, so by
their own object-driven standards, they couldn't include him.
Nationalist politicians urged them to do so anyway, but they
resisted. ``You're in the hands of the collector and have to live
with the accidents of survival,'' Dalgleish said.
</P>
<P>
   To fill their 20th-century galleries, the curators asked Scots,
famous and unknown, to submit objects they thought best illustrated
their lives. In came, among other things, mobile phones, compact
disks, chewing gum and a Fender Stratocaster electric guitar
submitted by Blair, who was born in Scotland and once played in a
rock band.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   That many of these things would illustrate modern life in Boston
or Budapest or Bangkok was the point, a way of freeing Scotland
from its freighted myths and symbols and pointing out that it
shares characteristics with modern societies elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish diaspora, thought to number 90 million people,
helped perpetuate an idealized and sentimental version of life on
this thorny thistle of a land. There were sentimental expectations,
with poets creating a world of noble Highland fighters and painters
turning Scotland's treeless wilderness into landscapes of brooding
romanticism.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Scotland sets out to restore reality. Tens of
thousands of Scots lived in squalid slums and tenements in the
industrial age. Displays in the museum recognize this with
unsparing views of life in the Saltmarket district of Glasgow.
</P>
<P>
   A display case at the entrance to the 20th-century galleries
offers an entertaining summary of the totems most often associated
with the Scots: against a background wall of red tartan flocking
are mass-produced Scottish curios like Robert Burns mugs, porcelain
bagpipers, miniature busts of Sir Walter Scott, a ``Scotland
Forever'' pattern book and kilts, dirks and sporrans.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Connery was among the Scots who responded to the summons to
submit things that represented their homeland. A Scots nationalist,
he spoke at independence rallies during the recent elections to the
new Parliament. Because he started out as a milkman in Edinburgh,
he sent in a copy of the Treaty of Arbroath folded into a milk
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   G.J. Moonan of East Kilbride, Lanarkshire, made a contribution
that touched on less heroic Scottish behavior. He submitted a
bottle of Barr's Iron Bru, a popular soft drink that also enjoys
fame as an antidote to hangover. Moonan added a fond note. ``This
sweet nectar,'' he wrote, ``must have saved more lives on a Sunday
morning than the chicken pox vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is open seven days a week. Information: (011)
44-131-247-4219, or at www.nms.ac.uk/mos on the Web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
