<HEADLINE>
EDITORS OF SUSPENDED COLUMNIST DISCIPLINED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Two editors of suspended San Jose Mercury
News columnist Chris Nolan were themselves disciplined Tuesday,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan, who wrote the popular ``Talk Is Cheap'' Silicon Valley
gossip column for the paper, was suspended last week after a Wall
Street Journal story revealed she had privately invested in and
profited from the initial public offering of AutoWeb, a local
Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan said she had informed her immediate editors about the
investment early on.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources at the newspaper, city editor Burt
Robinson, Nolan's immediate supervisor, received a two-day
suspension over the incident. Peter Hillan, the paper's executive
business editor, received a letter of reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury spokeswoman Pat Thompson declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement last Wednesday, Mercury News executive editor
David Yarnold said Nolan had ``at a minimum, created the appearance
of a conflict of interest for herself and the Mercury News, and she
failed to exercise a reasonable level of professional
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   That announcement came after the Wall Street Journal reported
Nolan earned $9,000 after privately buying Autoweb.com stock at a
discount and later selling her shares for a profit when the company
went public.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Autoweb.com is a close friend of Nolan's
and offered her the stock through a legal ``friends and family''
offer not available to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury News' ethics policy says staffers shouldn't make
news decisions about companies in which they have a financial
interest, and advises business news staffers not to invest in local
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan said she had no comment on these recent developments,
except to say that ``the action of those concerned speaks for
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has caused considerable discussion in Silicon Valley
newsrooms over reporters' relationships to Internet companies, and
it has even sparked a Web site called ``Friends Supporting Chris
Nolan'' (www.fresher.com/ chris.htm).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
