<HEADER>
A7175 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     07-28 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE GADGETS FOR MACS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mac is back. Apple Computer Inc., which was nearly given up
for dead a year ago, has emerged as the most innovative and
aggressive personal computer maker in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has sold nearly 2 million colorful iMac computers in the
past 11 months, and it asserts that nearly half of those went to
first-time computer buyers or people who were returning to the Mac
after being seduced by cheaper but more complicated PCs based on
the dominant Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Apple filled the last gaping hole in its product line last week
at the Macworld trade show in New York, introducing a low-cost
portable iMac computer called the iBook. Particularly intriguing
was the iBook's optional Airport wireless networking system.
</P>
<P>
   But while the $1,599 iBook was clearly the Apple in everyone's
eye, a number of other Macintosh-related products on display added
to the festive and optimistic atmosphere of the show.
</P>
<P>
   XLR8 had two impressive new products. For owners of older
PowerPC-based Macs, including most Mac clones other than those made
by Motorola, XLR8's Mach Carrier G3 upgrades provide a relatively
easy way to tap into the power of the G3 chip without having to buy
a blue-and-white G3 Mac.
</P>
<P>
   It is an upgradeable upgrade, consisting of two pieces: a
plug-in Carrier card that has a zero-insertion force (zif) socket,
and a G3Z (zif-based) microprocessor card that plugs easily into
the socket. A Carrier card and 450-MHz G3Z processor costs $899.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best bargains at the show was another XLR8 product,
InterView, a $99 Universal Serial Bus (USB) cable and software
bundle that allows Mac users to create Quicktime digital video
clips from nearly any source, such as a camcorder or a video
cassette recorder (Www.xlr8.com).
</P>
<P>
   The bundle includes a full working version of Strata's VideoShop
4.5 professional video editing software, which normally sells for
more than $350.
</P>
<P>
   Another great bargain, if a 10-cent piece of plastic that sells
for $9.95 can be considered a bargain, is Macsense's iCatch, which
for lack of a better term is a mouse transmogrifier
(Www.macsensetech.com).
</P>
<P>
   The iCatch is a piece of molded translucent plastic (offered in
any of Apple's fruit colors) that clips on top of the horrible
round mouse that Apple now inflicts on all its desktop models. This
simple modification makes the mouse easier to use and reduces hand
fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft has an even better mouse for the Mac coming this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The company was demonstrating its Explorer optical sensing mouse
that connects to the USB port on Macs
(Www.microsoft.com/product/icatch.html). The $74.95 mouse will also
work with computers running Microsoft Windows.
</P>
<P>
   With its sleek silver design, exquisitely precise cursor
control, programmable control buttons and glowing red tail and
belly lights, this is the ``think different'' mouse Apple should
have invented, instead of the feeble little puck that has earned
the scorn of most serious Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also makes software, and it was offering peeks at its
Outlook Explorer 5.0 program for managing electronic mail.
Scheduled for release this fall, OE5 for the Mac has been
significantly improved, especially in using file attachments and
filtering junk mail. It is also free.
</P>
<P>
   I'm always leery of software that is marketed specifically for
the iMac, because the iMac uses the same operating system as any
other Macintosh. What are they going to do, issue the CD-ROM disks
in fruit-salad colors?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's new Word 98 special Edition for iMac iBook,
which Microsfot is offering only until Jan. 31, 2000, is actually a
good deal.
</P>
<P>
   For $99 (after a $30 mail-in rebate), the user gets the same Mac
Word 98 processing software that normally sells for $350, plus
5,000 clip-art images, templates and other goodiies. And, yes, it
works with all other Macs.
</P>
<P>
   Aladdin Systems, better known for the Stuffit utility program
used by nearly everyone who downloads Macintosh software from the
Internet, showed off a fun little $29.95 program called MacTicker
that places a customizable, scrolling stock ticker on the screen
(www.aladdinsys.com).
</P>
<P>
   The software requires an Internet connection, and the stock
quotes are delayed at least 15 minutes, but for those who want to
track their portfolios constantly, MacTicker is a clever hack.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive software at the show, however, was a
graphics arts program called Studio Artist, from Synthetik Software
Inc. Studio Artist ($249) uses technology derived from the study of
human brain functions to create what its developers call a graphics
synthesizer, in effect a smart assistant for painting, drawing and
manipulating all sorts of digital images, including video
(Www.synthetik.com).
</P>
<P>
   Canon and Epson showed off new multifunction peripherals for the
Mac. My favorite was the Epson Stylus Scan 2500, which will cost
$499 when it is shipped in October. The single USB device includes
a color ink-jet printer, a flatbed color scanner, and a color
digital copier, all in one relatively compact box that saves desk
space (Www.epson.com). Epson demonstrated a clever software
interface for the Stylus Scan that makes it easier to use than most
multifunction devices on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Many other intriguing products were on display at Macworld, but
in the end all were merely the supporting cast for the star of the
show, the iBook.
</P>
<P>
   Although the iBook prototypes on display weighed more than 7
pounds, Apple executives said they would get the weight down to
about 6.5 pounds by shedding extra metal needed in test models to
shield against electromagnetic radiation.
</P>
<P>
   The iBook is an impressive portable for its $1,599 price, and it
is hard to overstate the significance of its operional $499
``Airport'' wireless networking system. Some Mac fans at Macworld,
however, were miffed that it does not have some features found on
other Mac machines, like video output, a high-speed Firewire port,
an infrared port, or a PC card slot.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, this is a computer designed and priced for consumers,
not for business users, who would be better served by the more
expensive Powerbook G3 models.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement over the new computer overshadowed the fact that
there was relatively little other news from Apple. The company did
not reveal its master plan for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There were no new announcements regarding the blue-and-white G3
desktop Macintosh, no new colors or configurations for the iMac. On
the software side, Apple yawned out an announcement of Mac OS 9, an
interim operating system update between the current Mac OS 8.6 and
the radically revamped OS X (10), due next year.
</P>
<P>
   And that is perhaps the best indicator of Apple's recent
success: People have come to expect exciting news and innovative
products from the company, just like in the old days. Other PC
companies are rather colorless in comparison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
