<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-EARLY-ENGLISH-NYT     07-28 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EARLY-ENGLISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE ARCHIVE TO PRESERVE CENTURIES-OLD ENGLISH BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Texas, Md.)   (bl)  
 By RITA BEAMISH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six decades ago, the threat of Nazi book burnings and German
bombs spurred a project to preserve some of the earliest writings
in the English language on microfilm. Eugene Power, a Michigan
microfilm entrepreneur who already had begun photographing the
first books printed in English, was selected by the Rockefeller
Foundation and a scholarly organization to make microfilm versions
of treasured British collections.
</P>
<P>
   Only temporarily impeded when a German torpedo sank the ship
carrying his cameras, Power, over five years, preserved
centuries-old manuscripts and books in photographic form. The
printed works from the project became part of Power's early English
microfilm collection, available today for sale worldwide. Now, a
modern extension of the late Power's work is under way: creating an
online version of that same microfilm, which covers nearly 80
percent of all books printed between 1475 and 1700 in England or in
English.
</P>
<P>
   At the climate-controlled vaults that Power built in Ann Arbor
to house his microfilm, crews are working around the clock to scan
the collection, according to Bell &AMP; Howell Co., which purchased
Power's company, UMI, and renamed it Bell &AMP; Howell Information and
Learning.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to complete scanning of the 96,000 works _ 22
million pages on more than 4,500 reels of microfilm, each 100 feet
long _ by the end of the summer. ``It's making this material much
more available to scholars around the world,'' said Jeff Moyer, the
company's vice president of product management.
</P>
<P>
   The target market for Early English Books Online, as the project
is known, is libraries, most on college campuses, which for a fee
will be able to tap into the materials. A half-dozen schools have
already signed up.
</P>
<P>
   Some see a chance to ease the strain on space _ and on floor
beams _ from large, heavy microfilm cabinets. Others cite relief
from the eye-spinning tedium of temperamental microfilm readers _
``a fact of library life,'' said Dr. Richard Oram, head librarian
at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center at the University of
Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most appealing to scholars is the comprehensiveness of
the early English collection, coupled with the ability to search
the title citations and sort by author, date and subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It enables you to think up projects you couldn't have done
before,'' said Dr. Mary Fissell, associate professor of medical
history who viewed a demonstration at Johns Hopkins University.
``If you know you can do that kind of work, you're going to be more
broad-ranging.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Billings, director of general libraries for the
University of Texas, which purchased the collection for its
15-campus, 150,000-student system, said, ``The importance of it is
having access to a larger body of knowledge available to most users
wherever and whenever they need it.'' That is not the case with
microfilm, where a given reel can be used by only one person at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   The online page images, saved in the TIFF format, lack the feel
of dog-eared parchment, but there are research benefits. Margin
notes, printers' markings, typography, illustrations and other
historical markers all can be studied in works as varied as
Chaucer's ``Canterbury Tales,'' Nicholas Culpeper's ``English
Physician,'' King James' tirade against the evils of tobacco and
the Thomason compendium on the English Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to see how it really looked on the page,'' said Dr.
Tom Izbicki, collection development coordinator for the Milton S.
Eisenhower Library at Johns Hopkins. ``You can't get to the library
that has the one and only copy. I think it's going to have a lot of
utility for people.'' Johns Hopkins plans to have the online
collection up and running by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The service is not inexpensive. Permanent access to the online
collection begins at $93,000. For year-to-year access, fees range
from $12,000 to $19,000 depending on whether a library already has
Bell &AMP; Howell's microfilm. The company expects to enlist between
150 and 250 libraries and recoup its development costs in three or
four years, Moyer said. The early English collection is a fraction
of the company's 5.5 billion-page microfilm archive that includes
newspapers, dissertations and other scholarly materials _ all
scheduled for online access in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a niche market,'' said Marta Nichols, a financial equity
analyst for Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``But if you position
yourself to be the primary content provider of archived information
going back hundreds of years, that's a lasting business model.
There will always be a demand for that information. If Bell &AMP;
Howell hadn't done it, at some point someone would have come along
and been able to digitize that information.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other, less-ambitious scanning efforts, the English
collection is ideal for Web-adept students who increasingly want to
work online, said Maureen Sullivan, president of the Association of
College and Research Libraries. ``The students want to hit a few
key strokes and have it available,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that easy, however, for Catherine Belsey, an English
literature professor at Cardiff University in Wales, where Early
English Books Online is on trial. After three hours of
unsuccessfully trying to call up books from Shakespearean times,
she said she wanted to hurl her computer ``at the proprietors of
EEBO or any passing stranger.'' Her colleague, Professor David
Skilton, had better luck and speculated that Dr. Belsey's office
computer might have been part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Even with collections like the EEBO going online, humble
microfilm isn't expected to lose its place as a reliable
preservation tool, much as libraries themselves retain a role in
the electronic world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly we're understanding that the library's place will
continue,'' Ms. Sullivan said. ``But it will be transformed so that
the information and resources will be available in a variety of
formats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
