<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BOHEMIAN-CLUB-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTABLES SIGHTED AT BOHEMIAN RETREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By B.W. ROSE   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ The two-week encampment of rich and
powerful newsmakers at the Bohemian Grove is winding down with
tales of sightings of power brokers, presidential contenders and
entertainment stars.
</P>
<P>
   Although officials at the Bohemian Club routinely decline to
affirm attendance at the exclusive all-male gathering, reports
abound that grove visitors included former President George Bush,
along with his increasingly famous sons, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
and Florida Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Reliable reports also had former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger, former House Speaker Newt Gingrich and former Gen. Colin
Powell attending some portions of the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Also spotted, according to camp insiders, were John
Ratzenberger, the bar-dwelling postman on the television sitcom
``Cheers,'' and big-screen actor Danny Glover.
</P>
<P>
   The annual event at the secluded 2,700-acre grove near the
Russian River in Monte Rio is attracting a measure of attention
from local residents hoping to glimpse celebrities emerging from
their private jets at the Sonoma County airport or driving by in a
limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations at the century-old men's club are rustic, with
wooden cabins under the redwood trees. Meals and entertainment,
however, are anything but modest. Gourmet meals are served and
entertainment is provided by the stars. Guests take turns appearing
in plays and musicals often written just before they are performed.
</P>
<P>
   Protests have been held outside the grove's gates in the past,
particularly during the Republican White House years, to draw
attention to issues ranging from nuclear weapons to abortion that
activists suspected were discussed by policy-makers in secret at
the grove.
</P>
<P>
   The official encampment program of events included speeches by
author and columnist David Broder; Richard Butler, the chief United
Nations arms inspector in Iraq; Charles Murray, controversial
author on race issues and fellow at the American Enterprise
Institute; and Frank Popoff, chairman of Dow Chemical. Also
scheduled to speak were JFK document expert Kenneth Rendell, NBC
sportscaster Roger Maltbie, and Mark Smith, chief executive of the
California HealthCare Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The event ends Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   B.W. Rose writes for The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
