<SLUG> BC-INHERIT-FIGHTS-600(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND THE MEEK SHALL INHERIT NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Minn.)   (EDS: 3rd take includes 575-wd sidebar on tips for dividing family
heirlooms.)  
(See also INHERIT-WORTH) 
(js) 
 By NEAL KARLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year after his father died in Florida, Richard Nelson, 51, can
finally talk about what he calls ``the war of the glockenspiel,''
when Nelson, an organizational consultant, and his younger brother,
Larry, battled for months over the instrument their father played
in the Shriner drum corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought like Cain and Abel over that glockenspiel, because
it represented the hours we both waited for him to come around the
corner in Shriner parades playing `When the Saints Go Marching In,'
'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   They had heated arguments over it whenever they saw each other.
``And we didn't see each other very much, because we were both so
mad that we'd always end up yelling about it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Nelson received the glockenspiel, after his mother
brokered a deal to stop the squabbling. ``Larry got visitation
rights,'' he said, ``as well as Dad's complete Spike Jones record
collection and the family's home movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Familial fights like the Nelsons' are ripping apart many a
middle-class clan. Six years ago, economists predicted that the
largest intergenerational transfer of wealth in history _
approximately $12 trillion _ would take place from then until
around 2020 as the security-minded Depression generation died off
and left its money and its carved mahogany bedroom suites,
split-level ranch houses, family china, grandfather clocks and
moldering photographs to its baby boom children, a generation
weaned on irony, credit cards and broken marriages. (The bull
market since 1994 may well have swelled the World War II
generation's stock portfolios and retirement fund accounts even
further.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if it's a lot or a little money,'' said Dr.
Henry F. Smith, a psychoanalyst affiliated with the Harvard Medical
School. ``Money is a way to quantify love. And both anticipating
and receiving the inheritance intensifies both the loving and
hating aspects of relationships between child and parent, and
sibling and sibling.'' That goes double when what is being
inherited is valuable and tangible: the ocean-front home in the
Hamptons, the collection of Art Deco furniture, even the drawer
full of Bakelite jewelry or Mother's old mink coat.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbling will be intensified by other problems along the
way. The youngest boomer is now 35 and the oldest 53. Their parents
are living ever longer. Some children could be receiving Social
Security before they see a penny of inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in the benchmark statistical study presented in 1994
by the economists Robert Avery and Michael Rendall, most of the
wealth turns out to be headed for the pockets of only the few.
According to the Avery-Rendall study, one-third of the money will
go to 1 percent of the baby boomers, who will receive about $1.6
million apiece. Another third, representing an average bequest of
$336,000, will go to the next 9 percent. The final slice, divided
by the remaining 90 percent of the generation, will run about
$40,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   For those in the top bracket, ``$1.6 million is worth fighting
about,'' said Kathryn A. Johnson, chairwoman of an American Bar
Association committee on trusts and estates and a lawyer in private
practice in San Francisco. She added, ``I think there is a big
future in trust and estate litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bulk of the population receiving $40,000, she said,
would be ill-advised to go to court. She continued, ``If they came
in my office fighting over $40,000 I'd have to question them about
why they were doing this, if they realized legal fees could eat
everything up, and try and talk them into family mediation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Besides, for most baby boomers, $40,000 is a drop in the bucket.
``There's a good chance baby boomers will blow it,'' said Robert H.
Frank, the Goldwin Smith professor of economics, ethics and public
policy at Cornell University and author of ``Luxury Fever: Why
Money Fails to Satisfy in an Era of Excess'' (Free Press, 1999;
$25). ``Children at the leading edge of the baby boom had their
habits forged in the 1970s, when if you saved you were considered a
chump. Now, a lot of baby boomer families are in deep debt, and a
lot of those inheritances will be fully accounted for before they
get it in the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   While some baby boomers are willing to do battle over a
glockenspiel, a fairly large proportion lack sentimentality toward
their parents' things, said Helaine Fendelman of Scarsdale, N.Y.,
co-host of the PBS program ``Treasures in Your Attic'' and one of
the country's leading fine-arts appraisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers are much less interested in Eames or traditional
18th- and 19th-century furniture or antiques,'' she said. ``They
want flashy things from their own youth like Barbie dolls or
baseball cards, but they want cash for their parents' most
cherished items.''
</P>
<P>
   That lack of sentimentality is compounded when there is another
generational remove, Ms. Johnson said. That is, the children will
tussle over who got the Baccarat; the grandchildren just want the
money. The fighting continues, however, since inheritance is like a
quadratic equation being solved for the value of love.
</P>
<P>
   And woe to the families left with an estate but no will. Six
years ago, Pete Jakowski, 46, a San Francisco artist from a family
he describes as ``mediocre middle class, between the lower middle
and just plain middle class,'' learned that his younger brother had
been killed while riding in a friend's car. His brother had left no
will.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I was literally shopping for caskets with my 76-year-old
mother,'' Jakowski said, ``my sister was cleaning out his house _
his furniture, car, stereo, keyboard and everything else of value.
I was still in shock, and she and her husband were doing double
time, completely emptying his place within 48 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakowski said his sister later gave him keys to a storage locker
and told him to keep anything he wanted. ``All that was in there
was his clothes, none of which fit me but which I held on to
because it's all I have left of him,'' he said. ``I come from a
churchgoing family where you'd think this would never happen, and
I'm here to tell you it does.''
</P>
<P>
   When telephoned about the contretemps, Jakowski's sister refused
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there is a will, a vague phrase like ``and the contents
of the house will be divided equitably among the surviving
children'' can lead to years of arguments over who got stuck with
the chipped majolica and who really wanted the Stickley breakfront.
Many of the bad vibes emanate from how American society has changed
since Ozzie and Harriet were considered the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started practicing law 39 years ago, divorce was
a rarity,'' Samuel Kaplan, a prominent Minneapolis business lawyer,
said. ``You only drew up antenuptial agreements when an 82-year-old
was getting married. There might have been unhappiness when the
head of the family died, but in almost every instance, those
differences were worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   No more. ``Now, divorce is common,'' Kaplan said, ``and once the
patriarch or matriarch who held the family together is gone, the
amount of fighting between second husbands or wives who want their
children treated appropriately can get quite brutal. The anger is
astounding, especially when one sibling devoted their own life to
caring for their parent at the end, while the others were gone.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the executors _ sometimes an oldest or
most-trusted child (a position of honor that can lead to more
family friction), otherwise a banker, lawyer or family adviser.
Perhaps the shrillest battle over executors this decade concerned
the estate of Joe Robbie, a Miami businessman and owner of the
Miami Dolphins who named three of his children as trustees of his
estate without informing his six other children they wouldn't have
direct control of their inheritance. After his death in 1990, a
five-year battle was waged in court for control of the $72 million
estate, with the three trustees ultimately dismissing the oldest
son from the family businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the money, childhood notions of fairness seem to lurk
behind many siblings' anger.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid battles over who gets what, Morris Everett, 58, the
owner of one of the largest accumulation of movie posters in the
world, has chosen to get rid of his collection before he dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be more of a burden to my family than an asset to
pass it on,'' he said of his 200,000-piece collection, worth $8
million to $10 million and housed in Cleveland. ``It represents
dollar signs for my son and daughter, so it's my job to maximize
the dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the emotional investment he made in a hobby that
he started in 1961 with a lobby card for ``Gunga Din'' that he
bought for 50 cents? ``The joy of collecting is in the discovery,''
Everett said. ``The worst thing to do is get handed a great
collection. To just lay on my children this massive responsibility
would be unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
