<P>
   TASTE OF INDIA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ India's food, like that of the world's, is a result of
wars, trading and conquering civilizations. But those fractious
events, and the resulting fractious population of Hindus, Muslims,
Christians, Buddhists and Sikhs, as well as some Jews, have melded
in a cuisine that is like no other. By BEVERLY BUNDY. Story will
move in ``d'' food and dining category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ I wasn't born in Louisiana, don't have any relatives
living there that I know of, can't speak a lick of French. I don't
even eat french fries very often. I once tried to fix my daughter's
hair in a French braid, but she said it didn't look right. I
thought it was fine. But there is a spiritual connection between me
and the food that is consumed under the spreading oaks and sagging
Spanish moss of southern Louisiana. It is Cajun food _ country
cooking with a little extra spice and ingenuity. By ART CHAPMAN.
Story will move in ``d'' food and dining category &QL; 
 &QL;
