<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INHERIT-FIGHTS-3RDTAK     07-28 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INHERIT-FIGHTS-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: be unfair.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not every family ends up fighting over stuff. Some siblings even
meet while their parents are alive and divide things up for later.
``You can horse trade,'' said Steven Greenberg, owner of a computer
company called Designstein in Minneapolis, who used this system
with his two siblings. ``I'd say, `I'll trade you my next two picks
for mom's glass sugar bowl' _ and the system worked.''
</P>
<P>
   But baby boomers _ conspicuous consumers _ may not have any room
left in their houses for the odd parental keepsake. And the items
to be inherited have to be to their taste. The Nelson brothers who
warred over their father's glockenspiel were not at all interested
in his white polyester pants. ``My mother begged me to take a
number of sentimental things, which I did out of respect,'' Nelson
said. ``But they never got out of the car before they went to
Goodwill.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no squabbling over their father's 50 bowling trophies,
which their mother insisted they have. ``To us they symbolized all
the time he didn't spend with us,'' he said. ``After we were done
grieving, Larry and I took great pleasure in throwing them into the
dumpster one by one.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, it's the baby boomer who wants to preserve
the past. Art Simon, 40, an assistant professor of film studies at
New Jersey's Montclair State University, refused to let his father
sell the five-foot-tall wood-block printing press from the 1940s
that once made window signs announcing sales in the family's
clothing store in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably only worth a couple hundred dollars, if I could
even find someone to buy it,'' Simon said. ``But it was part of my
family's history.''
</P>
<P>
   When his father died in 1996, Simon refused to put the printing
press in the family's estate sale. Instead, he drove cross-country
with the thing in the back of his car. ``Now it's in storage,'' he
said, ``just like my dad had it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a sentiment beyond dollars and cents that Ms. Fendelman,
the appraiser, would applaud. ``Whether you get an objet, or objet
d'art, consider yourself lucky,'' she said. She tells clients,
``The one thing no one can take from you is your memories.''
</P>
<P>
   (SIDEBAR BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FOR DIVIDING FAMILY HEIRLOOMS
</P>
<P>
   Settling which family members receive which family treasures is,
like anything important, best done yesterday, worst done tomorrow
and, if not done yet, should be done today.
</P>
<P>
   Some tips for the children:
</P>
<P>
   _ If parents are still alive, gather the siblings with them to
discuss what to do when they die and _ if not the specifics of
their assets, the mechanism by which those assets will be
distributed. ``Sex is pretty easy to talk about these days,'' Dr.
Henry F. Smith, a psychoanalyst in Cambridge, Mass., said. ``But
money is taboo.'' It will take effort to overcome everyone's
reticence, but a candid discussion will make things easier later.
</P>
<P>
   _ Failing that, if a parent dies without leaving a clear
indication of who gets what, hold a draft. Gather all the siblings
in one room with every item to be divided up. Any gift given by a
child to a parent automatically reverts to that sibling. Then
proceed down the line from oldest to youngest, with the children
taking turns putting Post-it notes on items they are claiming.
Prepare to horse trade.
</P>
<P>
   _ Even if there is little or no value to an estate, make sure
parents and siblings are aware of the one item that means the most
to you. ``Be generous of spirit,'' said Mike Veeck, one of nine
children of Bill Veeck, the Baseball Hall of Fame team owner and
promoter who died in 1986 leaving little money but a lifetime of
good karma. Mike Veeck wanted an oil portrait showing his father
sitting in a bar. So did some of the other children. ``But I'm from
Chicago,'' he said, ``so I called up mom and fixed it, like a
closed election.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tips for the parents:
</P>
<P>
   _ Helaine Fendelman, a fine-arts appraiser, advises parents to
learn the value of items, from abandoned G.I. Joe dolls to
fireplace andirons, and if they have any chance of being worth
something. ``A lot of parents leave messes for their children,''
she said. ``And that's not a very nice thing to do when they're
dealing with the loss of a parent.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Take an extension course in estate planning that goes beyond
mere dollars. Ann Barrash, 75, a Dubuque, Iowa, mother of six,
attended a special class for women sponsored by the American
Association of Retired Persons at Iowa State. ``I was advised that
every child would be fighting over this and that after we were
gone,'' she said, so she and her husband, Meyer, 76, a retired
physician, made a list of every item they owned, circulated it
among the kids, and made the children prioritize their choices.
``It takes a long time but it really worked,'' she said, ``because
we didn't decide for them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have an estate large enough to be subject to the estate
tax _ any amount above $650,000 for one person or $1.3 million for
a married couple _ then before you die or become incapacitated you
should hire an estate lawyer to work out what to do. An estate
lawyer can show you ways to combine charitable gifts and insurance,
for example, to pass on more to heirs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Serious collections may be sold now and money passed on to the
children. If the collection remains intact, leave detailed
instructions on how it should be disposed of and through which
experts, so the children will not have to hold a fire sale.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give items to children now, up to the $10,000 tax-free limit a
year per parent. If a daughter needs a dining room table today, why
wait?
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a will. And include every single thing you own in it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Neal Karlen
</P>
</TEXT>
