<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INHERIT-WORTH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE CHINA SWANS AND CELERY DISHES JUST HAVE TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also INHERIT-FIGHTS) 
(js) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you've inherited a Matisse, you probably know what
to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you've been left two cardboard cartons full of cut
glass ashtrays and celery dishes? A vintage 1947 Lionel train set?
A Russian sable _ with only a small tear under the arm?
</P>
<P>
   How do you get rid of this stuff _ and, you hope, realize its
full worth?
</P>
<P>
   At first, it may strike you as easy: just call up that
antique-dealer friend, the one who's always telling you how much
money she'll give you if you ever decide to part with your
great-aunt's possessions.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly she isn't returning your calls. Or when she does,
she wants to give you $10 a boxload of crystal. You visit the
nearby consignment shops, but they take 50 percent, and you see the
dust motes gathering behind the Waterford decanters they already
have. (And yours isn't even Waterford.)
</P>
<P>
   The experts _ appraisers and estate lawyers _ say there are two
tried-and-true ways to get rid of a lot of stuff you don't want:
auctions and house sales.
</P>
<P>
   Don't hold your own house or estate sale unless you really know
what you're doing. It's a lot of work to price all the objects, and
do you really know what they're worth? Generally speaking, it's
better to let a qualified house-sale company hire the necessary
staff, unpack and price the stuff, sell it and, perhaps most
important, get rid of the leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   But which approach to select?
</P>
<P>
   House Sales
</P>
<P>
   _ First you need a house. (Co-op boards frown on apartment sales
because of the traffic; they really don't like strangers wandering
around the halls.) It's better if it's the house of the person who
died, rather than your own, because if you're going to be hauling
the stuff around, you may as well move it all directly to an
auction house. And the more charming and classy the home, the more
money you'll get for the items, said Joneen Connor, the proprietor
of Serendipity Estate Sales in Fairfield, Conn., a business that
arranges house sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many people, part of the allure is the magical mystery
tour they get of the house,'' she said. ``They love poking in the
closets, seeing everything.''
</P>
<P>
   At one house sale in Westbrook, Conn., at a gorgeous 1760
Georgian mansion, cheap newish white china swans that cost about
$10 each were selling for $125, strictly because they were owned by
the well-known antiques collector who had owned the house _ and who
had just passed away. At a sale at Castle Howard in England, ripped
draperies went for more than $1,000 _ because they came from a
castle.
</P>
<P>
   But those may be exceptions. At your run-of-the-mill estate
sale, you get a lot of cheap people who will pick up an oil
painting marked $3 and offer $2 (and then put it down, and go
peeking in the closets).
</P>
<P>
   And not every house is chosen. Most house-sale professionals set
a minimum: Ms. Connor usually likes to see between $8,000 and
$10,000 worth of objects. They can be almost anything; a recent
estate sale in Darien, Conn., advertised ``a former milliners'
cache of vintage hats,'' hat blocks, Depression glass, iron patio
chairs, an old violin and a lawn mower, among dozens of things.
</P>
<P>
   One of the advantages of a house sale is that you can get rid of
items that few self-respecting auctioneers would accept: everything
from the whistling tea kettle to old tires in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   One of the disadvantages is that the house becomes a circus,
with staff members coming and going, followed by hordes of
customers who leave ruts in the lawn and line up outside hours
before the doors open, clutching their admittance numbers and
getting into arguments about who shoved whom.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, estate-sales companies take a percentage of the gross
sales; the average seems to be 25 percent. This figure usually
includes paying all the staff, but some companies charge extra for
the advertising. So, be sure to check.
</P>
<P>
   House-sales specialists don't always advertise in the Yellow
Pages, but try scanning the listings under ``Tag Sale Services.''
Look in your local newspaper or those shopping gazettes in the
supermarket for upcoming house sales, and call the people who are
holding them.
</P>
<P>
   But Helaine Fendelman, who holds house sales in the suburbs
north of New York, said that she gets 99 percent of her customers
through word of mouth. So, check with your friends, too.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Auctions
</P>
<P>
   _ Now, it's clear that neither Sotheby's nor Christie's is going
to be rushing to take those Lionel trains off your hands. Or the
mink. But there are plenty of auction houses that will, especially
if they come with a house full of other once-cherished possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Manhattan, the Tepper Gallery, an auction house on East
25th Street, said it would take those two cartons of cut glass _
but you'd have to bring them in yourself if that's all you have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd take them _ but it's not exactly what I'm looking for,''
Kenneth Hutter, an owner, said. What is he looking for? ``Big
estates with lots of Picassos.'' Fine, but he'd still take the cut
glass.
</P>
<P>
   He'd even send an appraiser to look at your newly inherited
objects. But only if you have an address he respects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say you live at 960 Fifth Avenue, I'd probably go,''
Hutter said. ``Anything between 59th and 96th Street we might go to
see. But if you call from East Ozone Park, we might tell you to
send a picture! We're not going out to look at one slant-front desk
that's probably only 40 or 50 years old, even if you think it's an
antique.''
</P>
<P>
   In the country, there are dozens of auction houses that would be
happy to clean out your house _ but most of them wouldn't do so if
they thought that you'd already had a house sale. They'd think the
house had been ``picked.'' Check the telephone book, or look in
Antiques and the Arts Weekly, which lists upcoming local auctions
throughout the Northeast by date, on page 66. (House sales appear
in the pages before that.) Information: (203) 426-3141 or
www.thebee.com.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of an auction is that you get rid of the stuff,
and with a lot of people bidding against each other, you often get
pretty fair prices. There are no ``backsies''; it's difficult to
take anything back, so make sure the relatives have had their pick
_ or tell them to go and bid. (The only way you would get anything
back is if you were to leave a reserve on the best of the items.
But most small-time auctioneers won't accept reserves, so figure
this in when you pick your auctioneer. Big-name auctioneers pick
and choose; they won't take the train sets or the mink, for sure.)
</P>
<P>
   The disadvantage is that you can't control the prices. (Oriental
rug dealers, for example, tend to bid as a team and then conduct
their own auction out in the parking lot later. Faced with such a
cabal, the average customer usually doesn't bid, or drops out
quickly _ which is the whole strategy behind the rings.) Even if
there's no ring of dealers trying to keep prices down, you may hit
a bad day: a snowstorm or a holiday or a night when there's a
bigger auction somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Auctioneers usually take between 15 percent and 20 percent of
the total income from a sale. For their percentage, they run ads
and hold exhibitions. In the country, they usually don't charge to
pick up possessions if there are enough of them. In the city, they
usually do, Hutter said.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the experts say you probably want to choose a method
of liquidation that leaves you with nothing but the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can try selling the stuff off through Ebay or by driving
it around to a lot of dealers,'' said Robert M. Kneeland, a retired
Connecticut antiques dealer, who said he spends more and more time
advising friends on how to clear their attics of things they have
inherited. ``But getting rid of it piecemeal like that can take you
the rest of your life. We all have better things to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
