<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING YOUR OLD SLIDES INTO DIGITAL IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have hundreds of old 35-mm slides in carousels. Is there a
way to convert them on my computer myself so i can have electronic
copies or send them to friends in e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you have plenty of time and want to invest in a scanner
for your computer, you can convert your slides to a digital format
like JPEG. Then they can easily be archived or sent as e-mail
attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Scanners, which translate photos into digital images, come in
many different models and vary greatly in quality. Prices range
from under $100 to several thousand dollars. If you're scanning
slides, you'll need to get a model that can handle transparencies.
Some scanners are made especially for slides. Most come with basic
image editing software and instructions to get you started.
</P>
<P>
   Once you begin to scan your pictures, you may run into a problem
of storage room. Image files generally take up more space than text
files, and you may find your hard drive filling up fast.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to get an external hard drive or a Zip drive to
store the files, or you could invest in a CD-ROM recorder, which
will let you copy the images. Once you have a CD recorder, you can
also make copies of some or all of your collection to give to
friends.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide that you don't want to convert the slides
yourself, it's usually possible to find a graphics service to do
the work for you.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7251 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MONKEY-GAME-NYT &LR;      07-28 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MONKEY-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART SIMIANS RUN AMOK IN APE ESCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Human beings and monkeys have two things in common: good
hand-eye coordination and joysticks. Both species are using the
former to make great progress with the latter.
</P>
<P>
   For people, the latest challenge is Ape Escape, the first video
game to use fully all 12 buttons and both thumb-size joysticks on
Sony's Playstation controller.
</P>
<P>
   The premise: Doddering professor invents two highly dangerous
devices _ a time machine and a bowl-shape metal helmet for
enhancing monkey intelligence (you can tell that this device is
incredibly advanced because it has a police light on top).
</P>
<P>
   Before either device is tested, a sly little simian escapes from
the local amusement park, steals the helmet, turns into a mad
monkey genius and fits hundreds of his monkey friends with these
brain-boosting colanders. They hijack the time machine, determined
to change history so monkeys will rule the world. (Sony has
dispensed with the zoological distinction between monkeys and apes
for the sake of a great title.)
</P>
<P>
   Your mission: go back in time and, with both thumbs and index
fingers, use a series of gadgets to recapture the monkeys and make
history safe for homo sapiens.
</P>
<P>
   The manual dexterity required is nontrivial. In general, you
control movement with your thumb on the left joystick, camera
angles with the left buttons, jumping and gadget selection with the
right buttons and gadget use with your other thumb on the right
joystick.
</P>
<P>
   To bag a monkey, you use the left joystick to chase it down
while swinging a stun club with the right joystick. Once the
creature is immobilized, you quickly switch from the stun club to a
handheld monkey net, using the right buttons, and maneuver the net,
using the right joystick, to nab the monkey before it snaps out of
its split-second torpor.
</P>
<P>
   But preteens with Playstations are not the only primate
population grappling with new joystick techniques. At the Sonny
Carter Life Science Laboratory at Georgia State University, monkeys
and apes are also getting a chance to play video games. For more
than a decade, researchers at Georgia State have been conducting
NASA-financed research on the ability of rhesus monkeys and
chimpanzees to use off-the-shelf joysticks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to the literature, and contrary to a number of
reasons why they shouldn't have learned, they did learn, and they
learned really quickly,'' said Dr. David Washburn, who has
published studies using a group of 10 rhesus monkeys who spend
their days selecting from a menu of simple computer games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done the concentration game, the memory game where you
turn over a bunch of cards, except in this case the cards are
computer generated,'' Washburn said. ``They've done two-dimensional
maze things that look a lot like Pac-Man.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, our primate cousins love video games. Left to
their own devices, they are happy to kill time chasing dots of
light across a screen, even when they're not rewarded with food.
``We have a chimpanzee who's been known to call up the task of
running mazes from the menu and worked on them 20, 30 minutes just
for the sheer joy of working on novel mazes,'' said Dr. Duane
Rumbaugh, a professor of psychology who supervises the joystick
studies.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will they play, but they can be trained to get better.
``We have training programs that are very simple that teach them
what happens when they move the joystick, and they have to do more
demanding things all the time,'' Rumbaugh said. At each milestone,
they're rewarded, often with an interesting visual display or a
sound that lets them know they've done a good job. ``So in a
stepwise manner,'' Rumbaugh said, ``they finally get very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is interesting because video games for people work the
same way. The first level of Ape Escape, for instance, is very
easy. None of the monkeys challenge or attack you, or shoot or
throw things, as they do later in the game. All you have to do is
get used to roaming around and learn how to use the stun club and
the net. After a few minutes, you've bagged all the monkeys, and
there is a flash of light around your character, Spike, as he jumps
up and yells, ``Yes!'' (along with an interesting visual display
and a sound to let you know you've done a good job).
</P>
<P>
   From there, you move on to a training room where you can master
your next gadget before moving on to the next level. Thus, in a
stepwise manner, even minimally literate youngsters can get very
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised at how quickly the 6-, 7- and 8-year-olds
were picking up the game,'' said Ami Blair, 31, a brand manager at
Sony who conducted extensive focus tests with kids who played Ape
Escape in groups of 10 (10 seems to be the magic number for monkeys
and grade-schoolers alike). After they had played the game for
eight hours straight, she said, ``they were having a much easier
time than I was, and I knew exactly what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Georgia State primate lab, Washburn has also been
outpaced by his test group. ``CNN picked up on the monkey work
about five years ago,'' he said. ``We had published a paper showing
that if you give them a task where the monkeys have to shoot at a
moving target, and then you put both monkeys on the same screen so
that they're competing, they change their behavior, reflecting the
fact that they're competing. And so in a CNN interview, in front of
the world, I had the dubious pleasure of saying, `And when I
compete against the monkeys, I lose.'''
</P>
<P>
   But then, Washburn is also over 30. One wonders how the Georgia
State monkeys would fare against the Ape Escape focus group.
Monkeys against first graders: may the best primate win. ``We've
actually had to do that,'' Washburn said. ``With things that
require quick reaction, we've had to use kids to compete with the
monkeys. Six-year-olds, plus or minus two years. The monkeys still
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait until the monkeys get T-1 lines. On-line gamers, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   Ape Escape; published by Sony for the Playstation; $44.95; for
all ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
