<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRANSLATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWARD BETTER COMMUNICATION ACROSS THE LANGUAGE BARRIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Members of the jet set, take note: Scientists have created
speech-synthesizer technology that translates spoken words from one
language into another, even when the speaker and listener are on
opposite sides of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   The technology was tested last week during an all-day video
conference that spanned six countries. In the United States, a
technologist at Carnegie Mellon University planned a hypothetical
trip to Japan by talking to technologists there without speaking a
word of Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese experienced the whole conversation in their native
tongue. Representatives from laboratories in Germany, Italy, France
and Korea also participated.
</P>
<P>
   But the scientists did not simply hear themselves talk. They
also tested, in separate demonstrations, what they call ``face
translation,'' where the faces of the speakers were morphed by
applying computer animation to the speakers' eyes and lips on a
static photograph of their faces. People at Carnegie Mellon, for
example, saw the lips of their Japanese counterparts move as if
they were speaking English, not Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked beautifully,'' said Dr. Alex Waibel, acting chairman
of the Consortium for Speech Translation Advanced Research, or
C-STAR (www.c-star.org). ``Some of it still looks a little goofy,
but that is a detail we can smooth out.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations were the culmination of nearly a decade of
work by C-STAR, which showed in 1991 that computers could translate
already specified sets of words. Since then, the group has worked
toward designing a system that can process casual speech. It has
created an intermediary computer language called interlingua that
can recognize words spoken in one of six languages, filter out
interruptions and turn them into short commands.
</P>
<P>
   At the demonstration, for example, the statement, ``OK, I'd like
to book a tour in Kyoto, please,'' was invisibly translated into
terse computer code, which was then translated into a Japanese
sentence that was spoken by a computerized speech synthesizer and
heard in Japan after a lag of several seconds.
</P>
<P>
   If the face-translation technology had also been included with
that test, scientists said, the synthesized voice would have been
synchronized with the animated movement of the English speakers'
lips.
</P>
<P>
   The speech-synthesis technology is already being used in a
wearable gadget for tourists that C-STAR hopes will become a
commercial product: a hand-held computer that provides geographical
directions and translates words from, say, a box-office operator in
Germany into something that can be read or heard by the person
wearing it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that C-STAR's technology can substitute for actually
learning another language, Waibel said. But, he added, ``it's good
to have some training wheels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
