<HEADLINE>
A PLACE FOR JOHN CARTERS AROUND THE WORLD TO FIND ONE ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla.)   (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago in Australia, back when the World Wide Web had
only a few strands, a computer consultant and grandfather in
Melbourne named John Carter received a message on Fidonet, a public
bulletin board, intended for a John Carter who lived in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   As the Internet grew, the Australian John Carter searched for
the South African John Carter and found a lot of other John Carters
in the process, via search engines like whowhere.com and Internet
Address Finder.
</P>
<P>
   So the John Carter home page, NetSmart John Carters,
(members.tripod.com/jcarter/jcwww.html) was born. Carter sent
e-mail messages to all the other John Carters he could find and
posted links to their home pages, when available, on his site.
</P>
<P>
   He also presented some of the replies he received, which begin
with salutations like ``Hi John, What a great name you have!'' and
``By gorrah, annudder one!''
</P>
<P>
   There's a story from John Robert Carter, an Australian living in
England, who visited a cafe there with the name ``John R. Carter''
printed in large letters out front. After a little discussion with
the owner, he wrote, ``it turned out that we were BOTH called John
ROBERT Carter, and that his birthday was the same date as mine, and
he was exactly 30 years older than me! Strangely, we didn't really
get on. He overcharged me for my cup of tea. So what's in a name?''
</P>
<P>
   And John Carter of St. Petersburg, Fla., wrote: ``In fact, at my
job (semitechnical position at a mutual fund company), one of the
corporate lawyers' name is John Carter. His secretary's name is
Debbie Carter (no relation), and Debbie's husband's and son's names
are both John Carter!'' He tips his hat to Dr. John Carter, a
character on the television show ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   The site is also peppered with mentions of ``John Carter of
Mars,'' the title of one Edgar Rice Burroughs novel and a character
in several others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be veritable plagues of me,'' wrote John
Carter, the South African. ``I know of John Carter the bishop, and
a John M. Carter the physicist. (John Carter the physicist once
caused my mother much alarm and despondency. The physicist and I
both worked at the Nuclear Physics Research Unit at the University
of the Witwatersrand at one time many years ago. One dark and
stormy night I was working late when my mother phoned asking for
me. She was vehemently told that I had gone off to New Zealand and
wouldn't be back for quite awhile.)''
</P>
<P>
   Via e-mail, the original Carter said he was not aware of any
other home pages for people with common names. A brief search for
sites for the James Smiths, Mary Joneses, Bob Johnsons and Jose
Rodriguezes of the world did not yield any similar pages. Their
loss. But people with common names have formed clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very gratifying at the time to receive responses from
namesakes from all walks of life around the world,'' Carter the
Webmaster wrote in an e-mail message. ``It made me realize just how
much the internet has shrunk the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
