<SLUG> BC-CONCIERGES-675(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBY NEED POLISH? VOILA! A CONCIERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Its front-line employees having completed a
three-month training program to improve service for travelers,
Amtrak announced in advertisements this month: ``10,000 employees
went back to school. 10,000 concierges graduated.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same way that the breakfast roll became a croissant, even
with a fried egg and Canadian bacon on it, the concierge has become
a concept that knows few bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked the word because `concierge' means someone you can
approach who will make it happen,'' said Barbara Richardson,
Amtrak's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Though it bases its popularity on the reputations of desk clerks
at four-star hotels, for whom no service request is unrealizable,
today's concierge industry is untethered to performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the attitude of a concierge, that's a large part
of it,'' said Holly Stiel, a former concierge who started Holly
Speaks, a consulting business in Mill Valley, Calif., whose clients
include Bank of America and Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   On Amtrak's No. 171 from New York to Washington on Saturday, the
newly trained ex-conductors and attendants had much in common with
the traditional concierge: the French war widow with the keys who
runs the hotel by her own rules. One conductor was helping two
extensively tattooed men not with tickets to ``Wit'' but with
return times to New York. In the cafe car, the attendant was
bullying a small boy into choosing a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next stop Newark!'' said Mike Sternfeld, the conductor on the
intercom, who introduced himself I'm-your-server style, listing the
stations like chef's specials. But the next stop was unannounced:
10 minutes in the bleached green marshes of New Jersey, as
unexplained as a delay between courses.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak is hopping a business trend for personal services.
Hospitals and kennels now boast concierges. ``I even received a
call from a prison that was interested in having me come and speak
to them,'' said Michael Romei, chief concierge at the Waldorf
Towers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, concierges are finding themselves back where they
started: on residential building staffs. Though they are not castle
candle-keepers, or ``comtes des cierges,'' as they were in the
middle ages, the one-year-old National Concierge Association
estimates that one-quarter of its 150 members are now residential
concierges.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the phenomenon is not new, but it is newly popular,
with a prosperous real estate market and a demand for the latest
level of, and last word in, building services. A concierge has a je
ne sais quoi, like a fragrance brand, that a doorman doesn't _ more
personal assistant than package-toter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A terrific number of buildings have inaugurated concierge
services in the last five years,'' said Stuart Saft, chairman of
the Council of New York Cooperatives and Condominiums. ``Certainly
new buildings have built front desks and designated clerks as
concierges. Interestingly, older buildings are doing it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Henenson, director of on-site sales and marketing at Douglas
Elliman, the commercial and residential real estate firm, agreed.
``The word has a certain cachet,'' he said. ``It's marketing as
much as anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the ambiance of having a concierge is specific, the
services are not.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Byrne, a concierge at the Exchange, at 25 Broad St., a
two-year-old converted office building, won't pick up or return
videotapes, but he will recommend them.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Waking Ned Devine,' '' Byrne said. ``A very nice Irish
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a concierge is asked to coordinate pickups and
deliveries, call car services, log guests in and out and expedite
requests, like making arrangements for repairs. Infrequently,
George Almegor, a concierge at a 1-year-old apartment building at
150 E. 57th St., has reserved a restaurant table or tickets for a
show. He has also fed fish. He has paid bills. He has played Cupid
for single tenants.
</P>
<P>
   When two women asked for male strippers, he gave them the yellow
pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have been my grandmothers,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At a previous job, he broke up a fight in the lobby. After
knocking on a door one night, he discovered a dead body. ``A guy
with a football helmet. Rubbed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Almegor admitted to stress on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``How to please everyone when you're pulled in 10 directions at
once,'' he said. ``People can be nasty, make a mountain out of a
molehill. Dry cleaning _ a missing suit at 8 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   If not the patience of a saint, Almegor has technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a step back, count to three, to recover my professional
poise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As people find themselves squeezed for time between work and
play, equally stressful schedule-flexing spheres in New York, the
perception of what a residential concierge can or can't do has
begun to shimmer like a mirage. For tenants thirsty for services,
the small desk in the lobby, palmy with pleasant, friendly faces,
is the nearest oasis in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   But few concierges end up working like camels. Most draw a line
in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   The city's newest luxury buildings are promising a caravan of
services through the concierge. At the Textile Building, at 66
Leonard St., which is now selling condominiums at $795,000 to $6.5
million, these include housekeepers, personal trainers, masseuses,
acupuncturists and caterers, said Annabelle Schachner, the sales
director. But even $6.5 million later, the concierge will talk the
talk, not walk the walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you where the line is,'' Ms. Schachner said of the
limits of the job. ``They can't leave the desk.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the desk is the front line in the new theater of war on
what the concierge is there to do. Because the concierge is not a
doorman or an elevator man, he or she is perceived as a free agent,
available to run errands, walk dogs, park cars and supervise
repairs, deliveries and other services upstairs in tenants'
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Szabo, at the Alfred, a condominium building on West 61st
Street, has been asked to do all of the above. Time permitting, he
complies, or ``you bow out gracefully.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You say, `I'm not available,' '' he said. ``They ask for
someone else on the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Szabo, a young man with stiffly gelled blond hair and a goatee,
was a doorman in the building for four years before becoming a
concierge four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all job titles,'' he said, sitting in a square enclosure
in the lobby. ``Basically it's the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Szabo will walk dogs on his break. Tenants' increasing time
pressures also make them forget. ``They forget to make arrangements
for a delivery, or they forget to tell you there's someone on their
way. You have to contact them at work.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many concierges in the city, Szabo recites the golden rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do it once, it becomes your job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriella Szathmary, a concierge at the new Trump Place
condominium at 200 Riverside Blvd., recited her version.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you do today as a favor, tomorrow they're going to
expect,'' she said, standing behind a marble desk that extends like
a ship's bow into the entrance lobby. Ms. Szathmary was previously
a private secretary for a woman living on Park Avenue. She will
walk dogs in an emergency. ``You would do it for your neighbor _
they know I'm not a dog-walker,'' she said. But doing errands is
not in the cards. ``Obviously, grocery shopping is not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Caudwell, a professor of English at Fordham University and
the author of ``A Short History of Rudeness'' (Picador USA, 1999),
explained that the rise in popularity of the concierge as a new
type of service staff member might be a convenient diffusion of a
difficult social situation: newly affluent tenants in an expanding
economy who are able to employ servants but uncertain about how to
engage them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rely on iconographic signs,'' he said. ``If someone's
behind a desk, or if the uniform looks more like a business suit,
it legitimizes more in the way of demands. You think: `A concierge
is a competent profession. I can stop at the desk and make any
demand I want to.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fabian Smith, a concierge at River Tower on West 63rd Street,
says no as the Japanese do: by saying yes-but.
</P>
<P>
   `` `I would love to do it, but I can't do it _ it's against
management rules,' '' he said, repeating his response to requests
he can't grant. `` `It's in our union contract.' I go into details.
If you say no bluntly, they think you're being rude.'' Smith
directs his large lobby briskly, like a traffic policeman,
dispatching service people, recommending a cleaning woman,
answering his telephones. He makes wake-up calls. He helps tenants
who can't cook with advice about oven temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   A young man in a business suit approached the desk and asked
Smith if he would supervise a furniture delivery, waiting in the
apartment until the furniture was installed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to,'' Smith explained, ``but I can't. It's
management policy.'' The tenant observed that the failure to gain
Smith's cooperation ``kind of defeats the purpose of a concierge
building.'' Smith smiled commiseratively, suggesting a call to
management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
