<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7282 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPCOWBOYS-2ndTake-T     07-28 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPCOWBOYS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
WICHITA FALLS, Texas: town movie houses. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   4. GET OUT OF TOWN: Lovers of history and small towns will want
to roam 20 miles south to Archer City, home of author Larry
McMurtry and his fascinating Booked Up store, the Spur Hotel and
the Texasville Chalk Hill Grill.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can head north across the Red River into the Comanche,
Choctaw and Chickasaw nations. Oklahoma attractions within about an
hour's drive of the Falls include Meers Stor in the community of
the same name, a century-old trading post with fabulous hamburgers
the size of deflated footballs, and the surprisingly gorgeous
Wichita Mountains National Wildlife Refuge, where a drive to the
top of Mount Scott takes you past roaming buffalo to a view
rivaling anything in the Texas Hill Country.
</P>
<P>
   In Duncan, Oklahoma's largest bronze sculpture sits in front of
the Chisholm Trail Museum. In Medicine Park, you can cool off in a
pretty old swimming hole and eat at the Old Plantation, within a
formerly grand resort. In Lawton, find frontier Army post exhibits
at the Fort Sill Museum, and the graves of Geronimo and other great
leaders at Chief's Knoll.
</P>
<P>
   5. EAT BIG IN THE SMALL TOWN: Plenty of down-home personality is
served at Garcia's and El Gordo, along with homegrown Mexican
flavors. McBride's Land &AMP; Cattle is the local favorite for an
old-fashioned steakhouse experience, while generations of
hardscrabble oilfield workers have sworn by the barbecue and red
draws (that's cold beer with a shot of tomato juice in it) at the
Deuce P2, though their wives and daughters weren't welcome until a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the most famous eatery in town might be the Bar-L, a dark
and blessedly chilly barbecue joint established in 1952. George
Strait and the Dixie Chicks blast from the jukebox, while the wait
staff hustles platters of giant ribs and ice-clad beer mugs, and
trades gossip (''Don't tell me he's in jail again!'').
</P>
<P>
   If he's of a mind, Star-Telegram sports columnist and WBAP
sports talk-show personality Randy Galloway will host his 6 p.m.
show some nights at the Bar-L.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   When NOT to go: Note that due to out-of-town exhibition games,
the Cowboys will be away Aug. 8, 9, 10, 15, 16, 21 and 22.
</P>
<P>
   Comfy lodging outside of town is found in Bowie, 50 miles south
of Wichita Falls on U.S. 287, at The Gazebo Bed and Breakfast (
(940) 872-4852) and Old Tucker Homeplace Bed and Breakfast ( (940)
872-2484). In Archer City, 20 miles south of Wichita Falls on Texas
79, good choices are McMurtry's Lonesome Dove Inn ( (940) 574-2700)
and the historic Spur Hotel ( (940) 574-2501).
</P>
<P>
   In Wichita Falls: A visitor-information kiosk is located on the
training-camp site at MSU, and the Wichita Falls Convention and
Visitors Bureau can be found on the Internet at
www.wichitafalls.org. Or, call (940) 716-5500.
</P>
<P>
   Dining includes Garcia's (2925 Southwest Parkway, (940)
691-3724); El Gordo's (513 Scott St., (940) 322-6251); McBride's
Land &AMP; Cattle (501 Scott St., (940) 322-2516); Deuce P2 (1409 Lamar
St., (940) 766-1232); and Bar-L (13th and Lamar streets, (940)
766-0003).
</P>
<P>
   For a B&AMP;B stay, call Harrison House (2014 11th St., (940)
322-2299, lovely 1919 prairie-style home.
</P>
<P>
   Chain lodging choices include the usuals, from Hampton,
Fairfield and La Quinta inns to Motel 6, Hawthorn Suites and the
Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Still need more?: Call the Cowboys Hot Line in Irving, (972)
556-9308, or Wichita Falls, (940) 397-7777.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The facts on the Falls: The destination of choice for discerning
football fanatics
</P>
<P>
   Population: 103,000
</P>
<P>
   Established: 1882, much to the distress of Caddo, Comanche,
Kiowa, Wichita and other previous residents
</P>
<P>
   Named for: A set of 5-foot-high falls on the Wichita River that
washed away in an 1886 flood but were replaced with a 54-feet-high
man-made one a century later.
</P>
<P>
   Climate: ``Hotter'n a two-dollar pistol,'' as the saying goes.
The typical high temperature this time of year is 97; the highest
temperature ever recorded in Texas was 120 on Aug. 12, 1936, in
Seymour, about an hour west.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest pre-Cowboys moments: The town boomed with the nearby
Electra oil strike in 1911 and the big one in Burkburnett in 1918.
Between 1910 and 1920, the population exploded from 8,200 to more
than 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lowest moment: Swindling took on Texas-size proportions when the
World's Littlest Skyscraper, downtown on La Salle Street, was built
using money from a $200,000 stock fraud in 1919. Newly rich
families invested in a building whose specs were detailed in
inches, not feet.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
