<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPCOWBOYS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOW OUR GAME PLAN FOR A HOT TIME AT THE DALLAS COWBOYS TRAINING
CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ So what if it was 105 degrees at 4 p.m.
on Saturday? The devoted will come anyway, thousands a day, every
day for the next four weeks, hoping to get a glimpse, or even _
dare they dream _ the autographs of their beloved Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year, the Midwestern State University campus
hosts America's Team's summer training camp. It is a sensational
event that has this otherwise flat, sedate West Texas oil town 112
miles northwest of Fort Worth rolling out red carpets and seeing
green.
</P>
<P>
   The Falls is more than ready for Camp II, which began Monday
when rookies reported and shifted into full blast Wednesday with
the veterans' arrivals. A profusion of street signs bedecked with
blue stars and arrows directing the madding crowd to the TRAINING
CAMP joins bright banners on local businesses, welcoming players
and spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's monthlong Camp Cowboys drew about 120,000 fans, says
Robin Thompson Scales, director of the Wichita Falls Convention and
Visitors Bureau, who likes to note that six of 10 visitors came
from more than 50 miles away and that plenty stayed overnight. Best
of all, she says, those visitors had an economic impact of $6.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad for four weeks' work,'' Scales says. ```We'll take
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the legions of fans will take it, too, despite heat-index
highs of 110 to 115 and elbow-to-elbow seating on metal benches.
But it's best to begin with a game plan.
</P>
<P>
   This in mind, we offer five best ways to survive Wichita Falls'
seasonal moment in the sun. Watch the Cowboys, but also get out and
see the sites. And don't forget the Coppertone.
</P>
<P>
   1. TACKLING TWO-A-DAYS: Whoever came up with the nutty idea of
practicing football in the heinous Texas heat, not once but twice
daily, was surely related to the head case who thought it would be
fun to ride a bike 100 miles in West Texas _ which 8,000 or so
enthusiasts will do here in late August at the Hotter 'N Hell
Hundred, but that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will indeed practice twice on most days, first from
8:45 a.m. until 10:45 a.m. and then from 4 until 6 p.m., through
Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no admission fee for fans, who watch the
proceedings from behind the fences surrounding the practice fields,
bring your wallet anyway, because you'll want to hit the concession
stands and the makeshift Cowboys pro shop (get your red-hot
T-shirts!). The team also offers a kids' game area called The
Dallas Cowboys Experience, where a small fee is charged.
</P>
<P>
   The players who sign autographs usually do so after practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rookies tend to sign for any and everyone,'' says Maura Allen
Gast, a PR executive with the Irving Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau,
which helps with the Cowboys' media efforts. And some of the more
famous players will sometimes oblige. Last year, Gast says, Troy
Aikman had a system in which his ``handlers'' would hand out cards
_ ``to kids only'' _ numbered 1 through 25; those 25 kids were
instructed to go to a designated area after practice to meet the
quarterback and his Sharpie.
</P>
<P>
   2. SEE THE TOWN BY DAY: OK, so you have five hours to fill until
afternoon practice. Take the kids and your stacks of quarters to
the Plex Family Entertainment Center. Located near the campus, the
center has miniature golf, laser games, a gigantic outdoor
batting-cage facility, a huge video arcade, Go Karts and bumper
boats.
</P>
<P>
   Or a couple of blocks west of campus, find glorious escape in an
afternoon of first-run movies at the Sikes Senter mall's 10-screen
cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Those with more of a mind for fine cultchah can try the cool
environs of the Wichita Falls Museum and Art Center, directly
across from the MSU campus. There's a planetarium and laser-light
show, as well as an exhibit called ``Imagination Texas,'' an
interactive city for kids.
</P>
<P>
   In the restored, historic downtown, you'll find a few dozen
antiques shops (some with tearooms) as well as the Wichita Falls
Railroad Museum, and the Fire and Police Museum. Kell House Museum
is a renovated and spectacular 1909 home also nearby _ but then,
nothing in town is more than 10 minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you do, you'll realize that this is the friendliest
town anywhere. Whether in restaurants or on the streets, locals
greet strangers with, ``Hidy, how y'all doin'?'' They don't expect
a reply; they're just nice like that.
</P>
<P>
   3. SEE THE TOWN BY NIGHT: This town was built during an oil
boom, and done so a good piece west of the Bible Belt. Translation:
There is no shortage of bars in Wichita Falls, most with live
country music and pool tables.
</P>
<P>
   The newest night scene, which sources say attracts plenty of
Dallas Cowboys, is Graham Central Station. Found about eight blocks
from camp, the five clubs under one roof include Denim and
Diamonds, a country music joint; a karaoke spot called Starz; Bell
Bottoms, a '70s/'80s disco-dance place; Paradise Beach, with more
dance music; and the Zone, a game room.
</P>
<P>
   For family fun, there's community theater at Backdoor Theatre in
a turn-of-the-century icehouse, as well as Wichita Theatre and
Opera House, with a ``Branson-style'' country-music show presented
on weekends inside the landmark that served as a vaudeville stage
and then the town movie house.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
