<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-CRUISES-0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    CONGRESS URGED TO LET STATES REGULATE GAMBLING DAY CRUISES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN Florida papers 
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Florida Attorney General Bob Butterworth urged a
congressional panel Wednesday to give states the power to regulate
gambling day cruises, but he faced warnings that a pending bill
would decimate the cruise industry and hurt a popular Sunshine
State port.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the impact of a 1992 law designed to give American
ships the same right as foreign-flagged vessels to operate cruises
in international waters with casino-style gambling often known as
``cruises to nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a federal appeals court recently ruled that the 1992
law did not pre-empt state regulation, the ruling does not apply
outside the Carolinas, Maryland and Virginia . Butterworth said
courts with jurisdiction over Florida and most other coastal states
have mistakenly ruled that the law prohibits states from regulating
casino cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth urged a clearly skeptical Subcommittee on Coast
Guard and Maritime Transportation to support a bill by Rep. Frank
Wolf, R-Va., that would make it clear that states could regulate
casino cruises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe the 1992 amendment allows floating casinos in
the state of Florida when the people three times in 21 years
rejected casino gambling,'' Butterworth said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Gene Taylor, D-Miss., a leading proponent of the 1992
change and the panel's ranking Democrat, argued that states have
the right to ban or limit casino cruises so long as the ban applies
to all vessels. He asked why the Florida legislature had not taken
advantage of the provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you asking 'Big Brother' to save you from the Florida
legislature?'' Taylor asked. ``Why doesn't Florida do it if that is
really the will of the state of Florida?''
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth said no action had been taken because of the
gambling industry's political strength and lawmakers' concerns that
such legislation could give the Seminole Indian tribe ammunition to
argue that it should be allowed to operate casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Bullock, president of the Day Cruise Association,
asserted that if Wolf's bill is adopted, only American-flagged
vessels would be affected. He noted that efforts in the Florida
legislature to ban casino cruises have never made it out of
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Port of Palm Beach Chairman Robert L. Williams told the panel
that the proposed bill would be devastating to the Florida port
where 20 percent of the income comes from casino cruises. Revenue
from such cruises doubled from 1997 to 1998 and is running 50
percent higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enactment (of the bill) would liquidate thousands of
cruise-related jobs and would hamper and curtail the current pace
of economic activity at the port,'' Williams said. ``It would be
devastating to our businesses, operation, and future development.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf indicated that if the transportation panel does not approve
his bill, he might try to attach it to the transportation
appropriations bill. He is chairman of the transportation
appropriations subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
