<HEADLINE>
PARENTS MUST PROTECT CHILDREN'S INNOCENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Aug. 5, 1999.)  
(nk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At my son's eighth birthday party, two of his classmates were
sitting in the kitchen talking to my husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why aren't you out there playing?'' he asked the two
second-grade girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys are doing boy stuff,'' they told him, ``you know,
football and wrestling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said, ``I see.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a boy,'' one of them said. ``So you probably like that
stuff too. Although, you could have a sex-change operation and
become a girl. I saw that on Jerry Springer.''
</P>
<P>
   They both giggled.
</P>
<P>
   A sex-change operation. Hardly a topic of choice for a
second-grader's birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, here we are. Even if my son has never seen daytime talk
shows, even if he has no idea what a sex-change operation is, you
can be sure a few kids in his class or day care or play group have.
And they, of course, believe in sharing this advanced knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   A friend and I were talking about child raising in the late
1990s, and we agreed that it feels like you're constantly trying to
hold back a storm surge of inappropriate images and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   How can you possibly screen all their conversations? Monitor
videos from someone else's overnight party? Stop the person in line
ahead of you from cursing a blue streak at the automatic teller?
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there's the Internet. I have to make sure Adam's
not even in the room when I log on to my service provider, for fear
he'll read one of the XXX spam messages that has slipped into my
e-mail, such as ``Live Hot Bodies Do Bad Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if he's going to be exposed to all the abnormal stuff
before he even knows what's normal,'' I told my husband, as we
discussed which parental filtering program to buy.
</P>
<P>
   I have friends who try diligently to shield their grade-school
children, and have succeeded in protecting most of their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   And then I have friends who have given up. Some let their
elementary-aged children watch ``South Park;'' others routinely let
their youngsters watch R-rated movies that have gory violence and
explicit sex scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why bother? They'll see it sometime. Better to have them used
to it and seeing it here with us,'' said one father.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of kids just aren't ready for what they're seeing.
</P>
<P>
   Are we in such a hurry for our children to grow up?
</P>
<P>
   As writer Bill McKibben states: ``If one had set out to create a
culture purposefully damaging to children, you couldn't do much
better than America at the end of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent USA Today story about ``Raising Kids in Toxic Times''
quoted parents as saying their children were becoming
``artificially sophisticated: They talk like adults. They know
things like adults, but they're not. They don't know what's behind
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And according to Nielsen television ratings, more than a million
kids watch Jerry Springer on TV, including the 8-year-old in my
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, entertainment critics say, live in a materialistic,
media-sated culture, so where do we expect our children to live?
</P>
<P>
   But here's the thing: We're the parents. We can draw the line.
In fact, we can draw lines all OVER the place.
</P>
<P>
   And we should.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a feature writer based in Atlanta for the New
York Times Regional Newspapers. The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part
of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUICIDE29-COX     07-28 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surgeon General Issues Call To Action To Combat Suicide
 &HT;    997.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Surgeon General David Satcher, accompanied by
Tipper Gore and leaders of an Atlanta-based suicide prevention
network, on Wednesday issued a ``call to action'' to combat suicide
in America.
</P>
<P>
   Although suicide is the country's eighth leading cause of death
_ accounting for nearly 31,000 deaths in 1996, compared with about
20,000 homicides _ victims of life-threatening despondency are
often ashamed to seek help, Satcher said.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief White House meeting, Satcher unveiled a national
strategy to increase research on suicide prevention and educate the
public on the causes and signs of impending suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must reduce the stigma of mental illness that keeps so many
people from seeking the help that could save their lives,'' Satcher
said at meeting at which he announced the suicide prevention
effort. ``People should not be afraid or ashamed to seek help.''
</P>
<P>
   Satcher called on people he described as ``natural community
helpers'' _ such as religious leaders, teachers, hairdressers and
even Little League coaches _ to learn how to recognize the signs of
potentially fatal depression and intervene.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to actual deaths, about 500,000 Americans are
treated in emergency rooms every year after attempting suicide,
Satcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Gore, wife of Vice President Al Gore, Satcher was
accompanied by Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev.,
Doris Smith, who is the president of the Atlanta-based Suicide
Prevention Advocacy Network (SPAN), and Chris Marshall, a
37-year-old Norfolk, Va., man who attempted suicide after years of
struggle with a mysterious condition diagnosed as panic disorder,
depression and ``social phobia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time I was six years old, I knew something was wrong
with me,'' Marshall said. ``I had a deep sense of fear. I would get
dizzy and sweat and fear that I was going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he said he continued to suffer ``vicious and
humiliating panic attacks, over and over,'' a family doctor said he
was merely suffering from a ``case of nerves,'' which he would get
over.
</P>
<P>
   He said his parents worried constantly about him and took him to
specialists, but the drugs they prescribed didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, he said, a succession of failures in college and
at various jobs, caused him to ``turn on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to live on my parents' farm, and after several months
with no relief from my symptoms, I could no longer take it,'' he
said. ``I became numb. On a starry night, I took my father's
shotgun and walked out onto a field. I was crying as I walked.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had been plagued with ``visions of killing myself''
because of ``my sick brain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loaded the gun and held the barrel to my forehead. I could
not do it. By some grace, in a completely numb state, I was able to
grasp hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Marshall said, he met a young woman who encouraged him to
try medication again and finally an antidepressant drug began to
relieve the irrational fears that had plagued him nearly all his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have a good job and I'm getting married (to the girl who
encouraged him to return to medication) next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group most at risk is senior citizens, who account for 20
percent of all suicides, Satcher said. Reid described the day in
1984 when, as lieutenant governor of Nevada, he got a telephone
call from his mother, who told him, ``Your pop shot himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Present in the audience were Jerry and Elsie Weyrauch, the
Marietta, Ga., couple who founded SPAN 11 years ago, following the
suicide of their oldest daughter, Terri.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Smith read a suicide letter left by her son, Mark Allen
Smith, who shot himself in the head in 1992 in their Atlanta home,
while studying for the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   A student leader in high school and college and a gifted
musician, Mark, ``although we didn't know it, was suffering from
depression,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret this had to happen on your birthday,'' he wrote. He
also apologized that he did ``not have more to say to you, other
than to say I love you very, very much and please tell my father I
love him too.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she ``did not know that depression was a disease that
could be treated or that you can get help.''
</P>
<P>
   She said after his death the family was shunned and was told
that ``blacks did not commit suicide'' and that ``if you commit
suicide, you will go to Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said suicide is ``not something that happens to other
people. It happens to people we know. It happens to ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, join me in breaking the silence,'' she said to a
gathering of about 100 persons, most of whom seemed to be
associated with SPAN. ``Together we will save lives, replace stigma
with acceptance, ignorance with understanding and fear with hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he hoped a resolution which he and Reid introduced in
Congress several years ago would send a message to people that
``it's OK. It's all right to talk about our feelings of despair, of
hopelessness, of suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all, we have to tell people that it's good to seek
help,'' he said. ``We must face this problem head-on.''
</P>
<P>
   Satcher said the national strategy would involve such agencies
as the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the Health
Resources and Services Administration, the Indian Health Service
and the National Institute of Mental Health, the Substance Abuse
and Mental Health Services Administration, as well as private
groups like SPAN, the Ad Council, Ronald McDonald House Charities
and the American School Counselors Association.
</P>
<P>
   Internet web sites with additional information on suicide
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ CDC, www.cdc.gov/ncipe;
</P>
<P>
   _ Health Resources and Services Administration,
www.hrsa.dhhs.gov;
</P>
<P>
   _ National Institute of Mental Health,
www.nimh.nih.gov/research/suicide.htm;
</P>
<P>
   _ Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration,
www.samhsa.gov;
</P>
<P>
   _ Office of the Surgeon General, www.surgeongeneral.gov.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
