<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DALLAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS: WHERE `WRETCHED EXCESS' REIGNS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In typical Texas understatement, tourism officials
boast that the area offers ``more thrills than Disneyland, more
music than Nashville and more shopping than New York.''
</P>
<P>
   But they don't mention ``wretched excess.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Beverly Hills, however, probably no other city in the
nation exemplifies showy living and ostentatious displays of wealth
more than Dallas. Need proof?
</P>
<P>
   Start at the Mansion on Turtle Creek, a luxury hotel that
regularly ranks near the top of the list of the world's best in
travel magazine rankings. Located in a renovated Italian
Renaissance-style residence in the Oaklawn area near downtown
Dallas, the hotel's main rule seems to be that if you have the
money to stay there, they'll grovel with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Even though our mission was secret, every hotel staff member
seemed to be our new best friend within minutes after we checked
in. It's amazing what the perceived aura of having money will do.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after settling into our room, which at a special weekend
rate of $235 was probably the hotel's cheapest, a tray containing a
pitcher of fruit-flavored iced tea and carrot cake was delivered,
along with a handwritten welcome note.
</P>
<P>
   Other nice ``wretched excess'' touches during the stay included
a bucket of ice delivered with a fresh rose in a vase (there are no
serve-yourself ice machines); a big bathroom with more marble than
the Vatican; plush terry-cloth bathrobes for lounging; and a $22
lobster taco, listed by one national magazine as one of the 100
best things to eat in America, served poolside.
</P>
<P>
   However, there were some disappointments. Bathrooms included no
towel racks, so we had to hang wet towels over the shower rod like
at home. The soap dish was bolted to the vanity, apparently to
deter souvenir hunters, and skin moisturizer, bath crystals and
shampoo were in refillable glass bottles designed not to be taken
home.
</P>
<P>
   And _ dare we say it? _ there was a dead shrub on the patio.
</P>
<P>
   When we told the receptionist, she seemed positive that the
gardener could bring the bush back to life. If so, he should be
working at Lourdes instead of the Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop on our self-guided tour was the Crescent, a gray
stone fortress on the edge of downtown Dallas modeled after a
French chateau. The hotel/office/shopping complex designed by famed
architects Philip Johnson and John Burgee includes two pricey shops
that give new meaning to ``wretched excess.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Korshak is a stark-looking clothing store where overly
friendly salespeople eagerly offer drinks while you shop for a
$2,000 suit. Men's Health magazine recently named the store one of
the five best places to shop in America. Its advice: ``Make sure
you bring a 10-gallon wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   The interior of Stanley Korshak seems downright spartan compared
with Lady Primrose's Shopping English Countryside antiques store.
</P>
<P>
   The 5,000-square-foot shop, the brainchild of oil heiress
Caroline Rose Hunt, is jammed with over-the-top collectibles,
ranging from antler chandeliers to a $6,000 music box. Upstairs, a
floral-patterned tea room has become a favorite gathering spot for
the ladies who lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Serious shoppers wouldn't think of missing the original Neiman
Marcus store in downtown Dallas. The ``mother ship'' of the upscale
speciality chain is not quite as impressive as it once was since
lavish retail stores have fled to the suburbs, but it's still
special.
</P>
<P>
   The multistory building has such touches as a shoeshine man in
the men's clothing department and elegant dining in the Zodiak Room
restaurant, where socialites who otherwise wouldn't dream of
leaving north Dallas come to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   A small museum on the fifth floor celebrates Neiman's glorious
92-year history. If you want to see what ``wretched excess'' was
really like, look at photographs of the store's Christmas interiors
in the 1940s and 1950s, and gaze at the Wall of Style, which
features such honorees as Princess Grace and Coco Chanel.
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving the store, however, be careful about hopping into
the first car the valet brings. Our valet brought a silver Lexus,
the car-of-choice in label-conscious Dallas, and opened the door as
the engine remained running for our departure. We considered taking
off in it, but common sense prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   A large chunk of ``wretched excess'' remains at the Wendy and
Emery Reves Collection at the Dallas Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 15 years ago, Marshall native Wendy Reves gave the museum
$35 million worth of impressionist paintings, rugs, porcelain and
ironwork with one big string attached: She insisted the items be
displayed in a replica of the French villa where she and her late
husband, Emery, entertained such notables as Winston Churchill and
Greta Garbo.
</P>
<P>
   So museum officials spent $6 million to reproduce six rooms atop
the museum roof and display the items exactly as Reves instructed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics complained that the best paintings can hardly be seen
among the clutter of furniture, vases, books, silver door knockers
and even Churchill's cigars. And they howled over such touches as a
pair of Reves' slippers casually cast off on the floor at the side
of the bed in her reconstructed bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   The museum director who approved Reves' demands is long gone,
but the collection remains a permanent part of the facility with
every item in place as she envisioned. On the day we visited,
however, no one else was viewing the Reves Collection. Long lines
of people waited downstairs to get a glimpse of the Stanley Cup,
the National Hockey League championship trophy won by the Dallas
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   While the locals go mad over ice hockey and are known to be
crazy about professional football, the real sport of Dallas is
shopping. So much so that Dallas Morning News columnist Maryln
Schwartz refers to a windowless mausoleumlike building that faces
NorthPark shopping center in north Dallas as the ``Tomb of the
Unknown Shopper.''
</P>
<P>
   The building, actually the Biblical Arts Center, is next door to
what the locals call Hillcrest Cemetery. Schwartz notes that some
shopping-crazed Dallasites have added provisions in their wills to
make sure their grave sites face the Neiman Marcus store across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   A fitting end for any ``wretched excess'' tour is the Mary Kay
Museum, located at the world headquarters of the gigantic
direct-sales skin care company.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, located in the stunning eight-story rose-and-black
marble atrium of a far north Dallas skyscraper, is a little gaudy
but fun, just like its founder and guiding spirit, Mary Kay Ash.
</P>
<P>
   Even though age and declining health has kept the Queen of
Cosmetics away from the office (a worker in the company cafeteria
says Ash hasn't been seen on the premises for a year and a half),
the museum holds a life-size Mary Kay mannequin and several of her
favorite gowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Mary Kay memorabilia also includes a porcelain doll
fashioned in her image and a bevy of diamond-encrusted bumblebees,
because the positive-thinking Ash often pepped up her sales team by
reminding them that, aerodynamically, the bumblebee shouldn't fly,
``but it does.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum's piece de resistance is a 1967 pink Cadillac with a
heart-shaped rear window. Early on, Ash gave her top sellers pink
cars, which became a symbol of the company. People magazine once
labeled Ash the ``Mascarared Moses'' for leading her chosen people
to a land of furs, diamonds and pink Cadillacs.
</P>
<P>
   A stylish company cafeteria in the lobby leads to an attractive
dining area with goldleaf columns, mauve carpet and teak tables.
The cafeteria is open to the public and includes a carving station,
salad bar and an area piled with lavish desserts.
</P>
<P>
   The prices are inexpensive, and the food is high-quality, so pig
out and end the tour with this valuable lesson: ``Wretched excess''
doesn't always have to cost a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Where to find them:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mansion on Turtle Creek _ Address: 2821 Turtle Creek.
Phone: 214-559-2100.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Crescent _ Address: 2200 Cedar Springs. Phone (Crescent
Court Hotel): 800-654-6541.cq
</P>
<P>
   _ Stanley Korshak _ Address: 500 Crescent Court. Phone:
214-871-3608.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lady Primrose's English Countryside _ Address: 500 Crescent
Court. Phone: 214-871-8333.
</P>
<P>
   _ Neiman Marcus _ Address: 1618 Main. Phone: 214-741-6911.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendy and Emery Reves Collection, Dallas Museum of Art _
Address: 717 N. Harwood. Phone: 214-922-1200.
</P>
<P>
   _ Biblical Arts Center _ Address: 7500 Park Lane. Phone:
214-691-4661.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mary Kay Museum _ Address: 16251 Dallas Parkway. Phone:
972-867-6300.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
