<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DALLAS-TREASURES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO IMAGES DEFINE DALLAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mention Dallas to almost any adult in the world and two
images come to mind: an assassinated president and a television
show.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not surprising that two of the Metroplex's most popular
tourist sites are a memorial to John F. Kennedy and a homage to
J.R. Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixth Floor Museum, located in the School Book Depository
building where it is believed Lee Harvey Oswald fired the shot that
killed Kennedy on Nov. 22, 1963, details the JFK presidency and
events surrounding the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, operated by the Dallas County Historical Commission,
opened in 1989 after much public debate. Some Dallas residents
opposed the establishment because they feared it would extend the
notorious reputation the city received from Kennedy's death.
</P>
<P>
   But now it draws more than 450,000 visitors each year, including
many young people who were not yet born when Kennedy was
assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, impressively laid out in a 9,000-square-foot
loftlike space, includes historical photographs, documentary films
and artifacts such as an Associated Press teletype machine with the
first news bulletin of the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit also examines various conspiracy theories, including
video footage of U.S. House of Representatives hearings in 1978
that concluded Oswald did not act alone.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department later determined there was no
conclusive evidence of a conspiracy and closed the case in 1988.
But a lot of people believe otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Sixth Floor Museum) basically tell you Oswald did it
and that's it,'' says John Nagel of the Conspiracy Museum, a
privately run exhibit located a few blocks away. ``We present the
other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Every weekend, Nagel guides visitors around the area and points
out inconsistencies with the Warren Commission report, which
determined Oswald acted alone.
</P>
<P>
   Nagel, who became interested in the assassination when he was 14
and has been studying it for 28 years, believes other assassins
shot Kennedy from behind a picket fence at the grassy knoll near
Dealey Plaza when the presidential motorcade passed by.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has got to be the most scrutinized six seconds in our
country's history,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Other self-appointed tour guides also hang out outside the Sixth
Floor Museum hoping to guide visitors around the area for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   The tours usually stop at Dealey Plaza, across the street from
the school book depository building, where two bronze plaques set
in a low granite wall trace the route of the 1963 motorcade and the
day's events.
</P>
<P>
   Then they continue for two blocks to a Kennedy memorial that was
erected by the city and county in 1970. It was designed by noted
architect Philip Johnson and approved by Kennedy's widow,
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are put off by the stark memorial, which has
30-foot-high concrete walls and an open roof. Nagel explains that
Johnson designed it as a cenotaph, or empty tomb. The unfinished
look symbolizes Kennedy's unfinished life.
</P>
<P>
   A JFK historical bus tour offered by Gray Line Tours also takes
participants by the Oak Cliff apartment where Oswald lived and by
the Texas theater, where Oswald killed a Dallas policeman a few
hours after the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 miles away, near the suburb of Plano, hordes of
tourists travel to a site that is equally well-known around the
world, thanks to television.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 flags fly outside Southfork Ranch, representing the
countries where ``Dallas'' continues to be shown around the world.
The series, which appeared on CBS from 1978 to 1991, also is
repeated regularly on cable's TNN (The Nashville Network).
</P>
<P>
   Sally Peavy, supervisor of the Southfork mansion, says she has
escorted groups ranging from Romanian dignitaries to a convention
of urologists. A recent tour group included visitors from Great
Britain, New Jersey and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love to come here,'' she says. ``It rekindles a family
memory or childhood memory of watching the show that crosses
generations.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour begins at an exhibit hall that features Lucy's wedding
dress, a convoluted diagram of the Ewing family tree and video
monitors that show classic ``Dallas'' episodes.
</P>
<P>
   A tram takes visitors along a quarter-mile route, past grazing
longhorns, miniature horses and a 63,000-square-foot event and
conference center that is rented out for weddings and corporate
functions. The barn also houses a clothing store called Lincolns &AMP;
Longhorns, which features Jock Ewing's 1978 Lincoln Continental
Mark V, and an eating place called Miss Ellie's Deli.
</P>
<P>
   Once at the two-story, columned house, Peavy escorts visitors on
a folksy half-hour tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're welcome to take pictures. Just don't take our pictures
off the wall,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Each room in the four-bedroom, seven-bathroom home is decorated
in honor of characters in the television series, even though no
inside filming took place during the series. Only shots of the
outdoor pool, patio and exterior of the home were filmed here. All
interior scenes were filmed on a sound stage in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Peavy drops little tidbits about the filming of
the series. She explains that camera operators used a wide-angle
lens and mirrors to make the swimming pool look larger and points
out that it would have been impossible for the character Kristen to
fall from the upstairs balcony into the pool because they were too
far apart.
</P>
<P>
   She also explains that the ranch is located on 40 acres, not
100,000 acres, as it was in the show.
</P>
<P>
   The home, built by Joe Duncan in 1970, was picked for the show
after producers helicoptered over the area in search of the
perfect-looking locale for the series.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan sold the ranch in 1984. A subsequent owner went bankrupt
and, in 1992, the ranch was purchased for $2.6 million by its
current owner, Arizona developer Rex Maughn, who refurbished the
property. His company, Forever Resorts, is considering plans to
build a fancy resort hotel on the property.
</P>
<P>
   Peavy says the two most-asked questions are: ``Does anyone live
here?'' (No) and ``Does anyone sleep here?''
</P>
<P>
   She explains that only the Dallas Cowboys cheerleaders are
allowed to stay overnight once a year, when they practice their
etiquette. Visitors taking a tour on that day get a kick out of
seeing the bikini-clad guests around the pool, Peavy says.
</P>
<P>
   As visitors leave the house, she cheerily offers these parting
words: ``Continue to watch `Dallas' so I'll still have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Where to find them:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Sixth Floor Museum _ Address: 411 Elm. Phone:
888-485-4854. Web site: www.jfk.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Conspiracy Museum _ Address: 110 Market. Phone:
214-741-3040. Web site: www.conspiracymuseum.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Southfork Ranch _ Address: 3700 Hogge Road, Parker, Texas.
Phone: 972-442-7800. Web site: www.southforkranch.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
