<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RANCH29-COX     07-28 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RANCH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ranch is No.1, pardner
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ranch dressing rules. The salad plate, the snack
basket, the pizza box.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, as ranch celebrates its 25th national anniversary
this year, it has become the No. 1 dressing, in no short thanks to
Texans. Only Florida has more cities on the Top 20 list of ranch
dressing dippers/pourers than Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Texans don't care that ranch dressing came from California, they
embrace it as their own. Is there a soul in the state who has not
ladled the blend of herbs, buttermilk and mayo on something _ from
lettuce to burgers to baked potato?
</P>
<P>
   There are no official figures for ranch use in Austin, but we
know it's a big favorite. ``We offer eight different dressings on
our 50-item salad bar and by far ranch is the most popular used,''
says Stefan Zuntag, a general manager of Souper Salad in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Texans also do some pretty strange things with it.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the state there is a cook who stirs ranch dressing
in her chocolate sheet cakes. We know because she sent the recipe
to a ranch dressing contest a few years back. Heck no, it didn't
win. Something about the combo turned the parsley in the dressing a
wild fluorescent green. The Hidden Valley Ranch folks are still
talking about that _ ah, creative _ soul.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is that business about Texans dunking slices of pizza
in ranch dressing. Hard to say where that came from, but I first
encountered the habit at Southwest Texas University in San Marcos
nearly two decades ago. Pretty odd, I thought, but look at how that
has caught on, even beyond the state line. One survey ranks pizza
dunking as the third most popular use, behind salads and
sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Other enthusiasts have stirred ranch dressing into soup, potato
and chicken dishes, sprinkled it dry on popcorn and put it out as a
dip for chicken wings, fries and fresh veggies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, parents say they can get kids to eat just about
anything _ from fish to veggies _ if they serve it with a bowl of
ranch dressing. Those are sweet words to manufacturers, who, being
no dummies, have teamed up with other foods. Hidden Valley Original
Ranch alone has partnerships with Fresh Express salad mixes, Hormel
Bacon Bits, Pillsbury Potato Buds, Nabisco Thin Crisps and Pizza
Hut _ all spreading the flavor of ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back at the real ranch, the place sits empty today,
despite its soaring fame.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't always so. Hidden Valley Guest Ranch, the
birthplace of ranch dressing, once was a hot spot, especially with
fun-loving college kids who partied there in the '50s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Described by a former hand as part nightclub, part dude ranch,
the 120-acre spread near Santa Barbara, Calif., was owned by Steve
and Gayle Henson. Having played around with his salad dressing
recipe since earlier days in Alaska, Steve had a huge herd of
high-spirited human guinea pigs to test his kitchen efforts. And
the guests loved his ranch dressing so much _ some even ate it on
ice cream _ that many took it home in glass jars . One guest from
Hawaii wanted 300 jars for a party on Oahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have anywhere near the 300 or so jars he needed to
take all that dressing with him, so I told him to give me a few
hours while I prepackaged a bunch of envelopes with my mixture,''
Henson recalls. ``I told him how to use the mix to make the
dressing when he got back to Hawaii. He called a few days later
wanting more. He said everyone had gone wild over the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Henson developed a more exact formula for the powdered mixture
and started marketing the dressing by mail order. No jars or
bottles, just envelopes of the dressing mix. Business began to
grow, but the vans needed to ship the product were having trouble
negotiating the narrow roads leading to Hidden Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Henson moved the operation to larger quarters in Sparks, Nev.,
in 1972 and sold the business to Hidden Valley Food Products Co.,
which went national in 1974. Henson retired, although his son Nolan
stayed for three or four years after the sale. Neither is
associated with the product now, but both are participating in the
dressing's 25th national anniversary celebrations this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ranch dressing has grown from envelopes of powdered mix, blended
at home with mayo and buttermilk, to bottles. It has gone from a
remote ranch to Wendy's salad bars everywhere. It has become so
common that its name is no longer capitalized. And now it has
surpassed Italian dressing to become the champ.
</P>
<P>
   Call it successful indoor ranching.
</P>
<P>
   TOP 20 `RANCH' HOMES
</P>
<P>
   1. Wichita
</P>
<P>
   2. Tulsa
</P>
<P>
   3. San Diego
</P>
<P>
   4. Tampa/St. Petersburg
</P>
<P>
   5. Boise
</P>
<P>
   6. Omaha
</P>
<P>
   7. Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   8. Dallas/Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   9. Des Moines
</P>
<P>
   10. Orlando
</P>
<P>
   11. Miami/Fort Lauderdale
</P>
<P>
   12. Kansas City
</P>
<P>
   13. Jacksonville
</P>
<P>
   14. West Texas/New Mexico
</P>
<P>
   15. North New England
</P>
<P>
   16. Salt Lake City
</P>
<P>
   17. Oklahoma City
</P>
<P>
   18. San Antonio/Corpus Christi
</P>
<P>
   19. Sacramento
</P>
<P>
   20. Boston
</P>
<P>
   Source: Information Resources Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Three ways Texans use ranch dressing outside the salad bowl and
pizza box:
</P>
<P>
   Tortilla Spirals
</P>
<P>
   1-ounce envelope ranch dressing mix
</P>
<P>
   2 packages (8 ounces each) cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 (12-inch) flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   4-ounce jar diced pimentos
</P>
<P>
   4-ounce can diced green chiles
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4-ounce can sliced black olives
</P>
<P>
   Mix dressing, cream cheese and onions. Spread on tortillas.
Drain vegetables and blot dry on paper towels. Sprinkle equal
amounts of vegetables on top of cream cheese. Roll tortillas
tightly. Chill at least 2 hours. Cut rolls into 1-inch pieces.
Serve with spirals facing up. Makes 3 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Ranch Trash
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (8 to 10 ounces each) mixed nuts
</P>
<P>
   14-ounce box Honey Nut Cheerios
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce box Quaker Oats Squares
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce box Rice Chex
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce box Wheat Chex
</P>
<P>
   15-ounce bag pretzel sticks
</P>
<P>
   SEASONING:
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 packages (1 ounce each) original ranch dressing
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 to 2 cups oil
</P>
<P>
   Mix dry ranch dressing with oil. In a very large container or
clean trash bag, combine and mix all ingredients. Stir in dressing
mixture well. This recipe does not call for heating. However, if
you prefer the toasted flavor or if the weather is very humid and
the trash does not retain its crunch, it can be toasted on a large,
sided cookie sheet (in batches) or in a roasting pan at 350 degrees
for 15 minutes or longer, stirring every 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Trash is a nickname that has been given to the popular party
mix, also known as Chex Mix.
</P>
<P>
   Taco Soup
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   28-ounce can tomatoes with juice
</P>
<P>
   15-ounce can kidney beans, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce can pintos, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   17-ounce can whole kernel corn or hominy with liquid
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 package taco seasoning mix
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce package ranch dressing mix
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   In a Dutch oven, brown beef and onion. Drain fat, and add
remaining ingredients. Simmer for an hour. Serve with tortilla
chips or cornbread. Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
