<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SUNDANCE-HNS &LR;      07-28 1723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SUNDANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH: ONE PLACE WHERE IT'S HIP TO BE SQUARE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent marks needed over a in Marton and a and o in Varo) 
 
By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sundance Square doesn't rate real high on
the ``hip quotient.''
</P>
<P>
   You're not likely to see cutting-edge couples strolling the
streets of the 20-block historical district in the middle of
downtown. Most people on a recent summer night were casually
dressed in shorts and polo shirts _ even when dining at the area's
nicest restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby streets are likely to be lined with Plymouth Voyagers and
pickups, far outnumbering the occasional Mercedes, Lexus or BMW
that strays into the area.
</P>
<P>
   But even without the glitz, Sundance Square is a major reason
why Fort Worth has the liveliest downtown in the state.
</P>
<P>
   While many U.S. cities are just now beginning to experience a
turnaround in their downtowns, Fort Worth's renaissance has been
going on for close to a decade.
</P>
<P>
   On most nights, the red-brick-paved sidewalks are jammed with
people going to movies, stopping for coffee, enjoying dinner or
browsing in bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it's a throwback to the 1950s and '60s, before people
fled to the suburbs, when a downtown area was the focal point of
shopping and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike San Antonio, where those meandering along the River Walk
are likely to be tourists, most of the people in downtown Fort
Worth live in the surrounding Metroplex area. Instead of traipsing
to a cheerless suburban shopping mall for entertainment, they flock
to the heart of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the comforts of suburbia are here. There is plenty of
free parking, and the area feels safe with the presence of
benign-looking security guards. Two multiscreen AMC Theaters,
totaling 20 screens, show the latest movies to large crowds.
</P>
<P>
   A Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstore takes up much of a city block. Even
toward midnight, it is full of people browsing among the books and
reading magazines next to a two-story-high faux bronze replica of
Frederic Remington's ``The Bronco Buster'' or sipping coffee in the
adjoining Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the locals prefer the Coffee Haus, an independent coffee
shop located a few blocks away with sidewalk tables and a menu that
includes Snickers cheesecake and Eskimoca, a nondairy frozen
caffeinated drink.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the area features several neighborhood pubs (the
Flying Saucer Draught Emporium seemed the busiest with its mix of
beer, billiards, cigars and live music), many restaurants, shops
and galleries.
</P>
<P>
   There is even one of the few urban outlet malls in the nation:
the Fort Worth Outlet Square features Spiegel, Nine West, Split
Rail, Samsonite and Radio Shack outlets. The corporate offices of
the Tandy Corp., which owns Radio Shack, are next door.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit for the area's revitalization goes to the
Bass brothers, a prominent family that spearheaded the development
of a two-block stretch of restored 19th-century buildings in the
early 1980s. The area was named for the Sundance Kid, a compatriot
of Butch Cassidy who, legend has it, once hung out in nearby
saloons, gambling parlors and dance halls.
</P>
<P>
   While the brothers initially concentrated on the construction of
two high-rise office towers and a luxury hotel, Ed Bass turned a
row of downtown storefronts into Caravan of Dreams, a combination
jazz club/restaurant/theater with a casual rooftop grotto bar.
</P>
<P>
   The quirky building topped with a geodesic dome and cactus
garden is the closest thing the area has to an alternative space.
On a sultry summer night, patrons order a beer from a cave bar on
the roof and then settle in a lounge chair along a number of brick
terraces where they can view the crowds below.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent addition to the district is the Nancy Lee and
Perry R. Bass Performance Hall, a $65 million European-style opera
house that has won rave reviews since it opened last year.
</P>
<P>
   The most dazzling element of the hall _ home to the Fort Worth
Symphony, Fort Worth Dallas Ballet, Fort Worth Opera and the Van
Cliburn International Piano Competition _ is a pair of 48-foot-tall
angels on the front of the structure.
</P>
<P>
   The limestone angels, designed and sculpted by Marton Varo,
extend over the street five stories below and herald onlookers with
golden trumpets to their lips.
</P>
<P>
   The best place to view the angels is from the outdoor dining
area of a restaurant appropriately named Angeluna across the street
from the performing arts center.
</P>
<P>
   The chic restaurant, founded by the owners of Mezzaluna
restaurant in Aspen, Colo., has a sophisticated menu that includes
duck foie gras, stuffed brie, wood-grilled salmon and five-spice
duck. Yet the dress code is so casual that shorts are acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   One resident says when Angeluna opened, it turned people off
because it was a little bit ``too Aspen.'' The owners toned down
the restaurant's attitude a bit, and it is now a popular gathering
spot.
</P>
<P>
   But if Sundance Square sounds a little too yuppiefied, then head
out to the Stockyards National Historic District, a few miles
northwest of downtown. Here it's easy to walk the brick-lined
streets of the area, which still looks much like it did at the turn
of the last century, and pretend you're in the west of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   The Stockyards once was teeming with real cowboys, who drove
their cattle to auction. At one time, it was the second-largest
stockyard in the country and home of the nation's two largest
meat-packing companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now most of the authentic cowboys are gone. Tourists predominate
_ particularly the urban cowboy kind.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the area hasn't been sanitized beyond recognition. It
maintains a certain kind of rough authenticity. Parts of the
Stockyards look like a faded movie set, and there's horse manure on
the sidewalk, so watch your step.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go downtown and find the perfect kind of young yuppie.
Here it's dirty, and there's a little bit of (the smell of) beer,''
says Gayle Hill, who owns the Maverick Fine Western Wear and
Saloon.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who owns a general store in the Stockyards that sells
everything from rain wear and kerosene lamps to beer and ice cream
_ ``You can get a beer float, if you want,'' she says _ has seen a
lot of changes over the years.
</P>
<P>
   When she opened the General Store and Trading Post in 1983, she
recalls there were still a few livestock in pens down the street.
Now the building that housed the old hog and sheep pens is called
Stockyards Station and features 30 shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Hill opened her clothing store in a building originally
constructed in 1905 that previously was a private social club and
saloon. She kept the long oak bar as part of the boutique. She now
serves beer and Texas wine to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can shop till you drop,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Susie Ward, a buyer of upscale ladies western wear for the
store, says local people often meet at the bar before going out for
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tourists just think it's fun,'' she says. ``You can shop
in here all day. The men don't mind sticking around.''
</P>
<P>
   Another establishment with a unique attitude is the White
Elephant Saloon, the scene of a famous 1887 gunfight between owner
Luke Short and former Marshal T.I. ``Long Hair Jim'' Courtwright. A
re-enactment of the duel takes place every Feb. 8. On most nights,
live bands perform.
</P>
<P>
   The infamous duo of Bonnie and Clyde once stayed at the
Stockyards Hotel, an authentic-looking three-story hotel built in
1907. The lobby is a throwback to another era, with red velvet
walls, tufted sofas, oak floors and a large staircase leading to
the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   The 52 rooms are decorated in four motifs _ Indian, western,
mountain man and Victorian. One of the Western rooms has a cowhide
headboard, a bleached skull on the walls and a nightlight made of
spurs.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to feel what it's like on a horse without riding
one, head to the hotel bar, Booger Red's Saloon, where saddles are
used as bar stools.
</P>
<P>
   Or walk over to Billy Bob's Texas, which is billed as ``the
world's largest honky-tonk.'' The 100,000-square-foot entertainment
center is a country-western amusement park of sorts for adults.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to live music every night with a big dance floor for
Texas two-steppin', the complex has a clothing store, ``cosmic
cowboy'' video games, pool tables and 40 bars.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, live bull riding takes place in an adjoining arena,
and icons of country music perform.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent night, five business types threw caution to the wind
in a corner of the complex and decided to have their picture made
on a stuffed bull.
</P>
<P>
   The photographer covered their suits with chaps, bandanas and
cowboy hats and artfully arranged them on various parts of the
bull. Then she instructed them to holler, ``Yee haw!'' and snapped
the picture.
</P>
<P>
   After disembarking from the bull, the group huddled around a
computer screen to see the photograph. They eagerly shelled out $10
for a copy of their cowboy experience.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that what Fort Worth is all about?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHERE TO FIND THEM: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
