<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7346 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN29-COX     07-28 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History surrounds town that dried up due to a well
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE GROVE _ Hot and tired after a hard day in the saddle, the
four of us rode into town from the west, dismounted and went into
the general store.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly 121 years earlier on another hot July day, the legendary
outlaw Sam Bass and his boys also rode into town from the west on
the same road. They also dismounted and walked into the the town's
general store.
</P>
<P>
   Not much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Bass and his cohorts picked out various foodstuffs from the
store's shelves and bins and ate their meal in the store.
</P>
<P>
   The store owner, W.J. Graham, didn't know the men.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men got up and walked over to Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you do,'' the stranger asked, ``if Sam Bass walked
in here and told you to give him all your money?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell him to go to hell,'' replied the storekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you say if I told you that you're talking to Sam
Bass right now?'' asked the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'd say that's a different matter,'' said Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Bass and his men laughed at Graham's response.
</P>
<P>
   The outlaws finished their meal, mounted up and continued east
to Salado and Round Rock where banks waited to be robbed.
</P>
<P>
   Bass never made it back to Graham's store. Tipped off, Texas
Rangers fought a fierce gun battle with Bass, who is buried in the
Round Rock cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   W.J. Graham told this story to his grandson, J. D. ``Unc''
Graham whose Planters State Bank in one corner of the general store
was robbed in 1927 by bank robbers who pulled up in a Model T Ford,
walked past seven men sitting on a bench outside the current store
and walked out a few minutes later with $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to picture the men sitting on the bench outside the
store where our motorcycles are parked and where the same bank
remains in the same corner of the store.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, in the middle of the same dusty street, is the water
well that Sam Bass and his men rode past. Some people say the well
killed the town.
</P>
<P>
   The Grove, named after a clump of live oak trees, was founded
alongside a buffalo trail by Wendish colonists in the mid-1800s.
They dug a 28-foot well that became an unending source of fresh
water and pride.
</P>
<P>
   The town grew and traffic grew along the road that connected
Gatesville and Temple. The well sat, and still sits, right in the
middle of the road.
</P>
<P>
   When the highway department decided to build a nice new road
through The Grove in the 1930s, the engineers said the well had to
go. The townspeople said no.
</P>
<P>
   State Highway 36 went around The Grove. Slowly but surely,
businesses began to close.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Austin antique collector Moody Anderson happened
into town, the town's bank, post office, doctor's office,
blacksmith's shop, cotton gin and Masonic Lodge were closed. J.D.
Graham and his general store were just hanging on.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson spotted a wealth of antiques in the store. ``Every time
I tried to buy something, the old man said, 'It's not for sale,'''
Anderson told us as we relaxed over cold soft drinks in the
Cocklebur Saloon next door to the old general store. Except for the
well out front, the town is dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally gave up and got in my car and started to leave when
I had an idea,'' Anderson said. ``I went back inside and offered to
buy the building and all its contents. He sold everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson bought other old buildings in town and moved in a
lifetime collection of antiques.
</P>
<P>
   The Grove is a trip back in time. It is open for tours on
Saturdays and Sundays for $2 a head. It also can be rented for
private parties or movie sets, which doesn't sit too well with some
of the descendents of people who dug the town's well.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
