<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will develop Thursday
across parts of the Middle Atlantic states as a pool of cold air at
19,000 feet moving over hot, humid air near the ground destabilizes
the atmosphere. A few thunderstorms will approach severe levels,
with strong winds posing a threat. Heavy rain and street flooding
are also possible.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will affect parts of the Great Lakes
and the Ohio Valley, as hot, humid air from the southwest is forced
to rise over pockets of rain-cooled air left over from Wednesday's
storms. Meanwhile, isolated, potent thunderstorms will erupt over
the Southeast in response to instability created by hot air near
the ground and cooler air filtering south at high altitudes.
Downpours are likely in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   A few thunderstorms will erupt over parts of the Tennessee and
middle Mississippi Valleys in response to uneven heating along
boundaries between rapidly heated air and pockets of cooler air
left in the wake of Wednesday's storms.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, scattered showers and thunderstorms will develop
across much of the Rockies as moisture streaming north from the
tropics at 10,000 feet combines with the uneven heating of
mountains and valleys to generate currents of rising, moist air.
Isolated storms will develop in California's northern Sierra Nevada
and Oregon's Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated thunderstorms will patrol the Gulf Coast from northeast
Texas to Florida as the leading edge of the sea breeze presses
inland and lifts hot, humid air.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Summer in the City
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the mercury hit 95 degrees in Central Park in New
York City, marking the eleventh time this month with temperatures
of 95 degrees or more. This tally of 95-degree days sets the
all-time standard for any month in the Big Apple. Though there have
been pockets of extreme heat in July, this summer, nationally
speaking, is not yet in a league with some of the record hot
summers of the past. During the summer of 1936, when there was
widespread, protracted heat, Kansas City recorded 53 days with
temperatures over 100 degrees, a benchmark for hot summers.
</P>
</TEXT>
