<HEADLINE>
ALTHOUGH DIFFERENT AND PRONE TO BICKERING, DALLAS AND FORT WORTH
ARE FLOURISHING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When checking into the Mansion on Turtle Creek, the
toniest hotel in Dallas and one of the ritziest in the world, a man
remarked that his flight from Houston was bumpy and the plane was
old. (That's what the Southwest Airlines flight attendant said to
explain the lack of overhead storage space.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you a pilot?'' the hotel receptionist, dressed in a
dramatic black pants outfit and designer glasses, asked
nonchalantly, as if everyone owns a personalized Lear jet.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Dallas, where image is everything.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, over at the Maverick Fine Western Wear and
Saloon in the Fort Worth Stockyards, owner Gayle Hill lamented the
fact that her part of the world has cleaned up its act over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled that two decades ago, the fancy hotel across the
street was a ``two-bit flophouse'' and the ladies of the evening
stole items from a drugstore she owned at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '70s, there were some old-time scum-bag bars and some
colorful characters around here,'' she said. ``When I think of it
that way, I kind of miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``It's still pretty authentic out here,'' she said.
``We still have some cowboys and down-and-out poets. It's not
Disneyland, knock on wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Fort Worth, where down-home style remains a way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Like a mismatched couple trapped in a rocky marriage, Dallas and
Fort Worth are constantly at odds. Folks in Fort Worth often
consider their Dallas counterparts ``uppity'' (one joke goes like
this: What are the two cities in north Texas? Fort Worth and Fort
Worthless) while many Dallasites have been known to look down upon
their Fort Worth brethren as unsophisticated rubes.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the bickering comes from their backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Established on a high bluff overlooking the Trinity river in
1849, Fort Worth was once a rowdy frontier town that served as a
way station for cattlemen driving their herds north on the Chisholm
Trail. When the railroad arrived in 1876, the city served as a
major shipping point for cattle and became known as ``Cowtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Though few real cowboys remain, the city has latched onto its
western heritage with gusto. Officials recently inaugurated a daily
cattle drive as part of the celebration to mark the city's 150th
birthday and tout the Stockyards National Historic District as an
authentic Old West experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of it,'' said Gil Stotler, director of
communications for the Fort Worth Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
``This is where the West begins.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, founded as a trading post in 1839 by a Tennessee lawyer
named John Neely Bryan, has long touted its image as a
sophisticated business, banking and retail center.
</P>
<P>
   Glitzy yet conservative, the city also established itself as a
leader in the areas of fashion, convention business and
transportation, particularly after the gigantic Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport opened in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   While seeking to highlight a haute image _ its tourism
information is sprinkled with the phrase, ``Dallas! The Texas
Star'' _ two events have defined the city in the eyes of the world:
the assassination of John F. Kennedy, which left a black mark on
the city's name, and the hit television series ``Dallas,'' which
rehabilitated it.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Dallas and Fort Worth are different, the two cities
are joined at the hip by location and the desire to impress the
world.
</P>
<P>
   While they argue about everything from who has the better
symphony hall to whether plans to expand Love Field will sabotage
the future of Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport, they have
too much at stake to divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Located 30 miles apart, they are bookends of an area known as
the Metroplex. Once a wide-open prairie, the area is now an endless
mass of suburban sprawl wedged between the two vastly different
cities.
</P>
<P>
   To suspicious Houstonians, the Metroplex seems nothing more than
an artificial term honchos in Dallas and Fort Worth devised to
stake a claim as the state's largest metropolitan area since
neither could claim the title on its own.
</P>
<P>
   While Houston remains the nation's fourth-largest city, with
more than 1.7 million, trailed by Dallas (No. 9 at a little more
than 1 million) and Fort Worth (No. 29 at just over 491,000), the
combined greater Dallas-Fort Worth metropolitan area totals more
than 4.5 million, edging out Houston and its surroundings at about
4.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Chamber of commerce types began looking for a comprehensive name
for the Dallas-Fort Worth area in 1972 to tout it in a national
advertising campaign. Marketing studies indicated the term
``Dallas-Fort Worth'' lacked sizzle, according to an account in the
Dallas Morning News. And too many people thought ``North Texas''
meant Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   So advertising agent Harve Chapman coined the word from
``metropolitan'' and ``complex,'' and it took hold, even though
it's still not listed in Webster's New World Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays just about everybody knows the term refers to the area
of the state stretching from the eastern outskirts of Dallas to the
western environs of Fort Worth, including everything in-between.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the roadside that links Dallas and Fort Worth has that
new and vaguely familiar suburban feel surrounding any major U.S.
city. There are gleaming new high-rise buildings, endless new
housing developments and familiar business names: Pappasito's,
Joe's Crab Shack, CarMax, Target, Ninfa's. If you didn't know
better, you might think you're still in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   However, some things are unique to the Metroplex, such as
wretched excess; a touch of the wild, wild West; the liveliest
downtown in Texas (and maybe the whole United States); and a rail
system that works.
</P>
<P>
   The Metroplex is not exactly Hollywood, but it has a movie
studio.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly Napa Valley, but it has wineries.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly Utopia, but it has some eye-popping sights
worth seeing.
</P>
<P>
   Within the pages of this section, come along for an
unconventional ride.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
