<HEADER>
A7352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN29-COX     07-28 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minister risks others' wrath just by offering to talk
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ This was news.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 20th century, this was news. Way past the fall
of the Berlin Wall, nearly a generation past desegregation, years
into the information age, when more people are connected in more
ways than once imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The news: A Baptist minister proposes a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   It made most newspapers. It made this newspaper. A former
president of the Southern Baptist Convention told a convention of
fellow Christians that it was time to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking past each other and it's time we talked to
each other,'' said the Rev. Jimmy Allen, who for most of the 1970s
led the world's largest Protestant denomination. He was speaking to
a convention of the Universal Fellowship of Metropolitan Community
Churches, the world's largest homosexual church.
</P>
<P>
   Allen doesn't speak for us, assured the Southern Baptist home
office.
</P>
<P>
   What the reverend proposed is pretty dangerous. It's one thing
to talk to someone. It's another to talk with someone, which is how
dialogue is committed. Left uncontrolled, dialogue might spread.
Uncontrolled, understanding can run rampant.
</P>
<P>
   No, it wouldn't be understanding about what makes homosexuals
what they are, or for that matter, how heterosexuals are what they
are.
</P>
<P>
   No, this understanding would embrace what enemies often discover
during cease-fire on smoldering battlefields as the dead and dying
are hustled away: The enemies discover their common humanity, their
utter lack of reason to hate one another.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Southern Baptist war room, a spokesman asserts that
Allen sends dangerous signals, that he may be ``forwarding the
agenda'' of the people he was addressing.
</P>
<P>
   Can Allen be helped, reprogrammed? It appears not. He's stopped
looking at people as pegs on a map. He's started looking at them as
people, even those with a sexual orientation he can't fathom.
</P>
<P>
   This came in part, Allen said through tears, because of a son
who is gay and has HIV. It also came because he watched fellow
Christians shun his own flesh and blood, his grandsons and his
daughter-in-law. Through blood transfusion she had contracted AIDS
and transmitted it to three boys. All three died.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's other son was pastor of a church in Colorado. He got
fired when word got out that his wife and sons were infected.
Another church turned the boys away when they sought to attend
Sunday school.
</P>
<P>
   As Jimmy Allen has made his journey from prejudice to at-peace
with facts of life he can't understand, I hope he hasn't beaten
himself up over his reasons. No doubt he's now realizing that there
was selfishness behind his breakthrough. His son, his son's friends
_ he was defending them.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it takes, I say. Ronald Reagan liked to make strawmen
of those with the ``gay agenda,'' then realized he'd been
dialoguing with a gay man, had invited him to the White House, and
thought the world of him. When Rock Hudson died of AIDS, Reagan
turned down his volume of judgment.
</P>
<P>
   You see, that's why some people are repulsed by suggestions of a
dialogue, because they know where that leads _ to toning things
down.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly you won't hear the TV preachers, commanders of the
airwaves, toning it down. They will, rather, turn it up.
</P>
<P>
   The Berlin Wall is down. The Red Menace has evaporated. How to
martial the troops, to raise the dollars to pay for godly
microwaves? The ``gay agenda,'' of course.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be news, that a pastor, a man of God, would be
talking about a dialogue with fellow believers. But since for some
people the whole dynamic of belief means forming distinct groups
that spend a lot of time focusing on distinctions, I guess what
Allen has done is unusual. Whether or not it is ungodly, you make
the call.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
