<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTER TECHNOLOGY AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Armada M300, Compaq Returns to Ultralight Market
</P>
<P>
   Compaq was one of the first computer makers to develop a really
light laptop, the Aero, but it was a laptop before its time and it
did not sell. This week, the Houston company returned to the
ultralight category with the Armada M300.
</P>
<P>
   Although it weighs only three pounds, the M300 has an 11.3-inch
screen and an almost full-size keyboard. And although it is just an
inch thick, it retains all the connectors on the back, so no
external port replicator is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Many owners of ultralight laptops have complained that to reduce
the weight, the printer and especially the serial port were
removed. The M300 comes with either a Pentium II or Celeron chip
running at 333 megahertz, 64 megabytes of RAM, and up to a
6.4-gigabyte hard drive. The units are to be shipped in August and
start at $1,999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the first ultraportable to the market, but it is one
of the best to get to market,'' said Cheryl Currid, president of
Currid and Co., a Houston technology consulting firm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One external device that potential buyers might consider is the
M300's portable docking station. Compaq calls it the mobile
expansion unit. Its advantage is that it provides a disk drive and
a multibay slot for a CD-ROM, DVD, an LS-120 drive, another hard
drive or another battery.
</P>
<P>
   While it is still necessary to carry around the extra devices,
there are not any cables to lose.
</P>
<P>
   _Stephen C. Miller
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Can Web browsing be hazardous to your health? A recent
ergonomics study suggests that it can be, even more than other
computer tasks.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study of 24 surfers by the ergonomics specialists
Anthony D. Andre and Jeff English, surfing can be particularly
dangerous because it tends to be more of a leisure activity and
people are less aware of their posture and the position of their
hands.
</P>
<P>
   For example, surfers tend to lean away from the mouse, which
puts extra strain on the wrists and elbows. Web page scrolling
forces users to keep constant pressure on the mouse-click button,
which can strain the fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that few participants took advantage of the
natural waiting periods of page downloads and instead kept their
hands on the mouse, a position the report called a ``mouse
freeze.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, which will be presented at the Human Factors and
Ergonomics Society's annual convention in September, recommends
that surfers move closer to the mouse, change position during
downloads, use a scrolling mouse and not lean on their nonsurfing
arm.
</P>
<P>
   And until there is an ergonomic study on the hazards of turning
pages, they could always read a book.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jennifer 8. Lee
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   You can now talk to your Palm III, sort of. Landware
(www.landware &QL; 
.com) introduced the GoVox digital voice recorder at the Macworld
Expo in New York last week. The GoVox recorder, which attaches to
the Palm in place of its lid, allows you to dictate short notes,
memos or reminders.
</P>
<P>
   The recorder is not linked so recordings cannot be translated
directly into text. Speech recognition is still a dream for Palm
owners. For now they must play back their words.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stephen C. Miller
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Free Hard Drive Service Is Available on Internet
</P>
<P>
   A start-up company in Santa Monica, Calif., is offering a free
desktop hard drive service on the Internet. But, like many
Manhattan apartments, the virtual hard drive does not come with a
lot of storage space.
</P>
<P>
   Founded this year, X:drive (www.xdrive.com) will give users 25
megabytes of remote hard drive space that is accessible from any
computer with Internet access. The service is intended for users
with high-speed access to the Internet, so those using modem access
might find X:drive slow, especially with large files.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most previous Internet-based file storage services,
X:drive is not on Web browsers for PC users. Instead, a special
application for Windows 95/98 that creates a hard drive desktop
icon to represent the virtual X:drive can be installed.
</P>
<P>
   Users can save documents directly to the drive or drag and drop
files as they would to a C or A drive. Users of Macintosh and other
platforms must use the slower Web-based interface.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of multigigabyte hard drives, 25 MB can hold only a
few MP3s and a handful of Power Point documents. If you outgrow the
allocated free space, $4.99 a month will buy an additional 25 MB.
</P>
<P>
   _Jennifer 8. Lee
</P>
<P>
   Do Violent Games Sell? Well, Not Necessarily
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the high school shootings in Littleton, Colo.,
the video game industry has been the focus of complaints by
politicians and activists, who contend that its products cause
real-life violence. But recent sales figures indicate that violent
video games are not as pervasive as some believe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics compiled by PC Data, Inc., of Reston,
Va., the best-selling games are relatively free of violence. Doom
and Quake, often cited as examples of violence-laden games, have
combined sales of 4.7 million copies, while Myst and its sequel
Riven, which are relatively nonviolent, have sold 5.5 million
copies. The initial games of both series were released in 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The less violent SimCity series _ SimCity, SimTower, SimEarth _
has sold more than 7 million copies since its release in 1989. The
current version, SimCity 3000 has sold nearly a million copies
worldwide since its release in January of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other perennial best sellers are card games, flight simulators
and chess. The ChessMaster series alone has sold more than 4
million copies since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   _Stephen C. Miller
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   This from the why-didn't-somebody-think-of-this-sooner file:
Compaq recently filed a patent for an ingenious keyboard that uses
the typing motion itself to recharge laptop batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is finding an easy and efficient way to convert the
kinetic energy from typing into electrical energy to run a
computer. Adrian Crisan, a Compaq software engineer, came up with a
conversion mechanism that uses tiny magnets that are attached to
the shaft of each key. When keys are pressed, the magnets move
through wire coils that surround them.
</P>
<P>
   The motion of the magnets induces tiny currents which,
aggregated, charge a capacitor. In turn, the capacitor builds up
charge to recharge the laptop's battery.
</P>
<P>
   While the magnets, coils and charging mechanism will add to the
cost of a computer, the economics of the keyboard have not
completely been determined. Given the instant message habits of
some users, the technique could lead to a kind of perpetual typing
motion machine.
</P>
<P>
   _Jennifer 8. Lee
</P>
<P>
   Software to Translate Between Mac and PC
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, when Brian Landwehr was trying to sell software
that enabled PCs to read Macintosh floppy disks, people probably
thought he was crazy. Here was a product based on two technologies
that surely would soon vanish: Apple computers and floppy
diskettes.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Apple has resurged, floppies are still around
and Landwehr has a new version of his product called MacDrive 98
Version 3. ``Trading files via removable media isn't going away any
time soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MacDrive is a software that can be installed on any Windows PC
to prevent incompatibility problems with removable disks that were
formatted on an Apple computer, including floppy and Zip disks.
</P>
<P>
   People who use the software can put a Mac disk in a Windows
machine and gain access to the files as if they were on a PC disk _
without getting annoying error messages or confusing requests for
reformatting.
</P>
<P>
   Landwehr said the software, which sells for $64.97, is already a
hit with parents who have children using Macs at school and PCs at
home. It can be ordered over the Web, at www.media4.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Lisa Guernsey
</P>
</TEXT>
