<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mourning the death of a fine attorney
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ A good man died too young last week. John
Mitchell, the district judge in San Augustine, died while on
vacation in Mexico. He was 51. It's unclear if he drowned or
suffered a heart attack. Whatever happened, that little county will
feel his loss, as of course will his friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   My first dealings with John came about a week after I moved
there in 1982 to run the ``San Augustine Rambler,'' a tiny weekly
in a town that had two newspapers and 3,000 people. He was city
attorney then, and just a few days after my arrival I covered a
city council meeting where the council blatantly ignored the Open
Meetings Act and went into secret session, just like they'd been
used to doing. I challenged them for doing so, wrote a scathing
editorial about it, and in that editorial pointed out that Mitchell
hadn't said anything to the council about their disregard for the
laws of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It made a bit of a wave, this wet-behind-the-ears newcomer
raising sand not long after getting the U-Haul unpacked. Further, I
was renting a house from the mayor, who lived next door. Eviction
seemed a possibility, though my fears proved misplaced. I was
nervous, being all of 26 years old, as to how my diatribe would be
perceived, especially when John was the Rotary Club speaker the day
after the paper came out. He was giving a talk on estate planning,
as I recall. I was covering it for the paper, Rotary Club speeches
being newsworthy in a town where not much happens day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   I stood up to take his picture to go with the story, and John
stopped, grinned and drawled that he hoped his coverage in ``The
Rambler'' was going to be a bit more favorable next week than it
had been this week. I realized then that I was dealing with someone
a cut above the usual small-town lawyer. The city council, to my
knowledge, never broke the rules after that, and John and I soon
became friends.
</P>
<P>
   Not close friends, understand, but we ran in the same circles
and hung out at various small-town events _ barbecues, the
livestock show, the annual trip to Houston for the rodeo and
cookoff. John and his wife, Lucy, gave the best parties in the
county, held at the old San Augustine railroad depot, which they
had bought and moved onto their farm.
</P>
<P>
   I admired John from somewhat of a distance. He was a hometown
boy who went off, got a law degree from the University of Texas,
married a fine woman and came home to practice small-town law and
help run the family title company. His brother, Charles, now
district attorney, joined not long after. During those dark years
when the Aggies kicked our tails every season, John, Charles, the
Oglesbees and me were the few Teasips in a town dominated in its
college alumni ranks by Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   John seemed to instinctively know how to be a small-town lawyer,
when to hold them and when to fold them. He effected that slow,
Southern speech and deliberate way of speaking and found so much
about life in a small town to be humorous, without being mean or
malicious about it. There was no doubt he genuinely loved that town
and its people, foibles and all.
</P>
<P>
   He and Lucy and their kids lived in town in a fine old house,
and he raised cows on the family place a few miles out of town. I
can blame him and then-County Judge Jack Nichols for me getting a
wild hair and buying cows once in a misguided fit of romanticism,
though it didn't take me long to realize I had about as much
business raising cows as I would have doing brain surgery. They
grew up in the business, and I was a dumb rank amateur.
</P>
<P>
   I rarely saw John in the past 10 years, once or twice as best I
can recall. My life had changed _ a busy job and different family
obligations. I always had it in the back of my head to sneak across
the river sometime and watch him run a courtroom, a job he'd won
since I left 12 years ago. Unfortunately, I never got around to it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm confident he was a fine judge. He had the level-headedness
and intellect, combined with the earthy common-sense that it takes
to dispense justice. I'm sure he found humor in much of what he saw
pass before his bench and that he had compassion when it was
justified.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much else to say, other than I mourn for the pain
his death causes his family and friends. It's a cliche that only
the good die young, but damned if it doesn't seem to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
