<HEADLINE>
CBS LOOKS TO WIDEN ITS AUDIENCE WITH `NOW AND AGAIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ ``Now and Again'' doesn't look like a CBS
show. It certainly doesn't feel like one.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it is a good show, real good one-hour drama (9 p.m.
Fridays, starting in the fall), the best one the network is rolling
out this September. But in an era of network ``branding,'' where
sibling shows are supposed to appear, act and sound the same _
think of the kids with the perfect eyes on the WB _ the unique
``Now and Again'' just doesn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worried about that. But I don't think `Moonlighting' was an
ABC show when it premiered,'' said executive producer Glenn Gordon
Caron, who also produced the singular Bruce Willis/Cybill Shepherd
comedy in the 1980s. ``I sort of follow my own muse and hope other
people are amused.''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of what CBS is doing now. The network got more viewers to
watch its shows last year than any other broadcaster _ and lost
money. That's because The Eye is continuing to try to appeal to
people beyond the lucrative targeted demographics, while other
networks are going for a specific audience in a strategy dubbed
``narrowcasting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, narrowcasting is a dirty word,'' CBS entertainment
president Nancy Tellem said. ``We've been a consistent broadcaster
and hold to that strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season CBS embarked on an effort to go after an audience
that had eluded the network: males and younger people. To a point
CBS succeeded, thanks in great part to the return of the NFL and
shows like ``JAG,'' ``Becker'' and ``Martial Law.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does CBS do for this coming season? It premieres three
female lawyer shows _ ``Family Law,'' ``Judging Amy'' and ``Work
with Me.'' These shows, two dramas and a sitcom, are not exactly
tailored toward young males.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are broadcasters. There are certain shows that appeal to
different people on our network,'' television president Leslie
Moonves said. ``Obviously, the people who will watch `Falcone' (a
Mafia show premiering in mid-season; see below) might not
necessarily be the `Touch By an Angel' fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Moonves continued. ``And I think it is going to
only be to our betterment that the other (networks) are all doing
the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now and Again'' is the story of John Goodman _ except he dies
in the first half. But the insurance salesman's brain and
consciousness are preserved and planted into the perfect
government-built body of Eric Close (``Magnificent Seven'').
</P>
<P>
   There are several side stories, including an extremely spooky
Asian walking around major cities with deadly sarin-filled eggs (in
the opening as the Beatles' ``I Am the Walrus'' plays in the
background). In a word, it's pretty trippy.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly ``Diagnosis Murder,'' is it? More like, what? A Fox
show?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are other networks where it might fit in,'' said
Caron. ``Would it fit in better? I don't know. They (CBS) sense
that it is different and might attract some different eyes for the
network.''
</P>
<P>
   Which makes CBS ... a broadcaster. What a new concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone,'' based on the true story of undercover FBI agent Joe
Pistone as portrayed in the mob flick ``Donnie Brasco,'' is a
strong drama that came around at the right time _ and the wrong
time.
</P>
<P>
   With the success of HBO's ``The Sopranos,'' the time was right
for a taut network Mafia drama. Unfortunately, it came to Les
Moonves' desk a week after the Littleton school massacre. Moonves
was in no mood for death on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have a visceral response to some of the violence
there,'' Moonves said. ``It was too early at that point to say,
yes, let's go ahead and put this on the fall schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we knew qualitatively that it was a terrific
show, one of our best pilots and something that had a lot of fans
throughout the company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' did not make the fall slate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, I was initially disappointed ... but I
understood it,'' executive producer Mark Johnson said. But now the
drama has been slotted as a mid-season replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at some of the tepid fall CBS shows, and the success of
recent mid-season replacements from ``Becker'' (CBS) to
``Providence'' (NBC) and even ``Dilbert'' (UPN), it may have turned
out best for the show after all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1728EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7361 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CROSSWORD-ART-2ND     07-28 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CROSSWORD-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: out there.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROSSWORD WEAVER
</P>
<P>
   Variety Games
</P>
<P>
   $49.95 with Diskette and Manual, $39.95 downloaded from company
website
</P>
<P>
   Windows 3.1, 95, 98 &AMP; NT
</P>
<P>
   Upon opening Crossword Weaver, any computer user will feel right
at home. The interface features familiar pull-down menu options and
button shortcuts to click on. The left side of the screen is filled
with a blank puzzle grid, and the right side has a tabbed notebook
for easy puzzle creation. There is little need to consult the
manual.
</P>
<P>
   This program is ideal for designing a puzzle quickly.
Construction is easy, but control and customization are not. If you
want a program that will rapidly create a puzzle for you, and using
your own vocabulary and design is not a priority, this is a good
software package to purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The program will construct a puzzle using only words you have
entered, or it will mix in words from its own dictionary to create
a tighter puzzle. If you choose to use the hybrid, you can design
your own layout or choose from the program's 50 stock patterns. You
can also choose from several different symmetry tools, which add
balance to the pattern for a professional-looking design. While the
idea of a tight, polished puzzle has obvious appeal, you will have
to turn to the Crossword Weaver's dictionary to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   This program puts more emphasis on layout than word choice. When
I used the Mix Dictionary Words function, the resulting puzzle
included very few of my own words. For example, in one puzzle
attempt, the program was able to create its own loosely constructed
layout and include 29 of my 42 answer words, but when I added the
Mix Dictionary Words function to make a tighter or more interesting
design, only nine of my words were included in the puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot choose to use a tightly laid out puzzle or a custom
design without adding dictionary words. I found that to be limiting
because an interesting shape can add to the impact of a puzzle,
particularly for children. Including dictionary words can have
negative consequences, making a puzzle appropriate for a different
age group or for a different educational purpose.
</P>
<P>
   These limitations can get in the way. I attempted to create a
puzzle for a friend's 30th birthday party but was forced to choose
either a computer-assigned pattern or a puzzle with dictionary
words that had no relationship to my birthday theme.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual feature of Crossword Weaver is a database of clues
available for the dictionary words. The program provides clues for
60,000 words. There is also a button to show alternate clues, which
allows the user to choose among several clue options. The program
turns to its clue database both when using the dictionary for word
selection and when entering custom words.
</P>
<P>
   While I was surprised that the program did not include a button
to import word lists from other software programs, like a
vocabulary list, I found it easy to do anyway. I created a list in
my word-processing program, saved it on my hard drive as a
text-only file and then clicked on the Add Words From File button.
</P>
<P>
   While this program has some obvious shortcomings, it can be a
quick and easy solution to crossword creation. I would not
recommend it, however, for creating crosswords that have special
shapes or that need to stick to a specific set of words.
</P>
<P>
   CROSSWORKS
</P>
<P>
   Homeware, $29.50
</P>
<P>
   Windows 3.1, 95, 98, NT
</P>
<P>
   There is a friendly, welcoming look to Crossworks. The program
seems to have been created with competent users in mind. If you
know what you want to accomplish and are comfortable in a Windows
environment, you can just jump in.
</P>
<P>
   What you will find is one of the most comprehensive crossword
programs, catering to the advanced creator's every need. You may
also find a fair measure of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other programs reviewed here, Crossworks does not
compose puzzles for you. You decide on the design, size and number
and placement of black-out squares. You place the words in the
design and fit them together as you would if you were doing this
with paper and pen, and the program provides a list of words that
will fit into a given across or down sequence.
</P>
<P>
   For example, as I was composing a puzzle I had a space that was
nine letters across to fill; the third letter was R and the word
ended with L. I clicked on Search For Words, and the program
provided 28 words from its puzzle dictionary that fit my space. The
words could be used for various topics and themes, providing many
potential solutions.
</P>
<P>
   To write your clues with Crossworks, you first go to Wordbase,
your personal database, and enter a word. You then have the option
of looking up the word in the dictionary. The dictionary's list of
synonyms can be used to help write your clue.
</P>
<P>
   After setting your grid layout in the main screen, you can
toggle between the across and down words by right-clicking your
mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the program's assistance, I found it frustrating to
create puzzles. For example, when I needed words to fill specific
gaps in a puzzle pattern, I found that such words simply did not
exist in the program's 100,000-word dictionary. I would face the
same problem in building a puzzle independently, of course.
Creating a good crossword puzzle is an art; the software helps by
showing you sooner, rather than later, if the words you need do not
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Crossworks has a section that can be used to help you solve a
puzzle from another source. I found the process simple but only
mildly helpful on a newspaper puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   The steps are easy. First you copy the black-square pattern of
the puzzle onto the grid, then you begin solving the puzzle. The
program has a function that allows you to type in the letters you
know of a word and keywords from the clues. The program uses its
dictionary to provide a list of alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   While I loved the idea of getting a little help, the software
was unable to assist me with most of my attempts to figure out
clues. And solving puzzles on screen was neater but somehow less
satisfying than the pencil-and-eraser method.
</P>
<P>
   CROSSWORD MAGIC
</P>
<P>
   Mindscape
</P>
<P>
   Available only through www.learningcompanyschool.com, $59.95
</P>
<P>
   Windows 95 and 98, and Macintosh OS 7.1 to 7.05
</P>
<P>
   I was somewhat surprised that upon opening Mindscape's Crossword
Magic, I was faced with a full blank screen containing only a
background color and a short menu bar along the top edge. There was
no puzzle grid, no eye-catching icon to draw you in. This was not
the impressive start I would have expected from one of the
better-known programs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this abrupt start, the program is user friendly, listing
all options in the top pop-up menu and covering all the basics of a
helpful crossword program.
</P>
<P>
   To create a crossword, you can enter your words directly into a
grid, type them in a word menu box, or import them from a
word-processing program. The program will assemble the puzzle and
give you a list of words not yet used. If you wish to put the words
together yourself, simply click on the grid and start typing. The
whole program is intuitively and sensibly designed.
</P>
<P>
   While this program easily allows you to print out colorful
puzzles, playing on the screen provides several helpful options.
The user can show various pieces of information, like the solution
for any one word clue or even the whole puzzle. If the puzzle is
used as a testing tool, that may make cheating too easy, but a
frustrated puzzle solver finds it refreshing to be able to ask for
as much or as little help as needed.
</P>
<P>
   While I was let down by the Crossword Magic interface, its
functionality makes it one of my favorites. There are no fancy
layouts, but it is a fantastic tool for pulling your work together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
