<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NIGHTLINE-REVIEW-N     07-28 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NIGHTLINE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BRAVE NEW WORLD': AWHIRL IN A SHORT-ORDER SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Program notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Please check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, it is possible to have an intelligent conversation on
television that is enhanced with visual approaches to matters of
the moment. If you doubt it, tune into ``Brave New World,'' the
eight-part ``Nightline'' look at the way the world is changing
around us and how those changes may be affecting human personality.
</P>
<P>
   With assistance from Silicon Valley enthusiasts, musical groups,
dancers, animators and others, ABC's engaging Robert Krulwich
orchestrates discussions on the fascination with speed, the promise
of robots, the appeals of cloning, the threat of extinction, the
nature of quarks, the life of a microbe and other provocative
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's opening program takes up speed in various
manifestations. Why is it, asks Krulwich, that everything seems to
go much faster these days, yet people keep getting less and less
patient? Rooting for speed and more speed is Michael Malone, who
edits Forbes A.S.A.P., a magazine devoted to an ever faster life,
which he maintains is a natural human need.
</P>
<P>
   Immediate gratification is everybody's goal. The telephone user
who not so long ago was content to wait a few seconds for a call to
be answered now loses patience at about the second ring. Malone
observes that ``we are trying to save time so we can live.'' The
trouble is that ``time is the hardest thing in the world to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   In a droll aside on the way speed incorporates itself into daily
life, Krulwich reports on how a short-order cook on Long Island
adapts to preparing 10 different breakfasts simultaneously so
customers can get what they want as soon as they want it, which is
right now. That leads to a discussion of the brain's automatic
response to the call of duty.
</P>
<P>
   As technology works on our expectations of instant satisfaction,
so the argument goes, it also changes us physically, which allows
for even less patience. Krulwich suggests that humans are rushing
around ever faster in order to stave off fears of dying.
</P>
<P>
   How serious he is about that, I cannot say, but such speculation
gives these programs their edge. Now, if only everybody would slow
down a little, we might have even more reflective television.
</P>
<P>
   NIGHTLINE IN PRIME TIME
</P>
<P>
   `BRAVE NEW WORLD'
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Thursday night at 10 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Willis, executive producer; Peter Demchuk and Lisa Koenig,
senior producers; Ted Gerstein, George Griffin and Mary Beth
Kirchner, producers.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FATHER-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     07-28 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY FATHER, DANCING': FLAWED FATHERS, DAUGHTERS WHO LOVE AND
LEARN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Mr. Sweetly Indecent,'' one of the most accomplished
stories in Bliss Broyard's wonderful first collection, ``My Father,
Dancing,'' the first-person narrator catches sight of her father
kissing a strange woman on the Manhattan street where he rents a
pied-a-terre. The narrator has just left an apartment nearby where
she has spent the night with a man she met through a friend at
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the next few days I waited for the phone to ring,'' she
reports. ``Neither man called,'' she continues, subtly reducing her
father to the class of the inconstant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to do anything,'' her father tells her when they
eventually meet for dinner at a restaurant to discuss what she has
seen. ``It doesn't change the way I feel about your mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ```But it makes everything such a lie,' I say, my voice now
catching with held-back tears. `What about our family, all the
dinners, Sunday mornings around the breakfast table, the walks we
love to take. ...' ''
</P>
<P>
   ```No. No. All of that is true. This doesn't change any of
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she is deeply troubled, and her parents, noting her
distress, treat her ``like I am sick or have just suffered some
great loss'' when she spends the weekend at their home in the
suburbs. After a tense Sunday dinner, she retreats to the kitchen
and is tempted to smash a platter in anger. Instead she peeks out
at them, still sitting at the table, and is reminded of a scene in
the past when she saw her father kneel before her mother and she
thought he was asking her to marry him again.
</P>
<P>
   But ``this time what I remember is the righteousness of my
mother's posture as she sat across from my father and tossed off
remarks and the guilty urgency of my father's movements as he sank
to his knees at her feet, and how there was something slightly
orchestrated about their behavior, as though their exchange had a
long history to it.''
</P>
<P>
   All the fathers are flawed in these stories, seductive and
overbearing. The daughters love and learn. In the collection's
comic masterpiece, ``The Trouble with Mr. Leopold,'' the resulting
tension breaks into open conflict. Celia attends the posh
Woodbridge Country Day School, where it is a tradition for
volunteering parents to prune the garden every fortnight, until the
topiary has become ``no longer recognizable.'' When Leopold assigns
Celia to write a film review, she turns for help to her father,
himself a reviewer (as was the author's father, Anatole Broyard, a
book critic for The New York Times), who in a burst of impatience
does the work for her.
</P>
<P>
   When the piece he writes gets a C-plus (Leopold having
recognized the author), Celia's father is outraged and over her
protests sets out to get Leopold fired. As her father harangues the
school's headmaster, Celia sits in the garden smoking an illegal
cigarette and reflects on the misshapen shrubbery. ``As I looked
around at the ungainly figures, any hint of their original outlines
lost long ago, I thought how of all the things that I could be sad
about today, this continuance of care made me the saddest, these
valiant, misguided efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the father will always haunt his daughter. In the title
piece, ``My Father, Dancing,'' the narrator, attending her father,
dying of cancer, in a hospital, recalls how he liked to dance with
her. ``As my body grew and pushed out in new places, I wriggled
these parts and tried on different movements, the way I would try
on new clothes,'' she writes. ``He was my first male audience, and
I used him as a mirror to understand what I looked like to the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once my father told me he wanted to be the first man to break
my heart,'' she continues, ``because then he could insure that at
least it would be done gently.'' But as she sits by him in the
hospital and waits vainly for some sign from him, ``I realized that
he was breaking my heart and it wasn't gentle at all.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Broyard's writing has any flaw, it is her dialogue, which
tends to be a little stiff and monochromatic. You would think a
sophisticated woman like Victoria in ``At the Bottom of the Lake''
would escape the author's habit of using ``like'' instead of ``as
if'': `` `That's absolutely fascinating, Frank,' said Victoria.
`God, I'd forgotten how miserable that drive is. I feel like I've
been up for days.'''
</P>
<P>
   But it is between the lines that Ms. Broyard's writing is most
effective. Between the lines, her personae confront the sexuality
with which their fathers overwhelm them. In ``Snowed In,'' a group
of boys and girls are stranded together and self-consciously play
sex games. Lily, the protagonist, gets drunk and falls asleep.
Bobby Callahan undresses her, then lowers his pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he leaned forward to crouch over her again, he saw that
Lily's eyes were open,'' the text reads. ``Look away, he thought.
Say something. Finally he rocked backward to his heels and yanked
his pants back up, hopped off the bed and walked out of the room.''
</P>
<P>
   The final paragraph of the story repeats the experience from
Lily's point of view. ``She kept waiting. ... Only now it was for
him to touch her again, and when at last she felt his fingertips on
her cheek, down her body, leaving warm traces on each place he
touched, she wasn't sure what she wanted. But when she opened her
eyes, the distance between them was much less than she imagined it
would be _ his face hovered over hers _ and she saw that what was
about to happen wasn't something that could be turned on or off at
whim. And once she saw that, she couldn't look away.''
</P>
<P>
   In these eight arresting stories, Ms. Broyard proves herself a
powerful writer who never looks away.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MY FATHER, DANCING'
</P>
<P>
   By Bliss Broyard
</P>
<P>
   189 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
