</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: ROUTINE CHECKS ON HOT WATER HEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Water entering your house from the municipal water supply comes
in cold. Before it gets to your faucets, some of the water is
diverted to a hot water heater, so that when you open the faucet,
hot water runs out.
</P>
<P>
   A hot water heater is essentially a large, glass-lined steel
tank with a heater under it. A layer of insulation surrounds the
tank, and the entire unit is enclosed in a sheet-metal jacket.
</P>
<P>
   The typical hot water heater is a self-contained appliance that
works automatically. Unless the unit malfunctions, most homeowners
rarely give it a second thought. Most hot water heaters last about
10 years, but this life span can often be extended if the unit is
properly cared for. An annual inspection followed by a little
routine maintenance can often keep your hot water heater
functioning properly.
</P>
<P>
   Start by looking at the control box and thermostat control near
the bottom of the tank. The thermostat control should be set to 140
degrees Fahrenheit. If the control is higher, at 160 degrees or
more, it could put more stress on the tank causing it to burn out
prematurely. Even a 140-degree setting may be too high if you have
small children or elderly members in your family; for safety
reasons, you may want to lower the setting to 130 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Also near the bottom of the tank is a faucet, called a hose bib,
that can be opened to flush the tank. Flushing the tank removes
sediment deposits that block the transmission of heat from the
burner to the tank water. This reduces the efficiency of the burner
so it takes longer produce hot water.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for this, homeowners often raise the thermostat
control. This results in higher energy bills and can shorten the
life of the tank by increasing thermal stresses. Sediment deposits
also contribute to tank corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   To flush the system, first shut off the water supply to the
heater. Then place a bucket under the faucet, or run a hose from
the faucet to a nearby drain. Open the valve and allow the water to
flow out. At first the water may be dark brown and heavy with rust
and muck. Keep the faucet open until the water runs clear.
</P>
<P>
   Older hot water heaters may need to be flushed more often, every
couple of months. Frequent flushings that carry a lot of sediment
are an indication that the lining in the tank has eroded and the
unit is nearing the end of its useful life. Another sign of buildup
is an audible gurgling or rumbling sound caused by air bubbles
rising through the sediment layer to the water above.
</P>
<P>
   Near the top of the hot water heater you should find a pressure
relief valve, possibly fitted with a long downspout. The pressure
relief valve is a safety feature that is found on most, but not
all, hot water heaters. (If your hot water heater doesn't have this
feature, consider having a plumber install one.) It senses when
water pressure inside the tank is rising to unsafe levels. It
automatically opens to relieve the pressure before it can burst the
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Part of your inspection should include a pressure relief-valve
test. Place a bucket under the downspout, then lift the lever on
top of the valve. Release it so it snaps back; the valve should
discharge a burst of water through the downspout. If it doesn't,
the valve is defective and should be replaced by a plumber.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a gas-fired hot water heater, you should inspect the
burner unit and vacuum the burner chamber. Remove the cover to the
burner chamber and look at the burner flame. The flame should burn
with a steady blue color. A yellow flame color is an indication
that the burner needs to be cleaned and readjusted. This is a job
for a heating specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Turn off the unit and allow it to cool before vacuuming around
the burner. Use a crevice wand attachment to vacuum up all rust and
dirt deposits around the burner.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a gas hot water heater you should make a backdraft
test at the hood (also called a vent hat) on the vent duct. The
vent duct delivers combustion gases from the burner to outside the
house. It is important that all the gases be pulled up through the
duct. This is called a positive flow. To check the flow, hold a
smoking incense stick near the vent hood. The smoke from the stick
should be drawn up under the hood into the vent pipe. If the smoke
blows away from the duct, there is a malfunction. This should be
corrected as soon as possible by a heating specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Edward R. Lipinski is author of ''The New York Times Home Repair
Almanac,'' published by Lebhar-Friedman Books.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
