<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7379 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     07-28 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV15-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., AUG. 15, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am building in some cabinets and work tables in my home
office and plan to make these units of plywood. I plan to finish
with stain and varnish rather than paint so what can you suggest to
cover up or conceal the raw edges of the plywood?
</P>
<P>
   A: The simplest and most common way to hide plywood edges is to
cover the raw edges with strips of wood veneer that come in tape
form and in various tones or wood species. The ``tape'' is usually
glued on. Another method often used to cover exposed plywood edges
is to glue or nail on solid wood strips or moldings, as shown in
the accompanying drawing. Corner joints can be concealed and the
edges covered by using corner molding that wraps around and
overlaps the corner joint, while single edges can be covered by
gluing on half-round, quarter-round, or cove-type moldings similar
to the ones illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are having a problem with mildew forming on the outside
walls of some rooms in our house. We applied a coat of stain killer
before painting over this mildew, but the mildew stains came back
in less than one year. How can I permanently get rid of this mildew
problem without repainting every year or so?
</P>
<P>
   A: Before painting over a mildewed surface you should first
clean off and kill the mildew by wiping on a solution of one part
liquid laundry bleach mixed with three parts water. Allow this to
dry on the surface for 10 or 15 minutes, then rinse off with lots
of plain water. Repaint with one coat of a shellac-base stain
killer, then finish with one or two coats of a paint that contains
extra mildewcide (some paint stores sell small bottles of extra
mildewcide that you can add to the paint).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our downstairs bathroom frequently has an awful smell _
almost like an open sewer. The fixtures have suitable traps and
these are not clogged. At our plumber's suggestion we had the vent
pipe above the roof extended higher, but the problem still
persists. Do you have any idea what else we can do?
</P>
<P>
   A: One possible caused is a partially clogged vent line. Another
is a missing or improperly installed vent line that is supposed to
connect each fixture to the main vent stack. I would suggest
calling in an experienced plumbing contractor to check out the
entire drain-waste and vent system connected to that bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We moved into our present home a couple of years ago and have
been having a constant problem with dampness in the basement after
every period of heavy rain. We can see no actual leaks, but we can
see a number of damp spots on the walls, especially near the floor.
Can we get rid of this dampness by applying a waterproofing paint
of some kind to the bare concrete?
</P>
<P>
   A: If there are no actual cracks, holes or other defects in the
masonry _ merely a slight seepage that is coming through the
concrete walls from outside _ then it is possible that a waterproof
paint or sealer applied on the inside may help. However, you should
also check around the outside to make certain that the ground
slopes away from the foundation on all sides so that water coming
down from the downspouts is carried away from the basement walls
before it can seep into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``MOLDINGS TO COVER RAW PLYWOOD EDGES''
goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Exposed plywood edges can be covered up by installing
strips of wood molding to hide the raw edges.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
