<HEADER>
A7383 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-28 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO KNOW HIM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Front-running Republican presidential candidate  &UR; George W. &LR; 
 &UR; Bush &LR;  has hired a Houston Chronicle sports columnist to ghost-write
his autobiography, reports Washingtonian magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The client list of ghost  &UR; Mickey Herskowitz &LR;  includes  &UR; Dan &LR; 
 &UR; Rather &LR; ,  &UR; Mickey Mantle &LR; ,  &UR; John Connally &LR; ,  &UR; Howard Cosell &LR; ,  &UR; Gene &LR; 
 &UR; Tierney &LR; ,  &UR; Bette Davis &LR;  and  &UR; Tom Kite &LR; , says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Before the authorized bio hits bookstore shelves,  &UR; Molly &LR; 
 &UR; Ivins &LR;  has one on the calendar for January. The title: ``Shrub: The
Short But Happy Political Life of George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. When the Washington Post asked Bush recently whether his
youthful escapades had ever included cocaine, he said that he had
``learned from my mistakes'' and that he wouldn't say more. ``This
is a game where they float rumors, force a person to fight off a
rumor. And I'm not going to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IS THE DOCTOR IN THE HOUSE? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A collection of Impressionist paintings bought and owned by Dr.
Paul-Ferdinand Gachet is wowing visitors to the Metropolitan Museum
of Art, but  &UR; Vincent Van Gogh &LR; 's first version of his ``Portrait of
Dr. Gachet'' seems to be missing.
</P>
<P>
   The work was bought nine years ago by  &UR; Ryoei Saito &LR; , a Japanese
businessman, for $82 million. When he learned that his heirs would
have to pay an inheritance tax on the work, he threatened to burn
it. Although Saito died three years ago, the painting has not been
seen since. A Met official told the BBC that the portrait ``may no
longer exist.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Martin Scorsese &LR; , 56, has announced his marriage, in New York
on July 22, to book editor  &UR; Helen Morris &LR; , 52, whom he met while
they worked on a companion book to ``Kundun.'' Morris is wife No. 5
for Scorsese, and he is her second husband.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charged.com has proclaimed the Top 10 Hairdos of History, a
list headed by the  &UR; Julius Caesar &LR; , ``the emperor of all
haircuts.'' Meanwhile,  &UR; Leelee Sobieski &LR;  told Details magazine that
she collects locks of hair from celebrities, but  &UR; Kathie Lee &LR; 
 &UR; Gifford &LR;  refused to participate in anything that might result in
hair rearrangement. Instead, she gave her a cast-off hairbrush,
from which a sample could be collected.
</P>
<P>
   _ In an introduction to Psalms in a new Grove/Atlantic Press
paperback edition of the King James Bible,  &UR; Bono &LR;  of U2 calls King
 &UR; David &LR;  ``the  &UR; Elvis &LR;  of the Bible,'' reports New York magazine. The
comparison apparently is based on looks rather than songwriting
ability.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bitterwaitress.com, a Web site that includes testimonials _
and, possibly, wild allegations _ from workers in the food trade,
has tarred both  &UR; Madonna &LR;  and  &UR; Willie Brown &LR;  with the 10
percent-tipper brush. ``It's not true,'' said  &UR; Michel Bonnet &LR; ,
owner of Le Central, where the mayor often eats. ``He's a fair and
very reasonable tipper, between 15 and 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Outside the Shattuck Avenue post office in Berkeley,  &UR; Joan &LR; 
 &UR; Finton &LR;  saw a nicely dressed man stooped over a manhole cover,
across which he was dragging _ by means of a red string tied around
the heel _ a woman's shoe in which a weight had been placed. The
researcher told Finton he was doing a study on the ``coefficient of
friction on a manhole cover, in case people slip.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Newspaper editor  &UR; Horace Greeley &LR; 's handwriting was so bad,
says the latest issue of Smithsonian, that no one could read it.
One staff member Greeley had fired via a handwritten note ``was
able to pass the note off as a letter of recommendation and
promptly land himself another job.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tony Schwartz &LR;  writes in New York magazine about the benefits
and pitfalls of e-mail, ``the quick pick-me-up that's scarily
addictive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the name of better and speedier communication,'' he notes,
``e-mail can be rude, clipped, superficial and depressingly
desiccated. A boon when it comes to making lunch dates and
answering yes-or-no questions, it is also an insistent source of
distraction from more demanding work. E-mail has proved fiercely
addictive _ cocaine for compulsive achievers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy secretary follows in the footsteps of American
greats such as Abraham Lincoln and Walt Whitman, and the new beard
will positively assist him in carrying out a visionary agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Sklar, executive director of the Solar Energy Industries
Association in Washington, praising Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson's new beard. Sklar, who wears a beard, said it implies
``support of renewable energy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
