<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7387 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-AUGUST-RECIPES29     07-28 3394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-AUGUST-RECIPES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summertime - and the cooking is easy
 &HT;    By Susan Puckett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frogmore Stew
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time:
20-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This Lowcountry classic is casual summer eating at its best.
Halve or double the recipe depending on the number of diners;
spread out newspapers on the table and put a bowl in the middle for
tossing the shrimp shells as you peel and eat them. Have some
crusty bread for dunking in the spicy liquid.
</P>
<P>
   4 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons Old Bay seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 celery ribs, cut in 2-inch
</P>
<P>
   pieces (optional)
</P>
<P>
   4 medium or 8 small red-skinned potatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 ears corn, husks and silks removed and ears cut in half
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound chorizo or other spicy smoked sausage, cut in 2-inch
lengths
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds large shrimp, peeled or unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   In an extra-large stockpot over high heat, combine the water,
salt, Old Bay, red pepper flakes and celery. Bring to a boil; cook
for 5 minutes. Skim and discard any foam that rises to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Add potatoes and cook just until fork-tender, 10-20 minutes
depending on size of potatoes. Add corn and sausage; cook 3-5
minutes longer. Add shrimp and cook until pink and opaque. Serve in
shallow bowls with some of the spicy liquid, if desired, for
dunking bread.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 752 calories, 56 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 31), 76 grams carbohydrates, 308
milligrams cholesterol, 1,403 milligrams sodium, 8 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Panzanella (Tuscan Bread Salad)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This easy-to-assemble, rustic salad depends on sturdy
country-style bread that's several days old for its success.
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces stale Italian or country-style bread, crust trimmed if
desired
</P>
<P>
   3 large tomatoes, diced
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 small red onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Greek-style olives, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup torn fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cut bread into fist-size hunks and dip each piece _ one at a
time _ in cool water for about 2 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze as much of the water out of the bread as you can and
crumble it into a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The bread can be as fine as couscous or as large as small
croutons. To the crumbled bread add the tomatoes, garlic, red
onion, olives, basil, vinegar and oil. Season to taste with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 266 calories, 6 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 35 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 340 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Poached Whole Chicken and
</P>
<P>
   Artichokes With
</P>
<P>
   Chipotle Mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't get much easier than this. Everything can be prepared
the night before and kept in the refrigerator. The chicken and
artichokes need little attention once they begin cooking. The
pungent chipotle-spiked mayo is made in the blender in seconds. Any
leftover chicken can be used for chicken salad.
</P>
<P>
   1 2 1/2-to-3-pound whole chicken, giblets removed
</P>
<P>
   1 whole lemon, halved
</P>
<P>
   2 stalks celery, halved
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium onion
</P>
<P>
   3 whole cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon whole peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   Artichokes:
</P>
<P>
   4 artichokes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 whole lemon, halved
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Chipotle mayonnaise for dipping (1 cup good-quality mayonnaise
and 1 chipotle pepper canned in adobo sauce, pureed in a blender
until smooth)
</P>
<P>
   In a stockpot, combine the chicken, lemon, celery, onion,
garlic, bay leaves, thyme, salt and peppercorns. Let it come to a
gentle boil, turn the heat down so that the water barely moves and
poach for 1 hour or until chicken is done.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rinse artichokes, pierce the bottoms with a fork and
place them in a deep pan. Cover with water and add salt, lemon, and
olive oil. Gently boil the artichokes over medium-high heat for
about 40 minutes or until they're tender.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with poached chicken and use chipotle mayonnaise as a
dipping sauce for the artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without mayonnaise): 403 calories, 35 grams
protein, 23 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 52), 15 grams
carbohydrates, 90 milligrams cholesterol, 1,093 milligrams sodium,
7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Mayonnaise, per tablespoon: 94 calories, trace protein, 10 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 99.6), less than 1 gram
carbohydrates, 8 milligrams cholesterol, 80 milligrams sodium,
trace fiber
</P>
<P>
   Black-Eyed Pea and Smoked Ham Salad With Roasted Red
</P>
<P>
   Pepper Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   With convenience items such as canned black-eyed peas and
bottled roasted red peppers, this recipe is a snap. Try it with
country ham for extra flavor.
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bottled roasted red peppers, drained (about 6 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 15-ounce cans black-eyed peas, drained and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound smoked ham, sliced 1/4 inch thick and then diced
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch arugula or mixed field greens, stemmed, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   Place the oil, vinegar, peppers and garlic in the work bowl of a
food processor. Process until smooth. Scrape the dressing into a
small bowl and stir in the salt. Combine the peas, ham and arugula
in a large bowl. Toss with the dressing to coat. Serve immediately.
_ From ``Cool Kitchen'' by Lauren Chattman (Morrow, $22)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 314 calories, 17 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 44), 28 grams carbohydrates, 23
cholesterol, 505 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Asparagus Frittata With Prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   and Mint
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of frittatas is that you can add almost anything to
them. This combination of asparagus, prosciutto and mint is light
and refreshing. For one serving, simply cut the recipe in half and
reduce cooking time to about 12 minutes stovetop and less than 1
minute under the broiler (or until desired amount of brownness.)
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   6 thick asparagus spears, trimmed of tough ends and sliced
diagonally in 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce, or 2 to 4 thin slices, of prosciutto, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   Pepper
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in an ovenproof 8-inch nonstick frying pan or
skillet over medium heat. Add the asparagus, season with salt and
pepper and saute until just tender, about 8 minutes. Reduce heat if
necessary to prevent browning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a bowl, whisk together the eggs, prosciutto, mint
and several grinds of pepper. When the asparagus pieces are just
tender, add the egg mixture to the frying pan and immediately
reduce heat to low. Stir gently to distribute the asparagus evenly,
then stop stirring and let the frittata set slowly over low heat,
about 15 minutes. It will still be runny on the top. Slip the
frying pan under the broiler and broil briefly to set the top.
Check after 1 minute. If not brown enough, broil another 30
seconds. Remove from broiler and invert a serving dish over the
frying pan. Carefully invert the plate and pan together and lift
off the pan. Let cool briefly; it's better served warm than hot.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 316 calories, 24 grams protein, 22 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 63), 5 grams carbohydrates, 660
cholesterol, 411 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Breasts With
</P>
<P>
   Artichokes and Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5-6 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking in parchment is a wonderful way to seal in juices,
especially in the microwave. Plus, it makes cleanup a breeze. Here,
whole garlic cloves become soft and considerably milder as they
cook with the chicken. Squeeze the cloves out of their skins and
spread them on French bread.
</P>
<P>
   2 skinless, boneless chicken breast halves
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) jar marinated artichoke hearts
</P>
<P>
   12 garlic cloves, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon rosemary
</P>
<P>
   Optional seasonings: salt, pepper and paprika to taste
</P>
<P>
   Tear off two 10-by-14-inch pieces of parchment (see note). Fold
in half and trim edges to form a half-moon shape. Place chicken
breast half to one side of crease on each piece of parchment.
Arrange half the artichokes (reserve marinade) and garlic around
each piece of chicken. Sprinkle with rosemary and other seasonings;
drizzle with marinade from artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   Fold over parchment edges to close and crimp to seal. Place on a
plate. Microwave on high 5-6 minutes, just until the chicken is
white throughout but still juicy. Let stand 2 to 3 minutes. Serve
in the parchment on a dinner plate. _ Adapted from ``365 Quick and
Easy Microwave Recipes'' by Thelma Pressman (Harper and Row)
</P>
<P>
   Note: Parchment is available in cookware shops and some
supermarkets. If you prefer, the chicken can be baked in individual
airtight foil pouches in a 350-degree oven for 30 to 40 minutes.
For guests, double or triple the recipe and set them all on a
cookie sheet. (Parchment may be used in the oven, but foil should
not be used in the microwave.)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 344 calories, 55 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 25), 7 grams carbohydrates, 145
milligrams cholesterol, 186 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Taco Salads
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   You can now buy in most supermarkets the ready-made tortilla
shells used for taco salads in restaurants _ or you can make your
own. Or, just crumble tortilla chips over the top.
</P>
<P>
   8 prepared tortilla shells (purchased or prepared according to
directions below)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground beef or turkey
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground red pepper (cayenne)
</P>
<P>
   1 can (15 1/2 ounces) kidney beans, drained (reserve empty can
if preparing tortilla shells)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium head lettuce, torn into bite-size pieces (about 10
cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded Cheddar cheese (4 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sliced ripe olives
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup Thousand Island Dressing or bottled dressing
</P>
<P>
   1 avocado, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Prepare Tortilla shells (see below). Cook ground beef in 10-inch
skillet, stirring occasionally, until brown; drain. Stir in water,
chili powder, cumin, salt, garlic powder, red pepper and kidney
beans. Heat to boiling; reduce heat. Simmer uncovered 15 minutes,
stirring occasionally; cool 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mix lettuce, cheese, olives, tomatoes and onion in large bowl.
Toss with Thousand Island Dressing. Pour ground beef mixture over
top and toss. Divide among Tortilla Shells. Garnish with avocado
and sour cream. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Tortilla shells: Remove label and both ends of reserved kidney
bean can. Wash and dry can. Heat oil (1 1/2 inches) in 3-quart
saucepan to 375 degrees. (Diameter of saucepan should be at least 9
inches.) Place one 10-inch flour tortilla on top of saucepan. Place
can on center of tortilla with long-handled tongs. Push tortilla
into oil by gently pushing can down. Fry tortilla about 5 seconds
or until set; remove can with tongs. Fry tortilla 1 to 2 minutes
longer, turning tortilla in oil, until tortilla is crisp and golden
brown. Carefully remove tortilla from oil and drain excess oil from
inside. Turn tortilla shell upside down; cool. Repeat with
remaining tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 481 calories, 23 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 50), 40 grams carbohydrates, 64
milligrams cholesterol, 556 milligrams sodium, 9 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Boiled potatoes provide the start to this delicious Greek salad.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Pappas' Famous Greek Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 generous servings Preparation time: about 30 minutes
Cooking time: 30 minutes for potatoes
</P>
<P>
   This authentic Greek salad sent in last summer by Sally Darcey
of Stone Mountain sounds like a perfect summer meal, but its long
list of ingredients may seem like too much kitchen duty. Thankfully
it's easily simplified: Start with a prepared potato salad, or make
a simple one with canned or microwaved potatoes bound with
mayonnaise, wine vinegar and olive oil. Then pile on as many or as
few toppings as you like: shredded lettuce, tomato wedges, cucumber
cubes, bell pepper rings, avocado slices, feta cheese crumbles,
ripe olives, green onions and shrimp. Drizzle on equal parts of oil
and vinegar and shake on dried oregano.
</P>
<P>
   For the potato salad:
</P>
<P>
   6 boiling potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-size onions or 4 green onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup thinly sliced green peppers
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   To assemble:
</P>
<P>
   1 large head lettuce
</P>
<P>
   3 cups potato salad
</P>
<P>
   12 roka leaves (Greek vegetable) or 12 sprigs watercress
</P>
<P>
   2 tomatoes, each cut in 6 wedges
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber, peeled and cut lengthwise in 8 fingers
</P>
<P>
   1 avocado, peeled and cut in wedges
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces feta (Greek cheese)
</P>
<P>
   1 green bell pepper, cut in 8 rings
</P>
<P>
   4 slices canned cooked beets
</P>
<P>
   4 peeled and cooked shrimp
</P>
<P>
   4 anchovy filets
</P>
<P>
   12 kalamata olives
</P>
<P>
   12 medium-hot Salonika peppers (bought in bottles)
</P>
<P>
   4 fancy cut radishes
</P>
<P>
   4 whole green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup each of olive and salad oil, blended
</P>
<P>
   Oregano
</P>
<P>
   For the potato salad: Boil potatoes in jackets for 30 minutes or
until tender but not soft. Drain, cool and peel potatoes, and when
cold, slice into bowl. Add onions, parsley and peppers. Fold in
mayonnaise and season to taste with salt.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Line large platter with outside lettuce leaves and
place 3 cups of potato salad in a mound in center of platter. Shred
remaining lettuce and place on top. Arrange roka leaves or
watercress on top of lettuce. Place tomato wedges around outer edge
of salad with a few on top, and place cucumber wedges between
tomatoes, making a solid base. Place avocado slices around the
outside. Arrange feta cheese on top, with green pepper slices over
all. On the very top, place sliced beets with a shrimp on each beet
slice and an anchovy filet on the shrimp. Arrange olives, peppers,
radishes and green onions as desired. Sprinkle with the vinegar
(more may be used), then with oil. Sprinkle oregano over all; serve
at once.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 710 calories, 20 grams protein, 41 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 72 grams carbohydrates, 72
milligrams cholesterol, 717 milligrams sodium, 13 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Larb Gai (Chicken)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground breast of chicken without skin (turkey, pork or
beef can also be used)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced shallot
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Garnishes: 2 tablespoons green onions, finely sliced; 2
tablespoons chopped roasted peanuts (optional); mint sprigs; 1
fresh red chile; plus cabbage leaves for scooping
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet over medium-high heat, cook ground chicken in
1/4 or 1/2 cup water (enough to prevent browning) until cooked
through, about 10 minutes. Drain and transfer to a large bowl; stir
in shallot, garlic, ginger, red pepper flakes, lime juice, fish
sauce and cilantro. Garnish with green onions, peanuts, chopped
mint and julienned red chile. Serve with cabbage leaves for
scooping.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without roasted peanuts): 236 calories, 34 grams
protein, 8 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 32), 4 grams
carbohydrates, 102 milligrams cholesterol, 540 milligrams sodium,
less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon and Peas With Mustard
</P>
<P>
   Mint Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 6-8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This quick but sophisticated dish from Gourmet magazine cooks in
the microwave in less than 8 minutes. It also works well with
spinach in place of the peas: Just put 6 ounces fresh spinach
leaves in the bottom of the pie pan, sprinkle lightly with water,
top with salmon and proceed. For the sauce, substitute red wine
vinegar for the lemon juice, omit the mint and add a bit of freshly
minced garlic. Save any leftovers. This is outstanding chilled,
too.
</P>
<P>
   For the sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons coarse-grained mustard, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons shredded fresh mint leaves or 1/2 teaspoon dried
mint, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   For the salmon:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen peas
</P>
<P>
   2 salmon steaks (each about 8 ounces, 1 inch thick)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Make the sauce: In a bowl whisk together mayonnaise, lemon
juice, mustard, mint and 1 tablespoon water and let the sauce stand
at room temperature for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, spread peas evenly in a 9-to-10-inch glass pie plate
and top with salmon steaks. Season salmon steaks with salt and
pepper, cover the plate tightly with microwave-safe plastic wrap,
leaving a 1-inch opening along the edge, and microwave the mixture
at high power (100 percent), turning the plate 180 degrees after 3
minutes, for 6 to 8 minutes, or until the salmon turns opaque and
milky and just flakes when tested with a fork. Remove the plate
from the oven and let the salmon mixture stand, covered loosely,
for 3 minutes. Divide the salmon steaks and the peas between 2
plates and serve the dish warm or at room temperature with the
sauce spooned over it.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 625 calories, 49 grams protein, 42 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 60), 12 grams carbohydrates, 144
milligrams cholesterol, 441 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Summer Squash Skillet uses zucchini and yellow squash along with
other vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Summer
</P>
<P>
   Squash Skillet
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A summery side dish to any simple entree, this simple saute can
also be a light meal in itself, with some good bread or corn bread.
You could also toss it with pasta.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter or olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, quartered and sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 zucchini squash, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 yellow squash, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a large skillet; add garlic and onion and cook 3
minutes over medium heat until tender. Add squash and cook 5 to 8
minutes, stirring often, until tender.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in tomatoes, basil, thyme and salt. Cook 3 minutes or until
hot. Sprinkle with Parmesan cheese. _ From ``Discover Dinnertime''
by Susan Dosier and Julia Dowling Rutland (Tradery House).
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 124 calories, 5 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 66), 8 grams carbohydrates, 5 milligrams
cholesterol, 417 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Southwestern Turkey Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Using standard items from the deli, produce bin and pantry, you
can make this colorful, spicy-sweet main dish salad.
</P>
<P>
   Dressing:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup peach preserves, large pieces finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Salad:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cubed cooked turkey
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 tomato, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 mango, peeled, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 (15-ounce) can black beans, drained, rinsed
</P>
<P>
   2 jalapeno chiles, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Combine all dressing ingredients in bowl; mix well. In large
bowl, combine all salad ingredients; toss gently to mix. Add
dressing; toss to coat. _ From Pillsbury
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 420 calories, 27 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 24), 53 grams carbohydrates, 55
milligrams cholesterol, 560 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
