</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-AUGUST29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A month's worth of kitchen strategies to ease you through dog
days of August
 &HT;    By Susan Puckett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When we drag in from the steam bath outside, the last thing we
crave is a slow-simmered stew or hot-from-the-oven roast. We wither
at the thought of rich, cheesey casseroles or cream-laden sauces.
And at this stage of summer, we're no longer thrilled to spend
every muggy evening sweating over a hot grill. So what does whet
our appetite? Light, bright, unadulterated flavors. Casual,
uncomplicated preparations. Cool or room-temperature fare.
Fortunately, nature makes that easier for us, for at no other time
are the produce bins and seafood cases more plentiful with fresh
fixings that need no gilding and little, if any, cooking.
Supplement these seasonal riches with a few high-quality, everyday
pantry staples and a little creativity, and you can eat well every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday August 1
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frittata: Eggs can hit the spot breakfast, lunch or dinner,
especially in the form of a frittata _ an Italian version of an
omelet, but flat. No scrambling, no flipping. And you can mix
almost anything in. This time of year, try asparagus and mint.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Aug. 2
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Black-eye pea salad: Take a can of peas, doctor it up with
cooked ham, bottled roasted peppers and a few other pantry staples,
and you've got a refreshing side dish _ or a meal in itself,
perhaps served over a few lettuce leaves and paired with a corn
muffin.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Aug. 3
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Greek salad supreme: You could toss some torn romaine lettuce
leaves with crumbled feta, tomato wedges, diced cucumbers, black
olives and oregano-spiked vinaigrette and end there. Or you could
turn it into a company-worthy masterpiece by fortifying it with
potato salad, shrimp, avocado slices and other embellishments.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Aug. 4
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Turkey pesto hoagies: Mix 1/3 cup of homemade or commercial
pesto with a 1/4 cup mayonnaise. Spread it on some hoagie or sub
rolls and then pile on the sliced turkey, mozzarella, bell pepper
rings and some alfalfa sprouts for a quick and tasty sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Aug. 5
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Turkish breakfast buffet. This light but fortifying meal works
any time of day. Start with a cut-up loaf of French bread with
butter and jam. Add some hard-boiled eggs, cut watermelon and other
fresh fruit, sliced cucumbers and tomatoes, oil-cured black olives
and slivers of feta cheese. It all tastes as good with a cappuccino
as a glass of very dry white wine.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Aug. 6
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tortilla club wrap. Try the vibrantly colored, flavored
tortillas in this wrap for a quick and festive meal. Spread a thin
layer of mayonnaise on a large tortilla, cover with deli slices of
smoked turkey , a few strips of pre-cooked bacon, thin avocado and
tomato slices, wrap and eat.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Aug. 7
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  No-work smoked pork chop dinner. It takes but a minute or two
to heat them on a grill or griddle. Garnish with a spoonful of
salsa, chutney or hot pepper jelly. Side dishes of couscous (cooked
in chicken broth according to package directions)and blanched sugar
snaps require no more work or time.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Aug.8
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Garlicky green beans. If you're having sandwiches for dinner
but want something a little more substantial than chips and carrot
sticks on the side, try this: String snap or pole beans and break
them into bite-size lengths. Boil in salted water until
crisp-tender, drain and rinse them in cold water. In a bowl, toss
them with a drizzle of olive oil, a squeeze of fresh lemon and a
grated or pressed garlic clove. Season with salt, toss well, and
serve. Great at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Aug. 9
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chicken breasts with artichokes, garlic and rosemary. Seal
these ingredients in parchment packets, zap them in the microwave
and you've got a delectable meal in minutes. Squeeze the softened
garlic cloves out of their skins and spread them on French bread.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Aug. 10
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tuscan bread salad. Don't pitch that slightly over-the-hill
baguette! It can be the basis for panzanella, that refreshing
Mediterranean summer salad that also uses on dead-ripe
tomatoes,oil, vinegar and a few other seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Aug. 11
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Poached whole chicken and artichokes with chipotle mayonnaise.
Throw the chicken and artichokes in the pot in the cooler evening
hours; they need little attention once they begin cooking.
Refrigerate and dig in the next day. The pungent chipotle-spiked
mayo is made in the blender in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Aug. 12
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Taco salads. A cool way to get your Tex-Mex fix is to cook up
some chili-seasoned ground beef or turkey, mix in some beans (you
can do this in the microwave) and serve it cool _ in a tortilla
shell with other taco fixings and topped with Thousand island
dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Aug.13
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spicy Southwestern Turkey Salad: Using such ingredients as
peach preserves, cooked turkey, chopped jalapeno chiles and canned
black beans, we show you how to assemble a spicy salad in a jif.
See recipe inside.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Aug. 14
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stuffed potato dinner. Promote this side dish to the center of
the plate. Microwave russet potatoes until they're completely
cooked. Scoop out the insides and place it in a bowl. Add about 1
tablespoon each Boursin cheese, minced green onion, crumbled bacon
(you can use pre-cooked) or diced ham and 1 tablespoon milk for
each potato. Mix well. Fill the potatoes with the filling and
microwave until hot. Add a salad, steamed broccoli or other veggie
side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Aug. 15
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shrimp with fresh herbs. Chop a cup of mixed fresh herbs
(basil, oregano, rosemary, Italian parsley, etc.). Toss into a
bowl; add 4 cloves crushed garlic, juice of 1 lemon, 3 tablespoons
olive oil and salt and pepper. Set aside. Meanwhile, place a cast
iron skillet on high heat. Toss a pound or so of shrimp (peeled or
unpeeled) in the skillet until the shrimp turns pink. Immediately
toss them with the herbs. Serve warm or cool, with salad and crusty
bread.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Aug. 16
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pasta with no-cook tomato sauce: A light and aromatic switch
from bottled sauce. In a shallow bowl, mix together 2 pounds of
diced Roma tomatoes, 1 cup chopped fresh basil leaves, 4 crushed
cloves of garlic, 1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil, a splash of
balsamic vinegar, pinch of crushed red pepper flakes, salt and
pepper to taste. Let steep at room temperature at least 1 hour
before tossing sauce with a pound of hot spaghetti or angel hair
pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Aug. 17
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Peanut noodles: Toss spaghetti noodles or Japanese soba
(buckwheat) noodles with bottled or homemade peanut sauce, grated
carrots and half-moon shaped cucumber slices. Garnish with sliced
scallions and chopped peanuts. Serve as a main dish or alongside
cold barbecued chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Aug. 18
</P>
<P>
   Thai larb: Sounds exotic, but this standby at many Thai
restaurants is really easy to make: Cooked ground chichen or pork
is seasoned with ginger, line juice, fish sauce and a few other
seasoning. Diners then scoop up the mixture with ice-cold cabbage
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Aug. 19
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frogmore stew:
</P>
<P>
   This Lowcountry combo of sausage, shrimp, corn and new potatoes
is little more than tossing ingredients in a pot and cooks in a
flash _ great for a family meal or casual company get-together.
Make extra shrimp so you can eat them cold the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Aug. 20
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tuna and white bean salad. Dump cans of drained tuna and white
kidney beans (or cannellini) in a bowl. Add a few spoonfuls of
minced red onion, a drizzle of olive oil, a squeeze of lemon juice
and salt and pepper to taste. Serve over lettuce or as is.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Aug. 21
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cold Lithuanian beet soup. This invigorating soup can convert
the most steadfast beet-hater: Shred or dice 3 medium-size cooked
beets (or substitute canned). Combine in a large bowl with 2 cups
buttermilk, 1/2 cup water, 5 thinly sliced green onions, 1 peeled,
seeded and diced cucumber, 1/3 cup chopped fresh dill and salt and
pepper to taste. Chill. Serve with pumpernickel bread. Makes about
a quart.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Aug. 22
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hummus-stuffed pitas. You can buy the ready-made
chickpea-tahini spread in most any supermarket deli section
(usually with the imported cheeses) these days. Tuck it into pita
halves with a few tomato slices, cucumber rounds or a handful of
sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Aug. 23
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asian-flavored rice salad: Use leftover rice as you would
pasta for any number of cool combos like this one: Mix cooked rice
with sliced scallions, shredded carrots, fresh bean sprouts, sliced
water chestnuts or julienned jicama, chopped celery and chopped
cilantro, if desired. For a heartier salad, add bits of cooked
chicken, shrimp or crabmeat. Toss with and a bottled lemon-grass
vinaigrette or a cilantro-lime dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Aug. 24
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Steamed mussels. Here's the simplest method: Place a pound of
scrubbed, debearded mussels in a large pot with a tight-fitting
lid. Put about an inch or two of water or white wine in a pot,
cover and cook over high heat until mussels open, about 3 to 5
minutes. Serve with crusty bread and Caesar salad from a bag.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Aug. 25
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Steak salad. Grill or pan-fry a filet mignon. Meanwhile, place
some salad greens in a large bowl. Add chopped tomatoes and a
handful of crumbled blue cheese. Slice the steak and add it to the
salad, drizzle with a mustardy vinaigrette and toss. Add a few
grindings of black pepper. (Leftover sliced potatoes are an
excellent addition.)
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Aug. 26
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cottage cheese sandwich. Spread raisin, seven-grain, oatmeal
or other hearty bread with lowfat cottage cheese. Add grated
carrots, slivered bell pepper, chopped green onions and a sprinkle
of ground cumin.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Aug. 27
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Summer squash skillet: A quick saute of these garden staples _
along with chopped tomatoes, sliced onions, garlic and herbs _ can
move from side dish to centerpiece if you toss on a generous
handful of grated Parmesan before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Aug. 28
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Grilled grouper sandwich: A lighter alternative to burgers:
Brush grouper steaks with a little oil, season with salt and pepper
and grill (or broil) about 4-5 minutes per side, or until fish
flakes easily when pierced with a fork. Serve on sesame seed buns
with lettuce and tomato slices and tartar sauce. Accompany with
pickled okra spears.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Aug. 29
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pork and butter bean stirfry. Use fresh butter beans from the
garden or frozen ones. In a large skillet, saute in a tablespoon of
vegetable oil 1 small sliced onion and 1 minced garlic clove until
soft. Stir in 3 or 4 cups of cooked butter beans and a cup of diced
cooked pork or ham. Heat through, remove from the stove and
sprinkled with copped mint or basil.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Aug.30
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Black bean and corn salad in tortillas. In a bowl, combine
equal parts canned black beans (drained and minced) and corn
kernels (fresh shucked or frozen, thawed) along with a generous
dollop of good-quality salsa, a sprinkle of olive oil and vinegar
and a few dashes of cumin. Place generous mounds on lettuce-lined
corn or flour tortillas, top with a spoonful of yogurt and roll up.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Aug. 31
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Salmon and peas (or spinach)
</P>
<P>
   Microwave them together in a pie plate, drizzle with a
vinaigrette or flavored mayo and accompany with corn on the cob _
either microwaved or boiled. Presto! You've got a sophisticated
dinner for two _ plus a cool and clean kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Pucket is Food Editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler, Reagan Walker, Marcia Langhenry and Sabine Morrow
contributed to this article.
</P>
