<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holding out for cake with seven flavors
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lynn Sullivan is counting on us _ so, no, five flavors
just won't do.
</P>
<P>
   Six, either. It had to be seven for Sullivan, who said if we
came up with the recipe for Seven-Flavor Poundcake, there was
someone in her office willing to bake it and bring it in for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of readers sent in the Five-Flavor Cake as published
here many years ago. Margaret Holland offered a hand-written copy
of Six-Flavor Poundcake, hoping ``maybe that will suffice.''
</P>
<P>
   But we held out for seven _ this one sent in by Shelia Skinner
of Decatur (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Now we hope Sullivan can count on that co-worker's offer.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Seven-Flavor
</P>
<P>
   Poundcake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   3 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 eggs, well-beaten
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coconut flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon rum flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon orange flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon brandy flavoring
</P>
<P>
   For the optional glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coconut flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon rum flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon orange flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon brandy flavoring
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Grease and flour 10-inch tube pan
or angel food cake pan. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, cream together butter, shortening and sugar
until light and fluffy. Add eggs and mix well. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine flour and baking powder. Add to
creamed mixture, alternating with milk and mixing well after each.
Stir in coconut, rum, butter, lemon, vanilla, orange and brandy
flavorings. Mix well. Spoon batter evenly into prepared tube pan.
Bake 90 minutes or until toothpick inserted in center comes out
clean. (See instructions below for glaze.) Cool in pan about 10
minutes before turning out on a wire rack to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   For the optional glaze: In a saucepan, combine sugar, water and
flavorings. Bring to a boil, stirring until sugar dissolves. Pour
half of the glaze on cake while cake is still in pan. Remove cake
from pan after 10 minutes and add remaining glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with glaze): 480 calories, 5 grams protein, 20
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 38), 69 grams carbohydrates,
68 milligrams cholesterol, 204 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe request
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Marlene Brown of Monticello, Ga., wants a Brunswick stew made
entirely with canned meat and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
