<HEADER>
A7390 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     07-28 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kronenbourg a gift from France
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The cheeses from France are fat and creamy, and
everyone knows their natural complement is wine. Cut a wedge of
Camembert or brie and you want to see beside it a bottle of
bordeaux, the first glass already poured and waiting.
</P>
<P>
   What always surprises people is that the French are brewers as
well as winemakers.
</P>
<P>
   A French beer?
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like an oxymoron. Yet the world's most devoted
gastronomes, as Michael Jackson tells us, call a favorite dining
place a ``brasserie,'' a word that means brewery, and the first
brasseries were brewpubs. At such places as Brasserie Lipp in
Paris, for example, beer is served as the house drink, and tables
are hard to get.
</P>
<P>
   The center of the French brewing industry is in Alsace, where
German was once the predominant language. The two countries have
fought over the region for centuries, and the cuisine reflects the
two-sided _ part French, part German _ history. Geography and soil
conditions played their part, but it's hardly an accident that
German winemaking has flourished not many kilometers distant.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are familiar with rieslings and other German wines,
entirely different from white French wines. But few know much about
French beer, even though Kronenbourg has been available in
well-stocked package stores for years. Brewed loosely in the style
of south German lagers, Kronenbourg is light but with a slight
sweetness you seldom find in German beers. The sweetness, similar
to what you'll find in an American lager such as Rolling Rock,
usually comes from the addition of corn to the grist _ an addition
the Germans would never allow.
</P>
<P>
   Because they're more or less conventional, they don't have the
versatility with food that some French beers do. These are beers to
enjoy with milder sausages, but not pate and goose dishes.
</P>
<P>
   But Kronenbourg, in addition to its house brand, also makes a
more distinctive beer called 1664, a pilsner with a touch of
dryness and a fresh, floral aroma from Saaz hops. Alongside a
platter of Port Salut and salad of greens with white beans
recently, it had just the right balance of body and hop for a meal
that was neither light nor heavy. Port Salut is a creamy cheese,
even if it is not a Camembert, and a beer without enough malt
backbone would have come off thin and watery. At the same time, a
hoppier beer _ not that I would have objected _ might well have
complemented the cheese but might also have overwhelmed the rest of
the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Kronenbourg 1664 is available in many metro package stores for
about $7 a six-pack, higher than many imports but also better than
most.
</P>
<P>
   The best French beers, unfortunately, stay home. These are
farmhouse beers brewed in Flanders, in the northwest. Because
Belgium is next door, they are greatly influenced by the
individualistic, top-fermented Belgian style. Yet they are French,
and many are served in corked champagne bottles, meant to be
cellared for a year or more before being drunk.
</P>
<P>
   One such beer, sporadically available locally, is Trois Mont, or
3 Mont, named for three hills near the brewery of St. Sylvestre in
a low-lying hop-growing region. Pale gold in color with a complex
malt character and an assertive but not aggressive hop presence, 3
Mont resembles some of the Belgian ales. But the resemblance is
only superficial. You couldn't say it's peculiarly French, but only
that it's a beer you'll find in France and nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The French call them bieres de garde _ beers to be laid down _
and they drink them with mutton, with mussels, with strong local
cheeses, much as the Belgians do.
</P>
<P>
   ``These beers,'' Jackson writes, ``represent a distinct regional
style. It may be a minor one, but it is worthy of attention, and it
embraces some delicious beers.''
</P>
<P>
   PICK OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   (RED SEAL ALE)
</P>
<P>
   Ask Mark Ruedrich how he came up with Red Seal Ale and he'll
tell you of a brewing festival he went to in Portland, Ore., in the
1980s. ``There was a guy from Hop Union (a growers' cooperative)
giving a presentation there,'' Ruedrich says. ``I walked into the
room and smelled this incredible hop aroma. I had to find out what
that hop was. I wanted to brew a beer using that hop.''
</P>
<P>
   What he found was a blend that botanists call only CFJ90, and
Ruedrich won't go beyond the botanical shorthand. ``It's our
secret,'' he says. ``I can tell you it's a blend of a couple of
hops, and it has an American profile.''
</P>
<P>
   That would mean it's more pronounced than classic European hops
such as Hallertau, Tettnang and Saaz, mainstays in the best German
and Czech lagers, or the East Kent Golding and Fuggles hops used in
British ales. Red Seal has a slight spiciness that makes you think
of Mount Hood hops and a subtle citrus character, but not like an
ale showcasing Cascade or Columbus hops.
</P>
<P>
   The real secret is how well the hops and the malts balance one
another. ``It has a soft character for such a hoppy beer (47
International Bitterness Units),'' Ruedrich says. ``Red Seal is
really a wonderful example _ if I may say so _ of how well malt and
hops can come together in a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons for that soft character is the house yeast,
which lets the hops and malts play their parts without getting too
much in the way. And yet, drinking it, you know this is very much
an ale _ and one of the most interesting ales to enter the metro
area this year.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitutiton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
