<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini video reviews
 &HT;    By Steve Murray, Phil Kloer and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Payback'' (R) _ It plays like it looks: cheap, tired,
bleached out. This is a remake of John Boorman's much better 1967
movie ``Point Blank''; the new version never justifies the revisit.
Going the anti-hero route, Mel Gibson plays Porter, a career thief
who heists $140,000 and then gets double-crossed by his cohorts and
is left for dead. Ah, but he isn't. And he returns with a
vengeance. Screenwriter Brian Helgeland, whose uneven record
includes both ``L.A. Confidential'' and ``The Postman,'' doesn't
seem to know what his movie is. It starts off grim but has flashes
of humor and turns almost farcical in climactic shootouts and
explosions. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Noah's Ark'' (unrated) _ Just say Noah. As in ``Noah's
Ark,'' NBC's spectacularly hyped, spectacularly awful miniseries. A
disclaimer at the beginning states: ``For dramatic effect, we have
taken poetic license with some of the events of the mighty epic of
Noah and the flood.'' This would explain the pirates attacking the
Ark. God is not in the details here. In fact, God's a stand-up
comic. Trying to decide whether to spare Noah and his family from
the flood, the voice of God muses, ``I would like a second opinion,
but who could I ask?'' Grade: D-
</P>
<P>
   _Phil Kloer
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Baby Geniuses'' (PG) _ Two-year-olds are cute, their
laughter often glorious to hear, their inquisitive looks precious.
``Baby Geniuses'' has all that _ and, sadly, a whole lot more. Like
a complicated plot with no payoff. And a potty-mouthed script.
Kathleen Turner and Peter MacNichol play rival researchers rushing
to crack the baby-talk code emanating from brilliant babes. First
it's just dumb, then it gets dumber. Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
