A7393 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-OCTOBERSKY29-CO     07-28 0252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-OCTOBERSKY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inspiring teen tale reaches for `Sky'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``October Sky'' (PG)
</P>
<P>
   The irresistible ``October Sky'' is a movie that takes its idea
of uplift literally.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Homer H. Hickman Jr.'s autobiography, ``Rocket Boys,''
the drama centers on four teenagers in tiny 1957 Coalwood, W.Va.,
obsessed with building and launching model missiles ... preferably
without killing any bystanders or setting the mountains on fire.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has plenty of explosions. But its core excitement
comes from watching these self-proclaimed ``hillbillies'' discover
their own worth _ and build futures they never dreamed of _ by
using their brains.
</P>
<P>
   ``October Sky'' makes old-fashioned learning seem sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Better known for action films, director Joe Johnston (``Honey, I
Shrunk the Kids,'' ``Jumanji'') delivers a movie rich in texture
and place (Tennessee subs here for West Virginia). It can remind
you, favorably, of Michael Apted's ``Coal Miner's Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   As Homer, Jake Gyllenhaal makes a soulful young hero, and he's
well-matched by the smoldering Chris Cooper, who plays his dad,
John.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is as corny as they come. It's also deeply satisfying.
And just try not to cheer when, after many goof-ups, the boys shoot
off a rocket that pierces the clouds. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
