<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-AMERICANA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Classic Van Zandt tunes a haunting, riveting tribute
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Servicex
<TEXT>
<P>
   During his edgy life, Townes Van Zandt was anything but
predictable, so it's no surprise that his most provocative work
would show up two years after his death. From its irony-laced title
to lyrics about ``squashed'' armadillos, this CD is like a last
laugh _ or perhaps a toast _ from the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Hardcore fans will debate how much of the sound here is actually
Van Zandt. Certainly the vocals are authentic; they were hummed
into a home studio microphone in the early '90s. Van Zandt gave
them to his wife, Jeanene, saying, ``You'll need these someday.''
After her husband's death by excess, Jeanene took the digital
audiotapes to producer Eric Paul, who used session players to flesh
out the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   What we are left with is classic Van Zandt (11 tunes have
appeared earlier), interpreted by some of the most creative
musicians to ever back him in the studio. In their hands, Van
Zandt's rambling is infused with energy that has often been missing
in his work. Perhaps the best track is a creepy cut called
``Sanitarium Blues,'' a breathy soliloquy about tuberculosis and
Thorazine that is absolutely riveting. It's one of two tunes here
that have never been heard before. From the ``Ghost Riders in the
Sky'' twanging guitar to the scorching, Slash-style solo lifted
from Guns N' Roses, the sound fits Van Zandt like shrink-wrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Far Cry
</P>
<P>
   From Dead''
</P>
<P>
   Townes Van Zandt. Arista. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
