<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7396 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS29-COX     07-28 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini CD reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray and Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't Stay Away''
</P>
<P>
   Too Short. Jive/Short Records.
</P>
<P>
   17 tracks. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Longtime rapper Too Short comes out of retirement towing his
signature use of the ``b'' word and other offenses closely behind
him. Musically this crisp, thinly layered effort sets an example in
this sample-heavy genre of how a live wah-wah guitar (``You Might
Get G'eed'') or bass (``Here We Go'') can be just as effective as
part of a Roger or Isley Brothers record. But when it comes to
writing, the Atlantan's flatly delivered words of wisdom (``Good
Life'') are outweighed by line after line of flagrancy. So for a
guy taking a ride to escape the reality of his boring sex life,
this redundant 11th album should serve as a fine soundtrack. If
it's variety he's looking for, this one won't travel well.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``No Time Like the Future''
</P>
<P>
   Incognito. Talkin' Loud/Blue Thumb. 10 tracks. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   ``No Time Like the Future'' will really have fans wishing for
Incognito past. Which is strange, because at first it seems like
that's what this accomplished acid jazz band is offering. Standout
vocalist Maysa Leake is back after a failed solo attempt. And for
added firepower, house music's top singer Jocelyn Brown joins in.
All of which is wasted talent when paired with hooks such as
``Wherever your river will flow/You know love will follow'' (``Wild
and Peaceful'') and supposedly serious attempts at political
awareness called, comically, ``Get Into My Groove.'' Given the
choice between its earlier instrumental-heavy albums, and this
beautifully produced lyrical disappointment, the choice is as
simple as many of these songs.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Night and Day''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Nelson. Perdenales/Freefall.
</P>
<P>
   10 tracks. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Given the status of Willie Nelson's voice as a national
monument, it may strike some as odd that this most individualistic
of songwriters would pause to record an album of instrumentals. But
what Willie's really doing on this woolly-yet-charm-
</P>
<P>
   ing disc is giving everyone a glimpse of his back pages. Backed
by members of the Family, his longtime touring ensemble, he pays
homage to one of his great inspirations _ gypsy guitarist Django
Reinhardt _ with a batch of standards he's probably been humming
for ages. Though ``Night and Day'' lacks the polish of its classic
predecessor, ``Stardust,'' its home-grown versions of ``All the
Things You Are'' and ``Nuages,'' among others, reconcile le jazz
hot and Texas twang with soulful affection.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray and Steve Dollar write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
