<HEADER>
A7397 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-PANIC29-COX     07-28 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-PANIC29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A more commercial Panic
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the jam-rock bands jamming away out there, Athens/
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta sextet Widespread Panic just may be the jammiest. That's
a blessing and a curse: The band's purist devotion to free-form
improvisation and elongated solos _ often at the expense of
conventional pop structure _ may please the hippie faithful but
hasn't won many admirers outside its cult fan base.
</P>
<P>
   So it's meant as a compliment when I say that, on its seventh
album, Widespread Panic sullies its sound with pop sensibilities.
``Til the Medicine Takes'' is by far the group's most palatable
album for the non-fan. Adorned with such spangly accessories as
gospel choruses and brass ensembles, Panic's usually lumbering
groove sounds surprisingly fleet-footed this time out. Especially
nimble are John ``Jojo'' Hermann's organ parts, which course
through many tunes, including ``Surprise Valley'' and ``Blue
Indian,'' with quicksilver effortlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is no Top 40 sellout. We're hardly three minutes
into the album when we're ``treated'' to a series of guitar, bass
and drum solos that stretch ``Surprise Valley'' to the limits of
endurance. And the lyrics are the usual melange of fuzzy non
sequiturs. What message are the lost souls preached to in ``Climb
to Safety'' supposed to discern from the lines ``You're runnng like
a rabbit/Stick your finger in the dike''?
</P>
<P>
   But on such tightly structured numbers as ``Bear's Gone
Fishin''' and ``You'll Be Fine,'' this heretofore shunned-by-radio
outfit sounds more than ready to conquer the airwaves. Dave
Matthews, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Til the Medicine Takes''
</P>
<P>
   Widespread Panic.
</P>
<P>
   Capricorn.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
