<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERRIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUEBERRIES AND RASPBERRIES MAKE A NICE COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Blueberries and raspberries seem to be like the
best married couples. They have a few things in common and just
enough differences to keep things interesting.
</P>
<P>
   They come from different backgrounds, have distinctly different
flavors and grow on different types of plants. Yet, they ripen
about the same time of year, they both have ``berry'' in the name
and they are both highly nutritious.
</P>
<P>
   Blueberries and raspberries seem to work together like a couple,
too, playing off each other's strengths, filling in each other's
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   While blueberries are sweetly tame and mild flavored,
raspberries are sweetly tart and intensely flavored.
</P>
<P>
   While raspberries have an abundance of small, hard seeds (one in
each druplet, as those little pockets around the core are called),
blueberry seeds are so small they appear nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   And while raspberries are delicate and extremely fragile,
bursting the moment they come under pressure, blueberries have
tough protective skins that can withstand a couple days of
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   These are good facts to know if you're deciding which berry to
buy since they are sometimes interchangeable in recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other things you should know from the Epicurious
Food Dictionary, Dole 5-A-Day for Better Health program, The Oregon
Raspberry and Blackberry Commission and the North American
Blueberry Council.
</P>
<P>
   Raspberries:
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of the raspberries produced in American are
grown in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid berries that are moldy, shriveled or soft. Also, look for
berries with the hulls (leafy tops) detached. If the hulls are
still on the berry, it was probably picked too early and will not
be ripe.
</P>
<P>
   Since raspberries are fragile, look for them packaged in a
single layer in plastic containers. If the berries are piled on top
of each other, the weight of the berries on top can be enough to
smash the berries on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Purchase raspberries no more than two days before using, as they
will not keep much longer. Store in the refrigerator. Do not wash
fresh raspberries until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Raspberries contain a fair amount of iron, potassium and vitamin
A but they are also one of the best sources of fiber. A cup of
fresh raspberries contains 32 percent of the daily value of fiber a
person on a 2,000-calorie diet needs daily. That same cup also
contains 40 percent of the vitamin C needed daily.
</P>
<P>
   Blueberries:
</P>
<P>
   Blueberries, which grow on shrubs native to the Northeast,
aren't bothered by harsh winters. This year's crop is available now
at area farm stands but it is starting to wane.
</P>
<P>
   Choose berries that are firm and indigo blue with a silvery
frost.
</P>
<P>
   Do not wash until ready to use and store in a moisture-proof
container in the refrigerator for up to 5 days.
</P>
<P>
   To preserve blueberries, stem them, rinse in a colander and
freeze in airtight containers or bags. Since many recipes call for
2 cups of berries, we find measuring and freezing 2-cup portions is
convenient.
</P>
<P>
   One cup of fresh blueberries contains 82 calories, a trace of
fat, no cholesterol and 16 percent of the fiber required daily.
</P>
<P>
   Raspberries and blueberries can be used individually or together
in recipes and even substituted for each other. Keep frozen berries
on hand to top ice cream, waffles, add to yogurt, toss on cereal,
blend with yogurt and milk for fruit smoothies and to add to
salads.
</P>
<P>
   Thawed frozen berries can also be pureed, strained and blended
with honey or lemon juice to make a fruit sauce for desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Or try these recipes:
</P>
<P>
   PHYLLO BERRY CUPS
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 6)
</P>
<P>
   2 containers (15 ounces each) part-skim ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   6 sheets frozen phyllo dough, thawed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups blueberries
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups raspberries
</P>
<P>
   Sugar for garnish Early in the day or the day before serving: In
a food processor with a knife blade attached, blend ricotta cheese
1 minute or until smooth. Place in a double-thick layer of white
paper towels in a medium strainer set over a small bowl. Spoon
cheese into towels, cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate, 2
hours to overnight, to drain.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 375 degrees. Stack phyllo sheets on top of each
other. With a knife, cut the stack lengthwise in half and then
crosswise in half. Keep the phyllo covered with plastic wrap to
prevent it from drying.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly brush 6 (10-ounce) custard cups with melted butter.
Place 2 pieces of phyllo on work surface. Brush with melted butter
and place flat in custard cup, leaving edges to hang over the
sides. Repeat with 2 more pieces of phyllo, placing these sheets of
phyllo crosswise across the phyllo already in the cup. Repeat with
remaining phyllo and melted butter to make 6 cups in all.
</P>
<P>
   Place custard cups on a jellyroll pan. Bake phyllo cups 12
minutes, until phyllo is crisp and golden. Cool on wire racks for
15 minutes. Remove phyllo cups from custard cups. Cool completely
on wire racks. Store in an airtight container if made a day ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, remove ricotta from refrigerator and
discard whey in the bowl. Transfer drained ricotta to the same
bowl. Add honey and orange peel and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, toss blueberries and raspberries. Spoon
ricotta mixture into phyllo cups and top with berries. Sprinkle
with confectioners' sugar and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 370 calories (39 percent from fat), 16 grams fat,
44 milligrams cholesterol, 18 grams protein, 38 grams
carbohydrates, 315 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Source: From ``Good Housekeeping Step-By-Step Great Desserts''
(Hearst Books, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   BERRY CAKE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 12)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plus 2 tablespoons softened butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar plus more to dust the pan
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 cups flour, sifted before measuring
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt 1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh blueberries or 2 cups frozen blueberries, rinsed
well and drained
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 325 degrees. Coat a bundt or tube pan with 2
tablespoons butter. Dust with sugar. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cream remaining butter and 2 cups sugar until light and fluffy.
Add eggs, one at a time, beating well after each addition. Add
vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Sift dry ingredients together. Reserve 1 cup of the flour
mixture. Gradually add remaining flour mixture to batter, beating
well. Dredge berries in reserved flour. Fold gently into batter.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon batter (it will be thick) into prepared pan. Bake for 1
hour and 15 minutes or until a skewer inserted halfway between
sides and tube comes out without raw batter. Cool in pan. run knife
around inside edges of pan and invert cake onto a plate.
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``Virginia Hospitality,'' by the Junior League of
Hampton Roads (1992).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
