<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-COX     07-28 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON LAWYER CALLS LAWSUIT 'PARTISAN RANT'
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, through his lawyer, has assailed
as ``partisan rant'' a filing in Federal District Court here that
asserts several women may have been intimidated in an attempt to
cover up various Clinton scandals.
</P>
<P>
   The president's private attorney, David E. Kendall, responding
to a request by a private ethics watchdog group to question nine
women about an alleged pattern of threats by Clinton and his
associates, told the court that the ``real purpose'' of the motion
``was to make scandalous allegations against the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The reply, filed earlier this month, is part of a lawsuit that
Judicial Watch brought on behalf of Dolly Kyle Browning, a former
friend of Clinton. Now a real estate attorney in Dallas, she
charges the president and three of his associates conspired to
threaten and intimidate her to keep her from revealing the facts
about a relationship she alleged she had with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the case, Judicial Watch is attempting to prove a
pattern of intimidation aimed at eight other women, including
Gennifer Flowers and Kathleen Willey, to discourage them from
testifying truthfully in previous cases.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the list of potential witnesses is Juanita Broaddrick,
an Arkansas nursing home executive who said in a televised
interview earlier this year that Clinton had raped her 21 years
earlier. Clinton's attorney has issued a statement denying that
charge.
</P>
<P>
   However, Judicial Watch is asking the court for permission to
question Broaddrick about whether she felt intimidated shortly
before investigators in the House of Representatives' impeachment
probe interviewed her last year. Broaddrick has told reporters that
she noticed a man following her and that she found her home had
been broken into, with only her answering machine tape stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Broaddrick, who has said little publicly since last February
when she aired her rape allegation, told Cox Newspapers Wednesday,
``It was a strange feeling, knowing that there was no evidence of a
break-in, yet, my cat was out and tape was missing from (my)
answering machine.'' She added that ``I knew right then that I
would never feel safe again. It was something that I was going to
have to get used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch is also seeking to ask Flowers, a former Clinton
girlfriend, about remarks she made to CNN's Larry King about
threatening phone calls and a break-in at her home. Willey, a
former White House volunteer who has alleged Clinton groped her,
has publicly related several incidents, including allegations that
the tires were flattened on her car and threats from a stranger who
approached her outside her home.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the prospective witnesses was brushed aside in
the Kendall response. ``There is no place for such scandalous
'non-evidence' in this proceeding,'' the lawyer said. Further, he
asked the court to take the unusual step of erasing from the record
the references to these nine prospective witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Judicial Watch chairman Larry Klayman said
``the president is dismissing the seriousness of the charges
against him.'' He added that Clinton ``thinks he can get away with
his political spin machine rather than answering legitimate
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
