<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7408 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MORNING-BOS &LR;      07-28 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MORNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORNING PROGRAMS SHOWING THEIR MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Ever imperturbable, Peter Jennings managed to
maintain a poker face Wednesday when he was told of a remark made
by the executive producer of ``Good Morning America,'' who
suggested that her program is or soon will be ``the flagship
broadcast of ABC News.''
</P>
<P>
   It's fair to assume that Jennings believes that title belongs to
the nightly newscast he anchors. But the claim by ``GMA'' honcho
Shelley Ross is not entirely farfetched.
</P>
<P>
   Once dismissed as the home of idle breakfast chatter, morning
programs like ``GMA'' and NBC's ``Today'' enjoy growing clout
within network news divisions for the most inescapable of reasons:
Their audiences are growing at a time when TV viewership is
dropping in every other time period throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``More viewers are coming to morning television than ever
before,'' remarked Charles Gibson, who coanchored ``GMA'' from 1987
to 1998 and returned to the program with Diane Sawyer in January.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the networks are pouring millions of dollars into
the morning programs, building new sets and hiring marquee talent.
The hotly competitive arena now boasts some of the biggest names at
each network: Katie Couric and Matt Lauer at top-rated ``Today,''
Sawyer and Gibson at No. 2 ``GMA,'' and Bryant Gumbel at CBS's
upcoming ``The Early Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an acknowledgment by all three of the major commercial
networks that morning television is important,'' said Gibson. ``The
devotion of resources now, by all three of the networks, is very
heartening.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are still too many silly stunts and fawning
over movie stars on the morning shows. But there is also some solid
journalism, and when it comes to big interview ``gets'' of major
newsmakers, the early broadcast hour and large audience often give
morning shows an edge over other network news programs. For
instance, when Hillary Clinton wanted to offer her spin on the
scandal engulfing her husband last year, she appeared on ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer, who had been out of morning television for 20 years
before returning with Gibson in January when their bosses implored
them to help turn around the faltering ``GMA,'' said she has been
struck by the change in the once-drowsy format.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's faster-paced,'' said Sawyer. ``It seems to me that it is
defining and sharpening the questions of the day in a way that it
didn't back then. And that's partly the pace at which we're all
moving and the fact that we all have so much more information right
away. We have the news right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opportunity now, in a new way, to move beyond just
the headlines and try to tackle some question at the center that
hasn't been answered before.''
</P>
<P>
   One question Sawyer herself did not want to answer Tuesday was
why she was not on the air for two days following the fatal crash
of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s plane. Her absence had prompted
speculation that Sawyer, a friend of Kennedy's, was too
grief-stricken at his death to cover the story. But she denied
that, saying that unspecified ``personal obligations'' kept her off
the air on the Monday and Tuesday after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in this country felt the weight of the
tragedy,'' she said during an interview session at the semiannual
meeting of the Television Critics Association. ``And I'm not saying
that I didn't too, but that was not the reason. I did have other
personal considerations, and they are personal, and we (at ABC) all
discussed them, and I think I did the right thing, and I'm glad to
say my colleagues do too. ... I think some things should be
personal. I just do.''
</P>
<P>
   David Westin, the president of ABC News, said he supported
Sawyer's decision. He ticked off the names of other anchors
available to ABC _ Jennings, Ted Koppel, Barbara Walters, and
Connie Chung _ and said: ``If we didn't have that deep a bench and
we needed Diane and we couldn't cover the story, it might well have
come out a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the return of Gumbel to morning television will affect
the competitive landscape, Gibson called it a ``healthy'' instance
of ``shaking it up'' for all three networks. Gibson said he and
Sawyer, who were originally seen as temporary fill-ins on ``GMA''
but have improved the show's ratings, have committed to remain on
``GMA'' through next May.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings appeared before critics Wednesday by satellite to tout
``ABC 2000,'' the network's planned marathon coverage of events in
the US and around the world on New Year's Eve. The network has
forged a partnership with broadcasters in 60 countries in order to
cover what Jennings called a ``great historical event'' that will
be ``a celebration of mankind's accomplishments in the last 100
years and its anticipation for the next 100 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
