<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Thursday, July 29. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Pat Ryan. The final FRONTPAGE will move later in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA (Pristina, Kosovo) _ The Kosovo Liberation Army has
taken sweeping political control in Kosovo, and its leaders are
vowing that they will not cede their power _ organized into a
network of self-appointed ministries, local councils and seized
businesses _ to the U.N. administrators appointed to oversee the
province. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate opens debate on how big a
tax cut the nation can afford in a era of anticipated federal
budget surpluses, with Republicans saying as much excess revenue as
possible should go back to taxpayers and Democrats warning that too
big a reduction would wreak havoc with the economy and starve vital
government programs. By Richard W. Stevenson. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-ACCIDENT (Interlaken, Switzerland) _ With the death toll
up to 19, and Swiss rescue workers still searching the rapids for
two missing people, Tuesday's water sport disaster in this Swiss
resort town has already shifted the way many view adventure sports,
particularly the latest trend of ``canyoning.'' By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-DRUGS (Tres Esquinas, Colombia) _ If there is a front
line in the Colombian government's war against the twin plagues of
drugs and guerrillas, it is here in this tangle of jungle and
rivers near the country's southern border with Peru and Ecuador. By
Larry Rohter. (Eds.: This story will be held if it does not make
Page One.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ISSUES (Washington) _ Talking with the vice president: His
strategy is to portray himself as the candidate of specifics and
substance on the issues (in contrast to George W.), and we examine
his stands on some of them. By Katharine Q. Seelye. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-CELLS (Undated) _ Scientists report they have used a
precise molecular recipe to turn normal human cells into cancer
cells in the laboratory, triumphing in a task that sounded simple
but eluded molecular biologists for more than 15 years. By Gina
Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   NANTUCKET-DEVELOP (Nantucket, R.I.) _ Nantucket is an island
under siege. Once treasured by a relative few for its cobblestone
streets, picket fences bathed in icy-pink roses and isolation,
Nantucket is awakening to the din and clash of construction,
threatening both its look and its historic integrity. Wealthy
visitors who crave a piece of its weathered charm are buying up
houses and ripping them apart, on a scale never seen here before _
often with the aid of loopholes in the town's laws. That may come
as a surprise to people who believe that Nantucket is protected by
the strictest preservation guidelines in the country. By Tracie
Rozhon. With photo.
</P>
