<HEADER>
A7417 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS &LR;      07-28 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY STILL OUT ON 49ERS' JIM DRUCKENMILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Given the way Jim Druckenmiller's career has
played out with the 49ers, the swell of camera crews and reporters
clamoring for his insights has seemed odd.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't Steve Young on the other end of those questions. It
was a third-year quarterback most observers had written off months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Druckenmiller still has a story or two to tell. His latest
involved a young woman lady in Virginia who accused him of raping
her earlier this year, an allegation that a jury in Montgomery
County,. Va., recently needed less than an hour to rule as false.
</P>
<P>
   So here Druck is again. Exonerated by one court and facing
judgment on the field, for when we last left him, his fate with the
49ers remained about as sketchy as the details in the claims of his
accuser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is behind me now,'' said Druckenmiller, who
declined discussing the specifics of the case. ``Now I can do what
I love again. I can concentrate on playing football and throwing
passes to receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing before the mass of media, Druckenmiller gave off that
same image that has dogged him throughout his pro career, that
oafish quality that leaves those with a pretentious bent
snickering.
</P>
<P>
   He always has come off as the guy you find at a 10-keg bash, the
gregarious drinker with a lampshade wedged over his head, and that
is one reason why the 49ers have never been high on him.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller has been expected to grow up over the last two
seasons and the indications are that he has yet to meet the team's
demands for maturity.
</P>
<P>
   So now he finds himself on the precipice of banishment, where
he's been since general manager Bill Walsh returned to run the team
in January. Walsh seems to view Druckenmiller as the antithesis of
a 49ers quarterback, and it will be was probably only a matter of
time before Druckenmiller finds found a pink slip in his locker.
</P>
<P>
   That's where his situation gets interesting. Though Walsh has
taken every opportunity to criticize Druckenmiller, there is little
reason to think the quarterback won't make this team come
September. Druckenmiller might even maintain his second-string
status.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Garcia, Walsh's candidate as the team's quarterback of the
future, hasn't been as impressive as Walsh claims he is. Steve
Stenstrom, the former Stanford star and Chicago Bear, is hoping to
just make the team. At this point, Druckenmiller looks as good as
anyone else in the lot and he'll fight with Garcia for the No. 2
spot. Said Walsh: ``The coaches feel like the position is wide-open
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Druck's knowledge of the offense is fine,'' said head coach
Steve Mariucci when asked for a progress report on Druckenmiller's
development. ``Now it's all about executing it. The most important
things for quarterbacks are decision-making, accuracy and timing
with decision-making being the key thing. That's where Druck needs
the preseason snaps and the practice time.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else Druck needed that he didn't have a few months ago
is relief. His accuser, a 21-year-old Virginia Tech graduate
student, filed rape charges in March, and Druckenmiller claims he
never feared a guilty verdict. He even has considered filing a
civil suit for defamation of character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize now that you're always in the public eye and under
scrutiny,'' Druckenmiller said. ``You're responsible for yourself
and those around you. That might not be fair, but that's the way it
is. The important thing is to keep myself out of certain situations
and surround myself with good people.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the end result was favorable for Druckenmiller, it only
added ammunition to those who believe that playing quarterback for
the 49ers requires both an articulate nature and a media-friendly
wit.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller already had problems with learning the offense and
harnessing his howitzer arm. Now, even in innocence, he can be
accused of bad judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Druckenmiller is used to playing against the odds and his
philosophy for this camp is no different from the one he has
adopted over the last two seasons. Even if people doubt him, he
will compete until somebody tells him his time here is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have something to prove every year,''
Druckenmiller said. ``No job is ever guaranteed. I'll come out here
with my gun loaded and firing and hopefully, I'll prove how good I
am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
