<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7418 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TASTEOFINDIA-1100(2Ta     07-28 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTEOFINDIA-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD OF INDIAN SUBCONTINENT MARRIES FLAVORS FROM FAR CORNERS OF THE
WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Muslims don't eat pork. Many Hindus and Buddhists eat no meat.
Jains are so adherent to the rules of vegetarianism that they often
won't eat root vegetables because insects might be killed in the
harvesting.
</P>
<P>
   What does this add up to? A nation of parts that serves up a
gloriously vivid cuisine painted with spices and fruit and
vegetables and nuts and mounds and mounds of the most splendid rice
on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   India's food, like that of the world's, is a result of wars,
trading and conquering civilizations. But those fractious events,
and the resulting fractious population of Hindus, Muslims,
Christians, Buddhists and Sikhs, as well as some Jews, have melded
in a cuisine like no other.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a trade route between the spice islands of the East
Indies and the traders of the Middle East, Indian food gathered
ingredients from both. From Persia came the tradition of rice. From
the East came cardamom and cinnamon and coconut and ginger and
peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Generally _ and this a very loose generally _ the food of north
India has more emphasis on meat and that of the south features more
vegetables. There's more bread in the north, and rice is the
prevalent starch in the south.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the heat issue.
</P>
<P>
   The food does get spicier the farther south one travels in
Europe and Asia. This, again, is one of the influences of trade.
Portuguese traders landed on the coasts of India, bringing their
love of chile peppers. (There's also the long-held belief that hot
food in hotter climes induces perspiration, cooling the body.)
</P>
<P>
   One absolute truism is that curry powder is not, and we repeat,
not, an Indian product. This turmeric-laden, one-note concoction
was most likely an invention of British Raj veterans looking for
spices that would give them a quick curry fix.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing Indians have to curry powder is garam masala,
a combination of spices unique to nearly every home. (For the
spice-challenged, packaged garam masala is available at Indian
markets and at Penderey's Mexican Chile Supply in Fort Worth.) If
you don't intend to cook Indian food often, it's a good idea to go
ahead and purchase a mixture. Most from-scratch recipes require
roasting and toasting of spices and make quite a large amount that
will no doubt lose its potency before want to use it again.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have a supply of fresh spices, Indian food is simple.
Techniques are basic _ grilling, braising and roasting predominate
_ and results are soul-satisfying. And best of all, no food is
better as a leftover. The flavors meld almost magically in the
refrigerator, letting you microwave tomorrow's dinner of ancient
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FRAGRANT ONION AND ZUCCHINI FRITTERS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   Peanut or corn oil, for deep-frying
</P>
<P>
   4 medium onions, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 small zucchini, grated
</P>
<P>
   1 cup, lightly packed, fresh cilantro leaves and tender stems
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chickpea flour (labeled gram flour or besan in Indian
markets)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground red pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pour oil into deep fryer to a depth of 2 inches. Heat over
medium heat to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine remaining ingredients in bowl and mix until vegetables
are evenly coated. Gently drop batter mixture in 2-tablespoon
amounts into oil. Make only a few fritters at a time, allowing
ample room for them to float easily in oil. Fry fritters, turning
them until they are golden brown all over, 8-10 minutes. Using a
slotted spoon, remove fritters and drain on paper towels. (The
fritters may be made ahead and refrigerated for up to 1 day or
frozen. Defrost frozen fritters before refrying. Reheat fritters in
hot oil for 30 seconds or reheat frozen fritters in a 375-degree
oven for 10 minutes.) Serve immediately
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 153 calories, 10 grams fat, 14
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 2 milligrams cholesterol, 181
milligrams sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _Julie Sahni's ``Introduction to Indian Cooking'' (10 Speed
Press, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TANDOORI-STYLE CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pounds chicken pieces, skinned (leg quarters, breasts or a
combination of the two)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 juicy lemon
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce container yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium onion, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   3/4-inch cube fresh ginger, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1/2 jalapeno or serrano pepper, roughly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons garam masala (available at Indian markets and at
Penderey's Mexican Chile Supply in Fort Worth)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons yellow liquid food coloring mixed with 1/2 to 1
1/2 tablespoons red liquid food coloring
</P>
<P>
   Lime wedges, optional
</P>
<P>
   Cut chicken leg quarters into 2 pieces and each breast into 4
pieces. Cut 2 long slits on each side of each part of the legs.
Slits should never start at an edge, and they should be deep enough
to reach the bone. Cut similar slits on the meaty side of each
breast piece.
</P>
<P>
   Spread chicken out on 1 or 2 large platters. Sprinkle half the
salt and squeeze the juice from three-quarters of the lemon over
them. Lightly rub the salt and lemon juice into the slits. Turn
chicken over and do the same on other side with remaining salt and
lemon juice. Set aside for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Combine yogurt, onion, garlic, ginger, jalapeno and garam masala
in an electric blender or food processor. Blend until you have a
smooth paste. Empty paste into a strainer set over a large ceramic
or stainless-steel bowl. Push paste through.
</P>
<P>
   Brush chicken pieces on both sides with the food coloring and
then put them, with any accumulated juices and any remaining food
coloring, into the bowl with the marinade. Mix well, making sure
marinade goes into slits in the chicken. Cover and refrigerate for
6 to 24 hours (the longer the better).
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to its maximum temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Taking chicken out of the bowl, shake off as much of the
marinade as possible. Arrange chicken in large, shallow baking tray
in single layer. Bake for 20-25 minutes or until just done. Serve
hot, with lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 216 calories, 9 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 27 grams protein, 85 milligrams cholesterol,
503 milligrams sodium, 37 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _Madhur Jaffrey's ``Indian Cooking'' (Barron's, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   GROUND LAMB KEBABS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground lamb (or beef)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon thinly sliced green chiles (serranos or jalapenos)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup lightly packed chopped fresh cilantro leaves and tender
stems
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garam masala
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil, for brushing the grill
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients thoroughly and shape into logs that can
be threaded onto thin skewers or cooked directly on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   Either cook on the grill (2 inches from the heat source) or fry
on a well-seasoned heavy griddle. Figure about 2 minutes on each
side for rare, 3 minutes for medium and 4 minutes for well-done.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 295 calories, 21 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 22 grams protein, 90 milligrams cholesterol,
72 milligrams sodium, 64 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _Julie Sahni's ``Introduction to Indian Cooking'' (10 Speed
Press, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER AND TOMATO RAITA
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 medium cucumber, chopped finely (5 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium tomato, chopped finely (5 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons corn oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cilantro leaves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Combine cucumber, tomatoes, yogurt, salt and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in small pan. Add mustard and cumin seeds. As soon as
they finish crackling, pour seeds and oil over the yogurt. Serve
cold with a sprinkling of cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 96 calories, 5 grams fat, 9
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 10 milligrams cholesterol, 42
milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Indian Spice Kitchen'' by Monisha Bharadwaj (NAL Dutton,
$29.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CUMIN RICE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon whole cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups basmati rice
</P>
<P>
   2 3/4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in large skillet. Add bay leaves and cumin. Saute for
1-2 minutes. Add onion and saute until transparent. Add rice and
saute until well-coated, then add water and cook, stirring
occasionally, for 10-15 minutes, until done.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 275 calories, 7 grams fat, 47
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 4 milligrams
sodium, 24 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Spice Trail'' by Sandeep Chatterjee
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Grocery glossary
</P>
<P>
   Basmati rice: The incomparable aromatic rice grown in the
foothills of the Himalaya Mountains. This long-grain rice is an
Indian staple.
</P>
<P>
   Dals: Lentils are a mainstay in this often vegetarian culture.
They're packed with protein, and colors range all over the wheel
from red to white to black to green to yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Chutneys and pickles: An Indian meal isn't complete without a
selection of condiments that diners can use to customize their
meals. Some (such as lime pickle) are hotter than blazes; others
(such as sweet mango) are used to cut the heat of dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Garam masala: A spice combination made from as many recipes are
there are cooks. But the combo (usually including cumin, cinnamon,
cardamom, cloves and pepper) is also ground commercially and sold
ready-to-go. But like our ``seasoned salt'' concoctions, brands
vary in flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Ghee: This jarred, clarified butter is called for in many Indian
recipes. (Vegetable oil often substitutes in these days of
lower-fat cooking and works just as well.)
</P>
<P>
   Pappadam: Lentil-flour cracker breads usually served gratis at
the beginning of restaurant meals. These crackers come in
tortilla-size rounds or small, bite-size shapes. To prepare, simply
microwave, heat over a Jenn-Air sort of grill or fry in a small
amount of oil until they puff up.
</P>
<P>
   Patak-brand mixes: This popular brand of jarred pastes (they
also make pickles and chutneys) make whipping up a curry or a
tandoori dish a snap. For the tandoori mix, for instance, simply
combine the paste with yogurt, marinate chicken and slap on the
grill. A very exotic timesaver that's handy to have in the pantry.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Books to read
</P>
<P>
   Madhur Jaffrey has long been the queen of Indian cookbook
authors. And it's her second career. This gentle-souled actress has
written books on other Asian cuisines, but her Indian ones remain
the jewels in the crown. My copy of ``Indian Cooking'' is
splattered with red and yellow spots from spices and marinades and
is falling apart at the spine. Yet, it's still the Indian book I
end up cooking from the most.
</P>
<P>
   Another must-check-out author is Ismail Merchant, one half of
the Merchant and Ivory film team. His books tend to have more
fusion elements _ blending Indian and European ingredients. His
celebrity-spiked headnotes are fun and his recipes are reliable.
His ``Passionate Meals'' is a delightful mix of stories and
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Sahni has written several encylopedic books about her
native fare. ``Classic India Cooking'' was a seminal book when
first published. Her more recent ``Introduction to Indian Cooking''
is more appropriate for the novice.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
