<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATE ENDURES; ONLY THE TARGETS CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The caller sounds like a best friend, at least in the way that
she addresses me.
</P>
<P>
   But I doubt that she could ever be my friend.
</P>
<P>
   She sounds as if she is in her mid-30s to late 40s, probably
white. I could be wrong about that as well. That's the problem with
stereotypes. They're based on observed behavior and may even have a
grain of truth in them, but they ignore human complexity and
individuality.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, I'm simply shocked by what I observe. That's
how I feel about the amount of hatred simmering inside some people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gracie, girl, I got news for you,'' the caller blared into my
voice mail last Sunday afternoon. ``That women's soccer team,
they're nothing but a bunch of sweaty, stinky ... dykies. That's
right, girl. Just like those dyke golf players, big old tough
linebacker golf-player women and those tennis-player girls. You
don't need to be glorifying them in a family newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   The temptation to be sarcastic in reply is powerful. But you
remember that hate is a powerful emotion, and that stereotypes are
hard to change.
</P>
<P>
   I received that call in response to a column I wrote about the
U.S. women's soccer team. While decrying the lingering inequities
between men and women in the workplace and in sports, I cheered the
women's win over China.
</P>
<P>
   I thought their victory was a wonderful thing. I still do. It
never occurred to me to consider whether some members of the team
might be lesbians. Even assuming that the caller is right and there
are several lesbians on the team, I would feel the same way,
because their sexual preference isn't relevant to their
accomplishment. Not in my eyes. And, I hope, not in yours.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 20 years in this business, I thought I'd heard
it all. But listening to the woman's diatribe, I also learned a new
term with sexual connotations. I won't repeat it here.
</P>
<P>
   I am especially sensitive to this issue because of how
African-Americans have been stereotyped over the years.
</P>
<P>
   And although racism is still a big problem in this country, we
have made some progress. Fewer racists are wearing their hatred
like a badge these days.
</P>
<P>
   Homophobia, on the other hand, remains one of the last
acceptable bigotries in society, and people seem to be spewing
their venom at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought blacks made some Americans uncomfortable, that
doesn't compare with the way many people feel about homosexuals.
Lawyer Marvyn Kornberg would know what I'm talking about.
</P>
<P>
   In his defense of New York cop Justin Volpe, Kornberg argued
that Haitian immigrant Abner Louima's injuries were not the result
of Volpe sodomizing him with a broomstick. Instead, he contended,
Louima had had sex with a man.
</P>
<P>
   His defense failed, but not only because it was a lie. It failed
because other officers testified against Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Shepard, the University of Wyoming student, should be so
lucky. He had a jury of two homophobes who pistol-whipped him to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Scott Amedure? He revealed during an un-aired episode
of ``The Jenny Jones Show'' that he had a romantic interest in
Jonathan Schmitz. Three days later, Schmitz killed Amedure. Schmitz
was convicted of the slaying, but the conviction was overturned on
a technicality.
</P>
<P>
   The point of my column last week was simply that while cheering
the success of the U.S. women's soccer team, we need to remember
that gender inequities still exist. The caller seems to think that
by acknowledging the victory, I was out to glorify homosexuality.
Frankly, sexual orientation never entered my mind.
</P>
<P>
   It reminded me, however, that hate still exists. Only the
targets change.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracis Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Star-Telegram. Send
e-mail to gbs\Nstar-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
