<SLUG> BC-TRVIIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO YOU WANT TO MAKE SWEEPING CHANGES...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am an avid player of sweepstakes. Where can I find a
magazine that has listings of sweepstakes and similar contests? _
S.A.C., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ One publication for sweepstakes enthusiasts is
``SweepSheet,'' a biweekly newsletter published by Sandy Gulliver,
a hobbyist who averages 150 prizes a year, including two $15,000
wins, another of $10,000 and 10 vacations.
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter costs $26 for 13 issues, $45 for 26 issues or $3
for a sample issue. To order, write to ``SweepSheet,'' 262
Hawthorn, No. 329, Vernon Hills, IL 60061, or visit the World Wide
Web site www.sweepsheet.com.
</P>
<P>
   On her Web site, Gulliver said that winning these contests
requires three P's: ``patience, persistence, and postage.''
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ I heard on TV about a ranch in Texas that teaches young
tennis players. Where is this school? _ L.T., River Oaks, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ You may be thinking of the John Newcombe Tennis Ranch
in New Braunfels, which offers programs for younger players from
ages 8 to 18 and for adult players.
</P>
<P>
   Weeklong summer camps for younger players begin each Sunday
through Aug. 15 this year. The cost is $525 for one week and $425
for each additional week.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (888) 444-6204 or visit the World
Wide Web site www.newktennis.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Where can I write to Mary Schiavo, former inspector
general of the Department of Transportation? _ F.R.C., Colleyville,
Texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ You can write to Schiavo at a California law firm where
she consults on commercial aviation litigation. Address the letter
to Mary Schiavo, Baum, Hedlund, Aristei, Guilford &AMP; Downey, 12100
Wilshire Blvd., Suite 950, Los Angeles, CA 90025.
</P>
<P>
   While serving as inspector general, Schiavo became an outspoken
critic of the Federal Aviation Administration. ``Only with a major
crash, only with people dead and sobbing survivors filling
television screens, does the FAA step up to the plate and make
changes,'' she wrote in the 1997 book ``Flying Blind, Flying
Safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiavo, 43, is also a professor of aviation at Ohio State
University.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
