<HEADER>
A7429 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     07-28 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV30-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: ONE BIG, HAPPY GARLIC-BREAD FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday, July 30)  
(yn) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do your family dinners have all the peace and tranquillity of an
English soccer riot? Chances are, you're not serving enough
Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread.
</P>
<P>
   According to a story in the May issue of Harper's, scientific
research has shown that the mood of a family dinner can be
dramatically improved by serving Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread. (I
suspect that the mood of a family dinner can also be dramatically
improved if each family member eats in a separate room, but let us
leave that for another time.)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alan R. Hirsch, director of the Smell &AMP; Taste Treatment and
Research Foundation in Chicago, recently published a paper titled,
appropriately enough, ``The Effect of the Smell and Taste of
Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread on Family Interactions.'' Two
identical spaghetti dinners were served to 50 (presumably
unidentical) families, but only half were given garlic bread. The
researchers found that eating Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread reduced
the number of negative family interactions by 22.7 percent and
increased the number of pleasant interactions by 7.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   From this, Hirsch calculated that, for a family of four, a
serving of Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread results in 31 fewer
negative interactions and 45 more positive interactions per dinner.
</P>
<P>
   This study raises several questions in my mind. Number one, I
wonder how many more times I have to write the words ``Pepperidge
Farm'' before Campbell Soup, the parent company of Pepperidge Farm,
lays a big wad of cash on me like it did on Hirsch so that he could
finance this ground-breaking (crust breaking?) piece of scientific
research on Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I am questioning the validity of Hirsch's research. I
think Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread is a fine product, undoubtedly
superior to other garlic breads not made by Pepperidge Farm. My
family and I have enjoyed many pleasant meals, alone in our
separate rooms, in which a Pepperidge Farm product _ quite possibly
Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread _ was a key component.
</P>
<P>
   Another question I have is whether the 25 families that were not
served Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread sat in the same room with the
25 families that were served Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread. Watching
other families enjoy Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread when you have
none is bound to increase negative family interactions, including a
lot of bickering over whose fault it is that they got Pepperidge
Farm Garlic Bread and you did not.
</P>
<P>
   I also wonder if the Pepperidge-Farm-Garlic-Bread group's lower
rate of negative family interactions was due more to the fact that
they had extra food to chew on, and therefore less time to speak,
than the families that were not served Pepperidge Farm Garlic
Bread. Most, if not all, dinner-table arguments could be avoided if
family members used their mouths for chewing only. By this
reasoning, the families that were given Pepperidge Farm Garlic
Bread would have been just as pleasant and convivial if they had
been served a side dish of leftover haggis, tofu or some other
foodlike substance not found in Pepperidge Farm's fine line of
products.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one has to wonder how Hirsch differentiated negative
family interactions from positive family interactions. A simple
request like ``pass the salt'' can be interpreted as either a
positive or a negative depending on the tone and context. ``Pass
the salt, you smelly little creep!'' is almost universally
recognized as a negative family interaction. (``Maybe you'd like to
wear that spaghetti, you ferret-faced jerk!'' is another.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, these questions are in no way intended to cast
aspersions, worms, artificial lures or anything else one might
think to cast upon Hirsch's research paper, titled, as you may or
may not recall, ``The Effect of the Smell and Taste of Pepperidge
Farm Garlic Bread on Family Interactions'', nor will they dissuade
me from serving Pepperidge Farm Garlic Bread at our next family
dinner, and every dinner thereafter, as long as we continue to eat
in separate rooms.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
