</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WOMEN _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, through his
lawyer, has asked a federal court to turn down a request to
question several women under oath about alleged efforts to silence
them on Clinton's conduct. ``This is not evidence but merely
partisan rant,'' the president's lawyer said in response to a
lawsuit brought by the group Judicial Watch. The lawsuit on behalf
of Dolly Kyle Browning, charges Clinton with conspiring to
intimidate her and other women, incuding Juanita Broaddrick, who
earlier this year charged that Clinton raped her 21 years ago.
(Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TAXENGLISH _ HUNTSVILLE, Ala. _ In multiple languages, Welcome!
flies on blue banners that flutter from lightposts. The local
chamber of commerce promotes international trade. Companies from
Greece, South Korea, Japan and Indoneisa run offices in town.
Populations of Hispanic and Asian residents are among the fastest
growing in Alabama. It's here Julio and Carmen de Paula chose to
retire. Immigrants from the Dominican Republic, they moved from New
York City in 1995 and bought a three-bedroom brick house for
$54,000. They were welcomed everywhere _ except in the office of
Madison County Tax Assessor Wayland Cooley. The 83-year-old
official refused to grant them homestead exemptions because they
couldn't speak English. Without the exemption, the de Paulas pay
nearly triple in property taxes. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   HORSESHOES _ GREENVILLE, Ohio _ Just as deliberate as that of an
underhand softball pitch, Eaton lobbed the horseshoe. One of its
heels caught the stake, and the shoe spiraled down. A ringer.
Seconds later, another metallic clink boosted Eaton's standing in
the World Horseshoe Tournament's 17-and-under girls division.
Before the World Horseshoe Tournament ends Saturday, some 1,500
competitors hailing from 47 states, Canada and Norway will pepper
scoresheets with thousands of X's and O's _ a tangible tribute to
Greenville's love affair with horseshoes. (Southerly, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS
</P>
<P>
