<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE ORDERED TO PAY $100,000 FOR TORTURING DRUG DEALER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France, a country that has proudly enshrined human
rights since 1789, was ordered by the European Court of Human
Rights on Wednesday to pay the equivalent of $100,000 to a
convicted Dutch-Moroccan drug dealer for violating his rights with
police ``torture'' to make him confess.
</P>
<P>
   France thus joined Turkey as the only two of the 41 member
countries of the Council of Europe to be found guilty of torture by
a court sitting on French territory in Strasbourg, an embarrassment
that Justice Minister Elisabeth Guigou suffered in silence when
asked for reaction by journalists Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The court, established in 1959, found that Ahmed Selmouni, 57,
had suffered heavy blows over almost all of his body in ``repeated
and sustained assaults'' over at least four days of questioning by
the police in the Paris suburb of Bobigny in November 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under these circumstances, the court was satisfied that the
physical and mental violence, considered as a whole, committed
against the applicant's person had caused `severe' pain and
suffering and had been particularly serious and cruel,'' the
decision said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such conduct had to be regarded as acts of torture for the
purposes of Article 3 of the Convention,'' the court said,
referring to the 1950 European Convention on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Selmouni, serving a 13-year sentence in Montmedy prison, sued
French authorities in 1992, saying he had been kicked, beaten with
a baseball bat to the point of losing sight in his left eye, and
sexually abused with a police billy club.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous European Court ruling said the charges of rape and
eye damage were not substantiated by the medical reports available
to it, but it said, ``The court also observed that the applicant
had been subjected to a certain number of acts which would have
been heinous and humiliating for anyone, irrespective of their
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17 judges, including one from France, also found that French
justice had taken an unreasonably long time, more than six and a
half years, to act on accusations by Selmouni and one of his
accomplices after they formally complained of police brutality a
year after their arrests.
</P>
<P>
   French prosecutors took years to investigate Selmouni's
complaints of torture and sexual abuse, finally charging five
police officers in 1997. They were tried in 1998 for assault and
``indecent assault committed collectively and with violence and
coercion.'' A criminal court in Versailles last March convicted and
sentenced four of them to three-year jail terms, and ordered the
immediate arrest of their commanding officer, Bernard Herve, and
giving him a four-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict brought nationwide protests by angry police
officers, but the sentences were reduced and suspended by a
Versailles appeals court on July 1, except for the three months
that Herve had spent behind bars, and the charge of sexual abuse
was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   More appeals in that case are under way, and Selmouni could also
try to reopen his conviction on drug smuggling charges. With the
backing of the Netherlands, he asked the European Court to transfer
him to a Dutch prison to serve out the rest of his term there, but
the court said it had no jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   It awarded him $18,383 in costs and expenses and $81,080 in
damages, a fifth of the amount he had claimed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
