u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS &LR;      07-28 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE OVERCOMES BID TO PREVENT PASSAGE OF GUN-CONTROL LEGISLATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate overcame an attempt Wednesday by Sen.
Bob Smith, I-N.H., to prevent the passage of gun-control
legislation, voting to begin conference negotiations with the House
aimed at producing a final juvenile justice bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version of the bill contains several new gun-control
measures to keeping certain weapons out of the hands of minors and
criminals by initiating tougher gun show background checks and
prohibiting the import of high-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill does not include any gun-control measures, but it
does contain a number of so-called ``cultural'' measures, such as
allowing the Ten Commandments to be displayed in schools, which
many senators find objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders are hoping to fashion a compromise with the House
that will allow some gun-control measures to remain in the final
bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith, a conservative who recently left the Republican Party
to pursue the presidency as an independent candidate, has sought to
undermine that effort by holding up administration nominees to
government positions and by employing other parliamentary tactics
to keep new gun-control legislation from becoming a reality.
</P>
<P>
   A defiant Smith took to the floor after the vote Tuesday to
denounce both Republicans and Democrats who support gun-control
legislation and to urge voters to defeat them at the polls,
regardless of party affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   He also called on the House negotiators to remain firm in
opposing gun-control legislation, calling the House juvenile
justice bill a far superior piece of legislation to the Senate
proposal. It would restore ``religion and values'' to America's
classrooms, he said. He described the Senate as an instrument of a
``tyrannical government'' determined to take away the right of
Americans to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend more time trying to deny religion and values in our
schools than we do with our kids,'' said Smith, adding that no
amount of gun control will help stop the kind of youth violence
that resulted in the deaths of 14 students and one teacher earlier
this year at Columbine High School in Littleton, Col.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moral decadence is the problem, not gun control,'' he said,
accusing gun-control advocates of taking ``advantage of terrible
tragedy'' in Colorado ``to mount an assault on the Second
Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill approved last month would crack down on juvenile
crime in a variety of ways, including tougher court penalties. But
it also includes a requirement for background checks, taking up to
three business days, on all sales at gun shows, as well as a
requirement that safety locks be sold with all handguns.
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal to the American people for help in fighting
gun-control legislation, Smith denounced the nation's judicial
system for allowing ``murderers'' and other criminals freedom after
serving minimal sentences. He said criminals were being treated
more fairly than victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some like Mr. Simpson,'' Smith said, referring to the O.J.
Simpson trial in which he was found not guilty of killing his
former wife Nicole, ``never go to prison when they should.''
</P>
<P>
   House GOP leaders have said they are ready to begin negotiations
with the Senate. But House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has
indicated that he would like to see some of the Senate gun-control
measures incorporated into the House bill, despite that many of
them were rejected last month in House votes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
