A7442 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREAK-SHOW-TEX     07-28 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAK-SHOW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORLD OF THE SIDESHOW MAKES A MODEST RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For generations of Americans, it was the high point of the year:
the arrival of the circus, with its smells and noises, odd
personalities, exotic animals _ and its sideshow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lured by the spiel of the barker, from the middle 19th century
to the mid-20th century, Americans paid their hard-earned nickels
to ``step right up'' for the privilege of viewing human and animal
deformities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the sideshow is back _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 version of Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey's ``The
Greatest Show On Earth,'' features attractions reminiscent of acts
from the heyday of the circus earlier this century.
</P>
<P>
   There are no three-legged humans or animals, no bearded ladies,
``Siamese'' twins or monumentally obese people such as those who
filled the ``freak shows'' of yore. There are, as part of the main
circus performance, a few tasteful, politically correct acts
recalling the past _ such as the world's tallest man, the smallest
man on Earth, the contortionist ``lady in the cube'' and a
fire-breathing ``human volcano.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it a trend or just a blip?
</P>
<P>
   If cultural indicators are to be believed, the sideshow is now
nearly mainstream. In the mid-1990s, ``Side Show,'' a Broadway
musical about conjoined twins who were part of the old sideshow
circuit, was judged an artistic if not a financial success. A few
seasons earlier, ``Freak Show,'' an off-Broadway production in the
tradition of the ``The Fantasticks,'' explored the psychology of
the freak-show attraction. The Jim Rose Circus _ a sado-masochistic
reinterpretation of sideshows involving ground glass,
regurgitation, razor blades and self-inflicted torture of external
organs _ is a current favorite attraction on the rock-concert
circuit. And an upcoming film about conjoined twins, ``Twin Falls
Idaho,'' was inspired by the story of 19th-century circus twins
Chang and Eng Bunker.
</P>
<P>
   LaVahn Hoh, a professor of drama at the University of Virginia _
and an official spokesman for the circus on its history _ sees a
real comeback in process, although in a changed form.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional sideshow died out as our culture changed,'' he
says. ``We don't like to look at human suffering now.'' He points
out, however, that attendance at circuses is up, and that the
revived sideshow offers something completely different for a new
generation. ``We have a generation that is growing up that hasn't
seen a contortionist,'' he says. ``The circus is bringing that
back.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Bogdan, professor of sociology and education at
Syracuse University in New York and author of ``Freak Show,'' a
history of the sideshow, doubts that the sideshow is making a
genuine comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a long-term thing,'' Bogdan says. ``The circus is a
fringe entertainment nowadays. For some time, it was the main
entertainment for rural Americans. But it's not a central
institution anymore. This sideshow is just a gasp for breath by a
drowning institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogdan says that the niche for freak shows nowadays is taken by
TV talk shows, which he refers to as ``emotional and lifestyle
freak shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts may argue over the historical significance _ or
insignificance _ of the current fad for sideshows and related acts,
but a few people do live the lives of sideshow attractions.
</P>
<P>
   As in generations past, a job with the circus can be a godsend
for the physically unique person. Pakistani-born Aurangzeb Khan,
37, is billed as the ``World's Tallest Man.'' At 8 feet tall and
380 pounds, Khan had difficulty earning enough money to buy clothes
and food in his native Pakistan. Life is easier now: ``I enjoy
it,'' he says. ``I have a big mobile home, made especially for me.
Everything is the right size.'' He earns his salary signing
autographs, greeting the crowd and providing a massive frame on
which smaller people perform acrobatic acts.
</P>
<P>
   Although some acts don't require besides physical uniqueness,
others demand extraordinary skill and mental focus.
</P>
<P>
   Human cannonball Mark Myers, 28, went to clown college after
high school and was working as a circus clown when he became
interested in his current occupation. He finds the work
exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like being teleported,'' he says, recalling the first
time he was shot from a cannon.
</P>
<P>
   Myers estimates that he is shot from a cannon about 450 times a
year in his travels with the circus. He remains constantly aware of
the physical risk; his mentor is paralyzed from the waist down from
overshooting the net because the shooting mechanism was adjusted
incorrectly. Myers realizes that it's a short career _ five to
seven years at most _ and plans to develop his acting skills when
he retires from the circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who is physically fit and who is in shape could do
it,'' says Myers, who is a trim 145 pounds on a 5-foot-7 frame.
``The most difficult part is the mental part. I try and keep myself
psyched up, and keep my energy up. On the days when I do it well,
it's beautiful. Time stands still. It's like flying in your
dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
