<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES CAMP DENIES TEMP ALLEGATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican presidential campaign of Steve
Forbes, the multimillionaire magazine publisher, denied Wednesday
it was seeking to pay temporary workers to attend a GOP straw poll
next month in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes campaign manager Bill Dal Col was responding to the
allegation made by the Iowa chairman of the Christian Coalition,
who also runs a temp agency in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie Gobel told the De Moines Register she was approached by a
Forbes representative in February about hiring workers for a day to
vote for Forbes at the party straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely untrue,'' Dal Col said. ``It's ridiculous on
its face. She shouldn't be spreading these untruths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely will not, have not paid anyone to attend the
straw vote or any other vote,'' Dal Col said.
</P>
<P>
   The quadrennial straw poll, scheduled Aug. 14 at Iowa State
University in Ames, has sometimes been a relatively accurate
predictor of what's ahead in the early Iowa presidential caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll is a test of candidates' organizational ability
as well as their campaign treasuries. Only Iowa residents with a
$25 ticket will be allowed to vote in the poll, a fund-raising
operation of the Iowa Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Several campaigns, including Forbes' and that of Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, have bought blocks of tickets and are offering them
to Iowans if they will participate in the poll. That raises
questions about whether the straw poll is up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Gobel's accusation came to light as another Republican
presidential candidate, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander,
began running television commercials in Iowa suggesting that Bush,
with his record $37 million warchest, is attempting to overwhelm
less well-financed campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just in _ the Iowa caucuses have been canceled,'' a mock
television reporter says in Alexander's advertisement. ``An auction
is under way on the White House lawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander appears in the ad to say: ``The presidency ought to be
about raising children, farm prices and standards ... not just
raising money.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's political director, Brian Kennedy, criticized Bush
for relying on a big campaign treasury, but he was muted in his
assessment of Forbes, who has not been reluctant to dip into his
personal fortune to influence the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Forbes has been coming to Iowa, campaigns in Iowa and he
talks about the issues, and that can't be said of all the
candidates,'' said Kennedy, former chairman of the Iowa GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spent an estimated $36 million of his own money in his
losing 1996 campaign for the Republican nomination. Even with Dal
Col's denial, the allegation may seem credible to Iowans who have
seen Forbes' lavish political spending.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col questioned the timing of Gobel's accusation, both her
claim that the approach was made in February and her making it
public less than three weeks before the voting.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Dal Col said, ``Who knew if we were even going to
do the straw poll?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, the accusation ``muddies the water so nicely.... I
would say there's just some mischief out there.''
</P>
<P>
   In at least one campaign appearance last week in Iowa, another
candidate, conservative activist Gary Bauer, said one of the
wealthy candidates was hiring temp workers to attend the straw
poll, according to Chris Clayton, an Omaha World-Herald reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Smith, a Bauer spokesman who said he was at the event in
Onawa, Iowa, said Bauer was responding to a question from the
audience. Smith said Bauer did not specify to whom he referred, and
Smith refused Wednesday to clarify the point.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col said the allegation had ``been around.'' He refused to
say which campaign was spreading it.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly after hearing of Bauer's allegation, an Iowa Republican
source said, Gobel ``started working the phones'' to get out her
version.
</P>
<P>
   Gobel did not return a telephone call Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   She told the Register that she was approached in February by
Jerry Keen, a Forbes organizer who is former chairman of the
Christian Coalition in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely told them no,'' Gobel told the Register. ``It's
deceptive, and I'm not here to deceive the people of Iowa. I'm here
to do God's work.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' campaign secured a statement from the national Christian
Coalition headquarters in which Gobel appeared to back off from her
accusation, the Register said.
</P>
<P>
   Gobel told the Register she did not write the statement and
said: ``I was told to go along with it, and I don't want to go
along with it. I'd rather burn a bridge than burn my country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
