<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARE29-COX     07-28 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CARE staffer recalls group's efforts
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mike Godfrey has seen many of the world's most
troubled spots in the 17 years since he joined the staff of CARE.
</P>
<P>
   But after his first visit to Kosovo, he was convinced that the
job ahead for CARE and other humanitarian organizations there is
going to be a tough one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't prepared for the level of destruction,'' said
Godfrey, 46, Wednesday as he described the trip he had just taken
in his new role as Balkans coordinator and deputy director of the
emergency group for Atlanta-based CARE USA.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that destruction is physical _ damaged homes, land-mined
fields, and neighborhoods and homes still going up in smoke in
retaliatory attacks _ but Godfrey said the destruction of the
social fabric struck him as even more bothersome.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled visiting Homestead, Fla., after Hurricane Andrew.
The houses were in splinters ``but the sense of community was
there,'' he said. Particularly in the Kosovo city of Mitrovica,
where tensions remain intense, he found little evidence of ``that
sense of community I thought would help with reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   CARE, nonetheless, has begun relief efforts, including
distributing blankets, bedding and hygienic supplies, to all
sectors of Mitrovica's society, including Serbs, ethnic Albanians
and Roma, or Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Kosovo, CARE staffers are also hard at work on
programs ranging from providing shelter to clearing landmines to
finding sources of fuel for the coming winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very depressing to see what was wrought and what
continues to be,'' said Godfrey, who served as CARE's director in
Guatemala before moving to the Atlanta headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge need,'' he said, adding that he hopes the world
has the will to help. Godfrey, meanwhile, is already planning a
return trip to the region later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Graham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
