<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OVER THE BUDGET SURPLUS LOOMS AS MAJOR ISSUE FOR 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 1)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a presidential election, the party that defines
the agenda for debate is the one that usually wins.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Democrats and Republicans are battling so hard over
how to divvy up the first federal budget surplus in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats would like the public to focus on their plan to
use the lion's share of the surplus to shore up Social Security,
Medicare, education and the environment and pay down the national
debt _ and then grant a modest cut in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans want the emphasis on their $792 billion tax
reduction over 10 years. They claim the surplus will be large
enough to accommodate such a tax cut as well as provide money for
vital programs such as Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers have reverted to a political strategy that
proved successful in the 1980 election of Ronald Reagan, and the
Democrats have resurrected a policy that has served them well since
the days of the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has made it clear he will veto the GOP tax
cut, and Republicans are prepared to attack the veto, assuming that
voters will not understand why, with such a big surplus, they
cannot have a reprieve from high taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats contend that the huge GOP cut would not permit the
government to fund essential programs and pay down the national
debt. Clinton has termed it ``irresponsible,'' warning that it
could prove dangerous to the economic stability of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasting future gyrations of the national economy is a
dangerous game. There is no guarantee that the budget will be
balanced and surpluses will accrue far into the future. If the
economy were to fall into recession, the government would have to
exchange black ink for red ink or reduce the size of the tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   But House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer of Texas
said last week, ``All American taxpayers created this surplus, and
it's only fair to return it to those who sent it here.''
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious, therefore, that the tax cut battle of this summer
will spill over into 2000 unless the two parties can reach a
compromise that Clinton will sign.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, look for the Republicans to label Clinton and the
Democratic presidential nominee, whether he is Al Gore or Bill
Bradley, as big-spending liberals.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats, as they're doing now, will point out that the
biggest beneficiaries of the GOP tax plan would be special
interests and wealthy Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The one certainty is that a vast amount of hyperbole will
pollute the political atmosphere between now and Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in 1992. Clinton defeated President George Bush
largely because he and his fellow Democrats repeatedly blamed Bush
and the Republicans for the recession then plaguing the economy.
The winning campaign theme was: ``It's the economy, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years earlier, Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis asserted that the campaign would be about competence not
ideology. But Bush and his handlers rejected that contention,
claiming that Dukakis was a fuzzy, big-spending liberal who was
soft on crime.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed to a convict named Willie Horton, who had attacked
a Maryland couple while on furlough from a Massachusetts prison
during Dukakis' governorship. Dukakis helplessly watched his
substantial lead in the public opinion polls dwindle to a deficit.
On Election Day Bush garnered nearly 9 million more votes that
Dukakis and carried 40 of the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   But if Republicans believe they can duplicate Reagan's 1980
triumph in 2000, they may be wrong. Circumstances have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's opponent, Jimmy Carter, was unpopular. Interest rates
and inflation were in the double-digits. Gasoline was expensive and
hard to get. American hostages had been held in Iran for a year.
</P>
<P>
   When Reagan, in a televised debate with Carter, asked Americans
whether they were better off than they had been four years earlier,
their answer was clear and decisive: They were not.
</P>
<P>
   On that Election Day, Reagan won 44 states to six for Carter.
What often is forgotten, however, is that the Reagan
across-the-board tax cut, which injected life into a stagnant
economy, also sent the national debt rocketing to unprecedented
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the economy is strong. Interest rates are down. Inflation
and joblessness are almost nonexistent and gasoline is plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   The debate next year could parallel that of 19 years ago, but a
whole new generation with different priorities will be voting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
