<HEADER>
A7466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-FATHER-SON-ART-     07-28 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-FATHER-SON-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY TORN BY POLITICS OF WAR AND BETRAYAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A locator map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ One of the strangest subplots in the war in
Congo, a conflict of innumerable betrayals and head-spinning
surprises, has been the very public disintegration of one of the
country's richest families, the Bembas.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Saolona Bemba, is a minister in the Kinshasa
government. The son, Jean-Pierre, is leading a rebel force in the
jungles of northern Congo whose aim is to march upon the capital
here and overthrow its government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a message from Papa: He should really think hard about
what he is doing,'' the father, 60, said in a recent television
interview. ``All I'm asking for is that nothing happens to him and
that he can resume his old life and take care of his family, his
little family, his wife and children. Let him come home and follow
what his Papa and President Kabila are busy doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The son, 39, reached on his satellite phone on the northern
battlefront, sounded a little testy upon hearing of his father's
plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a kid anymore. I can fly on my own wings,'' the son
said, juggling two satellite phones, barking military orders into
the other one, judging from the French words sprinkled in with the
local Lingala: ``fuel,'' ``recruits,'' ``ammunition.''
</P>
<P>
   Betrayal, if there is one leitmotif to this war, runs through
it. But few would have predicted the spectacle of so famous a
father and son accusing each other of betrayal, two men who had
defied this country's political gravity for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The father was a businessman who became one of the nation's
richest men through his close ties with former President Mobutu
Sese Seko. The elder Bemba, a legendary survivor who married off a
daughter to one of Mobutu's sons even as he himself married a niece
of Mobutu's main political rival, was beaten and jailed after the
late dictator's fall two years ago. Curtains for Bemba, people here
thought.
</P>
<P>
   His son emerged from the father's shadow a few months after war
erupted across Congo last August. Sketchy reports began filtering
out of the impassable jungles in northern Congo. A second, shadowy
rebel movement was stirring up there, and towns were falling in its
path.
</P>
<P>
   Once this movement's satellite phone numbers began circulating,
the name of its leader became known: Bemba. That is to say,
Jean-Pierre Bemba, oldest son of Saolona, a lifelong civilian, who,
it became clear, was bent on toppling President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   But the old man, written off prematurely, it turned out, chose
an equally unexpected path. He ingratiated himself with Kabila _ no
small feat since Kabila had spent half of his life hidden in a
jungle dreaming of the day he would depose Mobutu and his class _
to the point that Kabila made him his minister of economy and
industry early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Theories flew across Kinshasa. Increasingly desperate, Kabila
had made the father a minister to put pressure on his son to
abandon arms. Or, the Bembas were in on it together: whoever won
this war, the family would win.
</P>
<P>
   The father, naturally, played up the former recently in a
Kinshasa television show called ``With Open Heart.'' Asked whether
he felt betrayed by his son, the father _ who had publicly disowned
Jean-Pierre late last year _ said: ``Of course. He may have his
ideals. But he's wrong, like many young people, incidentally.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Punctuating the father's plea, a recent issue of the
pro-government daily, Le Palmares, published the son's picture on
the front page with the caption: ``J.P. Bemba: le reve d'Icare?''
or ``The dream of Icarus?''
</P>
<P>
   So is Jean-Pierre a reckless son, doomed because of his stubborn
refusal to listen to wise Daedalus? Or, to take a contemporary
myth, is he Luke Skywalker trying to redeem a father who chose the
dark side?
</P>
<P>
   The son said he had given up a millionaire's life in exile in
Europe, where his wife and children were now, to risk his neck in
the bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has chosen to serve the devil and I have chosen to serve
the people,'' the son said, adding: ``Besides, I was disowned in
October, so I don't know what son he's talking about. He had me
when he was 20 years old and he disowned me a year ago. Am I hurt?
What I am doing here is bigger than all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jean-Pierre Bemba, if the decision to head a rebellion was a
surprising one, it was not incomprehensible. As the son of a Mobutu
crony, he belonged to the small circle of children of the Congolese
elite, an entitled class that could do practically anything with
impunity. Almost overnight, its members saw their fathers jailed by
Kabila, their fortunes seized and, more important, their once
limitless future here at a dead-end.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Olivier Kamitatu, 35, recently abandoned his highly
respected public opinion research company, whose reports were
scrutinized by Western diplomats, to become Jean-Pierre Bemba's
secretary-general. Kamitatu was schooled in Europe, like most
members in this circle, said his father, Massamba Kamitatu, 68, a
former minister and ambassador to Japan under Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my son,'' said Kamitatu, who was now living in his
daughter's small apartment, his house confiscated after Mobutu's
fall. ``He's an adult. He's made the political decision of his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   No such words of understanding from Bemba pere, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not up to me to go to him,'' the father said, and
alluding to African societies where the paternal authority is
almost never questioned, added: ``I am an African. He must come to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let my son come back home,'' he added. ``The family needs him.
Every father needs to see his children. I need him. I raised him to
replace me.''
</P>
<P>
   The son, at first distracted by his other phone call, grew
hungry for details about his father's television interview. He
laughed. ``It's a little pathetic. It's funny. He must have made
people laugh in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never particularly close to my former father anyway,''
added the younger Bemba, whose mother died when he was 12. ``I was
very close to Maman. I miss her a lot. You know, I'm a boy and boys
are always closer to their mothers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
