<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-NOTEBOOK29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC Notebook: Spurrier spices up SEC meetings
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM _ As usual, Steve Spurrier added a little spice to an
otherwise business-as-usual day at the annual Southeastern
Conference football kickoff meetings Tuesday. ``We played lousy,
and we were still 10-2 last year,'' the Florida coach said. ``I
think you ought to check out all those teams we beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans were getting a little restless,'' Spurrier said. ``We
had Auburn down 24-3 and were trying to run out the clock, and they
booed us. Can you imagine being up on Auburn 24-3 and that wasn't
enough?''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran Gator was asked about the SEC's Eastern Division
this year. ``All you've got to do is look at the history over the
past nine years. I don't see much changing.'' Florida has put up a
93-18-1 overall record during Spurrier's nine-years in Gainesville
and posted a 66-9 SEC mark while winning five SEC titles.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier was told that Tennessee coach Philip Fulmer had
commented that it was harder to win the SEC East than it was to win
a national championship. ``He doesn't have to play Florida State
the last game of the season every year,'' Spurrier quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer also had said a day earlier that his relationship with
Spurrier was better than most people thought. ``It probably is,''
Spurrier said. ``It's about like I have with all the other
coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier is a longtime and outspoken advocate of a playoff
system and again said he felt the best scenario was to have a
16-team playoff, with the teams being chosen by a committee, much
as college basketball does it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they don't ask my opinion about it,'' he said. ``They hear
it a lot, but they don't ask for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Get moving fast
</P>
<P>
   Gator wide receiver Travis Taylor, Florida's most experienced
returning pass-catcher, said he is anxious for the season to begin.
``I think on our team there's a sense of urgency,'' Taylor said.
``We feel we need to get back to what we had in 1996,'' when
Florida won a national title. Taylor, a junior, was asked what team
he pulled for in last year's national championship game between
in-state rival FSU and SEC rival Tennessee. ``If they both could
have lost, that's what I would have liked to have seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Low profile
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Tuberville, who jumped from Mississippi to Auburn, says
he's taken a different approach. ``When I first got to Ole Miss, I
was trying to get my name in the paper,'' he said. ``Now at Auburn,
I've just been trying to keep my name out of the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprise
</P>
<P>
   Ole Miss offensive lineman Todd Wade says the '98 Rebel team was
unique. ``I was surprised how well we played in our bowl game,'' he
said, referring to Mississippi's win over Texas Tech in the
Independence Bowl. ``I think our fans were too. They didn't expect
us to win after the coaching change and we lost our last three
games of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't take it
</P>
<P>
   Former Tennessee offensive coordinator and new Ole Miss head
coach David Cutcliffe says he watched his former Vols beat Florida
State in the national championship game on television in Oxford,
Miss. ``I watched the first half by myself, and then I called up
former player Jerry Colquitt at halftime. I told him, 'Jerry, come
over here and watch this game with me before I hurt myself or break
something.' I felt like I was levitating over the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar name
</P>
<P>
   Cutcliffe recruited Eli Manning, the younger brother of former
UT All-American Peyton Manning, to play quarterback at Ole Miss.
``In a perfect world, you'd try to redshirt him, but I'm not sure
we can,'' Cutcliffe said. ``Physically, he's a lot like Peyton.
They throw with the same type motion. He may be a little further
along physically by all the time he's spent in the weight room.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
