</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BALKANS-0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, ALLIES TO SEEK STABILITY, INCLUSIVENESS FOR WAR-TORN
BALKANS AT SUMMIT
 &HT;    700&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    EDs: President Clinton is scheduled to land at Aviano Air Base
in Italy Thursday night. He will leave there on a military aircraft
for Sarajevo Friday morning.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton leaves Thursday to lead an
international conference on Balkans renewal in Sarajevo, the
Bosnian capital that gave most of the world its first glimpse of
the ethnic-based horror at the heart of Europe's worst fighting
since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The day-long conference Friday comes on the heels of an
international donors' conference Wednesday in Brussels, where more
than 60 nations pledged a total of $2.1 billion in immediate
reconstruction aid for war-shattered Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The United States pledged $500 million, U.S. diplomat James
Dobbins told reporters in Brussels. Japan put up $200 million,
Germany pledged $190 billion and Britain promised $145 million, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after NATO bombing ended the latest chapter in nearly
a decade of Balkans bloodshed, Clinton will lead his counterparts
from three dozen other nations -- including most of Europe and
Russia -- in a summit he hopes will help advance his vision of
rebuilding Kosovo and helping to knit the rest of the war-tattered
region back into the fabric of central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the conference is slated to launch a blueprint for
that plan, the Balkan Stability Pact, agreed upon earlier this year
by U.S. and European leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has three main objectives: advancing political and economic
reforms in Southeast Europe; promoting cooperation, tolerance and
security there; and working ultimately to integrate the region into
the European mainstream,'' Clinton's national security adviser,
Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger, told reporters at the White House on
Wednesday. `` We have a really historic opportunity, after Kosovo,
to bring these nations into Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Notably absent will be Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president
of Yugoslavia, who has been indicted for war crimes against ethnic
Albanians in the Serb province of Kosovo. Friday's summit will
underscore the impact of the decision by Clinton and his allies not
to provide reconstruction aid to Serbia -- the main republic in
Yugoslavia -- so long as Milosevic remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   The message to the Serb people, ``will be simple,'' said Berger.
`` With Milosevic, you are excluded from the Stability Pact and
isolated from the rest of Europe. With a government
</P>
<P>
   committed to democratic reform and international cooperation, we
are prepared to help bring Serbia into the European mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders will gather in the Olympic arena where figure skater
Katerina Witt, competing for what was then East Germany, captured
her gold medal in 1984. Shelled to ruin by Serb gunners just a
decade later, the largely reconstructed venue will provide a
powerful backdrop for international efforts to help salvage a
region ravaged by war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a symbol of Sarajevo and its multi-ethnic and
international character,'' said Craig Buck, the Sarajevo mission
director for the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID).
``It's a symbol of Bosnia's regeneration.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarajevo, however, is also replete with symptoms of failure in a
country where some 6,200 U.S. troops are deployed as part of a
larger NATO force of 29,000, and Americans have spent well over $6
billion during the past four years in peacekeeping and
reconstruction efforts that are nowhere near complete.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton and other alliance leaders meet to map out the road
ahead for neighboring Kosovo and the region at large, many Balkans
analysts are hoping the leaders will learn some lessons from the
Bosnia experience, and not simply repeat past mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symbolism of Sarajevo can cut both ways,'' said Kurt
Bassuener, associate director of the Balkan Action Council, a
Washington, D.C. research group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no war in Bosnia now,'' he said. ``But the fact that
there's no end in sight for the U.S. troops deployed there, because
we haven't dealt with the fundamental issues of Bosnia, that is not
a model of what we want the region to look like.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other critics, Bassuener said the United States and its
allies have largely squandered the opportunity to remake Bosnia
during nearly four years of NATO peacekeeping operations, and he
hopes Clinton and his counterparts will take notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in a holding pattern for four years, with very
little real progress,'' Bassuener said. ``Every delegate who
actually gets out of his chauffeured car on the way to the
convention will hopefully see that.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself is well aware of the failings in Bosnia. In a
report to Congress this week, he named several of them, including:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  its de facto partition along ethnic lines;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the slow progress in building the foundations for a civil
society governed by a functioning democracy;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the continuing impediments to replacing a state-centered
economy with market-driven, private companies;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NATO's failure to turn over indicted war criminals like
Radovan Karadic and Ratko Mladic, respectively, the political and
military leaders of the Bosnian Serbs, to the U.N. tribunal on war
crimes in the former Yugoslavia;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and, most fundamentally, the inability of some 1.2 million
Bosnians displaced by fighting and ethnic terror to return to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge before Clinton, who has invested more heavily of
his time and foreign policy resources in the Balkans than anyone
might possibly have imagined when he first took office six and a
half years ago, is how to maintain the focus on Bosnia while trying
to rebuild neighboring Kosovo and reaching out to the rest of the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank, which priced Bosnia's short-term rebuilding
needs at $5.1 billion over four years, has estimated Kosovo's
immediate needs at roughly one-fourth that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Longer-term needs, though, could well top $10 billion for the
Balkans, Europe's poorest region, with 47 million people producing
$82 billion worth of goods and services per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having won the war, we must win the peace,'' said Gene
Sperling, director of Clinton's National Economic Council. ``And
winning the peace means, not only the immediate humanitarian side
for Kosovo, and even the longer-term reconstruction of Kosovo, but
also working on an economically viable vision for Southeastern
Europe as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
