<HEADLINE>
NASA INSPECTORS FIND SOURCE OF HYDROGEN FUEL LEAK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ With the shuttle Columbia safely back on
Earth, NASA quickly found the holes Wednesday that allowed hydrogen
fuel to leak from a rocket engine nozzle, threatening the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Initial inspections of the nozzle found holes in at least two
and perhaps four stainless steel tubes that circulate hydrogen
through the nozzle on its way to the engine's combustion chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The leak, as well as an electrical short circuit, threatened the
shuttle's July 22 climb into orbit with five astronauts and the
Chandra X-ray observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Characterizing both problems as significant, agency officials
said they would work aggressively to find the causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we have a problem,'' said NASA administrator Dan
Goldin, who greeted Columbia commander Eileen Collins, pilot Jeff
Ashby, flight engineer Steve Hawley, mission specialist Catherine
``Cady'' Coleman and French astronaut Michel Tognini as they landed
at NASA's Kennedy Space Center late Tuesday. ``We will diagnose it,
find out what went wrong and fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Had either problem worsened, Columbia's three main rocket
engines would have shutdown prematurely, forcing the shuttle
astronauts to attempt an unprecedented emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let down. We've got to make sure we understand these
failures, get them resolved before we fly again,'' said Bill
Gerstenmair, NASA's shuttle planning manager. ``We will do that
with both of these failures.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA's next shuttle mission is tentatively planned for
mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Columbia returned from its five-day flight, engineers
zeroed in on the damage to the narrow cooling tubes within the
nozzle of the shuttle's right main rocket engine.
</P>
<P>
   The perforations explained an unusual bright streak coming from
the nozzle that shuttle engineers spotted when they studied
photographs taken as it launched. Space agency experts made the
photographs public last Sunday, saying the irregularity suggested a
small leak of explosive hydrogen.
</P>
<P>
   Collins joined her crewmates and shuttle program managers in a
runway inspection of Columbia after their return to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what appeared to be three small holes, not straight down
the tubes, but in a little bit of a diagonal pattern,'' Collins
told reporters. The nozzles for the three main engines each have
1,080 tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Gerstenmair said the cooling tubes will be inspected this week
with for signs of a perforation from a debris strike, corrosion or
structural failure. Then the damaged portions of the tubes will be
removed, cut into sections and analyzed for further indications of
how and when the damage occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Though small in quantity, the fuel loss triggered the shuttle's
engines to consume liquid oxygen at a higher than normal rate to
maintain thrust during Columbia's 8 1/2-minute ride to orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers will attempt to trace the electrical short to either
the shuttle's wiring or the computerlike controller on the
Columbia's center rocket engine. During the launch, the short
disrupted the primary controllers on the right as well as the
center engine. Had backup controllers not taken over, the engines
would have shut down prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mission's rocky start, Columbia's crew successfully
deployed the shuttle's primary payload, the Chandra X-ray
Observatory, a new space telescope developed to help astronomers
determine the size and age of the universe as well as how the stars
and galaxies evolved.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, NASA's first female shuttle commander, drew praise for
guiding her colleagues through the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eileen Collins represents the best of this country,'' said
Goldin. ``She was cool and calm and handled the problems. She did a
terrific job just like all of our other commanders.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said her crew handled the potential emergencies just as
they had trained to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that we definitely need to take a very close, hard look
at what happened,'' she said. ``We don't want that to happen again
on a future mission.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials greeted Collins on the runway following touchdown
along with her husband and 31/2-year-old daughter, Bridget.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 500 to 600 people met her on her return to Houston,
including many little girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has not only equaled but surpassed Amelia Earhart in the
history of flight,'' said Vice President Al Gore, who attended the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Houston, Collins described how she felt when
the warning lights flashed moments after liftoff. ``This isn't
right. This isn't what I'm expecting,'' she thought to herself. But
she and the crew had trained for multiple failures during launch
and knew what responses would be required.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just amazed that I don't think my stress level was any
different, other than I heard the call and I went, `Wow, I'm
surprised that happened,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
