<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKING-FOR-CHARITY-T     07-28 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKING-FOR-CHARITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHARITY BEAT GOES ON WITH NEW BENEFIT DISCS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing no one ever really expected a rock star to do: give
money to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1971, George Harrison became one of the first immensely
popular rockers to do so. Embracing the pleas of his friend/musical
inspiration Ravi Shankar, the famed Indian sitar player, Harrison
organized the Concert for Bangladesh to aid victims of war and
famine in that country. The concert, which featured Harrison, Eric
Clapton, Bob Dylan and others, was recorded and later released as a
three-disc set, again with proceeds going to a Bangladesh fund.
</P>
<P>
   After that, rock 'n' roll became a lot better about opening its
heart and wallet. Harrison undoubtedly paved the way for the
monster Live Aid famine relief concert in 1985, the yearly Farm Aid
festivals and the countless benefit discs that flood the market
every year.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, three more benefit discs have been organized,
with at least four more to follow this year, including one for
Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   Although some recent benefit discs have been plagued with old
material, or just plain bad songs, the three new ones contain new
tracks, interesting duets or once-rare B-sides. Filler, this
stuff's not.
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``No Boundaries: A Benefit for the Kosovar Refugees''
(Epic Records)
</P>
<P>
   The cause: Humanitarian relief for Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The music: Mostly alt-rock.
</P>
<P>
   Contributors: Pearl Jam, Oasis, Rage Against the Machine, Neil
Young, Alanis Morissette, Korn, Black Sabbath, Bush, Ben Folds
Five, Sarah McLachlan, Indigo Girls, the Wallflowers, Jamiroquai,
Tori Amos and Peter Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   Unreleased material?: Some, but most of what's here is live, a
remix or a B-side. Amos, The Wallflowers and Ben Folds Five offer
new tracks. And this is the only way to get Pearl Jam's new song, a
cover of Texan J. Frank Wilson's 1964 hit, ``Last Kiss,'' about a
couple's final moments together after a fatal car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: ``Last Kiss,'' definitely; a live version of Neil
Young's ``War of Man:'' Rage's metallic reworking of Bruce
Springsteen's ``The Ghost of Tom Joad:'' and an interesting remix
of Korn's ``Freak on a Leash,'' retweaked by Garbage drummer Butch
Vig.
</P>
<P>
   Available: Now.
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``Music for Our Mother Ocean 3'' (Surfdog/Hollywood
Records)
</P>
<P>
   The cause: The Surfrider Foundation, a California-based
organization devoted to preserving the oceans.
</P>
<P>
   The music: Good mix of pop, adult contemporary and hard rock
artists doing surf-rock-tinged music. Most tracks have some sort of
summer/sun/let's-go-surfing theme.
</P>
<P>
   Contributors: Brian Setzer with Brian Wilson, Snoop Dogg and
Rage Against the Machine, Smash Mouth, Sprung Monkey, B---hole
Surfers, Beck, Lisa Loeb, Jane's Addiction, Pearl Jam, Allison
Moorer, Paul McCartney and Wings, Gary Hoey, Jimmy Buffett, Red Hot
Chili Peppers, Everclear, Ben Harper, James Taylor, Beastie Boys,
Lit, Chris Isaak.
</P>
<P>
   Unreleased material?: Plenty, including a ton of covers, such as
Setzer and Wilson's duet on the Beach Boys classic, ``Little Deuce
Coup,'' the Surfers' thrashing of The Lovin' Spoonful's ``Summer in
the City'' and Everclear's run-through of an old Ventures
instrumental, ``Walk, Don't Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: All the covers are great, as is a new song by the
Chili Peppers, ``How Strong,'' Snoop Dogg and Rage's duet, ``Snoop
Bounce'' and Jane's Addiction's ``Ocean Size.''
</P>
<P>
   Available: Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The disc: ``More Oar _ A Tribute to the Skip Spence Album''
(Birdman Records)
</P>
<P>
   The cause: To help pay medical bills and other expenses for Moby
Grape singer Alexander ``Skip'' Spence, a schizophrenic who died in
April. In 1969, Spence released a solo record called Oar, hence the
benefit disc's name.
</P>
<P>
   The music: Experimental rock ranging from well-known acts such
as Beck, Tom Waits and Robert Plant to obscure, underground groups
such as Flying Saucer Attack and Engine 54; each artist covers a
Spence or Moby Grape tune.
</P>
<P>
   Contributors: Robert Plant, Mark Lanegan of Screaming Trees,
Alejandro Escovedo, The Durocs, Jay Farrar of Son Volt, Mudhoney,
Robyn Hitchcock, Diesel Park West, Tom Waits, Greg Dulli of Afghan
Whigs, The Ophelias, Flying Saucer Attack, Alistair Galbraith,
Engine 54, Outrageous Cherry, Beck and the Minus 5.
</P>
<P>
   Unreleased material: Nothing here has been previously released;
all the tracks were recorded exclusively for this disc.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Screaming Trees vocalist Mark Lanegan does haunting
justice to ``Cripple Creek,'' turning it into a sad, acoustic
ballad. English ambient troupe Flying Saucer Attack offers a
spacey, mesmerizing ``Grey-Afro.'' And Texan Alejandro Escovedo
adds a melancholy blues-rock vibe to ``Diana.'' Actually, the
atmosphere of the entire record is dismal, and seems even more so
now that Spence has died.
</P>
<P>
   Available: Now.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
