<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-WOES-COX     07-28 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-WOES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COKE: Suspect business practices or 'piling on'?
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola's overseas problems expanded Wednesday when
Australian regulators said they were investigating the company's
largest bottler in the Asia Pacific region for possible abuses of
its market power.
</P>
<P>
   The move came just a week after European Union officials said
they were launching an inquiry into whether Coca-Cola bottlers
there were giving illegal incentives to retailers to sell their
products.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Goldman, a global beverage analyst for Merrill Lynch, said
the inquiries, on top of the overseas regulatory problems the
company has faced in trying to buy Cadbury Schweppes' brands, may
be the result of piling on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a person is perceived to be down, you kick him, and we
may be seeing some of this now,'' Goldman said. ``Why is all this
happening now in Europe and Australia,'' Goldman asked
rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Marc Cohen of Goldman Sachs agreed, saying ``there's no
doubt'' that some piling on is occurring.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Cohen said issues like this begin to
arise when a company becomes so dominant in individual markets.
</P>
<P>
   And Goldman agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke and Pepsi are of comparable strengths in U.S.
supermarkets,'' Goldman said. ``But in Australia and Europe, Coke
is in a class by itself from a market share standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Pepsico acknowledged last week that its complaints were
partly responsible for the EU probe of Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Australian regulators said they began investigating the bottler
Coca-Cola Amatil Ltd. after receiving recent complaints about its
sales practices. Those complaints were lodged while the regulators
from the Australian Competition Commission were evaluating whether
Coca-Cola should be allowed to purchase Cadbury Schweppes' brands
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has twice rejected Coca-Cola's effort to buy
those brands, including Sunkist and Schweppes, on anti-competitive
grounds. It is now looking into Coca-Cola Amatil's sales agreements
with Australian retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at a very early stage,'' said Lin Enright, a spokeswowan
for the competition commission. ``We haven't even established if
there is a breach'' of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Amatil said it believes its marketing practices comply
with the law. The Sydney-based bottler is 43 percent owned by
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola. But that stake is expected to fall to 37
percent after Coca-Cola completes a deal to acquire a majority
stake in F&AMP;N Cola of Singapore, a major bottler in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, EU authorities last week seized documents from
Coca-Cola and bottlers in the United Kingdom, Austria, Denmark and
Germany. They are investigating whether the Coca-Cola system
offered rebates and other financial incentives to retailers that
offer a wide range of Coke products while removing rivals' drinks
from store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Cohen described the EU investigation as an ``annoying
complication'' for Coca-Cola at a time when it is in the process of
rebuilding its image after a recall of its products in Belgium,
France and several other European countries.
</P>
<P>
   The EU probe comes only two months after Coca-Cola decided to
eliminate 20 European nations from its Cadbury purchase because of
antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which excludes the United States, is expected to close
in about 160 nations soon. Some analysts predict later this week.
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement would not be consummated in three key markets
_ Australia, Mexico and Canada _ because the companies still need
regulatory approval. Mexican regulators have rejected the deal
once, although the companies are still trying to work it out with
them. Canadian regulators have not yet ruled on the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, in South Africa, Coca-Cola is negotiating to
purchase Cadbury's brands. Regulators there already have said they
would approve such a transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's shares fell $1.12 1/2 Wednesday, closing at $61.37
1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
