<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7496 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-CNN-COX     07-28 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-CNN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth to offer day's headlines, e-mail through phone
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coming soon _ catch the news on your phone.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the opening salvos for what is sure to be a loud and
bitter battle for customers, BellSouth announced Wednesday that it
will offer CNN Mobile reports, as well as e-mail, over its digital
wireless phones later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a portfolio of various information services
that we can offer the customer,'' said Carlton Hill, director of
product development for BellSouth's cellular unit.
</P>
<P>
   Although no pricing has yet been set, plans call for the first
version of the service to be a ``push'' technology in which stories
of up to 160 characters are broadcast to the user and stored on the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the service is primarily aimed at two groups: early
adopters who are quick to try new technology and mobile
professionals who expect to stay connected as they travel.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting those expectations, the news-to-the-phone service
will be packaged together with the company's offerings to
``high-end'' customers, who use a lot of wireless minutes and spend
a fair amount of money each month.
</P>
<P>
   Data is almost certainly the next big thing in wireless, a
potentially lucrative game in which competitors will certainly
scramble for a headstart.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers are expected to leap with both feet on the data
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Some have already announced commitments. For example, Sprint in
June announced plans to deliver a range of features from Yahoo, the
Internet powerhouse. By the end of the year, Sprint plans to offer
e-mail, address books and daily feeds of news headlines from Yahoo
News. That includes sports, finance and weather, according to
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   But Nextel and Southern _ which have Motorola technology that
combines two-way radio with cellular phones _ will be one step
ahead _ at least at the start. By late summer, both Nextel and
Southern plan to launch a data service that lets users surf the
Internet _ albeit without the graphics and multimedia options.
</P>
<P>
   That option is superior to just passive reception, said Southern
spokeswoman Stacey Liederman. ``It is one thing to get the
information to your phone, but if you can't do anything with it,
it's just information; it's not interactive.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth plans to add interactive functions in the next
generation of the technology, and other carriers will no doubt do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   That notion fits with the CNN mission, said Mitch Lazar, vice
president of new media for Turner International, a unit of Turner
Broadcasting which produces CNN. ``Our goal has been to provide
news and information to people all over the world on whatever
device they want to use.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN licenses the service, receiving a fee for the reports as
well as the use of its world-known name. CNN's arrangement gives
BellSouth a window of several months during which CNN promises not
to license its service to another carrier. But CNN is virtually
sure to announce other similar arrangements once that window
closes. ``BellSouth is the first, but there are others as well that
we continue to talk to,'' Lazar said.
</P>
<P>
   The company believes the idea of pumping news to phones has
tremendous potential, but needs time _ and as many outlets as
possible, said Lazar. ``We need to seed the market and educate the
market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The services are new to U.S. phones, although some paging
customers have been getting news for years. No one knows for sure
how fast the U.S. demand for such services will take off and how
much customers will pay for them. But similar services are offered
in Europe and have grown in popularity, especially among young,
mobile professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are customers that are data-savvy and device-savvy,''
Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
