<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7502 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-INDEPENDENT-SPI &LR;      07-28 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INDEPENDENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT FILMMAKERS IN SEATTLE FLOAT BIG DREAMS ON TINY
BUDGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   July 26, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Dear Quentin Tarantino: Please consider the following treatment
for the big screen. It's Seattle. It's strange. It's sexy, in a
damp, twisted Jet City kind of way.
</P>
<P>
   Yrs,
</P>
<P>
   M.L. Lyke
</P>
<P>
   cc: G. Lucas, S. Spielberg, F. Coppola et al.
</P>
<P>
   Synopsis: Dreams and heartache are the themes of this story. The
dream is to make a film, a bustaway independent feature film that
knocks mainstream Hollywood on its liposuctioned tush. The
heartache is what can happen in the process. It is set in Seattle,
city of anti-heroes, low clouds, high suicide rates, rain and
Microsoft millionaires. It stars bright, eager young filmmakers _
most white, most male _ who will hock everything to get a script on
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Sample Scenes:
</P>
<P>
   Scene One: Time is money
</P>
<P>
   Focus on dark, post-apocalyptic movie set built in Underground
Seattle, beneath busy Pioneer Square sidewalk. Scan past set of
devastated convenience store _ the melted videos, a Home magazine
charred and curled at edges, the ceilings dripping fried wires. Pan
in on a 24-inch-tall model of hunchbacked, insectoid alien. Follow
hyperkinetic director onto set of cryogenic lab, with two mummified
corpses and two very alive, bare-bellied combat babes in Mad Max
gear.
</P>
<P>
   Catch hectic gestures of director Tim Hines, head-to-toe in
black, as he rehearses his subterranean cast of two in escape
scene. ``You come out shooting. Like this: Blew! Blew! Blew!''
</P>
<P>
   Hines, 38, with several well-received indie features under his
belt, is a breathless whirlwind, talking 100 miles per hour. His
hands flit like butterflies, the wings curling, shaking, then
taking flight as his body bends and face twists, giving direction.
</P>
<P>
   His producer Lora Oliver, with rolls of gaffer tape hanging on
her belt, looks worried. She checks her watch.
</P>
<P>
   Close-up of watch: ``It's 10:33!'' she calls out.
</P>
<P>
   Time is money. Money is short. Producer Oliver and
director/writer Hines have budgeted three weeks to shoot `Bug
Wars,'' a sci-fi film about spiderlike aliens who invade Earth
after a doomsday war.
</P>
<P>
   It's a three-week, 12-hour-a-day race, requiring breakneck
decisions and turbo-charged stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``11:06!'' Tick, tick. Ka-ching, ka-ching.
</P>
<P>
   The film is low budget. Ultra low: $65,000, a sneeze in
Tinseltown terms, and a big comedown from $35 million. That was the
``Bug'' budget when Hines was still in negotiations with a
Hollywood distributor.
</P>
<P>
   The distributor offered Hines $17.5 million. All Hines had to do
was come up with the other half. He spent a year and a half trying.
</P>
<P>
   Close-up of Hines' eager, Boy Wonder face. ``Raising that money
was impossible! Six or seven times I built up the tower, then one
piece would fall out and the whole thing crumbled.''
</P>
<P>
   Focus on hands curling, uncurling. ``Hollywood _ how it works is
they offer you a bunch of money, but it's like a greased balloon.
Every time you reach for it, it slips farther away.''
</P>
<P>
   Scene Two: Dumpster diving
</P>
<P>
   Cut back to combat babes _ two cryogenic engineers unfrozen
decades after the obliteration of their species. They are awaiting
their cue in the devastated lab. They're trapped by invisible
aliens. Their weapons are toy guns, spray-painted black and brown.
Their sweet, unlined faces are streaked with burnt cork.
</P>
<P>
   Pan across set to director, behind camera. ``One ... two ...
three ... and ... action,'' says Hines. The camera is rolling. The
babes inch across the set in high-topped black leather boots,
bodies alert, faces taut. Their timing's perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Close up on director's animated face: ``Wonderful! Beautiful!''
beams Hines. He nails the scene in one take. That's footage saved,
time saved, money saved. Hines has become a regular Zorro at
cutting costs. ``A voice in the back of my head said, `You can do
this on a tiny, tiny budget.'''
</P>
<P>
   Flashback to Hines poring over ``Bug'' budget. He explains the
bulk of ``Bug Wars'' will be shot on green screens, and
computer-created special effects will be superimposed in
post-production. The 24-inch insectoid alien will become an
18-foot-tall nightmare, the walls of this dank basement will become
a collapsing subway, the two barely clad Earth girls will battle
aliens against a ``virtual'' city modeled on Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Focus on Hines' zippy hands as he explains how he and his
multitasking crew of four maxed a meager budget. They scavenged
Value Village and Goodwill thrift stores, garage sales and back
alleys in Pioneer Square to create sets and costumes. They became
die-hard Dumpster-divers. ``If a Dumpster was unlocked and open,''
says the director, ``we were in it.''
</P>
<P>
   They dragged styrofoam, display racks, a tossed-off camouflage
net to the set, spray-painted them, and transformed them into
desolate reminders of a toasted human civilization.
</P>
<P>
   They borrowed extension cords from everyone they knew to wire
lights and sound. They scored 10 truckloads of computer parts
headed for a landfill. ``The deal was, don't return them,'' says
Hines.
</P>
<P>
   They created a camera dolly with a wheelchair found at a
hospital thrift shop and improvised special effects, splattering
the actresses with ``bug guts'' made of strawberry applesauce and
Rice Krispies.
</P>
<P>
   They filled a crock pot with beans to feed the crew, bought
bread and pop and an 80-ounce jar of Adam's 100 percent natural
peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   And then they made a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Scene Three: The Death Scene
</P>
<P>
   Pan the set. Catch crop-topped combat babes huddling between
takes, the pale flesh on their arms covered in goose bumps from the
chill of the dank basement. Corree Dibble, ivory-skinned and
copper-curled, demonstrates the death scene she has rehearsed for
days in a mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Close up of Dibble's delicate features twisting grotesquely:
``So the bug bites off my ear and my hand and I'm looking at my
hand, and it's gone, and I'm, like, `Ehhhhh!'
</P>
<P>
   Dibble is half the cast of ``Bug Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   The other half is Darlene Sellers, a dark-eyed beauty who is
using vacation time from her job at the King County Parks and
Recreation Department for the three-week shoot. Sellers, 28, has
some previous indie experience. Dibble, a 23-year-old waitress from
Portland, is a neophyte.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've got lots of energy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Back up for lingering full-body shot of Dibble, whose pierced
belly button peeks over black stretch shorts. Along with 50 other
hopefuls, she answered the audition call for ``Bug Wars'' in the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The director found her a natural. Dibble agrees. She's got the
bug. And it's not just superhero fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I'm going to conquer Hollywood!'' she exults, then
laughs, looking around her at the blackened, devastated set.
``Although I don't think this is how I'm going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scene Four: Knock on wood
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to portrait of an exhausted, but happy Hines. He
has finished the ``Bug Wars'' shoot ahead of schedule, doing 900
setups in 15 days. He and Oliver will spend the next five months in
post-production. They won't bother with a theatrical print. This
film's not headed for the minimal multiplex. It's going straight to
video, cable, pay-per-view and syndicated TV markets.
</P>
<P>
   Will it make money?
</P>
<P>
   Hines laughs. ``It's conceivable,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there any wood nearby to knock on?''
</P>
<P>
   He's already at work on the sequel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7504 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-RISKS-SPI &LR;      07-28 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RISKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAKES ARE HUGE IN INDEPENDENT FILMMAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deep background
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaking is addictive, seductive, as alluring as the vamp with
bedroom eyes clinking cubes in her whiskey and soda at the end of
the smoky bar. Money and fame lurk in those eyes. And _ for
lustful, young independent moviemakers in Seattle _ danger.
</P>
<P>
   Odds of an upstart indie filmmaker crashing into the big time
are on par with winning the lottery. But even the lottery has
winners. Low-budget breakaways such as Kevin Smith's quirky
``Clerks'' (cost: $30,000) and Robert Rodriguez's ``Il Mariachi''
(original budget $7,000) have established mainstream Hollywood
careers for their creators. They also have fueled an unprecedented
boom of independent filmmaking across America.
</P>
<P>
   A boom _ and a glut.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an explosion now of what I call independent junk,''
says Kathleen McInnis, a programmer for the Seattle International
Film Festival. ``Too many filmmakers haven't paid their dues. They
haven't learned the storytelling part. They have no vision. They
just want to make a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 700 indie feature films from around the world were
submitted to this year's festival. About 150 ended up on screen,
and only four of those were from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Yet five or six indie films may be in production at any given
time in the Rainy City. ``The more people hear about it, the more
do it. It has a snowball effect,'' says 31-year-old Seattle
filmmaker Erik Hammen, creator of ``Love My Guts,'' a $45,000
romantic comedy about two young Seattle artists that ``deglamorizes
the starving artist thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammen, by day a contractor at Microsoft, moved here three years
ago from rural New York after hearing tales of an emerging film
scene. ``It's only increased since I moved here.''
</P>
<P>
   He compares the local film scene to the scrappy, underdog music
scene that burst into the national consciousness in the early '90s
as the chicly un-chic Grunge movement. ``Eventually, a film from
Seattle will break through and become famous. Then we can say we
knew Seattle in the good old days, before it got sold out.''
</P>
<P>
   These could, indeed, be the good old days for Seattle
independents.
</P>
<P>
   The city's hopping alternative scene offers would-be auteurs
classes, advice and access to low-cost/no-cost equipment.
Restaurants such as Mama's Mexican Kitchen, the Coastal Kitchen and
the Alibi Room, a hangout for filmies, donate food and space for
fund-raisers. Some local breweries and wineries exchange goods for
``product placement'' in films.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in this city are willing to support the arts,'' says
Hammen. ``They like Seattle to be a city that is vibrant and
artistic.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a city of young money, young ideas and disposable income.
New millionaires from Amazon.com and Microsoft have dug into their
pockets to help bank indie films. As the Dow soars, so does
investor potential.
</P>
<P>
   The risks are huge: artistic risks, emotional risks, financial
risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many, many stumbling blocks in filmmaking, and they
are very, very large,'' says Jamie Hook, director of Wiggly World,
a non-profit studio on Capitol Hill dedicated to providing
independents with the equipment and facilities to create ``great
art.''
</P>
<P>
   Some projects may implode two scenes into a shoot. Some long
before that. The stories are legion.
</P>
<P>
   Indie filmmakers Lorn Richey, 37, and Rebecca Tartarsky, 28,
scraped together savings from their 9-to-6 jobs, then sold shares
in a limited partnership to finance their $120,000 film. Called
``Pickers,'' it told the story of hip young shoppers who buy
castaway retro clothes at thrift shops and garage sales and resell
them for big bucks to vintage stores.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-May, the young married couple gathered the ``Pickers''
cast and crew at a benefit party at Wiggly World. Filming was to
begin in June. The buzz was on. But not for long.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors pulled out. The schedule fell into chaos. The
film was indefinitely postponed. ``It's pretty depressing,'' said
Richey. ``I've been progressing to larger and larger projects. This
was going to be the biggest.''
</P>
<P>
   Snohomish filmmaker Sam Severn's ``Cosmic Ray,'' a $300,000 rock
'n' roll sci-fi film that began filming in Seattle this spring,
deconstructed for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   A set's a volatile place, one filmmakers alternately describe as
a pressure cooker and a time bomb. This one went off. ``The
artistic differences led to a lot of bad feelings about the
direction the film was going,'' says Severn. ``I feel like I've
gone through the gates of hell.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Severn and his wife years to raise money for ``Cosmic
Ray.'' Now the family, including three children, are cinching
belts. ``We pretty much burned off all of our own money,'' says
Severn.
</P>
<P>
   Money's the hated despot of independent filmmakers. Some have
mortgaged homes to bank films. Some have maxed out credit cards,
sold blood at blood banks, depleted college trusts, sold bodies to
medicine and, allegedly, sold bodies to other humans.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Schmidt, author of ``Feature Filmmaking at Used-Car
Prices,'' advises hawking family antiques, or going a year without
paying the rent if necessary. He confesses to robbing his
daughter's piggy bank at a particularly low point.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, of course, sold his own used car to bank a film.
</P>
<P>
   That's the indie gamble. Stakes are huge. But the pull is
powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who walk through our door are excited for the
wrong reason. They think they're going to make it big,'' says
Wiggly World's Hook. ``They think they're going to be famous. They
have stars in their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the dame.
</P>
<P>
   When that sultry temptress at the end of the bar finally crooks
a long, red-tipped finger, winks, and pats the well-worn seat next
to her, what yearning young filmmaker wouldn't dream of a happy
Hollywood ending?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
