<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TIPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST-CUTTING TIPS FOR MAKING INDEPENDENT FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Costs of making an independent feature film continue to drop
dramatically as technology evolves. ``If you can afford to drive a
car, you should be able to make a film,'' writes Rick Schmidt in
``Feature Filmmaking at Used-Car Prices'' (Penguin Books, 354
pages, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt's book is a veritable hints-from-Heloise for
corner-cutting indies. He advises:
</P>
<P>
   _ Shoot in 16 mm, instead of 35 mm, and shoot in black and
white. These can halve the cost.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shoot scenes in a minimum number of takes to conserve valuable
film footage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use cheap locations _ an overgrown backyard can become the
wilds of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use cheap labor. Many actors and crew members will work on
low-budget productions for deferred salaries or profit shares.
Non-actors and beginning crew may work simply for the experience _
i.e. free.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep the faith. ``If you don't quit, you can finish your
no-budget feature before you die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
