<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-COURTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS URGED TO AMEND DEPORTATION LAWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying immigrants deserve their day in court, civil
rights leaders Wednesday urged Congress to amend three 1996 laws
that give the federal government largely unrestricted deportation
authority.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders' call for change touched off a dispute between the
Immigration and Naturalization Service and Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas, who chairs the House immigration subcommittee. The INS
agreed that the laws improperly removed the discretion of federal
judges in deportation cases. Smith countered that the problem with
immigration is not bad laws but inadequate INS enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In passing the three laws, Congress attempted to stem illegal
immigration by giving the INS the ability to quickly deport
immigrants, including those with resident status, who have criminal
records.
</P>
<P>
   The laws assisted the government's effort by requiring judges to
consider an immigrant's criminal past in deciding whether to uphold
a deportation decision.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of three civil rights groups said Congress went
too far, and they assailed the 1996 laws for depriving immigrants
of their due-process rights. In particular, the statutes
inappropriately removed judges' long-standing authority to
disregard a resident immigrant's criminal record in deportation
proceedings, said leaders of the American Immigration Lawyers'
Association, the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights and the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
</P>
<P>
   The three laws are the 1996 Illegal Immigration Control and
Immigrant Responsibility Act, the Anti-Terrorist and Effective
Death Penalty Act and the Personal Responsibility and Work
Opportunity Reconciliation Act.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Butterfield, executive director of the lawyers'
association, denounced Congress for stripping immigrants of their
due-process rights in a ``frenzy of anti-immigrant backlash.'' She
added that ``Congress needs to act now'' to restore those rights.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Henderson, executive director of the leadership conference,
decried the laws for stripping judges of discretion. ``It is
important that civil rights be measured by a single yardstick,'' he
said, adding that immigrants should be afforded the same rights in
court as U.S. citizens enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Jess Hordes, government affairs director of the anti-defamation
league, said the United States should have strong immigration laws
to protect its citizens but that the 1996 statutes are excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course the U.S. has the right and the obligation to ensure
that unworthy applicants do not take advantage of the asylum
system,'' Hordes said. ``But this should never be done in haste,
without adequate protections. The current system belies our
nation's moral character and humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   INS spokesman Russ Bergeron echoed the call for a restoration of
judicial discretion. Judges should be permitted to expunge the
record of upstanding resident immigrants who committed minor
offenses years ago and have already paid their debts to society,
Bergeron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a lot more sense to have the immigration judges
decide an individual's case ... and make (the immigrant) whole
again,'' Bergeron said. ``That's simply in the best interests of
all the parties, including the alien.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said the laws are not the problem. Smith, an outspoken
INS critic, said the agency should take a more active role in
expediting the admission of qualified immigrants while ensuring
that undesirables be denied entry to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The INS hid for years behind the shoddy claim it had no
discretion to intervene in the deportations of true hardship
cases,'' Smith said. ``But like every other prosecutor in the
nation, it does have discretion. It just hasn't been willing to
exercise it to benefit immigrants.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
