<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Editors note: The San Francisco Chronicle rounds up the best
of  the unusual for home and garden in this regular feature, Off
the 
 Wall.   Start Your Own Papier-Mache Menagerie 
 &HT;       
   
 By Karyn Houston  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Invite a little bit of Mexico into your home with
handmade papier-mache products that are sure to spark some lively
conversations.
<P>
   Alfred Preciado got into the papier-mache importing business in
a roundabout way. In 1965, his uncle, who produces the distinctive
art  &LR; pieces in Mexico, offered him a job selling the products in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Preciado wasn't interested. He had a good-paying job in the
automotive industry and wasn't about to give up those benefits.
</P>
<P>
   A stress-induced heart attack in 1990 made him change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left the job and went back to Mexico,'' Preciado said. He
asked his uncle: ``Do you still have that job open?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been open for 35 years,'' his uncle replied.
</P>
<P>
   A business was born.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; st  &LR; All of  &UR; Casa de Preciado's &LR;  sculptures are made in Mexico
using a centuries-old 12-step process. Time is taken after each
step to be sure the product properly dries before the next step.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, a reusable plastic mold is made of the product.
Artists fill the mold with cardboard and paste. After the piece is
released from the mold, it is sanded, covered with newspaper and
ultimately hand painted with its final design, then lacquered to
preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   The best seller is the colorful macaw on a perch. Other hot
sellers are 7-foot-tall giraffes, carousel horses and a sun with a
face painted on it. A miniaturized set of seven angels also sells
well, as does a group of mariachis that can be hung on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   The products are recommended for indoor use only, though they
can be put outside for short periods. One San Francisco shop owner
places a giraffe in front of the store each morning to attract
customers. It has been a great conversation piece.
</P>
<P>
   Preciado sells the colorful creatures at gift shows and by
appointment. Some are available immediately; others must be
ordered.
</P>
<P>
   The giraffe retails for $1,211; the macaw for $462; and the
carousel horses from $353 to $738. Custom orders are available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHERE TO ORDER
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _Casa de Preciado &LR;  papier-mache sculptures are available by calling
(650) 755-9529 or e-mailing  &LR; preciado &LR; worldnet.att.net. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
