<SLUG> BC-HOTSTUFF-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Editors note: Psst! Read the latest? If not, you haven't
read  HotStuff, the San Francisco Chronicle's weekly roundup of
great 
 new home-and-garden items and places to visit.   HOT STUFF: Book Honors Revival of Arts and Crafts Style  
 
    Chase Reynolds Ewald, a writer in Tiburon, Calif., truly loves
furnishings made in the Arts and Crafts tradition.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That love affair intensified when she moved into a Frank Lloyd
Wright-inspired home designed by a fellow of Taliesin West. She
wanted to fill the home with furniture of the same genre, and so
she became intimately familiar with artists involved in the
revivalist Arts and Crafts movement. Many of them are in the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a stunning book of artistic profiles entitled
 &UR; ``Arts and Crafts Style and Spirit, Craftspeople of the &LR; 
 &UR; Revival.'' &LR;  It is a testament to Ewald's painstaking research about
artists who are currently making Arts and Crafts-style furniture in
the tradition of Morris, Stickley and Greene &AMP; Greene.
</P>
<P>
   The Arts and Crafts movement was in full swing between 1900 and
1920, when people were looking for a simple response to
overwhelming technological advances.
</P>
<P>
   Ewald thinks the same type of response is occurring now, as
artists re-create the straightforward functionality of a Morris
chair or Stickley chest of drawers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in the whole artistic process _ I'm interested
in people who are driven to do what they do,'' she says. ``No one
does this for the money, or fame or glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the artisans profiled here are from Northern California.
The book is filled with photographs of simple, elegant pieces from
artists like Debey Zito of San Francisco (furniture), Michael Adams
(metalwork) and Dianne Ayres (textiles).
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Arts and Crafts Style and Spirit,`` by Chase Reynolds Ewald &LR; 
 &LR; (Gibbs Smith; $34.95), is available in bookstores or via &LR; 
 &LR; amazon.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; _ Karyn Houston, San Francisco Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Company Makes Words to Live By &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Carrol Caldwell used to enjoy hand lettering quotations on the
walls of her home. But painting a long quotation by Yeats in her
bathroom while tottering on a stepladder was agonizingly slow, so
she decided to speed up the process.
</P>
<P>
   After she had the words printed on vinyl, she completed the
project in just 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The graphic artist decided to share her speedy new technique
with others by starting a company called  &UR; Wall Words &LR; , based in
Orange County. She says anyone can easily master the technique of
transferring the letters to flat surfaces, using a wooden burnisher
that comes with the letters.
</P>
<P>
   She offers 63 sayings in four categories: loving quotations,
positive quotations, higher power quotations and kitchen slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell says many people enjoy putting funny sayings in their
kitchens. Two popular ones are: ``No husband has ever been shot
while doing the dishes'' and ``A balanced diet is a cookie in each
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   For other rooms in the house, people prefer more thoughtful
sentiments. Caldwell wrapped one of her favorites, by Peter
Ustinov, around a seven-foot-tall mural of her daughter that she
painted in her home. It says, ``Love is an endless act of
forgiveness, a tender look which becomes a habit.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters come in 11 colors in two standard typefaces and 22
custom styles. The standard faces cost $19.95 for 10 words, or
$29.95 for 11 to 20 words. Custom faces sell by the letter,
starting at $1 for a one-inch letter.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Wall Words are available by calling, toll-free, (888) &LR; 
 &LR; 422-6685; Web site: &LR;  www.wallwords.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; _ Terry Nagel, San Francisco Chronicle
</P>
</TEXT>
