<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7519 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BLAIR-SPI &LR;      07-28 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLAIR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLAIR WITCH' CAPTURES YOUNG VIEWERS' IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By D. PARVAZ  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not real. Was it real?'' asked Tony Brave, 19.
Relieved to hear that indie horror flick ``The Blair Witch
Project'' is only a movie, Brave reflected on why it scared him
more than mega-bucks Hollywood slasher fests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it was (shot) with home videos, and it looked more
realistic than the glamour that you see on other movies.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend, Sarah Campbell, 17, took a more sociological look at
the movie's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people buy tickets because they want to feel fear.
This movie only does well because of fear, and I think fear is not
a good human emotion, man,'' said Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can relate with those emotions. Everybody's felt
fear,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   They were just two of the thousands of moviegoers, most of them
teenagers or 20-somethings, who have made incredibly low-budget
``The Blair Witch Project'' the surprise hit of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Its appeal might be a bit of a mystery to those who believe
``Big Budget Blockbuster Equals Boffo Box Office Bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie about three young filmmakers who disappear while
making a documentary about a legendary witch had an initial
production cost of around $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   So far it's taken in about $5 million, including $2 million last
weekend, while playing on just 31 screens across the country. The
take is expected to increase dramatically after it expands to about
1,000 screens on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, ``Blair Witch'' brought in just over $130,000 in its
first week at the Neptune Theatre in the University District. The
total is up to about $231,000 now at the Neptune, which has
exclusive local rights to the film for its first two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's first-week take broke _ indeed, doubled _ the
Neptune's previous record of $64,000 for ``Star Wars: Episode One _
The Phantom Menace.'' Seven Gables/Landmark Theaters, which
operates the Neptune, cut short its scheduled run of the ``Star
Wars'' prequel in order to show ``Blair Witch.''
</P>
<P>
   All this aside, it's interesting to see why young people are
lining up for tickets at the Neptune.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about lining up at 5 p.m. for tickets to a
midnight showing.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking a movie made by unknown directors, starring
unknown actors, with nada special effects.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking giving up cherished and rare sunny Seattle days
for a 1 p.m. showing.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's draw has something to do with the fact that not many
of us can relate to being Neve Campbell, chased through a gorgeous
campus by a knife-wielding, mask-wearing psycho (see ``Scream,''
``Scream 2'' and _ sooner than later _ ``Scream 3'').
</P>
<P>
   We don't know what it's like to be Jennifer Love Hewitt, bosom
heaving, hair wild, running from a fisherman with a fetish for
disembowelment (``I Know What You Did Last Summer,'' and (sigh) ``I
Still Know What You Did Last Summer'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, those movies were cheesy scary, not legitimately
frightening,'' said Amy Lifson-Leu, 20, who along with friends
Dashal Moore, 19, and Magdalena Wolfe, 21, was waiting in line for
the 3 p.m. show at the Neptune on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one's supposed to be more realistic,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   It's been said the appeal of the movie lies in what you can't
see. That's not so much the appeal, but the reason why audiences
find it so effective as a horror story. It's everyone's horror
movie because being afraid of things that go bump in the night is
something we can all relate to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard it's really frightening, that it's really scary,''
said Moore, in response to the question of why she's in line to see
a movie on such a gorgeous day.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, Lifson-Leu and Wolfe all agreed what they'd heard of the
film's unusual format was a big draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I want to see it because it's based on a true story,''
Moore added.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not,'' piped in Lifson-Leu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's what I heard ... '' Moore responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just popular mythology to make people want to go,''
explained Lifson-Leu, knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is not alone in thinking the movie is somewhat fact-based.
In fact, ``Blair Witch'' seems to be effective in spooking
audiences because some actually believe that it's a true story (or
at least based on one).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this speaks of a certain willingness to believe that
all those freaky stories we heard at summer camp had some grain of
truth to them, that there really is a Boogeyman (or in this case,
woman) out in the woods, that we weren't just being had.
</P>
<P>
   The misconception that the movie is reality-based (a calculated
move by ``Blair Witch'' directors and marketers) is also a
testament to how genuine the film's ``mockumentary'' style really
is. It looks like someone's home movie, complete with shaky camera
work and images so fuzzy you have to use your imagination more than
you'd like.
</P>
<P>
   Off the record, more than one viewer mentioned liking that
they're getting to see it before anyone else _ a kind of a hipster
nose-thumbing thing that is such a guilty pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the additional staff brought in to deal with the big
crowds have yet to see the movie. For one thing, ``A lot of people
are getting motion sickness because the camera's being all shaky,''
said David Pickett, 17.
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear he wasn't going to see the film. ``At least
three to five people throw up during each show.'' At the concession
stand, Jenet Yasuda-Verline, 19, had also made some observations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big football player-type of guys come in and they're like `Oh,
I'm not going to be scared of this movie,' and they come out,
really scared,'' she said, adding with a giggle, ``especially the
ones who see it at night, and they have to walk out into the
dark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
