<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Water, Water Everywhere  
 The fastest-growing garden idea glitters everywhere  
   
   
 By Janet Fletcher  
 Chronicle Staff Writer  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Plants give gardens their color and texture, but
water brings gardens to life. No wonder garden designers are almost
unanimous in suggesting that a water feature _ in the form of a
pond, a gurgling fountain or simply a beautiful water-filled urn _
belongs in every landscape. And apparently clients are listening.
Bay Area designers, pond installers and nursery staffers report a
soaring interest in water gardening.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Water is really a phenomenal focal point,'' says Louis
Devereux, a San Francisco landscape designer who says he installs
water features in about half of his projects. ``Of all the things
you can put in a garden, it is among the most dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazel White, the San Francisco author of a book on water
gardening, says water appeals to our most basic instincts,
invariably drawing and holding our attention. ``It's like a
fireplace indoors,'' she says. ``People are attracted to water in
the same way they're attracted to fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Properly located, a water feature shimmers in direct sun.
Overhead branches trace patterns on the water, and mystery lurks in
its murky depths. A breeze sends a floating water lettuce scurrying
across the surface; a hovering mosquito lures a goldfish up for a
snack.
</P>
<P>
   Features with moving water, such as fountains and streams, also
captivate viewers and soothe them with sounds that block out urban
noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the softness of plants, the softness of water, and
then the hardness and strength of stone,'' Mill Valley
water-feature expert Ron Stotts says. ``There's a balance there
that resonates with people whether they're aware of it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Plain or Fancy
</P>
<P>
   A water feature can be as rustic as a salvaged old sink nestled
among garden plants or as grandly dynamic as the 65-foot stream
flowing into a pond that Stotts designed for filmmaker George
Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   White suggests that novices start with a single simple bowl to
explore reflections and see if they like the look of plants on
water. Antiques stores and salvage yards can yield attractive old
birdbaths, basins, flowerpots and urns; many nurseries have
handsome ceramic or granite containers suitable for water
gardening.
</P>
<P>
   White prefers containers that are dark inside. ``If it's light,
you see right to the bottom and you see everything collected on the
bottom,'' she says. ``There's no mystery.'' Surface reflections are
also brighter against a dark background.
</P>
<P>
   You can raise a beautiful container on a pedestal or sink an
unattractive one in the ground and disguise its edges with plants.
You can plug any drainage holes with corks and silicone caulking
and make porous containers watertight with sealant. Used wine
barrels should be fitted with readily available plastic liners to
prevent leached wine from harming plants or fish.
</P>
<P>
   More-ambitious water gardeners may want to advance to a pond,
which is really just a big container. Although many people turn to
a professional, building a pond is within the reach of a handy
homeowner. Garden centers and hardware stores sell rubber pond
liners, filters and pumps; numerous books detail the process of
digging, lining, filling, planting and maintaining your pond.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dietter of San Francisco has built 200 to 300 ponds in the
Bay Area in the last six years, most of them one- to two-day
projects. After digging the hole, Dietter puts down an underliner
to protect the liner from puncture. Made from EPDM _ ethylene
propylene diene monomer _ a new material that has revolutionized
pond building, the liner is flexible and guaranteed to last for 20
years, Dietter says.
</P>
<P>
   Stotts' ponds are more elaborate and consequently more
expensive. To give the bottom a natural appearance, he covers the
EPDM liner with earth-color concrete, then sets rocks in the
concrete. Not surprisingly, this pond artist scorns the preformed,
rigid liners that some garden centers sell. ``You can never hide it
in a way that looks natural,'' Stotts says. ``It always looks like
you've got a preformed pond.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall fountains require a water-collection basin and both a
submersible pump and tubing that must be hidden. ``As soon as you
get into moving water, you're getting into disguise,'' White says.
Perennial vines, such as ivy, can help mask the mechanics that
would otherwise ruin the romance. Submersible pumps can also add
pleasing movement and sound to ponds and to the simplest container
gardens.
</P>
<P>
   With few exceptions, most experts recommend putting a water
feature in full sun to get the benefit of reflections on the water.
``The most beautiful aspect of a water feature is the
reflections,'' White says. ``Put it in sunshine so you get the
glitter and the diamonds on the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts offer other tips as well:
</P>
<P>
   If possible, position the feature away from messy trees and
shrubs, or you will be constantly skimming unwanted leaves and
berries.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the view from the house and the deck. You may want the
water visible from an upstairs bedroom or from the kitchen window.
</P>
<P>
   Put the feature within reach of garden visitors so people can
trail their fingers through it.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid putting a pond at the bottom of a slope, or rain and
irrigation water may wash mud into it.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to planting a water feature, experts part company.
White is a purist, preferring to plant sparingly and leave space
for reflections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people overplant,'' she says. ``I ask people to consider
the beauty of the reflections _ the clouds passing overhead,
overhanging branches, upside-down pictures of roses, reflections of
an arbor or the architecture of the house. If you put too many
plants on a water feature, you lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, planting thickly helps reduce algae growth by
blocking sunlight and providing competition for nutrients. Some
designers recommend covering at least half a pond's surface with
floating plants to discourage the slimy green growth.
</P>
<P>
   And some water features need no plants at all. When Devereux
found a two-foot boulder in a client's backyard, he drilled a hole
through it, ran copper tubing through the hole, set the boulder
over a disguised water basin with a pump and created a riveting
water feature.
</P>
<P>
   Before you plant anything in a water feature, learn to recognize
the different kinds of aquatic plants. Some, like water lilies,
like to be planted in deep water so most of the plant is submerged;
their leaves may float on the surface, but their roots are in soil.
Others, such as water hyacinth, are true surface floaters with
roots floating freely in the water. Some aquatic plants, known as
oxygenators, live totally underwater. Finally, shallow-water
plants, such as water iris, like their roots in the soil but most
of their foliage in the air.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planting a small container that you can drain and
clean easily, you can get by with just one or two plants chosen
purely for aesthetics. But a pond or large container garden needs a
more balanced ecosystem to minimize algae growth. Experts recommend
planting both surface floaters to shade the pond (algae dislike
shade) and oxygenators to compete with algae for nutrients.
Properly planted and maintained, says Stotts, most ponds won't need
a mechanical filter.
</P>
<P>
   Because water plants grow quickly if unrestrained, most people
suggest planting them in plastic pots filled with aquatic potting
soil, garden soil or sandy loam. Never use soil with organic
amendments or fertilizers, which will leach into the water and
nourish the algae. Top the planting with pea gravel to keep the
soil in place, then lower into the pond or container. Bricks or
other platforms can keep the pots at the desired height.
</P>
<P>
   Water gardens need minimal maintenance. Small containers need
topping up frequently, especially in hot weather. Most aquatic
plants will need dividing and repotting once a year. Walt
McAllister of McAllister Water Gardens in Yountville says he drains
all his ponds in spring, root-prunes or divides the plants, then
repots them. For water lilies, which are heavy feeders, he buries
some slow-release fertilizer in the soil. Most other plants get all
the nourishment they need from the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Adding fish to a pond or tub garden will help control mosquitoes
and algae. County water abatement districts will also deliver free
mosquito fish to any pond owner at no charge, and these tiny fish
provide effective control. Unfortunately, there's no surefire way
to banish marauding raccoons. Electric fences deter them but shock
children and pets, too.
</P>
<P>
   For most water gardeners, a bigger concern is algae growth.
``It's the No. 1 thing that disturbs people,'' McAllister says,
``and there's no easy answer.'' Water-gardening pros like
McAllister and White encourage people to relax about algae, to
recognize it as a natural occurrence in every pond and not a sign
that something is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you call it a problem, then everyone has a
problem,'' McAllister says. Plants and fish can control it but will
never vanquish it; the best attitude is acceptance, maybe even
modest appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't actually dislike algae,'' White says. ``It doesn't
mean the water is dirty. It's a natural thing, and it can be
extremely beautiful. An algae stain will age a water feature so it
doesn't look brand new. Besides, you don't want it superclean, or
you can see the mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   For the serenity they add to gardens and the hospitable home
they offer to many desirable plants, water features earn high marks
from almost every designer. ``There's a level of intimacy that
happens around water,'' Stotts says; people naturally gather there
and want to stay. When clients agree to add a water feature, he
says, ``they don't understand the gift they're giving themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; AQUATIC PLANTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Successful ponds include a variety of plants. Some plants, such as
water lilies, help shade the surface. Others (the oxygenators)
compete with algae for nutrients. Still others, such as the
shallow-water plants, provide beauty at the margins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUBMERGED PLANTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Some, like water lilies, have leaves that float on the
surface. All need their roots in soil in deep water.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Aponogeton distachyus &LR;  (water hawthorn). Straplike floating
foliage; white flowers have vanilla scent; submerge 1-2 feet;
dormant in summer.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Myriophyllum brasiliense &LR;  (parrot feather). Fast-growing; sun
or shade; submerge 1 to 2 feet; evergreen.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Nymphaea  &LR; (water lily). Require 1 to 2 feet of water depth;
need full sun and fertilizer to bloom well.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; el,2  &UR; SURFACE FLOATERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   These plants float free, with their roots in water.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Eichhornia crassipes &LR;  (water hyacinth). Lavender flowers in
summer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &LR; Pistia stratiotes &LR;  (water lettuce). Fleshy foliage in green
rosettes; not frost hardy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; el,3  &UR; SHALLOW-WATER PLANTS &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (ALSO &LR;   &UR; CALLED MARGINALS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In nature, these plants would be found at the edge of a pond.
They like wet feet but dry ankles. This category includes many
rushes and grasses.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Acorus gramineus &LR;  (sweetflag). Grassy, pointed, irislike
foliage; variegated cultivars available; some evergreen varieties.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Colocasia esculenta  &LR; (green taro). Heart-shaped leaves on long
stalks; sun to part shade; deciduous.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Iris laevigata &LR;  (water iris). 2 to 3 feet; blue flowers in
midsummer; many named cultivars in different colors, some with
variegated foliage.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &LR; Juncus effusus  &LR; `Spiralis' (corkscrew rush). Curling, twisting
stems to 2 feet; sun or part shade; usually evergreen.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; el,3  &UR; OXYGENATORS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   These plants grow completely under water. Check aquarium stores
for a good selection. Many are frost-sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Ceratophyllum demersum  &LR; (hornwort). Dark green, needlelike
foliage; usually free-floating just beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Elodea canadensis &LR;  (Canadian pondweed). Small, dark green
leaves in dense whorls; evergreen.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; Myriophyllum verticillatum &LR;  (milfoil). Needlelike green
foliage; inconspicuous flowers; hardy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WHERE TO LEARN MORE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; ``The Basics of Water Gardening,'' &LR;  by William C. Uber
(Dragonflyer Press, 1999; $28.95).
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; ``Quick &LR;   &UR; and Easy Container Water Gardens,'' &LR;  by Philip
Swindells (Storey Books, 1998; $22.95).
</P>
<P>
   _`` &UR; Water &LR;   &UR; Features for Small Gardens,'' &LR;  by Ethne Clarke (Ward
Lock, 1998; $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; ``Water Gardens: Simple Projects, Contemporary Designs,'' &LR;  by
Hazel White (Chronicle Books, 1998; $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WHERE TO FIND WATER FEATURES AND SUPPLIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Berkeley Horticultural Nursery, &LR;  1310 McGee Ave., Berkeley;
(510) 526-4704. For aquatic plants and water gardening supplies.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Louis Devereux, &LR;  The Extravert Landscaper, San Francisco;
(415) 584-4656.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Craig Dietter, &LR;  Dietter's Water Gardens, San Francisco; (415)
586-6384. Dietter's ponds typically cost $2,000-$4,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; McAllister Water Gardens &LR; , 7420 St. Helena Highway (Highway
29), Yountville; (707) 944-0921. Open 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. Thursday
through Sunday. For aquatic plants, containers and planted
containers.
</P>
<P>
   f_ &UR; Ron Stotts, &LR;  Creative Waterways, Mill Valley; (415) 381-0652.
Expect to pay $10,000 and up for Stotts' elaborate water features.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; The &LR;   &UR; Urban &LR;   &UR; Farmer Store &LR; , 2833 Vicente St., San Francisco;
(415) 661-2204. Also, 653 E. Blithedale Ave., Mill Valley; (415)
380-3840. For pumps, EPDM liner and other pond-building supplies.
</P>
</TEXT>
