<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7522 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-28 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: POLITICIAN, BE THYSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: Mr. Safire is going on vacation. The next SAFIRE-COLUMN
will be filed Wednesday, Sept. 8, for publication on Thursday,
Sept. 9) 
(bl) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Politicians looking to their days of takeover now
submit to imageers to find ways of makeover. They steer not by
their internal compass but by some wind-sensitive telltale, and
mistakenly assume that what worked for Bill Clinton will work for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Take Al Gore. He is a man we all know _ solid, dependable, a
little kooky on the environment but experienced in foreign affairs
and a proven killer in TV debates. Because he is the scapegoat for
Clinton's sins, the vice president is running behind the untested
son of Clinton's predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he is being told to remake his persona. Spooked by
macabre bumper stickers like ``Nixon in 2000 _ he's not as stiff as
Gore,'' his handlers are hectoring him to squeeze more hands, bite
more lip and feel more pain. Focus groups want him to morph himself
into Clinton with rectitude.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Gore is well positioned now as the overdog for the
nomination and underdog for election. Time enough in the
Gore-Bradley debates to reassert his grasp of message; after that,
he can assert that the natural narrowing of poll gaps with George
W. shows a surge of interest in the underappreciated old shoe. But
if he panics and pretends to be a ``new Gore,'' he's finished.
</P>
<P>
   Same with Hillary. Told by pollsters that her liberalism is
passe in New York, she embraces the upstate dairy cartel that will
increase milk prices to her formerly cherished inner-city mothers
by 12 cents a gallon. She hastily abandons her pro-Palestinian tilt
to make ``aliyah'' to Jerusalem. Image remakers think that's smart
politics, but she is more danger to the GOP as an authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Now take the Russian PM-of-the-month, Sergei Stepashin. Boris
Yeltsin's current favorite is here to wheedle a few more billions
out of the IMF. He is a cop _ the interior minister who messed up
in Chechnya _ but in this tour, he is determined to fake a sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   He told a joke at the press club. Fifty years ago, it went this
way: An American, being shown the new Moscow subway, says,
``Beautiful station, but where are the trains?'' The Russian
replies, ``And what about your lynchings?''
</P>
<P>
   But in Stepashin's labored version, the punch line was
translated as ``And aren't Negroes being killed in America?'' It
bombed. So did all his other bungling attempts at lightness and
charm. (Didn't work for New York City Rudy Giuliani either on his
madcap visit to Arkansas.) If you're a cop, try to be a nice cop,
but not a comedian.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Stepashin about the idea of removing Lenin from his tomb
in Red Square and burying him in a regular cemetery. Moscow sources
say that Yeltsin wants to do this because he could then use the
ensuing demonstrations by Communists, infuriated at any desecration
of their shrine, as an excuse to ban the party before next summer's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin straddled: he thought Yeltsin would not do that, but
he personally felt an argument could be made for burial one day.
``I would like the Communist Party to disappear and become the
Zyuganov party,'' the prime minister said, referring to the current
head of the Reds. ``Orthodox communism is unconnected to human
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow the phrase ``human values,'' adopted to win friends in
the West, seemed incongruous coming from this hard-eyed enforcer of
Kremlin decrees. When asked by NBC's Andrea Mitchell if the
surprise move of Russian troops into Kosovo's main airport showed a
lack of Kremlin control over its military, Stepashin the Cop
reverted to type: ``That subject is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the real Stepashin, more refreshing than the fake. Here's
my advice to ``the semya,'' as fearful Russian apparatchiks refer
to the family propping up Boris Yeltsin, who flexes his muscle by
hiring and firing prime ministers. It applies to Stepashin as well
as to New York's Hillary and Arkansas' Rudy: Cut the restyling,
unfocus the groups and what we'll see is what we'll get. Let Gore
be Gore, Hillary be Hillary, etc.
</P>
<P>
   This is not as goody-goody as it sounds. Rarely has there been
such a longing for trustworthiness and a contempt for pandering.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of popular cynicism, campaign-trail conversions are
easily mocked, but authenticity can be dressed up to sell.
Positions and personality traits that irritate a minority are
marketable to the majority as characteristic of character.
</P>
<P>
   You have August to work it out. I'll be back after Labor Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
