<SLUG> BC-RALSTON-APPOINTMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL'S APPOINTMENT REFLECTS NATO'S CHANGING MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG and STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's decision to name Air Force Gen.
Joseph Ralston as NATO commander was a historic victory for the Air
Force and reflects the theory that future NATO military engagements
will rely on air power, military experts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The post has been held by a four-star U.S. Army general during
NATO's 50 years except for the appointment of Air Force Gen. Lauris
Norstad by President Eisenhower in 1956. The NATO commander's
mission during the Cold War was to make plans to defend Europe
against a potential massive Soviet ground attack.
</P>
<P>
   Former Air Force leaders said the appointment of Ralston,
currently the vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, was an
acknowledgement that NATO's future wars likely will resemble the
11-week conflict in Kosovo earlier this year when the 19 members of
NATO relied on air power, .
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how Ralston's nomination to the NATO post will
fare in the U.S. Senate, which must confirm him for the job.
Ralston's acknowledgment in 1997 of a past adulterous affair
sparked political opposition to his planned appointment as chairman
of the Pentagon's Joint Chiefs of Staff. Ralston ended up
withdrawing his name rather than undergo Senate hearings and a
floor vote.
</P>
<P>
   His selection for the NATO post sparked enthusiasm among his
supporters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest deal for the Air Force from a personnel
standpoint in the last 30 years,'' said retired Air Force Lt. Gen.
Buster Glosson, the architect of air operations during the 1991
Persian Gulf War. ``I can't think of a bigger deal. That is the No.
1 commander job in all of the world, period.''
</P>
<P>
   The appointment reflects that air-dominated wars ``are
significantly more likely to occur'' than land wars as NATO maps
out the future, said Glosson.
</P>
<P>
   Led mainly by U.S. air crews, the NATO attack in the Balkans was
designed to force Yugoslavia to end a repressive campaign against
ethnic Albanians who lived in its southern province of Kosovo. The
alliance didn't send ground forces into Kosovo until after Yugoslav
leader Slobodan Milosevic announced he would withdraw his forces
from the province.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Merrill McPeak, who as Air Force Chief of Staff in
the early 1990s unsuccessfully fought to have an Air Force officer
as NATO commander, called Ralston's appointment ``a major
breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   The appointment is all the more unusual because Ralston, a
native of Hopkinsville, Ky., didn't attend the Air Force Academy,
in Colorado Springs, Colo., a training ground for senior officers.
He graduated from Miami (Ohio) University in 1965 and entered the
Air Force through the Reserve Officer Training program.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the easy way to get to the top,'' said McPeak.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot who has logged over 2,500 flying hours in F-4s, F-16s
and F-15s, Ralston flew 147 combat missions over Laos and North
Vietnam. Other assignments have included a stint as the Air Force's
top official in charge of training and equipping all active-duty
combat squadrons.
</P>
<P>
   His medals include the distinguished flying cross and the legion
of merit.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston's appointment will become effective next May after the
departure of Army Gen. Wesley Clark, who commanded NATO's conflict
against Yugoslavia and whose term Cohen cut short by two months.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clark and administration officials often sparred over
the course of the Balkans' conflict, White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart insisted Wednesday that the Army general was not being
punished.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Lockhart said, Clark was being let go early to make room
for Ralston, who must leave his current Pentagon post by early next
year. By law, Ralston must get a new four-star position within 60
days or retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is being pushed out, no one is being forced out,'' said
Lockhart. ``The president has the highest regard for Gen. Clark. He
did incredible and invaluable work in the Kosovo conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen praised Clark Wednesday and
attributed his early replacement to a matter of timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked for the same qualities that Gen. Clark had in serving
in his capacity as commander as the European forces,'' said Cohen.
``I see the same qualities in Gen. Ralston, namely diplomatic
skills, his ... war record as such and the capability of serving in
that capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also praised Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's done a great job at a time when NATO was asked to
do something that it had not done for 48 years, which is to carry
on an active military operation,'' said Albright.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, Clark pushed a reluctant White House to prepare
for a possible ground war. At the same time, he was criticized by
some Air Force officers for barring low-level bombing runs and for
not allowing pilots to aggressively attack the full breadth of
Yugoslav targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost nobody rallied behind Wes Clark. He was a lonely
commander out there and took hell from all sides,'' said McPeak.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Ralston had been the leading candidate for the
chairmanship of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the nation's top
military position. But he was passed over after acknowledging his
involvement in an adulterous affair in the mid-1980s that surfaced
as the Air Force was embroiled in the fate of the service's first
female B-52 bomber pilot, 1st Lt. Kelly Flinn, who was prosecuted
for an adulterous affair.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen tried to draw a distinction between Flinn's and Ralston's
cases and argued that Ralston's affair did not disqualify him for
the post.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston supporters argued that Flinn faced a court-martial,
while Ralston did not, and that she had disobeyed an order to end
her affair and had lied about it. Ralston did not.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen reasoned that Ralston had an affair with a civilian when
he and his wife were separated, and that Ralston had no troops
under his command at the time. Cohen said Ralston did not hurt
``good order and discipline,'' unlike Flinn who was having an
affair with an enlisted Air Force woman's civilian husband.
</P>
<P>
   But criticism from women's groups and some members of Congress
led Ralston to ask that his nomination not go forward.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Wednesday that Ralston's earlier problems would
not bar his appointment to NATO. And Sen. John Warner, R-Va., the
chairman of the Armed Services Committee, said Wednesday that he
backs Ralston in the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have my support,'' said Warner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
