<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMMO-CLIPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DROPS FEINSTEIN'S BAN ON IMPORT OF HIGH-CAPACITY AMMUNITION
CLIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein on Wednesday accused
``anti-gun control forces'' of using ``dastardly'' parliamentary
maneuvers to block her legislation banning the import of
high-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   The California Democrat had succeeded in folding into the Senate
Juvenile Justice bill her legislation that would prohibit the
importation of foreign-made, high-capacity magazines that hold more
than 10 rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said these high-capacity clips are used with firearms
developed by the military for killing large numbers of people in
close combat. She said they have no use in hunting or self defense
but have become fatal instruments in the hands of high school
students.
</P>
<P>
   She cited the example of the April massacre at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., in which one of two student shooters
used a high-capacity magazine, resulting in the gun-shot deaths of
13 children.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein expressed outrage Wednesday on the Senate floor after
discovering her ban on the magazines had been stripped away last
week from Senate crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something rather dastardly has happened to it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation, which was approved in May, is designed
to crack down on juvenile crime, with a handful of gun control
provisions attached. These include a requirement for instant
background checks on all sales at gun shows and a requirement that
safety devices be sold with all handguns.
</P>
<P>
   A similar House bill contains none of those provisions, although
efforts at negotiating a compromise are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein blamed ``anti-gun control forces,'' for a
parliamentary maneuver known as a ``blue-slip challenge,'' that
knocked her provision out of the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the House argued that because the importation
of high-capacity clips generates revenue for the treasury _ in the
form of a 4.2 percent tariff on some of them _ banning these
imports would cost Americans money and therefore means the Senate
Juvenile Justice bill is actually a tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   However, under the Constitution, ``all bills for raising revenue
shall originate in the House.'' And because the provision
originated in the Senate _ and since the House Juvenile Justice
bill contains no matching ban on the import of high-capacity clips
_ the Senate bill became illegal as long as it contained
Feinstein's provision. So, Senate Republican leaders were compelled
to take it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainly, we were sideswiped and given no time to recover,''
Feinstein said of the last-minute maneuvering. She said the
parliamentary challenge was a ``cynical maneuver'' and ``an attempt
to further delay the will of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to name the House members who challenged her
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein pleaded with House and Senate negotiators who will
hash out a compromise Juvenile Justice bill between the two
chambers to reinsert the ban on the import of high-capacity
ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Will those who claim to support reasonable,
limited, targeted regulations on firearms finally put their money
where their mouths are, or will they continue to use unprecedented
parliamentary maneuvering to avoid the issue and give the National
Rifle Association its very own Christmas in July,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the House voted unanimously to approve a measure
similar to Feinstein's legislation, but it was upended when the
larger gun control bill it was attached to failed.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Powers, an NRA spokesman, said Feinstein is wrong in
thinking that banning the importation of ``a piece of metal and a
spring,'' will curb crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she had her way, she would ban (all firearms,)'' Powers
said. ``She would go around to Mr. and Mrs. America and pick them
all up.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers said semi-automatic firearms have been around for more
than 200 years and are used in competitive shooting events,
including in the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Powers also denied the NRA was involved in stripping Feinstein's
provision from the bill. ``We don't make the rules, Congress
does,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Feinstein spearheaded the passage of legislation that
banned American companies from manufacturing semi-automatic assault
weapons and high-capacity clips that hold more than 10 rounds.
</P>
<P>
   But a loophole in that law allowed the high-capacity clips to be
imported. Last year, more than 11.4 million of these clips were
approved for importation into the United States from 17 different
countries, according to Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
