<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY OUTLINES PRACTICE OF GIVING VOTERS GIFTS PRIOR TO ELECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ One in every three Mexicans who cast ballots
earlier this month in a crucial election won by President Ernesto
Zedillo's governing party now say they received groceries,
scholarships, crop payments or other government handouts before the
vote, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of those who received the gifts voted for the
party, the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, the study
found.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, carried out in the state of Mexico, where the party
won the governor's race on July 4, is one of the first measurements
of the influence that government aid programs are having in
elections in a period when reforms have made outright ballot theft,
a common tactic in the past, almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders say the PRI has used government resources to
buy votes not only in the elections in the state of Mexico, but
also in elections in Guerrero, Tamaulipas and other states. The
votes are seen as dry runs for presidential balloting next year.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was carried out during the third week of July by Mori
International, a private, independent firm. The state of Mexico, a
sprawling region of industrial suburbs and hardscrabble farms
surrounding Mexico City, is the country's most populous, with 13
million residents, and like the federal presidency, its statehouse
has been controlled by PRI governors for 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   Arturo Montiel, the PRI candidate, was elected governor with 41
percent of the vote. But the two losing candidates, from the
center-right National Action Party and the center-left Party of the
Democratic Revolution, insist that the PRI's overwhelming use of
government resources on behalf of its candidate made the election
unfair. They have joined forces to carry out continuing protests.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Lund, who directed the Mori survey, said he decided to
study the state of Mexico elections after noting before balloting
for governor last year in Guerrero that the government was
systematically using state-financed aid programs to persuade
farmers, students, housewives and other poor people to cast ballots
for the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we call pork in the United States,'' Lund said.
But the PRI's power to deliver government aid to constituents is
extensive because the party has held presidential power since the
1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``All over the world, there's an advantage to incumbency,'' Lund
said. ``But the powers of an incumbent are far greater for a party
that's been in power for seven decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Reta Martinez, a PRI spokesman, acknowledged that during
the state of Mexico elections there were numerous complaints about
local governments handing out food, building supplies and other
gifts to buy votes. But he said all three parties had engaged in
the same vote-buying practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the cleanest elections that we've had,'' Reta
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Duran, the National Action candidate, who finished
second, with 34 percent of the vote, denied that any cities
controlled by National Action had used municipal programs to buy
votes, although he conceded that the party had distributed baseball
hats and T-shirts bearing the party insignia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its not accidental that 80 percent of the people who said in
this poll that they received government aid said they voted for the
PRI,'' Duran said.
</P>
<P>
   Persons interviewed for the poll identified nearly a dozen
distinct forms of government aid that the pollsters concluded were
used to persuade voters to back the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Both in Guerrero and in the state of Mexico, Lund said,
scholarship payments were delayed for two months, with checks
finally delivered to parents of poor students just before the
balloting, often as PRI members made copies of parents' voting
credentials. The government also delayed delivery of farm payments
until just before the balloting, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more effective in garnering votes was the delivery of
groceries to poor families, selected from detailed lists of
low-income households compiled by a government anti-poverty agency,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   This practice was widely documented by journalists. In the
working class Mexico City suburb of Ecatepec a week before the
elections, a neighbor working for the PRI knocked at the door of
Maria Garcia Romero, a young mother, inviting her to visit a nearby
home serving as the party's neighborhood headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving away groceries,'' the party worker told Mrs.
Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   After Mrs. Garcia waited in line behind other neighbors, PRI
workers gave her a bag of sugar, oil, eggs and other foodstuffs,
wrote down her name and address from her voting credentials and
took her photo, Mrs. Garcia told a reporter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
