<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 What's For Dinner? Hire a Personal Chef   By Tara Duggan 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  First, the gods of food technology bestowed upon
us the TV dinner. Then there was Lean Cuisine, its foil packets
glistening like astronaut food. Today, you can get organic
Sichuan-style string beans in the freezer case. All this
convenience makes you wonder if the homemade dinner will make it
very far into the next millennium.
<P>
   It may _ but cooked by others. As Americans opt for quicker
solutions to eating, the answer for many is personal chefs. They
arrive, knives and groceries in hand. Surprisingly, many of these
personal chefs can cook a homemade dinner for less than the cost of
a meal at Denny's.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike private chefs, who are usually associated with the
wealthy, personal chefs do not live in your home. Instead, they
visit your kitchen as frequently as you want, cook for a few hours,
and stock the refrigerator and freezer with homemade meals _
complete with reheating instructions. They'll even wash the dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm with a partner, I enjoy cooking a meal as a way of
spending the evening together,'' says Martin Marks, who pays
personal chef Rachel Stewart $20 per meal to come to his home and
cook for him once a month. ``But as a single person, there's no way
I'm going to shop, cook, serve it, and clean it up just for myself.
I don't have that kind of time. No, I don't make that kind of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Meals prepared by personal chefs range from $7 to $20 per
person. Price depends on location _ the Bay Area tends to be on the
high end _ and the number of meals you order. Chefs are flexible
with meal preparation, but usually have a minimum service of 15 to
20 meals per month.
</P>
<P>
   Some personal chefs prefer to work in professional catering
kitchens and deliver the just-made food, others work in clients'
kitchens but seldom spend more than five hours there. ``Chefs work
in their clients' home in order to provide a more personalized
service,'' says David MacKay, executive director of the United
States Personal Chef Association. ``Like I always tell the chefs,
`if you get a customer who wants chitlins, you best get the pig
boiling.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since personal cheffing is such a new concept, many potential
clients are reluctant to have strangers come into their home and
cook for them. To help assure potential clients, to provide
references and to try to instill an accepted set of standards for
the chefs, David MacKay and his wife, Susan Titcomb, started USPCA
in Albuquerque in 1991. The organization also gives independent
chefs a professional affiliation. In 1992, the organization
registered 15 members. Today, there are more than 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   USPCA also offers certification training for its members. Rachel
Stewart, who trained American Express employees for 13 years before
becoming a personal chef, recently led one such seminar for eight
aspiring personal chefs in her San Anselmo home.
</P>
<P>
   Students at the seminar ranged from a San Francisco pastry chef
who had had enough of the grueling pace of restaurant work to a
Turlock rancher who was looking for something to do after raising
her kids. During the two-day seminar, Stewart lectured her students
on issues such as food safety, business planning and marketing. She
also supervised the students' preparation of a few recipes
developed by the USPCA to work well when made ahead of time and
then refrigerated or frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Robfogel, who started a personal chef company called A Zest
for Life in Oakland last October, says it's difficult getting new
clients not to think of their service as an unaffordable luxury.
``The other day I delivered this meal to a customer who said at
first that the service was too expensive for them,'' Robfogel
explains. ``But after she and her husband ate it, they loved it so
much they decided to order three meals a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the cost, customers tend to worry about the fact that
some of the meals are frozen. But Robfogel's partner, Heidi
Hornikel, a Culinary Institute of America-trained catering chef,
develops recipes that work well in the freezer. For example, they
offer an apricot-stuffed pork chop with braised mustard greens and
potato gratin. Or there's Armenian stuffed cabbage with homemade
marinara sauce and steamed green beans and baby carrots.
</P>
<P>
   A Zest for Life meals usually cost between $15 and $18 per
person. This price tag results from an insistence on using organic
vegetables and top-quality, free-range meats whenever possible,
Robfogel says. ``The quality of the ingredients is very important
to us, which I guess is why we're on the pricier side. But everyone
has a different way of measuring the value of their time. For the
most part, the convenience is really worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The USPCA estimates that more than 30,000 people nationwide now
use personal chefs. Despite this rise in popularity, there are
relatively few personal chefs in the Bay Area. The USPCA has 35
members registered in the Bay Area _ as opposed to 80 in Los
Angeles _ although many personal chefs work independently. But with
its glut of chefs and its food-loving population, the Bay Area may
become a prime market for personal chefs of the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
