<SLUG> BC-SECRET-BERRY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS OF SUCCESS  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Pudding the Berries in Bizou's Summer Dessert   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Loretta Keller first tasted Summer Berry Pudding
when she was the chef at Stars Cafe in the 1980s. She fell in love
with the way it showcased the abundance of berries at the height of
the summer season. So when she left to open Bizou, she adapted the
recipe for her own use.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pudding has a dense, berry-saturated texture that you don't
find in most versions of this dessert. She first cooks the berries
until they begin to break up. Then she soaks the bread in the
juices and layers it with the berries in a glass or ceramic mixing
bowl. The top is then gently pressed for up to 24 hours with a
three-pound weight, so the mixture becomes dense and heavy with the
syrup.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, the pudding can be unmolded for an
impressive presentation _ a wonderful ending to a summer meal.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bizou, 598 Fourth St. (at Brannan Street), San Francisco; &LR; 
 &LR; (415) 543-2222. Lunch weekdays, dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS: &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _ Pressing the pudding. &LR;  By weighting the pudding in its bowl, the
bread becomes saturated with berry juices and the flavors deepen
and meld.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Adding cassis. &LR;  This black currant liqueur adds a vibrant
note to the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BIZOU'S SUMMER BERRY PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 pints strawberries, rinsed, hulled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 pints raspberries
</P>
<P>
   5 pints blackberries
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cassis liqueur
</P>
<P>
   1 loaf  &LR; pain de mie  &LR; or Pepperidge Farm sliced white bread
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the strawberries, lemon juice and sugar in a large
saucepan. Place over medium heat and cook for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the raspberries and blackberries and cook until they begin
to break up. Stir in the liqueur. Remove from heat and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Taste for a balance of sweet and sour. If necessary, add more
sugar or lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To form the pudding:  &LR; Cut off the crust from the  &LR; pain de mie, &LR; 
then cut the loaf in half lengthwise. Slice each half into
1/8-inch-thick slices. If using Pepperidge Farm bread, simply cut
off the crusts and cut each slice in half.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the cooked berries to a shallow pan. Dip enough
half-slices of bread into the berry juices to line a glass or
ceramic mixing bowl. Using a slotted spoon, add some berries to the
bowl. Continue layering dipped bread and berries into the bowl
until the pudding comes 2 inches from the rim of the bowl. Place a
piece of plastic wrap directly on top of the pudding. Set a flat
plate on top and place a 3-pound weight on the plate (use a large,
heavy can of food such as tomatoes, or use a plastic container
filled with water). Place the bowl in a baking pan to catch any
drippings.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate the pudding for 18 to 24 hours, until set.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, remove the weight and plastic wrap, and either unmold
the pudding onto a serving plate, or spoon the pudding into
individual bowls. Garnish with dollops of softly whipped cream, or
pass the cream at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 730 calories, &LR;   &LR; 13 g protein, 157 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 7 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 516 mg
sodium, 35 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
