<SLUG> BC-TASTE-FUDGE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASTER'S CHOICE  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Decadent Chocolate Sauce Rates Lip-Smacking Raves  &HT;        By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Where there's ice cream, chocolate sauce isn't far
behind.
<P>
   Today's panel tasted a total of 11 sauces, but limited the
tasting to those labeled hot fudge or chocolate sauce. Chocolate
syrups were not included.
</P>
<P>
   All of the sauces were heated in the microwave and stirred
before serving. They were served individually in cups as well as
with vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors went to  &UR; Susan Elaine's Incredibly Decadent Fudge &LR; 
 &UR; Sauce &LR;  (9.75 ounces, $5.99 at Andronico's). Two panelists described
it as ``classic American'' chocolate sauce. One thought the vanilla
flavor was too strong, but others liked the balance. Three would
buy it, one might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Second best was &UR; Chocoholics Semi-Sweet &LR;  (10 ounces, $4.99 at
Andronico's). Some described the flavor as burnt. But three
panelists liked the chocolate flavor. Four would buy it, one would
not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mrs. Richardson's Hot Fudge  &LR; (16 ounces, $1.99-$2.79 at many
supermarkets) came in third. One panelist thought it was too thick
and sticky, but others liked the fudgy texture. Two panelists also
thought it was too sweet, but two others liked the balance. Three
would buy it, one might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hershey's Chocolate Shoppe Fudge Topping &LR;  (16 ounces for
$1.99-$2.59 at many supermarkets) scored only two points lower than
Mrs. Richardson's. Two panelists described the texture as more like
caramel than chocolate, though most liked the flavor. One dissenter
disliked the overly sweet taste, however. Three would buy it, one
might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place went to  &UR; Whole Foods Dark Chocolate Sauce  &LR; (10
ounces, $4.99 at Whole Foods). Two panelists described the flavor
as cheap tasting, but another thought it had good balance of sweet
to bitter. One would buy it, two might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Smucker's  &LR; (11.75 ounces, $1.99-$2.49 at many supermarkets)
came in sixth. Two panelists described the texture as pasty. One
panelist didn't like the sauce on its own, but thought it was good
on ice cream. One would buy it, two might buy it, and two would
not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Fran's, The Silver Palate, Smucker's Dove,
Narsai's and Wagner's, but they scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna
Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Roland
Passot chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in
Larkspur and Menlo Park, and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
