<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD IN THE NEWS  
   
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Those Little O's Awarded FDA Label of Approval   By Kim Severson 
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  If you were surprised by recent ads linking
Cheerios and cancer prevention, you weren't alone.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what industry observers call a victory over strict
restrictions placed on food advertising by the Food and Drug
Administration, the maker of cereals like Cheerios, Total and
Wheaties earlier this month won the right to claim the products
might help fight heart disease and some cancers. Print and
television ads pushing the message hit within days.
</P>
<P>
   The fight began when General Mills asked the government for
permission to state on some product packages that eating a low-fat
diet high in whole-grain foods may reduce the risk of heart disease
and certain cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Foods rich in dietary fiber can already make certain health
claims on packaging. But General Mills cited a 1989 conclusion by
the National Academy of Sciences that whole grains mix other
important nutrients with fiber and thus are disease-fighting, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration accepted that conclusion, and
paved the way for makers of foods containing 51 percent or more
whole grain ingredients by weight to start advertising the health
link.
</P>
<P>
   Not all foods sold as whole-grain products necessarily provide
the benefit, so check the label. The first ingredient listed should
be a whole grain, such as ``whole grain oats,'' ``whole grain
wheat'' or ``whole wheat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Grape Expectations
</P>
<P>
   Think the world needs more seedless grapes? Government
scientists in Fresno do.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers with the 76-year-old United States Department of
Agriculture grape breeding program announced earlier this month
that they have cuttings from three new varieties available for
growers and breeders. They expect the new grapes to hit the market
in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa, a new white seedless grape, yields large, sweet fruit.
Program geneticist David Ramming says these grapes ripen in about
the same time as Thompson seedless but the vines produce good-size
fruit without being sprayed with a growth regulator _ a common
practice.
</P>
<P>
   The new Summer Royal black seedless grapes are sweet, large and
firm, making them ideal for snacks and salads. And they fill a
production gap at the end of August, when there are usually no
American-grown black seedless grapes on the market, Ramming says.
</P>
<P>
   The third variety, called a summer Muscat seedless grape, is
designed especially for raisin producers. It's easy to candy-coat
because it's seedless. Most raisin grapes have seeds that have to
be removed mechanically, making the raisins sticky and hard to
process.
</P>
<P>
   The Fresno breeding program, best known for developing Red Flame
seedless grapes, has been testing some of new varieties for as long
as 18 years in the San Joaquin Valley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Shape Up, America
</P>
<P>
   We're getting fatter. According to a report released last week
at the American Medical Association's annual meeting in Chicago, a
third to half of adult American women are overweight, and nearly
one-fourth are clinically obese.
</P>
<P>
   National studies suggest that 14 percent of children and 12
percent of adolescents are overweight. The American Academy of
Pediatrics' committee on nutrition has established obesity as the
top problem in child health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
