<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE POTPOURRI  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Sturdy Varietals Distinguish the Delta   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Wine grapes like moderation. If it's too hot,
grape sugars soar and acids drop. If the temperatures are too cool,
sharp acids dominate and grape sugars are shy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   California's Central Valley is not the best place for
cool-climate white varieties like Chardonnay. But the sturdier
Chenin Blanc, and a handful of other wine grapes, mature nicely
with balanced acids and sugars in cooler parts of the hot Central
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The best site for wine grapes in this vast region is the Delta,
a wetlands that lies roughly between the Sacramento Valley _ the
upper part of the Central Valley _ and the larger southern Central
Valley, also known as the San Joaquin Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly triangular in shape, bordered by the San Joaquin and
Sacramento rivers, the Delta consists of a network of small
islands, many of which are home to the region's small wine-grape
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Chenin Blanc and Petite Sirah do well here because, while
daytime temperatures are warm, the nights and early mornings are
tempered by maritime influences from the San Francisco Bay.
Clarksburg and Merritt Island are the two AVAs (American
Viticulture Area) known mainly for Chenin Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle and R &AMP; J Cook, both located in Yolo County, are the only
two wineries in the Clarksburg AVA. Bogle is a major grape supplier
to other wineries throughout the state and also makes its own wines
although, ironically, not Chenin Blanc, as the grapes were pulled
out to plant more Chardonnay. Smaller than Bogle, R &AMP; J (Roger and
Joanne) Cook still makes a Clarksburg Chenin Blanc, among other
wines, including a white and red Delta blend.
</P>
<P>
   Although other grape varieties are grown in the Clarksburg part
of the Delta, winemakers throughout the state favor the clean,
honeyed melon flavors and bright citrusy acidity of Clarksburg
Chenin Blanc. Dry Creek Vineyards, Baron Herzog and Weinstock
purchase Clarksburg Chenin Blanc grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Further east is the Lodi AVA, with main vineyards between
Sacramento and Stockton. Chenin Blanc, Sauvignon Blanc and some
other grapes are grown in the area, but Zinfandel is the star. Lodi
Zinfandels are known for ripe berry flavors and an earthiness that
adds depth and complexity. Noteworthy brands include Lucas Winery,
Pierano and Las Vinas. Mondavi-Woodbridge winery, known for quality
value wines like Zinfandel, is one of the largest wineries in the
region. Sonoma's Kenwood bottles a Lodi Zinfandel and Sebastiani
produces its Vendange wines in a winery near Woodbridge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Gerald D. Boyd is a Chronicle staff writer. Send questions for Wine
Q &AMP; A to him at Food Department, The Chronicle, 901 Mission St.,
San Francisco, CA 94103; or e-mail him at  &LR; food &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
