<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-SALAD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING TO COOK  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Old Time Dressing Goes Tropical   By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  As part of a meal, salads are rarely memorable.
But they can be. If you make salads as carefully as you would an
entree or dessert they can add verve and freshness to a simple
dinner.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget the idea that salad can be made by tossing a hodgepodge
of ingredients in a bowl then calling it a day. I've included some
basic rules for making salads that should ensure good results.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, before the advent of commercial salad dressings,
everyone cooked their own creamy-style dressing. The Hawaiian
Dressing recipe I've included today, from Helen Brown's ``West
Coast Cookbook,'' is in that vein. It is very good on tropical and
some summer fruits.
</P>
<P>
   The range of salad possibilities is almost endless. Remember,
your best tool when cooking is to taste everything as you are
making a recipe. Trust your palate.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Marion Cunningham, Bay Area cooking teacher, is the author of
``Learning to Cook,'' ``Cooking With Children,'' ``The Fannie
Farmer Cookbook'' and ``The Breakfast Book,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Here are step-by-step rules for salad-making.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discard any blemished, yellowed, limp or wilted leaves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rinse all fresh, raw ingredients under cold running water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dry all rinsed greens. Salad dressings won't adhere to wet
leaves. Dry the greens with paper towels or cloth towels, or use a
salad spinner. It works just like the spin cycle on your washing
machine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Store greens in a plastic bag, adding a damp towel (wet the
towel and then wring it out) to the bag. Leave a little head space
before closing the bag.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vary your salads by trying different greens, either by
themselves or in combination. Try small spinach leaves, watercress,
red oakleaf and small amounts of fresh herbs like basil or fennel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't put the dressing on a tossed green salad until you are
ready to serve it.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are making a salad of cooked ingredients, you may add
the dressing earlier so it penetrates the ingredients and fully
flavors the salad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; HAWAIIAN DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   This is very good over slices or cubes of mango, pineapple or
pear. Preparing it is a good learning lesson because you have to be
careful not to overcook it. It only takes a couple of minutes, so
don't turn away from the stove for any reason while you are making
this.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pineapple juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup salad oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup white wine vinegar or cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the sugar, salt, mustard and cornstarch in a 11/2- to
2-quart saucepan. Stir to mix well. Add the pineapple juice, salad
oil and vinegar; stir to blend thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the heat to medium and, using a whisk or a spoon, stir
constantly. In a couple of minutes the mixture will become slightly
thickened. Watch carefully. As soon as the mixture thickens and
changes from a cloudy light color to a translucent clear light
color, remove from the heat. If you overcook the dressing, it will
separate and become lumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into a jar and let cool completely before using.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 11/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 55 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 3 g carbohydrate,
5 &LR;   &LR; g fat (0 saturated), 0 cholesterol, 45 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; TROPICAL FRUIT SALAD WITH HAWAIIAN DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe mangoes, or 4 Bosc pears, or 5 cups pineapple chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 head butter lettuce, leaves separated, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiian Dressing (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Peel and pit the mangoes, or peel and core the pears. Cut the
fruit into cubes. Combine the fruit in one covered container, the
lettuce in another. Refrigerate until ready to assemble and serve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble:  &LR; Just before serving, arrange a couple lettuce
leaves on each serving plate, making a cupped nest. Divide the
fruit among the lettuce cups. Drizzle 2 or 3 spoonfuls of the
dressing over each serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (with 2 tablespoons dressing): &LR;   &LR; 180 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1
g &LR;   &LR; protein, 21 g carbohydrate, 5 g fat (0 saturated), 0 &LR; 
 &LR; cholesterol, 49 mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; BASIC VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red or white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cold water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the vinegar, water and salt in a small bowl; let
stand for a few minutes. Add the pepper, then slowly stir or whisk
in the oil. Taste for acid and salt. Add more if the dressing is
too bland.
</P>
<P>
   Stir to blend before using, or store in a jar with a
tight-fitting lid and shake well before using.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 11/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 40 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 0 carbohydrate, 5
g &LR;   &LR; fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 44 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
