<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY AREA CLASSICS  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 The Baltic Transcends Time   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  When the Baltic, a historic bar-restaurant in
Point Richmond, has a boisterous night with jazz, drinks and food,
it might seem a quiet time compared to some of the goings-on here
earlier in this waning century. And when the restaurant experiences
a rare lull _ say, at 6:30 on a Monday night _ the scene might seem
lively compared to another brief period in its past. Because at one
time fairly early in its 95-year existence, the place was a
well-patronized bordello, and for a few years in the '30s, it was a
funeral parlor. Before, after and in between, the sturdy Victorian
brick building was an adjunct to the adjoining old firehouse, which
has since moved across the street, served as city hall and, during
Prohibition, housed a speakeasy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may have had a few other personae as well, but exact dates
are hard to come by. It is documented that the Baltic was initially
a tavern built four years after the Santa Fe Railroad established
its western terminus in 1900 in what was to become Richmond,
ferrying passengers to and from San Francisco across the bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltic's checkered past has one constant: the bar, says
current co-owner (with chef/partner Charles Wise) Paula Helene. The
bar _ a great period piece in dark wood with an enormous back
mirror, brought over from an even older San Francisco establishment
in 1904 _ has its firm place in local lore and documented history:
Jack London mentions it in one of his books, and a brass plaque in
the comfortable bar room attests to its authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Helene, a New York-born singer/entrepreneur, acquired the
establishment in 1993. She added an eclectic mix of musical
entertainment (rhythm and blues, jazz, rock and flamenco) three
nights a week; she initiated a new period, capitalizing on a
well-planned combination of old and new that's reflected in
everything from the decor to the menu and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The room is decorated with dark wood-paneling, a high dark green
ceiling and green-cloth covered tables topped with white butcher
paper. The main dining room has a comfortable, if slightly worn,
old-time feeling. The well-protected, heated patio holds planters
with country-garden flowers and thriving herbs, which are put to
good use in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Wise, a graduate of Johnson &AMP; Wales' culinary program, also
hews the line between tradition and 1990s sensibilities: He
presents such late-century favorites as tempura shrimp, fresh
mozzarella with prosciutto and basil, confit of duck ravioli,
vegetarian capellini and grilled salmon with mango salsa.
</P>
<P>
   But he also dishes up food that wouldn't have startled Baltic
tavern patrons 90 years ago: oysters on the half shell, creamy
mushroom soup, a mixed grill (pork loin, duck breast, halibut) and
a seared flat-iron steak draped over a mound of fluffy mashed
potatoes and anointed with a rich gravy. Maybe the shiitakes in the
gravy wouldn't have been there, but it's still a plate full of
nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect harking back to earlier times are the large
portions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want people to leave hungry,'' says owner/entertainer
and sometimes waitress Helene as she puts a mountainous,
whipped-cream-topped slice of praline ice cream pie (house-made, of
course) in front of a diner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
