<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERRIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO FERRY GODMOTHER TO SOLVE SAN FRANCISCO CAR CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUSSELL LONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For many years, Americans _ particularly
American environmentalists _ have had a love affair with the ferry
boat.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do ferries relieve roadside congestion (as well as
nerves frayed from sitting in bumper-to-bumper traffic), but
conventional wisdom says ferries also reduce air pollution by
getting us out of our gas-guzzling cars.
</P>
<P>
   While this may have been true 25 years ago, when automobile
engines produced far more pollution than today, ferries have
escaped tough scrutiny and Clean Air Act requirements for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, boosters perpetuated the myth of their
cleanliness. The result? Most people still think ferries are as
environmentally friendly as Tall Ships on the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   Abetting this illusion is our romantic view of seafaring craft.
</P>
<P>
   Often graceful and sleek, many ferry boats seem part of the
wondrous ocean itself.
</P>
<P>
   As the world's first vehicle, they continue to capture our
imaginations. We name them, just as we do our children, and we are
willing to spend small fortunes to maintain them.
</P>
<P>
   Similar romantic notions are almost certainly diverting the
high-powered mayors and other members of the Bay Area Water Transit
Task Force, currently pushing their proposal for the world's
largest ferry service through the California Legislature with
wake-jumping alacrity.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed $2 billion system would bring 120 huge,
5,000-horsepower catamarans operating at speeds of up to 50 mph
into a spider web of routes around the San Francisco area, starting
as early as 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, despite good intentions to reduce traffic
congestion, the task force has so far neglected to study air
pollution and safety impacts. Had members done so, they would have
discovered that even the most modern ferries are 10 times more
polluting per passenger than recently built cars, and 34 times more
polluting than the natural-gas bus designs proposed for Golden Gate
Transit.
</P>
<P>
   How can this be?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: California automobiles have become far cleaner in
the past quarter-century, emitting only 6 percent of the
smog-forming pollutants they used to. Buses have also become much
cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Ferries use a dirtier type of diesel fuel than do buses. The
boat engines spew massive amounts of cancer-causing particulates
and sulfur emissions into densely populated urban shorelines often
inhabited by low-income and racially diverse constituencies. The
task force has not yet addressed these problems of environmental
justice.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Harbor Safety Committee, a government group
replete with marine industry experts, has expressed concerns,
citing the increased risk and danger of collisions with other
vessels, possibly leading to an oil spill in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Windsurfers, kayakers and fishers should also be worried about
collisions. It's difficult for a high-speed ferry skipper to spot
small craft when spray is hitting the windshield at 50 mph.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposed ferry service goes forward, it will be a lot
harder to enjoy peace on the bay, especially on foggy days, knowing
you could instantly become sushi when a ferry confuses you with a
whitecap. Freighters and cruise ships have a 15-mph speed limit for
a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to air pollution and safety problems, high-speed
ferries would also create large wakes that erode shorelines,
causing damage to sensitive wetlands and wildlife habitat and
endangering threatened mammals such as sea lions.
</P>
<P>
   Their engines will dump cancer-causing dioxin into the ocean.
The craft will create significant noise pollution and diesel fumes
that will annoy marine enthusiasts and shoreline residents,
destroying one of the last truly peaceful natural areas in the
region. To paraphrase Lewis Mumford, adding a high-speed ferry
system to relieve road congestion is like loosening your belt to
lose weight. While it might make you feel better, it makes no
sense, especially if it means destroying our environment, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Examiner contributor Russell Long, executive director of
Bluewater Network in San Francisco, is a former America's Cup
yachting skipper and a Guinness recordholder as fastest sailor in
the world.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
