<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIG-BOARD-SURVIVE-ART     07-28 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-BOARD-SURVIVE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVAL OF NYSE AT ISSUE IN CHANGING TECHNOLOGICAL WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(yn) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A quarter-century ago, when Richard A. Rosenblatt was
first developing his skills as a trader on the floor of the New
York Stock Exchange, it was widely predicted that the Big Board's
days were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Fixed commissions were banned in May 1975, plunging Wall Street
into a frenzy of competition for customer trades. As trading fees
shrank, dozens of less efficient brokerage firms closed their
doors. With member firms dropping away, the price of an exchange
seat even dropped as low as $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenblatt's eyes shine when he remembers those fearsome
days. ``For a young entrepreneur, the opportunities just
exploded,'' he said. With prices suddenly within his reach, he was
able to borrow money and buy a seat on the exchange in 1979; it
became the cornerstone of the institutional trading firm that bears
his name.
</P>
<P>
   Today, skeptics are once again predicting the demise of the Big
Board. Its trading floor in lower Manhattan is no match, they say,
for the new computer-driven systems that are attracting a growing
share of the trading that traditionally has been done on the
exchange and its archrival, the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, Rosenblatt is optimistic. ``This game is for the
New York Stock Exchange to lose,'' he said confidently last week,
on the eve of the exchange's confirmation that it hopes to
transform itself into a for-profit corporation with public
shareholders before the end of the year. ``They've got it _ they've
got a better product for the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as the New York exchange and its chief executive,
Richard A. Grasso, search for a survival strategy, Wall Street's
central symbol faces a daunting array of challenges. The exchange
must protect its franchise and find a way to blend the best aspects
of its floor-based auction system with the speed and the capacity
that only computers can provide. It must become more cost-efficient
without becoming less careful about policing its business _ a
challenge of such public importance that Arthur Levitt, chairman of
the Securities and Exchange Commission, warned Grasso earlier this
week that regulatory competence will be the make-or-break issue
when the commission reviews his plans.
</P>
<P>
   And, as a public company, the Big Board must figure out how to
make money doing all this _ enough money to placate potentially
impatient shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt has a personal stake in how well the exchange fends
off its new competitors. ``I need an environment where I can make a
difference to my customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Big Board has lost only about 5 percent of its
trading volume to the electronic communications networks, or ECNs,
that have gobbled up nearly 30 percent of the Nasdaq market's
volume.
</P>
<P>
   But keeping a grip on its primary business is likely to be more
of a challenge for the Big Board in the future than it has been in
the past. In recent weeks, the New York exchange has liberalized
its Rule 500, which prevented companies from withdrawing from the
exchange without their shareholders' approval. Now, companies can
withdraw merely by obtaining the approval of their independent
directors.
</P>
<P>
   The theory behind this change was that more companies would be
willing to list on the Big Board in the first place if it was
easier for them to leave. But the practical effects may simply be
that it is easier to move elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Another bellwether is the fate of Rule 390, which requires
members of the exchange to trade all Big Board stocks that were
listed before April 1979 only on a registered stock exchange, most
likely to be the Big Board itself during the hours the exchange is
open.
</P>
<P>
   The rule now affects only about a third of the Big Board stocks,
its supporters point out. But if this rule falls _ and the Nasdaq
market has been muttering for years about challenging it _ the New
York exchange could soon find that more of its trading volume has
moved to other markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Board's fabled liquidity _ a volume of trading so deep
that large blocks of stock can be traded quickly without a dramatic
impact on prices _ is a key element of its premier ``brand.'' A
migration of trading volume to competing trading systems would not
only reduce its revenues, it would also undermine the value of that
brand.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a critical issue _ the real dollars-and-cents issue
for the Big Board,'' said John C. Coffee Jr., a securities law
professor at Columbia University and a member of the legal advisory
committees for both the Nasdaq market and the Big Board. ``It's a
key part of their franchise, and I cannot see them liberalizing it,
especially as they move to become public.''
</P>
<P>
   But Benn Steil, a senior fellow for foreign economic policy on
the Council on Foreign Relations in New York, argues that the
elimination of Rule 390 would simply increase the healthy pressure
on the exchange to create a trading structure that people want,
rather than one they are required to use.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the Big Board may have no choice but to live
without the protections of Rule 390. ``I can't imagine that it can
remain in place,'' he said. ``It is such an anomaly, with so many
competitive pressures arguing against it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is considerable speculation that the New York exchange
will be able to increase revenues by making strategic acquisitions
_ perhaps buying one of the upstart ECNs, or purchasing one of the
for-profit stock exchanges that are proliferating abroad, or buying
a company that develops innovative software for trading services.
</P>
<P>
   But for the near-term, the Big Board will most likely make its
money the old-fashioned way: by charging fees for companies to list
on the exchange and for investors to trade there. And in today's
competitive environment, both listing fees and trading fees ``are
going to be under competitive pressures,'' Steil said.
</P>
<P>
   To cope, he said, ``they need to bring their costs down.''
</P>
<P>
   Steil believes that cost pressures in competition will force the
exchange to abandon the expensive trading floor _ a trading
environment that Rosenblatt insists is the symbol of the exchange
and ``the envy of the world'' _ and replace it with an electronic
trading system.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt disagrees. ``You don't want to automate the
auction,'' he insisted, arguing that the relationships and
reputations of individual floor traders allow them to get better
prices for their customers. ``But you sure want to automate
everything around it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Either option requires money, of course. And the need to pay for
swift and dramatic improvements in technology will increase the
pressure on the Big Board to curtail its other costs.
</P>
<P>
   And that raises questions about whether the exchange will be
able to produce profits for its new shareholders and still
adequately pay for its self-policing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   It is an issue that already faces the for-profit ECNs that elect
to compete with the Big Board and the Nasdaq market by becoming
full-fledged stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you allow the ECNs to become exchanges, regulating
themselves, you are inevitably going to have scandals,'' Coffee
said. Under pressure to produce profits, the for-profit exchanges
may well ``start to shop for the cheapest and the least, shall we
say, `intrusive' regulator,'' he continued. ``If that trend
accelerates, you've got a race to the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt, the SEC chairman, wants to prevent that race from
starting.
</P>
<P>
   He offered one suggestion in his first response on Monday to the
idea of allowing for-profit stock trading entities: ``More formally
separating the self-regulatory role from the role of exchanges as
trading venues.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what the National Association of Securities
Dealers is planning if it proceeds with a proposal to spin off the
Nasdaq market as a for-profit corporation early next year.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not the scheme that Grasso outlined for the exchange
last week. Instead, he envisions retaining the exchange's
regulatory operation within the new for-profit company.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee worries that in-house regulators would be vulnerable to
cost-cutting pressures. His concern is shared by James J. Needham,
a former SEC commissioner who was the first paid chairman of the
New York Stock Exchange, from August 1972 to May 1976.
</P>
<P>
   With for-profit exchanges, ``there is the potential for serious
conflicts of interest,'' Needham said. ``We cannot rely on
self-regulation anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Don, a securities lawyer in Chicago with wide experience
in advising newly public companies, was less concerned about an
erosion of regulatory efforts. ``You just have to have sanctions
sufficiently strong that noncompliance becomes uncompetitive
behavior,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt, the veteran floor trader, has heard the various
arguments, and said that he did not think members of the exchange
care where the regulators hung their hats. ``We just care that
regulation is not so cumbersome that you can't function, and that
regulators understand the difference between jaywalking and
premeditated murder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Needham, the former New York exchange chairman, said that the
changes in ownership structure now being contemplated by the Big
Board and the Nasdaq market are so dramatic that the SEC ought to
hold public hearings before approving either proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing would be for the public to lose confidence
because they don't understand what's happening,'' Needham said.
``Before we take the next step, let's find out what we're really
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt, staring down at the unstylish side-laced shoes that
cushion his feet during long days on the trading floor, wondered
aloud whether anyone could truly assess where the changes of today
will leave the markets of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``For anyone to think that, five years from now, any of us will
be doing business the way we do today would be dangerously naive,''
he said. ``You show me a better way to trade, and I won't trade one
more share on the NYSE. But nobody's shown me that yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
