<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-POISONING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREATEST FOOD POISONING DANGER ZONE: THE HOME KITCHEN
</HEADLINE>
 
EDS: Has sider, EGG-SAFETY (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food poisoning made headlines this summer when 58 North Texas
young people returned from a drill team camp with stomach-churning,
serious E. coli infections.
</P>
<P>
   The incident rekindled consumer fear that arose five years ago
,when tainted hamburgers traced to a fast-food restaurant chain
killed four children in the Seattle area. Some mothers still forbid
their children to eat hamburgers because of that tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, another E. coli scare caused the recall of 25
million pounds of hamburger patties, and in November, 1.5 million
pounds of hot dogs and cold cuts were pulled from the market.
</P>
<P>
   Although large outbreaks of food-borne illness generally grab
national attention, the more menacing food-poisoning threat lies
closer to home, experts say _ in your kitchen. Most food-borne
disease originates in the home and is caused not by food but by
what we do with food, says Joan Horbiak, a food safety expert with
the American Dietetic Association.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is getting worse, says Horbiak, even though a few
preventive measures would go a long way toward curbing the rise of
in-home cases of food-borne illness. Those incidents _ caused by
insufficient cooking; inadequate refrigeration; cross-contamination
from germs on raw foods, hands, cutting boards, platters and
cooking utensils; and food sitting out at room temperature for too
long _ rose by 25 percent over the past five years, Horbiak says.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimate
that 9,000 people die of food poisoning each year; up to 33 million
contract food-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say 6.5 to 33 million cases each year, because so many
people have it without knowing what it is,'' Horbiak says. ``We are
slow to equate the `summer bug' with mishandling of food, but often
flulike symptoms including fever, chills and nausea, especially
during warm weather, are actually symptoms of food poisoning. When
you have an outbreak at a restaurant, it's headline news. When
people get sick at home, nobody stops to figure out why.''
</P>
<P>
   To combat the rise in home-related food-poisoning incidents, the
dietetic association recently launched a three-year campaign to
teach consumers how to prevent food poisoning in their homes and at
family picnics, especially during the hot summer months when
reported incidents increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bacteria grows like crazy at higher temperatures. If it's 80
degrees outside, you've got to get your picnic fare back into a
cooler within one hour,'' says Horbiak, national spokeswoman for
the new campaign, ``Home Food Safety ... It's in Your Hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside an air-conditioned house, you have a two-hour window,''
Horbiak says. ``Every 30 minutes, bacteria doubles. Refrigerating
promptly is one of the biggest things you can do to protect
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers tend to think food safety is complicated, that it's
out of their hands, but it's not. We are emphasizing four simple
steps. There are a million tips out there, but these four can have
a great impact, and they are quick and easy,'' Horbiak says.
</P>
<P>
   The tips:
</P>
<P>
   Wash hands often.
</P>
<P>
   Keep raw meats and ready-to-eat food separate.
</P>
<P>
   Cook to proper temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate leftovers promptly below 40 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds simplistic, but 50 percent of food-borne illness
could be prevented if we washed our hands more,'' Horbiak says.
``People rinse, they don't wash. They don't use soap and they don't
take enough time. You should wash for 20 seconds. Time counts.''
</P>
<P>
   FYI BOX
</P>
<P>
   The American Dietetic Association's new home food-safety
campaign aims to help people realize that food-borne illness is a
serious problem, with simple solutions that take only seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is funded by a grant from ConAgra, one of the
largest food companies in the world, representing brands including
Healthy Choice, Butterball, Act II, Orville Redenbacher's, Peter
Pan, Swiss Miss, Hunts, Wesson, Armour and Swift Premium.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call ADA's consumer nutrition hot line at
(800) 366-1655. To receive the free brochure, ``Take Control of
Home Food Safety,'' send a self-addressed, business-size envelope
with two stamps to The American Dietetic Association, NCND-Home
Safety Brochure, 216 W. Jackson Blvd., Chicago, IL 60606.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
