<HEADER>
A7548 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EGG-SAFETY-TEX     07-28 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGG-SAFETY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASTEURIZATION TOUTED AS ANTIDOTE TO SALMONELLA DANGER
</HEADLINE>
 EDS: This is a sider to FOOD-POISONING 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunny side up, over-easy or scrambled, hard-boiled or soft and
runny, even raw in milkshakes, eggnog and Caesar salad dressing, we
eat more than 70 billion eggs in this country each year.
</P>
<P>
   If even one in 20,000 has a little salmonella bacteria on the
shell or inside the egg (from a virulent strain that infests the
chicken's ovaries and is passed on in the egg before it is ever
laid), a lot of people can get sick.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the home front and food safety, though, news on
the egg is encouraging, thanks to measures by the federal
government to improve food safety practices and private efforts to
pasteurize the egg.
</P>
<P>
   First, new labels warning that eggs ``may contain harmful
bacteria known to cause serious illness, especially in children,
the elderly and persons with weakened immune systems'' are proposed
for all egg cartons, effective Aug. 27. The warnings, proposed by
the Food and Drug Administration, state:
</P>
<P>
   ``For your protection, keep eggs refrigerated; cook eggs until
yolks are firm; and cook foods containing eggs thoroughly.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA and U.S. Department of Agriculture's Food Safety and
Inspection Services also announced this month a new federal
requirement that all eggs and egg products packed for consumers be
refrigerated at 45 degrees or below. Distribution warehouses and
transport vehicles as well as supermarkets, restaurants, delis,
caterers, vending operations, hospitals, nursing homes and schools
fall under the regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Cooling and cooking eggs properly ``may prevent up to 66,000
illnesses and 40 deaths per year,'' according to the directive
issued by Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala.
</P>
<P>
   The warning labels and refrigeration requirements are among
measures promised by President Clinton to improve food safety in
this country. The President's Council on Food Safety is developing
a strategic plan, due Nov. 1, to improve the safety of eggs in the
shell and processed egg products.
</P>
<P>
   But a more promising development in egg safety may be a new
pasteurization process that has been developed that eliminates the
threat of salmonella from whole eggs in their shells without
changing their texture, appearance or taste.
</P>
<P>
   John Davidson, president of Pasteurized Eggs L.P., the company
that developed the new process, says whole pasteurized eggs will be
available along the East Coast from Boston to Washington, D.C., in
October and nationwide early in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look, cook and taste exactly like nonpasteurized, but
they are completely safe,'' Davidson said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Pasteurization makes eggs as bacteria-free as fresh pasteurized
milk.
</P>
<P>
   Ultrapasteurized and homogenized liquid eggs have been available
for years in containers that look like milk cartons, and are widely
used in restaurants for omelets, custards, quiche, dressings and
sauces. These liquid eggs, sold under the brand name Easy Eggs,
work well scrambled, but cannot be prepared ``sunny side up'' or
even ``over easy'' because yolk and white are mixed in the
processing.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson's eggs look like any other whole eggs and are sold in
the shell, by the carton. The whites can be separated easily for
meringue, and some of the yolks separated and omitted to lower
cholesterol in a particular recipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hard-boil it, beat it, scramble it, fry it, nothing
changes,'' Davidson says. ``If you look very closely, the yolk of a
pasteurized egg is slightly larger than its counterpart, the
formation of the white doesn't run all over the pan when you fry
it, and before cooking, the white is slightly more opaque, but you
really have to look for the differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar efforts involving microwaves and radiation have been
attempted in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The secret, Davidson says, is in heating the eggs enough to kill
bacteria without soft-boiling them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You apply heat to kill the targeted bacteria, in this case
salmonella,'' he explains. ``Government standards say to heat every
particle to the equivalency of 140 degrees for 3.5 minutes to
achieve destruction of any salmonella that may be present, but it
comes out soft-boiled if you do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, we determined the equivalency at a lesser temperature for
a longer time. My process varies the amount of heat and the time
required in three separate steps.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he can pasteurize 1,000 cold eggs a minute, within
one-10th of 1 degree.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson says the processing is expected to add about 35 cents a
dozen to the price of eggs.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
