<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 DELTA DINING: A Round-Up of Waterfront Restaurants That Offer  Good
Eats and Generous Drinks   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISO _  If you can dream it, you can do it. So says the
mantra about outdoor activities in California, where you can ski in
the morning and be at the beach before the sun sets.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the hottest spots for summertime fun is the
Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta, 1,000 miles of tributaries
cutting through the Central Valley from Sacramento down to Antioch
and Pittsburg. On weekends, boats of all sizes full of water
skiers, scurfers (a combination of surfing and waterskiing),
fishers and sun worshipers pack the waters from dawn to dusk.
</P>
<P>
   With that big of a social scene, it's no wonder that restaurants
have popped up at just about every marina. In fact, many
restaurants actually have docks specifically for those just coming
in for a bite to eat.
</P>
<P>
   So what are the best restaurants in the Delta? Well, hot day
dining isn't the same as four-star food, but we found 10 places
right on the water with menus ranging from well-prepared standards
like burgers and fries to more upscale options with a little style.
</P>
<P>
   While these places are all accessible by boat, they're also easy
enough to get to by car (most even have parking lots) so even those
who don't have boats can take part in the fun.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sl,12p2  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; ANTIOCH
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Humphrey's &LR; . This popular dining spot in Antioch has been open a
long time, but new owners took over four years ago. The decor
remains the same: huge windows overlooking the marina, lots of
mirrors, plastic swordfish and flowers for color. But the feeling
is comfortable and somewhat formal for the area, with servers in
tuxedo shirts and cummerbunds as well as food at higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Appetizers are likely to disappoint, but since the entrees come
with soup or salad, potato or rice, and vegetables, they're
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The menu features mostly Italian-style food like thinly pounded
chicken piccata in a tangy lemon butter sauce and scampi with lots
of garlic. The spinach pasta primavera would have been better with
about a quarter of its smothering pesto-cream sauce, but the
addition of cauliflower, zucchini and carrots gave the dish a fresh
taste.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Humphrey's, 1 Marina Plaza (at L Street), Antioch; (925) &LR; 
 &LR; 778-5800. Open lunch through dinner daily. Full bar. &LR; 
 &LR; Reservations and credit cards accepted. Parking lot. Entrees: &LR; 
 &LR; $9.95-$22.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sl,12p2  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; BETHEL ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Sugar Barge &LR; . Sugar Barge is an expansive restaurant with
outdoor seating and a casual menu on the rooftop, an
air-conditioned bar area and comfortable dining room. It's
decorated in Miami Vice tones of greens, pinks and blues, but it
complements the area.
</P>
<P>
   Many people consider the food in the dining room to be some of
the best on the Delta, but sometimes the kitchen cuts corners. The
rice pilaf served with entrees, for example, tasted suspiciously
like it came from a mix, and the cheese topping the Caesar salad
was waxy and cheap.
</P>
<P>
   But if you stick to the more casual menu of fried calamari and
burgers served on the rooftop patio, you won't be disappointed. And
be sure to order one of the frozen cocktails which come in colored
sugar-rimmed hurricane glasses with colorful straws.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of DELTA 7- (96706 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Sugar Barge, 4515 Willow Road (near Sugar Barge Road), &LR;   &LR; Bethel
Island; (925) 684-8585. Open lunch through dinner &LR; 
 &LR; Wednesday-Sunday. Full bar. Reservations and credit cards &LR; 
 &LR; accepted. Parking lot. Prices:  &UR; $13.95-$22.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sl,12p2  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; STOCKTON
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Garlic Brothers &LR; . Garlic Brothers offers some of the best casual
food on the Delta. Diners have the option of dining under colorful
canvas umbrellas on the wood deck or in the industrial-looking
dining room with a concrete floor and colorful paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Fried calamari was some of the best we tasted, with a crispy but
not heavy coating and decent cocktail and tartar dipping sauces.
The quesadilla is big enough for two for lunch with cheddar,
Monterey jack cheese and grilled chicken between two tortillas
topped with wonderful roasted tomato salsa, guacamole and sour
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbo, something of a specialty here, sports a good balance of
heat to sweet flavors, and is packed with big chunks of chicken,
sausage and rock shrimp. Burgers, too, are a step above what you'll
find at other places. Here, they're served on focaccia bread that
holds up to the burger's juices. And the fries are terrific, too.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant also has a number of specialty cocktails,
including the Absolut Razz Monster, a pint-size glass filled with
vodka, raspberry liqueur, citrus juices and 7-Up _ cool and
refreshing on the hottest of days.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Garlic Brothers, 6629 Embarcadero Drive (near Benjamin &LR;   &LR; Holt),
Stockton; (209) 474-6585. Open for lunch and dinner &LR; 
 &LR; Tuesday-Sunday. Full bar. Reservations and credit cards &LR; 
 &LR; accepted. Street parking. Entrees: $6-$14.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Peta's Yacht Harbor Restaurant &LR; . It's hard to imagine wanting
hefty German food after a day of sweltering on the Delta, but the
food at Peta's is so good it can't be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Thick split pea soup, for example, might be better suited to a
cold winter night, but there's no denying its exceptional flavor.
Sweetly-spiced sauerbraten and crispy wiener schnitzel are great,
too. Entrees are served with soup or salad, plus side dishes of
sauerkraut, vinegary warm German potato salad and slices of dark
pumpernickel bread. Nothing on the menu is over $15 and is even
less at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The interior of this 19-year-old restaurant is dingy, filled
with dusty beer paraphernalia, but the outdoor patio is more
pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Peta's Yacht Harbor Restaurant, 445 W. Weber Ave. (near &LR; 
 &LR; Center Street), Stockton; (209) 941-8605. Lunch and dinner &LR; 
 &LR; daily. Full bar. Reservations and credit cards accepted. Street &LR; 
 &LR; parking. Entrees: $10.95-$14.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sl,12p2  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; WALNUT GROVE
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Wimpy's &LR; . Wimpy's is the king of nothing-fancy restaurants;
everything is nicely prepared and served in sparkling clean
surroundings. The front area looks like a diner with a long counter
with seating and vinyl booths. The main dining room is
wood-panelled and well-decorated with American flags, in case you
thought you were in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   Try the crawdads when they're on the menu. They arrive piping
hot with a little plastic cup of cocktail sauce, lots of lemon
wedges and instructions on how to twist, crack and peel the
critters.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of DELTA 7- (96706 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  We suspect that some of the rest of the food begins with
ingredients from the freezer, but the final product can still be
good _ crispy fish and chips, and hamburgers in several forms
including a patty melt and a chili burger. Dinners include a lot of
beef _ chopped sirloin, chopped sirloin Mexicana, chopped sirloin
western, for example _ with a few chicken and fish options.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Wimpy's, 14001 W. Walnut Grove Road no cross street to this &LR; 
one, unless you count the freeway which is 14 miles away) &LR; , &LR; 
 &LR; Walnut Grove; (209) 797-2544. Open for breakfast, lunch and &LR; 
 &LR; dinner daily. Full bar. No reservations. Credit cards accepted. &LR; 
 &LR; Parking lot. Entrees: $7.95-$13.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sl,12p2  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; SACRAMENTO
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Rio City &LR; . This restaurant on the river in Sacramento's Old Town
gets an A+ for creativity, even though the kitchen sometimes falls
short on execution.
</P>
<P>
   Appetizers include dishes we're used to seeing in the city (ok,
the  &LR; other &LR;  city), such as raw tuna, but here it's served as
``nachos'' tossed with wonton chips and a sesame-ginger dressing.
Grilled polenta studded with mushrooms has exceptional flavor, but
the dish is marred by too much of a balsamic vinegar reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Other dishes have flaws as well _ Caesar salad had lettuce with
brown spots, a wild rice pilaf was dreadfully undercooked _ but the
open, warehouse-size space is pretty and the wine list outshines
most others we saw.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Rio City Cafe, 1110 Front St. (near Neesham), Sacramento; &LR; 
 &LR; (916) 442-8226. Open lunch through dinner daily and brunch on &LR; 
 &LR; Sunday. Full bar. Reservations and credit cards accepted. &LR;   &LR; Street
and garage parking nearby. Entrees: $11.95- &LR;   &LR; $19.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rh1 &LR;   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Riverboat Delta King &LR; . Riverboat Delta King resides on an old
river paddleboat that also serves as a hotel. The decor is
well-kept, with upholstered chairs and booths and tons of gleaming
wood.
</P>
<P>
   The food is somewhat old-fashioned, but for the most part nicely
prepared. Caesar salad could be punched up with a bit more garlic
and anchovy, for example, but at dinner time, it's made tableside
which is a pleasant reminder of days gone by.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch includes dishes like decent portobello mushroom sandwiches
and crispy fries. Cioppino can be ordered at lunch or dinner and is
surprisingly good. The mild tomato broth tastes of sweet fennel and
the briny flavors of the seafood including salmon, calamari,
shrimp, mussels and clams.
</P>
<P>
   Skip dessert; you'll be happier stopping in one of the ice cream
or candy stores in Old Town.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Riverboat Delta King, 1000 Front St. (near K Street), &LR; 
 &LR; Sacramento; (916) 441-4440. Lunch and dinner Monday-Saturday; &LR; 
 &LR; Sunday brunch. Full bar. Reservations and credit cards &LR;   &LR; accepted.
Street and garage parking nearby. Entrees: $13.95- &LR;   &LR; $27.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Crawdad's Cantina &LR; . Crawdad's shares marina space with Chevy's
and Wood'ys  &LR; (sic) &LR;  Riverfront Grill, and the place is packed,
especially on weekends with diners and partyers. The space is
decorated in bright island colors, a little reminiscent of Islands,
a burger chain in Southern California. But most people head to the
enclosed patio which is simple and functional.
</P>
<P>
   The food here is better than much of what you'll find along the
Delta, except for the calamari which was tough and flavorless.
Appetizers include creative and well-made dishes like
coconut-coated shrimp in a spicy-sweet glaze. Sandwiches, like the
grilled portobello mushroom and the grilled chicken with
caramelized onions, come on big slices of focaccia bread instead of
boring buns.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of DELTA 7- (96706 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  But don't miss the gumbo or the jambalaya, which are great and
fit the warm weather. You'll break a sweat with both, though the
jambalaya is the more mild of the two. Both are packed with
chicken, crawfish and shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Crawdad's also does a decent job with desserts, especially the
banana-coconut layer cake which sandwiches banana cream between
yellow cake and covers the whole thing in coconut.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Crawdad's Cantina, 1375 Garden Highway (near Interstate 5), &LR; 
 &LR; Sacramento; (916) 929-2268. Open lunch through dinner daily. &LR; 
 &LR; Full bar. Reservations for parties of 10 or more. Parking lot &LR; 
 &LR; and street parking. Entrees: $11.95-$14.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Wood'ys  &LR; (sic) &UR; Riverfront Grill &LR; . Wood'ys is located at the same
marina as Crawdad's, but up the embankment of the river, surrounded
by trees. The outdoor patio is naturally shaded from the blazing
sun but doesn't afford the same view of the Sacramento River.
</P>
<P>
   Food here isn't as good as Crawdad's, either. But the restaurant
does offer some mean cocktails including a Pain Killer _ dark rum
with lots of fruit juices in a super-sized glass usually reserved
for water.
</P>
<P>
   If Crawdad's is packed and you can't get into Chevy's, the menu
at Wood'ys has a lot of options. And after a Pain Killer, you might
not care that the fish tacos are dry and the barbecued ribs have no
flavor save the sauce itself. Plus, the prices are right. You can
put together a big meal for two for about $30.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Wood'ys, 1379 Garden Highway (off of Interstate 5), &LR; 
 &LR; Sacramento; (916) 924-3434. Open lunch through dinner daily. &LR; 
 &LR; Full bar. Reservations for parties of 8 or more. Credit cards &LR; 
 &LR; accepted. Entrees: $7.89-$14.99. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Jammin' Salmon &LR; . Jammin' Salmon may be the best kept secret in
Delta dining. The restaurant is located far enough down the
Sacramento River to be out of earshot of the bustling marina where
Crawdad's and Wood'ys are located. And that gives the place a
peaceful, almost romantic feel.
</P>
<P>
   The inside dining room is simply decorated in shades of yellow
and red, but as with most restaurants along the river, many diners
opt for the standard patio.
</P>
<P>
   The menu features an eclectic mix of food we've come to regard
as California-style, with influence from France, Italy and Asia.
Start with the jumbo steamed artichoke which arrives bathed in a
buttery broth studded with sweet fresh rock shrimp and tomatoes.
Grilled asparagus were good, too, but marred by clunky pieces of
thick-cut prosciutto.
</P>
<P>
   For entrees, try the blackened ahi with a drizzle of wasabi
cream atop nutty brown rice or the grilled skirt steak with Asian
spices. Mushroom risotto is good, although soupier than more
traditional executions.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Jammin' Salmon, 1801 Garden Highway (near Interstate 5), &LR; 
 &LR; Sacramento; (916) 929-6232. Open for lunch weekdays, dinner &LR; 
 &LR; daily, brunch weekends. Reservations and credit cards accepted. &LR; 
 &LR; Parking garage. Entrees: $9.95-$14.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of DELTA 7- (96706 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
