<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7550 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN0801-COX     07-28 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE COOL STORY BEHIND THE HEAT WAVE
 &HT;    For release Sunday, August 1.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON When the top story nowadays, often as not, turns out
to be the mid-summer heat wave that has scorched much of the
nation, you know that we're also enduring a slow news cycle.
Reports of persistent temperature records are coupled with the
opinions of presumed experts on the meaning of changing weather
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Dehydration that stems from extreme heat can prove fatal. But
doctors have long recognized that sweltering temperatures should be
properly seen as one of several contributing causes to death
whenever other serious medical problems are also present.
</P>
<P>
   The real story of the Big Boil of 1999 is not how many people
have been subjected to the heat but rather how many millions have
all but escaped its full impact in temperature-controlled houses,
offices, cars and malls.
</P>
<P>
   Today, three in four American homes are air conditioned.
Houston, the nation's fourth largest city, plans to spend over $750
million this year just to keep cool. It's a good investment: In
1900, only some 45,000 people lived there, sweltering each summer
by the Texas Gulf coast.
</P>
<P>
   Like television, air conditioning has been around for much of
the 20th century. A year after earning a master's degree in
electrical engineering from Cornell in 1901, Willis Carrier
patented a unit that soon came to comfort the very comfortable,
much as private jets do today.
</P>
<P>
   But the broad middle class had to wait several more decades for
its turn. And, by and large, poor people, among whom a good deal of
heat-related suffering occurs, are still unable to obtain relief.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Hollywood made a movie, ``The Seven Year Itch,'' based
on the premise of a ``bachelor'' who sends his wife and kids to the
beach for the entire summer to escape their sultry apartment,
thereby setting up his sultry escapade with Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager living in a hot and humid New York City in the
1940s, I'd escort my future wife to a ``healthfully chilled'' movie
house on summer weekend afternoons. There we'd cool off, sitting
through two feature films, cartoons, newsreels and coming
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   As grown-ups in 1970, we bought a house from a partner in a
regional movie chain. When building the house in 1949, he mounted a
nine-ton water-circulation tower by the driveway, utilizing the
same crew and much the same gear that served his movie emporiums.
</P>
<P>
   At first all went well _ once we had found a technician who
could decipher the various dials, valves and switches needed to run
the massive commercial-grade apparatus. But then came the oil shock
of the mid-1970s and the sticker shock of soaring electricity
bills.
</P>
<P>
   The last straw came when the power company's chieftain wrote to
inform us that we'd been chosen for a ``special study'' by dint of
being among the utility's top 100 residential customers.
</P>
<P>
   Our over-engineered ``movie'' air conditioning system _ more
powerful than even the pioneering one Carrier installed in 1922 at
Graumann's Metropolitan Theater in Los Angeles _ had to go.
</P>
<P>
   In its place came a heat pump, a bunch of fans and utility bills
appropriate to a journalist's salary. They aren't newsworthy, but
they'll help us get by until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
