<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-CAMPAIGN-ADS-NYT &LR;      07-28 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CAMPAIGN-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER LAUNCHES IOWA AD CAMPAIGN SNIPING AT BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Texas, Tenn.)  (bl) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican presidential hopeful Lamar Alexander
began a last-ditch television advertisement campaign in Iowa on
Wednesday that attacks George W. Bush's fund-raising success
without mentioning the Texas governor's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``An auction is underway on the White House lawn,'' an announcer
says as the ad begins, just before the camera captures a group of
men, wearing Texas-style string ties, shouting out their bids.
``The nomination is going to the bidder with the most cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, a former Tennessee governor, is staking the future of
his struggling presidential bid on a strong showing in the Iowa
straw poll to be held in Ames, Iowa, on Aug. 14. The poll is not
binding, but it is an important early indicator of popular support
in the state where the nation's first presidential caucus will be
held in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing the ad right now because voters are paying
attention,'' said Brian Kennedy, the political director of
Alexander's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, whose campaign has been beset by money woes all year,
is buying the commercials with $90,000 that he has in the bank and
the proceeds of fund-raising events held in recent weeks. Alexander
managed to raise $2.5 million in the first six months of 1999, and
has had trouble paying some bills. In May he was forced to make
deep cuts in his staff in Washington and in Tennessee. At the end
of June, Alexander reported that he had debts totaling $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Bush's Republican rivals have criticized the fact that
his campaign raised $37.3 million in just four months, a
record-setting sum that is more than the combined total amount
raised by the rest of the Republican field. But Alexander is the
first candidate to buy advertisements that suggest Bush is
attempting to buy the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   After the scene on the White House lawn, Alexander appears on
the commercial to deliver the anti-Bush message that he has
repeated often in recent weeks on the campaign trail. ``The
presidency ought to be about raising children, farm prices and
standards, not just raising money,'' he says. ``I've been all over
Iowa because the presidency is too important to be bought or
inherited. It ought to be earned.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, a spokesperson for Bush, declined Wednesday to say
whether the Bush campaign would broadcast advertisements in the
weeks leading up to the straw poll. But she suggested that voters
in Iowa will not be amused by Alexander's advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that the grassroots supporters of Governor Bush
in Iowa will appreciate this kind of politics,'' Ms. Tucker said.
``We would hope that Lamar Alexander, and all the other candidates,
would join Governor Bush in running a positive, issue-oriented
campaign, rather than criticizing their opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander campaign officials refused to tell the cost of the
advertisements, which were shown for the first time Wednesday on
television stations in Des Moines, Cedar Rapids, Sioux City and the
Quad Cities area.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention in the advertisement of Bush or his
fund-raising prowess. But the point is clear enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Alexander's strategy is to focus on Iowa and talk
about the issues,'' Kennedy said. ``Governor Bush's strategy is to
break fund-raising records and not talk about the issues. He hasn't
even come to Iowa much.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, and strategists for several other Republican
candidates, said today that they hope to play upon a growing
resentment among Iowans that Bush and Steve Forbes, a wealthy
publisher, are spending big money to win the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is spending $10 million on radio and television
advertisements in Iowa and New Hampshire. The advertisements are
intended to introduce Forbes to the public. One ad shows Forbes
with his family. ``The real success in life is not the things we
often see in the news or read about in the history books, but the
seemingly mundane tasks of day-to-day _ getting kids up, getting
the homework done,'' Forbes says.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa radio spots, Forbes said that he hopes the August straw
poll ``can serve as a catalyst to get the candidates talking about
the issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
