<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7552 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-ARGYLE-HNS &LR;      07-28 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-ARGYLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST-ARGYLE REPORTS RESULTS FOR QUARTER AND FIRST HALF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hearst-Argyle Television, Inc., announced Wednesday
that revenues for the second quarter grew 69 percent to $186.1
million over last year's second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast cash flow grew 56 percent to $89.7 million, the
company said. After-tax cash flow rose 44 percent to $43.4 million,
or $0.49 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Income applicable to common stockholders before extraordinary
item declined 37.3 percent to $13.1 million, or $0.15 per share,
the company, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, revenues rose 52 percent to $299.5 million
and broadcast cash flow climbed 48 percent to $134.7 million.
After-tax cash flow grew 40 percent to $62.5 million or $0.85 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Income applicable to common stockholders before extraordinary
item declined 41 percent to $15.6 million or $0.21 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The results include the operations of the Kelly Broadcasting
Sacramento properties since Jan. 5 and the operations of the
Pulitzer broadcast group since March 18, the respective dates on
which Hearst-Argyle's acquisitions of those properties were
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced pro forma results as if it owned the
Pulitzer and Kelly/Sacramento properties at the beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On a pro forma basis, the company's revenues for the quarter
declined 7 percent to $186.1 million. Broadcast cash flow for the
quarter declined 13 to $89.7 million. After-tax cash flow declined
16 percent to $43.5 million, or $0.47 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Income applicable to common stockholders declined 35 percent to
$13.3 million, or $0.14 per share.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, revenues declined 3 percent to $347.6
million. Broadcast cash flow declined 7 percent to $153.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   After-tax cash flow declined 9 to $74 million, or $0.80 per
share. Income applicable to common stockholders decreased 31
percent to $13.2 million, or $0.14 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors contributed the company's revenue performance in
the quarter, according to David J. Barrett, president and co-chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall demand was below expectations, depressing pricing and
rate yield, and we were not as successful as we expected to be in
replacing the $13 million of political advertising we received in
the second quarter of 1998,'' Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Category spending for movies, General Motors and
telecommunications providers was also well below last year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our NBC stations were impacted by the unfavorable comparison
to the Seinfeld finale in May 1998, while ABC's sluggish ratings
performance impacted inventory pricing in the second quarter,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
