<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SANDERS-BOS &LR;      07-28 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDERS TRAVELS TO LONDON _ AND OUT OF THE NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barry Sanders landed in London Wednesday. Paris and Amsterdam
are also part of his itinerary. Chances are he's not auditioning
for a job in NFL Europe, though he's now eligible.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Lions' nonpareil, on the verge of becoming the most
prolific rusher in National Football League history, announced his
retirement Wednesday via a statement released through the web site
of his hometown newspaper, the Wichita (Kan.) Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``My desire to exit the game is greater than my desire to stay
in it,'' said Sanders, the former Heisman Trophy winner from
Oklahoma State who has gained at least 1,000 yards in each of his
10 seasons with the Lions and needs 1,458 to break Walter Payton's
career record of 16,726. ``I have searched my heart through and
through and through and feel comfortable with this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but he seemed to treat it a bit awkwardly. ``I don't
know the right way to retire,'' the 31-year-old Sanders said upon
arriving at London's Gatwick Airport. ``This is just my way of
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, it's irrevocable _ for now, anyway. ``I'm going
into retirement,'' Sanders told English reporters before retreating
into seclusion, ``and I don't see my plans changing.''
</P>
<P>
   If they do, his address won't. Patriots fans _ including those
who already have called the club inquiring about how Sanders might
be lured to Foxboro Stadium _ can stop salivating. Though the
Patriots could dearly use a running back of his pedigree _ then
again, who couldn't? _ Sanders has no realistic alternatives to the
Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit placed him on the reserve: did not report list, not the
reserve: retired list. That means he can be activated any time
before Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Barry comes back,'' said general manager Chuck Schmidt at a
news conference, ``we would like him to come back to the Detroit
Lions.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, assuming anything else would be sheer fantasy.
Declaring his retirement does not make Sanders a free agent; the
Lions retain his playing rights. And because of the six-year, $36
million contract he signed two years ago, the cost of moving
Sanders would be prohibitive. If the Lions traded or released him,
he still would count as $5 million against their salary cap, which
would mean they'd have to deal as many as a half-dozen veterans
just to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Sanders seems dead set against a return,
anyway. His statement began, ``Shortly after the end of last
season, I felt that I probably would not return for the 1999-2000
season.'' Toward that end, he had been incommunicado during the
offseason, skipping both mandatory and voluntary minicamps. When he
made up his mind Monday, his agents, David Ware and Lamont Smith _
with whom Schmidt had been in contact during their client's
self-imposed exile _ were unable to dissuade Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years is a lot of football,'' he told the London media.
``I'm just really not feeling like playing. It's just getting to
that point. It's not the same game. Really, I've been battling for
the last few years. As I've gotten older, the game has changed in
my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that hasn't changed is the Lions' lack of success _
they won one playoff game during Sanders's tenure, went 5-11 two of
the past three seasons, and do not loom as a viable contender in
the foreseeable future. That, along with disenchantment with coach
Bobby Ross, reportedly were factors in his decision, though he said
in his farewell statement, ``I truly will miss playing for the
Lions. . . . I have enjoyed playing for two great head coaches,
Wayne Fontes and Bobby Ross, who are good coaches and leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   However, as Sanders remained mum while the rumors swirled during
the offseason, his father, William, said, ``He's sick of (the
Lions). He's sick of losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders told no one in the Detroit front office of his decision,
and at Wednesday's press conference, Ross refused to speculate
about the reasons for it. Its impact was another matter. ``I felt
there was the potential for a big play every time I lined up with
him,'' said the coach, ``and no matter who replaces him, that won't
be part of the feeling you will have on the sideline. Obviously,
we're very, very disappointed because we lose a great football
player.''
</P>
<P>
   To be precise, they've lost their offensive fulcrum, which was
why wide receiver Johnnie Morton said, ``It's a huge hole missing
right now. I think we're in a shock state of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Added quarterback Charlie Batch, ``I wish he would have given a
hint. He's got a lot of good years left in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who stood to be displaced by Sanders in the record book,
agreed with Batch's assessment and said he'd like to see Sanders
return someday.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Sanders was insisting otherwise. The only issue that
seemed to concern the accidental tourist was: Which side of the
road do you drive on?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
