<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7554 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-LATINOS29-COX     07-28 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LATINOS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hispanic conference participants ask, ``Where's Bush?''
 &HT;    Moving in (w)Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore was the headliner at the
National Council of La Raza convention Wednesday, but conference
participants made it clear they had another presidential candidate
on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore addressed the nation's largest Hispanic civil rights
organization, many gathered at the Houston convention site wore
lapel stickers emblazoned with the day's looming question:
``Where's George?''
</P>
<P>
   Frustration among Hispanic leaders is growing over Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's failure to appear at the La Raza event and at
three other recent conferences held by Hispanic groups. Bush is on
vacation with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's call for a ``compassionate conservatism,'' his ability to
speak Spanish and his departure from the Republican party platform
on issues such as bilingual education have made him popular with
Hispanic voters in Texas. According to one widely-reported
estimate, he won 49 percent of that vote in his re-election bid
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But some Hispanic leaders warned this week that Bush, considered
the leading contender for the GOP presidential nomination, is
making a mistake if he thinks he's got their community's support
sewed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the governor's popularity with
Hispanic voters is real, but it is also fragile,'' said Lisa
Navarrete, spokesperson for La Raza. ``The question now is
substance. What is he going to talk about? What are his positions
on issues of concern to the community? We need to hear from him
about that and that's what we expected to hear from him at our
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Gore and Bush, La Raza also invited Democratic
candidate Bill Bradley and Republicans Elizabeth Dole and Sen. John
McCain (R-Arizona) to the conference. McCain attended.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Bush declined to speak at Unity, the
nation's largest-ever meeting of minority journalists. The meeting
was held in Seattle, Wash., where Bush was campaigning. He reversed
course, appearing at the last minute, but refused to participate in
a question-and- answer session, drawing vehement criticism from
journalists in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unity to Bush: You blew it,'' read the headline in the next
day's conference newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also declined recent invitations to address the League of
United Latin American Citizens and the National Association of
Latino Elected and Appointed Officials.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gonzalez, Washington, D.C. director for the Association of
Latino Elected and Appointed Officials, said he is still giving
Bush the benefit of the doubt. But he also voiced concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to believe that they're taking us for granted
already,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to hear about issues. How are we going to reduce the
dropout rate? What are we going to do about affirmative action,
bilingual education, restructuring INS?''
</P>
<P>
   The non-partisan group also invited Gore to speak at its June
meeting, an invitation he accepted.
</P>
<P>
   None of the presidential candidates accepted invitations to the
recent meeting of the League of United Latin American Citizens
(LULAC) in Corpus Christi, Texas. All but Pat Buchanan were
invited.
</P>
<P>
   Salena Walsh, the group's spokesperson, said Bush attended last
year's conference and met with LULAC officials in Austin in
February.
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, she said Bush and LULAC leaders ``agreed to
disagree'' on school vouchers. Bush supports them, while LULAC
opposes vouchers. In addition, she said the group pressed Bush on
his qualified support for bilingual education. He says he supports
it if statewide tests show it works. They urged him to bone up on
the long-debated issue of granting amnesty to illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said LULAC leaders had hoped Bush would speak about his
stand on such issues at their conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still would like to hear more assertive responses to our
questions, questions that are of the utmost concern to the Hispanic
community,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, campaign officials say Bush is trying to accommodate
the host of groups inviting him to speak and that he is trying to
reach out to all voters. They point out that he recently met with
Hispanic leaders in Iowa and that he discussed issues such as
bilingual education and immigration on a Spanish-language public
affairs television program in California.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he is scheduled to deliver welcoming remarks at the
Urban League's annual convention in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Henry Bonilla, (R-Texas), said he believes that
Hispanic voters at the grass-roots level are getting Bush's
message. And he urged voters to look at, ``the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he's going after solid Republican areas to win
primary states,'' Bonilla said. ``Al Gore is hitting unions hard.
He's having fund raisers with trial lawyers and Hollywood types
because he has to work his base very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Bush officials acknowledge that the campaign has been
focused on ensuring primary support from its core _the vast
majority of which is conservative and non-Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   That could be a mistake, said William Boone, associate professor
of political science at Clark Atlanta University. He said Bush
should not underestimate the importance of symbolism when it comes
to winning votes across racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably something that bears rethinking by the Bush
campaign,'' Boone said. ``It can appear to be insensitive to the
needs of these people. And symbolic needs are just as important as
substantive needs in some instances.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said Bush advisors are aware
of the criticism. She wouldn't say if it will make a difference
should Bush receive future invitations from Hispanic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's noted,'' she said of the criticism. ``The
governor's always looking for additional ways to reach out to the
Hispanic community. We're always going to give a serious look to
every invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be reached at jenah(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
