<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7555 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-LARAZA29-COX     07-28 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LARAZA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore targets GOP tax cut and Bush at La Raza convention
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) political categories.
 &HT;    By Scott Shepard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Vice President Al Gore, capitalizing on the
controversial absence of Texas Gov. George W. Bush from the annual
convention of the nation's largest Hispanic organization, charged
Wednesday that Republican tax cuts in Congress would drain the
federal budget surplus and jeopardize programs that are popular
among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   And while he refrained from mentioning Bush by name, he made the
most pointed political jab yet at the Texas governor in suggesting
that the GOP presidential frontrunner is standing with fellow
Republicans in Congress in support of a ``risky scheme'' of tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, alternating comfortably between English and Spanish
throughout his keynote address to the National Council of La Raza
(NCLR), also highlighted some unflattering statistics on the plight
of Hispanics in Texas to underscore his criticism of the GOP tax
cut plan in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He said several times, for instance, that 24 percent of the
children in Texas have no health insurance, the second highest
percentage in the nation, and that more than half of the state's
uninsured children are Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we care about all these children ... how could we even
consider taking this hard won surplus and just blowing it all on
schemes for special interest tax breaks,'' Gore said. ``And here in
Texas, the state with the second-highest percentage of uninsured
children in America, we need to question how any leader would
support such a risky scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from Bush's campaign. The
governor is on vacation in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the budget surplus should be used to shore up Social
Security and Medicare and to meet ``urgent needs'' in education,
such as combating Hispanic school dropout rates _ ``not to blow it
on another round of Republican roulette'' that produced record
budget deficits under the Reagan and Bush presidencies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the frontrunner for the Democratic presidential
nomination, also issued a veiled challenge to Bush to oppose his
party's attempts in Congress to prevent the use of statistical
sampling in the 2000 census in order to avoid the kind of
undercount of minorities that occurred in the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we possibly allow a census that last time undercounted
the Hispanic community by more than 5 percent and at a time when
the needs are greater, political aspirations are high and the need
for champions ... who can fight for you are even greater,'' he
said. ``Where is the leadership (in the Republican Party)?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made no overt pleas for support of his presidential bid to
the NCLR, a nonprofit, nonpartisan organization established in 1968
to reduce poverty and discrimination against Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   But Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, in his introduction of the
vice president, underscored the political nature of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Spanish, Richardson noted that ``the governor (Bush)
did not make it here, ``in contrast to the vice president _ a man
who is on our side with a record and a passionate commitment to our
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson reminded the thousands of Hispanics attending the
conference that 90 percent of the Latino community is concentrated
in states that account for 80 percent of the 270 electoral votes
needed for election to the presidency: California, Texas, Florida,
New York and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year is going to set the political tone for the new
century,'' Richardson said. And with Hispanics expected to become
the largest ethnic minority in the country in the next century, the
next election could be ``the most important in the millennium and
in the history of Latino political development (in the United
States).''
</P>
<P>
   The NCLR's rank-and-file members generally agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is going to make things happen for Hispanics,''
said Oscar Noriega Jr., 28, a former migrant worker who now heads
the Idaho Migrant Council, a public interest group that helps
migrant workers with health care, child care and education.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
