</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-STRATEGY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wall Street frowns on MindSpring
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Within a half hour after MindSpring Enterprise's
conference call to explain its earnings and future plans to
analysts Wednesday morning, its stock began a tumble that lasted
all day.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring closed at $35.50, down $4.75, a loss of almost 12
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the analysts downgraded the stock after Chairman and
Chief Executive Charles Brewer and President and Chief Operating
Officer Michael McQuary told them that future profits might be
sacrificed in the company's quest to reach 2 million subscribers
from its current 1.2 million by the second quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Departing from its aggressive acquisition model, MindSpring said
it would increase spending by $45 million to $50 million on a
marketing and advertising campaign, more than the 20 percent of
revenue it originally planned to spend. Brewer restated his desire
for MindSpring to ``break out of the pack and become a clear No.
2'' behind industry leader America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brewer told the analysts that if a good acquisition
opportunity came along he would take it, he indicated that
``organic growth'' was the plan for the immediate future, and that
MindSpring's profitable status _ rare in the Internet world _ would
be forfeited in the near term for that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport &AMP; Co. almost immediately downgraded MindSpring from
``hold'' to ``underperform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``MindSpring had been traded at a premium because they had a
profit and good control'' of their costs, Youssef Squali, an
analyst at Ladenburg Thalmann &AMP; Co., told Bloomberg News. He still
rates the stock a ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock is down because there's no takeover play,'' says
Jeff Sadler of FAC Equity in New York. Sadler still rates
MindSpring a ``buy'' but doesn't think MindSpring can cross the 2
million mark by this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   He's also wondered why MindSpring didn't detail the marketing
plan for analysts during the call. Rival company EarthLink
undertook a similar plan earlier this year, but invited analysts to
its Pasadena, Calif., headquarters to explain how it would work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely the time to do this,'' Sadler says, ``and
they are probably six months late at that. EarthLink realized this
nine months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler also says MindSpring's failure to address how it will
keep its new subscribers is making investors nervous. The company
made no mention of building out its start page to keep users around
beyond the free trial period. ``It's like herding cattle,'' Sadler
says, ``Once you get them in you have to have a sturdy fence.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's aggressive spending plans to grow subscribers is
at odds with the June 24 announcement that the company was
considering ``various business combinations.'' Neither Brewer nor
McQuary would comment on possible acquisitions or partnerships. But
Brewer did not rule out the possibility entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still interested in acquisition,'' Brewer said, ``but
we plan to pursue an aggressive organic growth plan. It will have a
negative impact on income, but it will help us become a stronger,
more valuable company.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company would continue to exercise the same
financial discipline in its marketing and advertising ventures that
led the company to a string of five profitable quarters. The string
ended in the first quarter of this year, when the company began to
absorb the costs of acquiring the venerable California Internet
provider Netcom.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts agree MindSpring may have to spend money on
advertising and marketing to grow its customer base. However, there
are concerns the company won't be able to meet its goal within the
one-year time frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear is they are spending just to tread water,'' Sadler
says. ``It's getting more competitive, and it's not getting easier.
AT&AMP;T and Microsoft are in a position to pull as heavy a trigger
when it comes to marketing as MindSpring.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
