<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hello 2000: Jennings to anchor 22 hours
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ If a millennium happens and TV doesn't cover
it, is it still a millennium?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not if you're at ABC, which plans 22 continuous hours
of millennial coverage around the globe. Peter Jennings will anchor
all 22 of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take it as a personal challenge,'' Jennings said of the
marathon assignment, noting the longest he can remember being
on-air for a stretch was 11 1/2 hours, during coverage of the
Challenger disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC coverage begins at 6 a.m. Eastern time, Dec. 31, with
Barbara Walters on a ship cruising the waters of the international
date line, where the millennium will be be rung in first. It ends
(barring an end of the world before that, which presumably ABC
would be positioned to cover extensively) 22 hours later, at 4
a.m., Jan. 1, on the U.S. West Coast (ABC won't finish out the 24
hours by ringing in the New Year in Hawaii, which is two hours
earlier).
</P>
<P>
   In between, ABC will be on hand as the new century is rung in in
each succeeding time zone. The network is part of a 60-country
consortium that will allow it to bring events from every continent.
</P>
<P>
   Among locations to be visited: New Zealand, where David Bowie
performs at midnight; Egypt, where the pyramids will be draped in
gold; an oil rig in Norway, where a concert is being held for the
workers there; and the South African island where Nelson Mandela
will visit the site of his imprisonment. Assignments to
correspondents are still being worked out, though Cokie Roberts,
for instance, could wind up in Rome, where her mother is ambassador
to the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   And Dick Clark _ who seemingly hasn't aged in a millennium _
will be his usual rockin' master of ceremonies for the ball drop in
New York's Times Square. He'll also narrate New Year's in the other
U.S. time zones, including at a $70-million-enhanced fountain at
the Bellagio Hotel in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to ABC 34 years ago, and Dick was already there for
some time, so he's got to be an integral part,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC coverage will combine entertainment, news and live and
taped reports, with time allotted for local affiliates to air their
own coverage. ABC will cover national celebrations and the common
happenings of the day. It'll look back and ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News President David Westin said he's been assured the
network has ``double and triple backup'' for any Y2K problems. The
network is also prepared to turn to any non-millennial-related news
that might occur that day.
</P>
<P>
   But he added of ABC's daylong coverage, ``We will not look like
a 24-hour cable news channel.''
</P>
<P>
   As for addressing the fact many believe the millennium doesn't
actually begin until 2001, Jennings said that school of thought
will be noted. But he added that the rush toward 2000 is ``a public
train ... and that train is not one I'd like to stand in front
of.''
</P>
<P>
   And the day after?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll all have a technological hangover,'' Jennings
said, ``and football will never look so good.''
</P>
<P>
   De Mornay, Alda on `ER'
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca De Mornay will appear in a five-episode story line of
NBC's ``ER,'' staring with the season opener, but she could remain
with the show after that. Best known for her film roles in 1992's
``The Hand That Rocks the Cradle'' and 1983's ``Risky Business''
opposite Tom Cruise, De Mornay will play a socialite who becomes
romantically involved with Dr. John Carter (Noah Wyle). Alan Alda
will also appear on ``ER'' for a five-episode arc, and Maura
Tierney (``NewsRadio'') is expected to join the regular cast.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
