<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARPED-TOUR29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Warped Tour' in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Punk Rock Summer Camp, also known as the Vans Warped
Tour '99, is coming to Atlanta as the quietly successful roving
festival makes its fifth jaunt through the summer's concert
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the hot punk and rap acts, skateboarders, Moto-X
riders and other extreme sports pros are an important part of the
tour, lending the scene a less sedentary air than some other
festivals. The hormonal surges and wanton destruction that raged
out of control at Woodstock '99 have more productive outlets on the
Warped Tour. The average Warped-goer is at least nominally more
political and the communal atmosphere created by the bands spills
over to the crowds. It may be among the last bastions of the punk
ethos, a credo that seeks to break down the barriers between the
bands and the fans.
</P>
<P>
   In that egalitarian punk spirit, there is no headliner on the
tour. The set times and performing order are decided on the day of
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Despite corporate sponsorship and bands with a higher profile,
the tour has tried to maintain its underground credentials with a
commitment to local and unsigned talent, a concerted effort at
cultivating female fans and a relatively inexpensive price tag of
$26.25 per ticket. A portion of the tour's proceeds benefits the
AIDS charity Camp Pacific Heartland, raising half the charity's
yearly operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes down to credibility with kids, though. So, is it
punk rock? As rapper Ice-T puts it on the tour's online radio show:
``On the Warped Tour, you're gonna be able to express yourself to
the fullest, have a good time. It's truly punk rock. The more
corporate the money, the better. Just take 'em and use their
money.''
</P>
<P>
   HOT ACTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blink-182 _Making a repeat appearance on the Warped tour, the
new-school punk trio has been toiling away since 1993. The band
just scored a big radio hit with ``What's My Age Again?'' from its
fourth album, ``Enema of the State.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eminem _ The 1999 tour also boasts the first Atlanta
appearance of the Detoit rap phenomenon . After a couple of
canceled dates, it looks like he might make it this time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sevendust _ Atlanta's own masters of metal mayhem. The quintet
is fresh from an appearance at the troubled Woodstock '99.
</P>
<P>
   1 p.m. today. $26.25 plus service charge at Ticketmaster, $29.25
at the gate. Lakewood Amphitheatre, 2002 Lakewood Way S.W.
404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Main Stage lineup (times, order determined day of show):
Pennywise, Blink-182, Sevendust, Eminem, Black Eyed Peas, Less Than
Jake, The Living End. Suicidal Tendencies, Molotov, Ice-T, 7
Seconds, The Vandals, Dropkick Murphys, Royal Crown Revue, Atomic
Fireballs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Bus Stage lineup (times, order, determined day of show):
Fenix tx, H2O, Frenzal Rhomb, Bouncing Souls, Spring Heeled Jack,
Buzz Poets, Reveille, Grinspoon, Deviates, L.E.S., Stiches.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
