<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTORS-MANAGED-CARE-     07-28 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-MANAGED-CARE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS, NURSES SAY PATIENTS DENIED SERVICES IN MANAGED CARE,
SURVEY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.) (rk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new survey shows widespread discontent among
doctors and nurses about the quality of health care under managed
care plans. A majority of doctors said some of their patients had
been denied coverage for a health service they needed, whether a
prescription drug, a diagnostic test or a treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was released in the midst of a struggle over
patients' rights legislation on Capitol Hill, and was immediately
criticized by spokesmen for health maintenance organizations and
the insurance industry as flawed and exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted for the Kaiser Family Foundation, a
nonprofit health research group, was just as quickly praised by the
American Medical Association and the American Nurses Association.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Altman, the president of Kaiser, acknowledged that doctors
are not always right when they prescribe a test, a drug or a
treatment, and that therefore not every denial of coverage by a
health plan is a bad thing. But he argued, ``I don't know that
anyone would strongly defend this level of conflict as an efficient
way to run a health system.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignani, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, which represents health maintenance organizations and other
managed care organizations, said the Kaiser study was
``inconsistent with existing research which has provided a very
different assessment of these issues.'' Previous studies have shown
that health plans approve coverage for the vast majority of
services recommended by doctors, she said, adding that the Kaiser
study failed to focus on how often doctors recommend inappropriate
care.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser study was conducted with the Harvard School of Public
Health and was administered by mail to a sample of 1,053 physicians
and 768 nurses, between Feb. 11 and June 5. The findings for the
doctors have a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3
percentage points; for nurses, of plus or minus 4 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one percent of doctors said insurance plans denied
coverage for a prescription drug for one of their patients on a
weekly or monthly basis. Thirty-one percent said they experienced
denials of a hospital stay on a weekly or monthly basis, and 42
percent said they had experienced denials of diagnostic tests or
procedures that often. (Another 27 percent said they had
experienced denials for diagnostic tests every six months to a
year.)
</P>
<P>
   Between a third and two-thirds of the doctors said their most
recent denial had resulted in a serious decline in the patient's
health status, depending on the type of service denied.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of the nurses surveyed said they saw patients'
health suffer because of decisions made by health plans. Thirty
percent of the nurses _ and 26 percent of the doctors _ said they
sometimes exaggerated the severity of a patient's condition to get
care they thought was necessary. And a majority of doctors said
that they or someone in their office would periodically try to
intervene with a health plan on their patients' behalf, and were
often successful.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and nurses did have some good things to say about
managed care, the HMOs and other health networks that now deliver
care to most Americans. Forty-five percent of the doctors and 42
percent of the nurses said managed care increased the likelihood
that patients will get preventive services.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of primary care physicians felt that way. And 68
percent of the doctors and 51 percent of the nurses said that
managed care had increased the use of guidelines and disease
management protocols, more modern and standardized ways of treating
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But in general, a strikingly negative view emerges of managed
care. Ninety-five percent of the doctors said it had increased the
amount of administrative paperwork for providers and patients.
Seventy-two percent said it had decreased the quality of health
care for people who are sick, and 77 percent said it had decreased
the ability of patients to get the tests and treatments they
needed. Eighty-six percent said it had decreased the ability of
patients to see medical specialists, and 83 percent said it had
decreased the amount of time doctors spend with their patients.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, these concerns affect the quality of the care
patients receive,'' said Dr. J. Edward Hill, a trustee of the
American Medical Association, who was on a panel convened by Kaiser
Wednesday to discuss the survey. ``Doctors know it, nurses know it,
and most importantly, patients know it. Not surprisingly, the only
sector of the health care industry that refuses to acknowledge this
fact is the one that has the most to gain from the status quo _ the
insurance industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In another survey released Wednesday, the National Committee on
Quality Assurance, a nonprofit organization focused on measuring
the quality of managed care organizations, evaluated data
voluntarily submitted from 410 health plans that cover 70 million
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that 57 percent of people rated their health
plans an 8, 9 or 10 on a 10-point scale, and that there was a
strong connection between accountability, clinical performance and
customer satisfaction. Three-fourths of consumers in the survey
said that getting needed care was not a problem, while 17.9 percent
said it was a small problem and 8.6 percent said it was a big
problem. New England health plans were out in front on a variety of
measures, like smoking cessation efforts and cervical cancer
screening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
