<HEADER>
A7566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZMAGS29-COX     07-28 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summertime leisure turns thoughts to how to retire early, with
money
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retire early, retire rich. Those are themes in a number of
midsummer issues of business and personal finance magazines, which
offer advice on how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune (Aug. 16) warns that a dream retirement ``will cost more
than you ever imagined, but you can get there. All you need is a
simple plan.''
</P>
<P>
   A retiree can generally expect to maintain a pre-retirement
standard of living on 65 percent to 85 percent of current salary,
the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Money (August), calling retirement ``America's newest
obsession,'' attributes the big trend to creation of the 401(k)
plan, which has often replaced traditional company-operated pension
systems. Thanks to the bull market on Wall Street, two-thirds of
all 401(k) contributors told pollsters they expect to retire early,
the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   According to Money (August), trying to guess the stock market's
every twitch and turn is a waste of time. Adopt a sound plan and
stick to it. Some suggestions: Take profits on investments that
have already soared, don't be shy about letting cash build up in
your portfolio, add bonds to balance your total holdings and look
for undervalued stocks.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth the loner
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (Aug. 2) says BellSouth must make acquisitions to
survive intact in the new, deregulated world of telecommunications.
That's what rivals of the Atlanta-based Baby Bell are already
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analysts say that BellSouth has a window of maybe two years to
bulk up before competitors digest their current acquisitions and
come hunting,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Officer F. Duane Ackerman is mum on all the
options but won't rule out anything, Business Week adds.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve may be creating an unintended problem with
its policy of low interest and inflation rates, says Individual
Investor (August). By keeping borrowing costs so low, businesses
are expanding too fast _ investment as a percentage of gross
domestic product is near a 70-year high. The risk is
overproduction, which usually leads to the very inflation the Fed
wants to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine (August) rates and ranks
more than 2,000 mutual funds in a special midyear funds edition
that tries to make sense of a stock market that is ``behaving in
new and strange ways.''
</P>
<P>
   All you need to start a successful new business is $1,000,
according to Inc. (August), which offers the advice you'll need to
make it happen. Among its suggestions: look for freebies
everywhere, and draft your family and friends for help.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
