<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS SAY THEIR FIRST-ROUND PICK IS HEADED TO EUROPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Dallas Mavericks are headed back to Plan A, which
means first-round draft pick Leon Smith is headed to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Coach and general manager Don Nelson said Wednesday the team has
informed Smith and his agent that the 18-year-old rookie is not
ready for the NBA. In fact, with Smith expected to miss the
Mavericks' remaining summer league games while in Chicago trying to
terminate his status as a ward of Illinois, the next time he wears
a Mavericks uniform will likely be next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not disappointed in him because this is exactly what we
expected,'' Nelson said. ``He's loaded with talent, but he doesn't
know what to do with it. He needs a lot of work on the
fundamentals, and the best way to get that is by lots of playing
time. We think the best place for him now is Europe for a year.
That was Plan A all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a 6-foot-11 center trying to make the jump from high
school to the NBA, made a shaky debut in Dallas, storming off the
court and refusing to run sprints after his first practice. His
play was considerably more promising, averaging 7.5 points and 5.4
rebounds while playing 14 minutes per game in seven summer
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   He had by far his best game on Saturday against the Ukrainian
National Team in Long Beach, Calif., scoring 16 points and grabbing
16 rebounds. He also, however, fouled out in only 28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the first time we just turned him loose and let
him play,'' Nelson said. ``He had a double-double, but he didn't
know what he was doing. He wanted a chance to prove he was ready
and we gave it to him. But there's no doubt, he's not ready. Not
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who indicated Smith agreed with the decision to delay
his NBA debut, said ideally he'd like to have Smith's season
overseas monitored by Tony Runzone, the team's director of
international scouting. Briefly Despite free-agent forward Gary
Trent deciding not to re-sign with the Mavericks immediately,
Nelson remains confident of retaining his No. 1 off-season
priority. ``His agent owes it to him to see if a big offer comes
out of nowhere,'' Nelson said. ``But we're still in the same, good
position.'' Trent, high on the wish lists of Seattle and the
Clippers, can begin formal negotiations with teams and sign a
contract Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent forward Samaki Walker, considered a priority only if
Trent leaves, is receiving interest from a number of teams, headed
by the Celtics. Walker, who would be Trent's backup in Dallas, has
an offer on the table to stay a Maverick. ``We either want to sign
him or sign and trade him,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks finish their summer league play Monday against the
Jazz in Salt Lake City. Nelson said his best three players have
been guards Greg Buckner and Anthony Carter, and second-year
forward Dirk Nowitzki. ``His confidence level is just so much
higher,'' Nelson said of Nowitzki. ``Plus, we think he's grown
maybe another half-inch up to over 7 feet.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
