<HEADER>
A7570 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-SUMMIT-BOS &LR;      07-28 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS TO DISCUSS FUTURE OF BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO _ It is billed as a group talk on peace and stability,
but Friday's meeting here with President Clinton and European
leaders on the future of the Balkans looks more like a
dysfunctional family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   At the birthplace of World War I _ still scarred from the more
recent 1992-95 Bosnian War _ participants at the two-day summit
will seek ways to heal the area's ailing economies and rebuild
war-ravaged lands.
</P>
<P>
   But will they stop feuding long enough to talk?
</P>
<P>
   The host nation, Bosnia and Herzegovina, suffers from tension
among Muslims, Croats and Serbs so severe that many analysts
believe war would break out if NATO pulled out its patrols.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Bosnia, signals are emerging that Balkans will keep
splintering, even after warfare's end in Kosovo. Slobodan
Milosevic, the starring actor in a decade of Balkan bloodshed, has
been pointedly excluded from the talks, but the nation he rules
will dominate discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Making noises about separating from Belgrade is Yugoslavia's
junior republic, Montenegro, whose Western-friendly President Milo
Djukanovic will attend the summit. He is considering escaping
Belgrade's economic deterioration by developing Montenegro's own
currency.
</P>
<P>
   But Yugoslav President Milosevic is also not likely to loosen
ties without a fight _ any more than he did with former Yugoslav
republics Slovenia, Croatia, and Bosnia. A war in Montenegro could
be especially bloody, analysts and Montenegrin officials warn,
since the republic is home to both Serb loyalists and Montenegrin
nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, so badly bloodied in the war with the Serbs, may also
move towards independence, despite worries that the majority ethnic
Albanians _ who have little experience with democratic self-rule _
are not yet prepared to run their own country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect parts of Yugoslavia will become independent
countries, and much faster than people think,'' said Paul Goble, an
expert on Eastern and Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While the West has been reluctant to back independence movements
in the region, it would be better off accepting that it simply
can't force people to stay together when they don't want to, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to hold countries together for the sake of holding
countries together will just get you violence or repression or
both,'' Goble said.
</P>
<P>
   International governments and aid organizations are hoping to
force some stability on the region by propping up their flailing
economies, and helping those still suffering from the wars.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels Wednesday, more than 100 countries and organizations
pledged $2.1 billion in aid for Kosovo, where hundreds of thousands
of refugees have returned to destroyed or severely damaged homes.
The United States offered the lion's share of aid, $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 120,000 homes _ more than half the houses in Kosovo
_ are damaged and 40,000 are completely ruined, according to a
study commissioned by the European Union. Home rebuilding alone
will cost $1 billion, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   For Kosovo, Balkan watchers say the West should learn from the
mistakes it made in Bosnia. While Bosnia has suffered little
violence since the war ended, its economy is still poor, despite
the billions of dollars the international community has put here,
said James Lyon, a political analyst with the Sarajevo-based
International Crisis Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are seriously discussing throwing huge quantities of
money at a part of the world that is completely unstable, and has
the possibility of exploding in a few years, or even a few
months,'' Lyon said. ``There has to be security'' first.
</P>
<P>
   Western nations are also using cash to punish, as well to help.
Most are concluding that upper Serbia should not be assisted in
repairing the damage done by 78 days of NATO strikes as long as
Milosevic is still in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a consensus that we should do what we can to
help the Serbia people. But there is no intention to provide
assistance for the Milosevic regime,'' Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said after meeting in Rome with Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a place in the stability pact for a democratic
Serbia,'' added Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee also voted Wednesday to
tighten sanctions on Serbia, and to provide $100 million to aid the
Serbian opposition. Serbian opposition figures were asked to attend
the Sarajevo meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The region's difficulties meanwhile extend well beyond
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia is feeling the heat from the International War Crimes
Tribunal, which Wednesday recommended life imprisonment for one
accused Croatian war criminal. The prosecution of Croatian military
leaders has led to speculation that Croatian President Franjo
Tudjman may himself be indicted, as Milosevic was in May.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal's chief investigator, Louise Arbour, also made a
formal complaint about Croatia Wednesday, charging that the nation
had been ``delinquent'' in cooperating with her probe into a 1995
Croatian attack on Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Albania's economy is a basket case, and the nation _ Europe's
poorest _ is marred by murders stemming from ethnic blood feuds and
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary and Romania are in a snit because Romania doesn't want
to allow the creation of a Hungarian-language university for the
ethnic minority there.
</P>
<P>
   And the Serbs are annoyed with Hungary's government for pushing
for autonomy for the northern Serbian province of Vojvodina, where
there is a 15-17 percent ethnic Hungarian population.
</P>
<P>
   With all of the simmering ethnic tension _ not to mention the
economic troubles and infrastructural damage _ Balkan stability may
take a long time, observers say. The unpredictability of the events
in the region, experts say, make calming the Balkans even more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not mathematics, It's algebra,'' Goble said. ``There are
just so many uncertainties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
