<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7571 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MORNING-SFCHRON &LR;      07-28 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MORNING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOOD MORNING AMERICA'S' TEMPORARY CREW LOOKS NOT SO TEMPORARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Charles Gibson said his brain was fried after
he'd risen early in New York, done ``Good Morning America'' and
then flown to Los Angeles with his co-anchor, Diane Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   So go ahead, Gibson said, make up quotations for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm supposed to say something about how much the program has
improved, which I do feel,'' he said. ``But whatever quote you'd
like to write down from my mouth about how much the program has
improved, I will endorse it and accept that totally.''
</P>
<P>
   All right:
</P>
<P>
   ``The program has made an infinitesimal improvement since I came
back to it,'' Gibson said. ``But frankly, I felt more comfortable
sitting at home in curlers and my fluffy pink housecoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to avail myself of this opportunity, in front of the
national television press, to say that every moment of working with
Diane Sawyer is as painful to me as a hot poker.
</P>
<P>
   ``And finally, I'd like to announce today that my next career
move will be to host a reality series on the UPN network. It will
be a revised version of the popular UPN series `RedHanded,' but due
to major content changes, it will now be called `WetHanded.'''
</P>
<P>
   So there you go. Or at least that's how I heard it, and I have
Charlie's unqualified endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   But enough of him. Just to his left, Sawyer was looking tired
and milky, and trying not to explain her work absences.
</P>
<P>
   Those would be Monday and Tuesday last week, when ``Good Morning
America'' and the rest of the news world were up to their nostrils
in covering the death of John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and his
sister-in-law. For those two days, Sawyer was absent with leave,
though neither she nor her indulgent bosses have been willing to
explain why.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the guesswork has centered on Sawyer's status as a
wealthy New York socialite-celebrity with personal attachments to
Kennedy relatives. Consequently, she was supposedly sharing the
Kennedy grief while her colleagues sucked it in and went to work.
</P>
<P>
   It's an explanation that might evoke mixed feelings about
Sawyer. As in loyal friend but fickle news star. Never mind, said
Sawyer. The ``grief-stricken'' account isn't true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the stories, I have no idea where they came from,''
she said. ``That was not the situation. ... I do want to make it
clear that I think a lot of people in this country felt the weight
of the tragedy. I'm not saying that I didn't too, but that was not
the reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated prods, Sawyer wouldn't elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just say that it was a personal decision ... some
personal obligations that I should make sure that I served,'' she
said. ``I'm so lucky that my co-anchor and my executive producer
and (ABC News president) David Westin agreed with me that that was
the right decision ... Everybody understood and seemed to agree
with me that I had, as I say, these obligations that I should tend
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer provided the same nonexplanation, in almost the same
words, three or four times.
</P>
<P>
   She has as much right as anyone to ``personal obligations,'' to
arrange work absences with her bosses and to duck questions.
</P>
<P>
   But bear in mind, as another critic was whispering in my ear
during the Sawyer-Gibson press session, that these people have no
compunction about poking a camera in the face of a teenager who's
just seen his best friends shot to pieces. Yet no one at ABC wants
to answer questions about why Sawyer missed two days of work. Hint
of a double standard, no?
</P>
<P>
   On to public business. The broadcast cranny of morning
television is in complete flux, with CBS readying Bryant Gumbel and
a glitzy new studio for ``The Early Show,'' while ABC is building
an open-face Times Square studio for ``GMA,'' and NBC's ``Today''
rules the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``GMA'' was circling the drain with Lisa McRee and Kevin Newman
until Sawyer and Gibson replaced them early this year. The ratings
stabilized and then began climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, Sawyer and Gibson have been designated from the
get-go as temporary co-anchors. Gibson said he and Sawyer are
``transitional figures,'' committed to ``GMA'' through next May.
But, he said, news president Westin has ``extraordinary persuasive
powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson added, ``My wife keeps asking me how much longer we're
going to do this, and I don't have an answer for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Should be easy. Until the UPN premiere of ``WetHanded.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
