<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BETTING-HNS &LR;      07-28 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BETTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLERKS PAY FOR MISTAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITTA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ If you're worried when placing a bet on
the horses, just think of the clerk who takes the money at the
betting window.
</P>
<P>
   If the clerk makes a mistake, he or she must pay for it. The
largest error last year cost one unlucky bet taker $1,500, close to
the $2,000 clerks may earn in a season.
</P>
<P>
   The pari-mutuel clerks just learned that at a recently completed
four-hour class conducted by the New York Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're nervous,'' said Vince Hogan, director of
mutuels for NYRA, who will have 400 of his 575 clerks taking up to
450 bets each.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day I'm gonna lose 50 of them,'' he said of the
anticipated resignations. ``I can bet on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The historic Saratoga track opens today for its 131st season, a
36-day meet that runs through Labor Day and features 35 stakes
races with purses totaling more than $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   NYRA hopes to match last year's opening day crowd of 25,570.
</P>
<P>
   Clerks may process more than $3 million in bets, as they did for
the 1998 opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be happy if we reach $2.5 million,'' Hogan said. ``Last
year we had an exceptional year.''
</P>
<P>
   At the sixth and final training session Monday afternoon, 40
candidates studied their 81-key terminals that compute bets but do
not calculate change.
</P>
<P>
   Wielding a microphone and with a Long Island accent, Jack Dunn,
a clerk and trainer, called out practice bets for the trainees to
process into the machines that spewed white dummy tickets toward
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that 20 percent of bets are straight: win, place,
show or across the board. The rest are the ``exotics,'' forward and
reverse wheels, trifectas, quinellas (which Dunn said is ``an
exacta that auto reverses itself'') and boxing of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little robot in the basement that sorts it all
out,'' Dunn said. Clerks also process wagers for simulcast events
and races from the Meadowlands or the West Coast. ``If you're gonna
screw up, let it be today,'' he counseled.
</P>
<P>
   Screwing up was on the mind of substitute elementary school
teacher Nancy Cross, 47, of Malta, N.Y., who took the class twice
to become more comfortable with racing lingo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt overwhelmed, but I'm starting to get it better,'' Cross
said. ``I'm doing this because I have four teenagers, one in
college. The money is needed ... And it's better than day care
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Homemaker Patricia Downey, 44, from Speigletown, N.Y., felt more
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really hard,'' she said. ``I've got a 13-year-old who
wants all these high-priced things for school, so this will help
out.'' Pari-mutuel clerks are fired for gambling. They must compute
transactions in their heads, protect themselves from quick-change
scams and endure stress from superstitious bettors.They also have
to work without a lunch hour and have only seven-minute breaks
between races. Clubhouse regulars have been known to travel with
bodyguards carrying suitcases filled with cash, veteran clerks
said. But big players are not always big tippers.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Guthrie, 39, of Saratoga Springs will begin her 12th
racing season today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get customers who come to my window every year,'' said
Guthrie, who described one couple that tips her $200 when their
two-week vacation in the city ends. ``I had another bettor five or
six years ago who won $52,000 on a Pick 6. My window was closed 45
minutes, we had to get a Pinkerton escort for him, and he tipped me
nothing. So that's the range.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's parting advice to the new recruits included how to endure
distractions like ``a few buttons open here and there'' or
celebrities like Tom Cruise and Sandra Bullock, both of whom have
made bets at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   For Guthrie, it's all part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep coming back because it's exciting,'' she said. ``It's
the human condition, different from any other job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
