A7585 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX     07-28 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIT BEING SO CONTRARY, BARRY, AND JUST COME BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guess the Detroit Lions got what they had coming to them, huh,
Barry Sanders? They couldn't win, so you just up and quit playing
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   And I thought Ken Griffey Jr. had it all wrong with his ranting
and raving that no amount of money could keep him with the
perennial losing Seattle Mariners. But at least Griffey didn't just
take his ball and go home. Yet you, Barry, are in London, laughing
as the rest of us, like mourners at a funeral, wonder ``Why?'' and
``Is he really done?''
</P>
<P>
   Sure glad other signature athletes in sports history didn't take
the low road out like you did, Barry. What if Ernie Banks had
retired early because he was tired of losing with the Chicago Cubs,
or if O.J. Simpson quit because he was tired of losing with the
Buffalo Bills?
</P>
<P>
   Get the picture?
</P>
<P>
   But it goes deeper than that. What kind of example could you be
setting for kids who look up to you as a hero? (''Uh, hey junior,
if the little league softball team loses again next week, it's OK
for you to quit on your teammates and take up harp lessons.'')
</P>
<P>
   Barry, I hope you really know what you are doing. It would be a
shame if you look back one day and say, ``Man, I wish I would've
played another year or two. I was just 1,458 yards away from
breaking Walter Payton's NFL career rushing record.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, everyone has the right to go when they think it's
time to go. And who are we to question what's in your heart, Barry?
In that statement you issued Wednesday morning, you told us that
you no longer had a desire to play the game. You said you had no
problems with the Lions or Lions management.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, then why last spring did you let your father
tell the Detroit newspapers that you were sick of the Lions and
sick of losing? Why not pick up a phone and call the Lions to
inform them of your decision? And why wait until the beginning of
training camp to announce a decision you had obviously made after
the end of the 1998 season?
</P>
<P>
   In your mind, Barry, maybe the Lions deserve their fate. But
what about your fans? Like Michael Jordan and John Elway, you,
Barry, will go down as one of the greatest athletic performers in
sports history. But you couldn't even get, ``Goodbye,'' right. When
somebody finally caught up to you Wednesday, you were in London
with trips to Paris and Amsterdam lined up. ``I don't know the
right way to retire,'' you deadpanned as your agents stayed in the
country to release your retirement statement. ``This,'' you said,
``is just my way of doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess part of the reason for such a passionately venomous tone
is out of jealousy. OK. There you have it, Barry. But man, we're
going to miss you. We'll miss the way you zigged when the
linebacker thought you were going to zag, the way you could make a
2-yard gain look like the most beautiful run ever.
</P>
<P>
   I was in Detroit that December day in 1997 when you became the
third player in NFL history to rush for 2,000 yards in a season.
There was an eerie feeling in the Lions' locker room afterward, for
you had reached the magic milestone on the same day that your
teammate, linebacker Reggie Brown, was temporarily paralyzed and
nearly died from a head-on collision during the game.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of us, much of your attention was on Brown's health.
Soon, though, we came to you for your thoughts on the game you
played and how you helped the Lions earn a playoff berth. I
remember looking at you, with your 5-foot-7 frame, and wondering,
``Is this the same little guy that did all of that out there?''
</P>
<P>
   In your answers to questions that day, you were so humble, so
unassuming. And that's what made the way you retired so puzzling.
Against the way you've always done things, you showed up the Lions,
the coaching staff and the Detroit fans.
</P>
<P>
   So what now? If you don't reverse field and come back to the
NFL, what are we left with? Terrell Davis? Jamal Anderson? Emmitt
Smith? Ricky Williams? Great backs, all, but none with quite the
ability you have to turn a 5-yard loss into an 80-yard gain, and
none at the doorstep of history.
</P>
<P>
   Call me selfish. But I'm not the only one who feels like we've
been unnecessarily cheated.
</P>
<P>
   Come back, Barry. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
