<HEADER>
A7588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-FARKAS-365&AMP;ADD-N     07-28 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FARKAS-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER S. FARKAS, 69; RAN FAMILY DEPARTMENT STORES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y.)  (yn) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alexander S. Farkas, who helped build Alexander's department
stores into the place where New Yorkers went to get stylish
fashions for a bargain and then watched as the chain went bankrupt,
died Wednesday in his home in Highland Park, Fla. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his brother, Robin Farkas, said.
</P>
<P>
   The chain was founded in 1928 by Farkas' father, George, who
named both his business and his son after his father. His strategy
was to offer fashions and housewares that were then the exclusive
province of full-service department stores at cut-rate prices by
getting rid of frills like fancy decor and free alterations. ``Dad
went right in between'' the high-end stores and cut-rate clothiers,
``not with decor and ambiance but with style, fashion and price,''
Robin Farkas said at the time of his father's death in 1980. ``It
had not been done that way before.''
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday in the 1930s, the Alexander's flagship store at
Fordham Road and the Grand Concourse in the Bronx served a grateful
cash-strapped immigrant population and boasted more sales per
square foot than any other retailer in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Farkas, who was known as Sandy, was born in New York
City. He was educated at Choate School and the Bronx High School of
Science, attended the University of Chicago and studied business at
Cornell University. Right after school, he got a job loading
freight and then went to work in advertising, but his strong-willed
father soon lured him into the family business, though it was not
necessarily his first love.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1985 interview in The New York Times, Bruce Farkas, another
brother, said, ``We were all coerced into the business. George not
only planned for it but expected our compliance.'' He remembered in
that interview that Alexander wanted to be a ``college history
professor.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Farkas was married five times. Besides his three
brothers, he is survived by his fifth wife, Linda Saltzman Farkas.
He is also survived by three children from his third marriage to
Francine Moss Glansrach: a son, Alexander Farkas of California, and
two daughters, Georgette Farkas and Cindy Glansrach, both of New
York City.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Alexander Farkas started as head of stock in the women's coat
department in 1951. His main responsibility, he later joked, was to
carry merchandise from rack to rack. While his father insisted on a
rigorous training program that included stints in all the
departments except the cafeteria, Farkas rose quickly and was named
president and general merchandising manager eight years later. His
father remained chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, Farkas began remodeling the image of the
store to be more fashionable. While he continued his father's
policies of ``no credit, no charge accounts, no deliveries and no
alterations,'' he opened new stores _ including the new flagship at
58th Street and Lexington _ and decorated them with touches like
crystal chandeliers. During his first year on the job, he doubled
the chain's advertising budget and developed exclusive arrangements
with European houses to get their excess inventories.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of bumps. After one warm winter season
resulted in disappointing sales and Farkas' father questioned the
new approach, Farkas quit and joined a men's clothing manufacturer.
A week later, his father wooed him back, but with a caveat: a
contract that promised Farkas control over the merchandise. ``I'm
probably the only son working in a family business who has a
written contract,'' Alexander Farkas once noted, ``but it has made
for harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next decades, Alexander Farkas helped build Alexander's
into a 16-store business with more than $500 million in annual
revenue. In 1968, the family took the company public. Soon
afterward the semi-retired George Farkas and his wife, Ruth, sold
their shares, and Farkas' brother Jonathan did the same. But
Alexander Farkas and his other two brothers, Bruce and Robin, held
onto shares worth significant stakes in the company, which opened
the way for a family schism years later.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, retailing was getting more competitive in New
York. Whereas Alexander's was one of the few alternatives to the
pricer department stores like Bloomingdale's and Macy's,
competitors like Kmart, Conway and outlet centers began chipping
into the store's clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the real estate Alexander's stores occupied was
appreciating at dizzying speed. The company stock soon attracted
investors like Interstate Properties Inc., a real-estate developer
in New Jersey, and Robert Bass, the financier from Texas, who were
mostly interested in developing such sites beyond retail, which was
not Alexander Farkas' main interest.
</P>
<P>
   After a bad acquisition led to some losses in 1980, Bruce and
Robin joined with Interstate to petition the Securities and
Exchange Commission to gain more influence over the company. Farkas
soon acceded to the dissidents' demands, agreeing to allow the
group to name five new members to the board; both Robin and Bruce
Farkas moved up in the company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Alexander Farkas resigned as chief executive. He said
it was just time ``to take life a little easier,'' but pressure
from Interstate, which owned 13 percent of the company by then,
clearly had some effect. He was succeeded by Robin and then by
outside management.
</P>
<P>
   The company went into swift decline and did not make a profit
after 1987 except when it sold stores. In 1992, Alexander's Inc.
declared bankruptcy and closed its last 11 stores. Mayor David N.
Dinkins called the closing ``a sad day for New York City.'' As it
turns out, however, Alexander's was worth more dead than alive. Its
stock, which had been trading at $8.50 in the days before
bankruptcy was declared shot up as high as $57 in the following
year as investors realized the value of its real estate.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
