<P>
   RALSTON-APPOINTMENT (Washington) _ President Clinton's decision
to name Air Force Gen. Joseph Ralston supreme allied commander for
NATO marks a watershed for the flying service. The Army has had a
lock on the position since 1963. The appointment also is an
acknowledgement that wars of the future may be fought as they were
in Kosovo _ relying on aircraft over ground troops. By ERIC
ROSENBERG and STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BALKAN-SUMMIT (Washington) _ A look at President Clinton's
upcoming visit to Sarajevo for a summit on Balkans peace. Clinton
and more than 50 other world leaders will begin work Friday on a
comprehensive strategy to reform and revitalize the region's
economy. By JOHN HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-GUNS (Washington) _ The Senate shoots down an attempt by
Sen. Bob Smith, I-N.H., to prevent the passage of gun-control
legislation. Members vote 77-22 to begin conference negotiations
with the House aimed at producing a final juvenile justice bill. By
GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   AMMO-CLIPS (Washington) _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein suffers a defeat
when the Senate rejected her legislation that would have banned the
import of high-capacity ammunition clips. Feinstein had argued that
hunters and sports shooters weren't interested in the clips and
that only criminals wanted them. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION-COURTS (Washington) _ Saying all immigrants deserve
their day in court, civil rights leaders urge Congress to amend
1996 laws that give the federal government largely unrestricted
deportation authority. STEVE LASH.
</P>
