<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTE ON HOLBROOKE LIKELY NEXT WEEK, DEMOCRATIC LEADER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate will probably vote next week on the
long-delayed nomination of Richard Holbrooke to the position of
chief American delegate to the United Nations, the Senate
Democratic leader said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thomas Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader, told
reporters that Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader,
had assured him that the Senate would hold a final vote on the
nomination before lawmakers left for their summer recess next
weekend. Lott's spokesman, John Czwartacki, indicated some
conditions still needed to be worked out, but Democrats said they
would be easy to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has indicated that it will probably take some debate time
and a vote,'' Daschle said. ``I certainly appreciate the need to do
that, given the opposition on his side, in some cases, to Mr.
Holbrooke. But we'll do that, we'll schedule the time and make it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Four Republican senators, including Lott, have held final
confirmation hostage until the administration addresses a series of
demands that largely have nothing to do with Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky have placed a ``hold''
on Holbrooke's nomination until President Clinton appoints a
conservative Ohio law professor to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley of Iowa says he will not lift his
objection until an accommodation is made to protect someone he
thinks was a whistle-blower at the U.S. mission to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. George Voinovich of Ohio is holding things up until he
reviews Holbrooke's role in the administration's Balkan
policy-making.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the holds seemed to be slipping on Wednesday in the wake
of criticism from Republicans like Sens. John Warner of Virginia
and Chuck Hagel of Nebraska that their leaders were hijacking an
important American foreign policy job over extraneous issues.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich appears ready to give up his hold this week,
Republican aides say; Lott and McConnell seem amenable to pursuing
their complaint with the White House, but no longer linking it to
Holbrooke, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday afternoon, Czwartacki had placed three new
conditions on a final vote that seemed intended to provide Senate
Republicans with political cover for their delays.
</P>
<P>
   The final vote will happen, Czwartacki told reporters, if Senate
Democrats cooperate with Republicans to move bills through the
Senate; if Lott finds no new problems in a ``second look'' at
Holbrooke's record; and if Grassley sees progress on his concern.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats are promising to be good, at least until after
the recess; Lott's aides privately say they do not expect him to
find any new questions about Holbrooke's files, and Grassley is
planning to meet with White House officials on Thursday to hash out
their views.
</P>
</TEXT>
