<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANYONING-DEATHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CANYONING' ADVENTURE TURNS DEADLY FOR 19 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS W. HAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA _ In heavy rain in the Austrian Alps last spring,
Hendrick Maat stood above a river canyon and watched an
adventurer's nightmare sweep past.
</P>
<P>
   Outfitted with wetsuits, helmets, harnesses and ropes, Maat and
a team of ``Canyoners'' eyed the gorge as clear water turned murky
and muddy. The rush of the river grew louder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just hear it and you know it's coming. You just have one
minute,'' he said. ``We had a flood wave coming through, and of
course we didn't go in.''
</P>
<P>
   The canyoners exploring a river in the Swiss Alps on Tuesday
were not so lucky. Police are still trying to figure out what went
wrong. But they are certain a group of 45 tourists and eight guides
were caught when a flash flood hit the Saxeten River, a popular
canyoning spot near the Swiss tourist town of Interlacken.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen people were killed and two are missing.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, such a tragedy is not a surprise. Canyoning is
a risky game, with the players rappelling down foaming waterfalls,
sliding over rocks, jumping into deep pools. Thousands of
Americans, Europeans and others are making canyoning one of the
fastest-growing extreme sports, from Australia and the Amazon to
the Alps and the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   What is surprising is that with so many people getting an
adrenaline rush by risking the rivers, the Saxeten accident is the
deadliest for the young sport.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when adventure aficionados drop $65,000 for Everest
expeditions and $50 for Bungee jumps, there is no shortage of
critics when things go wrong. But dedicated canyoners characterize
their sport as one in which mistakes are measured in scrapes,
bruises and broken bones _ not corpses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first accident I've heard of in canyoning where
there are dead people,'' said Maat, a five-year canyoning veteran
who opened his own adventure company in the Austrian Alps this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea of canyoning is to rush down a river the way
water does. Canyoners wear wetsuits and helmets to slide over some
rocks; they hurtle over others. When the rocks are too steep, or
waterfalls too high, canyoners clip on ropes and rappel to a pool
below.
</P>
<P>
   Tour guides say their clients include thrill-seekers and nature
lovers. One guide led 40 Boy Scouts from England, ages 8-14, on a
two-week journey. But older customers sometimes rappel 150-foot
waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customers, they want action, they want adventure, because
most of the customers work in an office,'' said Armin Liedl, who
runs Canyoning Adventure Team in central Austria. ``But they don't
want to spend a lot of time to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Adventure outfitters have flourished in mountain resorts,
particularly in the past three or four years, promoting canyoning
as a step beyond whitewater rafting. Many advertised day trips for
beginners for as little as $50.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure World, the company that led the ill-fated journey
Tuesday, is a leader in the field, billing itself among the biggest
adventure companies in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The company has taken more than 100,000 people rafting, bungee
jumping, mountain biking, rock climbing, paragliding and skydiving.
But canyoning, developed just 15 years ago in France, has become
the company's number one sport. More than 35,000 people have gone
canyoning with Adventure World.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's group was exploring a well-known area around Saxeten,
a river that drains into Lake Brienz, when the flood hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, it's absolutely no problem at all. Hundreds of
thousands have made it already,'' said Urs Zuagg, Interlaken's
director of tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Zuagg said that flash floods are extremely uncommon this time of
year. But heavy rains at high elevations can come as a surprise
downstream, where the weather may be fine.
</P>
<P>
   A local jogger first spotted seven bodies clad in life jackets
floating into Lake Brienz. It is not clear wheter the victims
drowned or were killed by rocks, fallen trees, or other debris.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the victims were from Australia, with casualities also
from Britain, South Africa, New Zealand and Switzerland.
Investigators said Wednesday that US and Canadian canyoners in the
group had survived.
</P>
<P>
   The father of one survivor said his 21-year-old daughter barely
made it. ``She said the water was crystal clear one minute and just
murk, mud and logs the next,'' Len Brajkovich told the Australian
Broadcasting Co. ``She went under and somebody grabbed her and she
grabbed somebody else and they just clambered straight up the sides
and back out of reach of the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Adventure World has halted its trips until an investigation is
completed. But hundreds more vacationers have arrived in Interlaken
for trips with other operators, Zuagg said.
</P>
<P>
   And in neighboring Austria, more tourists have been signing up
than ever before. Alexandra Fluer, tourism director in the town of
Imst, hasn't been canyoning yet. But she's keeping a date for this
weekend, when she and her staff have plans for a group trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that it's dangerous,'' she said, ``but it is
adventure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
