<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7600 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALUN-GONG-COX     07-28 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALUN-GONG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falun Gong followers alarmed
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yuan Li spent years studying to be a scientist. He
earned a Ph.D. in electrical engineering at Princeton, studying
under Professor Daniel Tsui, who won the Nobel Prize in physics in
1998. He moved to Duluth, Ga. and got a job as an engineer at
Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, something was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I can become the top expert in the field, and still
the knowledge we have is very limited,'' Li said. ``People talk
about how they live life, what they live for. We don't know those
things in physics.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, two years ago, a friend gave him a book called ``Zhuan
Falun,'' written by Li Hongzhi.
</P>
<P>
   The book was hard to read at first, and it seemed illogical. But
Li read it again, carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, I thought, `Oh, this book has a lot of answers to
this, and it's very convincing,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He began performing the prescribed exercises _ once a week, at
first, then every morning. His energy improved. He needed less
sleep. His allergies disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   He had become a practitioner of a discipline called Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a few million other people.
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong has only existed publicly (adherents say the
knowledge is ancient) since 1992. Yet the discipline has spread
around the world. In China, where Yuan Li grew up, the group
estimates it has 70 to 100 million members, though the Chinese
government estimate is 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the number, the government obviously feels threatened.
</P>
<P>
   After April 25, when more than 10,000 practitioners of Falun
Gong surrounded the Communist Party's leadership compound in
Beijing to protest the arrests of practitioners, the government
ignored the group, pretending that the largest protest since those
at Tiananmen Square a decade ago had simply not happened.
</P>
<P>
   Then the government cracked down. Last week, it banned Falun
Gong, arrested practitioners, incarcerated them in sports stadiums
and launched a televised attempt to discredit Li Hongzhi, the
philosophy's founder.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run Xinhua News Agency said earlier this week that
large amounts of the founder's materials had been confiscated
across the country, including more than 73,000 books in Tianjin, a
port near Beijing; 130,000 books and 27,000 audio tapes in Wuhan,
in central China; and 3,200 books and thousands of tapes in Urumqi,
the capital of Xinjiang in the country's far west. Wednesday, the
crackdown intensified, as police in at least 12 provinces raided
book dealers and destroyed hundreds of thousands of the group's
manuals.
</P>
<P>
   All this has U.S. adherents of Falun Gong worried. Practitioners
from around the country have gathered in Washington to exercise and
protest in front of the Chinese Embassy, hoping to avert a more
brutal crackdown, which they fear could include executions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got together here to try to let the whole world know about
the critical situation there,'' said Xiaohua Du, a student at
Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Practitioners say they are not angry about the crackdown _ Falun
Gong calls for an end to anger _ but they are sad and concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Participants from 30 states, including Yuan Li, will hold a news
conference in Washington today in front of the U.S. Capitol _
preceded and followed by rounds of Falun Gong exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Those who believe in Falun Gong maintain that the group is
neither religious nor political.
</P>
<P>
   But the sheer numbers of adherents are enough to prompt the
Chinese government to worry, said Yawei Liu, associate director of
the China Village Elections Project at the Atlanta-based Carter
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Liu, reached by telephone in China, said he thinks Falun Gong's
estimate of its numbers is wildly inflated. But he also thinks the
government's estimate is far too low.
</P>
<P>
   The group has grown so fast, Liu said, because it appeals to
those who feel weak and dispossessed, those ``who feel disgusted
with government policy or sort of feel insecure in society.''
</P>
<P>
   China, Liu said, has many such people. ``And once they get
organized, they could become a very viable political force.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that, despite denials of political aims by those
who practice Falun Gong, some people find the date of their large
protest _ April 25 _ to be significant. On that date in 1989, the
People's Daily ran an editorial describing students protests as a
riot, and the reaction helped fuel the massive protests that took
place that year in Tienanmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Han Park, director of the Center for the Study of Global Issues
at the University of Georgia, said the government is concerned,
too, because historically in China, changes in regime have been
fueled by religious movements. But he said Falun Gong is not an
organized movement, and he thinks the government erred in
attempting to suppress it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of crackdown will in fact facilitate the
cohesiveness of the sect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly is Falun Gong? Also called Falun Dafa, it is a new
school of qiqong, a traditional practice that uses exercise and
meditation in an effort to channel unseen forces to improve health,
mixed in with some tenets of Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   It was founded by Li Honhzhi, 47, a former grain bureau clerk
who now lives in America, and its growth around the world has been
fueled in part by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Li has said in an interview that he supports the protests by his
``students,'' and that the government, by outlawing Falun Gong,
threatens to lose the confidence of more than 100 million people.
</P>
<P>
   The practice consists of Tai Chi-like exercises and philosophies
urging the avoidance of anger, jealousy and hatred. Less mainstream
aspects include the belief that adherents have implanted in their
abdomens a Falun _ a law wheel, or miniature of the universe _
which spins and absorbs energy from the universe, and that the
practice can cure cancer.
</P>
<P>
   For all the fears of the Chinese government, adherents say they
are not in competition with the government and seek no political
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to improve ourselves,'' said Xueke Wang, a
software engineer from Duluth. ``We take our losses and gains
lightly. What they are pursuing is not what we are pursuing.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: falundafa.org/
</P>
<P>
   Don Melvin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
