<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BOYS-GIRLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOSTS BOYS, GIRLS NATION GUESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Draped in red, white, and blue and with a Boys
Nation badge pinned to his chest, Anthony Orlando sat awestruck in
the East Room of the White House Wednesday as he listened to
President Clinton speak about the nobility of public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``His presence just amazed me,'' said the 17-year-old from
Leominster, Mass. ``When he talked, he was so passionate. He just
grasped my attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando was in Washington this week, along with 200 other
students from all over the United States, as part of the American
Legion's Boys and Girls Nation. Two boys and two girls from each
state acted as senators, creating and voting on mock legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years ago, Clinton sat in the same room as part of
Boys Nation, listening to a similar speech by President John F.
Kennedy. Clinton then shook hands with Kennedy in the Rose Garden,
and the experience is said to have fueled Clinton's dreams of
becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Kennedy's sentiments, Clinton told the teenagers,
``America is a place that comes with great opportunity, but also
great responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Orlando said he does not think he'll ever run for
president, he said Clinton's speech made him feel less cynical
about politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that the president was in a sense just like
everyone else. He probably has the same problems we do and
sometimes worries about the same things,'' Orlando said. ``For some
reason, that makes me respect him and his office so much more.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the student senators debated topics such as gun
control, internet regulation, and US relations with China and
India. When Clinton was part of Boys Nation in 1963, he acted as a
senator from Arkansas and helped pass a mock civil rights bill, one
year before the actual Civil Rights Act passed in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The president told the students that Kennedy had congratulated
him and the other student senators who passed the mock legislation
for ``doing what real senators weren't able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting how the Civil Rights Act has created opportunities for
many women and minorities in America, Clinton told the students
they should hold similar foresights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gift of life doesn't always fall according to a rational
plan,'' Clinton told them. ``The great test is to make the most of
every day, but still sow the seeds for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Students from the New England area said their experience in
Washington has shed a positive light on the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have a cynical view of politics,'' said Jesse Lore,
17, of Londonderry, N.H. ``But when I was out there debating over
legislation, I realize that real senators must also argue with the
same kind of passion. That made me respect them more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has convinced me that public service is a
wonderfully noble thing,'' Orlando said. ``I definitely want to
serve my community is some way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily Gupta, 16, of Westborough, Mass., said she learned ``how
utterly difficult achieving bipartisanship is.''
</P>
<P>
   Gupta described herself as a liberal Democrat. ``There are some
issues I just can't be moderate on _ gun control, euthanasia,
abortion. Some things, it's hard to find a middle ground. Now I see
why Congress has so much trouble agreeing on anything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Carr, 17, of Westminster, Mass., said she used to
``shy away from politics because I didn't know how much of an
impact I would make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in Washington, listening to the president, meeting so
many other passionate people, makes me realize I have a voice and
this is something I can see myself doing,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
