<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. Kashmir policy may sway upcoming elections in India
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The two-month war in Kashmir has ensured the return of
India's last government in upcoming elections, a ranking Indian
Cabinet member said Wednesday. But if the polls were open today, he
joked, Bill Clinton just might be India's next prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Minister of Law Ram Jethmalani said Clinton has won millions of
new friends in India by acknowledging ``trespassing'' by Pakistan
and urging the withdrawal of fighters from the Indian side of the
cease-fire line in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has finally won the war is one single statement from your
president for which India will remain eternally grateful,''
Jethmalani said during a one-day stop in Atlanta. ``This kind of
forthright denunciation has never taken place. . . . (It) wipes out
years of a roller coaster ride. Clinton has struck a warm chord.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of three wars between India and Pakistan have been fought
over disputed land in Kashmir. Early this year, hundreds of Islamic
fighters seized Himalayan peaks on India's side of the cease-fire
line. In May, India launched a campaign to evict the guerrillas,
most of whom left after India and Pakistan agreed to halt fighting
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the United States has come to the aid of its Cold
War ally, Pakistan, Jethmalani said. But now that the Soviet threat
is gone, Pakistan's strategic value has diminished while India's
importance as the world's largest democracy has grown, he said.
Clinton's anti-Pakistan position on the conflict was a big feather
in India's cap, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the United States is totally free of the compulsions of
the Cold War,'' Jethmalani said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, also, there is a greater appreciation of the fact that
democracies must swim or sink together. Pakistan today is in a
shambles. It is a millstone around any friend's neck,'' he said,
referring to the rise of Islamic fundamentalism in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic, Jethmalani said, that Pakistan should be
responsible for bringing back to power India's Bharatiya Janata
Party, whose unwieldy coalition government collapsed in April from
lack of public support, forcing general elections this fall. The
BJP is known to have Hindu nationalist tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Previously-important domestic issues now are taking a backseat
to the victory in Kashmir, providing a big boost for the BJP. A
poll in Saturday's Times of India said most Indians _ 72 percent _
were satisfied with the government's handling of the conflict,
compared with only 21 percent who were unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paradoxically, the Pakistanis are the best friends of the
government they hate,'' Jethmalani said.
</P>
<P>
   Moni Basu writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
