<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CANCER-SOCIETY-59     07-28 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-SOCIETY-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER SOCIETY WITHDRAWS SPONSORSHIP FOR GROUP SUPPORTING STEM CELL
RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lobbying over the issue of human embryonic stem cell research
has generated so much controversy that the American Cancer Society
has withdrawn its sponsorship of Patients' Cure, a group founded to
publicize the medical benefits of stem cell research.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal occurred after Cardinal William Keeler of
Baltimore wrote the cancer society to urge it to reconsider its
position. Whether the letter influenced the society's decision is
in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, in at least one instance, pledges to the cancer
society to support breast cancer research were returned by a Roman
Catholic group, which told the society of its moral opposition to
stem cell research, a Catholic church official said.
</P>
<P>
   Human embryonic stem cells are derived from the surplus embryos
generated at in vitro fertilization clinics. The cells, which can
give rise to all kinds of human tissue, arouse strong emotions
among those opposed to abortion because human embryos must be
destroyed to obtain them.
</P>
<P>
   The National Conference of Catholic Bishops has lobbied Congress
not to allow federal money to be used for research on the cells,
fearing that the government would otherwise appear to approve of
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists hope that embryonic stem cells will serve as an
all-purpose repair kit for a variety of serious diseases, and
Patients' Cure, which began operating in May, is a coalition of
medical research groups that hopes to persuade Congress to let
embryonic stem cell research proceed under guidelines being devised
by the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer society, which receives more than $500 million a year
in public donations, was a part of the coalition until this month.
Daniel Perry, the chairman of Patients' Cure, said he was told that
the society ``wanted to take a lower profile,'' although it still
agreed that stem cell research should be financed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, they had had a protest at a fund-raiser,'' said
Perry, who has since dropped the cancer society's name from the
Patients' Cure list of sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal request did not come directly from the cancer
society but from Myrl Weinberg, president of the National Health
Council, a lobbying group in Washington. Ms. Weinberg did not cite
fund-raising problems, but rather pressure from the Roman Catholic
Church.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer society, she said, had received ``tremendous response
from people within the Catholic community expressing concern''
about stem cell research.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John R. Seffrin, chief executive of the Cancer Society,
``agreed to meet with a person high in the Catholic community,''
Ms. Weinberg said. After that meeting, she added, the society said
it wanted to take a lower public profile while it re-examined its
position on the research.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said he did not doubt Ms. Weinberg's authority to relay
the society's views because Seffrin also is the chairman of Ms.
Weinberg's organization.
</P>
<P>
   Seffrin was not available for comment. Greg Donaldson, the
Cancer Society's national vice president of public relations, said
the society had withdrawn from Patients' Cure because of a policy
disagreement and not because of pressure from the Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lent our name to Patients' Cure in May,'' Donaldson said,
adding that the intention was only to oppose general restrictions
on research and not for any specific position on stem cells, an
issue on which the society is still developing its views. ``It was
an error to allow them to represent our position on stem cell
research,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Perry said the position of Patients' Cure on stem cells had not
changed since it was founded.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said the Cancer Society and the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops had exchanged letters, but he denied that there
had been any suggestion that donations might be at risk. ``There
have been no threats made and no disruption of funds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Doerflinger, associate director for policy development
at the bishops conference, said he knew of an instance where
pledges for a breast cancer fund-raiser were returned after
families learned of the Cancer Society's support for stem cell
research. The families also met with members of the society's
Washington office, but the dispute over the pledges ``was not
something that we promoted,'' Doerflinger said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, letters were exchanged between Seffrin and Keeler,
chairman of the Committee for Pro-Life Activities at the bishops
conference, Doerflinger said. The letter from the cardinal asked
the Cancer Society to reconsider its position as a supporter of
federal funding for human embryonic stem cell research.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the letter had suggested that donations to the Cancer
Society might be at risk, Doerflinger said: ``No, I don't work that
way. We just argue the issue on its merits. Obviously, our goal is
not to reduce funds for cancer research.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry said other organizations in the Patients' Cure coalition
had come under pressure, but only the Cancer Society had withdrawn
its support. Publicly supported groups have difficulty taking sides
on controversial issues, Perry said, ``but I applaud those small
groups which are vulnerable to pressure for sticking by their
guns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
