u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-Q-AND-A-CO     07-28 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dan Reeves: `We'll get the job done'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The absence of All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson annoyed
Falcons coach Dan Reeves, although Reeves was smiling Wednesday
afternoon on the eve of his third training camp with the team.
Reeves answered several questions about defending the NFC
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where does this team stand compared with last season's team?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are some questions we didn't have this time last year _
replacing (wide receiver) Tony Martin (who was released), and if
Jamal doesn't come in, that becomes a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can this team replicate the chemistry it had last year? Does
Anderson's situation threaten that?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's something you don't have any control over. As far as our
chemistry here, we'll get the job done somehow. It certainly is a
distraction, though. People are focusing on why Jamal is not here,
what is happening with the contract _ all that rather than
preparing for (the season-opener with) Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can your staff do to help preserve that chemistry?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just bring in the right kind of people, the kind of people
who work hard and do the right things on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In Anderson's absence, who becomes the top running back?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're going to have to be careful with Byron Hanspard (who
missed last season with a serious knee injury), but he's close to
being 100 percent. (Second-year man) Ken Oxendine is the other guy
you have to look at, because he was there last year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can this team repeat as NFC West champion without Anderson?
Would there be sufficient confidence in the locker room to face a
much tougher schedule?
</P>
<P>
   A: If anything, you wonder if you've got enough talent to do it.
I think we have the kind of guys who know what it takes. It's all
about controlling your division. You still play very similar
schedules within the division. The bye (in the first week of the
playoffs) is very important to us because our last regular-season
game is on a Monday (at home against the 49ers). It would be a
short week (if the Falcons didn't get it).
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's sounds as though you're planning to make the playoffs,
even with the question at wide receiver, and the fact that Keith
Brooking will take over for leading tackler Cornelius Bennett at
weak-side linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   A: We feel much more comfortable that we've got somebody who can
step in for Cornelius (who was waived to save money.). There just
aren't many Tony Martin types out there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The closing of the Falcon Inn hotel necessitated the move of
training camp from team headquarters in Suwanee. Most NFL teams go
away for camp. Is this good or bad?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'd say being at home is the best scenario of all, but if you
have to be away, this is the best distance. Families can come up on
the players' day off. It's just a two-hour drive. And this is a
marvelous facility.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Any lasting effects from your open-heart surgery in December?
</P>
<P>
   A: I feel great, but I wish it was a lot cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
