<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons finding the good and bad of new camp
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ It's nice here where the Piedmont meets the
foothills of the Smoky Mountains, and the apartments Falcons
players are staying in during training camp are new. They even get
golf carts to get around.
</P>
<P>
   But there are drawbacks to moving camp from team headquarters in
Suwanee to here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every evening after meetings (in Suwanee) I would go home and
visit with my wife and daughter, which was just five minutes away
(in Duluth),'' said wide receiver Terance Mathis, who brought a TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a beautiful campus, and I think it's great some
people who normally wouldn't get to see us practice can.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to Furman, where the Falcons held training camp from
1971-78 before the Suwanee facility opened, was a must. The Falcon
Inn hotel _ where players lived during camp from 1979-98 _ closed
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no relief from the heat. It was 95 degrees
Wednesday, and more of the same is in store for the first practice
at 3 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule not fixed
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's midnight curfew was a loose one, as players
technically do not have to report until 9 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   There will be practices at 9:30 a.m. and 3:30 p.m. Friday. There
is tentatively an afternoon practice Saturday, but that could be
moved to morning, or there could be two practices.
</P>
<P>
   All practices, and the controlled practice with the Jacksonville
Jaguars on Aug. 7, will be open to the public. Sunday is a day off.
</P>
<P>
   Lend an arm
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons/Red Cross blood drive will be noon until 6 p.m. Aug.
6-7 at Akers Mill Square, Gwinnett Mall Corners and Southlake
Festival malls.
</P>
<P>
   Participants will receive a pair of tickets to the preseason
opener Aug. 13 against Detroit in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Field of fools
</P>
<P>
   The media played like media with bumbling errors, miserable
pop-ups and dubious baserunning in Wednesday's 5-0 loss to the
Falcons staff, perhaps the only shutout in slow-pitch softball
history.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
