<SLUG> BC-FAT-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE FAT, THEY'RE FINE AND THEY WANT THE WORLD TO KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAYCE T. ATAIYERO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Dana Stuart is fat. She's not overweight, plump, or
chubby, or any other euphemism meant to politely describe her large
frame. She's just fat. And she likes it that way.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a time when she couldn't bring herself to say the
f-word, like the time her parents enrolled her in Weight Watchers
at age 9 and she stood dwarfed by women who were fighting lifelong
battles with their weight. Or the time when her father forced her
to jog alongside the family car for exercise, frustrated with his
daughter's escalating size.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she says the word without shame or reservation. Fat.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a black mesh bodysuit with fuchsia feathers at the
wrists and her long red hair flowing down her back, she proudly
displayed the roundness of her form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm fat. So what? That doesn't mean that I have to be
miserable, that I have to wear a big polyester moo-moo and hate
myself,'' the 31-year-old Californian said Wednesday. ``If my fairy
godmother were to come and wisk away the pounds, sure I would
choose to be thin. But that's not going to happen, so I choose to
be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart is one of nearly 500 people who have flocked to
Framingham, Mass. this week for the 30th anniversary convention of
the National Association to Advance Fat Acceptance. Some were
fearlessly fat, sporting thong bikinis at a private pool party.
Others were slowly coming out of their shell, attempting to shed
years of self-consciousness and shame. NAAFA president Bettye
Travis said they had gathered for one purpose: to tell the world
that being fat is fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all taught to be ashamed of being fat. We were all
taught that fat people are stupid or worthless, but we aren't
buying that anymore,'' said Travis. ``No matter what your size, you
deserve respect. That is what we are hoping to get people to
realize, that being fat is not a crime. It's what we are and we are
proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association to Advance Fat Acceptance is a
Sacramento-based nonprofit organization dedicated to improving the
quality of life for fat people through education, advocacy, and
member support. The group's 4,000 members participate in regional
and national activities that work to affirm their self-worth and
dispel the negative connotations of being overweight. The last 30
years have brought about some progress, Travis said, but the
struggle against stereotyping and discrimination continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still fighting the fight of size discrimination. Things
have changed a bit but we still have people losing their jobs
because they are fat or kids who are taunted in class because of
their weight, so the battle rages on,'' she explained. ``I have two
young daughters who I fear will one day struggle with dieting and
it is for them that I do this the most, so that they can be
accepted for who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis said the hard part for most people who join the group is
coming to terms with the fact that they are overweight. This was
true for Jeanete DePattie, a 30-year-old marketing executive from
St. Louis who said she tried just about every weight-loss pill,
shake, and cream _ to no avail. When she finally decided to accept
her weight, she said she found an inner peace that had always
escaped her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always attached my self-worth to weight. Then I found
out that about 2 to 10 percent of those who diet keep the weight
off, which meant that I had a 2 to 10 percent chance of being
happy, and I wasn't willing to accept that,'' DePattie said.
``There was a sense of hopelessness that came with every diet and I
became fatter and more unhealthy each time. So I decided to just
eat what I want and exercise and try to be healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Ahlers, an exercise physiologist in Newton, said
people should not accept obesity and resign themselves to a
lifetime of medical complications as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excess weight brings about numerous increased health risks
such as diabetes, high blood pressure, and joint and orthopedic
complications, all of which can be reduced by losing weight,'' she
said. ``I don't believe that overweight people can't change their
metabolism through behavior modification and lose weight. I'm not
saying they are going to be thin, but they shouldn't just sort of
say, `I'm overweight and that's just how it has to be,' because
it's not true. It doesn't have to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues being discussed at the convention: the drive
for national legislation to make size discrimination a civil rights
violation. Michigan is the only state that has such legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Wann, publisher of FAT!SO? magazine, was host Wednesday
of a women-only Fat Body Art workshop that invited participants to
explore the joy of round forms by painting each other's nude
bodies. The idea, she said, is to help fat women see the beauty in
other fat women in hopes that they will realize the beauty in
themselves. Standing with her hot pink and turquoise hair and black
sandals, without a stitch of clothing covering her 5-foot-4,
270-pound frame, she said being fat gets more fun with each layer
of shame she sheds.
</P>
<P>
   She referred to the convention as a family reunion, saying that
fat people are rarely in a situation where they are in the
majority. She said the week is about fat liberation, fat pride, and
fat power, more than just acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people to come out as a fat person _ use the f-word. I
know it's scary but do it anyway,'' she said. ``People tell us to
lose weight but I say `What if we don't want to be thin? What if we
just want to be who were are?' I tell them that instead of going to
Jenny Craig and giving her $1,000, go buy a killer wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Wann added, ``I don't envy thin people. I don't see one walking
down the street and wonder why not me. I think they look great . .
. I think I look great too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 2020EDT &QL; 
