u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CALDWELL-BOS &LR;      07-28 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CALDWELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALDWELL WILL GO TO ARKANSAS FOR ACADEMIC POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Sarah Caldwell, founder and artistic director of the
Opera Company of Boston, has accepted an appointment as
distinguished professor at the University of Arkansas in
Fayetteville. She will head the opera department there.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell, now 75, founded the opera company in 1958 and during
the subsequent three decades made Boston an international operatic
capital, a center of both innovation and scholarly attention to
tradition. Because of the tangle of financial, legal, and
public-safety issues surrounding her theater, the Opera House on
Washington Street, Caldwell's company has been inactive since the
world premiere of Robert di Domenica's ``The Balcony'' in June
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Caldwell has repeatedly tried to revive her company,
whose strongest hope remains a project announced by the Theatre
Management Group Inc. in Houston, which has applied for permits to
restore and reopen the Opera House. (The local representative of
Theatre Management Group was not available for a progress report
Wednesday.) Caldwell recently sold her home in Lincoln and has
moved to an apartment near the Opera House. She is also house
hunting in Fayetteville.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in Fayetteville, Caldwell said, ``This new situation
will allow me to do some very interesting things; we will have
students of conducting and stage direction working alongside the
voice students, and we will be able to do productions. The fall
term opens August 23, and I will start hearing the singers then in
order to determine what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell is pleased to renew her association with a university
where her stepfather, Dr. Henry Alexander, served as professor of
government and political science, and where she briefly studied as
a psychology student. ``Another nice thing is that the chairman of
the music department, Stephen Gates, is a cellist who used to play
in the Opera Company Orchestra and toured with the American
National Opera Company when I ran that. There is also a wonderful
new chancellor of the university who seemed to want to do some of
the same things I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of her career, Caldwell chaired the opera
department at Boston University, and for years she hoped to make
the Opera Company of Boston a major center of operatic training,
and in fact many of the movers and shakers of today's operatic
world passed through its doors. She is writing a book about her
vision for opera, and she says, looks forward to the Arkansas
opportunity to put some of her educational ideas into practice.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell says she will continue her activity as principal guest
conductor of the Ural Philharmonic in Ekaterinburg, in Russia. In
the last few years she has also been involved in a project to
transcribe and publish 72 ancient Chinese and Japanese musical
scrolls that were discovered in the 1970s. In September, she will
be in Cambridge, England, to record and film some of this music.
The pipa virtuoso Wu Man, who appeared at Tanglewood this week, is
also involved in the project and will participate in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell was unaware of any change in the status of plans to
reopen the Opera House. ``There was one legal problem still to
resolve, but I think everything there was proceeding nicely. I
would not be sitting here in Fayetteville if I thought the job
would interfere with the work I am planning for Boston. My new job
is a very interesting and important thing to be doing, and it
allows my work in Russia, in England, and in Boston to continue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
