<HEADER>
A7631 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE-2T     07-28 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CHALLENGES TO NASDAQ LOOM LARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During the past year, Frank G. Zarb, chairman of the
National Association of Securities Dealers, has struck deals to buy
the American Stock Exchange, forged alliances with three overseas
bourses and promised investors 24-hour access to the Nasdaq stock
market. And at an NASD board meeting Thursday, Zarb will present
his plan for making the Nasdaq market a for-profit, publicly held
company separate from its regulatory unit.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Zarb has been busy. But has he been effective?
</P>
<P>
   This question is being raised by people both inside and outside
the NASD following the flurry of activity. As the Nasdaq stock
market faces increased competition from well-capitalized private
companies running electronic communications networks, or ECNs, the
effectiveness of the NASD chairman is more crucial than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what Zarb is trying to do,'' said Patrick J. Healy,
president of the Issuer Network, a company in Chevy Chase, Md.,
that advises public companies on where they should list their
shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think their ability to get these things running smoothly
is less than stellar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges to the NASD certainly loom large. The business of
who facilitates investors' securities trading and ensures that the
participants abide by the rules is up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   As for Zarb, he argues that the NASD is setting the pace. ``I
think we're leading the parade,'' he said. ``Not everybody always
agrees with me. I think we've responded to events and maybe even
gotten a little ahead of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But he will have to run faster and faster just to keep up. New
competitors are entering the business almost weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Any moves the NASD may want to make are hindered by its
considerable infrastructure. By definition, an entity that is both
a market and a regulator to thousands of brokerage firms across the
nation cannot be as nimble as startups with no regulatory
obligations. ``It's like dealing with the old AT&AMP;T,'' said Alan
Davidson, president of the Independent Broker-Dealer Association.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons an offering of stock in Nasdaq is compelling
is that some of the proceeds would be used to fund the regulatory
unit, which would be spun off.
</P>
<P>
   Frank E. Baxter, chairman of Jefferies &AMP; Co., a brokerage firm
based in Los Angeles and a NASD board member, concedes there are
challenges. ``I think that events externally and internally are
moving extremely rapidly,'' Baxter said. ``We have a large
battleship, and it's going to take a tremendous amount of will to
get where we should be. I feel confident that the board and the
membership has that will.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the captain of this battleship, the pace of
change in the industry poses a greater threat to Nasdaq than to its
archrival, the New York Stock Exchange, which announced its own
plans to go public last week. Trading on ECNs now accounts for 30
percent of Nasdaq stock market volume; every trade that takes place
on an electronic network is one less trade handled by a Nasdaq
market maker firm. Electronic networks trade less than 5 percent of
New York Stock Exchange volume.
</P>
<P>
   While electronic networks do not represent a total loss for the
NASD _ trades executed on a network can still produce revenues for
Nasdaq in the form of fees for using its Selectnet system or small
order execution system. But the 30 percent of volume traded on ECNs
definitely hurts the large brokerage firms that make markets in
Nasdaq stocks. These firms are one of Zarb's biggest and most
powerful constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   And if electronic networks become exchanges where companies can
list their shares, this will cut into the fees Nasdaq receives from
companies whose stocks it trades. These charges accounted for 19
percent of the NASD's $739.5 million in revenues last year.
</P>
<P>
   Those who worry about whether the NASD is slipping behind say
that Zarb has great vision, but that his ability to follow through
quickly on plans is not up to the same standard.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, Zarb is coming under fire from members of the
American Stock Exchange, which merged with the NASD last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis D. Lowenfels, a former member of the Amex board, advised
the exchange's floor brokers on the NASD merger. On Wednesday, he
said: ``There is widespread dissatisfaction amongst Amex floor
members with the failure of Nasdaq to fulfill some of the promises
they made to induce the merger. I think it's important that Nasdaq
management begin to address these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the promises was an aggressive sales team that would
deliver at least 100 new companies to list their shares on the Amex
in the first quarter of this year. In reality, only 40 new
companies had listed as of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Zarb acknowledged that the initial goal was too optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time ever where we're combining the
specialist system with the multimarket-maker system _ giving
issuers the choice,'' he said. ``We're redefining that process as
we go along. Given six months, our report card is pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   A new team has been formed at the Amex to attract listings.
</P>
<P>
   Salvatore F. Sodano, chief operating officer at the NASD is
overseeing the Amex merger. He called the complaints ``a lot of
big-time baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're not hearing about are all the other things we've
done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited several examples, including a huge investment in
technology that has brought down the number of system failures on
the floor, a sales effort to bring more corporate bonds and foreign
issues to list on the exchange, and the development of 27 new types
of derivatives to be traded on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another area of concern is the inability of the NASD to bring to
fruition its proposal for a centralized customer order system that
would allow investors to meet without the interference of a dealer,
as they increasingly do now on ECNs. The proposal has languished
ever since going to the SEC for approval 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   That stalemate is a testament to one of Zarb's biggest
challenges _ the warring factions that make up the NASD Large
market maker firms, afraid that a central limit order book would
cut into the profits they made executing customers' trades in
Nasdaq stocks, objected to the plan with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   With Zarb unable to overcome the opposition, the NASD is now in
the position of scrambling to keep up with electronic networks. And
to add insult to injury, some of the same firms that objected to
the central order book concept are now investors in the networks.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One of the matters that will come before the board at Thursday's
meeting is an improved version of the limit order book.
</P>
<P>
   In response, owners of small firms are becoming increasingly
vocal in their criticism of the NASD, arguing that it is too
ossified and bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't appear to know how to run a business,'' said
Davidson of Zeus Securities. ``They have lost 23 percent of their
membership in 10 years and 30 percent of Nasdaq business to ECNs.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Zarb is hoping that turning Nasdaq into a for-profit
company will help him align the fractious constituencies that make
up the NASD by giving them a common interest in the form of a
profit motive. The deal will bring together people who today mostly
look at things separately as ``investors, vendors, issuers and
market makers big and small,'' he said. ``That in itself will give
a common interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
