<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-JOBCUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ TO CUT UP TO 8,000 JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. said it will cut between 6,000 and 8,000
jobs, close more facilities and take a third-quarter charge of up
to $900 million as part of its latest restructuring campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing its plans Wednesday, the Houston-based personal
computer maker declined to say how many of its 11,000 employees in
New England will lose their jobs or say which units will be
targets.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts come on top of a layoff of 17,000 employees tied to
Compaq's $9.1 billion purchase of Digital Equipment Corp. of
Maynard, Mass. last year.
</P>
<P>
   But since then Compaq has been struggling with falling personal
computer prices and a shift to direct sales over the Internet. The
additional cuts are needed as part of an effort to reduce costs by
$2 billion a year, said Compaq's new chief executive, Michael
Capellas.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to announce more specifics by Aug. 15,
Capellas said, and to complete the bulk of the layoffs by the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq had previously warned of more cuts but hadn't cited
specific numbers before Wednesday, when it reported its
second-quarter results.
</P>
<P>
   For the three months ended June 30, Compaq said it lost $184
million, or 10 cents per diluted share, on revenue of $9.4 billion.
Revenue grew by 17 percent on a pro forma basis over the combined
revenues of Compaq and Digital for the same period a year ago,
Compaq said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq blamed the loss on rising expenses, and on tight profit
margins stemming from fierce competitors like Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in some of the company's service-related business lines
also grew at a ``disappointing'' rate, Capellas said.
</P>
<P>
   But overall the results met Wall Street's expectations, and
analysts seemed to approve of the plans for more cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they might have done differently,'' said
J.P. Morgan Securities analyst Daniel R. Kunstler. ``We have to
trust them for better execution than they have had in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Compaq moved quickly to announce its decision, said
Wasserstein Parella analyst Stephen Dube. ``Probably the best thing
I can say about Mr. Capellas so far is that he does seem much more
a man of action than the prior characters at Compaq,'' Dube said,
referring to former Compaq chief executive Eckhard Pfeiffer.
Pfeiffer was removed in April after a series of financial
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, Dube said, ``I think things are going to happen
fast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq employs about 70,000 people worldwide. Of the 17,000
layoffs previously announced, it has completed 15,250, Capellas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's New England work force includes about 7,000 in
Massachusetts, including many members of its services division, and
about 4,000 people in New Hampshire. In May Compaq said it would
shut a Salem, N.H., factory that once employed 900.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq announced its results after the close of trading. Prior
to that, shares rose 9/16 to close at 25 15/16 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
