<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVITY DOWN AS INVESTORS AWAIT KEY ECONOMIC REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Computer-related stocks lifted the Nasdaq market to
its second straight gain Wednesday, even as a majority of other
issues sagged. Activity slackened as investors braced for key
economic reports from Washington Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market is waiting for some heavy-duty data,'' said
Christine A. Callies, chief investment strategist at CS First
Boston, mainly to examine the date for any signs of inflation that
might persuade Fed policymakers to raise short-term interest rates
again.
</P>
<P>
   Although Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, made his
second congressional appearance in two weeks Wednesday, he provided
no fresh clues about the central bank's intentions on interest
rates, and members of Congress concentrated their questions on the
wisdom of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, market operators are now awaiting Thursday's Labor
Department's survey of employment costs and the Commerce
Department's first estimate of gross domestic product, both
covering the quarter ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is sort of slip-sliding around here'' except for a
``relief'' rally in high technology, said Robert H. Stovall,
president of Stovall/21st Advisers. After skidding four of six
sessions for a loss of 245 points, the tech-dominated Nasdaq
composite index has now posted back-to-back gains for the first
time since mid-month.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's bounce of of 26.51 points, or just under 1 percent,
was aided by a decision by the Financial Accounting Standards Board
to postpone tougher rules for writing off research-and-development
costs in acquisitions, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dow Jones industrial average could not sustain its
Monday advance and finished with a loss of 6.97 points, closing at
10.972.07, after having been ahead by as many as 45.
</P>
<P>
   And the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index, while eking out a
gain of about two-tenths of 1 percent, showed little strength apart
from technology. Falling components outnumbered rising ones by 277
to 203, with 20 stocks unchanged. The index closed up 2.56 points
at 1,365.40.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates were little changed Thursday as the Treasury's
$15 billion auction of two-year notes went smoothly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Stocks highly sensitive to interest rates have been prominent
among those making new 52-week lows, Stovall noted, reflecting
fears of narrowed margins and dampened business. New lows overall
swamped new highs 134-54 Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange,
where 1,602 issues fell and 1,374 rose.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover eased to 690.96 million shares from 714.6 million
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the general lackluster mood did not keep speculative-minded
investors from chasing the latest Internet IPO. Drugstore.com's 5
million shares were offered at 18, began trading at 65 and changed
hands at 70 before closing at 50\ on volume of 8.86 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Intel was once again a market star, rising 2} to 70 5/16 after a
4 11/16-point surge on Tuesday as chip prices were reported to have
firmed and S G Cowen raised its rating from ``neutral'' to ``buy.''
Volume climbed to 41.7 million shares from 39 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Other big high-tech winners included Texas Instruments, up 5
7/16 to 148 9/16; Broadcom, up 11] to 128; Micron Technology, up 3~
to 61}; Microsoft, up 1 3/16 to 90; Priceline.com up 11 11/32 to
85, and Ebay and Amazon.com up 5] and 4}, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer edged up 9/16 to 25 15/16; after the close the
company, the biggest maker of personal computers reported a
second-quarter loss that was in line with analysts' forecasts and a
restructuring to cut costs that will result in the loss of 8,000
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Dow blue chips, Dupont gained 11/16 to 72 13/16 after
reporting earnings at the top end of expectations and IBM gained 2[
to 128]. Exxon and Mobil each rose more than a point.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, stocks were moderately higher in Tokyo, Hong Kong and
Britain, slightly higher in Germany and France and down by
four-tenths of 1 percent in Brazil. Mexico and Toronto jumped 1.43
percent and 1.26 percent, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
