<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arsenal tires of prima donna striker
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ceremonial start of the English season might be tempered a
bit Saturday as Manchester United and Arsenal meet at Wembley
Stadium in the Charity Shield friendly match. The clubs who
finished just a point apart at the top of the Premier League will
put most of their best players forward a week before the official
schedule gets under way _ with two notable exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Brooding 20-year-old French striker Nicolas Anelka's summer-long
melodrama took a new twist Tuesday when Arsenal took him off the
transfer list and ordered him to report to training camp. He is
bunkered somewhere in Paris, blaming his absence on ``depression.''
While scoring 17 goals for the Gunners, Anelka complained
repeatedly about life in London, the British press and teammates
not passing the ball enough to him. His growing legion of handlers
decided to milk his unhappiness for all they could.
</P>
<P>
   United captain Roy Keane is balking at the club's $13 million
offer to extend a contract that expires after the coming season.
The Irish midfielder wants $16 million to remain with United, which
is the league, FA Cup and European champion, and is expected to
work things out in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Anelka saga, however, is setting new lows for ugliness and
greed, worse than Ronaldo's protracted move from Barcelona to Inter
Milan in 1997. After Arsenal offered Anelka to Italian Serie A
runner-up Lazio for $35 million, matching the second-largest
transfer on record, his two brother ``advisers'' demanded a weekly
wage of $96,000 for the player. That's an amount that even the
high-spending Roman club, which has forked out $160 million in the
transfer market over the last two years, had a hard time
swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   It's an astonishing demand for a player who has had just one
good professional season. Lazio, which needs scoring help after
packing Christian Vieri off to Inter for a world record $50
million, isn't giving up hope, despite Arsenal's action. ``It was
not a surprise for us,'' said Anelka's attorney, Marc Roget, who
won the Bosman case in 1995 that opened up European free-agency.
``We have no reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Anelka's future ex-teammates did. ``None of us could care
less,'' midfielder Ray Parlour told The Daily Telegraph on
Wednesday. ``I've forgotten about the bloke. Whether he plays in
the first team again will be very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico slips up against Egypt
</P>
<P>
   Egypt scored twice in the final 12 minutes, including the
equalizer from Samir Ibrahim in the 85th minute, to draw 2-2 with
host Mexico on Tuesday in the Confederations Cup. Mexico is all but
assured of a spot in the second round, but the other qualifier from
Group A is up for grabs. Bolivia and Saudi Arabia tied 0-0 in the
other half of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Tabloid loses libel suit
</P>
<P>
   Britain's largest daily newspaper, Rupert Murdoch's tabloid The
Sun, was ordered on Wednesday to pay $134,900 in damages and
$793,800 in attorneys' fees to former Liverpool goalkeeper Bruce
Grobbelaar. The British High Court ruled in the goalkeeper's favor
in his libel suit against the newspaper, which alleged in 1994 that
Grobbelaar was paid $75,000 to help Liverpool lose a match against
Newcastle. Grobbelaar and three other men were acquitted in London
on charges two years ago that they assisted an Asian gambling
syndicate. He was suspended for wagering on soccer matches but
denied betting against his own team. The Sun is appealing the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers seek bigger stage
</P>
<P>
   The Glasgow Rangers' dominance of the domestic scene in Scotland
figures to be secure once again this year, but they have more
continental ambitions. Rangers, who won the league, Scottish Cup
and League Cup crowns, have added depth in their bid to prosper in
Europe, where they have only one trophy _ the 1972 Cup Winners'
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been building a squad simply to play in the
Scottish Premier League,'' chairman David Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   League season begins Friday, but Rangers got their European
Champions League campaign off to a strong start Wednesday in
routing FC Haka of Finland 4-1. American midfielder Claudio Reyna,
signed late last season, started and had an assist. The draw has
been unkind to Rangers, however, with a second-round series against
UEFA Cup champions Parma on tap if they advance.
</P>
<P>
   MLS: Revs get Graziani
</P>
<P>
   Ecuadorian striker Ariel Graziani, a prime MLS target all year,
has been allocated to the New England Revolution, which certainly
isn't opposed to having him. It's just that the Revs could use a
central defender more. Player-coach Walter Zenga had been pursuing
Ghanaian defender Joseph Addo, but Graziani took up the remaining
foreign-player slot in MLS. . . . Commissioner Doug Logan will meet
with German sweeper Lothar Matthaus during the Confederations Cup
this week to consider his desire to play in the league. Matthaus,
38, has expressed an interest in leaving Bayern Munich to play for
the woeful MetroStars next season. The U.S. team is looking for its
second win of the year over Germany in Guadalajara on Friday. . . .
The MetroStars might be bad _ 5-13, second-worst record in the
league _ but they're never boring. Newly signed Serbian forward
Sasha Curcic arrived at Giants Stadium for his first game Saturday
with his head shaved and declared, ``I am your Dennis Rodman.'' No
signs of tattoos or a wedding dress, however. . . . Raul Diaz Arce,
second in career goals and points in Major League Soccer, suited up
for his fourth team in the league last weekend after being traded
from San Jose to Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
