<HEADLINE>
ABC NEWS WANTS TO BE THE PLACE TO BE FOR NEW YEAR'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ If Peter Jennings had any dreams of ringing
in the year 2000 at some exotic hideaway, far from all the
carousing and the Y2K frenzy, he's not saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent some time convincing my wife that Times Square is
the place to be for New Year's Eve 2000,'' Jennings said Wednesday
by satellite hookup from New York. It's not because he doesn't like
to travel. It's because he has to work Dec. 31, and he'll be
working from ABC's new studio now under construction at 1500
Broadway near Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings will anchor ``ABC 2000,'' a 22-hour overview of New
Year's celebrations and millennium-related events around the world.
Starting at 3 a.m. Pacific time on Friday, Dec. 31, and continuing
until 1 a.m. New Year's Day, the live broadcast shapes up as the
most ambitious cooperative venture of its kind. With the assistance
of broadcast partners in 60 countries, ABC says it plans to be the
place to be for news of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   To those who would argue that the new millennium doesn't begin
until Jan. 1, 2001, Jennings says: ``As this has been the century
of the common man, I think we have all just increasingly begun to
defer to the common man's instinct that the turnover date is
2000.'' Though he intellectually accepts the argument that the
current millennium has a year to go, he said the momentum in favor
of celebrating the new millennium prematurely is unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I confess,'' Jennings said, ``that that train is not one which
I would like to stand in front of.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Gibson and Diane Sawyer, who have been ``subbing'' as
co-anchors of ``Good Morning America'' while ABC tries to figure
out if there's a potential morning team out there that has similar
star power and can keep ``GMA'' out of the ratings Dumpster, are
signed to their indefinite assignment at least through next May.
</P>
<P>
   But Gibson adds: ``There's this funny situation where David
Westin calls us in, and he has extraordinary persuasive powers, and
he says, `Well, would you mind just extending for ...?' And we say,
`OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Westin, the president of ABC News, is completely vague
about how long Gibson and Sawyer will stay at ``GMA.'' ``The
long-term plan is to have the right people on the program in all
the positions,'' he said Wednesday, ``and Diane and Charles have
been gracious enough to give us as much time as we need to identify
the right people and groom them and introduce them to the audience.
... We'll know when we have it right, (but) we're not prepared to
make that transition now and I don't have a certain date in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   _ We all know Oscar winner Kathy Bates can act. But can she
sing? Producer Craig Zadan was wondering the same thing when
Broadway veteran Victor Garber suggested Bates for the role of the
heartless Miss Hannigan in a new ``Wonderful World of Disney''
production of ``Annie,'' due on ABC next season.
</P>
<P>
   Garber, who plays Daddy Warbucks in the film, appeared with
Bates in the film ``Titanic'' and knew she was ``dying to do a
musical,'' as Zadan tells it. ``The next thing we knew we had a
meeting,'' Zadan said, ``and wait unil you hear her sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates, who until now has confined her vocal performances to
shower stalls and automobiles, taught herself to play the guitar
and sing when she moved to New York in 1970. She actually sold a
song to Milos Forman for his film, ``Taking Off,'' but because she
couldn't read music and lacked formal voice training, she felt she
didn't belong in the musical milieu.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I put all my eggs in one basket and went into the acting
aspect of it,'' she said. ``But I was a bit frustrated all these
years and I kept thinking, `Oh, you know, one of these days I'd
really do it.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
