<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7648 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SMITH-HNS     07-28 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SMITH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
WICHITA FALLS _ Emmitt Smith showed up at Cowboys camp Wednesday as
the NFL's active career rushing leader thanks to Barry Sanders'
surprise retirement earlier that morning.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smith, who arrived here one day before the mandatory reporting
date for veterans, was stunned upon hearing the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're joking,'' Smith said. ``That's got to be a joke. I
don't buy it just yet, because the man has many, many, many years
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can sympathize with the man's situation over there. He's
been everything Detroit wants, but has Detroit been everything he's
needed? Probably not. So frustration and a lot of disappointment
are on his side.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders amassed 15,269 career rushing yards in 10 seasons with
the Lions, just 1,457 shy of Walter Payton's 13-year record of
16,726. Considering his average per season topped 1,500 yards,
Sanders might well have reached the mark this year, making the
retirement that much more shocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, dealing with coming back into training camp, dealing
with the organization maybe not putting in place what they need to
put in place in order for them to have a successful team, he's
probably had enough,'' Smith said. ``It's been 10 years for him.
They had 10 years to do what they committed to doing _ and that's
putting together a team that allowed them to win _ and they've
failed to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot put myself in his position. I've been fortunate
enough and blessed by God to be put in an organization that's been
committed to winning and has won and has brought in some players to
keep it going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Dickerson (13,259) and Tony Dorsett (12,739) stand between
Sanders and Smith, who is in fifth place on the all-time list with
12,566 yards over nine seasons. And it will now be Smith who has
the most immediate chance to dethrone Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has topped the 1,000-yard mark in every year but his
rookie season and, despite turning 30 this year, says retirement is
nowhere in the picture right now. He needs 4,161 yards to become
No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm far from retirement,'' Smith said. ``I think last year was
the first year I've completed a complete season feeling healthy. I
look forward to what we have this year.''
</P>
<P>
   With Sanders out of the picture, all eyes will be on Smith, but
that's not the way the Cowboys star wants to etch his name in the
record books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a selfish person would look at it that way,'' says Smith,
whose words reflect his disbelief at Sanders' retirement. ``I want
to see it happen (Sanders breaking the record). He's got an
excellent opportunity. He could do it this year. It would be
exciting to watch and be part of history, knowing that I was in the
same time frame, being able to watch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And hopefully, someday, my time would come. That's all I want,
my chance to come, whether it be Walter, or whether it be Barry. I
just want my chance to come someday.''
</P>
<P>
   However, at 31, Sanders likely could have played for several
more seasons and put the record out of Smith's reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Barry would have been the first back to actually break
the 20,000 barrier,'' Smith said. ``I actually believe that. He had
many, many years in front of him. This is a very unfortunate
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is only temporary. Maybe he'll reconsider and come
back. Maybe they might trade him away. Who knows? It's sad for the
NFL, because they're losing one of the best backs they've ever had
in the game _ and at a young age. He's walking away like Jim Brown
(No. 6 on the all-time list) walked away (after nine seasons).''
</P>
<P>
   Considering Sanders had four years left on a six-year, $36
million contract, Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin said his
retirement proves not all players are greedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should tell a lot of people that it's not just about
money,'' Irvin said. ``You underestimate the power of just winning.
Barry has great things in front of him. Probably, if he just plays
and is 75 percent of the man he was in the past, there are so many
things he can accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's saying that even if he's playing at 100 percent, and
Lord knows that's been great, it's not going to help that team win.
The most important thing is winning. That tells you the kind of
person he is. He's got money on the table, and he says it's not
about it. It's about winning. That's why you play the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmitt has three Super Bowl rings. That's the key. I can
guarantee you this: Barry would switch with Emmitt any day of the
week. That's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Sanders return if he could play elsewhere? Smith said he
would love to see the league office step in and force Detroit to
make a trade if it would bring Sanders back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the league should step in, because you're losing
basically the cornerstone of the National Football League,'' Smith
said. ``There have been only four guys to rush for over 2,000
yards. He's one of those guys. He's been a stand-up individual for
the National Football League for 10 years. He's been committed and
helped the National Football League for 10 years, been a bright
spot in that organization for 10 years. The man deserves to be on a
winning team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not management. I can't force that decision. I can't
make that move. If he decides to leave the game, it's his choice.
The only thing I can say is I wish he wouldn't at the present
moment, because I would love to see him break the record. I would
love to see that happen. And I wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees with Smith, especially if a trade might mean
seeing Sanders with a division rival such as Washington, which made
offseason inquiries about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it, but if the NFL steps in to try to help Barry
no,'' Irvin said. ``Don't send him to the East. I love Barry, but
he either plays in Detroit, or don't play. Don't let him come to
Washington. Washington has all those draft picks that might get
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to run over to Jerry's (Jones) office today to throw
a red flag on this. Don't bring him to the East. There are a lot of
great guys who haven't had a chance to win a championship. I wish
he had, and I hope he does, but it has to be in Detroit. Don't let
him come to the East.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, all his friends can do is support Sanders _ or maybe
beg a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on back,'' Smith pleaded. ``Come on back. Don't let me
end up being the Lone Ranger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
