<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDY-ALA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giuliani courts Alabama cash
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM _ It was nice while it lasted.
</P>
<P>
   That's clearly what New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was
thinking Wednesday afternoon soon after beginning a press
conference smack in the middle of a busy day of fund-raising all
over Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the international press corps and the joviality that
had greeted him Tuesday in Little Rock, onetime home of first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton. Gone, too, was Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee
to toss around funny gifts and most of the more humorous barbs at
the expense of Clinton, Giuliani's likely Democratic foe in the
2000 Senate race in New York.
</P>
<P>
   One day later, nobody was having quite as much fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't (ITAL) imagine (END ITAL) we're spending so much time
on this,'' Giuliani said exasperatedly at the end of an
increasingly cantankerous exchange with several New York reporters
about his seemingly spur-of-the-moment decision Tuesday morning to
order the Arkansas state flag flown above City Hall in Manhattan.
The Democratic speaker of New York's City Council didn't like that
decision, and the much smaller press contingent that trailed
Giuliani in Alabama made sure he knew about it.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they made sure he knew the one-word description a White
House official used to characterize Giuliani's two-day southern
fund-raising swing: ``Goofy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine why the White House would be interested in
that,'' Giuliani said, displaying only a flicker of the smile that
had flashed so broadly for much of the day in Arkansas. ``I don't
think I'll comment on that except to raise the question of what's
the White House doing commenting on this unless they're running
somebody's campaign from the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what else needed to be said?
</P>
<P>
   The New York race, should Giuliani and Clinton both officially
enter it, is serious business. Doubtless that is why the mayor of
New York sped from Little Rock to New Orleans on Tuesday night for
a fund-raiser. After dinner and a stroll in the French Quarter,
Giuliani decamped to Huntsville, where a morning visit to the
Marshall Space Flight Center was about the only break in a day
packed with meetings and three separate $1,000-per-person
fund-raisers in Huntsville, Tuscaloosa and Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani spokesman Bruce Teitelbaum predicted the two-day trip
would raise between $150,000 and $175,000, all of which will come
in handy if, as is widely predicted, New York Rep. Rick Lazio
decides to challenge Giuliani in a Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a Clinton-Giuliani race everyone seems to want in
Alabama. The Alabama fund-raisers all were arranged by Tuscaloosa
real estate developer Stan Pate, who says it is Giuliani's ideas,
not his opponent, that most interest him.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to defeat Team Clinton apparently would just be a bonus.
``I do not admire the first lady or the first family,'' Pate said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Big Sky Bread Co. in nearby Mountain Brook, meanwhile,
everybody seemed to have something to say about New York's 2000
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is making this into a national election,'' said
Birmingham schoolteacher Helen Milteer, 30. ``This could only
happen in New York, or California.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone in the place seemed to prefer Giuliani _ ``If
that's what he's coming for, money, more power to him,'' said Joyce
Wohn.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton did have at least one supporter. ``I want Hillary to
come down here, too, because she's kind of a celebrity,'' said Big
Sky's owner, Jeff Pierce. ``I mean, this is fun, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Just as long as he didn't say goofy.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
