<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPRESSION-WALK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walking 1,000 miles in mental health advocate's shoes
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost every day for the past three months, someone has stopped
Stuart Perry on the road, wanting to talk about depression.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, when he left his hometown of Americus, Ga., Perry has
walked on back roads all the way to Chicago _ 1,000 miles _ talking
about depression to anyone who would listen.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, 40, who has recovered from a major depression, began his
trek to educate people about the devastating illness and to give
hope about treatment. Step by step, his ``Journey for Life'' has
pounded away at the stigma that surrounds mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   And today, Perry will deliver thousands of petitions collected
along the journey to the American Medical Association headquarters
in Chicago, urging the nation's doctors to screen their patients
routinely for depression, which strikes an estimated 18 million
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum has grown along the route. Perry has spoken in
</P>
<P>
   his down-to-earth manner to churches, rallies and rotary clubs.
He has done interviews with more than 75 newspapers, TV and radio
stations. He has appeared on call-in shows, was honored at
Louisville, Ky.'s Churchill Downs racetrack and met the inventor of
Prozac, the anti-depressant that Perry credits with saving his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Did he have doubts about covering 1,000 miles ? ``I knew I'd
make it,'' Perry said. ``If you've been clinically depressed, this
is a breeze.''
</P>
<P>
   It has meant covering 15 to 25 miles a day, seven days a week,
with only two days off, when he rested in bed. ``I didn't miss a
mile,'' Perry said. He adds, laughing: ``I have a heck of a tan.''
</P>
<P>
   He's working on his fifth pair of sneakers. He has survived a
close call with a Tennessee rattlesnake (``It scared me to
death''), an infected toe and a car of kids throwing bottles at
him, trying to run him down (``I jumped into a ditch''). Over the
last few days, as he was winding up the journey, the Midwestern
heat index hit triple digits.
</P>
<P>
   Friends accompanying Perry have kept his spirits high. Donations
have ranged from two Fleetwood motor coaches, grants from drug
manufacturers, to home-cooked meals along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly changed lives here,'' said Jill Kartisek of the
Mental Health Association of Northern Kentucky. Through his
interviews, she says, Perry reached an unusually high number of
males, who showed up at depression screenings, or sought
information about depression.
</P>
<P>
   One couple heard him on a talk show, then followed him on the
road, helping him plant a tree in Kokomo, Ind. ``They lost their
son to suicide,'' says Perry, whose father killed himself 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Perry also visited a state hospital for the mentally ill in
Kentucky. ``He gave hope to those people _ that you can come out on
the other side with a life that has meaning and productivity,''
said Margaret Pennington, commissioner of Kentucky's department of
mental health and mental retardation.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with the AMA, Perry will return to his family and
Americus, where he plans to help run a counseling center. He's
thinking about another walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it,'' he said. ``I don't know where I'm going,
but I'm going somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
