</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLARK-RETIRE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION OFFICIALS DEFEND DECISION TO SPEED UP CLARK'S
RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The president's top security adviser on Wednesday
defended the decision to speed up the retirement of the NATO
supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, by a few months to make way
for his intended replacement, insisting it did not signal any
displeasure with the general's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Clark is a superb commander,'' said Sandy Berger, the
national security adviser to the president. ``The president has the
highest degree of confidence in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Secretary of Defense William Cohen chose Gen.
Joseph Ralston, the vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, as
his candidate to succeed Clark as the next head of U.S. forces in
Europe and NATO commander.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said on Wednesday that moving Ralston
to the prestigious NATO post was the Pentagon's primary motive.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston is required by law to leave his current post next
February, because he will have served the maximum four years. That
timetable in turn led to the decision to ask Clark to vacate his
post a few months early. He had been scheduled to retire next
summer when his extended term expired.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Clark was taken aback by the suddenness of
the decision to have him retire in April or May, a message relayed
to him by telephone on Tuesday while he was traveling.
</P>
<P>
   ``His assumption was that he would remain as long as he was
doing a good job,'' said a NATO official who asked not to be
identified. ``This came sooner than expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Several officials felt compelled to dismiss any notion that
Clark's many disagreements with the Pentagon and other NATO member
nations during the Kosovo air war may have contributed to this
decision. Clark urged a more aggressive bombing campaign and asked
the Pentagon for speedier deployment of equipment and troops.
</P>
<P>
   His insistence that NATO prepare for the possibility of a ground
war was at odds with the administration, which did not want to
pursue a ground invasion that would be publicly unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   Officials went to great lengths on Wednesday to downplay that
friction, and turn the spotlight on the promotion of Ralston.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright joined on
Wednesday in praising Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done an outstanding job in serving this capacity as
commander of the European forces and supreme allied commander,``
Cohen said at a news conference in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, met with senior military commanders, including Clark, in
Tampa, Fla., but nothing was said to Clark about his impending
early retirement, several officials at the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, when Shelton telephoned Clark who was on an official
visit to Lithuania, to tell him the news, Clark was upset that he
had not been told in Florida, according to a NATO official.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Shelton said the chairman had telephoned Clark
as soon as the final decision was made over the weekend and Ralston
had agreed to become a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said on Wednesday that he considered the action part of a
routine change of command. ``When a soldier's journey is over, it's
over,'' he said in Vilnius, Lithuania, according to the Baltic News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon and on Capitol Hill, reaction to Clark's early
retirement was muted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is much ado about very little here,'' said Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, who opposed the air war, but is
close to Clark. ``I don't think this is in any way a slap at
General Clark. It's not unusual to make a two- or three-month
adjustment in someone's tour to accommodate another officer.''  &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lawmakers and officers praised Ralston, 55. ``Joe Ralston will
be very good,'' said Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., who is on the
House Armed Services Committee.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A highly decorated former combat pilot in Vietnam and an
administrator known for his skills at consensus building, Ralston
withdrew from consideration for chairman of the Joint Chiefs two
years ago after it was disclosed that he had had an affair in the
1980s while separated from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   He had planned to retire to Anchorage next year. But during his
last two years as the vice chairman, his job performance helped
erase military and administration concerns that he could not
surmount the adultery scandal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
