<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-GATEKEEPERS-BO     07-28 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-GATEKEEPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CANCER CELL RESEARCH COULD LEAD TO SPECIFIC TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- For the first time, scientists say they have created
human cancer cells in a laboratory dish by disabling the few
essential ``gatekeepers'' that keep normal cells from turning into
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we know what a bare-bones cancer cell could look like''
and may be able to use that knowledge to design a more effective
therapy, said Robert Weinberg, the cancer research pioneer whose
laboratory group at the Whitehead Institute in Cambridge carried
out the work being reported in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, making human cells cancerous in the lab has been
puzzlingly difficult except by bombarding them with toxic chemicals
and radiation. The new experiment shows that the feat can be
accomplished with precision _ it just takes knowing which few
switches to pull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cancer cells have been black boxes,'' said Weinberg, but the
new findings give scientists a way to identify and ``catalogue''
the different broken genes inside cells that transform them into
dangerous tumor cells.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists called the report a ``landmark'' paper that
could aid the search for highly specific cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg suggested that in the future, ``we will be able to take
a cancer cell out of a patient, determine the set of (mutant) genes
that are present, and tailor-make the therapy'' to fit that gene
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer is considered a genetic disease, not because it's
inherited (though a predisposition to it can be) but because broken
or altered genes inside cells are what triggers the cells'
malignant behavior, like growing out of control and invading
healthy tissues. The genes may be altered by chemicals inside the
body or outside it, including substances in food; radiation, or
mistakes occurring during cell division.
</P>
<P>
   As individuals accumulate more DNA changes with age, those
mutations are more likely to send some cells over the brink into
malignancy.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, Whitehead scientists led by Dr. William C. Hahn
and including Weinberg and others say they have identified just
four basic chemical hurdles that must be overcome to prod a cell
into endless growth _ the hallmark of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes the whole way we look at cancer,'' said Hahn, who
is also an oncologist at the Dana Farber Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we've taken cancer cells and tried to figure out
what makes them cancerous. Now, we've taken a normal cell and
figured out what the minimum number of changes is...in the future,
we may be able to treat those changes'' to prevent or suppress
cancer, he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   For a number of years, scientists have been able to transform
rodent cells by inserting mutant genes called ``oncogenes'' into
the cells. These inserted mutant genes disrupt the normal
growth-control mechanisms in the cell, causing the cell to escape
its built-in restraints on chaotic, cancerous growth.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers have found it difficult to duplicate this feat
with human cells, which seem to have more inherent barriers to
becoming malignant.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to find the minimum number of gene changes it would
take to make a human cell malignant, the Whitehead researchers
inserted some logical suspects, one at a time and in combinations.
</P>
<P>
   One of the oncogenes they tried was a piece of a monkey virus,
called the SV40 large T antigen. Another was an oncogene called
ras, which is found in many human tumors.
</P>
<P>
   And the third gene was one that causes the cell to make an
enzyme called telomerase. This enzyme keeps the DNA in cells from
deteriorating, as it normally does, when the cell divides. In fact,
the deterioration of DNA in the cell's chromosomes is believed to
be the ``clock'' that consigns human cells to death after a certain
number of divisions. Telomerase, by keeping the DNA intact, in
effect can make cells immortal _ a key feature of cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   However, telomerase by itself, while making the cells immortal,
did not make them malignant _ that is, they did not show all the
features of a truly malignant cell.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitehead group demonstrated that these three genes, when
inserted into skin and embryonic kidney cells in the laboratory,
made the cells immortal and able to cause tumors when injected into
laboratory animals.
</P>
<P>
   The three genes actually caused four crucial changes in the
cells, since the SV40 large T antigen disrupted two separate
growth-control safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying article in Nature, two French scientists
noted that the group had succeeded in answering a question at least
15 years old _ what is the ``minimum number of defined `genetic
hits' (gene mutations) required for tumor formation?'' This
``landmark paper,'' wrote Jonathan B. Weitzman and Moseh Yaniv of
the Institut Pasteur, should spur other scientists to implicate
other genetic ``players'' in causing cancers of different types.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Cancer Institute, researcher Curtis Harris
called the paper ``important'' and said it ``provides another tool
to investigate not only these pathways but drugs that might utilize
these defective pathways to treat cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris heads the laboratory of human carcinogenesis at the NCI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
