<HEADER>
A7669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMOS-DOCTORS-BOS &LR;      07-28 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMOS-DOCTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS, NURSES DECRY HMOS' EFFECT ON CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as the US House is poised to take up the contentious matter
of patients' rights, a new national survey of doctors and nurses
concludes that HMOs often refuse to cover care, with serious
consequences for patients much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Substantial percentages of doctors said managed-care plans
overrule their decisions on a monthly or weekly basis, according to
the study, released Wednesday. Among physicians who reported HMO
denials, from 37 to 65 percent said patients had somewhat serious
or very serious deterioration in their health as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurers scrambled to discredit the findings, conducted
by researchers at the Harvard School of Public Health and the
Kaiser Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This research is subject to real misinterpretation,'' said
Karen Ignani, president of the American Association of Health
Plans. She said its findings are contradicted by prior research _
including a 1995 study from the same researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Kahn, president of the Health Insurance Association of
America, added that the survey ``showcases attitudes of doctors and
nurses'' that ``don't mesh with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry's defensiveness may reflect its worries about the
politics of patients' rights in Congress, where some Republican
physician-congressmen (and a dentist) have split with party
conservatives who want to limit new federal HMO regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed its version of a patients' rights bill on July
15 on a 53-47 party-line vote. But many Democrats _ and the
renegade Republicans in the House _ say the Senate version isn't
stringent enough and leaves most HMO subscribers' rights to the
uncertainties of state regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors in the House have parted company with their
traditional allies on this issue because they're doctors,'' said
Drew Altman, president of the Kaiser Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Altman said the California-based foundation, which often funds
polls on health issues, is not trying to influence the outcome of
the HMO patients' rights debate. But he maintained the new results
show that problems with managed care ``are not just a bunch of
anecdotes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just about politics,'' Altman said. ``It's about
real problems out there in the health care system. I think this
study shows that whether you're for the Republican or Democratic
approaches, there's a need to reduce the disputes beween health
professionals and health plans and a need for a mechanism to
resolve these disputes when they occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Another national snapshot of HMOs, also released Wednesday,
found that care is improving steadily _ at least among the health
plans that monitor their performance and report on it publicly. But
``there is still substantial room for improvement in managed
care,'' said the National Committee on Quality Assurance, which
compiles the yearly report card for 247 HMOs that voluntarily
report their performance on a dozen quality measures.
</P>
<P>
   The quality gap between high- and low-performing HMOs ``remains
enormous,'' the National Committee said. For instance, the
percentage of diabetic patients who receive annual eye exams to
spot potentially blinding disease ranged from 10 percent in the
worst-performing plans to 80 percent among the best.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of heart disease patients who received beta
blocker drugs to prevent a heart attack ranged from 40 to almost
100 percent. Nationally, an increase in the appropriate use of beta
blockers rose from 63 percent in 1996 to 80 percent last year, an
improvement that has saved an estimated 2,179 lives, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report card found for the second year in a row that New
England HMOs achieved the highest scores nationally, ranking first
on nine of 12 quality measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser-Harvard report, a mail survey involving 1,053 doctors
and 768 nurses selected randomly, is one of the first to document
the frequency and seriousness of health plan denials, at least from
the health professionals' perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are a step closer to real stories and more detailed
quantification of impact of these decisions on patients,'' said
Karen Donelan, the Harvard project leader.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that nearly 9 in 10 physicians reported a care
denial in the previous two years, and a third to two-thirds of
these coverage denials seriously harmed patients, depending on
whether the refusal involved a prescription drug, hospital stay,
diagnostic test, specialist referral, or mental health care. About
half of nurses said HMO decisions had resulted in a decline in
patients' health.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significant, the survey discovered that managed
care denials occur on a regular basis among substantial percentages
of health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   Three out of five doctors said HMOs overruled their prescription
drug decisions on a weekly or monthly basis, resulting in a ``very
serious'' decline in patients' health in five percent of cases and
a ``somewhat serious'' deterioration in another 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Physician reports of monthly or weekly denials were less
frequent for diagnostic tests (42 percent), hospital stays (31
percent), specialist referrals (29 percent), and mental health care
(18 percent).
</P>
<P>
   However, adverse consequences were significant, ranging from 39
percent for hospital stays to 46-50 percent for diagnostic tests
and specialist referrals and 65 percent for mental health care.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and nurses said they often intervened for patients after
denials _ and sometimes exaggerated patients' conditions to get
coverage. In each doctor's most recent such intervention, the HMO
ruled in the patient's favor 42 percent of the time and compromised
in another 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers compiled a random sample of care providers'
comments on the consequences of care denials. One involved a
60-year-old woman with a stroke. ``Patient denied rehab by HMO
because it had contracts to place patient in a nursing home,'' her
doctor wrote. ``After a 20-day stay, patient was sent to
intermediate care with no therapy and no hope of improving mobility
and ADL (activities of dailing living) status, ending effectively
any hope of independent or assisted living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
