<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:JITTERS-BACK-TO-SCHOOL-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAME THOSE BACK-TO-SCHOOL JITTERS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By KRISTIN HOWELL, High School Student 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Going to a new school? Worried about making the transition to
middle or high school? Want summer to last forever? Keep dreaming.
If you really want to know the truth, there's absolutely nothing to
fret over. In a week or two, you'll have a new best friend and your
whole schedule memorized.
</P>
<P>
   Until then? You could start off like high school sophomore
Krista Farquhar and drive yourself crazy wondering about what all
your friends from last year will think of your new wardrobe
selections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent endless hours trying on every piece of clothing in my
closet to make sure I had the perfect outfit picked out,'' she
says.'' Then I'd spend two hours in front of a mirror before school
making sure my makeup and hair looked good.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a good idea to decide the night before what clothes
you want to wear. If you're brave enough to copy a hairstyle from a
magazine, practice taming your locks so you'll know exactly what to
do when you wake up.
</P>
<P>
   A small warning: Upperclassmen are intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way around it,'' says high school student Mary
Stanwood. ``Sixth and ninth grade were definitely the hardest for
me because I thought all the older kids would want to beat me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that eighth-graders and seniors have all been in
your shoes. They may be bigger, but they probably won't try to beat
you up. They'll be so wrapped up in their own lives that they won't
even take time to notice you.
</P>
<P>
   Don't care about what others think. Take advice from Jason
Parks, 16, who says he ``doesn't get nervous 'cause it's just
another year.''
</P>
<P>
   If you keep that in mind, all those imaginary put-downs and
butterflies will disappear. Also, don't be afraid to ask someone
for directions, especially if it's that cutie you've had your eye
on since first period.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
