A7694 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS:STUDY-BACK-TO-SC     07-28 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:STUDY-BACK-TO-SCHOOL-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET ORGANIZED FOR STUDY TIME 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those alarm clocks are tuned. Pencils are sharpened. The first
set of grades has been distributed.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't quite up to par, now is the time for students to
rethink their study strategies. Being organized is one of the
secrets to making school more enjoyable and helping students
succeed, according to Dale Jarrett, editor of the Orlando-based
newsletter ``The Get Organized News.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tricks suggested in the newsletter:
</P>
<P>
   _De-clutter closets and dresser drawers so students can find
their clothes easily in the morning and not waste time looking for
socks.
</P>
<P>
   _Clean out the study area. Clutter offers too many distractions
when it is time to do homework.
</P>
<P>
   _Set up a work area with supplies, reference materials, good
lighting, comfy chair, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _Evaluate whether it is more effective to study alone or with a
buddy.
</P>
<P>
   _When doing homework, avoid distractions such as TV. Soft music
is OK _ for some students.
</P>
<P>
   _Create organizers with baskets, shoe boxes, mugs, jars and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   _For kids who prefer to do their homework in bed, acquire a lap
desk and side table with shelves for storage.
</P>
<P>
   _Set up a launch pad near the pantry, den or kitchen where all
school-related items are kept. Include a basket for lunch money,
teacher notes, permission slips, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _Make a checklist of things to be done in the morning and
evening.
</P>
<P>
   _Use a planner or assignment book. Encourage kids to get in the
habit of writing down their assignments and checking them off when
completed.
</P>
<P>
   _Have a planning session to discuss ``what if'' strategies. What
happens if Tommy loses his lunch money? What if John is locked out
of the house when he gets home? What if the car-pool driver forgets
to pick up Suzy?
</P>
<P>
   _Parents can communicate with teachers through sticky notes and
even e-mail, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
