<HEADLINE>
ONLINE HELPERS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many sites on the Internet can be used to enhance your
educational experience. Here are a few:
</P>
<P>
   www.wordcentral.com
</P>
<P>
   This site by dictionary publisher Merriam-Webster can help kids
become word whizzes, with info on how to spell, pronounce and use
words. To help build your vocabulary (and impress teachers, not to
mention your friends) check out the Daily Buzzword feature.
Remember, sooner or later you're gonna have to take the SAT, and
you'll need to know the definitions of a variety of English words,
so start now.
</P>
<P>
   www.algebra-online.com
</P>
<P>
   So you don't understand algebra either? Lots of people have
trouble mastering algebra, but it is not impossible. And
after-school help is available. This site will let you submit
information to tutors and chat with others going through algebra I
courses. A handy feature called Quick Math lets you enter an
equation and then shows you how it calculated the answer.
</P>
<P>
   www.exploratorium.edu
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to recharge their brains after the summer can
take a virtual tour of a San Francisco museum that offers a Web
site packed with information. Dial up this site for the scoop on
the eclipse that's going to occur Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   www.bonus.com
</P>
<P>
   This site calls itself The SuperSite for Kids, and it has
interactive features, including the Weekly Arcade of games, Pop
Craze, with facts about your favorite celebrities and Talk Back,
where kids can give advice and share tips and just chat.
</P>
<P>
   Other fun sites to visit are:
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon: www.nick.com
</P>
<P>
   Worm World: www.yucky.com
</P>
<P>
   ESPN Sports: www.espn.go.com
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated for Kids: www.sikids.com
</P>
