<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-MARTENS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTENS FACES CLASSIC CONTEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTAIC, Calif. _ He was scouting cypress trees on a bayou in
the Deep South for the most important bass tournament of his young
life when something of phenomenal proportions in the black swamp
water took the bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm yanking on it and pulling on it and bubbles are coming up
and I thought, `What the hell is this thing?''' said Aaron Martens,
26, of Castaic, a first-time qualifier for the internationally
acclaimed BASS Masters Classic. ``I thought, `I'm here in Louisiana
by myself and I don't know what this thing is.'''
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden ``this thing'' crawled five feet across the
bottom and stopped. ``I back off a little bit because I got a
little scared,'' Martens said. Then the creature broke the surface
and what the angler assumed was a giant catfish turned out to be a
14-foot alligator.
</P>
<P>
   After a few ``oh my Gods,'' he calmed down enough to snap a
couple of shots of the breathtaking catch.
</P>
<P>
   The incident late last month serves as a metaphor for Martens as
he begins the three-day world championship of bass angling today on
the expansive Louisiana Delta and Mississippi River Basin: He
really isn't sure what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I did very well prefishing; I didn't catch
enough fish,'' Martens said during a recent break from packing
artificial lures into two boxes provided by tourney officials, as
required by the unforgiving rules. ``My fishing skills are there;
it will take me a little while to adapt to the fishing conditions
out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' he added. ``I just wish it was somewhere else,
anywhere but the delta. It's so unfair; there is too much water.''
</P>
<P>
   The 45 anglers vying for a share of the $350,000 purse and a
shot at the $100,000 champion's payout _ which comes with beaucoup
sponsorships and household fame in the bass-angling community _ can
basically target the southern half of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   But like the water moccasin that crawled into Martens' boat
motor after the gator disappeared, don't be surprised if this
rookie shows some serious bite; he hasn't won three Angler of the
Year awards in Western professional bass circuits on luck alone.
</P>
<P>
   Martens chatted about his chances in this candid interview with
the Daily News. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DN: What is the biggest challenge?
</P>
<P>
   AM: ``The biggest challenge there is getting better quality
fish. It's hard to get big ones. It's endless water. There are some
areas that have more big ones than other areas. A lot of people
will have a hard time just getting fish. There will be some guys
traveling 2{ to 3 hours to get to a spot. I have a spot that is an
hour and a half away.''
</P>
<P>
   DN: What will it take to win?
</P>
<P>
   AM: ``It will take a (five-bass) limit and one big fish _ 3 to 4
pounds or more _ each day to win. There might be some guys getting
14 to 20 pounds (of bass a day), but, if it's like it was last
month, it'll be more like 10 to 11 pounds. The average fish caught
is a pound and a quarter. I'd be really happy if I got 10 pounds a
day; that would maybe get you in the top five.''
</P>
<P>
   DN: What makes your fishing style suited for this contest?
</P>
<P>
   AM: ``It's flipping and pitching and topwater-fishing mainly,
and that's what I do best.''
</P>
<P>
   DN: What shortcomings could hurt you?
</P>
<P>
   AM: ``The only weakness that will hurt me in this one is not
being on the right fish and not being where the big fish are. It
was too big an area to practice (well).''
</P>
<P>
   DN: Can you win?
</P>
<P>
   AM: ``There's a possibility; I have stuff going on. I want to be
in the top five; that would make me really happy.''
</P>
<P>
   DN: Is qualifying for the BASS Masters Classic (by finishing in
the top five in the four-event BASSMASTER Western Invitational
series) your biggest accomplishment?
</P>
<P>
   AM: ``I think my biggest accomplishment was probably quitting my
job (as a gas-station attendant) after I won my first tournament in
October 1993 (in only the second pro tourney he'd fished). This is
probably right up there, and, of course, if I win this it would
take the cake for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   BASS MASTERS &QL; 
CLASSIC FACTS &QL; 
When: Today through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Louisiana Delta and Mississippi River Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Purse: $350,000 (winner's share: $100,000; last place: $4,000).
</P>
<P>
   Field: 45 anglers.
</P>
<P>
   Results: Updated daily at www.bassmaster.com, with Saturday's 5
p.m. final weigh-in and trophy presentation at the Louisiana
Superdome in New Orleans linked up live via the Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring: Competitors may weigh in five bass daily, with a
minimum length of 12 inches; the angler with the heaviest combined
weight after three days of fishing wins.
</P>
<P>
   Tackle allowed: Artificial lures only.
</P>
<P>
   Most wins: 4, Rick Clunn.
</P>
<P>
   Largest bass: 8 pounds, 9 ounces, Ricky Green, 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Heaviest winning weight: 75 pounds, 9 ounces (21 bass,
seven-bass daily limit), Rick Clunn, 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Lowest winning weight: 15 pounds, 15 ounces (14 bass), George
Cochran, 1987. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
