<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-PREMIUMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND'S LARGEST HMO PLANS 15 PERCENT PREMIUM INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Members of Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, New England's
largest health maintenance organization, can expect to pay an
average of 12 percent to 15 percent more next year in health
insurance premiums, according to the HMO's new chief executive,
Charles D. Baker Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The rate hike, the steepest for Harvard Pilgrim members in more
than six years, is a cornerstone in the HMO's plans unveiled
Wednesday to rebuild its finances. Harvard Pilgrim last year lost
an unprecedented $54 million and appears to be losing money at an
even faster rate so far this year. Baker estimated Harvard Pilgrim
has already lost more than $45 million in the first six months of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   To stem the losses, Harvard Pilgrim's aggressive turnaround plan
also involves laying off hundreds of workers, completely revamping
its notoriously arcane computer systems, selling off chunks of
assets, and exiting unprofitable markets.
</P>
<P>
   Baker Wednesday declined to specify how many of the HMO's 4,400
employees would be laid off in the coming months, but estimated
that efforts to ``reduce administrative costs'' would save up to
$75 million over the next six to nine months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the HMO is expecting a one-time windfall of up to
$50 million from selling various assets, including a
240,000-square-foot office building adjacent to Boston in Quincy
and its money-draining Rhode Island operations, which cares for
155,000 patients.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Harvard Pilgrim's turnaround plan involves
overhauling its computer systems, which Baker characterized as a
``mess'' as he produced a two-page diagram of the HMO's computer
system that resembled a rat's nest of interconnected rectangles and
circles.
</P>
<P>
   For Harvard Pilgrim's patients and doctors, the convoluted
computer matrix has resulted in thousands of unpaid bills,
improperly denied claims, and general confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Walt Kagan, an oncologist with Commonwealth Hemotology
Oncology in Quincy, said his practice has unpaid claims he sent to
Harvard Pilgrim in 1997. Harvard Pilgrim, which once owed the
practice more than $500,000, was so far behind on its payments that
Kagan's practice had to once borrow ``a couple hundred thousand
dollars'' to pay its employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have a problem collecting their premiums, they just
cut people off,'' Kagan said of Harvard Pilgrim. ``We can't do that
to our patients. It's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Kagan said the HMO has been making an effort to catch up on its
payments, but that progress has been frustratingly uneven.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Stott, operations manager of Women's Health Care, an
obstetrical practice in West Newbury, said Harvard Pilgrim owes his
practice $60,000 in claims, 50 percent of which are more than 90
days overdue. By contrast, only 4 percent of claims to Blue Cross
and Blue Shield of Massachusetts are similarly past due.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Harvard Pilgrim is our worst payer,'' Stott said.
</P>
<P>
   Furious, physicians and hospitals have filed legislation on
Beacon Hill to force insurance companies to pay on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a case of simple fairness that HMOs pay their
bills on time,'' said Judy Glasser, spokeswoman for the
Massachusetts Hospital Association, who noted that Harvard Pilgrim
is not the only insurer with problems paying its bills.
``Twenty-four other states have filed timely payment legislation,
so it's not unique to Harvard Pilgrim.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker promised an eventual end to the technical snarls that have
plagued the health plan for years. His plan involves outsourcing
Harvard Pilgrim's claims processing tasks to Perot Systems Corp.,
based in Dallas. The $300-million, five-year contract with Perot
Systems calls for Perot Systems to take over Harvard Pilgrim's
computer systems, process all claims, maintain and upgrade the
computers, and manage the large databases containing the company's
medical and financial information.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether the 1,100 Harvard Pilgrim employees
currently working on the company's information systems will become
Perot Systems employees, remain on Harvard Pilgrim's payroll, or be
laid off.
</P>
<P>
   By the year 2001, Baker wants a much simpler computer system
where patients and health care providers can use personal computers
to communicate with the HMO, file claims, enroll, or check
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the errors and the gunk that creates the clogs, bumps, and
denials go away because we will be dealing with a much simpler
system on a real-time basis,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim's turnaround plan mirrors steps recently taken
by Blue Cross, which in response to steep losses also raised
premiums, sold assets, shed unprofitable businesses, laid off
workers, outsourced computer-related functions, and simplified
contracts with customers and vendors. Blue Cross' efforts appear to
have paid off; the company was the only health insurer in
Massachusetts to have made money in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Managed-care observers say Harvard Pilgrim is on the right track
in trying to clean up its Frankensteinian computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to generate the information that allows them to
understand where they spend their money,'' said Phil Caper, chief
executive of Codman Research, a managed-care information systems
company in Lyme, N.H. ``It really points out the growing urgency
among plans to get control of their expenses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
