u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISS-ACCIDENT-ART-2T     07-28 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-ACCIDENT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS RIVER DEATHS FUEL QUESTIONS ABOUT `CANYONING'
</HEADLINE>
  (With SWISS-CANYONING) 
(ART ADV: Locator map and canyoning diagram are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERLAKEN, Switzerland _ With the death toll up to 19, and
Swiss rescue workers still searching the rapids for two missing
tourists, the river disaster in this pristine Swiss resort town on
Tuesday is already raising questions about the inherent dangers of
the adventure sport known as ``canyoning.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five clients from as far away as Australia and South
Africa, most of them young and thrill-seeking, signed up on Tuesday
with the Swiss company Adventure World to experience the adrenaline
rush of using their bodies to slide down a rope through Alpine
waterfalls, swimming through rapids, or hopping from rock to rock.
</P>
<P>
   A sudden, pronounced downpour swelled their mountain stream into
a torrent. It swept at least 19 people, including three of the
eight guides, to their death; six people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Local police have not completed their investigation of what is
the worst tragedy in the sport's history, and Swiss authorities
Wednesday suspended all canyoning expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy has focused attention on how affluent members of
society often straddle a thin line between calculated risk and
recklessness. Interlaken, a charming village of wood chalets and
neatly trimmed flower beds 40 miles south of the capital of Bern,
has in the '90s become the kind of youth mecca that Amsterdam was
in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of seeking drugs and rock music, twentysomething
backpackers, many of them American, gather to mingle and experience
the summertime high of extreme sports: paragliding, rafting, ice
climbing, bungee jumping, and canyoning.
</P>
<P>
   Interlaken's quaint streets are lined with shops selling and
renting mountain bicycles, hiking boots, rafts, ropes and wet
suits. Young people hang out at scruffy youth hostels like one
called Funny Farm sipping beer by the pool, enveloped in pop music
and strewn extreme-sports gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the thing to do, you go to Interlaken, and you go
canyoning,'' said Heather, a 23-year-old Californian who had
canyoned for the first time the morning of the accident; she was in
a beginner's level excursion of nine clients and two guides
provided by Adventure World. She had no training, and received none
from the company. She refused to give her last name.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had no previous climbing or rafting experience, and
was scared at first, but found the sport ``really exciting.'' She
added, ``I never felt unsafe. I wanted to carry on, I wished it
would get harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if, after the accident, she would try it again, she
hesitated. ``I don't know, now.''
</P>
<P>
   Local authorities and representatives of Adventure World
canceled an afternoon meeting Wednesday with reporters, without
explanation. At a news conference earlier in the day, local
officials said they had not yet identified the dead. Police
officers said identification could take several days and asked
relatives of the missing to bring dental records, X-rays and other
data that could help identify the victims.
</P>
<P>
   They said the victims, four women and 15 men, came from
Australia, New Zealand, Britain, South Africa, and Switzerland. No
Americans were believed to have died in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's consul general in Geneva, Malcolm Skelly, told
Australian radio that most of the victims were Australian and New
Zealanders. He said he spoke to one injured Australian who
survived, and was told, ``Everything happened in a flash,'' and
that the group was in the river bed ``when suddenly the water swept
everything away.''
</P>
<P>
   Georg Hoedle, the founder of Adventure World Company, was
visibly shaken when he told Swiss television Wednesday, ``I am
terribly sorry for the victims and those left behind.'' But neither
he nor other company representatives have given much information
about the fateful excursion. It is not yet known, for example,
whether the 45 clients were on a beginner's course, or a more
advanced one.
</P>
<P>
   And the company has yet to explain why the afternoon excursion
was carried out when weather services predicted thunderstorms.
Local people said the sky began turning cloudy and dark by early
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Web site Wednesday posted a condolence note (``The
accident is the most tragic occurrence, that has come upon us. It
has shaken us to the core, and we would like to express our deepest
sympathies to all those involved.'') and went on to give a company
profile, boasting that it had served 28,400 clients since its
founding in 1993 and that its team of guides ``consists of
experienced Adventure-professionals from all parts of the world.
Safety is our highest priority in all activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, at the main offices of Adventure World, a modern
chalet-style brown-shingle building in Wilderswil, a hamlet outside
Interlaken, red-eyed company employees turned reporters away,
saying they could not yet discuss the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Marooned in Interlaken, banned from the extreme sports that drew
them, many would-be canyoners huddled in morose groups, reviewing a
sport that is popular around the world; in the United States the
sport, known as canyoneering, is typically practiced in a less
extreme form than in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been us,'' Gina Onorato, 19, of Baltimore, said.
She and her friend Melena Pappas, 20, had heard about canyoning
from other tourists they met traveling in Europe, and had signed up
for an excursion Wednesday morning, which was canceled after the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said it's the best thing, you've got to do it,'' she
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Though traveling through Europe, even by backpack, is an
expensive pastime, canyoning is relatively cheap. Five different
adventure sports companies operate in the Bern region, with average
prices ranging from the equivalent of about $55 for a half day to
about $135 for a full day.
</P>
<P>
   Affordability has popularized the sport. Its popularity may have
blurred its inherent risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept asking, `Is it dangerous?''' Ms. Onorato said.
``Everyone said, `Oh no, people do it all the time.'''
</P>
<P>
   The two girls said they were cutting short their stay in
Interlaken. ``We're leaving for Paris tomorrow,'' Ms. Onorato said.
``It's dead here now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The accident was first discovered around 6 p.m. Tuesday by a
jogger who saw bodies floating in Lake Brienz. The bodies had swept
into the lake from the Lutchine River, which is fed by the Saxeten
Brook, where the excursion began about 90 minutes earlier.
Canyoners routinely wear wet suits and crash helmets. Most of the
victims were said to have worn lifejackets.
</P>
<P>
   Torrential rains began around 5 p.m. and did not let up for two
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding, caused by rain and also melting snow from surrounding
Alpine peaks, are a frequent hazard in the area. In 1987, heavy
rains caused the Saxeten to double in volume, flooding parts of the
nearest village, Wilderswil. The most recent canyoning fatality in
the Bern region occurred in 1997, when a 24-year-old man's rapel
cord caught on a rock, and he drowned in the rapids.
</P>
<P>
   Some canyoning experts dismissed the accident as an
unforeseeable act of God. ``I heard that the water came down like
an avalanche. There is nothing you can do in that situation,'' said
Felix Schmidhalter, an independent canyoning and mountain guide who
works for another sports adventure company, ``No Limits Center'' in
Verbier, Switzerland. ``You know skiing is usually safe, but the
day you have an avalanche, what can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I think for a while there will be fewer people
canyoning, but in France and Switzerland lots of people canyon or
climb. They will start again.''
</P>
<P>
   People living in the area, however, took a dimmer view of the
sporting fad that has made Interlaken a lure for restless youth.
``I think these young foreigners, they find life too dull, they
want thrills,'' Eva Seiler, a 66-year-old retired cosmetics store
owner said as she waited for police to lift a blockade to the
stream where the deaths occurred, which runs past her house. ``But
all these schools and companies, they are profiting from the
boredom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
