<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TEEN-DRIVING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHFUL DRINKING, DRIVING ON RISE, REPORT FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROB NELSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The rate of drunken driving among teenagers and young
adults in Massachusetts is rising at an alarming rate, leading to
increased deaths and dangerous conditions on Bay State roads,
according to a comprehensive state study of underage drinking
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that the number of juveniles charged with
drunken driving nearly doubled between 1993 and 1997, while the
percentage of juveniles on probation for alcohol abuse-related
offenses jumped from 25 percent in 1987 to 42 percent two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The study's findings that more teenagers _ who are not legally
able to buy liquor _ are driving drunk is especially disturbing
because it comes at a time when adult drunken driving court cases
are declining, says the report issued by the Massachusetts Trial
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing an emerging pattern of greater alcohol abuse by
teenagers, coupled with a rising incidence of drunken driving and
even motor vehicle homicide crimes by adolescents, points to a need
for greater understanding of this small but significant population
of drunk drivers,'' stated the report, prepared by the trial
court's probation commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the study, researchers focused on 117 people between
17 and 20 years old who had been arrested for drunken driving in
the 1980s. They found that 17 percent had a prior drunken driving
arrest and 22 percent had been charged with other motor vehicle
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which its authors say is the state's first long-term
research project on juveniles and drunken driving, also found that
underage drunk drivers had a high likelihood of continuing to drink
and drive.
</P>
<P>
   State officials tracked the 117 young drunken driving offenders
for 10 years and found that four out of 10 had at least one
subsequent arrest for driving under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad commentary on what our society is like,'' said
Raymond Crowley, the chief probation officer for Hampden Juvenile
Court. ``It's a signficant indicator that something is going
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, the statewide total of juveniles charged
with driving under the influence of alcohol jumped from 38 in 1993
to 68 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1994, the state dropped the blood-aclohol level needed to
charge drivers under 21 with drunken driving from .10 to .02 _
equal to one drink _ which may account for the sudden spike.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers, noting that juveniles cannot legally drink,
said the trend toward greater underage drunken driving is still
disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the number of juveniles charged with
motor vehicle homicides rose from three in 1994 to 10 two years
ago. ``The small but rising number of motor vehicle homicide cases
where the driver was a juvenile raises another alarm,'' the report
noted.
</P>
<P>
   The study's findings do not surprise Barbara Harrington,
executive director of the state's chapter of Mothers Against Drunk
Driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely confirms the importance of the work MADD has
done to understand the problem of underage drinking in this
country,'' she said, adding that the organization had recently
changed its misssion statement to include targeting underage
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said one possible way to curb the number of repeat
drunken driving offenders is to require mandatory supervised care
for anyone convicted of driving under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that data from the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse
and Alcoholism have shown that teens who start drinking at age 13
have a 47 percent chance of developing a lifelong dependency on
alcohol. But, Harrington added, that percentage drops to 10 percent
if young adults do not start drinking until they reach the legal
drinking age of 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most of us have thought for years has turned out to be
true and has been substantiated by this study,'' Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Crowley added, he has started to recognize the
names and faces of youthful offenders who are repeatedly brought
into court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a message that we've got to meet this problem head
on,'' Crowley said, adding that underage drinking is a problem that
should not fall solely on the shoulders of the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all comes back to the breakdown of the family,'' he said.
``There are more youngsters today who have less supervision. This
is everybody's problem _ the family, the schools, the Department of
Social Services.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Cicchetti, director of research for the state's Office of
Probation, said the report's findings point to one way to combat
underage drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It emphasized the need for early intervention with this part
of the population,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cicchetti said his office would expand its research on underage
drinking by taking a more in-depth look at the backgrounds of
juveniles with more than one drunken driving arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to develop a good sense of who these kids are and why
they got involved in these problems,'' Cicchetti said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
