r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWINFALLS-REVIEW-LADN     07-28 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWINFALLS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNUSUAL LOVE TRIANGLE, TAKE ON JEALOUSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
OUR RATING: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ ``You look pretty normal,'' Penny the hooker says
upon meeting her latest, immaculately dressed trick in his crummy
skid row room. ``This hotel is full of freaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she meets his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twin Falls Idaho'' starts off with such a bizarre, eerie
ambience, you think someone made a mistake with the title and
really meant ``Twin Peaks.'' But this first feature by the
identical twin Polish brothers _ Mark writes, Michael directs and
co-writes, both act _ turns into a sweet, quirky little love story
with what can only be described as an intriguing twist.
</P>
<P>
   Blake (Mark Polish) and Francis (Michael) Falls are conjoined
twins, ex-sideshow performers with two arms, three working legs and
two hearts between them. Blake has the stronger constitution;
indeed, Francis would not survive a separation from his brother's
life-pumping circulatory system. But the deeper question is, can
either Blake or Francis survive emotionally free of the one person
who's always _ and we do mean always _ been there for them?
</P>
<P>
   This subject comes up not only because of Francis' failing
health, but because Penny, well-played by waif-vamp model Michelle
Hicks, takes an interest in the boys after overcoming her initial
revulsion. The deal is, despite her profession, Penny is
fundamentally a loner. While the polite, generally good-humored
brothers inevitably evoke a sympathetic response and bring out her
protective instincts, Penny mostly is inspired by their concern for
one another, the way they communicate in whispered semaphores, even
how they can play the guitar as one entity.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to be a part of this unique togetherness, and she does
so by romantic overtures to both twins, although her preference
seems to be for Blake. Naturally, this leads to jealousy and
confusion, but is Francis jealous of Blake or of Penny?
</P>
<P>
   All three principals' emotional agendas are just ambiguous
enough to keep the story intriguing _ and honest, since there's no
easy solution to this triangle's basic predicament.
</P>
<P>
   Polish the director does a good job of putting the audience in
Penny's shoes, shooting everything at first under sickly colored
lights, then in warmer tones as she gets to know the Falls brothers
as people. And whatever her personality flaws may be, that open,
accepting nature becomes her saving grace. As everyone else who
encounters the boys instantly assigns them to one kind of
conceptual box or another, she remains committed to discovering
more about who they really are.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as we naturally gravitate toward her point of view,
we're also made privy to the twins' hermetic existence. It turns
out that they're not all that different, just longing for love and
acceptance and fearful of rejection like the rest of us, only in an
understandably extreme context.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the movie's great strengths, but also the
wellspring of its most nagging weakness. While ``Twin Falls' ''
journey from freak show to touching human drama is certainly
admirable, some unfortunately maudlin notes are struck along the
way. They cheapen what, for the most part, is a rigorous, absorbing
little picture that avoids sensationalism while insistently
exploring lives we don't see in movies every day. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: ``Twin Falls Idaho'' (R; language). &QL; 
The stars: Mark Polish, Michael Polish, Michelle Hicks, Lesley Ann
Warren. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Michael Polish. Written by Mark and
Michael Polish. Produced by Marshall Presinger, Rena Ronson and
Steven J. Wolfe. Released by Sony Pictures Classics. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 40 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Playhouse 7, Pasadena; Sunset 5, West Hollywood; Monica,
Santa Monica. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
