<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKEN-VESSELS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTYING PARAMEDICS ROLL IN `BROKEN VESSELS`
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A kind of low-budget appetizer for Martin
Scorsese's upcoming ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' ``Broken Vessels''
follows a pair of paramedics on a 911 call to their own doom.
</P>
<P>
   A stylish, gritty little number that should alarm anyone who's
even considering having a medical emergency, the movie ultimately
blows a lot of good acting and persuasive ambience on, well, too
many drugs. In director Scott Ziehl and co-writers David Baer and
John McMahon's minimum-wage L.A., everybody's flying high on one
kind of controlled substance or another. This includes the people
you call when someone ODs.
</P>
<P>
   Our unreliable narrator is Tom (Jason London), a med school grad
from Pennsylvania with a quizzical wish to ply the low-paying
ambulance trade. He's assigned to veteran driver Jimmy (Todd Field,
seen briefly in ``Eyes Wide Shut'' and even more briefly in ``The
Haunting''), who's burned through an inordinately high number of
rookie partners.
</P>
<P>
   Tom soon discovers why. Although personable and dedicated to
back-watching teamwork, Jimmy drinks, smokes all kinds of dope and
turns the back of the unit into a rolling love machine, all while
on duty. He shakes down dealers at drug emergency calls and buys
illegal pharmaceuticals from the driver's seat. Jimmy's only real
relationships are with his nursing home-bound grandfather (who is
also a junkie) and his speed-freak sculptress neighbor (Susan
Traylor), who eventually establishes a meth lab in her garage.
</P>
<P>
   The apparently impressionable Tom is sucked deeper and deeper
into the deceptively ``together'' Jimmy's living pipe dream. Tom's
only potential escape route, a relationship with a sweet young
nurse (Roxana Zal, who produced the film with Ziehl), is inevitably
fumbled. You feel for the lost kid, yet there are indications,
well-planted, that he's not the corrupted innocent he appears to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broken Vessels'' is strongest when it illustrates the workaday
horrors paramedics must deal with, and with how these particular
rescuing angels abuse the trust the public unthinkingly places in
them. The style ranges from the vulgar verite of TV's ``Cops'' to
more expressionistic stretches, with some well-deployed humor
worked in to relieve the overall grimness.
</P>
<P>
   The acting remains very good as Tom and Jimmy's narcotic spiral
takes over the narrative, but it's something we've seen in a
hundred other movies that didn't start out as distinctively as this
one.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointing and tedious as it may become, ``Broken Vessels''
remains a well-observed and smartly executed slice-of-life drama.
And while it surely doesn't represent the general quality of
ambulance attendants in our fair megalopolis, it sure gives you a
lot to ponder that you probably never otherwise would have _ or
would have wanted to. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Broken Vessels'' (R; drug use, violence, sex,
language, nudity). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Todd Field, Jason London, Roxana Zal, Susan Traylor. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Scott Ziehl. Written by Ziehl, John
McMahon and David Baer. Produced by Zal and Ziehl. Released by
Zeitgeist Films. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 30 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Playing: &LR;  Nuart, West L.A. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
