<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7720 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-UNITDEAL-H     07-28 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-UNITDEAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Be careful how quickly you analyze trades. You never know how
they're going to look one year later.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday marks the one-year anniversary of the Astros'
improbable coup that lured Randy Johnson from Seattle in exchange
for a trio of minor-leaguers whose names might as well have been
Mo, Curly and Larry as far as most were concerned.
</P>
<P>
   But Seattle's haul in the trade _ righthanded pitcher Freddy
Garcia, lefthanded pitcher John Halama and infielder Carlos Guillen
_ hardly looks like the Three Stooges these days. Despite suffering
a season-ending knee injury after playing in just five games,
Guillen is still regarded as the Mariners' second baseman of the
future. And Garcia and Halama are 10-5 and 7-2, respectively, as
rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The criticism) was understandable,'' Mariners manager Lou
Piniella said of the heat his team took for the so-called no-names
they received in the trade. ``You would think when you trade a
Randy Johnson, you would get immediate help. But I'll tell you
what: It looks like a good deal now.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Johnson, he bolted for Arizona as a free agent during the
offseason and is 10-8 with a 2.65 ERA and a major-league-leading
240 strikeouts for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   So was the joke on the Astros? Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson didn't pitch them to the World Series _ the
ultimate goal of the trade _ he didn't do anything to hurt their
chances, posting a 10-1 record in 11 starts and a 1.28 ERA with a
.191 opponents' batting average.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Unit also attracted big crowds, luring an average of
45,655 (more than 15,000 above the season average) to his five
starts at the Astrodome. And while that all seems a distant memory
in life after Johnson, no one associated with the Astros regrets
the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would do it again 100 times out of 100,'' said Astros
general manager Gerry Hunsicker, baseball's reigning Executive of
the Year. ``Last year was a special year, and I really felt like we
not only had the talent, but they were all playing up to or
exceeding their abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was set for this team to take it all the way. I
said last year, and I'll say it again: We may never have a better
opportunity than we had last year of going to a World Series. That
doesn't mean I don't think we're going to get to the World Series.
My point is, on paper, we may never have a better team assembled
than we did coming down the stretch last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won a franchise-record 102 games in 1998 and claimed
the National League Central title for the second year in a row.
They were bounced from the first round of the playoffs by San
Diego, against which Johnson was 0-2 with a 1.93 ERA and 17
strikeouts in two starts.
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson was tabbed as the man to lead the Astros to the
promised land, his job description didn't include anything about
performing miracles on their bats. The Astros produced only eight
runs in four games against the Padres _ just two in Johnson's two
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly was a disappointment that we didn't get to the
World Series, because in hindsight I still feel the team we had on
the field last year should have gotten to the World Series,''
Hunsicker said. ``But that's not the way sports works. This is a
great example of why you have to be careful when making trades in
the middle of the season, because in reality there's only one team
in the National League that gets to the World Series, and the odds
aren't great regardless of what moves you make.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly have to take that into consideration, because if
you continually live by the philosophy of `live for today and don't
worry about tomorrow,' you'll end up paying a heavy price.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may be fortunate enough to get to the playoffs or maybe
win the World Series one year and then spend the next three or four
years trying to get out of last place, and that's not what I want
for this franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   It's highly unlikely the Astros will make a blockbuster deal
before Saturday's trading deadline, mainly because no one of
Johnson's caliber is available but partly because the farm system
has been thinned by recent deals.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Johnson trade seemed unlikely, too. Hunsicker
contacted Mariners GM Woody Woodward regarding Johnson several
months prior to the deadline but was told the Big Unit was not
available at that time.
</P>
<P>
   But as the deadline neared, the Mariners were aggressively
trying to deal Johnson, whom they no longer felt they would be able
to re-sign as a free agent. In the final days before the deadline,
Woodward's focus was on the Astros, Indians and Yankees, with the
Astros winning the sweepstakes because they were willing to include
two pitchers in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we gave up more than we wanted to, even for Randy
Johnson,'' Hunsicker said. ``You have to look at the complexity of
a transaction like this. Part of that is, What are the odds of
reaching the goal even if you make the deal, and what impact is
that going to have on the future _ on your ability to compete for
the next two or three years?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were willing to pay more for his services than anyone else,
and that's what it came down to. In reality, the Yankees or the
Indians could have acquired him if they wanted to. As it turned
out, he was of more value to us than he was to the Indians or the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until an hour before the deadline, I did not want to put
all three of those kids in the same deal, and I especially didn't
want to put two pitchers in there just because of how difficult it
is to acquire pitchers. We saw last year as a very special
situation, and that's very important to understand, because I don't
think that most years are like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although 1998 didn't end the way the Astros hoped, the Johnson
trade is one of the most significant transactions in franchise
history. Never before had they acquired such an impact player at
such a crucial time of the year, and not since Nolan Ryan had the
team employed a player with such celebrity appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to make a symbolic move, and I think the Randy
Johnson trade really sent a strong message to everyone, especially
our veteran players,'' Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. said. ``It
showed that we are committed to winning. At the time, that was the
right move to make. Randy gave us a confidence that we never had
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We paid a big price in terms of the players we traded, and we
added $2 million in salary with Randy. I think the fans understand
that cost is a consideration, and we can't continue to do that year
after year. But trading for Randy was a remarkable situation, and
no trade in my seven years in baseball has ever come close to it. I
would absolutely do it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
