<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION DEFENSE IS OPEN, REVOLVING DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Revolution have tried almost everything to restore
their central defense since dropping Alexi Lalas and Francis Okaroh
two years ago. Last year, the Revolution went through a dozen
pairings before being eliminated from playoff contention in August.
</P>
<P>
   This year, player-coach Walter Zenga seemed to have brought
stability to the team. But just when the Dan Calichman-Brian
Dunseth central combination should have been shifting into a gear
of competence and comprehension, Calichman was injured and Dunseth
benched.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Calichman (hip pointer) is questionable for the
Revolution's visit to Tampa Bay Saturday, leaving the team
vulnerable to a potentially explosive attack guided by Carlos
Valderrama.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga will attempt to find a satisfactory combination among
Dunseth, Chaka Daley, and Mario Gori, who shared the central
defensive positions in Wednesday's training session. All three are
lacking either the experience or skill to command the position,
though.
</P>
<P>
   Dunseth could regain his starting role _ he had a 13-game
starting streak ended as the Revolution lost to D.C. United, 2-0,
Sunday. Daley, acquired from the Boston Bulldogs to replace Manny
Motajo, has performed as a reserve in one game. Gori, the most
accomplished and experienced of the three, is a left back.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga had hoped to have Joseph Addo, a Ghanaian whose
athleticism, experience, size, and skill would have solved the
problem. But either the league or the Revolution did not move
quickly enough to sign Addo, and instead the Revolution received
striker Ariel Graziani as an allocated player this week.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani was scheduled to receive a visa, then clear customs in
Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, Wednesday. He will arrive in Tampa late
Thursday and be available for Saturday's match.
</P>
<P>
   But Graziani is a forward and will do little to bolster the
defense, which has surrendered at least two goals in six of the
last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do a better job defensively as a team,'' Dunseth
said. ``We need to communicate better, and we've addressed that on
the field. We need to work on doing the little things better, step
to the man quicker, work harder for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunseth has been impressed with Graziani after watching him play
for Veracruz and Morelia in Mexico and for Ecuador's national team.
``He can only help the team,'' Dunseth said. ``I've seen him in
Copa America and in the Mexican League, and he is a great player
with a nose for the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley had been playing the left side of defense in the Bulldogs'
3-5-2 sweeper alignment. But he grew up playing in the middle in
Toronto, Florida, and in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been as sharp as I want to be in practice,'' Daley
said. ``But your game gets tidier and sharper if you are involved
in real games. I just have to be patient and work hard and
practice, wait for my opportunity. Hopefully, I'll do well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Addo met with Tampa Bay coaches and players Wednesday and will
attend Thursday's game against the Miami Fusion in Fort Lauderdale
and probably Saturday's match in Tampa. Addo could join the Mutiny
as early as next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
