<HEADLINE>
DRUG COMPANY ADS ATTACK MEDICARE COVERAGE OF DRUGS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (rk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Flo,'' an arthritic Medicare beneficiary, made
her debut Wednesday in television commercials and newspaper
advertisements, cautioning Congress about potential pitfalls in its
effort to establish Medicare coverage for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements, financed mainly by drug companies, do not
explicitly endorse or oppose President Clinton's proposal to offer
drug coverage to all 39 million Medicare beneficiaries. On the one
hand, Flo says Congress should ``help more seniors get prescription
drug coverage.'' On the other, she declares, ``I don't want big
government in my medicine cabinet!''
</P>
<P>
   Flo's message is thus less clear-cut than that of ``Harry and
Louise,'' the couple whose television commercials, financed by the
insurance industry, helped kill Clinton's plan to guarantee health
care for all Americans in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The drug companies sponsoring the current advertising campaign
want to be sure the government does not regulate drug prices or
decide which medicines will be available to the elderly or the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the advertisements says they were ``paid for by
Citizens for Better Medicare,'' a coalition that includes drug
manufacturers, large and small businesses and some patients'
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   The Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, a
trade association for more than 100 drug companies, said it was
putting up most of the money, but refused to say how much. At a
board meeting two weeks ago, directors of the association discussed
plans for a $30 million advertising campaign, but the actual amount
will depend on the course of the debate over Medicare coverage of
prescription drugs in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements and commercials, which are appearing
nationally on cable television, show Flo in a bowling alley,
wearing a bright orange bowling jacket. While Medicare generally
does not cover outpatient drugs, Flo says she has drug benefits
through her ``retirement plan,'' and she notes that ``two-thirds of
America's seniors have prescription drug coverage'' already.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' she asks, ``what about seniors who don't have
prescription drug coverage? Something ought to be done.'' In the
print advertisements, she urges readers, ``Let Congress know you
support the right Medicare reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Flo apparently shares the companies' concern that price controls
could choke off the revenue needed for pharmaceutical research.
``The right Medicare reforms,'' she says, will ``guarantee research
for tomorrow's cures.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition, Citizens for Better Medicare, includes the
National Association of Manufacturers, the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, the United Seniors Association and the National Kidney
Cancer Association.
</P>
<P>
   The executive director of the coalition, Timothy C. Ryan, said:
``We want more seniors to have drug coverage, but we want to do it
the right way. The choices seniors have today should not be
displaced by a one-size-fits-all, government-managed program.''
</P>
<P>
   From January 1998 until last Friday, Ryan said, he was
advertising director of the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America.
</P>
<P>
   Martin A. Corry, director of federal affairs at the American
Association of Retired Persons, criticized the advertisements.
``This phony coalition, created and financed by the pharmaceutical
industry, is what we've come to expect from drug companies over the
last decade,'' Corry said. ``Fundamentally, they're in favor of the
status quo, which leaves millions of older Americans without drug
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials are just the first phase of advertising by the
drug industry and its allies. After establishing her identity and
her personality, Flo will have more to say about specific
legislative proposals for Medicare drug benefits, an issue likely
to preoccupy Congress and political candidates next year.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements were produced for the coalition by Alex
Castellanos, a Republican media consultant, and his company,
National Media Inc. of Alexandria, Va. But Ryan said, ``We want the
coalition to be a bipartisan effort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
