<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS CUT WILLIE CLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- With the Patriots trying to sign Ty Law to a contract
extension and all of their draft picks prior to the start of
training camp Friday, veteran free safety Willie Clay took the
salary cap hit and was released from the final year of his contract
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clay, a three-year starter at free safety who averaged 95
tackles and five interceptions per season, was due to earn $1.5
million this year. Patriots coach Pete Carroll said he had hoped
Clay would be the final cut he'd have to make among the veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the rookie signings will depend on whether the Patriots
could redo Law's contract. If not, another veteran may go, and
Shawn Jefferson could be next on the hit list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision, and after we went through the entire
roster, this is the move we decided to make. It's never easy, but
we hope we have some people who can compete for that position,''
Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said competition for the free safety job was wide open
between rookie Tony George, three-year veteran Chris Carter, and
Larry Whigham.
</P>
<P>
   The news hit Clay hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got screwed,'' said Clay, who said he heard the news from
Carroll at mid-afternoon and then went to the team's Foxboro
offices to meet with Patriots vice president of player personnel
Bobby Grier. ``Being released is part of the business. I can live
with that, but the biggest thing was the timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a family and this is my livelihood. I feel they didn't
show me any respect by doing it this late. The Arizona Cardinals
cut Larry Centers a month ago, and he was able to hook on with
another team and get into another program. I have to believe they
knew they were going to do this awhile ago. After they signed their
draft picks, they knew they needed money. They said it was a salary
cap move, but they never even came to me to say they wanted to
renegotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a way to treat people who have been good to your
organization, and I was that. I never missed a day of practice, I
played all the time. I was always prepared and I was a
professional. I spent all off-season in the workout program and I
could have been home with my son if I'd known this was going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay, who was considered a leader of the Patriots' defense,
doesn't understand the loyalty shown to some and not to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I helped groom some guys and they'll be the first one to tell
you that,'' said Clay. ``I've been here through good times and bad
times here and I thought we had a defense that was ready to really
jell after being together the last three years. I took hits for the
coaches and for the team and I was never fully appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay said he was accused of not having a good first half of the
season because he wound having to ``babysit'' the right corner
spot, where Chris Canty was lost during his stint as starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never complained about it. I just dealt with it,'' said
Clay.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said that while Clay's leadership would be felt, the
coach thought it was time for Milloy to take over that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be the leader of our secondary. He's ready. We believe
it's time for him to take that,'' said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were continuing to try and hash out a deal for free
agent Terry Allen, as they have been for months. The Patriots will
also look at the waiver wire to see if another running back becomes
available.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have been rejected by agent Jack Bechta on the
reworking of Todd Rucci's contract. The Patriots were trying to
work down the 5-year, $10 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While bidding adieu to Clay, the Patriots welcomed three draft
choices onto the payroll, signing second-rounder Kevin Faulk, a
running back from Louisiana State, to an estimated five-year deal
worth $3 million with a $1.2m signing bonus; third-rounder Tony
George, a safety from Florida, to a 3-year, $1.09 million deal with
a $340,000 bonus; and fifth-rounder Derrick Fletcher, an offensive
lineman from Baylor, who received $84,000 to sign and salaries of
$175,000, $250,000, and $325,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots now have signed six of their eight draft picks, and
their training camp roster totals 85. Their two first-round
selections _ Boston College center Damien Woody and Ohio State
linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer _ have not agreed to terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
