<HEADLINE>
PRISON BRUTALITY BEING INVESTIGATED AFTER DEATH OF FLORIDA INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(Eds: Spelling of ``Raymon'' in 26th graf is correct.) 
(yn) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Nine men know what happened inside a 7-by-9-foot cell in
Florida State Prison on the morning of June 19, when prison guards
armed with stun guns arrived to forcibly extract Frank Valdez, a
death-row inmate who murdered a corrections officer 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez, his body marked with bruises in the shape of boot prints
and his ribs broken, was beaten to death, state investigators said.
The nine, all corrections officers who the investigators said
either witnessed, knew about or took part in the beating, are not
talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have classified this as a homicide,'' said Elizabeth Hirst,
a spokeswoman for the Florida Department of Law Enforcement, which
investigates suspicious deaths in the state prison system. ``We
don't know exactly how many people took part in the killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdez was, according to prison and criminal records, one of the
most violent residents of what is called the X-wing _ a long
corridor lined with tiny cells that dead-ends at the state's
execution chamber _ in the maximum security prison in Starke, in
northern Florida. It only houses murderers like Valdez, 36, who are
moved from place to place in chains.
</P>
<P>
   But the violent nature of Valdez's own death, and the refusal by
the prison guards to cooperate with the investigation, has prompted
the FBI to join a state investigation that widened this week to
include complaints of brutality in prisons throughout the system.
</P>
<P>
   The homicide investigation has not led to criminal charges so
far but has resulted in suspensions _ with pay _ of the nine prison
guards and two other corrections officers who have refused to
cooperate with investigators. The investigation has been stymied by
that silence, said state investigators _ 12 of them in all _ who
are working from a command post set up outside the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 11 guards suspended, nine are believed to be directly
involved, said C.J. Drake, director of public affairs for the
Florida Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' Drake said, ``this appears to be an isolated
incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucia Ross, the press secretary to Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida,
said Wednesday that ``it's a little premature to come to any
conclusions that there's any widespread problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But the killing has lent credibility to a drumbeat of complaints
by inmates of brutalities in Florida's 53-prison system. Those
complaints _ usually in the form of unsolicited letters to the
courts, reporters and lawyers _ are often ignored.
</P>
<P>
   One letter, from a prisoner on X-wing received by The Miami
Herald on July 15, two days before Valdez was killed, was eerily
similar to the picture investigators paint of his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sounds of prisoners screaming in pain and of bodies being
beaten keeps the inmates on the entire wing up all night,'' wrote
Mike Lambrix, a convicted murderer in X-wing, in a letter dated
July 6. ``I can hear the officers forcibly take inmates from their
cells. The wretched sound of fists and boots striking flesh are
unmistakable as is the sound of some kind of weapon (a stick or a
broom handle?) being used. They scream. They whimper. Then there is
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody needs to get the feds in here,'' he continued, ``to
stop this before someone gets killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hirst said investigators are now looking at other such
complaints that were made both before and after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just caution you that there's two sides to every
story,'' Drake said. ``The Valdez incident has created an
atmosphere in which prisoners feel they can rehash a lot of
allegations against the prison system.'' In many cases, he added,
``we did investigate them and found that they are without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis Rubin, a lawyer who is representing the Valdez family,
said the family wants the federal authorities to take over the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of Florida investigating itself is like the fox
guarding the chicken coop,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators will be following up on those complaints
as part of the broader investigation, Florida officials said,
leaving state investigators free to concentrate on the homicide. A
few inmates from X-wing who may have seen or heard the attack have
been moved to another part of the prison.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, state prison officials announced that they would
videotape the removal of violent inmates from their cells _ what
the officials term ``extractions''_ to avoid speculation about what
actually happens, Drake said. State officials have been considering
the taping for some time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valdez incident merely accelerated our decision,'' Drake
said. ``But I wouldn't take it as a sign that we have a lack of
confidence in our prison guards.''
</P>
<P>
   If such a system had been in place, it would have shown what
happened that morning to Valdez, who has been in and out of prison
since 1980 for violently resisting a police officer, burglary,
robbery, kidnapping and grand theft.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, while trying to help another prisoner escape from
Glades Correctional Institution, Valdez shot to death Fred Griffis,
a corrections officer. A Palm Beach County Circuit Court sentenced
him to die.
</P>
<P>
   His death warrant had not yet been signed by Bush when the
extraction team of five officers, along with other officers, came
to remove him so they could search for weapons or other contraband.
Prison officials said the search was triggered when he had
threatened to kill a guard.
</P>
<P>
   The guards, armed with stun guns, fought with Valdez, who was,
from the results of a medical examination, struck and kicked
several times, investigators said. He was then placed in a cell,
without medical attention for several hours, and pronounced dead
later that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The corrections officers' union has said the men were just doing
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The officers suspended in the incident are Capt. Timothy Alvin
Thornton, 33; Sgt. Montrez Lazort Lucas, 30; Sgt. Charles Austin
Brown, 25; Sgt. Andrew William Lewis, 28; Sgt. Jason Patrick
Griffis, 26; Sgt. Robert William Sauls, and officers Dewey Marce
Beck, 51, Donald Michael Stanford, 51, and Raymon C. Hanson. The
two officers suspended this week were Daren Patgett, 34, and Philip
Maddox, 26. Griffis is no relation to the slain guard.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently handed the prison system over to Michael Moore,
who had a reputation as a tough jailer as head of the South
Carolina prison system. Moore ordered a review in January of the
use of force.
</P>
<P>
   Prison watchdog groups have lashed out at the Florida prison
system after the death. No matter how violent Valdez was, they say,
it was wrong to mirror his actions with even greater violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brutality and violence are not a legitimate response to
criminal conduct,'' said Jamie Fellner, associate counsel for Human
Rights Watch, based in New York. ``You can't fight crime with
crime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
