<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-ODWYER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attorney for O'Dwyer denies assault charge
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The attorney for Bengals guard Matt O'Dwyer
fought back on Wednesday, saying that allegations of assault
against his client are false.
</P>
<P>
   New York attorney William Zaccaria said all charges against
O'Dwyer, stemming from a July 10 brawl at a Long Beach, N.Y. bar,
should be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dwyer faces a $3.825 million civil suit from three police
officers who allege he injured their eyes during a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   The civil suit against O'Dwyer was filed in New York Supreme
Court, Nassau County, on Monday _ the same day of his scheduled
pretrial hearing, which was postponed until Aug. 16 in Long Beach
City Court.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dwyer, 26, is charged with disorderly conduct, second-degree
harassment, two felony counts of second-degree assault and a
fourth-degree charge of criminal mischief. He was released from
jail on $50,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dwyer, who signed a two-year, $2.7 million contract with the
Bengals on June 22, is due to report to the team's training camp on
Friday at Georgetown (Ky.) College.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my client's position _ it always has been _ that he
didn't commit any crimes of any nature,'' Zaccaria said. ``That the
charges against him are not properly brought, that they should be
dismissed, and he certainly is not guilty of anything charged in
any lawsuit since he didn't do anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaccaria said he hasn't seen a copy of the civil complaint
against O'Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if there are any charges alleging an assault or personal
injury, he accepts none of the responsibility for that and it'll
come out in the end that he shouldn't have been arrested to begin
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Long Island attorney Lawrence Elovich, who filed the civil suit
against O'Dwyer and New York Jets tackle John ``Jumbo'' Elliott on
behalf of three police officers and two other bar patrons, said the
football players ``engaged in a raucous brawl, fighting and pushing
patrons and throwing items throughout the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Elovich said O'Dwyer ``kicked out the right rear window of the
police car,'' with flying glass ``cutting and embedding the face
and eyes of police officers John O'Sullivan, Dean Burke and Anthony
Rivelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``O'Dwyer was intoxicated, out of control and refused to go
peaceably into the police car for which he would have been arrested
just for disorderly conduct,'' Elovich said. ``Instead, he lost
control and went wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The police) used a stun gun with 50,000 volts of electricity,
which didn't even knock him down or move him. He told the police
officers: 'Is that all you got?' They finally had to use a pepper
spray on him, which was finally able to subdue him.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaccaria said O'Dwyer doesn't have to be present for the Aug. 16
court appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In September, we'll go a little further down the road and see
what's going to happen with these charges,'' he said. ``After that,
the court will determine what the time frames are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bengals fourth-round draft pick Craig Yeast signed a three-year
contract worth a reported $1.01 million. The deal included a
$260,000 signing bonus for the 5-foot-7, 160-pound wide receiver
from Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The top two picks, quarterback Akili Smith and cornerback
Charles Fisher, remain the only unsigned players on the eve of
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Craig is going to be a great player for a long time in
this league,'' agent Rick Scalzo said. ``He has all the capability
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
