<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-SHIP-ASSAULTS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE LINE SAYS IT UNDERREPORTED ALLEGATIONS OF SEXUAL ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Carnival Cruise Lines said on Wednesday there
were 108 allegations that crew members were involved in sexual
assaults and sexual misconduct aboard its ships in a five-year
period that ended last August, not 62 incidents as reported by the
company two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the increase of more than 70 percent reflected
a more thorough search of its records. It also provided the first
case-by-case breakdown of the allegations, which included 16
reports that passengers were raped by crew members and 6 cases in
which crew members claimed they were raped by fellow workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These figures alone should tell you that Carnival ships
provided one of the safest vacation environments anywhere in the
world,'' said Curtis J. Mase, a lawyer for the company, which
carried 6.5 million passengers during the period.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the cruise industry has taken several steps to
defuse concern over crimes on board ships. The trade group for the
largest passenger lines serving ports in the United States, which
includes Carnival, said its members had adopted a ``zero
tolerance'' policy for crimes. Under the first industrywide
standard, all allegations of crime will be reported to the FBI or
other appropriate law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, some victims had complained that they were pressured
not to report crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of allegations disclosed by Carnival to news
organizations on Wednesday was sharply higher, company officials
said most cases were less serious than indicated earlier. The
majority involved allegations of unwanted touching, kissing and
other inappropriate advances, according to Carnival's compilation.
</P>
<P>
   Even in what were described as minor incidents, the company said
that crew members were fired for violating its policy against
fraternizing with passengers or for being in unauthorized parts of
the ship. In all, 47 crew members were fired in the five-year
period, according to Carnival's records.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For example, a cabin steward on the ship Celebration lost his
job in May 1997 after a passenger complained of an unwanted kiss.
The company report said its investigation was unable to verify the
claim, but the employee was dismissed for violating company
policies on fraternizing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Carnival produced the initial statistics in connection with a
lawsuit in Miami against the company by a former employee who said
she was raped and sodomized by an officer aboard a ship last Aug.
13. The company provided the compilation after being ordered to do
so by a Miami-Dade County judge and a state appellate court. The
company said it would provide the new statistics to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Mase said the new statistics resulted from a better search,
which included examining complaints from passengers after cruises.
Some of those complaints were made weeks or months after the
alleged incidents, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   In the instance that resulted in the suit by the crew member,
the company said its investigation found that the relationship
between the two employees was consensual, something the crew member
has denied.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in Miami indicted the alleged assailant on
charges of aggravated sexual assault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
