</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JUDGE WHO GAVELED THE UNITED STATES INTO IMPROVEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second-best thing that Dwight D. Eisenhower did as president
was to appoint Frank M. Johnson Jr. as federal district judge for
middle Alabama in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   A close second.
</P>
<P>
   Like Earl Warren, whose nomination to the U.S. Supreme Court
topped all else that Eisenhower did in the White House, Johnson
made and participated in decisions that changed America irrevocably
for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Some would even say that the Alabama jurist contributed more to
extend civil rights protections to all Americans than did Warren,
who headed the Supreme Court that rendered the historic 1954 ruling
of Brown vs. the Board of Education of Topeka, Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   In support of that assessment, they would cite Johnson's:
</P>
<P>
   Voting with the majority in 1995 when a three-judge panel found
that the law requiring segregation on city buses in Montgomery,
Ala., was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   1961 order prohibiting bogus tests used to prevent blacks from
registering to vote in Alabama. Johnson ruled that any black whose
qualifications equalled those of the ``least qualified white'' must
be allowed to vote. A year later, he eliminated the poll tax in
Alabama and joined two other judges in ordering that
reapportionment for voting in that state be based on population.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the 1965 civil rights march from Selma to Montgomery to
proceed under protection of the federalized Alabama National Guard
after the marchers had been brutally attacked by state police on
the Edmund Pettus Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing the killers of civil rights worker Viola Liuzzo to 10
years in prison for violating Liuzzo's civil rights. A Lowndes
County jury has previously acquitted the three Ku Klux Klansmen of
murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Those are among the most noted of the many rulings that Johnson
made or shared during the 1950s, '60s and '70s that helped consign
racial segregation to the dustbin of history _ rulings that
provided equal access to government facilities and places of public
accommodation, advanced the cause of fairness and equity before the
law, and allowed black Americans to exercise the most fundamental
privileges of citizenship in a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   For doing those things, Johnson, who died last week, received
considerable overdue recognition in his later years. Three
noteworthy biographies chronicle his life, including one by Robert
F. Kennedy Jr. In 1993, Johnson became the first recipient of the
American Bar Association's Thurgood Marshall Award, which honors
someone who ``most exemplifies Justice Marshall's spirit on behalf
of protecting civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But during his years on the federal bench in Montgomery, Johnson
was subject to threats of violence, verbal vilification and much
social ostracism. His mother's house was bombed, and crosses were
burned on his lawn. It became necessary for federal marshals to
protect Johnson and his family.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the hate mail and insults from anonymous people,
Johnson had to endure much vitriol from prominent people, including
the then-governor of Alabama, George Wallace. The champion of
segregation ``today, tomorrow and forever'' accused Johnson of
usurping the governorship and called the federal judge an
``integratin', carpetbaggin', scalawaggin', baldfaced liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Branded a judicial activist by enemies such as Wallace, Johnson
said that as both a trial judge and an appellate judge on the Fifth
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, he had endeavored to ``follow the
law and the facts without regard to the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's pursuit of the law and the facts led to a better and
freer America. And for that, all Americans owe the Lincolnesque man
from Haleyville, Ala. _ big-time.
</P>
<P>
   He was a champion of justice at a crucial time for justice in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. said more than once that ``the universe
is on the side of justice.'' In that case, the universe (''God''
may be used synonymously here) provides the means to allow justice
to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   It was not by accident that Eisenhower appointed Frank M.
Johnson Jr. at a time when this nation's capacity for doing justice
and loving mercy was being severely tested.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a ``Star-Telegram'' columnist and editorial
writer. You can e-mail him at cecil &LR; star-telegram.com or call him
at (817) 390-7663. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
