r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STURBIN-COLUMN-TE     07-28 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING STOCK OF BRUTON SMITH'S DRAG-RACING PLANS AT TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A short list of possible motives, altruistic and ulterior, have
surfaced in the week since motorsports developer Bruton Smith
announced plans to build the finest drag strip on the planet at
Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Let's review some of the theories: Smith's decision to go drag
racing is altruistic. He really and truly wants to take the
National Hot Rod Association to the next level with improved
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Smith already has begun delivering with his revamped Bristol
(Tenn.) Dragway, a project that cost Speedway Motorsports Inc. $14
million. Similar price tags have been placed upon the quarter-mile
drag strip under construction at Smith's Las Vegas Motor Speedway,
which has landed a national event weekend on the NHRA schedule in
April 2000, and for the projected facility at TMS in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Smith plans to build corporate suites down the quarter-mile, the
type of innovation that could convince corporate sponsors _ and
live TV _ to give drag racing another shot. Smith's decision to go
drag racing is designed to stick it to Billy Meyer and his plan to
relocate the Texas Motorplex from Ennis to Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, a former Funny Car driver from Waco, is attempting to
complete a master plan and financing with Grand Prairie officials
that would allow him to build a $74 million facility (including
real estate costs) on 500 acres. The Grand Prairie City Council has
discussed a November referendum on a sales tax that would help pay
for the facility.
</P>
<P>
   If Smith can sideswipe the Grand Prairie project and keep Meyer
in Ennis, he stands to improve his chance of trying to entice the
NHRA out of its 15-year exclusivity contract for national events
with Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Smith and Meyer also have a short and nasty history.
It dates to Meyer's announcement in November 1994 that he planned
to build a superspeedway at Pinnacle Park in Dallas _ one day
before Smith and his group announced plans for their project here.
</P>
<P>
   Smith easily won the superspeedway war, and he and Meyer since
have operated under an uneasy truce. But Smith and Eddie Gossage,
TMS' executive vice president and general manager, have taken a
cavalier attitude toward Meyer's Grand Prairie project and his
contract with the NHRA.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has a long memory for those who cross him, and the timing
of Smith's announcement smacks of payback. Smith's decision to go
drag racing is an indication that, despite his public posturing, he
genuinely is worried about landing a second NASCAR Winston Cup date
for TMS. Drag racing potentially offers him another way to ``feed
the monster.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, International Speedway Corp. completed its merger
with Penske Motorsports Inc., a deal announced May 10. The merger
has placed 10 racetracks under the banner of International Speedway
chairman and chief executive Bill France Jr., who also is president
of NASCAR and thus controls Cup race dates.
</P>
<P>
   International Speedway Corp. also is ``developing'' oval tracks
in Kansas City, Chicago, New York and Denver. That is tantamount to
saying each facility will land its first Cup dates before Smith's
tracks in Fort Worth and Las Vegas _ and even International
Speedway's California Speedway _ are granted second dates.
</P>
<P>
   The merger also promises International Speedway Corp. a bigger
chunk of NASCAR's impending consolidated TV package.
</P>
<P>
   If those moves have relegated Smith's Speedway Motorsports Inc.
to a secondary role in NASCARland, perhaps Smith feels that NHRA
drag racing will allow him to rule an alternative empire and keep
his stockholders smiling, whatever the motives.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON: SHARP AIMING TO TAME DOVER'S `MONSTER MILE'
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR driver Sterling Marlin has likened racing a Winston Cup
stock car on the high-banked, all-concrete, half-mile Bristol
(Tenn.) Motor Speedway to flying a jet plane in a gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   That analogy also fits this weekend's stop on the Pep Boys Indy
Racing League schedule. The IRL's open-wheeled cars will spend
Sunday afternoon whipping around the one-mile, high-banked,
all-concrete surface of Dover Downs International Speedway in
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sharp emerged as winner of the IRL's inaugural visit to
the ``Monster Mile,'' its bumpy surface and 24-degree banked turns
last summer. Sharp finished 0.689 seconds ahead of Buddy Lazier in
a race that routinely produced laps run at 183-plus mph with zero
margin for error. The tight confines also resulted in seven caution
periods that consumed 99 of 248 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like a real-life video game for me _ 19-second
laps that feel like 10 seconds,'' Sharp said. ``It's one of the
biggest survival races on our schedule. You've got to have your
wits about you to go for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp scored his first victory of 1999 on the 1.5-mile Atlanta
Motor Speedway quad-oval on July 17. That track also is banked at
24 degrees, but its longer length, wider corners and smoother
surface distinguish it from Dover Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the toughest place we go to,'' said Sharp, who has taken
some comfort in the fact the race has been reduced to 200 laps.
``It's incredibly rough and incredibly bumpy. Until you get it (the
chassis) working on the bumps, you can't even read your dash.
That's pretty wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart, last year's pole-sitter, can attest to how wild.
Stewart was pulling out a healthy lead, until his car's dash
vibrated loose and dropped into his lap. He was forced to pit four
times before the crew could tape the dash back into place. Stewart
finished eighth, 28 laps behind Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``As bumpy as it is, it's another challenge,'' said Sharp, 31.
``Nobody in the IRL wants to go to the same kind of racetracks all
the time. Dover is very unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp's victory at Atlanta vaulted him from a tie for fifth into
second in the points chase, 21 behind Scott Goodyear with four
races remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of points on the table. What I'm excited about
is our pace,'' said Sharp, who shared the 1996 IRL championship
with Buzz Calkins. ``The whole team is pretty pumped up at the
moment. We have that confidence the car is going to roll off the
truck pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS TMS SURVEYS OPTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Speedway Motorsports Inc. engineers are studying the landscape
on the east and west sides of Texas Motor Speedway as possible
sites for the track's new drag strip.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage, TMS' executive vice president and general
manager, said the west side of the speedway, where the front
entrances are located, has paved parking that could double as a pit
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's not a lot of utility service there,'' Gossage
said.
</P>
<P>
   The east side of the property is better serviced by utilities,
but would have the strip and its grandstands fronting Interstate
35.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aesthetically, do we want it located between I-35 and the
oval-track? Is that the view you want to present?'' Gossage said.
``The engineers have got to come up with the most cost-effective
locale. And maybe neither of those are the place to be.'' BAD DASH
FOR `MAD MAX'
</P>
<P>
   Max Papis' heartbreaking last-lap, out-of-fuel loss to Tony
Kanaan in CART's U.S. 500 at Michigan Speedway on Sunday has been
traced to a telemetry glitch in the car's dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The telemetry went out when Max left the pit lane,'' said Tom
Cindric, Team Rahal's team manager. ``If the telemetry freezes up,
the fuel system goes to full rich, or 100 percent. Max tried to
lean out the fuel in the cockpit, but the system was already set at
that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Papis reportedly fell approximately 12 ounces of methanol fuel
short of his first Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series
victory. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Native Texan and two-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion Terry
Labonte, 42, has agreed on a three-year contract with Hendrick
Motorsports. Winner of the Primestar 500 at Texas Motor Speedway in
March, Labonte has driven for Rick Hendrick since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   _ Funny Car driver Ron Capps plans to debut a Victory-built
chassis under his Copenhagen Chevrolet Camaro Z/28 during the
NHRA's Prolong Northwest Nationals at Seattle International Raceway
this weekend. The defending race champion, Capps is winless through
12 events.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pennzoil World of Outlaws season finale at Las Vegas Motor
Speedway has been expanded to three days, Nov. 1-3. Drivers will
compete in full race programs on Monday and Tuesday while
attempting to qualify for Wednesday's finale. LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``God just didn't want me to win today.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Max Papis, after running out of fuel on the last lap of CART's
U.S. 500 Sunday
INSIDE THE NUMBERS ONE SHARP DRIVER
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sharp, a two-time Sports Car Club of America Trans-Am
champion, has adapted from running road and street courses in a
full-fendered car to the open-wheel, all-oval Indy Racing League.
Sharp's IRL career statistics: Year Starts Wins Top 5 Top 10 Laps
