<HEADLINE>
TCU WOMEN'S BASKETBALL COACH LEAVES TO JOIN GOPHERS' STAFF
</HEADLINE>
 WOMEN'S COACH-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Coach Mike Petersen led the TCU women's
basketball team to its first winning season in Division I, to its
first postseason victory and to its first vote in the women's poll.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after three seasons, he's leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen resigned Wednesday to become an assistant men's
basketball coach at Minnesota. The position was offered after the
Golden Gophers hired Dan Monson to replace Clem Haskins earlier in
the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard decision,'' Petersen said. ``In three years, we
have taken TCU from ground zero to where it's on the verge of
making national noise and being nationally recognized. When you
spend the kind of time and make the kind of effort we have, to
decide not be here to enjoy the fruits is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU athletic director Eric Hyman said a national search already
has begun to find a replacement. He said he didn't have a specific
timetable for bringing in a new coach, but would like to have
someone hired ``as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of candidates is led by Horned Frogs assistant coach
Art Prevost, who was on Petersen's original staff. Beyond Prevost,
Hyman said that he had yet to assemble any names.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you like a direction a program is going, you owe it to
yourself to look from within,'' Hyman said. ``I told Mike the
institution is indebted to his accomplishments because what he has
done makes it a much more attractive position.''
</P>
<P>
   When Petersen came to TCU in 1996, the Horned Frogs had won
three games in the previous two seasons combined.
</P>
<P>
   TCU finished 13-14 in its first season under Petersen, 13-15 in
his second and 16-12 last season, earning the Frogs a berth in the
Western Athletic Conference Tournament. They defeated UT-El Paso,
67-58, in the first round for the program's first postseason
victory before losing to New Mexico in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen brought his players to campus Wednesday to break the
news. It was, by all accounts, a teary scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are blown away right now,'' TCU guard Amy Sutton said. ``We
had no clue why they had called us to come down today. Our whole
team, it seemed like from the response, was devastated and hurt.
... Even though he's leaving, he left a family behind. He didn't
score any of the points or any of the baskets. We did, and we're
still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Petersen said the direction the program was heading and his
relationship with the players made it difficult to leave, but his
long-standing friendship with Monson made it difficult to say no.
</P>
<P>
   The two have known each other for more than 15 years. Petersen
will be the best man in Monson's wedding next weekend. Petersen
also served as a men's assistant coach under Monson's father, Don,
at Oregon from 1989-1992.
</P>
<P>
   Monson also brought in another close friend, Bill Walker, an
assistant coach at Central Missouri State, to be an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to have coaches on my staff who know me and my style of
basketball,'' Monson said. ``Mike and Dan both fit this
description. They are excellent coaches, very good friends and they
bring a wealth and variety of experience to the position.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Petersen: ``We've been talking about being on the same
staff together for as long as we've known each other. It's a
tremendous opportunity for me professionally.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
