<HEADER>
A7737 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SANDERS-RETIRES-C     07-28 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDERS-RETIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanders: `It felt like it was time'
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barry Sanders, almost certain to become the NFL's career rushing
leader this season, abruptly retired from football on Wednesday and
took flight to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, only 1,458 yards short of breaking former Chicago Bears
running back Walter Payton's record of 16,726, said his reason for
quitting was simple: He's lost interest in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders, 31, also apparently was discouraged by the Detroit
Lions' failure to build a competitive team, and his relationship
with third-year coach Bobby Ross had soured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I am retiring is very simple,'' Sanders said in a
statement. ``My desire to exit the game is greater than my desire
to remain in it. I have searched my heart through and through and
feel comfortable with this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders arrived in London on Wednesday after a three-hour
delayed, overnight flight from Detroit. Reached by The Associated
Press at Gatwick Airport, Sanders said he planned on staying in
London for several days, and then would travel to Paris or
Amsterdam. Sanders said he'd return home in ``about two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years is a lot of football,'' Sanders said. ``I'm just
really not feeling like playing. It's just getting to that point.
It's not the same game. Really, I've been battling for the last few
years. As I've gotten older, the game has changed in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thinking about doing other things. It's still fun,
but not as fun. It just felt like it was time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would change his mind, Sanders shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's going to happen,'' he said. ``I'm not
really thinking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   David Ware of Atlanta, one of two agents who represents Sanders,
said he told Lions executive vice president Chuck Schmidt of his
client's intentions late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after last season ended, I think he really began to
seriously consider retiring and contemplated what he should do,''
Ware said. ``I really think it took him this long to decide. He's
absolutely sincere.''
</P>
<P>
   Ware said he attempted to change Sanders' mind, but the 1988
Heisman Trophy winner from Oklahoma State wouldn't budge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought that the (NFL career rushing) record was
motivation for him,'' Ware said. ``He's just not that type of
player or person. . . . I have to take him for his word. He said
that mentally he wasn't prepared to play another season. I don't
think he wanted to cheat the fans, so he thought it was better not
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, the former Georgia Tech and San Diego Chargers coach known
for his fiery temperament, said that he made at least 10 telephone
calls to Sanders, and had written him three or four letters in the
offseason, but Sanders never responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal feeling is that we're looking at a situation where
the man got tired of playing the game,'' Ross said. ``Do I feel
that Barry left because of me? No, I don't feel that way at all.
This isn't about me; it's about Barry.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement stunned many in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he retires, it will be a waste of talent,'' said Atlanta
Falcons linebacker Jessie Tuggle. ``I think the guy can play two or
three more years at that level. It would be a lot of wasted
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Falcons coach Dan Reeves: ``He's been an awesome player. I
don't know that anybody's been as big for their team as Barry's
been for his. There's a lot of guys that you can name, but he's
been awesome. Whenever you have a player that's that good for his
team, he's also great for the league. If the guy is sincere and he
hangs it up, you're going to miss a great running back that's one
of the best of all-time, no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This season would have been Sanders' third in a six-year, $36
million contract, which included an $11 million signing bonus. The
Lions have the right to demand back a pro-rated portion, which is
$5.4 million, according to Ware. If Sanders decides to return to
the NFL, he would still be obligated to fulfill the final four
years of his contract with the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' retirement gives Detroit $3.3 million in salary-cap
room. If Detroit traded him to another team, Sanders would still
count $2.1 million against the Lions' salary cap, meaning they'd
probably have to waive four or five players or restructure several
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, which had the NFL's 14th-ranked offense last season,
will probably turn to fourth-round pick Sedrick Irvin, who rushed
for 1,167 yards at Michigan State last season. The Lions also have
five-year veteran Ron Rivers, who rushed for 102 yards on only 19
carries in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
