<HEADER>
A7740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-MCCOY-COX     07-28 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-MCCOY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Great pitching would be a dream-come-true for contenders
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cincinnati Reds relief pitcher Scott Sullivan had
a dream recently, nothing like Martin Luther King's dream, more
like a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dreamed I was traded to the Chicago Cubs,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   For Sammy Sosa?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, more like a box of jock straps,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that leads us to a similar subject.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league baseball teams still in contention are looking for
pitching, including the Cincinnati Reds, but they all seem to be
rummaging around in what amounts to boxes of frayed and well-worn
jock straps. And the teams who own them are asking exhorbitant
prices for inferior products.
</P>
<P>
   Teams out of contention want to get rid of their high-priced
(mostly overpriced) pitching failures. Why are those teams out of
contention? Because the pitchers they are offering weren't good
enough to put their teams in contention. General managers of those
teams are trying to foist their mistakes upon pitch-starved
contenders and contending GM's feel as if they are dealing with
Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   With the failure of Steve Avery, the sore shoulder owned by
Steve Parris, the ouchy rotator cuff of Pete Harnisch, the Reds'
starting staff is held together by baling wire, Scotch tape and
safety pins.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jack McKeon had to rob the bullpen of Dennys Reyes and
Gabe White to start games this week. And who does every team that
talks to general manager Jim Bowden want? Relief pitchers. . .Danny
Graves, Scott Williamson, Reyes, or starter Brett Tomko. As McKeon
and Bowden both put it, ``We'd have to rob Peter to pay Paul.''
</P>
<P>
   If you were general manager of the Reds, would you do any of
this?
</P>
<P>
   Bowden talked to Los Angeles general manager Kevin Malone about
Ismael Valdes. Malone wants Williamson or Graves and a minor-league
prospect. For that, the Reds get a pitcher who is 8-8 with a 3.33
earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is in pursuit of Tampa Bay's Rolando Arrojo, but GM Chuck
LaMarr wants Reyes. For that, the Reds get a pitcher who 2-6 with a
6.62 ERA, was on the disabled list this year with shoulder
tendinitis and is listed as 31, but may be as old as 35. He is a
bargain at $800,000 and isn't eligible for arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, though, has stiff competition for Arrojo. The New York
Yankees had four scouts at his last start, the Cardinals are
interested and Houston was interested. ``They are overplaying their
hand in what they want,'' an Astros scout said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden talked to Anaheim general manager Bill Bavasi about Omar
Olivares. Bavasi wants Graves and starter Brett Tomko. For that,
the Reds get a pitcher who is 8-9 with a 4.05 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same everywhere. Montreal would trade Dustin Hermanson.
Why not? He is 3-10 with a 5.53 ERA. The Cubs would trade Steve
Trachsel. Why not? He is 3-14 with a 6.55 ERA. The Dodgers would
trade Carlos Perez. Why not? He is 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA and is owed
$12.6 million over the next three years. The Rockies would trade
Darryl Kile. Why not? He is 5-10 with a 6.35 ERA and is owed $8
million next year.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sellers market and the demand is so great teams are
going to overspend for underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, Seattle's Jeff Fassero (4-11, 6.86) pitched
against Kansas City's Kevin Appier (8-9, 5.00). Both are available.
Scouts were tripping over each other in the media dining room.
</P>
<P>
   So all this leaves Bowden in a Catch-22. He can add starting
pitching, as bogus and as dubious as some of those guys are, but it
would cost him greatly in his bullpen, the team's strongest asset.
</P>
<P>
   Some stolen advice for Bowden, ``Just say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
