<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAMALANDERSON-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Falcons pull offer; fines await Anderson
</P>
<P>
   By Matt Winkeljohn
</P>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ The Falcons rescinded their latest offer to
running back Jamal Anderson on Wednesday and coach Dan Reeves said
there will be no further contract extension negotiation until the
running back reports to training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons players reported Wednesday to Furman University, where
practice begins at 3 p.m. today. Anderson, an All-Pro last season,
is at home in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offer was pulled off the table at noon,'' Reeves said.
``He gets fined ($5,000) every day he's not here because he does
have a contract. It hurts our . . . team.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 26, led the NFC last season with a franchise-record
1,846 yards on an NFL-record 410 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The final year of his contract calls for a salary of $1.6
million plus another $1 million in incentives triggered last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't say we wouldn't negotiate any more; this is more a
move to protect (the franchise),'' general manager Harold
Richardson said. ``What's to stop a guy from coming in here the
third week of the season and saying, `OK, I'll take that deal'?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an ultimatum; it's just common sense. We want him
here sooner than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Something might happen quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's agent, Jim Sims of Oakland, leaves Friday for a
two-week vacation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get a sense they will try to get a deal done by the end
of training camp, we'll get Jamal in there,'' Sims said.
</P>
<P>
   The next move is Anderson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can say to me they're going to work on it,'' he said,
``something may change. I have every intention of honoring my
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The sides are in agreement on a five- or six-year deal worth
$28million to $34 million, but the signing bonus and yearly salary
schedule remain the holdup.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had sought a bonus of more than $10 million and then
dropped it to $8 million. The Falcons had countered at $6 million
and recently went to $7 million. Also, Anderson and Sims want more
of the money in the first three years and more of the $9million
fifth-year compensation moved to the fourth season.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
