</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
14 UMPIRES SAY UNION'S STRATEGY WAS DOOMED TO FAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While the National League debated which 13 umpires to
jettison from its suddenly crowded staff, a group of 14 umpires
Wednesday lamented the loss of any jobs and said its union
leadership's ``flawed strategy'' had hurt the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the business day, the league had not completed a
task its officials did not pursue with exuberance. ``It's not
easy,'' one baseball official said.
</P>
<P>
   But officials left no question that 13 umpires would be lopped
off the NL staff to which 13 minor league umpires had been added
before 32 umpires rescinded their resignations Tuesday. The task is
expected to be finished Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Umpires in both leagues who had withdrawn their resignations
last week were told their jobs would be safe. However, the umpires
who rescinded Tuesday, after the union lost the initial round of
its court fight, had no guarantee that they would continue working
after Sept. 2, the effective date of the resignations. The American
League had notified nine of its umpires that their resignations had
been accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Only four NL umpires were assured of their jobs. Mark Hirschbeck
never resigned, Wally Bell and Jeff Nelson withdrew their
resignations soon after submitting them and Greg Bonin's letter of
resignation, which the union said he signed, never reached the
league office.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck, Bell and Nelson joined 11 AL umpires in issuing a
statement Wednesday that punctuated the division that the
resignation strategy has created in the Major League Umpires
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major league umpires have been seriously harmed,'' the
statement said, ``because union leadership adopted a flawed
strategy that was doomed to fail from the beginning. The advice to
quit jobs in order to keep them made no sense at all, especially
under a collective bargaining contract that not only ruled out
strikes, but also ruled out `other concerted work stoppage.'''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the loss of 22 jobs, the statement said: ``It grieves
us that more than 20 umpires will apparently lose their jobs as a
result of this flawed and doomed strategy. We have been able to
save some of our colleagues by convincing them not to resign or to
quickly rescind their resignations. If we had not taken a stand,
all major league umpires could be facing the end of their
careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the umpires said, ``It is essential that we proceed
with a realistic view of the world and do what is in the best
interest of all umpires, our families and the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 11 AL umpires who issued the statement, John Hirschbeck,
Joe Brinkman, Terry Craft, Tim McClelland and Durwood Merrill never
resigned, and Gary Cederstrom, Jim Joyce, Dave Phillips, Rocky Roe,
Dale Scott and Tim Welke resigned but rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Welke had been members of the union's board of
directors, but they resigned from the union, John Hirschbeck said,
when they rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   The statement made no mention of Richard Phillips, the union
leader, who designed the resignation strategy. Asked if the signing
umpires would call for Phillips to step down as the union's chief
negotiator, a position that pays him more than $300,000 a year,
John Hirschbeck said: ``At this point, no. We're leaving open our
options at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, a lawyer from Philadelphia, did not return a telephone
call seeking comment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the umpires who issued the statement have not formed a
formal group, John Hirschbeck and Brinkman are considered the
leaders of the anti-Phillips bloc because they have been the most
outspoken in questioning the strategy of the union leadership. They
led the opposition to Phillips when he received a five-year
extension last February.
</P>
<P>
   Two other umpires didn't resign and eight others withdrew their
resignations, but their names were not on the statement. Hirschbeck
said they could not be reached Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, Hirschbeck said, was issued in response to
comments that union leaders and other umpires had made about the
so-called dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time that people, starting with our fellow
umpires, know what this was all about,'' Hirschbeck, a 16-year AL
umpire, said in a telephone interview. ``Accusations have been made
that it was personal, and it's anything but personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Several umpires said the dissidents acted as they did because
they had a vendetta against Phillips. ``Why would I have a vendetta
against Richie?'' Hirschbeck said. ``I felt for a long time that we
have not been receiving good union leadership. That's what this is
all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the statement could widen the division in the union,
Hirschbeck said: ``I think the division that's there has been
created by the union leadership and the flawed strategy. Telling
union members to resign from their jobs was doomed from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck said he did not think the position he and the others
had taken would weaken the union's negotiating position for a new
labor contract to replace the current agreement, which expires Dec.
31.
</P>
</TEXT>
