<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXES-ECOSCENE-ART-NY     07-28 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-ECOSCENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: TAX-CUT PLANS THAT UNDERMINE PROGRESSIVE INCOME
TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Senate debates plans this week to lower taxes, Democrats
point to Republican proposals for $800 billion in cuts over 10
years and cry foul: the rich come away with gargantuan tax
reductions compared with those for everyone else. Republican
leaders respond that their large tax cuts are fair because
high-income families pay a gargantuan share of federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Whose arguments win?
</P>
<P>
   There are two issues. Many budget experts say that congressional
estimates of the effect of the proposed Senate bill and the bill
the House passed last week are stacked with assumptions that make
the tax cuts look more even than they truly are. Estimates by
Citizens for Tax Justice, a liberal research group, which uses
methods akin to those adopted by independent budget experts, show
that the Republican bills pile up tax cuts for high-income families
far beyond their share of the current tax burden.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the fight over numbers, there is a dispute over
principle. The seemingly innocuous idea that the distribution of
federal tax cuts should mirror the distribution of current tax
payments is anything but innocuous.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would cut income-tax rates across the board by 10
percent, reduce the tax on capital gains, phase out the estate tax,
increase tax deductions for married couples and provide several
corporate tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republican bill would cut the bottom income-tax rate
to 14 percent from 15 percent, raise the income threshold for the
28 percent tax bracket, lower the tax on married couples and
increase deductions for retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   According to Citizens for Tax Justice, the House bill is heavily
tilted in favor of the rich. Those making more than $300,000 a
year, the top 1 percent, would receive about 45 percent of the
total tax cut, an average around $54,000 each. By contrast, the 20
percent of taxpayers earning less than about $13,000 would get only
about half a percent of the total cut _ about $30 each.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill distributes the tax cut less unevenly. The top 1
percent of taxpayers would receive about 30 percent of the tax
cuts, and the top 20 percent would receive 76 percent of the cuts.
Estimates by the Treasury Department are similar, though its
numbers for high-income families are somewhat smaller in part
because it does not take account, as Citizens for Tax Justice does,
of proposed cuts in corporate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans offer two rebuttals. First, tables provided by
the House Ways and Means Committee show that the top 2 percent of
taxpayers pay 40 percent of federal income taxes, and the top 15
percent pay about 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Greenstein, director of the Center on Budget and
Policy Priorities, a research group, says that the focus on income
taxes is misleading: ``Perhaps two-thirds of families pay more in
payroll taxes than they do in income taxes. So the share of total
taxes that the richest families pay is considerably smaller than
the tables from the House Republicans indicate.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, the Republicans defend their proposals by pointing to
tables from the Joint Committee on Taxation. These estimates do
take account of payroll and other federal taxes. The numbers show
that the Senate and House bills spread benefits almost evenly so
that the share of tax payments across income groups barely budge.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenstein considers these tables highly misleading. ``The
committee's tables only go through 2004,'' he said. ``But most of
the tax cuts that primarily favor wealthy families _ for example, a
provision in the House bill that prevents high-income families from
using tax shelters to eliminate most of their tax _ would phase in
largely after 2005.'' Besides, the committee's estimates exclude
some provisions, like cutting estate taxes, that overwhelmingly
benefit wealthy families. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Citizens for Tax Justice estimates the effect of all the key
provisions of the tax bills when they are fully carried out. Its
figures show that the tax cuts would go disproportionately to
upper-income families _ their share of the proposed tax cuts exceed
their current share of total tax payments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the group estimates that the 20 percent of
taxpayers with the highest incomes pay 67 percent of total federal
taxes under current law. But these families would receive almost 80
percent of the tax cuts under the House plan and 76 percent under
the Senate plan.
</P>
<P>
   The top 5 percent of taxpayers account for about 40 percent of
payments under current law, but would reap more than 60 percent of
the tax cuts under the House plan and 47 percent under the Senate
measure.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the bottom 60 percent of the families account for
almost 15 percent of current federal tax payments but would receive
only 9 percent of the savings under the House bill and less than 11
percent under the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond economics, there is an important debate over principle.
The Republican sponsors of the tax-cut bills say the cuts rightly
go to the families who pay most taxes. But to accept that principle
accepts the idea that Congress should not use the federal tax
system to alter the distribution of income _ a proposition that
runs counter to the longstanding use of progressive tax rates to
redistribute income from wealthier to poorer families.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when the wage rates of high-paid, educated workers are
soaring above wage rates for everyone else, the Republicans are
calling on the federal government to sit on the sidelines.
Greenstein asks why ``at a time when income disparities are at a
post-World War II high, should we be handing very large tax breaks
to the nation's wealthiest families.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7753 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN-SFC     07-28 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SILENCED DISSIDENTS PUT OUT THE RALLYING CRY IN CYBERSPACE  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ The Berkeley, Calif., protesters demonstrating
outside radio station KPFA have a powerful tool that was not
available to their radical forebears in the 1960s: the Internet.
<P>
   The groundbreaking station may have taken its progressive voices
off the air, but there's no silencing cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had had this back in the '60s for the free speech
movement, it would have been great,'' said Susan Druding, who runs
one of the protest Web sites at www.fsm-a.org. ``It helps when
you're being muzzled by the media.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, angry about management changes at the venerable
lefty broadcaster, have taken their crusade online and
international with a host of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   They may even start Web-casting audio soon, putting the silenced
voices of KPFA onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the battle, the Pacifica Foundation, the
nonprofit parent of KPFA, has its own Web site, at which it posts
its own news releases about the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The country's oldest listener-sponsored station was closed two
weeks ago, shortly after marking its 50th anniversary, and Pacifica
is broadcasting tapes from its archives at its spot at 94.1 FM.
</P>
<P>
   The station has generated quite a bit of news so far this year,
including gunshots fired into Pacifica offices (no one was hurt),
the sudden firings of the KPFA station manager and others, a live
broadcast that caught security guards hauling off radio host Dennis
Bernstein after he discussed the controversy on his show, and the
arrest of more than 100 people at protests outside the station's
Berkeley offices.
</P>
<P>
   But the protests go on, both at the offices and on the Web. The
main protest sites at www.savepacifica.org and www.savepacifica.net
maintain a list of links to other angry listeners. ``People will
have a particular area of the conflict that they know about,'' and
they'll post information about their particular area of expertise,
Druding said.
</P>
<P>
   She cited a Web site at www.SineWave.com/ksvp/reply2divcoa2.htm
that addresses Pacifica's statements about its efforts to bring
greater cultural diversity to the station.
</P>
<P>
   For obvious reasons, organizers couldn't use KPFA to plug last
week's protest concert featuring Joan Baez and Utah Phillips, and
they couldn't afford to buy any ads. So they plastered a few
posters around, sent out lots of e-mail, advertised on the Web _
and engineered a sold-out show with an audience of 3,700 people.
``I really credit a lot of that to the Internet,'' Druding said.
</P>
<P>
   The groups' use of the Net also shows how the medium, for better
or worse, allows people with no formal training to act as
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Druding, who came to Berkeley in 1964 as a marine biology
student, ultimately earned a master's degree in textiles and owns
Straw Into Gold, a Berkeley crafts store specializing in spinning
and weaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going out to the rallies, I had my digital camera, and
I'm pretty good with graphics online, and I thought, I could
document what things look like,'' Druding said.
</P>
<P>
   When she heard rumors that the protesters were chucking Molotov
cocktails, she took photos of children playing in makeshift
sandboxes, people playing soccer in the street and a community of
protesters breaking bread together. ``It does not look like people
making Molotov cocktails,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the KPFA site at www.kpfa.org is barely
changed, except for a note explaining that ``KPFA staff is on
administrative leave. Regularly scheduled programming has been
replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacifica's site at www.pacifica.org looks like business as
usual, but its own news releases at the bottom of the home page are
dominated with headlines about KPFA. The most recent release is
from July 19 _ the day before Pacifica abruptly dismissed its
communications director, Elan Fabbri, and replaced her with San
Francisco image-buffers Fineman Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Fineman hasn't updated the Web site, it probably knows
something about steering Pacifica through the KPFA crisis.
Fineman's own Web site, www.finemanpr.com, describes how it helped
Odwalla map a strategy in the first few days of the E. coli product
recall crisis in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   TALK TALK: It's the domain name that got away. Talk, the new
magazine from former New Yorker and Vanity Fair editor Tina Brown,
is slated to launch next week after a year in the planning stages,
but the publication does not have the coveted cyberspace real
estate of www.talk.com.
</P>
<P>
   That domain name was available, for a price, as recently as
April, when San Francisco media firm Wired Digital sold it to a
telecommunications company in Reston, Va., that went by the name of
Tel-Save.com, and is now called Talk.com.
</P>
<P>
   Talk.com bought www.talk.com for an unspecified sum, but it
didn't fetch anywhere near the record $3 million that Compaq paid
for www.altavista.com. Instead, Talk.com Vice President Ed
Meyercord said his company got the name in a marketing deal that
involved buying ads on such Wired Digital properties as HotBot.
</P>
<P>
   Talk.com, which has long traded under the ticker symbol TALK,
offers long-distance and calling-card plans to Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown had to settle for www.talkmagazine.com. ``There was
never a discussion of talk.com,'' said spokeswoman Hilary Bass.
``It was always talkmagazine.'' The site will launch next week, but
it will only be a stopgap measure until a comprehensive site can
launch at a later date, Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER TECH BIZ PUB? _ In a market that's glutted with
magazines covering the nexus between business and technology, how
could anyone stand one more thing to read? Yet the glut obviously
indicates an interest in the subject, so here comes Mortimer
Zuckerman's Fast Company _ the fat monthly magazine published in
Massachusetts _ with a new quarterly venture, Net Company.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine ``will cover the new world of digital business in
much the same way that Fast Company covers the new world of work,''
according to the company's press release. It debuts on newsstands
August 24 and will go to Fast Company subscribers in the September
issue.
</P>
<P>
   That issue, by the way, clocks a fat 193 ad pages, while Net
Company launches with 11 ad pages.
</P>
<P>
   TECH TV: A new San Francisco company, B3TV, wants to provide
Internet-style e-commerce over television. The company is having
its coming-out party at Red Herring's ``Herring on Hollywood''
conference in Los Angeles next week and promises to announce
partnerships with a local cable station, a cult-hit television show
and a major advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, B3TV chief executive David Kaiser will only
talk about the technology, and the name _ which, as it turns out,
has no meaning. ``We wanted a name that looked like call letters,''
Kaiser said. ``We just made it up. It doesn't stand for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the domain name was available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
