<HEADER>
A7756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEC-MEDIADAYS-COX     07-28 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-MEDIADAYS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuberville switches off Auburn `soap opera'
</P>
<P>
   By Tony Barnhart
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM _ Tommy Tuberville was thrilled on Wednesday to
address the media about the Auburn football team for this season.
</P>
<P>
   Really. Even though the prognosis for the Tigers this fall is
not good. In fact, most preseason magazines have them finishing
last in a competitive SEC Western Division.
</P>
<P>
   But for Tuberville, talking about the relative strengths and
weaknesses of his first Auburn team was preferable to dealing with
all of the negative events that hit the school in the past 10
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auburn hired me to coach a football team, not to sit around
and watch soap operas,'' Tuberville said.
</P>
<P>
   But a soap opera, and a bad one at that, is what Auburn has
becomesince Oct. 23, when coach Terry Bowden suddenly resigned.
Since then just about everybody has taken a shot at the proud
Auburn family.
</P>
<P>
   And the controversy is far from over, given these headlines from
the past 10 days:
</P>
<P>
   _ A judge has ordered former assistant coach Bill Oliver and the
school to mediation over a lawsuit that could get really ugly if it
goes to trial.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kent Partridge, the school's highly respected sports
information director, grew tired of being the middle man in the
fiasco. He has resigned and is going to Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key alumni wondered on the record this week whether a complete
housecleaning might be in order at the athletics department.
</P>
<P>
   When Auburn opens the season on Sept. 4 against Appalachian
State, the media will remind the world again that the Tigers bought
their way out of a game against Florida State. More than one person
will suggest that Auburn's battle cry should be ``War Chicken''
rather than the beloved ``War Eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was a relief, Tuberville said, to be talking about
football finally, even if the talk isn't especially positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have a schedule to play, that gives people
something to focus on,'' he said. ``If we win, that's great. But
even if we lose, people will be talking about the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn's players echoed Tuberville's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that after everything this team has
been through, we're still together,'' defensive tackle Jimmy
Brumbaugh said. ``Now, we all want to focus on football and really
give people something to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuberville knows about taking over programs in trouble. When he
became head coach at Mississippi in 1995, the school was hit with
two years of NCAA probation and the loss of 24 scholarships. Many
people predicted that it would be five or six years before the
football program would recover. By Tuberville's third season, the
Rebels were 8-4 and in the Motor City Bowl. In his final season,
Ole Miss reached the Independence Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot to offer here at Auburn. We have great fans,
great facilities, and a winning tradition,'' he said. ``But right
now, the Auburn family is divided. Our job is to bring them back
together.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Auburn family probably won't be able to rally around a
winning football team. Eight starters return on defense, but the
offense lacks talent at the skill positions. Auburn's top two
running backs from a year ago, Michael Burks and Demontray Carter,
no longer are in the program. Clifton Robinson, the top receiver
from a year ago, still faces rape charges and might not return.
After Robinson, Auburn has no proven receivers. Sophomore
quarterback Gabe Gross completed 44.7 percent of his passes last
year and is fighting a sore arm.
</P>
<P>
   And even without Florida State, Auburn plays the toughest
schedule in the SEC. The Tigers are the only team in the Western
Division that plays all three Eastern Division powers _ Tennessee,
Florida, and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Auburn's players are looking forward to playing _ and
maybe getting a chance at redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to feel like we did last year when we went 3-8,''
tackle Jeno James said. ``That why we're so anxious to get started.
It's the only way we can fix what is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
