<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan shooting for Friday return
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Friday is only a target date for the return of Braves
cleanup hitter Brian Jordan, but he'll have to wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had a second cortisone shot in his right hand on
Wednesday, this shot in a knuckle as opposed to his wrist, and he
is hoping the pain subsides enough for him to return to the lineup
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who was hit by a Mike Thurman pitch on June 22, has been
bothered since. He's been out of the lineup since Sunday to rest
his ailing right hand and right shoulder. He also has a pinched
nerve in his right shoulder but said that's an injury he can play
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can deal with the shoulder, it's the hand,'' Jordan said.
``If I can get my hand all right, I don't mind lacking some power.
I'll keep hitting my line drives.''
</P>
<P>
   If his hand is still bothering him on Friday, Jordan will have a
bone scan to determine if there's a break. No fracture is showing
up on X-rays.Trade talks
</P>
<P>
   As the trade deadline nears, the Braves continue to surface in
potential deals around baseball. In the leadoff hitting/lead field
department, Tony Phillips has resurfaced as a distinct possibility
to join the Braves at the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old has been playing second base for the A's most of
this season but was brought to Oakland to play left field. He's
cooled off since the All-Star break, going 9-for-his-last-53 to
drop his batting average to .234. But his on-base percentage of
.342 is significantly better than the .309 on-base percentage the
Braves leadoff hitters were hitting through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is Cubs shortstop/utility player Jose
Hernandez (.269 with 13 homers, 37 RBIs, .355 on-base percentage),
who the Braves have discussed as an offensive upgrade for the top
of the order. Arizona is also after Hernandez, seeking a
replacement for Andy Fox, but the Braves have been more aggressive
in talks.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' roll
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan still out, Andruw Jones was hitting cleanup against
left-hander Bill Pulsipher on Wednesday night. And the way Jones
has been swinging lately, it makes good sense.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has seven home runs this month, including his 21st of the
season on Tuesday night off Hideo Nomo, keeping pace with Ryan
Klesko, who has eight home runs this month and Chipper Jones, who
has 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being real patient,'' Jones said. ``I'm seeing the ball
good. I know what pitches they're going to throw. I know the
situation. With a man on second, I'm not just going to hack.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for his slow starts, Jones would have an easy shot at 40
home runs. He's on pace to hit 33 home runs, which is two more than
he had last season. Jones hit .272 with four home runs this April
and in his three major league seasons he's hit .240 in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully one day I'll start good in April so I can make an
All-Star team,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly . . .
</P>
<P>
   Braves trainer Dave Pursley said Dr. James Andrews had reviewed
Odalis Perez's MRI and has recommended he go ahead with surgery to
repair his torn medial collateral ligament. The surgery hasn't been
scheduled yet. . . .Reliever John Hudek rejected his minor league
assignment with the Braves, as expected. He has until Friday to
clear waivers and if he does, the Braves will release him. Hudek
was 0-1 with a 6.48 ERA in 15 appearances for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Thomas Stinson contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
