<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKINGHOUSE-DISCRIM-     07-28 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKINGHOUSE-DISCRIM-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SUES MORGAN STANLEY IN SEX BIAS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For more than a dozen years, Allison K. Schieffelin
was on Wall Street's fast track. One of a small number of women who
specialize in selling exotic financial products, Ms. Schieffelin
thrived at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, one of the finance
industry's most respected firms. She took home well in excess of $1
million each year. She felt certain she would became a managing
director, the equivalent of partner.
</P>
<P>
   All that began to unravel a few years ago. Ms. Schieffelin
claimed that her exclusion from male-only events, like golf outings
and visits to Manhattan strip clubs, hurt her chances of bonding
with top executives. She was passed over when she first became
eligible to become a managing director in late 1996. She was
bypassed in 1997 as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1998, her boss made it plain that she would
probably never be promoted, telling her that ``not everyone gets
managing director.'' Men who contributed less to the firm were
promoted, according to a recounting of her views, available in
legal documents.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schieffelin's claims are so far untested in court. But the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission has launched a sweeping
investigation into Morgan Stanley's pay and promotion policies as
they affect women. The commission's decision seems likely to make
Ms. Schieffelin's complaint a test case of what some women have
called Wall Street's glass ceiling, an invisible barrier that they
say blocks even the most successful female bankers and traders from
the top executive jobs in finance.
</P>
<P>
   To file a sex discrimination lawsuit, an individual first has to
apply to the EEOC. At some point, the agency could either sue on
her behalf or free her to file her own lawsuit in court.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the EEOC took Morgan Stanley to U.S. District
Court in New York, seeking to force the firm to release information
the agency has been seeking as part of its investigation. The
action came after Morgan Stanley failed to comply with a subpoena
from the federal authority that sought data on its promotion and
compensation policies. The commission is now seeking a court order
forcing Morgan Stanley to turn over all of the subpoenaed
information. That court filing made public a discrimination charge
filed with the commission by Ms. Schieffelin late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Her complaint, which still has not been filed publicly, also
alleges that Morgan Stanley retaliated against her after the firm
learned that she was contemplating a discrimination lawsuit.
Seeking to prevent Ms. Schieffelin from filing a lawsuit in court,
Morgan Stanley took peremptory action against her in an industry
arbitration forum, effectively suing one of its own employees
before she had filed any kind of complaint. The maneuver failed
when the arbitration board of the New York Stock Exchange rejected
Morgan Stanley's efforts to force the matter into arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The charge of acting aggressively when confronted with a
complaint by an employee echoes some allegations raised in an
unrelated racial discrimination lawsuit filed against Morgan
Stanley by a dismissed black employee, Christian Curry. The firm's
actions in the Curry case _ Morgan Stanley secretly paid a police
informant involved in arranging a sting operation against the
ex-employee _ prompted an investigation by the Manhattan district
attorney earlier this year. That investigation has since been
dropped and charges were never filed; prosecutors said they
concluded the firm had exercised poor judgment but did not have
criminal intent.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission's court filing makes clear that Morgan
Stanley objected to the commission's subpoena on the grounds that
it was overly broad in seeking more information than might be
necessary to determine whether the firm discriminated against Ms.
Schieffelin. The court filing also recounts a Morgan Stanley
argument that it was concerned that by complying with a request to
supply home phone numbers and addresses for its employees would
invade their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The commission says in the same filing that its request for
information from Morgan Stanley is justified given the fact that it
is examining whether or not there is a pattern of discrimination at
the firm.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to Morgan Stanley said that the firm conducted an
internal investigation that found Ms. Schieffelin's charges of
discrimination to be without merit. This person also defended
Morgan Stanley's peremptory legal action against Ms. Schieffelin as
a prudent step to protect the firm against baseless lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Carleton Fiorina, Hewlett-Packard's new chief executive, may
have declared last week that the glass ceiling is a thing of the
past. But women have complained about discrimination on Wall Street
for years, claiming that the finance industry has a culture of
machismo that tends to exclude women. In recent years women have
filed class-action lawsuits against Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and
Citigroup's Salomon Smith Barney unit, attracting attention from
the media, civil-rights groups and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schieffelin's case is a bit unusual, however, in part
because she remains at the firm. As a senior saleswoman in the
convertible bond department, Ms. Schieffelin, 38, manages client
accounts and has in recent years played a prominent role in
recruiting business school graduates to work at Morgan Stanley. She
has also been paid like a star, earning $1.35 million in salary and
bonus in 1998, and $1.25 million the year before. Some men in the
department who have worked at the firm for a similar amount of time
did not take home as much, said her lawyer, Wayne Outten.
</P>
<P>
   ``She intends to stay there. She is trying to reform the
institution,'' Outten said. ``Someone has to speak up, and who
better than someone like Allie, who has an impeccable record.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schieffelin declined to comment on her complaint. Her lawyer
cited Morgan Stanley's strictly enforced rules that prohibit
employees from speaking to the media without authorization.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Boston College and Kellogg Graduate School of
Management at Northwestern University, Ms. Schieffelin began her
career at Morgan Stanley in 1986 and never left. Outten said she
was the ``archetypal Morgan Stanley person,'' committed to do
whatever it took to advance at the firm as the highest priority in
her life. Ms. Schieffelin, who is divorced, has no children.
</P>
<P>
   One of the top ``producers,'' or income-producing salespeople,
in convertible bonds, Ms. Schieffelin claims credit in her EEOC
complaint for helping develop a new online system for tracking
prices of convertible bonds that are not traded on exchanges. She
also helped to develop ``Road Show Link,'' a way to broadcast
investment banking sales tours on the Internet for people who
cannot attend in person.
</P>
<P>
   Outten said his client was the No. 1 ranked salesperson for a
custom convertible bond product that was highly touted by Morgan
Stanley in 1996, the first year she became eligible for promotion
to managing director. He said her performance reviews, as well as
her salary, gave every indication that she was a top performer
destined for promotion. When she was denied promotion, Morgan
Stanley effectively capped her salary, Outten said, adding that
managing directors in her department are believed to make in excess
of $3 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to Morgan Stanley disputes Ms. Schieffelin's
description of her performance at the firm. This person, who
declined to be identified further, said Ms. Schieffelin was a
middle-ranking salesperson. This person also said that bosses and
colleagues wrote in their reviews of her performance that she was
not a team player, a key criterion for managing directors.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Things began to go wrong for Ms. Schieffelin in 1995, her
complaint claims, when she filed internal sexual harassment charges
against a superior. The complaint says that Morgan Stanley
responded promptly to her charge and handled it properly but that
her career suffered thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   In her complaint, she said she was excluded from events that
were bonding opportunities for men at the firm and valuable chances
to develop relationships with key clients. She cited a five-day
annual golf outing in Doral, Fla., to which clients of hers were
invited but she was not. Male colleagues in her department also
took her clients to men's clubs like Scores in Manhattan, sometimes
without her knowledge, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schieffelin also recounted in her complaint that a boss once
told her that she was ``snippy'' during tense trading situations.
Ms. Schieffelin said that men in the department who exhibited the
same characteristics would be praised for being aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley declined to comment on Ms. Schieffelin's claims
or the commission's lawsuit Wednesday. A spokesperson said that the
firm has a long track record of promoting women and minorities and
prides itself on having a diverse work force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
