construction, threatening both its look and its historic integrity.
(Rob Benchley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1999 -- CLARK-RETIRE, 07-28 --
Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, right,
confers with Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme NATO commander, in
April prior to the NATO anniversary ceremony in the Capitol
Rotunda. NATO officials said Clark was taken aback by the
suddenness of the decision to retire him early and move Gen. Joseph
Ralston, vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to replace
him. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1999 -- CIR-CROSSWORD, 07-28 --
With many crossword software programs to choose from, you should be
clear about what you are looking for before you purchase. Some
programs excel in layout and personalization, while others include
large dictionaries to help you come up with word options. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- July 28, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 07-28
-- The typical hot water heater is a self-contained appliance that
works automatically. Unless the unit malfunctions, most homeowners
rarely give it a second thought. Most hot water heaters last about
10 years, but this life span can often be extended if the unit is
properly cared for. An annual inspection followed by a little
routine maintenance can often keep your hot water heater
functioning properly. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times
Illlustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SAN RAFAEL, Calif. -- July 28, 1999 --
CIR-PIRATED-FILMS-2, 07-28 -- Gordon Radley, president of Lucasfilm
and producer of ``Star Wars: Episode I - The Phantom Menace'' -
perhaps the most widely pirated film to date. ``The fact that
movies can be disseminated digitally on the Internet, illegally, is
a serious concern,'' he says. ``Our copyright laws have been there
since the time of the Constitution. Just because there's a new
technological advancement doesn't change things in any way.''
(Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) HOBOKEN, N.J. -- July 28, 1999 -- CIR-PIRATED-FILMS-1,
07-28 -- A pirated copy of ``Star Wars: Episode I - The Phantom
Menace'' is played on a home PC's CD ROM drive. The film is
contained on 2 CDs and contains about 2 gigabytes of information.
(Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1999 -- CIR-PHONES-DRIVING, 07-28
-- It's not hard to find drivers engrossed in conversations that
just won't wait as they drive along the streets of New York.
Phoning while driving has been banned in several countries,
including Israel, Spain, Brazil and parts of Australia. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1999 -- CLINTON-FLOATER, 07-28 --
President Bill Clinton reacts while getting a pin from John Feeney,
vice president of Boys Nation, at the White House on Wednesday. It
was as a member of Boys Nation that Clinton met John F. Kennedy in
1963. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HINGHAM, Mass. -- July 28, 1999 -- TV-ROGERS-ARTHUR-BOS,
07-28 -- Marc Brown, left, with Fred Rogers in February. On a sunny
morning in February, Rogers, of ``Mr. Rogers' Neighborhood'' fame,
met Brown, creator of ``Arthur,'' at Brown's home on Main Street.
The summit meeting between two members of public television's royal
family, children's program branch, was taped for later broadcast on
Rogers's show, and Wednesday (July 28) was the day. (George
Rizer/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- July 28, 1999 -- FOOD-GNOCCHI-BOS, 07-28 --
Joe Tinnirello with samples of some of the pastas he makes for
Terramia Ristorante. The pastas are Ravoli, Egg Cappellini, Potato
Gnocchi, Spinach Fettuccine and Pappardelle. Tinnirello, 24, born
and bred in East Boston, has cut his eyeteeth almost literally in
this little restaurant, learning traditional Italian cooking from
chef and co-owner Mario Nocera in the six years that Terramia has
become a success story. (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PLYMOUTH, Mass. -- July 28, 1999 -- MA-ANCESTORS-BOS,
07-28 -- Lois Brewster, whose ancestor William Brewster was a
minister on the original Mayflower, stands near the Mayflower II.
Massachusetts is known for nothing if not its historic figures. But
while many folks can rightfully claim to descend from, say,
Pilgrims aboard the Mayflower or rebels in the Revolution, only a
handful of such offspring carry the surnames of their famous
forebears. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WINCHESTER, Mass -- July 28, 1999 -- MUSIC-PLATTERS-BOS,
07-28 --Herb Reed, an original member of The Platters, holds a gold
record for the group's song, ``Remember When,'' one of the group's
several gold records, during an interview on Tuesday. To musicians
like Reed, who founded the original Platters and coined the group's
name more than 45 years ago, the growing prevalence of copycat
bands, many of whom pass themselves off as originals, amounts to
blatant musical plagiarism. (Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1999 -- TAX-CONGRESS-2, 07-28 --
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan before the Senate Banking
Committee on Wednesday. Greenspan said that Congress ``probably
would be better off'' delaying a tax cut. The central bank
chairman's warning, which he has made before, was renewed as the
Senate prepares to debate a $792 billion Republican tax cut
proposal. (Paul Hosefros/New York times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1999 -- TAX-CONGRESS, 07-28 --Sen.
Connie Mack, R-Fla., right, listens to Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
during a news conference on Wednesday about tax issues being dealt
with by the U.S. Senate. The Senate opened debate on its version of
the tax bill, with amendments voted on through the night. A final
vote is not expected until Thursday. (Paul Hosefros/New York times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) EDINBURGH, Scotland -- July 28, 1999 --
SCOTLAND-MUSEUM-2, 07-28 -- The interior of the new Museum of
Scotland in Edinburgh's medieval old town. The notion that Scotland
is a more beguiling place than the dark and rugged land it occupies
has found fitting expression in the alluring new museum. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) EDINBURGH, Scotland -- July 28, 1999 --
SCOTLAND-MUSEUM-1, 07-28 -- The new Museum of Scotland in
Edinburgh's medieval old town. The notion that Scotland is a more
beguiling place than the dark and rugged land it occupies has found
fitting expression in the alluring new museum. (Jonathan Player/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GRACKO, Yugoslavia -- July 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-2, 07-28 --
A British NATO soldier stands guard as Serbs walk past to a
cemetery during a funeral procession on Wednesday for 14 Serbs
killed recently near the village, some 15 miles southwest of
Pristina. As a NATO helicopter buzzed overhead, hundreds of
villagers mourned 14 Serb farmers and demanded better NATO
protection from ethnic violence in Kosovo. The 14 men were killed
with automatic weapons fire in an attack Kosovo's Serbs accuse
ethnic Albanians of committing. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) GRACKO, Yugoslavia -- July 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-1, 07-28 --
Serb family members mourn one of 14 Serbs killed recently in the
village, 15 miles southwest of Pristina, the provincial capital of
Kosovo, on Wednesday. Some 350 mourners attended the funeral for
the 14 men who were killed with automatic weapons fire in a wheat
field near the village. Kosovo's Serbs accuse ethnic Albanians in
the slayings. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOUSTON -- July 28, 1999 -- RACETRACK-CHAPLAIN-HNS, 07-21
-- Chaplain Randall ``Randy'' Weaver, an Assemblies of God
minister, prays with jockeys prior to the start of races at the Sam
Houston Race Park. Since the racetrack's opening in in 1994,
Weaver, 44, has ministered to hundreds of track employees, jockeys,
grooms, trainers and racing fans. ``I really didn't want to go into
the ministry,'' he says. ``God just about had to send a lightning
bolt with a note on it in order for me to get the picture.'' There
are 39 racetrack chaplains nationwide.( D. Fahleson/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
