<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Wednesday, 07/28/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1999 -- FIENNES-BOOK, 07-28 -- From
left, Joseph, Sophie and Ralph Fiennes worked to publish their
mother's book. Now, almost six years after her death, ``Blood
Ties,'' written under her maiden name, Jennifer Lash, has been
published to growing notice, thanks to the efforts of some of her
children and their considerable star power. ``She had an urgency to
realize this book,'' says Ralph (pronounced Rafe, the English way),
36. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1999 -- NY-WILLIAMS-AIDS, 07-28 --
Nushawn J. Williams during an interview to be broadcast Thursday
night. Williams, the drifter from Brooklyn who officials say may
have infected more than a dozen young women and girls in upstate
New York with the virus that causes AIDS, now says that he may have
had sex with as many as 300 women. (WPIX/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1999 -- GORE-ISSUES, 07-28 --
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, fourth from left, and
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, left, look on as Vice President
Al Gore attacks Republican tax cut proposals on Tuesday. Hardly a
day goes by that Gore does not express his position on one topic or
another. The blizzard of proposals is the essence of the Gore
presidential campaign, designed to show voters that the he has
ideas and experience and, by contrast, to suggest that his
opponents have not. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) MIAMI -- July 28, 1999 -- FLA-PRISONS, 07-28 -- The nine
men who beat death-row inmate Frank Valdez to death June 19 were
all corrections officers who investigators say either witnessed,
knew about or took part in the beating, but they are not talking.
``We have classified this as a homicide,'' says Elizabeth Hirst, a
spokeswoman for the Florida Department of Law Enforcement, which
investigates suspicious deaths in the state prison system. ``We
don't know exactly how many people took part in the killing.''
(Department of Corrections/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CUERNAVACA, Mexico -- July 28, 1999 -- MEXICO-SPA-HNS,
07-26 -- Las Quintas is a quiet oasis of calm amidst the hustle of
Cuernavaca. The hotel and spa is set among flowering gardens, a
statuary and green lawns. (Julie Cooper/San Antonio Express-News
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- July 28, 1999 -- CIR-WALKMAN, 07-28 -- The
success of the original Walkman created the category of personal,
portable technology and filled consumer's pockets with an array of
new products in an expanding range of formats. Clockwise, from
upper left: Pansonic SL-Sw870 CD player; Sony PSYC Walkman; Casio
portable television; Sharp minidisc player-recorder. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) DAYTON, Ohio -- July 28, 1999 -- CHERRY-TOMATOES-COX,
07-28 -- At this point in the summer, cherry tomatoes ripen in
waves. Vines, like this one, are weighted down with clusters of
ripe tomatoes. Cherry tomatoes come in a variety of sizes, colors
and sweetness, from the so-called yellow pear to red grape
tomatoes. (Jim Witmer/Dayton Daily News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- July 28, 1999 -- BIG-BOARD-SURVIVE, 07-28 --
Richard Rosenblatt on the floor of the New York Stock Exchange of
which he is a member. Skeptics are once again predicting the demise
of the Big Board. Its trading floor in lower Manhattan is no match,
they say, for the new computer-driven systems that are attracting a
growing share of the trading that traditionally has been done on
the exchange and its arch-rival, the Nasdaq market. Rosenblatt
,though, is optimistic. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) KINSHASA, CONGO -- July 28, 1999 -- CONGO-FATHER-SON,
07-28 -- Saolona Bemba, the minister of Economy and Industry in the
government of President Laurent Kabila, pleads with his son
Jean-Pierre to abandon his rebellion and return home during an
interview on a television program titled ``With Open Heart.'' Few
in Congo would have predicted the spectacle of so famous a father
and son accusing each other of betrayal, two men who had defied
this country's political gravity for decades. (Norimitsu Onishi/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BOSTON -- July 28, 1999 -- FAT-IMAGE, 07-28 -- From
left, Elizabeth Fisher, of Baton Rouge, La., Cathy Woods, of
Houston, Texas, and Francine Juneau, also of Baton Rouge, in the
lobby of the hotel hosting the national convention for the National
Association To Advance Fat Acceptance on Wednesday. About 700
members are taking part in the five-day convention billed as an
effort to spread the message that no one should feel self-conscious
about their weight. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NANTUCKET, Mass. -- July 28, 1999 -- NANTUCKET-DEVELOP,
07-28 --A house under construction on Mill Street maximized use of
a small lot. Nantucket, an idyllic, mist-covered island 30 miles
out at sea, is under siege. Once treasured by a relative few for
its cobblestone streets, its picket fences bathed in icy-pink roses
and its isolation, Nantucket is awakening to the din and clash of
construction, threatening both its look and its historic integrity.
(Rob Benchley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- July 28, 1999 -- CLARK-RETIRE, 07-28 --
