<HEADLINE>
LOONY TIME, OR IS COWBOYS' DEFENSE REALLY GOOD?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Insanity already seemed to prevail over
in-house evaluation of the Dallas Cowboys' defensive future. So, if
a certified loony like Alonzo Spellman is added to the mix, as the
current speculation goes, there's obviously no problem with Alonzo
being a fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody else seems to think we'll suck, while we think we'll
be pretty good,'' was Wednesday's perfect evaluation from defensive
coordinator Dave Campo.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   Like where's the hand-wringing and excuse-making and
brow-sweating over on-going unanswered questions about the
``Leon-Deion'' issue?
</P>
<P>
   Defensive survival would seem to depend on when those two step
on the field again.
</P>
<P>
   But Chan Gailey opened training camp here the other day by
saying, ``Why is everyone so concerned about the defense? I'm
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones, the always bubbly owner, confidently added to the
show of unity by predicting, ``Our defense will rank top 10 in the
league, maybe top eight.''
</P>
<P>
   Even by normal Jerry standards, this claim is grandiose.
</P>
<P>
   And this is also the same Jones who said Wednesday he is seeking
additional bodies, via slim free-agency pickings or a trade, to
upgrade the defense. Spellman, the once-mentally troubled former
Bears' defensive end, was mentioned on an ESPN report Tuesday night
as talking to the Cowboys about employment.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, Jones had no interest over the summer in bringing
back Charles Haley, who is considered locker room trouble by many
at Valley Ranch. When Haley signed a large contract with the 49ers
this week, Jerry shrugged it off by indicating Charles couldn't
have passed a Cowboys' physical because of his back ailments.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Cowboys' defense is viewed league-wide as mainly a
bunch of nobodies or has-beens, and that's even if ``Leon-Deion''
are in the mix. Frankly, Leon Lett performed like a has-been
candidate last season.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, however, Campo has seen it all and heard it all before.
The defensive coordinator for four seasons, he also goes back to
1989 as an original member of Jimmy Johnson's first staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a training camp in the last eight years,
even when we were winning (Super Bowls), where the doubts didn't
center on the defense,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Modesty prevented Campo from adding that in most every season
the defense has also performed way above summertime expectations.
Starting with Dave Wannstedt, and then with Butch Davis, and now
with Campo, the history of the defense is built around being a
pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer is a bit different,'' Campo said, ``because we
have a bunch of names the media doesn't recognize. When that
happens, expectations will be low. From my standpoint, the
personnel we will line up with, I happen to like.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lett awaits suspension time by the league, Campo noted, ``At
this point, he's just a name who's not here.''
</P>
<P>
   And Deion? ``If we don't have him, then we don't have him. My
only concern has to be with people who are here.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on current information, the Cowboys will flunk every major
defensive requisite for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   They can't stop the run, can't rush the passer and their
shut-down-half-the-field cornerback has only nine good toes.
</P>
<P>
   But while reading a national football publication this week,
Campo admitted to being jolted by an opinion that the Cowboys'
defensive line will rank No. 30 in a 31-team league.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought that was true, we could all go home right now,''
he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   No one says so publicly, to avoid early pressure, but Campo and
defensive line coach Jim Bates are eager to see second-year man
Michael Myers filling in at Lett's tackle spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early yet,'' said Campo, being cautious, ``but Myers
reminds me so much of Russell Maryland. He's fast, quick, a
tireless worker, and has a football mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Up and down the defensive line, plus at linebacker, and even in
a Deion-less secondary, Campo claims he sees players and
playmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The description of our defense is fast, young and hungry,'' he
added. ``It will be the fastest defensive unit we've had. I like
that. We got away from the speed scheme over the years. I'm glad to
get back to it. To me, speed is the most critical weapon in today's
NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey raised eyebrows the other day when he described defensive
end Kavika Pittman as ``a potential star.'' Well, he's fast, but
until a slight spurt last season, Pittman also was seemingly
hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   Contradictions are everywhere. It's crazy. Welcome, Alonzo. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
