<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-PARADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Downtown parade honoring Armstrong is Aug. 9
 &HT;    By By Gary Estwick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The city of Austin will host ``Austin's
Celebration of Lance Armstrong,'' a parade for the Tour de France
champion on Aug. 9, said Karl Haussman, director of the Lance
Armstrong Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Haussman said Wednesday that a definite time has not been set
for the parade, although 7 p.m. has been mentioned as a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Event organizers expect as many as 15,000 spectators for the
parade.
</P>
<P>
   The parade will start at the Capitol, proceed south on Congress
Avenue and finish at Auditorium Shores off Riverside Drive.
</P>
<P>
   After the parade, which is scheduled to have floats and a local
marching band, Armstrong will be part of a ceremony that will
include Austin Mayor Kirk Watson. Gov. George W. Bush's attendance
has not been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Several opening and headline bands will perform at Auditorium
Shores after the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Haussman said the parade will be supported financially through
corporate and individual donations. Excess proceeds will be donated
to the Lance Armstrong Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the city's chance to show Lance their appreciation and
support,'' Haussman said.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Rodriguez, marketing director of Capital Sports Ventures,
said Austinites seem ready to celebrate Armstrong's victory.
Armstrong's agent, Bill Stapleton, is president of Capital Sports
Ventures, a sports marketing agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the response that we have seen in our office
through the office phones and the Web site, the people of Austin
couldn't be prouder with Lance Armstrong's accomplishment,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at him as an example of the possibility of
overcoming the odds, looking at death in the face and returning to
an even better lifestyle than he had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, diagnosed with testicular cancer in 1996, has made a
full recovery and dominated the 86th Tour de France that ended
Sunday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Estwick writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
