<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0518 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GWBUSH-FAITH-COX     07-28 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GWBUSH-FAITH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush would broaden government, faith-based organization ties
 &HT;    (EDS: WITH SIDEBARS _ FAITH-PRESIDENT and FAITH-WHAT. This is
the third in an occasional series on presidential campaign issues
and Gov. George W. Bush's record by The Austin
American-Statesman.)By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Anne Cancino bagged groceries at H.E.B. and
tested computer chip wafers on a Motorola assembly line, but she
always dreamed that a college degree would make her ``something
bigger.'' Obstacles, though, loomed large. Cancino had three young
children and no husband. Her mother told her she wasn't smart
enough for college. Eventually, she stopped working to spend more
time with her kids, relying on welfare checks and food stamps to
get by.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Interfaith, a coalition of churches, synagogues and
schools, gave Cancino the tools to dig herself out. The group's
Capital Idea program offered math and reading classes, child care,
housing help. Though government can and does provide all that,
Capital Idea's teachers gave her something more: faith in herself.
Cancino, 21, recently passed the state's college entrance exam and
is about to enroll in Austin Community College to become a
semiconductor technician.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush argues that privately run, taxpayer-funded
programs like Capital Idea can transform lives in ways that
government can't, and he has pushed hard for more ties between
Texas and ``faith-based'' and community groups. There are plenty of
success stories like Cancino's, but state officials don't have
solid empirical evidence on the performance of faith-based programs
_ in fact, they don't even know for sure how many of them get
taxpayer money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the front-running GOP presidential contender, said last
week that he would expand the relationship between government and
faith-based organizations by allowing such groups to use taxpayer
money to provide any social service now delivered by government.
The other presidential candidates, Democrat and Republican alike,
have also endorsed a greater role for faith-based groups.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said he wouldn't ask any group to ``compromise its
core values and spiritual mission'' to get public dollars. But
critics worry that might violate the constitutional ban on
promoting religion.
</P>
<P>
   Even though religious groups have been getting government money
for years, the Supreme Court has heard only a handful of cases
challenging the practice, and the constitutional boundaries remain
fuzzy. If the partnerships multiply, so will the legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``needs to be aware that it's a very complicated task. It's
way more than 'You guys run our welfare program in the state of
Texas,''' said Oliver Thomas, a Baptist preacher and civil rights
lawyer who is a special counsel to the National Council of
Churches. ``If we take that kind of simplistic approach, there will
be widespread abuses, lawsuits and eventually federal judges will
step in and shut down these programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking time out from a college prep class last week, Cancino
wiped tears from her cheeks as she talked about how Capital Idea
has changed her life. ``I really appreciate what they did for me,''
she said. ``They make you feel like, 'Oh, yeah, I can do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its affiliation with Austin Interfaith, religion isn't
part of the program at Capital Idea. But it provided services that
would be tough to find at a state office. One teacher, Eva
Lleverino, helped Cancino find diapers late one night when she
couldn't afford to buy them and gave her money to cover the deposit
on her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``State workers have a mindset of 8-5,'' said Lleverino, who
used to work at the Texas Workforce Commission. ``We don't require
all that red tape to get accepted and get going on something. We
just want them to finish their training and be able to succeed in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Unencumbered by regulation and inspired by their faith,
religious groups can succeed where government fails, many people
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a recognition that human life at its heart is a mystery
and that we are persons not statistics, and faith-based groups seem
to know that,'' said the Rev. Thomas W. Currie III, who chaired
Bush's 1996 task force on faith-based groups. ``They try to deal
with them as a whole person, rather than seeing them as a potential
recipient of a government program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Charitable choice,'' a part of the 1996 federal welfare reform
law, has allowed states to forge more faith-based ties. It allows
them to give money to faith-based groups to provide job training
and other services to former welfare recipients, as long as there
are secular alternatives. Bush, who has also signed bills easing
regulations on religious organizations, has made Texas a leader in
implementing ``charitable choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Bush hopes to do for America what he's done for Texas. He
has promised that a Bush White House would ``look first'' to
community and faith-based groups in addressing social problems, and
he pledged ``a commitment to pluralism'' in choosing which groups
to support.
</P>
<P>
   Bush didn't, however, talk about how he would prevent government
support of faith-based groups from slipping into government support
of certain religions.
</P>
<P>
   A Brenham welfare-to-work program that uses some Department of
Human Services dollars illustrates how ``charitable choice'' can
blur the line between church and state. The program, which is
sponsored by eight local businesses and eight local churches,
includes Bible classes designed to show the value of work.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas says such programs prove that ``charitable choice'' lacks
sufficient safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can just hand money to the First Baptist
Church, pat them on the back and say, 'We trust you to provide
secular child care.' There's going to be abuses in that kind of
system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, it may not be possible to treat every faith-based
group equally when there is limited government money. In choosing
which groups to support, government also might be put in the
position of deciding which beliefs are acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Faith-based groups don't get any special scrutiny in Texas. A
Bush aide serves as a ``clearinghouse'' for faith-based groups and
is compiling a database to track them, but there isn't a central
state office. Texas agencies monitor all of their contractors to
make sure taxpayer money isn't being wasted, and contracts with
faith-based groups prohibit proselytizing. But state officials
don't always know which of its contractors are faith-based, let
alone how they are using religion in their programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Workforce Commission, which as the state's primary
welfare-to-work agency has numerous financial contracts with
faith-based groups, can't say exactly how many it deals with, or
how much money it gives to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't track these programs like you would think we would
track them,'' said commission spokesman Larry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that the only way to ensure that faith-based groups
that get public money aren't promoting their religion is to require
them to hire workers without regard to faith. Under current law,
faith-based groups that get government money can't discriminate in
serving clients but can hire whomever they want.
</P>
<P>
   But many faith-based groups would rather do without government
help if it means dropping religion from their programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long history of believing that with government money
comes government control,'' said Weston Ware of Texas Baptist
Christian Life, the public policy arm of the Texas's largest
Baptist group. ``We're basically of the position that church and
state should be kept separate, and that we as a denomination
shouldn't use the coercive powers of government or powers of
taxation to line our own pockets or fulfill our religious agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. Kim Sue Lia Perkes contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
