<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUBURN GLAD OFF-SEASON IS OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Looking forward to football season is a given
in the Southeastern Conference. But at Auburn, the season could
have started Wednesday and it would not have been too early.
</P>
<P>
   Playing games _ even with a team that is expected to trail the
pack in the SEC West _ will provide welcome distractions. The past
nine months have been anything but plain on The Plains, producing
enough negative stories to fill a hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come through some tough times and we're still
together,'' senior defensive tackle Jimmy Brumbaugh said Wednesday
at the Southeastern Conference's football media days. ``It's good
to know that in two weeks we'll be starting practice and in about
six weeks we'll play our first game. Then maybe we can give
everybody something else to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   The off-season has been filled with talk of last season's messy
resignation of head coach Terry Bowden, Auburn buying out of a date
with Florida State in the season opener and the ongoing lawsuit
involving former interim coach Bill Oliver and the university.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-8 season in this football-mad state would provide enough
discussion topics to fill the typical off-season for any football
program. Auburn hired a public relations firm to help with the
onslaught of problems and questions. That is atypical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has all seemed rapid fire,'' first-year coach Tommy
Tuberville said. ``I've made decisions that I thought needed to be
made to get this team back on its feet. They didn't hire me to sit
around and watch soap operas.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an apt description for Auburn's off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The mess started with Terry Bowden's resignation last October.
Bowden stepped down as coach because he was convinced that Auburn
trustee and power broker Bobby Lowder was maneuvering to get Bowden
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Bill Oliver was appointed interim coach.
Oliver is suing the school because he believes that athletic
director David Housel told him he would be the new coach.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the school hired Tuberville of Mississippi for
approximately $800,000 a year (after agreeing to settle Bowden's
contract for $620,000). Tuberville, who had considered taking the
Arkansas job two years ago, left few friends behind in Mississippi
because of his perceived lack of loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn took a publicity hit earlier this year when it announced
that it was paying $500,000 to buy its way out of the season opener
against Florida State. Originally scheduled to pit Terry Bowden
against his father Bobby, the game became unpalatable for Auburn
officials because they were worried it would dredge up Bowden's
resignation. The joke is that the school's rallying cry has been
changed from War Eagle to War Chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a decision that I thought would be in the best interest
for the long run,'' Tuberville said. ``I didn't think it would be
that much of a controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   In late April, Tuberville created another firestorm when he
rescinded the scholarships of six players. That leaves Auburn with
60 players on scholarship; the NCAA limit is 85. Tuberville's
comment: ``It's a business. We probably wouldn't have recruited
those players.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Tuberville and his players are looking forward to the
Sept. 4 opener _ even if it's against Division I-AA Appalachian
State, the team that replaced Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got to Mississippi (in 1995), I was just looking
for a way to get my name in the paper,'' said Tuberville, who
guided the Rebels out of NCAA probation to a winning program.
``Here, I've just been worried about keeping my name out of the
paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of it was blown out of proportion. We brought a
lot of the controversy on ourselves. We've tried to get some things
behind us. It's been pretty rough.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0520 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAITH-PRESIDENT-COX     07-28 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAITH-PRESIDENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where other candidates stand on faith
 &HT;    (EDS: Sidebar to GWBUSH-FAITH.)By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's Republican rivals have
expressed support for giving faith-based organizations a greater
role in delivering government services. So has Democratic
front-runner Al Gore _ although the timing of his support has been
the subject of some controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad to see George Bush following Al Gore's lead to work
with faith-based organizations,'' Gore campaign chairman Tony
Coelho said after Bush's speech at an Indianapolis church last
week. Coelho was referring to Gore's remarks in May at an Atlanta
Salvation Army adult rehabilitation center. The vice president
endorsed ``carefully-tailored partnerships with our faith
community, so we can use approaches that are working best.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush and Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft, the author of the
``charitable choice'' provision of the 1996 welfare reform law, say
it is Gore who is jumping belatedly on the faith-based bandwagon.
Bush has been aggressively promoting Texas partnerships with
faith-based groups since 1996. In contrast, the Clinton-Gore
administration expressed constitutional concerns about a proposal
to expand charitable choice to some non-welfare government grants
and, according to Ashcroft, has ``undermined implementation'' of
charitable choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, the vice president's campaign has confused being
in the lead with getting lapped,'' Ashcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers say the administration was simply urging caution
during debate on expanding charitable choice. They say Gore, who
spent a year at Vanderbilt's divinity school, is a big believer in
the power of faith-based groups, although he wouldn't go as far as
Bush in allowing them to deliver government services.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's rival for the
Democratic nomination, voted for the charitable choice provision of
the welfare bill.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
