<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CBS-MOONVES-NYT &LR;      07-28 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-MOONVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS EXTENDS DEAL WITH HEAD OF TV OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ CBS extended its deal with Leslie Moonves to
serve as the president of CBS Television Wednesday, locking him
into a long-term situation that will ensure he continues as the
leader of its broadcast TV operations.
</P>
<P>
   Under Moonves, CBS has improved its competitive position in
prime-time programming, reaching more total viewers last season
than any other network for the first time since 1993. The network
had been third in that category when Moonves joined CBS in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The move ended widespread speculation in Hollywood that Moonves
was a leading candidate to replace the recently departed Robert
Daly and Terry Semel as the head of the Warner Brothers studio.
Before joining CBS, Moonves served as the head of Warner's
television division, and he maintained a close relationship with
Gerald Levin, the chairman of Warner's parent company, Time Warner
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves said Wednesday that he had considered the opportunity at
Warner Brothers ``for about a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It would have been going home. But I feel like I'm
starting to build something at CBS. I think I have the right people
in place now.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS did not disclose the terms of the new deal. Moonves said the
length of the deal was ``in the range'' of five years.
</P>
<P>
   He called it ``a nice situation'' financially and praised the
CBS chairman, Mel Karmazin, for aggressively pursuing completion of
the new deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel didn't mess around,'' Moonves said. ``That's one of the
other reasons I made the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Little will change in terms of Moonves' duties, though he will
become a member of the CBS board of directors, having been elected
to the board Wednesday. But otherwise he will continue to manage
all of CBS's television assets other than its cable television
division. CBS Entertainment, News, Sports and its television
stations all report to Moonves.
</P>
<P>
   During the last year, CBS passed NBC as the most watched network
in terms of overall viewers, though the network is still
handicapped financially because its viewers are much older than
those of any other network. Most television advertisers prefer
young adult viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But Moonves has embraced CBS's strategy of counter-programming
the youth-oriented shows on the other networks with shows of older
appeal. He said the CBS television network will make a profit this
year for the first time in three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
