<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLER-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-28 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLER-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER BREWING MOVES THE ACCOUNTS OF ITS TWO BIGGEST BRANDS.
AGAIN. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wis., Minn., Ore., Ill.)   (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A beer blast for two unconventional agencies known
for their creative prowess turned into a beer bust Wednesday when
the Miller Brewing Co. abruptly turned over their assignments, for
its two largest beer brands, to big, mainstream shops that work for
Miller's parent, the Philip Morris Companies.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in less than three years that Miller has
dismissed agencies hired to create campaigns for the two brands,
Miller Lite and Miller Genuine Draft. Both brews have continued to
lose sales and market share despite repeated revampings of
advertising approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The action pretty much speaks for itself,'' said Susan
Henderson, a spokeswoman for Miller in Milwaukee. ``The brands have
not performed up to the category. We need to take a fresh look.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden shifts underscore the ferment roiling the nation's
beer industry, particularly as Miller struggles to bridge a
widening revenue and profit gap being opened by its principal
rival, the Anheuser-Busch unit of the Anheuser-Busch Companies.
They are also emblematic of the quickening pace of agency
reshufflings in competitive consumer product fields like beverages,
computers and financial services.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissals, effective immediately, deprive Fallon McElligott
in Minneapolis of creative duties on Miller Lite, an account with
billings estimated at $95 million, and Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in
Portland, Ore., of creative duties on Miller Genuine Draft, an
account with billings estimated at $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Both brands are leaving for units of WPP Group PLC: Miller Lite
to Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide in New York and Miller Genuine Draft
to J. Walter Thompson Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, this week's issue of Time magazine carries an
eulogy of David Ogilvy, the founder of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather who died
last week, written by Pat Fallon, chairman of Fallon McElligott.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal removes Fallon McElligott from the Miller agency
roster after it landed the Lite assignment from the Leo Burnett Co.
in Chicago in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody must have decided they needed a change,'' Fallon
said. ``It's disappointing, but these things happen in our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We did some great work along the way and we made some mistakes
along the way,'' he added. ``I'm sad about it, but we're
resilient.'' There would be no layoffs as a result of the loss,
Fallon said.
</P>
<P>
   Wieden &AMP; Kennedy was also hired by Miller in December 1996,
gaining Genuine Draft from Bates USA in New York, part of the Bates
Worldwide unit of what is now Cordiant Communications Group PLC.
Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, however, keeps the creative chores for another
brand, Miller High Life, with billings estimated at $15 million to
$20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sad to lose MGD and proud of the work we did,'' said
David Luhr, chief operating officer at Wieden &AMP; Kennedy. ``And
we're happy about High Life; the sales results have been
fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   The dismissals came only three-and-a-half months after Philip
Morris ousted the head of Miller and two top lieutenants in an
effort to reverse the unit's flagging fortunes, which were
attributed in large measure to the poor response by most beer
drinkers to the campaigns for Miller Lite and Miller Genuine Draft.
</P>
<P>
   The reassignments are intended to provide ``compelling and
meaningful consumer communications,'' said Robert Mikulay, senior
vice president for marketing at Miller, that would ``help convince
consumers to choose one brand over another.''
</P>
<P>
   The new agencies ``bring a solid understanding of and deep
appreciation for the power of brands,'' he added, ``as well as a
proven track record of grasping a brand's essence.''
</P>
<P>
   Mikulay was one of the executives brought to Miller by Philip
Morris after their predecessors were ousted. The Miller chief
executive, John MacDonough, was replaced by John D. Bowlin, a
former top executive at the Kraft Foods division of Philip Morris.
Tellingly, Ogilvy and Thompson handle numerous assignments for
important Kraft brands like Maxwell House coffee, Post cereals,
Kool-Aid, Kraft cheeses, Oscar Mayer cold cuts and Miracle Whip
salad dressing.
</P>
<P>
   To appeal to consumers in their 20s, the ads for Miller Lite and
Miller Genuine Draft eschewed typical elements of beer pitches in
favor of offbeat images and sardonic humor. Critics complained
vociferously that the campaigns put off older beer drinkers and
simply entertained younger ones without providing reasons for
buying Miller beers.
</P>
<P>
   The critics were particularly dismissive of the initial work by
Fallon McElligott for Miller Lite, which featured strange
characters like a make-believe adman named Dick, a 1970s-style
stuntman named Jimmy, a magician's assistant who sprouted mice
under her arms and cowboys who sang about beer on the way to the
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The Miller Lite campaign was toned down last year and in March,
after Fallon McElligott survived an agency review, was replaced
altogether with more conventional imagery centered on celebrities
discussing the brand's taste and quality attributes.
</P>
<P>
   The Miller Genuine Draft ads, which at first showed grungy
20-somethings in unglamorous locales like trailer parks, were
replaced in May with similarly more broad-based imagery. But both
revampings apparently came too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first job is to define the brand essence'' of Miller Lite,
said Shelly Lazarus, chairwoman and chief executive at Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather, ``and frankly, from looking at the advertising, I can't
tell what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where we do our best work, with brands that have lost
their way a bit,'' said Ms. Lazarus, whose agency has helped
rejuvenate brands like American Express, IBM and Jaguar. ``To me,
it's what does the brand mean to people?''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, for Maxwell House, ``it's not about the beans,''
she added. ``It's about `Good to the last drop' and significant
moments over the course of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller Lite will be Ogilvy &AMP; Mather's first beer brand since
Schaefer, an assignment that ended in 1981. Thompson Chicago, part
of the J. Walter Thompson Co., worked for Miller from 1984 to 1994
on brands like Lowenbrau and Sharp's.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Lite was once America's best-selling light beer and the
No. 2 brand over all behind only Budweiser from Anheuser-Busch. But
the brand lost its lead to the light version of Budweiser, Bud
Light, and is now the third-best-selling brand behind those two
brews. Shipments of Miller Light fell 1.5 percent in the second
quarter compared with those in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Genuine Draft, the best-selling premium-priced regular
Miller brand, ranks seventh among all beers. Shipments for that
brand also declined in the second quarter by an unspecified amount.
</P>
<P>
   Media duties for all Miller brands remain at Starcom U.S.A. in
Chicago, part of the Starcom Worldwide unit of Burnett.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
