<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDERS-NUHNCOLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanders' retirement looks like real deal...for now
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When fat salaries began to permeate sports in the
1980's, one of the worries was that our best athletes would amass
their fortunes, exit early and leave us wanting more.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the best players held on longer and longer because
their earning power was so great at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we had the specter of Steve Carlton, unable to admit he had
lost his slider, being ripped like a batting practice bobo; and of
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar sky-hooking through the cobwebs; and even now,
of Warren Moon, unable to let go, waiting for his next injury.
</P>
<P>
   If his retirement is serious, Barry Sanders is the first to
actually leave with 6 or 7 years of highlight reel performances
left.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Michael Jordan still had a couple of magical years in his
tank when he quit after last season, and John Elway maybe had
another decent season available.
</P>
<P>
   But in the main, our best have overstayed rather than sneaked
out early. And none has left this early since Jim Brown quit the
Cleveland Browns in an era when money was a reverse factor _ that
is, Brown could make more in Hollywood than he could running with a
football.
</P>
<P>
   At first I thought Sanders' retirement was like one of those
boxing retirements of Muhammad Ali or Sugar Ray Leonard. I thought
he was angling to be traded or to rework his contract. But Thursday
I talked with a friend who knows Sanders pretty well, and he said
it's real.
</P>
<P>
   He told me that late in the final game of his 1989 rookie
season, Sanders needed 10 yards to claim the NFL rushing
championship, but the game was meaningless for both teams and
Sanders was out of it. Coach Wayne Fontes approached him and asked
if he wanted to carry the ball a couple more times and pass
Christian Okoye of Kansas City for the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the 1,458 yards he needs to pass Walter Payton means
so little to him. He is one of those rarest of athletes,
unconcerned with personal accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   And money? He's made plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Plus he was tighter than scuba gear with that money. ``He drove
the same old clunker he had in college his first four or five years
in Detroit,'' my friend said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, his relationship with management was poisoned by
losing. The Lions have been mostly mediocre (78-82) in his 10
years, and when they allowed three of last year's offensive linemen
to escape via free agency, Sanders apparently saw more years of
mindless drifting and didn't want to play through it.
</P>
<P>
   That he waited this long to make his decision, giving the team
no time to adjust, is a mark against him.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bobby Ross said he made 10 phone calls and wrote three or
four letters to Sanders in the off-season, and Sanders never
answered any of them. Whatever his reasons, that was not the
honorable thing to do, but it certainly spoke to the much-denied
but apparently real conflict he had with Ross.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the end, Sanders' legacy is unclear. He was brilliant
in spurts, but of all the feature backs in the league in his 10
years, he was the last guy you wanted to hand the ball to on
3rd-and-1 because he too often would get immersed in trying for 21
and end up not getting the one.
</P>
<P>
   I still expect to see Sanders back in uniform eventually, maybe
after a one-year respite, similar to Jordan's. I always thought
Sanders played with a joy, and if I'm right, he'll miss the game
more than it misses him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
