<HEADER>
A7853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-PATTERSON-COX     07-28 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-PATTERSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate will likely approve military base construction
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A banner budget year awaits Wright-Patterson Air
Force Base with final votes on a military construction bill that
includes $43.6 million in improvements for the base.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the House of Representatives is expected to take up the
bill that emerged this week from a House-Senate conference
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is likely to provide its approval next week, which
could make the $8.4 billion spending plan the first appropriations
bill for fiscal year 2000 to reach President Clinton's desk.
</P>
<P>
   After a rocky budget process that featured deep cuts in critical
research spending and a credible attack on the F-22 fighter,
Wright-Pat has emerged as a clear winner in the budget season,
amassing more big projects in a single budget than it has in recent
memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be the biggest budget for us ever,'' said Dan Curtis,
vice president of the Miami Valley Economic Development Coalition.
``If it's not the biggest, it's one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the construction projects, the base also is in
the running to receive millions more in program dollars as part of
an overall defense bill that still must be finalized between the
House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the projects in the military construction bill is
$13.6 million for a long-sought avionics laboratory that would
consolidate the work of several existing buildings into a single
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the work of separate labs has been a priority because,
in addition to improving efficiency with better facilities, it
heightens security to permit the study of more important, more
highly classified projects. The lab will work on the systems that
integrate jet fighter avionics with battlefield information
gathered by such things as space-based lasers.
</P>
<P>
   The construction bill also has $17.5 million for an aerospace
structures lab at the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those, I think, should position the base well as the Air Force
moves further into the the space age,'' said U.S. Rep. David L.
Hobson, R-Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Positioning the base to perform space research became a priority
this year when the Air Force abruptly eliminated nearly $100
million in aviation research, much of it done at Wright-Pat, to
fund pet Air Force projects in space study. Although Miami Valley
representatives have lobbied to restore funding to some of those
aviation projects, the Air Force has made it clear space programs
will get more and more priority in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``When military construction dollars are declining, it is a big
achievement to get funding for five projects at one base,'' said
U.S. Rep. Tony Hall, D-Dayton, who will control the rules for
debate when the bill reaches the House floor today.
</P>
<P>
   Hobson was in a key position to help secure the local funding,
as chairman of the House subcommittee on military construction and
a member of the House-Senate conference committee that negotiated
the final bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, having someone from the area as chairman of the
military construction subcommittee pays dividends,'' said Curtis,
whose group is a collection of regional leaders who lobby Columbus
and Washington on economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also includes $6.7 million for an F-16 flight training
complex at Springfield's Air National Guard base. And it has money
for so-called quality-of-life improvements throughout the military,
including at Wright-Pat, something Hobson emphasized during the
drafting of the bill. Wright-Pat will get an occupational health
center and an updated physical fitness center.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said he's excited by the success of the construction bill
because it includes forward-looking projects such as $4 million to
replace the base's aging control tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first step toward preparing for an operational
unit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright-Pat has only a reserve bomber wing located on the base
despite its enormous size and runway capacity. Ohio leaders want
the Air Force to consider it as a logical receiver site for an
operational unit if long-threatened base closings ever become a
reality.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate were split over how to spend the bill's
total budget, and none of the Wright-Pat projects were included in
both versions, which could have led to trouble in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But the final bill included all the local projects listed in
each version.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress is on the verge of approving an extraordinary
investment in Wright-Patterson Air Force Base,'' said U.S. Sen.
Mike DeWine, a Republican from Cedarville.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
