<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TVERDOVSKY ACCEPTS DUCKS' OFFER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Oleg Tverdovsky officially returned to the Mighty
Ducks' flock on Wednesday when he agreed to a one-year contract
with Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The defenseman, who spent 3 1/2 years with the Winnipeg/Phoenix
franchise after being traded for Teemu Selanne, accepted Anaheim's
qualifying offer and will earn $1.7 million in the 1999-2000
season, the same amount he made last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the Ducks, agent Don Meehan and Tverdovsky) agreed that
his salary is right for what he brings a team,'' said Ducks
president and general manager Pierre Gauthier of Tverdovsky, who
was a restricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky, acquired from Phoenix on draft day for a first-round
draft choice and center Travis Green, scored seven goals, 25 points
and was plus-11 for Phoenix last season.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier said he didn't feel pressured to sign the 23-year old
defenseman to a multi-year deal even though Tverdovsky did hold out
once in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope a year from now I have to pay Oleg a lot more money,
because that will mean he's had a great year,'' said Gauthier, who
expects Tverdovsky to provide the Ducks a much needed offensive
presence on the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky's deal was the latest to be worked out as Gauthier
strives to have all his core players under contract by the time
training camp begins on Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jason Marshall has an arbitration hearing set for
Aug. 10. Defensemen Ruslan Salei and Pavel Trnka and forward Antti
Aalto are unsigned restricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no hurry,'' he said of those talks. ``It's the quality
of the deal that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gauthier has been busy signing his own players this summer
he has been in no rush to sign free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very weak year for free agents and as we all know New
York (Rangers) did it's thing and we all let them do it,'' said the
GM, who reportedly was interested in checking center Tim Taylor
before the Rangers signed him for $5.8 million over four years.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier said the Ducks would like to improve their depth, but
added that the team is committed to its young players -- not older
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't going to get in the way of those players,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
