<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: East Timor Poll Postponed
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has pushed back to Aug. 30 a referendum on
independence for the disputed territory of East Timor, Foreign
Minister Ali Alatas said. U.N. officials said they were still
trying to bring under control a campaign of violence and
intimidation by organized anti-independence thugs who are seeking
to derail the vote.
</P>
<P>
   India: Politician Penalized
</P>
<P>
   The Election Commission barred Bal Thackeray, the political boss
of the Shiv Sena, a party that leads a coalition government in the
state of Maharashtra, from voting or standing for office for six
years for inciting hatred between Hindus and Muslims in an election
speech.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: `Bloody Sunday' Ruling
</P>
<P>
   Three Appeal Court judges ruled that 17 former British soldiers
be permitted to testify anonymously before an inquiry into the
so-called ``Bloody Sunday'' killings of 14 Roman Catholics in
Northern Ireland in 1972. The former soldiers argued that
disclosure of their identities would imperil their lives.
</P>
<P>
   France: Cabinet Shuffle
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin chose Dominique Gillot, a fellow
Socialist, as health minister, but he disappointed the Greens
Party, which did better than the Communists in last month's
European Parliament elections, by not giving it more Cabinet seats
in the coalition government. Environment Minister Dominique Voynet,
the only Greens member, turned down the health post unless her
party could also keep the Environment Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Student Strikers Pilfer Files
</P>
<P>
   Student strikers broke into administrative offices at the
National Autonomous University of Mexico, which has been closed
down for 100 days, and removed academic files and video equipment,
the authorities charged. Last week, a group of strikers painted the
date 1999 over a corner of a well-known mural on the campus by
David Alfaro Siqueiros, in a protest action that drew criticism
even from other strikers.
</P>
</TEXT>
