<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7859 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOGAN-STOWAWAY-BOS &LR;      07-28 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOGAN-STOWAWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHFUL STOWAWAY DEFIES SECURITY, JETS TO LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A 17-year-old youth with visions of impressing Israeli
spies, cut the razor wire atop a perimeter fence surrounding Logan
International Airport, walked for two miles across restricted
areas, and stowed away aboard a British Airways Boeing 747,
aviation sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The July 12 incident is being investigated by the Federal
Aviation Administration, the Massachusetts Port Authority _ which
owns and operates Logan and is directly responsible for the
airport's perimeter security _ and the airline, which is
responsible for security in its terminal and around its airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The youth, identified by two aviation sources as Abraham Derman
of Brookline, Mass., climbed over the fence and dropped down onto
the tarmac area north of the main terminals before making his trek
to the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   The incident raises questions about security at Logan and is
even more troubling because it involved an international flight.
Such flights have long been considered likely targets for terrorist
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Massport and at British Airways said the breach was
extremely serious and exceedingly rare. Both have launched
investigations to make certain the event cannot happen again.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of sources say the following occurred:
</P>
<P>
   Derman walked unchallenged for two miles to Terminal E, where he
climbed the exterior stairs of a jetway and boarded British Airways
Flight 214 to London, which departs daily at 8:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior doors on jetways _ which are the responsibility of
the airline _ have combination locks, so either the lock was not
working or was bypassed, the door was propped open, or someone
opened the door to let Derman into the jetway. From there, he was
like just another passenger bound for Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Once on board the jumbo jet, Derman apparently headed for the
coach section. The seat he selected was already assigned to another
person and he was asked to move. He calmly headed to the business
section, found an empty seat and sat down for the flight to London.
In business class, Derman had a more comfortable seat, better food,
plus a choice of 12 movies.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, airlines hand count the passengers on board a flight
and compare that number to the number of tickets pulled as
passengers leave the gate area to board the airplane. It is unclear
why the youth was not discovered during that check.
</P>
<P>
   ``British Airways is cooperating fully with Massport and the
FAA,'' said British Airways spokesman John Lampl. ``We are treating
this situation extremely seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the plane landed at London's Heathrow Airport, Derman
somehow gained access to a restricted area at Heathrow and was
confronted by operations officials.
</P>
<P>
   Heathrow, one of the world's busiest airports, has had problems
with security in the past but has become more aggressive. ``I was
there last year and they really put the lid on things,'' said an
aviation security specialist from Maryland who spoke on condition
neither he nor his company be named.
</P>
<P>
   After Derman was discovered, British Airways returned him to
Boston. Upon his arrival here, Derman told investigators he wanted
to go to Israel and he thought the stunt would impress Mossad, the
Israeli intelligence agency. He also said that he initially tried
to gain access to Logan's tarmac by going through Terminal E, but
was stopped and told to leave. He apparently then walked out and
scaled the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Derman could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal charges have been filed against Derman, and sources
said it is unlikely they will be brought because he is under 18 and
his parents understand the gravity of the situation. The FAA is
considering levying fines, which can be as high as $11,000 per
violation, against the airline, the airport, and Derman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no comment on the specifics, because the matter is
under investigation,'' said FAA spokeswoman Arlene Salac. ``But
this would come under airport and air carrier security, and if they
find violations _ and one case can have a number of violations _
there could be fines.''
</P>
<P>
   Massport spokesman Jeremy Crockford said ``We take this very
seriously, but the most important thing to understand is this is an
aberration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing this is unbelievably foolish. He could have been shot,
or killed by a plane, car, or truck out there. In some ways, this
is equivalent to a computer hacker getting into a military
computer. It is a case where a bright young man misused his
talents.''
</P>
<P>
   The aviation security specialist in Maryland said the incident
``has all kinds of interesting failures in it before the system
finally worked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure he exploited a weak spot here. After all, he went
through barbed wire and a locked door,'' the specialist said.
</P>
<P>
   At Heathrow, however, he was not permitted to walk the tarmac
unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   Derman was returned to Boston on a British Airways flight on
July 13. He flew back in coach, and British Airways is likely to
ask for compensation, a round-trip business class ticket runs
$5,557, unrestricted coach is $1,389.
</P>
<P>
   When Derman flew back in coach, there were no movie choices. The
only selection playing was ``The Out-of-Towners.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Staff member Thomas C. Palmer Jr. contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
