<HEADER>
A7863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DYLAN-SIMON-REVIEW-NY     07-28 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYLAN-SIMON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMON AND DYLAN IN CONCERT, NOT QUITE AN ODD COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They were no Simon and Garfunkel, no Bob Dylan and
the Band. They weren't even as good a match-up as Bob Dylan and
Elvis Costello singing ``I Shall Be Released'' during the encore of
an impromptu Dylan show the night before at Tramps. But Bob Dylan
and Paul Simon weren't exactly the odd couple either at Madison
Square Garden on Tuesday night when their tour finally came to town
and they shared the stage for four songs.
</P>
<P>
   The two have much in common. Born in 1941, they are among the
best and most expansive songwriters of their time, each with one
hand firmly clasping the political and intellectual zeitgeist. They
were both lifted out of the '60s Greenwich Village folk scene by
Columbia Records, and they are both constantly reinventing their
sound when their audiences least expect it. Simon covered Dylan's
``Times They Are A-Changin''' on the first Simon and Garfunkel
album, and Dylan remade Simon's ``Boxer'' on his ``Self-Portrait.''
</P>
<P>
   For baby boomers, they are measures by which to gauge one's own
growth from time to time: Simon, developing through extroverted
collaboration and leaving his American roots; Dylan, developing
through introverted exploration and digging into his American
roots.
</P>
<P>
   On their own during Tuesday night's three-and-a-half-hour show,
they performed strong sets, particularly Dylan, who has been on a
streak of smiling, dancing, harmonica-wailing, well-enunciated
performances. But when Simon joined Dylan and his band for ``The
Sound of Silence,'' ``Knockin' on Heaven's Door'' and a medley of
``I Walk the Line'' and ``Blue Moon of Kentucky,'' it became clear
that the similarities between the two are only surface deep.
</P>
<P>
   Where the cryptic Dylan is a tangled, dusty back road on which
it is impossible to see more than a few feet ahead, the more
transparent Simon is as obvious and scenic as a parkway. And though
singing harmony is second nature to Simon, trying to harmonize with
Dylan is like trying to catch a fly with chopsticks. As a result,
``The Sound of Silence'' turned from a haunting ballad to a
cacophonous prophecy punctuated with a harmonica solo while
``Heaven's Door'' sounded slightly better when the two took turns
singing. Simon gave the song an older, even more cynical conclusion
by interjecting the lyric ``I hear you knockin' but you can't come
in,'' which Dylan also began singing.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Dylan responded to his 1966 motorcycle accident by
shunning the touring life, since his heart infection in 1997 he has
been a road warrior, performing with one of his tightest backup
groups in years and presenting himself as a bedraggled journeyman
for whom performing is just a paid job. On Monday night at Tramps,
Dylan and his band (with the addition of Charlie Sexton on guitar)
were in rare form, delivering a blistering, highly animated club
show that dipped into obscure pockets of his back catalog. At
Madison Square Garden they catered to the baby boomers and
delivered the '60s hits, deviating most notably for an expressive
version of a newer song, ``Highlands,'' with Dylanesque details
changed in the lyrics. (For reasons having to do with age,
obstinacy or respect for his audience Dylan has not allowed
photographers into shows on the tour, instead issuing a retouched
photograph of a Denver performance with Simon.)
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with his third song, ``A Hard Rain's A-Gonna Fall,''
Dylan began to perk up and become what for him is lively,
illustrating his lyrics with half-finished gestures and shuffling
dance steps (a little from him has always been a lot). Most songs,
like ``Mr. Tambourine Man'' and ``Tangled Up in Blue,'' were
radically rebuilt _ the keys, arrangements and melodies altered _
while Dylan's phrasing stretched and shrank each word to fit, or
not.
</P>
<P>
   He has been so inside his songs for so long that he seemed back
on the outside, leaving leeway for his guitarists Larry Campbell
and Sexton to solo and punch up the choruses with backing vocals.
Dylan filled in the gaps with short bursts of guitar, choking up on
the neck for staccato solos as if he were playing a mandolin. His
mumbling was so rare that when he slurred a line during ``Like a
Rolling Stone,'' the audience burst into applause, as if he were a
jazz singer scatting.
</P>
<P>
   Like Dylan, Simon rearranged his songs, infusing nearly each
one, particularly ``Mrs. Robinson,'' with globe-trotting rhythms
and solos. But unlike Dylan, he left the core of his songs alone,
leaving them recognizable from the first bar. On his first tour
since the early '90s, Simon led a large, rhythm-oriented band _
able to shift easily from zydeco to South African township jive _
letting them carry the weight of the music.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by as many as four percussionists and a three-man brass
section, Simon played music intended to make the audience get up
and dance, whereas Dylan's was oriented more toward looking inside
and thinking. It makes sense, since Dylan is a songwriter who
innovates by looking within while Simon innovates by looking
outside himself, finding music in the street or seeping under the
door, as he sang on ``Late in the Evening.'' Audience members on a
nostalgia trip burst into applause when Simon sang of lighting a
joint in the same song.
</P>
<P>
   But the highlights of Simon's set were not the oldies (even with
his son, Harper, finger-picking ``The Boxer''). They were the songs
from his disastrous recent encounter with Broadway, ``The
Capeman,'' particularly the set's island of soulfulness, ``Born in
Puerto Rico,'' which featured the Panamanian singer Ruben Blades
and the Puerto Rican singer Danny Rivera, and the songs from
``Graceland,'' particularly ``Boy in the Bubble'' and the title
track.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the latter song that the fundamental difference
between Dylan and Simon became clear: with the lyric ``Everybody
feels the wind blow,'' Simon sang of the wind as a connective
tissue not unlike the Brazilian and African rhythms that he has
come to enjoy mining, but Dylan sang of a wind that is elusive,
blowing the answers around and separating us from meaning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
