<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-DOOMSDAY-NYT &LR;      07-28 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DOOMSDAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOOMSDAY FROM 0 TO 10 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, July 29: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We live, of course, in a world full of risks and the
probabilities assigned to those risks. There is a statistical
measure for the safety _ or danger, if you're feeling pessimistic _
of nearly any activity you can name. But all these probabilities
and statistical measures are grounded on a basic assumption: the
survival of Earth. You can't take everything for granted, however.
Now, for people who like to worry about the sky falling, there is
the Torino Impact Hazard Scale, created by Dr. Richard P. Binzel, a
professor at MIT, and approved by the International Astronomical
Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Torino Impact Hazard Scale measures the likelihood that a
particular extraterrestrial object, like a meteor, comet or
asteroid, will collide with Earth. It uses a scale that runs from
O, a complete miss, to 10, a catastrophic bulls-eye. The Beaufort
scale, which measures wind, the Fujita-Pearson scale (tornadoes),
the Richter scale (earthquakes) and the Saffir-Simpson scale
(hurricanes) calibrate the force of real events, but they do not
gauge the likelihood that they will occur. The Torino Scale is a
way to state only the probability governing a comet, for instance,
once it has been sighted and its trajectory described. The scale
has nothing to say about the possibility of some comet striking the
earth someday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Torino Impact Hazard Scale will not always remedy the
problem it has been devised to solve _ clarifying the likelihood of
catastrophe for worried lay people. The scale is useless without
accurate calculations of trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   For one brief unsettling moment in March last year, it was
thought that asteroid 1997 XF11 might pass very near Earth, perhaps
even striking it, in 2028. Then the trajectory was recalculated,
and it was discovered that, where XF11 was concerned, a miss is as
good as a mile, as good as 600,000 miles, in fact, which is as near
as it will come to Earth. Had Binzel's creation been in effect,
XF11 would have gone from an 8 or so on the Torino Scale to a 0.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow that does not convey all the comfort it should, nor does
it do anything to diminish the chance of future miscalculations.
Human error is always likely, though how likely it is always hard
to say. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0545 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WILLIAMS-AIDS-ART-     07-28 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WILLIAMS-AIDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN GUILTY OF SPREADING AIDS VIRUS SAYS HE HAD HUNDREDS OF SEX
PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., N.C.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nushawn J. Williams, the drifter from Brooklyn who
officials say may have infected more than a dozen young women and
girls in upstate New York with the virus that causes AIDS, now says
that he may have had sex with as many as 300 women.
</P>
<P>
   That number is even higher than health officials feared in
October 1997, when their concerns that Williams, was spreading the
virus through a number of rural upstate towns led them to take the
unusual step of publicly identifying him and his health status.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 22, made his remarks in an interview from the Clinton
Correctional Facility in Dannemora, N.Y., that is scheduled to be
broadcast Thursday night on WPIX-TV's ``News at Ten.'' He is
serving a 4- to 12-year prison sentence after pleading guilty to
charges of statutory rape and two counts of reckless endangerment
for knowingly infecting two girls with the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   In the first extensive interview since his case attracted
national attention, Williams spoke with a mixture of candor, regret
and braggadocio about his days as a gang member and a drug dealer,
about what he considered his success in attracting scores of women
and his anger at the portrayals of him in the media.
</P>
<P>
   At times he seemed proud of his past (``Basically, it was a life
that was worth living, you know?'') and at other times, his
comments were tinged with regret (``I was living my life in the
fast lane _ now that I think about it, I wish I was living life in
the slow lane.'').
</P>
<P>
   He said he had had sexual partners in New York City and
Rochester as well as in towns in far western New York and as far
away as Charlottesville, Va., and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials said Williams could be telling the truth about
the number of sexual contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible,'' said Dr. Robert Berke, the Chautauqua County
health commissioner, whose office did the epidemiological detective
work that identified Williams as the common denominator in the
rapid spread of HIV in the area. ``This guy was extremely active.
We found 47 women here over a long period, but in a couple of
months alone there were 20 contacts. In New York they were looking
at 50 to 75.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Williams appeared to be in denial about his
health status, couching his comments by saying ``If I am
HIV-positive'' and ``I still don't even know if I got it now.''
Despite his guilty plea and the fact that health officials say he
was told in 1996 that he was HIV-positive, he said he did not know
he was positive when he had sex with dozens of girls _ some as
young as 13 _ around the state until his arrest on a drug charge in
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I gave them a death sentence, but it wasn't knowingly,''
he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, whose mother had drug problems, was raised primarily
by his grandmother in the Crown Heights section of Brooklyn. He
said he began selling drugs upstate because he did not want to be a
burden on his family. There, he said, he found himself unusually
successful with girls who were unhappy with their lives and curious
about his urban roots.
</P>
<P>
   He said the youngest girls he had sex with _ who were only 13 _
had lied to him about their age.
</P>
<P>
   When the interviewer, Jonathan Dienst, asked him if he felt he
owed them an apology, Williams said: ``I think I owe them an
apology as far as having sex without wearing a condom, or not
having safe sex, stuff like that. I owe them an apology on those
grounds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
