A7868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOBBYISTS-MONEY-NYT     07-28 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBBYISTS-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAB FOR WASHINGTON LOBBYING: $1.42 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lobbyists were paid $1.42 billion last year to try
to influence politicians, a 13 percent increase over the $1.26
billion they received in 1997, a research group said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyists were paid by organizations of airplane
manufacturers, bankers, doctors and lawyers, drug companies,
hospitals, universities, Indian tribes _ in short, by
representatives of just about any person or institution that had
business before the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly nothing inherently illegitimate about any of
these interests having their voices heard,'' said Paul Hendrie,
communications director for the group, the Center for Responsive
Politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think so, either,'' said Tom McMahon, a spokesman for
Cassidy &AMP; Associates, which took in $19.9 million in fees last
year. Cassidy dislodged Verner, Liipfert, Bernhard, McPherson &AMP;
Hand as the capital's top lobbying firm by about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hendrie said, the huge sums spent on lobbying are cause
for concern. ``People who don't have the money to spend are not
going to speak with as loud a voice,'' he said. ``Money does
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Through more and more mouths, he might have added. In mid-1997,
there were 14,946 lobbyists registered in Washington, the center's
report said. A year later, there were 18,590 and by June 15 there
were 20,512, or about 38 lobbyists for each of the 535 members of
the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics describes itself as a
nonpartisan, nonprofit research organization that tracks money in
politics, and money's effects on elections and public policy. Its
report was based on disclosures filed with the secretary of the
senate and the clerk of the house under lobbying-disclosure
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrie said his organization was not advocating legislation to
curb lobbyists. As for the money spent by interests trying to have
their way with the federal bureaucracy, he said, ``It's hard to say
what a reasonable figure would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list for the second-straight year was businesses
involved in real estate, insurance and finance, which spent $203
million on lobbying in 1998. (Those businesses, one of 13 broad
economic sectors defined in the report, are also the perennial
leading spenders on campaign contributions, the center said.)
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that money was not always spent to get things
done. Sometimes it was spent in the hope that things would not get
done. Tobacco companies spent $67.4 million on lobbying last year,
nearly double the $38.2 million they spent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Was the money well spent? It is impossible to make a direct
connection, of course, but whatever happened to the bill that would
have raised the tax on cigarettes by $1.10 a pack?
</P>
<P>
   The money spent on lobbying last year also bore more than a
coincidental relationship to important legislation. The American
Hospital Association, for instance, spent just over $10.5 million
in 1998, up from about $7.9 million in 1997, as it lobbied against
Medicare cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said that Cassidy &AMP; Associates' top client last
year was Boston University, which paid the firm $760,000, and the
biggest single lobbying fee paid in Washington last year was $3.6
million to Verner, Liipfert from Philip Morris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
