<HEADER>
A7870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CRIME-SCENE-NYT     07-28 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CRIME-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Giuliani administration has tentatively agreed to
make crime scenes more accessible to news organizations by changing
police practices that news executives said had inhibited the
coverage of crime, rallies and other events in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed agreement, the Police Department would
significantly limit its use of barricades to keep reporters,
photographers and television camera crews away from crime scenes,
fires, demonstrations and other events.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials also promised to honor police press passes,
which are supposed to permit reporters and camera crews to cross
police and fire lines.
</P>
<P>
   The barricaded areas, known as press pens, have often been set
up a block or more from the site of an event, sometimes making it
impossible for reporters to gather information and for
photographers and television camera crews to capture images of
crime scenes, fires and rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Drafts of the tentative agreement were made available Wednesday
by lawyers for a coalition of news organizations. It still faces
review by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani before it can become final.
</P>
<P>
   News executives have complained since 1995 about the barricades
and about what they say is a pattern of harassment of news
gatherers by the police. Police officers have sometimes
deliberately blocked news photographers and television camera crews
from taking pictures or videotape of crime scenes, auto accidents
and even parades.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, news executives said, the media had less access to
public events than New Yorkers who simply happened to walk by the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   The news organizations contended that the Police Department's
actions repeatedly violated its own media guidelines, as well as
the news media's First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative agreement resulted from negotiations between city
officials and a coalition representing The Daily News, The New York
Times, Newsday, The Associated Press and the New York Press Club.
The coalition had been preparing to sue the city in federal court
over the lack of access to crime scenes, demonstrations and other
public events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
