<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-ALA-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUROR OVER FLAG TRAILS GIULIANI ON FUND-RAISING VISIT TO THE SOUTH
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ As he pumped hands and collected donations in
three Southern cities Wednesday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani also found
himself fending off criticism from politicians back home who were
incensed by his decision to fly the Arkansas flag over City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani announced during his visit to Little Rock, Ark., on
Tuesday that he would briefly fly the star-studded scarlet flag
over City Hall to thank his Republican hosts for their hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, Giuliani's aides raised an Arkansas flag over City
Hall in New York, leading several Democratic lawmakers to fire off
statements of outrage.
</P>
<P>
   City Council Speaker Peter Vallone called the flag-hoisting
blatantly political, saying its presence atop City Hall had no
purpose other than to taunt Hillary Rodham Clinton, the mayor's
potential opponent in next year's race for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Bill Perkins, who is black, went further, complaining
that the Arkansas flag was ``designed to commemorate the
Confederacy.'' According to the state's Web site, three stars below
the word Arkansas on the flag represent the three nations that have
held sway there _ Spain, France and the United States _ and a
single star above symbolizes the Confederacy, which the state was
part of from 1861 to 1865.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone tracked the mayor down by telephone Wednesday morning
and insisted that he immediately order that the flag be taken down.
Giuliani refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the speaker this morning he should send that objection
to President Clinton,'' Giuliani, who also visited Huntsville and
Tuscaloosa on Wednesday, said during a news conference at a hotel
here before a $1,000-a-plate fund-raising dinner. ``The flag of the
state of Arkansas has been displayed in the White House and flown
throughout Washington, D.C., without objection.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who flew home Wednesday, originally said the flag
would fly for a few days, but Wednesday afternoon, he announced
that it would come down that night. ``I think we are making a lot
out of nothing because it is probably a very slow news day,''
Giuliani said in response to reporters' questions about the flag
controversy. ``But I have it in perspective. This is the silliness
of partisan politics.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Back in New York, aides on both sides of City Hall pored over
the city's administrative code to determine who has authority over
flag-flying. Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota accused the City Council of
``parochialism'' and ``closed mindedness.''
</P>
<P>
   He also distributed copies of Section 3-102 of Chapter 1 of the
administrative code. It says: ``All authority to display flags or
other decorations on, in or about the public buildings within the
City Hall Park is vested in the mayor, unless otherwise ordered by
the Council.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Council, Lhota contended, could not issue an order
until its next full meeting on Aug. 11. He also pointed out that
other flags have flown over City Hall to honor dignitaries and that
in 1994, the flag of Texas flew there after the Houston Rockets
defeated the Knicks in the NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   In Arkansas, a spokesman for Gov. Mike Huckabee said that only
the Stars and Stripes, along with the Arkansas flag, flew over the
state Capitol during the mayor's visit.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, Rex Nelson, said he did not expect the flag issue
to interest people in Little Rock much. ``I have a feeling it's not
an issue that reverberates with anybody outside maybe two of the
five boroughs'' of New York City, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
