<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7877 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LIONS-SANDERS-ART     07-28 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LIONS-SANDERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDERS PUTS IT IN WRITING: HE'S GONE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As quietly and as unassumingly as he entered the NFL, Barry
Sanders has left it, simply issuing a statement Wednesday that he
is retiring after 10 seasons as a Detroit Lions running back.
</P>
<P>
   His statement, in part, read:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I officially declare my departure from the NFL. I leave
on good terms with everyone in the organization. The reason I am
retiring is simple: My desire to exit the game is greater than my
desire to remain in it. I have searched my heart through and
through and feel comfortable with this decision. I wish my
teammates, coaches and the entire Lions organization all the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Little fanfare. No glitzy news conference. Just a written
statement and then, like one of his shimmering runs, poof! He was
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was spotted Wednesday outside London at Gatwick Airport
after having arrived from Detroit. ``I'm going into retirement, and
I don't see my plans changing,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would spend two days in London before visiting
Amsterdam and Paris. Asked why he happened to be in London, Sanders
answered: ``I don't know the right way to retire. This is just my
way of doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Sanders says his career is over, is it really over?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on the `Reserve: Did Not Report' list, not the `Reserve:
Retired' list,'' said Chuck Schmidt, the Lions' general manager,
noting that if Sanders chooses to be activated any time before Dec.
5 he would be eligible for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention of trying to trade him,'' Schmidt said.
``If Barry comes back, we would want him to come back to the
Detroit Lions.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not seem likely to Bobby Ross, the Lions' head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're very disappointed because we lose a great
player,'' he said. ``From what I know about Barry, when he makes up
his mind, he makes up his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a puzzling situation.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, 31, is still in the prime of his career despite having
played a decade, and he is only 1,457 yards shy of breaking Walter
Payton's career rushing record of 16,726 yards. He shows no hint of
slowing or of his sparkling skills waning. He is the premier
running back in the NFL and one its brightest stars.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit was 78-82 during Sanders' 10 seasons. The Lions had five
seasons in the playoffs, five seasons out and a 1-5 record in
playoff games. They had five consecutive playoff losses, too, with
the lone victory coming more than seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Ross was hired as head coach. He ran Sanders sparingly
for the first two games. Over the remaining 14 games of the regular
season, however, Sanders, Ross, his coaching staff and the Detroit
offensive line rolled, as Sanders became only the third player in
league history to rush for more than 2,000 yards, joining Eric
Dickerson and O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   It was something on which to build.
</P>
<P>
   But last season there were more changes to the offensive line, a
quarterback change (from the veteran Scott Mitchell to the rookie
Charlie Batch two games into the season) and more Lions mediocrity.
Ross blew up over the mess, blamed the players more than the
coaching, and the Lions tumbled again. There was consternation over
whether Sanders was more effective in a one-back or two-back set,
although the Lions generally used two backs.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he called Sanders, who has played two years of a
six-year $36 million contract, at least 10 times during the
off-season and sent him him ``three or four personal, handwritten
letters each five to nine pages in length.'' But Sanders never
responded, Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   William Sanders, Barry's father, said during the off-season that
his son was ``sick of the Lions. He's sick of losing. He's sick of
the whole situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he would like for Sanders to let him know by July 1 if
he planned to retire, so that the Lions could plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders decided one day before the start of Detroit's training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a state of shock,'' Lions receiver Johnnie Morton
said. ``This puts us in a pinch.''
</P>
<P>
   Do his teammates feel betrayed?
</P>
<P>
   ``You wish he had done it a different way,'' Batch said. ``But
maybe he didn't know until this weekend what he was really going to
do, so that would explain him waiting so long to announce this. I'm
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was seen in the Detroit area within the past week by
Lions coaches and players. They thought that was a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he is gone.
</P>
<P>
   His father hinted last May that it could happen this way. Few
took him seriously then, but many do now. This is what William
Sanders said:
</P>
<P>
   ``He can do just like Jim Brown did in '65 _ walk away from the
game and never let it faze him.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that someday Barry Sanders simply may not show up. That
day has come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990728.0552 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT &LR;      07-28 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGERS _ HAMSTRING IN DOUBT _ PITCHES AN EFFECTIVE SIX INNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kenny Rogers trotted to the mound Wednesday, hoping
for a fresh start with the Mets in an old city. It was a new team
in a new borough and in a new league, but there were still the old
yet valid questions about whether Rogers could succeed as a pitcher
in New York after faltering with the Yankees in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As Rogers tossed his first warm-up pitches at Shea Stadium,
``Bittersweet Symphony'' by the Verve played on the public-address
system. Richard Ashcroft's vocals were appropriate for Rogers'
debut with the Mets because the song includes the lyrics, ``I can
change, I can change, I can change.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Rogers can change. He pitched artistically and
effectively, allowing the Pittsburgh Pirates no earned runs and one
hit in six innings before leaving because of tightness in his right
hamstring. Rogers left with a one-run lead, but didn't get the
victory because Dennis Cook gave up a home run to John Wehner that
tied the score before the Mets used a seven-run eruption in the
eighth to secure a 9-2 triumph. Benny Agbayani's double delivered
the go-ahead run, while Rey Ordonez and Edgardo Alfonzo drove in
two runs each in the outburst.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Rogers, obtained in a trade with the Oakland A's
last week, did not get a decision and conceded that his strained
hamstring may persist, it was a rewarding day. Rogers notched 12 of
18 outs on grounders, displayed a tricky sinker, a nifty curveball
and an effective changeup, and he might have flirted with a
no-hitter were it not for a questionable umpiring call that
prolonged an inning.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mets were smiling. Sort of. Manager Bobby Valentine
called Rogers a warrior and praised his performance, but cautioned
that the 34-year-old left-hander might miss a start because of his
hamstring. Rogers does not think he will miss a turn, but he
grimaced in the dugout, limped in the clubhouse and bent his leg so
his knee could rest on a suitcase during interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw six innings of one-hit ball,'' Valentine said.
``Don't get me wrong; it's not like he was out there pitching with
a bloody stump. But there was a lot of trepidation in my viewing of
what if, what if, what if. When you go six, seven innings and
you're waiting for something bad to happen, it's a lousy feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers did not argue when Valentine removed him with a 2-1 lead,
but he was ready for the seventh. Valentine called Rogers' injury
the worst kind to decipher because he must rely on the player to
get information, which can sometimes be a problem with Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers has pitched in pain before and even angered Yankee
Manager Joe Torre by disguising the extent of a spring training
shoulder injury in 1996. Valentine spoke of how the Mets needed
Rogers ``for the long term,'' and how having six starters would
make it easier to skip him if the tightness in his hamstring did
not ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could be a lingering problem, but I think today and
being able to get through it, was a big plus,'' Rogers said.
``Knowing I can go out there and compete with it, even if it's
still there. I really wanted to pitch longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years to the day after Rogers became the first American
League left-hander to pitch a perfect game, as a member of the
Texas Rangers, he was nearly flawless for the Mets. Rogers broke
off a 3-2 curve to Brian Giles in the first that looked so much
like a strike that he ambled off the mound. It was called a ball.
Kevin Young singled, which was Pittsburgh's only hit off Rogers,
but he retired Ed Sprague on a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo and Robin Ventura blasted homers off Todd Ritchie in the
first inning to give the Mets a 2-0 lead. While catcher Todd Pratt
noticed Rogers favoring his hamstring in the second and said it
kept him from finishing breaking pitches, Rogers still retired 12
of 13 from the second until the fifth. Rogers actually tweaked his
hamstring when he sacrificed in the fifth and ran to first. He was
being too feisty and stopped after 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, with a runner on second, Rogers flipped a
pickoff throw to Ordonez that sailed into center field. Rogers said
that Andre the Giant could not have caught the errant throw, which
played a part in Pittsburgh's first run. It was obvious Rogers was
hurting, but it was also obvious that he had conquered New York for
a day. ``There are always pressures,'' Rogers said. ``I think
because you're in New York, it's a little more pressurized with
everybody watching. For me, as long as I'm able to go out there and
show I'm healthy, I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Rogers must get healthy, which was why Valentine
bolted out of his office and gave his new pitcher magnets to apply
to his hamstring. Valentine tore the magnets from a sheet and
instructed Rogers on where to put them. All the while, Rogers
smiled. It was the end of a day that was a new beginning, and
Rogers, injury and all, was pleased. ``Give me that stuff,'' Rogers
said. ``It's like voodoo, man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
