<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-PLEAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9 ENTER NO-CONTEST PLEAS IN UCLA PARKING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nine UCLA football players pleaded no contest
Wednesday to illegally obtaining handicapped parking placards, and
were sentenced to fines, community service and probation. And later
in the day, the school suspended those still on the team for the
first two games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   As the players emerged from the courthouse, a handful of
protesters in wheelchairs outside chanted, ``Hey hey, ho ho,
parking cheats must go.''
</P>
<P>
   In a late-morning arraignment near the Men's Central Jail, nine
of the 14 players charged in the case quietly entered their pleas
and each was sentenced to two years' probation, a $500 fine that
will increase to $1,500 with penalties and fees and 200 hours of
community service to be split evenly between the Special Olympics
and other charities. The players will also spend a day in a
sensitivity program talking to disabled people and their advocates.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the pleas, a second count of giving false
information to the California Department of Motor Vehicles was
dropped. The hearings of the five other current and former players
were postponed until Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Abdul Azziz, a reserve outside linebacker last season, read
a statement for the players in which he said that the placards were
used only as a substitute for regular student-parking permits,
which cost $129 to $162 a quarter, and that players mostly did not
displace disabled drivers by parking in handicapped spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to apologize to our school, our teammates and
most importantly the disabled community,'' Azziz said. ``We did not
realize the seriousness of our actions. If we had realized then how
offensive our actions were to the disabled community or anyone
else, we would never have committed these acts. We realize we
exercised bad judgment, and we're anxious to make amends for what
we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine players, including seven of those sentenced Wednesday, are
returning to school and will be suspended from playing in the first
two games of the season, Albert Carnesale, the UCLA chancellor,
said at a news conference Wednesday afternoon. They will also
receive additional penalties students face in such cases, ranging
from disciplinary probation to suspension from school. Six of the
players were projected as starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This behavior is particularly insensitive because it was
carried out by student-athletes, for they are among the most
able-bodied of all,'' Carnesale said.
</P>
<P>
   Illegally possessing handicapped parking placards is a
misdemeanor which carries a maximum penalty of six months in jail
and a $1,000 fine. Brian Williams, the deputy city attorney who
prosecuted the case, said, ``We think this is a very fair and just
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Harland Braun, a lawyer who represented six players, said they
may have entered no contest pleas believing that guilty pleas might
affect the school's disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   The players were charged earlier this month after an
investigation by University of California campus police found that
they submitted applications to the Department of Motor Vehicles
citing made-up physical handicaps _ including one who said he
suffered from Bell's Palsy, a facial nerve ailment _ and bearing
signatures from nonexistent physicians.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to the investigation said the inquiry was
continuing and that more charges were possible. The Los Angeles
Times has reported that UCLA's star quarterback last year, Cade
McNown, had a placard in 1997 when he was fit enough to be
practicing with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Sam Ohta postponed hearings for the five other players. A
lawyer for Craig Walendy, a senior fullback last season, said he
was at the San Francisco 49ers' training camp and could not be in
court Wednesday. Another player, Mark Raynosa, a senior
special-teams player last season, asked the judge for more time to
hire a lawyer. Raynosa would not say how he intended to plead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
