u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RADOJEVIC-NYT &LR;      07-28 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RADOJEVIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: RADOJEVIC FAR FROM HOME BUT CLOSER TO SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan.)  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few days after he was drafted into the NBA, Aleksandar
Radojevic took a flight from New York to Los Angeles to compete in
the Long Beach Summer League.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot-3-inch center, taken 12th overall by the Toronto
Raptors, was dreading the six-hour flight. Until Adam Sandler
walked up and introduced himself to the native of Montenegro, a
region of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good guy,'' Radojevic said in broken English of
Sandler, the actor and comedian. ``Very funny. He make jokes for
long time. I tell him I want to see `Big Daddy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Big Alek may be better theater. In November, he is coming to an
NBA arena near you, the towering project of the Raptors. He will
most likely not win the rookie of the year award, and who knows how
long before he transforms himself into a decent young center and
learns the ways of a veteran. But he is patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Charles Oakley,'' he said. ``If he is in Toronto, I hope
he can teach me. Some people tell me he can help me go shopping for
new clothes, but I feel the colors he wear are too bright.''
</P>
<P>
   He uses humor well to camouflage the grimmer parts of his
odyssey. Because of the war in the Balkans, Radojevic has not gone
home since coming to the United States two years and three months
ago. Radojevic, who was 20 when he left Montenegro, spoke no
English then. He played at Barton County Community College in
Kansas the past two seasons, averaging 15.4 points, 9.0 rebounds
and once blocking 12 shots in a single game. His home country's
instability forced him to stay in Kansas even when his father died
last season at age 67.
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic had signed a letter of intent to play for Ohio State.
But on May 11, the NCAA ruled that because Radojevic received
$13,000 for playing a total of 19 minutes for a Yugoslav club team
two years ago, he was ineligible to play for the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA didn't want him. He could not go back home because it
meant he might be drafted into the Yugoslav army and perhaps be
sent to fight in Kosovo. He needed a new home, and the NBA obliged.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked out for 17 teams,'' said his agent, Marc Cornstein.
``I would be fired if I suggested that to most kids, but he knew
not a lot of them had seen him play. Instead of complaining, he
persevered. He's the most quality kid I've ever had, just a
genuinely good person. And he's got an incredible sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he didn't know English real well, he would spend all his
time in Kansas watching TV. His favorite show is `Sanford &AMP; Son.' I
heard his first words in America were, `Show me the money!'''
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic is Cornstein's first bona fide, big-time client. A
28-year-old Cornell graduate, Cornstein also works as a
commissioner for the New York State Athletic Commission and for the
New York City Sports Commission while trying to run his own one-man
agent business.
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic said the relationship he shares with Cornstein is
similar to the one between Cuba Gooding Jr. and Tom Cruise in
``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even better than that relationship from the movie,'' Radojevic
said. ``He talk about my job, but mostly we are good friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Falk, he don't have that relationship with his players
that I have with Mark,'' Radojevic added, referring to the game's
most prominent agent. ``It's more than business. I can tell him my
personal problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic hopes to bring the rest of his family to the United
States from Montenegro within the next three years. He knows if his
NBA career does not pan out, there are limited options.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for me,'' he said. ``I have a lot of memories,
but I got to do what I got to do. I'm not going back. There is
nothing for me there now. As soon as I bring my family here, there
is no concern left for me.''
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the draft last month in Washington, two women
who worked for the NBA and had followed Radojevic's story began
crying as Radojevic's name was announced by Commissioner David
Stern. Radojevic was one of the last players to leave the MCI
Center. Cornstein had another client he had hoped would be picked
in the second round, and Radojevic was enjoying the moment.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he left, the television crews were cleaning up and
the restaurants were closed. He wanted something to eat, so he and
his agent and two family friends went to the Renaissance Hotel,
where the league had a buffet for its employees and the news media.
Radojevic later retreated to the news-media hospitality room, a
first for an NBA draftee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is smart,'' he said. ``I knew if I do something stupid,
it will be in newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he put two bottles of Budweiser up to his mouth at once
and starting pouring and smiling. ``I was so happy to be in the
NBA,'' he said. ``I can't imagine my life with no laughing. The
most important thing in my job is when tough times come, I keep
good attitude and be happy. That is what's going to keep me in this
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Aleksandar Radojevic could not return home and could
not play college basketball anymore. Today, he is less than three
months away from his first Toronto training camp. They always talk
about players joining the NBA family. Never has there been a
7-footer more thrilled to meet his new cousins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
