<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE LAWYER NOMINATED FOR 9TH CIRCUIT JUDGESHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ President Clinton has picked Richard Tallman, a
longtime Seattle lawyer who specialized in white collar criminal
defense, to fill a vancancy on the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Tallman was one of three potential nominees recommended to the
White House by Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., after Washington state
Supreme Court Justice Barbara Durham withdrew her name from
consideration for the post.
</P>
<P>
   He is likely to be formally nominated after a required FBI
background check. Two other nominations _ Seattle lawyer Ron Gould
to the 9th Circuit and King County Superior Court Judge Marsha
Pechman to U.S. District Court _ are awaiting confirmation by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I add Richard Tallman's name to Marsha Pechman and Ron Gould
on a list of terrific judicial candidates from Washington state. I
hope Dick's nomination moves along quickly,'' said Sen. Patty
Murray, D-Wash, who endorsed Gorton's list of nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 9th Circuit position has been open for far too long, and
it is unfortunate the process was delayed,'' Murray added.
</P>
<P>
   Tallman was longtime chairman of the white-collar criminal
defense group at Bogle &AMP; Gates, a major Seattle law firm that
closed March 31. He is a partner in the recently formed firm of
Tallman &AMP; Severin.
</P>
<P>
   Tallman once represented the Seattle Mariners baseball team in
legal disputes over scheduling rights in the Kingdome. He has
handled medical malpractice and defense procurement cases..
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be listened to. He reasons well and he is not
automatically liberal or conservative,'' said Frederic Tausend, a
former law school dean and partner at Preston Ellis &AMP; Gates, who
has practiced with Tallman.
</P>
<P>
   Tallman was once a law clerk for U.S. District Court Judge
Morell Sharp, and is a graduate of Northwestern Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Based in San Francisco, although several of its judges sit in
Seattle, the 9th Circuit court is a key decision-maker in the
West's major economic, social and environmental conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The court upheld President Clinton's forest protection plan, but
recently ruled against a major land exchange between Weyerhaeuser
and the U.S. Forest Service. Overruling a district judge, it upheld
Washington state's law against assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the 9th Circuit is currently deciding an
Exxon Corp. appeal of a $5.1 billion judgment in a suit brought by
Alaska fishermen over the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   The court is home to several of the nation's most outspokenly
conservative judges _ and more liberal jurists. Its ideological
balance has led to fierce confirmation fights in the Senate. Seven
seats on the 28-member court are vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton was given a leading role in filling the appellate court
vacancy as a result of an agreement worked out between the GOP
senator and White House Counsel Charles Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Gorton withdrew his threat to block Senate
confirmation of Clinton's federal judicial nominations in the
Northwest. The Republican-controlled Senate confirmed several of
the president's nominees, while Gorton was given a voice in picking
federal judges in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The vacancy on the 9th Circuit was created by the retirement of
longtime Judge Betty Fletcher of Seattle. University of California
law Professor William Fletcher, the judge's son, was confirmed last
year to a San Francisco-based seat on the appellate court. Several
Republican senators had objected to having mother and son on the
same federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-controlled Senate has moved at a glacial pace this year
in confirming judicial nominees.
</P>
<P>
   It has confirmed only five of Clinton's 45 judicial nominees.
One of the judges to win confirmation was a college fraternity
brother of Senate Majority leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Several other appointees have been approved by the Senate
Judiciary Committee and await a vote by the full Senate. One of
them is Pechman, who is expected to win confirmation with little
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But one nominee to the 9th Circuit, Judge Richard Paez in
California, has waited three and a half years for a hearing. Gould,
of Seattle, was tapped to the federal appellate court in November
1997, but has yet to receive a hearing by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   One major roadblock was cleared on Wednesday. Bowing to pressure
from Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
Clinton on Wednesday nominated a conservative Republican lawyer
from Utah, Ted Stewart, to a U.S. District Court vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch had broadly hinted that he was holding up confirmation
hearings of Clinton's nominees until the president agreed to
nominate Stewart, a friend of the senator's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
