<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ASTHMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN ASTHMA EMERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 29:
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is a chronic inflammation of the respiratory system that
makes breathing difficult, and in its acute forms starves its
victims of air, landing them in the hospital. The disease has
become increasingly common, afflicting more than twice as many
people today _ about a third of them children _ as it did just two
decades ago. Unless scientists find out why _ and learn to curb the
increase _ asthma will clog hospital emergency rooms and undermine
the national effort to control health costs.
</P>
<P>
   It has long been known that poor children are more likely to
suffer acute asthma attacks that require hospitalization than more
affluent youngsters. But the extent of the disparity was documented
this week when a study of New York City by the Mount Sinai School
of Medicine found that hospitalization rates for acute asthma were
as much as 20 times higher in poor, minority communities than in
affluent ones.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the disease is easily controllable through medication
and life-style choices, the differences suggest that the poor and
their families lack access to both advanced care and accurate
information about this chronic disorder. They may also be more
exposed to possible environmental determinants of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The causes of asthma are still a mystery. Airborne pollutants
might play a role. The fact that children remain indoors more than
in the past _ where they are subject to a variety of pollutants in
inferior housing _ is also being considered. New York City, which
has three times the national hospitalization rate, is the perfect
laboratory for investigating the causes of this problem and the
means of solving it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
