<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HOLMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTANCE HOLMAN, 91, PIONEER IN MEDICINE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Vt.)  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Constance Friess Holman, the first woman to become chief
resident in medicine at New York Hospital, died last Friday at
Brattleboro Memorial Hospital in Brattleboro, Vt. She was 91.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pneumonia, her daughter, Jane Clough, said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being first in her class at Cornell Medical School, she
got the residency at what is now the New York Weill Cornell Center
of Presbyterian Hospital only because the man originally chosen had
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   While studying at Barnard College, she tutored and cared for the
grandchildren of Adolph S. Ochs, then the publisher of The New York
Times. Ochs lent her the money to attend medical school and
arranged to have the debt forgiven upon his death.
</P>
<P>
   She retired in 1988 after a long career practicing internal
medicine in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   She was divorced from her first husband, William Alexander
Cooper, in 1969. Her second husband, Cranston W. Holman, died in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her daughter, Jane Clough of Paris and Pound
Ridge, N.Y., she is survived by a son, Peter A. Cooper of
Brattleboro, Vt., and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
