<HEADER>
A7894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-HNS &LR;      07-28 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES PROVIDES NFL `FRAMEWORK' FOR AGREEMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN McCLAIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSEMONT, Ill. _ As expected, Los Angeles presented the NFL with
a nonbinding, exclusive negotiating agreement Wednesday that allows
the city to move forward with its attempt to keep the expansion
franchise it was conditionally awarded over Houston in March.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League did not sign off on the agreement,
which shows Los Angeles' stadium design and location but doesn't
address financing.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue called it a ``framework to move
forward'' toward the Sept. 15 deadline Los Angeles has for
presenting a solid stadium financing plan for the New Coliseum at
Exposition Park. If Los Angeles can't make the deadline, it risks
losing the team to Houston and prospective owner Robert McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was re-emphasized that Sept. 15 is a fair and firm date,
and we need to stick to that date,'' Tagliabue said. ``We're still
not there. We need to keep working to see how it can get done. This
document is just the framework. I don't see any need to execute it
now. There are some things we're in agreement with, and there are
some things we aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair didn't attend the meeting but said from Houston,
``They're being very positive, but once again, they haven't
answered the key question of how they're going to come up with a
financing plan for the stadium to make sure they have a successful
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they put a financing deal on the table showing public
contribution, I feel good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Chadwick, appointed by California Gov. Gray Davis to
represent the state interests, made a presentation with the two
ownership groups of Michael Ovitz and Eli Broad/Ed Roski. Their
presentation showed the new stadium design and the location for the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the owners) didn't exactly bring down the house with
applause,'' Chadwick said after the presentation at the O'Hare
Hyatt. ``There are legitimate economic concerns, and our primary
focus has to be on financing the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Both groups said they are planning a 2003 start-up season, not
2002 like the NFL wants. Both groups said they don't want to play
in an existing stadium such as the Rose Bowl in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   McNair has no problem playing the 2002 season in the Astrodome
if he gets the team and his new stadium can't be completed on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to, we will,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   The two Los Angeles ownership groups said they have been slowed
because the league has yet to determine the expansion fee. The fee,
likely to be at least $500 million, could be determined by Sept.
15.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the league could accept offers (bid by the two
groups), and if they aren't high enough, the league might establish
the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been accomplished in the past month is to provide a
structure for continuing negotiations to get it done,'' Tagliabue
said. ``We're encouraged by the site development and stadium plan.
The (expansion) committee co-chairs (Carolina Panthers owner Jerry
Richardson and New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft) will write
a letter recommending league support for the New Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   League support would come in the form of a $150 million loan,
the payback of which is guaranteed by the sale of club suite
premiums. That type of loan would also be available to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the owners agreed that Los Angeles has made progress,
but it still pales in comparison to what Houston has on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of work to do by Sept. 15,'' Kraft said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Denver owner Pat Bowlen: ``I'm encouraged. They've got a
good opportunity to get things done by Sept. 15.''
</P>
<P>
   A huge issue has been a lack of parking on the New Coliseum
site. Chadwick presented a plan for 20,400 structured parking spots
at Exposition Park and hopes bonds can be issued to pay for the
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our estimates are $425 million on the low end for the stadium
and about $150 million for parking (including $115.5 million for a
10,500-space primary parking garage),'' Chadwick said. ``But one
thing I've found is that construction budgets are usually on the
low side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner said today that it could come in between $350
million and $600 million. That's quite a range. Add the franchise
fee, and we're talking about a billion-dollar project. Everyone
will continue to work as hard as we can to get as much done by the
deadline, but I don't think we'll have everything done by then. I
think we'll be close.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz pointed out that Los Angeles is desperate for financial
help because of the magnitude of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult deal to make,'' he said. ``The main issue is
how we're going to finance the entire project. The NFL and the
state have to help us. The deadline's a concern, but the reality is
that we've met every deadline so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's room for Houston. There are a lot of people who want
to move. Houston's got a good deal. We were hoping Bob McNair would
be here today so we could ask him to loan us some money for the
L.A. project.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Oakland Raiders owner Al Davis insists he still owns
the rights to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about their presentation _ I'm just
concerned that we get paid,'' Davis said. ``L.A. hasn't done
anything in the five years since we left. If they (the owners) kill
the deal, I've got a state-of-the-art deal at Hollywood Park.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
