<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FEMALEREF-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTRESS MADE HISTORY AS FEMALE REFEREE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gwen Adair, playing the part of a nurse, had roles in 18
episodes of the hit TV show MASH. The Los Angeles woman played a
barmaid in three episodes of Starsky &AMP; Hutch and also had a part in
the movie ``Soylent Green.''
</P>
<P>
   As a small-time actress, her resume reads well.
</P>
<P>
   None of it, however, can compare to the rush Adair got when she
became the first female referee to work a major world championship
fight.
</P>
<P>
   On June 5, 1998, Adair was referee for the IBF junior
middleweight title bout between Yory Boy Campas and Pedro Ortega in
Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   For the history-making feat, Adair was honored by the World
Boxing Hall of Fame last October. Friday in Hollywood, Adair will
be honored by the Golden State Boxing Association in a ceremony
entitled ``Women in Boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Five other women will also be honored, but Adair's
accomplishments are easily the most noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are other females who judge bouts, you might be
able to count on one hand the number who actually referee
professional fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never even seen another woman referee,'' said Don
Fraser of the Golden State Boxing Association.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: No other female has refereed a world title
bout. For this, Adair can thank hard work and determination. She
was passed over three other times for title bouts, but she did not
quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was for things that were ludicrous, like I didn't have
enough experience,'' said Adair, who has been a California state
referee for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, she was passed over because of her gender. But
nobody is going to admit to that.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Adair got what she deserved -- but only after she had
threatened the state athletic commission with a lawsuit. She agreed
to withdraw it, provided the commission recommended her the next
time the IBF called.
</P>
<P>
   (Adair signed with the IBF five years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Adair says she will never forget her experience in Tijuana. Most
of it was good. Some of it was stressful. Like when a guy Adair
said was a member of the commission in Mexico started to complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the weigh-in and this guy says, `What is this? A
woman?' '' Adair said. ``And I was thinking, `Don't tell me they're
going to mess with me at the last minute.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. The fight was on. History was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Referee) Bob Byrd said, `You know, you are making history
here. You are the first woman in the world to do a major title
fight,' '' Adair said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Mexican people treated Adair like royalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous, but people were all over me afterward,
congratulating me, asking me for my autograph,'' she said. ``It
meant they had accepted me, that I did a good job.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were rewarding me by letting me know they appreciated me.
I was ready to move to Mexico. Take me back to Tijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it wasn't easy for Adair. She endured all the
resistance a female venturing into male territory usually faces.
</P>
<P>
   She started off going to the Olympic Auditorium with her mother,
and then her husband, in the 1970s. Adair eventually managed one
fighter for 15 bouts. But after he went back to karate, Adair had
no fighter. So she decided she wanted to become a referee.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame referee Dick Young is 84 and the oldest active
referee in the world. Young was one of the first to gripe about
Adair becoming a referee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest,'' Young said this week, ``when I first heard
that they had licensed a woman referee, I said, `Oh, my God. Women,
they belong at home, barefoot and pregnant.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Gwen has made me swallow those words. And I'm happy she did. I
think she is outstanding, I truly do. Being a female, there is the
physical end of it. She doesn't have the strength of a man to break
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she moves good. She has good control of her fighters. I
think she has developed into a standout referee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
