<SLUG> BC-NY-POWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CON ED DATA SHOW WEAK FEEDER CABLES IN UPPER MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The power distribution cables in upper Manhattan were
among the most trouble-plagued in Consolidated Edison's system for
years before seven of them failed on July 6, plunging the
neighborhood of Washington Heights into the city's worst blackout
in 22 years, company documents show.
</P>
<P>
   While they have not finished investigating the cause, Con Edison
officials have described the sequence of events that left 200,000
people north of 155th Street without power for 18 hours as a
random, highly unusual occurrence. They said it could have happened
anywhere in a system straining under record demand, with the city
simmering through its second consecutive 101-degree day, the
hottest in four years.
</P>
<P>
   But annual reports filed by the utility with state regulators
show that the feeder cables in Manhattan north of 110th Street have
failed more often than those in any other part of the borough, and
are among the likeliest anywhere in the city to fail. An analysis
of those documents shows that during the last five years, the
feeders supplying Washington Heights and Harlem have shut down at a
rate 80 percent higher than those for the rest of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Since the blackout, elected officials and others have wondered
aloud whether Con Edison had neglected an area populated largely by
low-income Hispanic and black people. The utility has denied the
charge. But Con Edison's own data appear to show disparities in the
resiliency of the system from one neighborhood to another,
disparities the company says it cannot explain.
</P>
<P>
   Most feeder failures do not lead to blackouts, but simply strain
the system. But if a series of feeders fail, as they did on July 6,
it can lead to a widespread loss of power.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison asserts that the best measure of performance is not
feeder failures but power failures, for which its record is
unmatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of last year, we had only 125 people out of service in all
of Washington Heights,'' said Robert W. Donohue, the vice president
who oversees the distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, despite the blackout of July 6 and 7, Con Edison, which
serves more than 3 million homes and businesses in New York City
and Westchester County, is by far the most reliable electric
utility in the United States, national data show.
</P>
<P>
   But because power failures are so rare in the city, and because
most affect a small number of customers, it is hard to draw any
conclusions from year to year, and to make
neighborhood-to-neighborhood comparisons. Feeder failures, on the
other hand, are a daily occurrence with wider implications, and
state regulators track them carefully as a crucial barometer.
Because of redundancies built into the system, most feeder failures
do not halt service, but they are a contributing factor to almost
every large blackout, Con Ed's documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Feeder cables, which do the bulk of the work to carry power, can
fail for various reasons, from excessive demand to corrosion caused
by road salt.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison's record on power failures results largely from two
factors that set it apart from other utilities. First, in
Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens and the Bronx, nearly all of the system
is underground, impervious to ice storms, falling limbs, crashing
cars and unlucky squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   Second, in those four boroughs, most of the customers are linked
in networks. Each network has from eight to 24 feeder cables,
usually capable of carrying 13,000 volts each, and each feeder is a
backup for the others. That way, one, two or even three feeders in
a network can shut down without a loss of power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
