<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-DUMAURIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DU MAURIER CLASSIC COULD OPEN DOOR TO HALL OF FAME FOR INKSTER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIDDIS, Alberta _ At the three most recent LPGA major
championships, players bombarded the courses with birdies. Dottie
Pepper shot 19-under-par to win the Nabisco Dinah Shore. Juli
Inkster shot 16-under-par to win both the U.S. Women's Open and the
LPG A McDonald's Championship.
</P>
<P>
   But the year's final major will be far more demanding. The du
Maurier Classic, which begins Thursday at Priddis Greens Golf and
Country Club on the outskirts of Calgary, will play the way a major
championship is expected to. The rough is thick, the greens are
firm and undulating, and the wind could be tricky. And while the
players expected a difficult test, few of them were complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably going to be the toughest major we've played all
year,'' said Karrie Webb, the LPGA money leader, who has won five
times this year, but who is still looking for her first major
championship. ``I'm excited. It's a major, you're supposed to hit
good shots. That's how it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the focus will be on Inkster, who could become the
second woman to win three of the four modern majors in one year,
joining Pat Bradley, who did it in 1986. And a victory would also
put Inkster into the LPGA Hall of Fame, based on the new points
criteria established earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Players must accumulate 27 career points to make the Hall of
Fame, with two points awarded for winning a major championship, one
point for winning any other LPGA event and one point for winning
the Vare trophy for lowest scoring average or the Rolex player of
the year award.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster has 26 career points from 21 victories, five of them
major championships _ including the du Maurier as a rookie in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I keep playing the way I have been, I'll have a chance to
win Sunday,'' said Inkster, who spent Wednesday morning intently
working with her coach, Mike McGetrick. ``But I'm not going to get
caught looking ahead. The Hall of Fame puts a lot of emphasis and
pressure on winning that last tournament to get in. I'm not going
to get caught up in that. It's difficult to win every week. There
are too many good players out here.''
</P>
<P>
   One player Inkster will not have to worry about this week is
Annika Sorenstam, who withdrew, saying she needed a rest. Sorenstam
played in Japan last week, and she has played seven of the last
eight weeks. Nevertheless, some players were surprised that
Sorenstam, the LPGA's leading money winner the last two years,
elected to skip a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand that,'' said Inkster, referring to
Sorenstam's absence. ``You only get four shots at majors. I never
would have taken off.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lopez, who is recovering from knee surgery, and the
defending champion Brandie Burton, who had recent shoulder surgery,
will also not play this week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the du Maurier's future after next year is in doubt.
Legislation will go into effect in Canada by 2003 prohibiting
tobacco companies from sponsoring sports events. Imperial Tobacco
sponsors the du Maurier, but that relationship is expected to end
after next year's event in Ottawa. Ty Votaw, the LPGA commissioner,
is still hopeful a solution can be reached that will keep the du
Maurier as the fourth women's major, but he could offer no
promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're set through next year, and beyond that, it wouldn't be
fair to speculate,'' Votaw said. ``But the du Maurier has always
been a first-class event and it continues to be. We've enjoyed a
great relationship. It has been great for us, the Canadian fans,
and Canadian golf.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the fan favorites this week will be Lorie Kane, born in
Prince Edward Island, who has become the best Canadian player on
tour. Kane is third on this year's money list behind Webb and
Inkster, yet nobody on tour has had more heartbreaking finishes
than Kane.
</P>
<P>
   She has placed second eight times in her career, including two
weeks ago at the Japan Airlines Big Apple Classic, when she lost a
five-hole sudden-death playoff to Sherri Steinhauer. The du Maurier
would be a great place for Kane to break through, and she is taking
a businesslike approach, asking her mother, Marilyn, to stay home
this weekend instead of watching the tournament in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I play for my family and fans, you have to be a bit
selfish,'' Kane said. ``My family wanted to be here, but I asked
that they stay home. This is the first du Maurier my mom has
missed.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kane wins, her mother will certainly understand. But don't
expect to see Kane, or her peers, make quite as many birdies as
they have at this year's other majors. ``It will be a good test of
golf,'' Inkster said. ``Sixteen-under par won't win this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
