<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-BREWERS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves take it on the Chen
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wednesday night was hardly the time for some more
learning on the job _ the only kind way the Atlanta Braves could
interpret their 10-4 loss to the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a National League pennant race growing hotter by
the minute, the Braves got a douse of cool reality when they turned
to rookie Bruce Chen again for a much-needed win.
</P>
<P>
   What they got was more of what Chen had been doing in his first
four major-league starts before last Friday _ tooling around. He
surrendered four runs before he'd recorded three outs as the Braves
got Russ Springer up in the bullpen in the first inning. Chen
managed to get out of the first inning, but the Braves never got
over it.
</P>
<P>
   After riding dominating pitching for three consecutive wins from
Tom Glavine, Greg Maddux and Kevin Millwood to keep the Mets at
arm's length, the Braves had to settle for much less. As a result,
their NL East lead is back down to a half-game, which is where it
will stay until Friday when the Phillies come to town for three
games.
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves thought the pressure was on by having the Mets win
9-2 on Wednesday afternoon, they were in for plenty more by the
time the Brewers got through with Chen in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Using a Mark Loretta single and a perfect Jeff Cirillo bunt down
the third-base line for a single, the inning started innocently
enough for Milwaukee. But a walk to Alex Ochoa gave Chen a
bases-loaded predicament for the fourth time in his six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Twice he'd given up grand slams. Once he'd escaped unhurt, in
Milwaukee, in fact. This time he looked like he had another way
out, but Marquis Grissom singled just inches out of Bret Boone's
reach at second to score one run. Geoff Jenkins chipped in another
with a groundout. Then Jose Valentin slammed a double to left field
to drive in two more runs.
</P>
<P>
   All four of the runs were scored on two-strike pitches from
Chen, who's still searching for ways to close the door on
big-league hitters. He lasted another 3 1/3 innings and another two
runs before exiting with his second loss.
</P>
<P>
   Chen had the perfect opportunity to prove he deserved the
fifth-starter job. But now the reality that Odalis Perez is lost
for the season with a blown elbow looks that much more daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
