<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MACHINISTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING CAN'T AFFORD TO GUARANTEE JOBS, MANAGERS TOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boeing Co. can't afford to guarantee job levels or promise
to stop searching for firms to help it build airplanes as part of
any new contract with its Machinists, Jerry Calhoun, Boeing's top
labor negotiator, told managers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Boeing and the International Association of
Machinists sat down to craft a new contract for roughly 49,000
workers. At the heart of the negotiations is the security of jobs
at the world's largest airplane manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The company is striving to become a leaner corporation, while
union members are struggling with layoffs and outside companies
that consume a portion of the company's work and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun, in an e-mail to Boeing managers obtained by the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer, argued that guaranteeing job levels at Boeing
won't solve either side's problems because it threatens the
company's existence. Preserving and enhancing Boeing's ability to
compete in the airplane business is the best way to protect jobs,
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the highly cyclical aerospace industry, across-the-board
guaranteed employment levels are a prescription for disaster,''
Calhoun wrote. ``In those cases where more efficient operations are
available outside the company, it is only prudent that we explore
that option.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders said they're aware the cycles of the aerospace
industry can lead to layoffs. However, they are calling on the
company to limit the use of outside firms and to provide other
assurances about future employment at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't address job security in a manner that is
satisfactory for the members, they are going to have a problem,''
said Bill Johnson, the head of the IAM's District Lodge 751.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of job security looms as perhaps the most explosive
item in the sensitive negotiations. Johnson suggested that
Machinists could walk off the job if the issue isn't addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members are fired up,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, on the other hand, is striving to balance these demands
with calls from investors to create a more efficient and
competitive multinational company.
</P>
<P>
   ``To succeed we must conduct our operations in the most
efficient, cost-effective manner possible,'' Calhoun wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts say Boeing should maintain some control over
how work is assigned inside and outside the company as part of
Boeing's effort to improve its financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be some flexibility where Boeing can still make
key strategic decisions about what business they want to be in or
not be in,'' said Byron Callan, an analyst who tracks Boeing for
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the restructuring effort, Calhoun repeated the
company's proposal to stretch the work week to seven days and 24
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many versions of this that can yield very productive
outcomes,'' Calhoun wrote in the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The union, however, has already rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way seven days,'' said Dick Schneider, a lead negotiator in
the talks for Boeing, repeating a slogan that members have
expressed in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun, however, expressed interest in working on two areas
important to union members: altering language on hiring
subcontractors and returning some outsourced work to the company.
</P>
<P>
   The Machinists union wants to strengthen language from the 1995
contract that requires the company to notify the union of
``significant'' outsourcing to allow the union to offer other
options.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to working with the union to explore options
to improve the process,'' Calhoun wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are still at an early stage and they won't
reach a critical point until the two camps move to a hotel on Aug.
15 for intensive negotiations. Negotiators from both sides stressed
that they are still working on the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The union members are expected to vote on whether to accept or
reject a proposed renewal of their contract, which expires on Sept.
2, on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The union has struck during two of the past three contract talks
and IAM's Schneider said they could walk out again if the company
doesn't address their concerns over job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't have teeth ... we are going to stand before our
members and recommend they shut this company down,'' Schneider
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
