<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-LAYOFFS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ MAY LAY OFF 8,000 AFTER BEING HIT BY $184 MILLION LOSS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Battered by weak sales, rising expenses and falling
prices for its products, Compaq Computer Corp. lost big money in
the second quarter and its new chief executive warned that as many
as 8,000 workers will lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how many workers at Compaq's Houston headquarters will
be laid off is not yet known. In a conference call with reporters
Wednesday, Michael Capellas, Compaq's new chief executive, said the
details are still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Between 6,000 and 8,000 employees will get pink slips as part of
a restructuring that also will have Compaq closing some facilities
and taking a $700 million to $900 million charge in the current
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will attack operating expenses aggressively throughout the
year, and we will get to a more competitive level,'' Capellas said.
``Our goal is to eliminate $2 billion in annual costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The $184 million second-quarter loss, equal to 10 cents a share,
comes on sales of $9.4 billion, up 17 percent over the same period
in 1998. In June, the company warned of a quarterly loss of as much
as 16 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The comparisons with last year's numbers are on a pro-forma
basis, as though Compaq and Digital were one entity throughout the
second quarter. The acquisition of Digital closed in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has about 69,000 employees worldwide _ about 12,000 are
in Houston _ so an 8,000-person layoff would reduce the company's
work force by 11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When Compaq acquired Digital, the company vowed to lay off
17,000 _ 15,000 from the Digital ranks and 2,000 from Compaq's.
</P>
<P>
   Capellas said another 2,000 employees remained to be cut as a
direct result of the Digital deal, and the 6,000-to-8,000 are on
top of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be exact, we've reduced by 15,250 since then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Kumar, an analyst with US Bancorp Piper Jaffray, said the
new layoffs could be heavy in Compaq's sales and marketing areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still plenty of overlap there between Digital and
Compaq,'' Kumar said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Compaq already has lost a lot of good employees as
the company's fortunes have tumbled and morale dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be careful about cutting the wheat instead of the
chaff _ there's not a lot of chaff left,'' Kumar said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's performance was actually better than analysts had
expected. The consensus of analysts' estimate gathered by First
Call had Compaq taking an 11-cent-a-share loss.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter last year, Compaq had sales of $8.02
billion and a loss of $3.63 billion _ or $2.33 cents a share _ as
the result of the Digital purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Capellas cited several reasons for Compaq's poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   He said Compaq was hurt by vicious price competition in its core
business _ personal computers sold to corporations. Lower prices in
this sector resulted in profits being squeezed. Compaq's
second-quarter gross margin _ the percentage difference when
expenses are subtracted from sales _ was just 20.5 percent,
compared to 24.7 in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that operating expenses jumped to $2.2 billion from
$1.9 billion in the first quarter. Those expenses were
wide-ranging, including completion of year 2000 readiness projects
to amortization related to the sale of AltaVista to increased
spending for promotion and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Ross, an analyst in San Francisco with ABN Amro, said
Compaq's complaints about pricing pressures continue to be an
anomaly in the industry. While its competitors face the same
downward trend in pricing, they have not felt it at the bottom line
in the same way as Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ultimately points to their own inefficiency, and they've
been hurt by it,'' Ross said. ``Their competitors can take the
pressure better than Compaq can.''
</P>
<P>
   The inventory that Compaq keeps in its dealer channel _ the
middlemen who sell Compaq systems to businesses _ actually shrank a
bit compared to the first quarter of the year, to 3.5 weeks as
compared with 3.9 weeks. Analysts had been worried that Compaq
products were beginning to pile up on its dealers' shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq reported its earnings after markets closed Wednesday. The
company's stock closed at 26, up 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   The company did have some good news to report in its consumer
sales. Compaq said it hit an all-time high for monthly shipments in
June, and that it had year-over-year unit growth of 63 percent and
revenue growth of 35 percent in that market.
</P>
<P>
   But the consumer segment is also the one with the thinnest
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar said Compaq could begin seeing the light at the end of the
tunnel in the fourth quarter, as the changes it is making now begin
to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Capellas said improvements in Compaq's financial situation could
begin to surface as early as this quarter. First Call analysts
estimate Compaq will post a 5-cent-a-share profit for the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has been struggling with industry-wide changes. The
cutthroat pricing that had been unique to the consumer business has
made its way into the traditionally more profitable commercial
side.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Compaq's business customers are increasingly turning to
computer makers who sell directly to them, rather than going
through resellers, who add costs. Chief among the direct vendors is
Round Rock-based Dell Computer.
</P>
<P>
   Recent market share figures from International Data Corp, a
research firm, show that Dell has almost caught Compaq as the top
PC maker in the U.S. market. Analysts say Dell could surpass Compaq
domestically this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   However, Compaq maintains a solid lead over Dell worldwide,
though Dell's global growth is greater than that of Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has been rocked by these changes since the first quarter
of 1998, and the company's rocky performance is one of the factors
that cost previous Chief Executive Eckhard Pfeiffer and Chief
Financial Officer Earl Mason their jobs in April.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on Wednesday was the first public outing for
Capellas as chief executive, who was promoted late last week from
his job as interim chief operating officer. Capellas came to Compaq
last August as its new chief information officer.
</P>
<P>
   After Pfeiffer was ousted, Compaq was run by a three-man
``office of the chief executive'' headed up by board Chairman
Benjamin Rosen. After Capellas was named president and chief
executive, Rosen dissolved both the office of the chief executive
as well as the chief operating officer's post.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
