<HEADLINE>
GORE COURTS HISPANIC VOTE IN SWING THROUGH HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LORI RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Weaving Spanish words through his English and against
the lilt of mariachi music, Vice President Al Gore campaigned
Wednesday in the heart of Houston's Hispanic east side and left his
Latino listeners pleased but wincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soy abuelito'' (I'm a grandfather), the Democratic
presidential front-runner told receptive Latinos gathered in the
gymnasium of a new educational center for the George I. Sanchez
Charter High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandson Wyatt was born on the Fourth of July, clearly a
precocious child. Perhaps my next grandson will be born on Cinco de
Mayo.''
</P>
<P>
   Jokes and halting Spanish aside, the point of the Gore trip to
the center, a 15-year-old dream of the venerable Association for
the Advancement of Mexican Americans, was politics in the home
state of the Republican front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   There and in a later speech to the annual meeting of the
National Council of La Raza, the nation's largest Hispanic advocacy
group, Gore scored major points merely by showing up.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is vacationing at his family's home in Kennebunkport,
Maine. His aides said he could not fit the Hispanic meetings into
his schedule, but he has courted the Hispanic vote at many stops
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They underestimated the reaction of our community,'' La Raza
President Raul Yzaguirre said of the rejected invitation by the
Bush campaign. ``People were angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzaguirre said Bush's absence fueled politically damaging
speculation that he was either taking his Latino support for
granted or distancing himself to keep peace with the Republican
right-wing that spawned former California Gov. Pete Wilson and his
anti-immigrant initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   A warmer, fuzzier Gore with a noticeably improved Spanish accent
hammered home a long list of accomplishments on issues critical to
the nation's fastest growing minority, including health care,
education and immigration. Gore was accompanied during his visit by
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, the highest-ranking Latino in the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not satisfied when even one Latino is left out of our
prosperity,'' said Gore, adding a refrain he used in both
appearances: ``Nuestras familias merecen lo mejor'' (Our families
deserve the best).
</P>
<P>
   ``I am certainly not satisfied when 10 percent of all of the
uninsured children in the United States live right here in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore never mentioned Bush by name, he repeatedly attacked
the Republican leadership for a tax-cut plan he said would
jeopardize Social Security, Medicare and other social services on
which many needy, elderly and disabled Latinos depend. Bush has
said he would sign the Republican tax cut plan now pending in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Texas, the state with the second highest percentage of
uninsured children in America, we need to question how any leader
could support such a risky scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked afterward whether his pointed remarks referred to his
Republican rival, Gore said, ``I didn't use that name but, if the
shoe fits, wear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's snub of La Raza spawned a flurry of ``Where's George?''
lapel stickers.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee piled on Bush in conjunction
with Gore's trip, noting his decisions to skip not only the La Raza
convention but also the meetings of the League of United Latin
American Citizens in Corpus Christi and of the National Association
of Latino Elected and Appointed Officials in Philadelphia. Bush has
agreed to address the meeting of the National Urban League, a black
civil rights group, next month in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's long and enthusiastically received speech to the more
than 2,000 La Raza conferees was his third appearance before a
major Latino group this month. On July 7, he swung by Philadelphia
to the NALEO meeting, and on July 17 he went to Long Beach, Calif.,
for the Southwest Voter Registration and Education Project
conference.
</P>
<P>
   He also met with a group of Latino leaders at the White House
and with members of the Hispanic Congressional Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt threatened by Bush, who captured about 40
percent of the Texas Latino vote in his 1998 gubernatorial
re-election, Gore said that Latino concerns have always been a
priority for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a new pattern for me and it doesn't come as a
response to any developments on the other side,'' Gore said. ``I
have been reaching out in exactly this way the entire time I've
been vice president. These events have always been on my
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the increased and improving Spanish, Gore said, in
Spanish, that he likes to practice his Spanish and welcomed every
opportunity to refresh his skills. ``It's like living la vida loca.
It just grabs a hold of me.''
</P>
<P>
   So, apparently, does campaigning among the nation's 31 million
Latinos, who are concentrated in the key electoral states of Texas,
California, New York, Florida and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   At the east-side gymnasium, still smelling of fresh paint, Gore
began by shaking hands with the mariachis and ended by plunging
into the audience. At La Raza, after giving his Spanish a thorough
workout, he startled several dozen mainly Latino servers in a
curtained-off preparation area when he stopped to collect more
handshakes, hugs and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He connected with the audience very well,'' said Yzaguirre,
who on Wednesday closed the conference of La Raza's 240 community
groups from across the country. ``He reached our hearts and he
reached our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
