<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY'S FORMER VISE SECTION CHIEF UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 Republic Washington Bureau  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House committee today will unveil evidence of new
favors, including a free stay at a luxury Scottsdale suite,
provided to a former visa official at the U.S. embassy in Beijing
by a Chinese government-owned conglomerate or its Valley-based
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Charles M. Parish Jr., the embassy's former visa section chief,
accepted a number of previously undisclosed gifts from Elizabeth
Mann, operator of a Phoenix real-estate company called BNU Corp.
that is owned by the conglomerate, according to House Government
Reform Committee investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is holding a hearing today with Parish expected to
be the lead witness.
</P>
<P>
   `` The Arizona Republic'' reported in March that Parish, in
violation of State Department rules, accepted free lodging at
corporate apartments in Las Vegas and Norwalk, Calif., in 1995 and
1996 from China National Cereals, Oils and Foodstuffs Import and
Export Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The committee says Parish, who has denied any quid pro quo
relationship, was providing visa assistance at the request of Mann
and others so that officials of the conglomerate, known as COFCO,
could travel frequently to Phoenix and other U.S. destinations.
State Department rules forbid embassy officials from accepting
gifts from anyone seeking visas or other official action.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Republic'' has learned that the committee plans today to
release new evidence that deepens the Parish-Mann relationship that
has piqued the interest of committee investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Mann was traveling Wednesday and could not be reached for
comment, according to her firm. Parish was also unavailable pending
today's hearing in which he will testify publicly for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Republic has learned that the new information includes:
</P>
<P>
   _Mann gave Parish ``a number of gifts,'' a former COFCO vice
president, Jay Ding, has told the committee staff. Ding has told
the panel's investigators he saw Mann pass several wrapped boxes
and an envelope to Parish while he was dining with COFCO and BNU
officials in Beijing and Phoenix. Ding told the committee he didn't
know what the gifts were. He said Mann mentioned a gold Rolex watch
and $2,000 in casino chips in connection with Parish, but Ding is
not sure she gave either to Parish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _The committee said Parish stayed free of charge at a COFCO
luxury suite
 &UR; in Scottsdale. The address could not be obtained from either the
committee or
 &UR; Mann's office.
</P>
<P>
   _Several e-mails in Parish's office suggest that Parish, at
Mann's request, helped Fuli Lin, the vice chairman of BNU, to
obtain a visa, according to the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Mann has not been summoned as a witness by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pursuing a number of issues involving Elizabeth Mann,''
said Mark Corallo, the committee spokesman. ``We intend to contact
her soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Parish told the ``Republic'' in March that his activities may
have raised questions, but he denied impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I ever abuse my position? No,'' Parish said.
</P>
<P>
   Today's hearing will focus not only on alleged improper action
by Parish, but on Burton's claim that others in the embassy seemed
to overlook any problems and the State Department has not
aggressively been investigating. Among those on the witness list is
Jacquelyn Williams-Bridgers, the State Department's inspector
general.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. embassy in Beijing is one of our most sensitive
diplomatic posts in the world,'' Burton said in a prepared
statement. ``It is unfathomable that these kinds of activities
could go on right under the noses of top embassy officials for a
year and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton's committee is the same one that has been looking into
whether Chinese government money was used to influence the 1996
U.S. elections.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also led an investigation several years ago into
whether Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, a former Arizona
governor, allowed politics to influence his department in the
rejection of an Indian casino application. The matter ended up in
an independent counsel investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
