<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT SHOWDOWN NEEDS IS TRASH TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The $1.5 million ``Showdown at Sherwood'' between
titanium-toting blasters Tiger Woods and David Duval will establish
diddly, except who happens to be the planet's best player on this
given Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   And who had the most profitable outing at Sherwood Country Club,
one of the nation's toniest golf establishments, as the winner
leaves town with $1.1 million in unofficial but extremely spendable
cash. The loser pockets $400,000, which is not a bad wage for a few
hours work. Each player will contribute $200,000 to charity.
</P>
<P>
   While match play _ where there can be a loser on every hole _ is
golf's version of sudden death, we'll have to wait until season's
end to find out which one stands atop the heap this year.
</P>
<P>
   This event won't have any trouble living up to the hype because
there really hasn't been any.
</P>
<P>
   Historically speaking, Billie Jean King's beating the pants off
Bobby Riggs will probably prove to be better prime-time theater. So
will ``Sports Night'' and ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragging rights are not even at stake, because both golfers have
downplayed any rivalry. Woods might do a little fist-pumping after
sinking a putt and Duval might actually blink behind those
wrap-around shades, but it's doubtful that the victor will do any
chest-thumping.
</P>
<P>
   About the closest thing this sport has ever had to an outrageous
statement was uttered by television yakker Curtis Strange, an
announcer at Monday's event, who after winning his second U.S. Open
in a row promptly said: ``Move over, Ben.'' He referred, of course,
to the legendary Ben Hogan, the last golfer to pull off the repeat.
</P>
<P>
   After Strange removed his Foot-Joy from his mouth, his game got
a dose of the big chill and he soon found himself behind a
microphone explaining how other players managed to shank a two-foot
putt or spray shots.
</P>
<P>
   Strange himself seems to long for a little edge to Monday
night's event. It would give ABC's promotion department something
to promote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If either player came out and said, `I want to beat his butt'
that would be something everybody would embrace and have fun with,
but that's not going to happen,'' he said during a conference call
with network producers and his announcing partner, Mike Tirico.
</P>
<P>
   This is an event that just about everybody has played down, not
up.
</P>
<P>
   Such as the rivalry between Woods, the current world No. 1
player, and Duval, the No. 2, who used to be No. 1. The showdown
will have no impact on these standings.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, including the brass at ABC, deny a rivalry even
exists since Woods and Duval have not declared war on each other.
</P>
<P>
   Strange has a strange take on this situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for rivalry, I don't think there is a big one yet because
we haven't seen it in a tournament. Until that happens, in either
tournament play or major championships, their true rivalry won't
happen. But they are both very young still. They are the future of
golf. I think the rivalry will happen eventually,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Golf is rife with rivalries, albeit some of them friendly. You
think 150 guys tee it up each week to finish 35th?
</P>
<P>
   So what do you suppose Woods and Duval will be thinking when
they step up to the first tee Monday? They will both be trying to
grind the other into dust and win by the biggest margin possible.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not too late to spice things up. Strange, while
pointing out that both are great players, believes Woods will be
the man Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to pick one over the other is like throwing dice. At
the current stage of both games, I think you have to pick Tiger as
a slight favorite because he is playing so well right now. During
the course of a year, players have ups and downs, and David is
going through a bit of a down right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Add showdown: The management at Sherwood Country Club reportedly
set the high ticket prices, which were originally $550 for a
clubhouse pass and $225 for a grounds pass. Sherwood officials
declined comment on the pricing policy. Spokesman Steve Brener said
that price of a grounds pass has been lowered to $100.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we wanted to give more people an opportunity to
attend,'' he said. The gallery is expected to be between 1,000 and
2,000 spectators. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Play will start on the 9th hole, the more mountainous section of
the course, to give Woods and Duval a better chance of finishing
while the sun is still shining.
</P>
<P>
   They will tee off at 4:30 p.m. and the telecast will start at 5
p.m., when the players are expected to be on their third hole. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
