<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC WILL BE ONLY BALKANS LEADER MISSING FROM SUMMIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the world opens its wallet to Kosovo and
considers rebuilding its Balkan neighbors, White House officials
are predicting that an international conference in Bosnia will
further isolate Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic will be the only Balkan leader excluded from the
conference, a gathering Friday to be attended by President Clinton
and top officials from 40 nations who hope to prod the war-torn
region toward economic and political reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a good deal of disaffection (in Serbia) with Slobodan
Milosevic, and I think that one of the most important elements of
Friday will be the empty chair,'' said National Security Adviser
Sandy Berger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbia will be the only country not there, (the) only country
not part of an enterprise that means rebuilding and rebirth and
growth and better lives for the people of the region,'' Berger
said. ``Most people in Serbia today ... believe that he has led
them down a path to destruction, that he has brought them four wars
and a ruined economy.''
</P>
<P>
   While Milosevic's government will not be represented, a handful
of Serb opposition leaders have been invited, a move Berger said
``certainly has our support.'' At the same time, while supporting
forces inside Yugoslavia ``who are working for democratic change,
Berger downplayed the suggestion that the U.S. or its allies are
trying to lead an insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the purpose of this meeting is to concert our
efforts with respect to change in Serbia,'' Berger said, adding
that the summit will signal that ``a new southeastern Europe is
taking shape, and the Serbian people are going to have to decide
whether they are simply going to not be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee approved
legislation _ supported by the White House _ designed to help drive
Milosevic from office. The bill sets aside $100 million to promote
democracy in Serbia and Montenegro, which make up the Yugoslav
republic, and to increase Voice of America broadcasts into the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before the Balkans summit opens in Sarajevo, the
capital of Bosnia, leaders from more than 60 nations met Wednesday
in Brussels and pledged about $2.1 billion to help rebuild Kosovo.
The U.S. agreed to contribute $500 million to the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Of the amount pledged by the donor nations, $245 million was
promised in time to help Kosovar refugees through the winter. In
addition to food and shelter for the Kosovar Albanians driven from
their homes by Milosevic's forces, the U.S. money was earmarked for
sanitation, water supply, land mine removal and prosecuting
suspected war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kosovo's) most immediate, urgent requirements, which were the
objectives of this meeting, have been met,'' Chris Poortman, World
Bank coordinator for southeastern Europe told reporters after the
Brussels conference.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meeting in Brussels and Friday's summit in Sarajevo
come seven weeks after the U.S.-led air war against Yugoslavia.
Toward the end of the conflict, Milosevic was indicted by the
International War Crimes Tribunal on charges stemming from
atrocities committed by the Serb army and police against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's Balkans summit, in addition to underscoring Milosevic's
pariah status, was described by Berger and other administration
officials as a first step in a long-term effort to bring peace and
stability to southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The summit, organized by the European Union, will not result in
additional, immediate financial commitments to aid the troubled
region, Berger said. ``Friday's summit is really to launch a
regional compact with the rest of Europe and set the direction on
democracy, on security, on economic reform that will bring this
region of the world, eventually, into the European mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Balkan countries will present ``their vision for
progress and cooperation on tasks including strengthening
democracy, civil society, ethnic and religious tolerance, economic
reform,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   The summit, scheduled to last three hours, will end with leaders
issuing a Sarajevo declaration describing the general commitments
made by participants.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the president's national economic adviser, said
the long-term success of rebuilding the Balkans states ``will
depend very much on the steps they take'' to reassure investors and
potential trading partners. ``Ultimately, someone still has to
believe there is a viable economic investment with a return to put
funds in there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The summit grew out of the Balkans Stability Pact, signed last
month in Cologne by the U.S., European Union, Russia, and other
industrialized nations. It will be the first meeting of leaders
from Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia-Herzegovina and Macedonia since they
broke from Yugoslavia at the outset of war in 1991. Other members
of the pact are Albania, Bulgaria, Hungary, Romania and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
