<HEADER>
A8057 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-1STL     07-28 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REPUBLICANS TURN ASIDE DEMOCRATS' PLAN FOR TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Subs 20th graf to correct spelling of Olympia Snowe's name) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in the Senate turned aside a Democratic
plan Wednesday to limit the size of their proposed tax cut, even as
centrists from both parties laid out a middle ground on which a
compromise could eventually be forged.
</P>
<P>
   But as Republicans moved closer to Senate passage of the largest
tax cut since 1981, they suffered a quirky procedural defeat that
in theory would force them to rescind their tax reductions in 10
years, just after they fully take effect.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of debate in the Senate on how big a tax cut
the nation can afford in an era of anticipated federal budget
surpluses, Republicans made a case for sending as much excess
revenue as possible back to taxpayers while Democrats warned that
too big a reduction would wreak havoc with the economy, favor the
wealthy and starve vital government programs.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans and a few Democrats were pushing for
legislation that would cut taxes by $792 billion over 10 years,
using the bulk of the nearly $1 trillion in projected surpluses
over the next decade that the two parties agree are up for grabs.
The House passed a tax cut last week along party lines that is the
same size but which is made up of different provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``After paying for the government programs for which Congress
has planned and budgeted, the change must now be returned to the
taxpayer,'' said Sen. William Roth, R-Del., the chairman of the
Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has threatened to veto either version, saying
both would risk a return to budget deficits and limit Washington's
ability to shore up the ailing Social Security and Medicare
programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has opened the door to negotiations, and has
countered the Republican plan with an offer of a tax cut of up to
$300 billion, a figure supported by most Democrats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not mislead the American people by promising them
massive tax cuts which may well be based only on phantom surpluses
which never materialize,'' said Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va. ``Even if
the surpluses do happen, this Republican tax cut plan could
emasculate national security, public investments and the operations
of government.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of 10 centrist Democrats and Republicans sought to kick
start the process of finding a middle ground Wednesday by proposing
a $500 billion compromise plan that includes elements sought by
both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Based on preliminary votes Wednesday, Republicans appeared to
have the votes they need to pass their $792 billion plan in the
Senate by the end of this week. They defeated an attempt by
Democrats to limit the tax cut to $290 billion over 10 years on a
60-39 vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans suffered at least a symbolic setback when they
were unable to sidestep a rule _ written at a time when Congress
was intent on limiting the growth of budget deficits _ that makes
it difficult to pass tax cuts that remain in effect for more than
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The rule essentially bars any provisions in a tax or budget bill
that results in the government losing revenue after the first 10
years, which a net tax cut of the sort under consideration by both
parties does by definition.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans asked for a waiver of the rule, a step that
requires 60 votes. But they could muster only 51 votes, while all
45 Democrats and three moderate Republicans voted to keep the rule
in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Senate bill become law _ an unlikely prospect given
Clinton's veto threat _ it would phase in most of its tax cuts
gradually over the next decade as the projected budget surplus
increases. The cuts would then remain in effect permanently. But
under the budget rule, the entire tax cut would be rescinded after
2009.
</P>
<P>
   The practical effect would not necessarily be so dire for
Republicans, who could pass new budget rules in future sessions of
Congress or could pass legislation extending the tax cuts past
2009.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, any compromise tax proposals will
require bipartisan support to become law, and any deal between the
Republican leadership and Clinton would likely bring along enough
Democrats in the Senate to get over the 60-vote hurdle needed to
waive the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the harshly partisan tone of Wednesday's debate in the
Senate, the $500 billion compromise plan advanced by five
Republicans and five Democrats suggested some willingness to reach
a deal, though probably not until after Congress finishes passing
some version of the current Republican proposals and Clinton vetoes
it.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsors of the compromise measure, which is likely to be
considered by the Senate on Thursday, said their plan has almost no
chance of being adopted at this point. But they said it could be
the basis for negotiations between the White House and Congress,
probably starting in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're serious about passing a tax cut this year, I believe
this alternative is the right way to go,'' said Sen. John Chafee,
R-R.I., one of the sponsors of the $500 billion compromise. ``If we
are successful, I believe the final package will look a lot like
our bipartisan alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Republicans backing the compromise plan were Sens.
James Jeffords of Vermont, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, and Susan
Collins and Olympia Snowe, both of Maine. The Democrats were Sens.
John Breaux and Mary Landrieu of Louisiana, Bob Kerrey of Nebraska,
John Edwards of North Carolina and Evan Bayh of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The $500 billion plan would substantially increase the standard
deduction, providing a $283 billion cut in personal income taxes
over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the current $7,200 deduction for married couples
filing jointly would be increased to $11,550 and the current $4,300
standard deduction for single filers would increase to $5,600.
Since upper-income households usually itemize their deductions, the
change would primarily benefit lower- and middle-income households.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise package would also reduce the so-called marriage
penalty, which leaves many two-income couples paying more in taxes
than they would if they were single and living together. It would
include a modest reduction in capital gains taxes and in
inheritance taxes on large estates, and would provide tax breaks
for education and the purchase of health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the $792 billion Senate Republican plan is a
reduction in the current 15 percent personal income tax bracket to
14 percent and an expansion of the 14 percent bracket to higher
income levels.
</P>
<P>
   The $290 billion Democratic alternative that was rejected by the
Senate on Wednesday was built around an increase in the standard
deduction for personal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans remained on the defensive Wednesday over comments
made by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. Repeating a
message he first sent to Congress last week, Greenspan told the
Senate Banking Committee that Congress would be ``better off
holding off on a tax cut immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said there is no certainty that the projected
surpluses will materialize, and that the economy would benefit more
from reducing the national debt than from tax cuts. But he said he
would prefer tax cuts to using the surplus for additional
government spending.
</P>
</TEXT>
