<HEADLINE>
SPURRIER MAKES PITCH FOR PLAYOFF AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Florida coach Steve Spurrier is a playoff
proponent. Southeastern Conference commissioner Roy Kramer is the
architect and director of the Bowl Championship Series, the
ratings-driven, non-playoff method by which college football is
crowning its ``mythical'' national champion.
</P>
<P>
   During Wednesday's Southeastern Conference football media forum,
Spurrier stated his opinion again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the `commish' is back there and doesn't like to hear me
talk about playoffs,'' Spurrier said, provoking laughter and a
smile from Kramer. ``If you had 16 teams and started playing it
down, maybe a team with one or two losses would win it. That team
might be the best team at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier advocates having a football committee similar to the
basketball committee that selects and seeds the NCAA Tournament. He
said that former Texas coach Darrell Royal would be the perfect
choice as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, but that's too logical,'' Spurrier said, again provoking
chuckles. ``They don't ask my opinion. They hear it a lot, but they
don't ask for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said that for all its criticism, the BCS accomplished its
mission last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We matched the consensus one and two teams \RTennessee and
Florida State\S,'' he said. ``We maintained the bowl system. And we
heightened interest in the regular season.'' \Nsubheds:BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ While western football fans will be watching the Colorado at
Washington game on Sept. 25, pitting the Buffs against former coach
Rick Neuheisel, there's an SEC coaching grudge match on the same
date when Mississippi plays at Auburn (and former Rebels coach
Tommy Tuberville).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players were shocked when he left for Auburn,'' first-year
Ole Miss coach David Cutcliffe said. ``There will be a lot of hype
about that game and to say they won't be excited about it would be
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Good news: Vanderbilt has its top two passers, top three
rushers and top six wide receivers returning. Bad news: The
Commodores were last in the SEC in offense and scored seven or
fewer points five times last season. ``I think our offensive line
is stronger,'' Vanderbilt coach Woody Widenhofer said of his hopes
for an improved offense. ``It's the first time in my three years
here we've had depth at quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kramer is busting his buttons over the SEC's 1998 season. ``It
was unprecedented for a lot of reasons,'' he said. First, the SEC
set an NCAA record with eight bowl teams. The SEC had six of the
top 10 teams in national attendance and its 12 teams played to 99.6
percent of capacity. Kramer said one of every five fans who
attended a Division I-A game last season was at an SEC game.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
