<SLUG> BC-HKN-CARBONNEAU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS STRIKE DEAL WITH GUY CARBONNEAU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars' desire to get younger and quicker cost
veterans Craig Ludwig, Pat Verbeek and Dave Reid their jobs.
However, the team's oldest player remains in the fold.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Carbonneau, the Stars' 39-year-old fourth-line center and
penalty-killing specialist, agreed to a one-year contract with an
option for a second year, the team announced Wednesday. Carbonneau
will receive at least $1.32 million this season, based on a
mandatory 10 percent raise he'll receive over last season's salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be part of it for another year,'' Carbonneau
said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal means Carbonneau, who was an unrestricted free agent,
could play until he is 41 if both sides agree to pick up the second
year, but he's not looking that far ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll talk about that after this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau was somewhat concerned there wouldn't be a ``this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Stars won the Stanley Cup, Carbonneau had what he
termed a ``good conversation'' with coach Ken Hitchcock and general
manager Bob Gainey and thought they wanted him back.
</P>
<P>
   Then the team started telling most of its veteran free agents to
find jobs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to see which way to go,'' Carbonneau said. ``We
had an older team, and they wanted to get younger.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the delay was that the Stars wanted to give
Carbonneau time to consider whether to put himself through the
grind of training camp and the regular season for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau said he briefly thought about going out on top after
winning the Stanley Cup for the third time, but then decided to
play at least one more season. When the Stars decided they wanted
him to return, the deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of happy when they called back,'' said Carbonneau,
who also played on Cup-winning teams in Montreal in 1986 and '93.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau had four goals, 12 assists and 31 penalty minutes in
74 regular-season games. He scored goals in each of the first two
playoff games against the Edmonton Oilers, and finished with six
points in 17 postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   He missed six games during the Stars' Stanley Cup run because of
a sprained medial collateral ligament and to attend the funeral of
his father at home in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau did not have the offensive numbers of fellow forwards
Verbeek and Reid, free agents who were told to seek jobs elsewhere,
but his value to the team goes beyond the stats.
</P>
<P>
   ``While his abilities on the ice are well recognized, the vast
leadership and experience that he can bring our club off the ice is
what makes his contribution so valuable,'' Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau has 250 points, 397 assists and 784 penalty minutes
in 1,249 career NHL games with the Stars, St. Louis Blues and
Montreal Canadiens since 1980. He is the only player other than
Gainey to win three Selke trophies as the NHL's top defensive
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Hogue is the Stars' only remaining unrestricted free
agent. The team's restricted free agents are Richard Matvichuk,
Manny Fernandez, Jamie Pushor, Derek Plante, Aaron Gavey and Warren
Luhning. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
