<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-28 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8065 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUMMERPRO-LBPT     07-28 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUMMERPRO-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOPER HAS SEEN THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Duane Cooper's playing style is defined by giving, so we've
invited him to give the sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you energy off the bench,'' he says. ``I'll give you
a leader. I'll give you someone who knows the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the former Lakewood High, USC and Laker point guard will
give you his interpretation of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think that's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Time for us to give you an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who turned 30 last month, was fielding an inquiry
concerning his capacity to make a contribution in the NBA. But
after presenting a list of standard, point-guard equipment, he
admitted his performance in the Summer Pro League hasn't inspired
much buzz among NBA talent sharpies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've done OK here,'' says Cooper, a no-nonsense point
guard who is proud to be burdened with about as much flash as a
rental car.
</P>
<P>
   In a performance comparable to that of the conductor of a garage
band, he has averaged seven assists per game for the SPL's
quixotically named NBA Pros. The Pros' lineup does include NBA
employees Cedric Ceballos and James Cotton, but - like Cooper --
the rest of his pals realize they're auditioning for paychecks in
Europe or one of the domestic minor leagues. ``It's still fun, and
I'd be playing basketball to stay in shape anyway, so I might as
well play here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper, chosen by the Lakers in the second round (the 36th
overall pick) of the 1992 NBA Draft, isn't about to dismiss the
memories of his halcyon days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I suited up with the Lakers,'' he said, ``I
looked around and there was Magic and James Worthy. That was quite
a feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   However, averaging 2.4 points and 2.3 assists in 65 games
enabled Cooper to know how it felt to catch an NBA waive. After six
days adrift, he was signed by Phoenix. Following cameo roles in 23
Suns games and a knee injury, he became another American basketball
mercenary. First the CBA, then a prized Yankee-for-hire in Europe.
It's a nice life, but there are no vagabond shoe contracts.
</P>
<P>
   And no whining from Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left Lakewood,'' he said, ``I thought I'd be at USC for
four years and then start a career in something other than
basketball. So I think I've done pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   A broken foot (his) postponed Cooper's third season at USC and
put him on the school's five-year plan. He spent that fifth season
riding shotgun for All-American Harold Miner and providing enough
juice - 12 points and five assists per game - to interest the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, I thought I was reluctant to shoot,'' said Cooper,
who still maintains an agenda of asking questions first. ``Now I've
found a nice middle ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Cooper must find another employer, and realizes his best
financial opportunities probably exist overseas. But while
reconciling himself to that job market, he can't help hoping for a
call from closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question about it,'' Cooper says of his ability to hold his
own in the big time. ``I compete with NBA guys all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all the time in the summer. Since the 1993-'94 season in
Phoenix, Coop's hoop odyssey has forced him to listen for the NBA's
siren song from distant ports.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he played in Poland until paydays became a mystery.
His agent, Don DeJardin, moved Cooper to Greece, where he was point
man for Panionios.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper probably will cross the water for the coming season, but
doesn't anticipate keeping the dream alive long enough to be
considered an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm already walkin' with a limp,'' he said of his hoop
longevity. ``As soon as you repair an ACL (anterior cruciate
ligament), arthritis sets in.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper also realizes many outstanding players will pass
through the SPL and never get the opportunity to suit up for an NBA
team. So the limp could be see as a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   It means he's been somewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
