u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-SPI &LR;      07-28 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPELINE SAFETY CHIEF NOT SATISFIED YET WITH COMPANY'S RESPONSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Olympic Pipe Line Company is not fully
cooperating with federal investigators and has not fulfilled
conditions necessary to reopen the portion of the line that
exploded in Bellingham, Wash., the nation's top pipeline-safety
official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Coyner, the administrator overseeing the U.S. Department
of Transportation's pipeline safety programs, criticized the
company for not providing enough information to determine what went
wrong in Bellingham last month and to assess whether the pipeline
is now safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all satisfied,'' Coyner said during a wide-ranging
interview in her office. ``It is a challenge for the company to
respond in this environment, but this company has yet to step up to
the plate to provide the full picture of what is going on on the
(pipe)line.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Olympic submitted a document responding to actions
sought by the Office of Pipeline Safety in the aftermath of the
Bellingham explosion, which killed two boys and a teenager. The
company called the document an important step in beginning the
federal review process leading to reopening the closed part of the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Coyner released the 12-page introductory portion of the
company's response but withheld numerous attachments, saying that
she is not allowed to release the technical data because it is
private commercial information and because it is part of an ongoing
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In its response, the company said its main computer and a backup
system had failed on June 10 because of inadequate processing
capacity, and it also said it has since upgraded the machines. The
company said it would test valves during a purging of the pipeline
system before startup.
</P>
<P>
   But the company asked the Office of Pipeline Safety to retract
its request for a survey of the condition of coating along the
pipeline, saying that there is no indication that this was a
problem in the Bellingham accident. The company also asked to be
allowed to conduct a hydrostatic pressure test of the pipeline only
in Bellingham _ not down the full length of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Coyner said even a cursory review of a document indicates that
the company has not met the federal requirements for reopening.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the basis of that response, we are not at this point
prepared to reopen the line,'' she said. ``We are reviewing what
they've given us, but there are also pieces of information that we
have not been given that have been promised. We're just not in any
kind of situation where on the basis of that we would reopen the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyner declined to estimate how long it would take to restart
the pipeline. She said the company itself has indicated that it
won't be able to supply some information sought by the government
until late next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't reopen it until we're satisfied that they have given
us information indicating that it is safe to reopen it,'' she said.
``We have to be confident that they have given us the information
that we've required, and secondly, once we get it, we have to have
confidence in it. If we don't, we're not reopening it, and that's
the basic bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Olympic Pipe Line Company said company
officials were shocked to hear of Coyner's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comments are of concern because we have felt we've been
very responsive,'' said the spokeswoman, Maggie Brown. ``We're
working very hard to cooperate with all investigators, and we will
redouble our efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that Olympic has supplied ``tons'' of documents to
federal investigators, has granted round-the-clock access to a
Department of Transportation investigator and has submitted a
comprehensive response to the federal agency's order for corrective
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be absolutely no reason for Olympic to want to
slow down this process,'' she said. ``We want to run a safe
pipeline. That's what we've done for 34 years, and we want to
figure out what happened here and make sure it never happens
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyner had some kind words for some steps that the company had
taken before the explosion, and argued that critical testimony from
the National Transportation Safety Board on Tuesday may have left
the misimpression that certain safeguards were not in place in
Bellingham.
</P>
<P>
   Coyner said that, despite a dispute between her agency and the
safety board over how to write regulations in these areas, Olympic
had trained employees running the pipeline, had a leak detection
system in place and had inspected the pipeline using both a ``smart
pig'' _ a sensing device sent through the line _ and hydrostatic
testing, in which water is sent through the line at high pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Coyner also said that an initial review of previous testing of
the pipeline suggests no reason to question the line's integrity.
But she said the Office of Pipeline Safety is hiring an outside
expert to review the analysis of those tests, which are quite
complicated to interpret and sometimes fail to detect external
damage to a pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   But Coyner, whose actions in this case are being carefully
watched by Congress, the NTSB and residents of Bellingham, made a
point of repeatedly stating her unhappiness with Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information, based on when we've done accident
investigations in other things, is not coming forth the way it
needs to come forth,'' she said. ``There's just basic kinds of
things. At the outset we had challenges getting a hold of the
documentation about the computer system, and the process has been
one piece at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyner suggested that the company needs to be fully forthcoming
with any information reflecting on the integrity of the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to underscore that it's the company's
responsibility to bring that information to the table,'' she said.
``It's not the investigators' responsibility to have to ask for
everything by page number to figure out what we're missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyner acknowledged that eight Olympic employees have refused to
testify for fear of incriminating themselves, but she added that
that does not wholly explain the company's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't make a person available who has a Fifth Amendment
right not to testify, but you can provide documents, you can
provide physical access, you can provide computer runs, and we
continue to press for that information,'' she said. ``It's been a
long, slow, tortured process to get that information from them, and
it's not that companies can't get this information.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyner said some information sought by the federal agency would
require time-consuming engineering work, but that for other
information ``it's getting a focus on what this is about, and it's
about their responsibility to give everybody confidence in their
(pipe)line. We have an oversight responsibility, but the company is
part of that community, and they've just got to come to the plate
and say, `Here's what we have: the good, the bad, and the ugly'.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyner said other pipeline companies have been subjected to
similar levels of scrutiny. She said the agency forced Colonial
Pipeline, the longest liquid pipeline in the country, to spend
millions of dollars on changes after an accident involving its
pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a high level of scrutiny,'' she said of the agency's
attitude toward Olympic. ``It's not an unheard of level of
scrutiny.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
