<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY STEPS FOR L.A. BID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Los Angeles bid to acquire the next NFL franchise
kept taking baby steps Wednesday, leaving some to wonder whether it
can ever walk all the way to completion.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners met here for two days, heard the first Los Angeles
``team'' presentation from Gov. Gray Davis' representative, nodded
their heads at the wonderful progress that had been made, and then
flew off to each of their 31 cities without taking any action.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Chadwick, welcome to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick is the investment banker Davis asked six weeks ago to
organize the Los Angeles franchise effort, which included bringing
the rival would-be ownership groups _ Michael Ovitz-Ron Burkle and
Eli Broad-Ed Roski Jr. _ together behind one plan.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are happy with the Coliseum renovation design and
Exposition Park site plan, which is basically the Ovitz design, but
remain skeptical over the economics. Which, translated, means: We
want more public money.
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick presented the owners with an exclusive negotiating
agreement for the stadium lease, which included some new details
but not too many, that already had been agreed to by the Coliseum
Commission and the California Science Center (Chadwick is the
board's director).
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectation is, we will have (the owners) sign off on that
document by the end of the week,'' Chadwick said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said later that the
league would not sign the agreement, but would work under its
framework. Instead of signing on, Tagliabue said, the expansion
committee co-chairmen would send Chadwick a letter of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't sign off on the entire document,'' Tagliabue said.
``There are things in there we agree with, and things in there we
are not in agreement with. It will need further negotiations. There
are some economic issues that need to be improved upon so a team
can be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Several owners are concerned that the agreement as designed by
Chadwick is too severe economically and would make it difficult for
a team to flourish in Los Angeles. The 30-year lease calls for an
annual $5 million payment, and some revenues that normally would go
to the team will be used as debt service on the $150 million worth
of bonds Chadwick ultimately will propose to build new parking
structures.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the NFL will look to wiggle public funding beyond
bonding, however masked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not sufficient to allow a team to work,'' Tagliabue
said. ``You couldn't field a competitive team.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the cost of renovating the Coliseum goes up every
time it's mentioned. When Broad and Ovitz made their separate
proposals to the owners in May, Broad was talking about spending
$275 million and Ovitz $295 million. The NFL estimated it would
cost closer to $400 million last week, and by Wednesday Chadwick
was talking about $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the commissioner said was, it was somewhere between $350
to $600 million,'' Chadwick said. ``And that's a big somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the $150 million for parking.
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick might not have gotten the NFL to sign his agreement,
which is nonbinding anyway, but Tagliabue said the league's letter
of support will recommend to owners that the NFL financially aid
the Coliseum renovation. The NFL is expected to contribute $150
million toward the new Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   But if the expansion fee is $500 million, and the team owner
still has to contribute $300 million toward the Coliseum, that
leaves a very thin profit margin for an enterprise Broad said is
expected to generate $25 million to $28 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, when I started, if I thought the returns would be
this skimpy, I'm not sure I would have started,'' Broad said. ``But
once you get involved, you're willing to do things that don't make
the greatest amount of economic sense.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite saying the league would establish a franchise fee to
avoid an auction, Tagliabue said Wednesday that he expects both
ownership groups to make offers prior to the Sept. 15 deadline
given Los Angeles for satisfying the league's expansion demands.
Then, he said, a franchise fee would be set.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the great Chinese jigsaw puzzles of all time,''
Ovitz said. ``Some of the problem Bill's had to date is, no one
wants to put their foot in the water first. Who's going to jump in
first _ the state, the ownership group, the NFL? I think what
you're seeing now is everyone converging into one plan.''
</P>
<P>
   If ever so slowly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
