<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDERS-SMITH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMITT SMITH SAYS NFL NEEDS TO KEEP SANDERS AT ANY COST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith
said the NFL should step in and do whatever it takes to keep Barry
Sanders from retiring. Emmitt's logic: Unprecedented action?
Unparalleled player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the league should step in because we're losing a
cornerstone of the National Football League,'' Smith said. ``There
have been only four guys in NFL history to rush for over 2,000
yards (in a season). He is one of those guys, plus he has been a
stand-up individual for the league for 10 years. The man deserves
to be on a winning team.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who came into the league one year after Sanders, has been
on three Super Bowl championship teams. Sanders has been on Detroit
Lions teams that have won only one playoff game in his 10 NFL
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   With Sanders retiring, Smith now becomes the NFL's leading
active rusher. He is fifth on the all-time career rushing list with
12,566 yards _ 4,161 yards behind Payton _ and could be the one
chasing down that record in three seasons or so.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith wasn't thinking of himself Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he would tell Sanders if he could talk to him,
Smith pleaded: ``Come on back! Don't let me be the Lone Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was genuinely moved and shocked by the news that
Sanders was quitting in spite of the fact that he is at the top of
his game and capable of breaking the NFL's all-time rushing record
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Barry would've been the first back to actually break
the 20,000-yard barrier before he was done,'' Smith said. ``I
really believe that because he's a running back with many, many
more years in front of him. This is an unfortunate situation. Maybe
he will reconsider and come back, or maybe they might trade him
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry was always a benchmark for me. He was always someone I
was chasing in terms of being the best running back in the National
Football League, just as he was one of the greatest _ if not THE
greatest _ ever to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was blindsided by the news upon showing up a day
early for camp Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all have to be joking,'' Smith said when first informed of
the news. ``Barry is not retiring. I don't buy it, just yet. The
man has many, many, many more years left. But I can sympathize with
his situation up there. The man has been everything Detroit wanted.
But has Detroit been everything he needed? Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that the two players never talked about the effects
of those bad Lions teams (78-82 overall) that apparently has driven
Sanders into early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Could Emmitt walk away with the rushing record in sight?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Smith replied. ``I can't put myself in his
situation. You can't compare apples and oranges. (Cowboys-Lions)
are two different things.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is coming off a 1,332-yard season with 13 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs feel fine,'' he said. ``I'm far from retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   And he wishes Sanders felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Barry chooses to leave the game, that's his choice,'' Smith
said. ``But I wish he wouldn't retire at the present moment because
I would love to see him break the record. He has a great
opportunity to do it this year. It would be exciting to watch. It
would be a part of history.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
