   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT21) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-CELLS (Undated) _ Usinf a precise molecular recipe,
scientists have succeeded in turning normal human cells into cancer
cells in the lab, a task that sounded simple but which eluded
molecular biologists for more than 15 years. Researchers hope that
with this new understanding of the mechanism that starts cancer,
they have moved one important step closer to finding specific ways
to turn it off. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-PRISONS (Miami) _ The FBI and state law-enforcement
officials are investigating Florida prisons to see whether there is
widespread abuse of prisoners by guards. The inquiry was set off by
the recent beating death of a death-row inmate. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT26) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-SOCIETY (Undated) _ Lobbying over the issue of human
embryonic stem cell research has generated such heat that the
American Cancer Society has withdrawn its sponsorship of Patient's
Cure, a group founded to publicize the medical benefits of stem
cell research. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   FAT-IMAGE (Framingham, Mass.) _ The caramel lollipops at
registration; the black thong bikini that Marilyn Wann, a proud 270
pounds, wore at the pool party; the very pool party itself, for
people who are usually pool pariahs: All these were political
statements of defiance here at the convention of the National
Association to Advance Fat Acceptance, as political as the T-shirts
reading, ``Fat! So?'' By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT20) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
