   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BANKINGHOUSE-DISCRIM (New York) _ For more than a dozen years,
Allison K. Schieffelin was on Wall Street's fast track. One of a
small number of women who specialize in selling exotic financial
products, Ms. Schieffelin thrived at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
one of the finance industry's most respected firms. She took home
well in excess of $1 million each year and felt certain she would
became a managing director, the equivalent of partner. But by the
spring of 1998, her boss made it plain that she would probably
never be promoted, telling her that ``not everyone gets managing
director.'' As a result, the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission has launched a sweeping investigation into Morgan
Stanley's pay and promotion policies as they affect women. By
Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   BIG-BOARD-SURVIVE (New York) _ As the New York exchange and its
chief executive, Richard A. Grasso, search for a survival strategy,
Wall Street's central symbol faces a daunting array of challenges.
The exchange must protect its franchise and find a way to blend the
best aspects of its floor-based auction system with the speed and
the capacity that only computers can provide. It must become more
cost-efficient without becoming less careful about policing its
business. And, as a public company, the Big Board must figure out
how to make money doing all this _ enough money to placate
potentially impatient shareholders. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT22) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ During the past year, Frank G.
Zarb, chairman of the National Association of Securities Dealers,
has struck deals to buy the American Stock Exchange, forged
alliances with three overseas bourses and promised investors
24-hour access to the Nasdaq stock market. And at a NASD board
meeting Thursday, Zarb will present his plan for making the Nasdaq
market a for-profit, publicly-held company separate from its
regulatory unit. Clearly, Zarb has been busy. But has he been
effective? By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ As the Senate begins debating plans this
week to lower taxes, Democrats point to Republican proposals and
cry foul: The rich come away with gargantuan tax reductions
compared with those for everyone else. Republican leaders respond
that their large tax cuts are fair because high-income families pay
a gargantuan share of federal taxes. Whose arguments win? By
Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   MILLER-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ A beer blast for two
unconventional agencies known for their creative prowess turned
into a beer bust Wednesday when Miller Brewing Co. abruptly turned
over their assignments, for its two largest beer brands, to big,
mainstream shops that work for Miller's parent, Philip Morris Cos.
By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
