   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INHERIT-FIGHTS (Undated) _ Familial fights over inheritance are
ripping apart many a middle-class clan. Six years ago, economists
predicted the largest intergenerational transfer of wealth in
history _ approximately $12 trillion _ would take place from then
until around 2020 as the security-minded Depression generation dies
off and leaves its money and its carved mahogany bedroom suites,
split-level ranch houses, family china, grandfather clocks and
moldering photographs to its baby boom children, a generation
weaned on irony, credit cards and broken marriages. By Neal Karlen.
</P>
<P>
   INHERIT-WORTH (Undated) _ If you've inherited a Matisse, you
probably know what to do with it. But what if you've been left two
cardboard cartons full of cut glass ashtrays and celery dishes? A
vintage 1947 Lionel train set? A Russian sable _ with only a small
tear under the arm? How do you get rid of this stuff _ and, you
hope, realize its full worth? By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   CONCIERGES (Undated) _ Its front-line employees having just
completed a three-month training program to improve service for
travelers, Amtrak announced in advertisements this month that
``10,000 employees went back to school. 10,000 concierges
graduated.'' In the same way that the breakfast roll became a
croissant, even with a fried egg and Canadian bacon on it, the
concierge has become a concept that knows few bounds. Though it
bases its popularity on the reputations of four-star hotel desk
clerks, for whom no service request is unrealizable, today's
concierge is untethered to performance. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-MUSEUM (Edinburgh, Scotland) _ The notion that Scotland
is a more beguiling place than the dark and rugged land it occupies
has found fitting expression in the alluring new Museum of
Scotland. In a modern building set on a hillside in Edinburgh's
medieval old town, the museum has a smoothly turned drum tower, a
furrowed roof terrace, slender windows and a sandstone exterior
with the amber flush of a sunset spreading across a Highland moor.
Enter and you're in a luminous castle keep. Indoor bridges span the
lofty courtyard space and staircases and narrow passageways
disappear invitingly into walls. It is a building of chanced-upon
spaces that promise a series of adventures. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
