<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS OFFICIAL DISMISS REPORTS OF GONZALEZ TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Rangers assistant general manager Dan O'Brien
dismissed a report in Wednesday's editions of ``The Washington
Times'' that claimed the organization discussed trading right
fielder Juan Gonzalez to the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Times'' cited an American League executive who said the
two organizations discussed a proposal in which the Rangers would
receive right-hander Mike Mussina and right fielder Albert Belle
from the Orioles for Gonzalez and center fielder Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   That trade proposal would be difficult to consummate.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts of Mussina and Belle include no-trade clauses, and
Gonzalez's contract contains a limited no-trade provision. The
contract allows the Rangers' two-time American League most valuable
player to choose 10 organizations to which he will not accept a
trade. It is not known, though, whether the Orioles are among those
10.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez missed his second consecutive start and third in four
games with a ligament strain in his right wrist and remains
day-to-day. WETTELAND'S STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland surrendered his single-season high ninth
home run Tuesday to Orioles center fielder Brady Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   It was at least the third time this season that an opposing
player hit a leadoff, ninth-inning home run against Wetteland on a
first-pitch fastball in which the opponent trailed by more than one
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to try to trick them there to get them out and
end up walking them and putting the tying run on base,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said of Wetteland. ``He's going to make them
hit it to get to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland expected Anderson to take the first pitch with the
Orioles trailing by three runs and threw a first-pitch fastball in
an attempt to get ahead in the count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't understand the thinking there when you're three
runs down with the middle of the order coming up, but that's
happened a lot this year,'' said Wetteland, who pitches according
to the situation. ``In one respect, it shouldn't be happening in
those situations. On the other hand, it didn't happen as much in
the past because I threw harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, who underwent arthroscopic surgery on his right elbow
during October, acknowledged that the 2-3 mph loss in velocity on
his fastball has played a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very typical byproduct of having surgery,'' Wetteland
said. DECISION ON GOODWIN
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Tom Goodwin expects a decision could be made this
weekend regarding his upcoming medical rehabilitation assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, who went on the 15-day disabled list July 28 with a
torn muscle in his left hip flexor, put the leg through a strenuous
test Wednesday and plans to do it again Friday at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know more after we leave here,'' Goodwin said. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Butch Wynegar, the Rangers' roving minor-league hitting
instructor, will resume those duties after the Rangers complete
their three-game series with the Orioles. Wynegar accompanied the
Rangers to Baltimore as an extra pitcher for batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Kansas City Royals announced right-hander Kevin Appier as
their scheduled starter for Sunday's game at The Ballpark in
Arlington. Most expect the Royals to trade Appier before Saturday's
trade deadline.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
