</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-ALLIANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES WEIGH CALLING OFF AN ALLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The proposed alliance between American Airlines and British
Airways may be called off as early as this week because the two
airlines cannot get approval from U.S. and British regulators,
according to people close to the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The two airlines have sought for three years to form a global
alliance that would allow them to coordinate schedules, sell each
others' tickets and share some profits. But the plans require
grants of immunity from antitrust rules that so far they have not
gotten.
</P>
<P>
   Other airlines have sharply criticized the proposed alliance,
saying it would make it far more difficult to compete on flights
between the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation has made it clear that it
will approve the alliance only if British officials allow other
U.S. carriers to use London's Heathrow Airport. Under a current
treaty, only American, a unit of the AMR Corp., which is based in
Fort Worth, and United Airlines, a unit of the UAL Corp., are
allowed to use Heathrow. Other U.S. carriers use Gatwick
International Airport, London's second airport.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines executives declined on Wednesday night to say
what would happen to the alliance. ``However this plays out,
American and British Airways will continue to build on the good
relationship they have developed in the past three years,'' said
John Hotard, an American spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The matter was first reported by the Financial Times of London
in an article published in Thursday's early editions. That article
quoted British Airways as having said that it still wanted to
pursue the American alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The planned alliance, if it comes about, would carry nearly
two-thirds of the traffic between the two countries and form the
core of a larger alliance, called Oneworld, that would include
several other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, British Airways said that it would settle for a
five-year phase-in of the alliance, after concluding that demands
by European officials that the two airlines give up 267 weekly
takeoff and landing slots at Heathrow was too great a price to pay
for quicker approval of the alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
